<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPERBOWL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
MIAMI _ Atlanta coach Dan Reeves can issue a public apology every
day this week. He can jump on a stage and do the Dirty Bird to try
to change the subject.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But as long as the Falcons are playing Denver in Super Bowl
XXXIII, his feud with Broncos coach Mike Shanahan and quarterback
John Elway will be the most highly publicized angle leading up to
Sunday's game at Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   When Reeves apologized Sunday night for his comments last week
that reignited a controversy that had been dormant for six years,
he wanted to put an end to the story that just won't go away _
certainly not this week, when his opponents are Shanahan and Elway.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, that's water under the bridge,''
Elway said this week. ``We've all gone our different directions. I
didn't think it deserved an apology.''
</P>
<P>
   When Reeves was in Denver with Shanahan and Elway, they were at
first one big, happy family. Slowly, Reeves' relationships with the
other two deteriorated, ultimately becoming a well-documented
family feud.
</P>
<P>
   When Reeves was fired, he blamed Shanahan and Elway, even though
Shanahan was coaching in San Francisco at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never been a question in my mind that Mike Shanahan's
a great coach,'' Reeves said last week. ``I couldn't have been
closer to someone than I was with Mike. It (their falling-out) was
a tough thing, but it happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that I'll ever get over the full situation. I
don't know that Mike will ever get over that, what it caused his
wife and his children. Same thing with me. It caused a lot of pain
for my wife and my children. It's something that won't ever go
away.''
</P>
<P>
   When Reeves opened the old wounds at a news conference last week
in Atlanta, Shanahan was stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really surprised that this has been brought up,'' Shanahan
said. ``I can't believe he's going into past scenarios. If he wants
to bring up dirty laundry, there's nothing I can do about it. I
thought we both were going to take the high road going into this
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Their relationship dates to 1984, Reeves' fourth season as
Denver's coach. Pat Bowlen bought the Broncos that season, and
Shanahan got his first NFL job when Reeves hired him to coach
receivers. That was Elway's second season.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan did such a good job in his rookie season that Reeves
promoted him to offensive coordinator for the next three years. As
the coordinator, Shanahan coached Elway. They became close friends,
so much so that their families took vacations together.
</P>
<P>
   Elway's relationship with Reeves was strained, but at that point
the damage was not irreparable. Reeves was old school. He was tough
on his quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, he screamed at me a bunch,'' Elway said last week. ``I
didn't scream at him nearly as much as he screamed at me. Most of
the time, he had a right to scream at me. It never got any better
than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Many who played with Elway said the crux of his problem with
Reeves was a conservative system. Elway thought the system kept him
from compiling Dan Marino-type statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Elway was envious of Marino. Miami coach Don Shula tailored his
system to take advantage of Marino's incredible right arm. Reeves
made Elway fit his system.
</P>
<P>
   Marino threw 48 touchdown passes in 1984, his second season, and
the Dolphins reached the Super Bowl. Elway didn't play in his first
Super Bowl until after the 1986 season.
</P>
<P>
   After the Broncos lost a second consecutive Super Bowl to end
the 1987 season, the Los Angeles Raiders hired Shanahan as head
coach. Without Shanahan in 1988, the Broncos finished 8-8.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan never saw eye-to-eye with LA owner Al Davis. The
Raiders were 7-9 in 1988, and when they began the 1989 season 1-3,
Shanahan was fired. He didn't stay out of work for long, because
Reeves brought him back immediately as quarterbacks coach.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves' relationship with Elway had deteriorated badly, and
Reeves needed a buffer. Shanahan was perfect. Elway was so unhappy
that he was prepared to retire and enter his automobile-dealership
business full-time rather than play for a coach who made him
miserable.
</P>
<P>
   With Shanahan back, Reeves kept a firm hand on the controls, and
the Broncos finished 11-5. They beat Cleveland in the AFC
Championship Game for the third time. Then, they lost a third Super
Bowl in four years, and they bottomed out in 1990 with a 5-11
record.
</P>
<P>
   It was after the 1990 season that Elway first went public about
how much he detested playing for Reeves. Reeves became angry at
Shanahan. He accused Shanahan of hiding exactly how Elway felt
about the head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think he had my best interests in mind at the time,''
Reeves said last week. ``If John had a problem with me, and you're
coaching that position, why did I not know that prior to reading it
in the paper?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were the position coach, and you're that close to the
quarterback, why didn't I know that? Hey, this is something you
ought to sit down and talk about, that this is a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   When Shanahan heard last week what Reeves said, he became angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``How am I supposed to know how John felt about Dan?'' he said.
``I thought I did a great job of keeping that relationship intact
for seven years. He came to me and was very upset about it. I said,
`What are you talking to me for? John said it. Go talk to John.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I went down to the weight room and got John and brought him up
to Dan's office. I said, `John, you tell Dan why you don't like
him. Dan, you tell John why you don't like him. I'm tired of being
in the middle of this stuff.' So they both did.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Reeves promoted Shanahan to offensive coordinator
again, and the Broncos rebounded with a 12-4 record. But they were
not happy campers. After they lost the AFC Championship Game at
Buffalo, everything came to a head.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves thought Shanahan was telling Elway things that were said
about the quarterback in coaches meetings. Reeves also accused
Shanahan of scripting plays behind his back.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, looking back last week, said, ``You say things in a
coaches meeting as far as critiquing the play of someone that you
would never say to the player. If John ever got any bad feelings
about something I said, it never was done publicly. It had to be
something from a staff meeting that you said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that mean Mike did it? You've got a lot of people on your
staff. (But) these are things that, in your mind _ I have no proof
of them _ I did what I thought was best for our football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Meaning he fired Shanahan and accused him of
``insubordination.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan said Reeves told him he was fired because Reeves wanted
to call the plays again. And besides, Shanahan said last week, if
Reeves admits now that he had no proof, why did he continue to
level the accusations?
</P>
<P>
   ``For a guy who doesn't have proof of something, he sure didn't
help my reputation,'' Shanahan said. ``To not have any proof but to
say somebody is insubordinate, that's one of the reasons I've had
such a tough time with this. That's a strong word not to have any
proof.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan believes the real reason he was fired is because ``Dan
wanted to run the offense, and he wanted complete control. He
really didn't want somebody with my type of personality around.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, when Elway heard about the charges Reeves was
leveling against Shanahan, he said, ``I just know thinking back
that everybody had their own opinion, and the way Dan was looking
at it was totally different from the view that I'm sure Mike was
looking at.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it was different from the way I was looking at it. So
it's hard for me to understand why this situation got to where this
situation did.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan was hired by San Francisco as offensive coordinator in
1992. That season, the Broncos finished 8-8, and Reeves was fired.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Two reasons. First, like many owners, Bowlen wanted to be
Jerry Jones, a hands-on owner who ran everything and won a Super
Bowl. One problem: Bowlen wasn't Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The second reason involved Elway. He was miserable without
Shanahan and never forgave Reeves for firing him. And he hated
playing for Reeves. Elway gave Bowlen a him-or-me ultimatum.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves was fired. He was confused. He was crushed. He didn't
understand.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bowlen interviewed three candidates _ Shanahan,
Broncos defensive coordinator Wade Phillips and New Orleans
defensive coordinator Steve Sidwell.
</P>
<P>
   Elway wanted Shanahan. Bowlen thought Shanahan would jump at the
opportunity, but Shanahan learned his lesson with the Raiders _ he
wanted control.
</P>
<P>
   When Phillips was announced as the new head coach, the news
conference had been called to introduce Shanahan. According to
sources on the team at the time, Bowlen tried to low-ball Shanahan,
thinking he would accept, but Shanahan refused unless he got
control.
</P>
<P>
   Bowlen went to Phillips and, in essence, said, ``Wade, how would
you like to be head coach?'' Phillips didn't have to get full
control, so he was hired.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said last week he thinks Shanahan would have taken the
job if the public relations wouldn't have been so bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, Mike would have been hired when I was fired, but
there was too much public opinion that would have made it almost
impossible for him to do it,'' Reeves said. ``I think two years
later was a much better situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Two seasons later _ after the Broncos missed the playoffs and
the 49ers won the Super bowl _ Bowlen fired Phillips and gave
Shanahan a seven-year contract and total control.
</P>
<P>
   Until last week when Reeves blasted Shanahan and Elway, all
three said the problems were behind them. They talked during the
offseason at Augusta Country Club. When Reeves underwent heart
surgery late this season, Shanahan sent him a get-well card, and
Elway made a donation to his foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it (the firing) hurt his family,'' Elway said.
``But there were a lot of people hurt in the whole situation. It
wasn't just us three.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that it was a business relationship, and
Mr. Bowlen decided to make a move. The thing I regret is that it
got to that point. It's too bad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
