<HEADER>
A8348 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     01-26 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MIAMI _ Each was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Reeves was too dictatorial and too much of a control freak.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Shanahan was a tad too cerebral for his own good, which
rendered him unable to show total deference to the authority of the
boss.
</P>
<P>
   And John Elway had an undisciplined streak, never mind a bratty
side and a penchant for misreading defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Each was also right, though.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, as the head coach, clearly had a right to have his
orders followed.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan possessed the more innovative offensive mind and
sharper instincts regarding Elway's needs.
</P>
<P>
   Elway, a non-traditional talent, needed a certain amount of
wiggle room to set free the genius within.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, Shanahan and Elway forged a good-enough partnership with
the Broncos to win three AFC championships and the corresponding
Super Bowl berths. They were never good enough together, however,
to go the next step and win the big game, which eventually set the
pot to boiling. Shanahan took the fall first at Reeves' hands, and
Reeves himself went down a year later in what came close to being a
me-or-him ultimatum from Elway, then as now Shanahan's staunchest
ally.
</P>
<P>
   We've been assured by all parties the hatchet has been buried.
It hasn't been, of course, but presumably only nice, politically
correct utterances will follow for the rest of this Super Bowl
week, no matter how relentlessly we prod and poke the three of them
with our pencils and microphones.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves already has apologized for going public with ``the
truth'' about what happened among the head coach, offensive
coordinator and superstar quarterback many years ago in Denver,
where to be of the Broncos family is to reside in a fishbowl inside
a glass house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I apologize for ever having brought it up, or having it affect
anyone,'' Reeves said. ``All I was doing was answering a question.
I'm not smart enough to have a strategy for anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan, for his part, has backed off on his implications that
Reeves, once his ``best friend,'' was a revisionist historian of
the first rank, if not an out-and-out fibber.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad it's over,'' Shanahan said.
</P>
<P>
   Over? Whoa, Mike, this thing is hardly over. It will remain the
underlying issue of Super Bowl XXXIII right on through the final
gun, no matter which side laughs last on the turf at Pro Player
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 33 jillion stories the 33 Super Bowls have generated
across a third of a century, this no-love-lost triangle stands out
for being unique, exceeding even the hype. Never before has The
Ultimate Game produced such a spicy, tantalizing entanglement,
where one team's coach once fired the other team's coach, only to
be brought down by the quarterback he must now try to beat.
</P>
<P>
   And we're supposed to believe each side wishes only the very
best for the other? Please.
</P>
<P>
   After his near misses in Denver, Reeves wants that ring any way
he can get it, particularly since Shanahan and Elway already have
theirs. But for him to secure same at the Broncos' expense, leading
a once-destitute Atlanta franchise that had done nothing of note
before his arrival, would be the ultimate of vindications, one
almost too rich to digest for a recovering heart patient.
</P>
<P>
   Although Reeves may never say, ``Take that,'' he wants to be
able to enjoy thinking it throughout the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   For Elway, in turn, to put a wrap on his career as a repeat
champion at the expense of a coach who had come to, he said, make
his life ``hell,'' would provide an ideal segue into a fully
satisfying retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides sincerely want to beat the other's brains out Sunday.
The more lopsided and embarrassing the outcome, the better. A
lingering score remains to be settled. That's just a fact, never
mind the polite platitudes and hollow homages we can count on
hearing repeatedly over the next several days.
</P>
<P>
   Bypass surgery gave Reeves a more mellow and appreciative life
view. He will now occasionally stop to smell the flowers and
dutifully count his blessings. It did not, however, make him any
less human, which is why he couldn't bite his tongue or stuff a
sock in his mouth last week.
</P>
<P>
   Despite fully realizing how radioactive the fallout from his
remarks would be, Reeves had to unburden himself because he still
feels wronged and because, deep down, he still sees Elway as an
ungrateful prima donna and Shanahan, the erstwhile prodigal son he
had kindly welcomed back from the evil Al Davis' clutches, as a
mutinous turncoat.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Shanahan and Elway see Reeves as hardheaded and
heavy-handed.
</P>
<P>
   This may no longer be a war of words, but it definitely remains
a real war.
</P>
<P>
   Which seems good for the Super Bowl. Too much of the game's
drama is of the manufactured variety. Reeves-Shanahan-Elway is the
real deal, darn near Jerry Springer material.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
