<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS REJECT PROPOSAL TO END CLINTON TRIAL WITHOUT
WITNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with adjournment, summarize
day's events, vote on witnesses skedded for Tuesday; Pickup 5th
graf pvs, Leiberman described ...; SUBS 2nd graf in 2nd take, Other
than ..., to UPDATE with prosecutors leaning toward calling
Jordan.) 
 (See related stories: IMPEACH-PUBLIC, IMPEACH-CONVICT,
IMPEACH-SESSIONS, IMPEACH-LEWINSKY, IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-SCENE,
IMPEACH-DEFENSE) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(fe) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL and ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As a weary Senate entered the third week of
impeachment proceedings, Republicans in a party meeting Monday
rejected a Democratic-backed proposal that would have ended the
trial against President Clinton without calling any witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, hoping to defuse a growing opposition to witnesses,
Senate Republicans worked behind the scenes in hallways and
hideaway offices throughout the day to persuade House Republican
prosecutors to draw up a modest witness list. The maneuvering came
hours before the Senate went into closed session Monday night and
debated for four hours a Democratic motion to flatly dismiss the
charges against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   With that motion given little chance of succeeding, the Senate
also will consider on Tuesday whether to allow witnesses to be
deposed. The outcome of that vote is uncertain. Trying to help
House prosecutors win the right to continue their case, Republican
senators advised them to put together a list small enough to keep
wavering Republicans from joining Democrats to form a majority
against witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, spurred by the partisan strife set off by the
House prosecutors' questioning of Monica Lewinsky, Sens. Slade
Gorton, R-Wash., and Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., offered both
parties a proposal. They suggested that the votes on dismissal and
witnesses be skipped and that the trial move to closing debate,
with a vote on articles of impeachment on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman described the plan as a ``mutual withdrawal of
forces'' under which Democrats would drop the effort to dismiss the
case outright and Republicans would not push for witnesses. It was
presented to the Democrats and Republicans at separate caucuses
Monday morning, and Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the minority
leader, announced that Democrats could support the plan.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the Republican caucus was still under way, John
Czwartacki, the spokesman for Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the
majority leader, said the idea had been ``summarily rejected.''
Republicans said that their caucus was divided, with some people
exhausted and leery of witnesses but others still wanting to give
the House prosecutors the right to move forward with their case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard for me to envision as a trier of fact who has taken
an oath, judging this case, without seeing the most important
witness or witnesses,'' said Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio. Sen. Tim
Hutchinson, R-Ark., said there was a ``difference of opinion''
among Republicans over the need for witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody would like this thing to end, and they hate to think
of a couple of more weeks of depositions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After rejecting the offer, Senate Republicans summoned some of
the House managers to the Capitol to winnow the prosecutors' list
of half a dozen witnesses down to two or three, in hopes that such
a list could win a majority vote later this week, perhaps even
winning some Democratic support.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans were also examining a plan for the end of the
trial under which the Senate could vote to find that Clinton had
committed the offenses charged in the two articles of impeachment,
but not actually remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Senate is thought to have no chance of assembling the
67 votes to convict Clinton, some Republicans believe this would
amount to a stringent form of censure. It would take only 51 votes
for the finding of facts _ meaning that it could be muscled through
by the Republican majority. The Democrats say the plan is
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   To keep pressure on the White House, Lott and nine other
senators submitted 10 written questions to President Clinton,
taking advantage of an opening that the White House had given them
and then retracted on Saturday. They asked that he respond ``in
writing and under oath'' to the questions, which began by asking if
everything the president had testified to in the case brought by
Paula Jones was true.
</P>
<P>
   ``If not,'' the question continued, ``what did you testify to
that you now believe is not truthful? Please begin your answer with
a yes or no.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the White House press secretary, said neither
Clinton nor his lawyers would respond to the questions, which he
said violated the bipartisan deal on trial procedures. ``I'd
suggest this has more to do with playing politics than with trying
to bring this to a fair and expeditious conclusion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the two parties once again parted ways, efforts
persisted to search for a bipartisan solution. Sen. Phil Gramm,
R-Texas, called Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., seeking support
for a two-person witness list and a date certain to end the trial.
After consulting Daschle, Kennedy relayed the message that the
Democrats were standing firm against witnesses, according to one
Democratic official.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One attempt at negotiation took place openly in front of a
cluster of reporters when Max Baucus, D-Mont., stopped abruptly in
the Senate's subway to ask Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, if the
Republicans had embraced the plan to move to the end of the trial.
``Could you think of an element that might help?'' Baucus asked.
</P>
<P>
   Grassley wondered in return whether Democratic opposition to
witnesses would extend to ``even a very circumscribed form for
witnesses, depositions, just a short period of time?'' Baucus said
it probably would, and the two men went their separate ways.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Facing a deadline of Tuesday to submit their witness list to the
Senate, the House managers _ a day after interviewing Ms. Lewinsky
_ began the day badly divided over how to proceed. Bowing to the
Senate's reluctance to call a large number of witnesses, some of
the prosecutors were willing to cull their list down to two or
three people, including Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But others continued to insist they needed to go beyond Ms.
Lewinsky and call a core group of five witnesses, to make their
case, including the White House aides and advisers Betty Currie,
Vernon Jordan, John Podesta, Sidney Blumenthal. There was also
interest in Clinton's former political consultant, Dick Morris.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate is over who should be added and whether they'd be
accepted by the Senate,'' Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., one of the
13 House prosecutors said after they held a midday meeting. ``We
believe in our case and we want a way to present it, and we're
going to keep arguing that point to the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as the meeting was ending, some of the prosecutors,
including Hutchinson and Rep. Lindsey Graham of South Carolina,
were summoned to a Capitol office by a small group of Senate
Republicans, including Sen. Arlen Specter, a Pennsylvania
Republican, to discuss the witness issue.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &UR; BC-IMPEACH-RDP-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WASHINGTON: witness issue. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Monday night, the four prosecutors who will make the case for
witnesses on Tuesday _ Hutchinson, James Rogan of California, Ed
Bryant of Tennessee and Bill McCollum of Florida _ were paring down
the list, and one Republican aide said there would probably be no
more than three names submitted to the Senate. Even earlier in the
day Rogan had signaled that they would move in this direction.
``We've got to prioritize and get down to a bare minimum and not
run the risk of getting zero witnesses because we put on one too
many,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Ms. Lewinsky, it was not certain which witnesses the
prosecutors would settle on. Monday night, the managers were
leaning toward Jordan and away from Ms. Currie. They were also
looking at one of the two White House aides, either Podesta or
Blumenthal. They were to meet again on Tuesday before the trial
begins.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors did win one victory on Monday. Ruling a day
after the prosecutors interviewed Ms. Lewinsky, Chief Justice
William H. Rehnquist rejected an effort by Sen. Tom Harkin, an Iowa
Democrat, to halt such interviews until after the Senate votes on
witnesses. In a letter to Harkin, the justice said, ``It is quite
debatable whether merely interviewing a witness'' violated the
bipartisan agreement establishing the vote on witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate went into closed session Monday night to debate the
motion by Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., to dismiss the trial. But the
pair of votes on that motion and on witnesses are not expected
until late Tuesday night or Wednesday. Lott said confidently that
the Republicans who control the chamber 55-45 ``have the votes'' to
block dismissal of the case.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And suggesting that even some Democrats might oppose dismissal,
Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., tried unsuccessfully to have the
vote on stopping the case, separated into two votes, one for each
article of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It was less certain how the Senate will vote on witnesses, a
motion that requires a simple majority of 51 votes to pass or fail.
Several Republicans have expressed unease at extending the trial by
calling the principals in the case. But it was not clear how many
of them would vote with Democrats against witnesses. If all 45
Democrats hold together to oppose witnesses, then six Republicans
are needed to prevent testimony. And some of the wavering lawmakers
are likely to be swayed by the scope of the House witness list.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody can show me that this will change the dynamics of
the trial,'' said Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., ``that's a different
story. I don't believe that's going to happen. But I haven't closed
my mind totally yet.'' He said a number of Republicans shared his
concern.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were also exploring whether they could end the trial
by voting on a statement of facts on each of the articles of
impeachment and then separately on the articles themselves. That
would allow senators to make a statement that Clinton had committed
perjury and obstructed justice as the House charged, but not to
remove him from office. Democrats said they would oppose such a
plan as unconstitutional.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
