<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8351 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT &LR;      01-26 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING CHANGE? KNICKS WON'T HEAR OF IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ The sermon topic Monday was the maligned
Patrick Ewing, as a passionate Jeff Van Gundy all but cited
Scripture and verse in an effort to save those who have wondered if
it is time to phase out the Knicks' aging superstar.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy was stomping out what he called Ewing
``misperceptions.'' When the Knicks' coach was asked if Ewing would
be a misfit for the sleeker Latrell Sprewell Knicks, or if his role
would be diminished, Van Gundy's face turned as sour as curdled
milk.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Ewing's impact would be downgraded on a team that
will rely less on the relic post-up offense and more on the
drive-and-kick abilities of Sprewell and Allan Houston, Van Gundy's
eyes rolled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most often discussed and misperceived issue that surrounds
our team is that Patrick has to totally change the way he plays,''
Van Gundy said after his team's morning practice session at
SUNY-Purchase. ``We need Patrick to play well for us to be
successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he going to take a back seat? There's no way he's going to
take a lesser role. Now, are we going to get the ball to him in
different spots? Maybe. When the ball is driven to the basket, he's
pulling out to get a 15-footer if it comes. It's unbelievable how
who shoots consumes everyone's mind. I don't understand the
obsession.''
</P>
<P>
   There are reasons for the fixation on Ewing. For 13 seasons he
has stood as a titleless fixture with hands raised in the paint. In
that time, he has neither opened himself up to the public nor
handed out multiple excuses.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing has rarely exhibited the verbal leadership his teammates
have privately craved and has not created himself as a sympathetic
figure. Mostly, Ewing has just smiled at his detractors and moved
on.
</P>
<P>
   But is there substance to the argument that Ewing will have to
change? Can Ewing adjust and tweak his game in order to blend in
with the Knicks' new approach?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to play my role,'' Ewing said. ``Whatever they
ask me to do, that's what I'm going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounds selfless and promising. It sounds as if Ewing, at age
36, is willing to disperse the weight of the offense as his career
inches toward the two-minute mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, he's not going to be the same guy he was at 27 or 26,
but he still brings a lot to the table,'' Herb Williams said.
``He's one of the 50 greatest player ever, and he's still going to
be Patrick. He can't change that after 13 years.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not Ewing's nature to fade into the background. And if
healthy, he won't. Van Gundy still expects Ewing to be a force, but
in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy is leaning on Ewing to rebound more on the offensive
boards, limit his turnovers and become the trailer in transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 13 years, I've been letting someone else do that,'' Ewing
said. ``I've been the one running down the court first.''
</P>
<P>
   In reality, it may not matter if Ewing can adjust. He has played
in only four games since he came tumbling down on his shooting
wrist in December 1997. About a week before training camp began,
Ewing talked about his wrist, a subject he has since shrugged off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, I'll get the strength and everything back,'' Ewing
said. ``It feels fine, or as fine as it can be. It's going to take
a year and a half before it feels the way it was before it was
injured.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the speculation about Ewing's ability to adapt to the
talent around him, no one knows when or if he will return to his
familiar form.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' said Van Gundy, expressing some concern. ``One
thing, don't underestimate the heart of a great player. He knows he
has a lot to do to be able to come back from a serious injury like
that. I would never underestimate that. But to say definitively
that I know he's healthy and he's got what he had before he left, I
don't think we'll know that before we see him play for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing does remain: Ewing's stubborn streak. Although Van
Gundy would prefer to rest Ewing for a game here and there during a
packed stretch of four games in five nights, Ewing said: ``Games
off? I don't know about that.''
</P>
<P>
   From the sideline, Van Gundy has observed Ewing for almost 10
years. He wonders why so much is made of his shot attempts when
they have decreased over the last two seasons. He can't fathom
questions about Ewing's defensive rebounding when he averages more
than 10 a game.
</P>
<P>
   The coach's exasperation was noted as he passed a man in the
stairwell and shouted: ``Patrick rebounds! Patrick Ewing
rebounds!''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Van Gundy's cathartic defense of Ewing grows out
of the irrationally loyal side of a head coach who knows his star
is partly responsible for his rise. In other ways, he was just
trying to make an emphatic point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick won't say this, and I know it's going to be, `There
goes Van Gundy protecting Patrick,''' Van Gundy said. ``But just
please, someone watch the game.''
</P>
<P>
   People did watch last season. And many saw a Ewingless Knicks
team that seemed liberated. They watched Houston develop his
aggressive side, and glimpsed the old all-star l/iving within Larry
Johnson. Suddenly, the Knicks were less plodding and more poetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Esthetically, I would agree,'' Van Gundy said. ``It was more
free-flowing. It was pretty, but we shot a lesser percentage and
scored less points.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Van Gundy did discover a Knicks team that could
drive-and-kick and be effective with that style. Now, with Ewing,
that something new will be incorporated with something old.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look over the last eight or nine years, primarily we
were a post-up team,'' Van Gundy said. ``Now, we want to have five
equal parts: transition, drive-and-kick, pick-and-roll, post-up and
second shots.''
</P>
<P>
   The diverse Knicks. Now that's different. So far, Ewing has not
resisted the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still an adjustment process, but we're still having
fun,'' Ewing said. ``I think we have great talent. On paper, we
have a lot of talent. We just have to put it together and start
playing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
