<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAME DATE, DIFFERENT NAME 
ROLLAND SMITH'S BACK EAST 
BUSTLING BARRISTERS 
PHOTO OP AT IVANA'S
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``You know why it was so hard to find a chairman?''
Tim Zagat, the restaurant-guide publisher, asked. ``Fran insisted
she find somebody with the same birth date as she had.''
</P>
<P>
   Fran is Fran Reiter, the former deputy mayor-turned-president of
the New York City Convention and Visitors Bureau. And the new
chairman will be Zagat himself, who, like Ms. Reiter, was born on
May 13.
</P>
<P>
   That was not his main qualification, of course. He had become
closely identified with a program that coordinated the low-price
lunches many restaurants offered during the 1992 Democratic
National Convention ($19.92 in 1992, $19.93 in 1993 and so on).
That program merged with the Convention and Visitors Bureau last
year.
</P>
<P>
   His first move as chairman will be to change the name of the
organization to NY &AMP; Co. and to broaden its reach beyond tourism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same message you give to tourists about being safer,
cleaner and more fun are messages you can give to businesses
contemplating coming here,'' Zagat said. Sounding as if he was
reciting a four-star review of Ms. Reiter's former boss, he added,
``The mayor has given us an easier job of selling the city. Safety
and cleanliness go a long way to assuaging criticisms people had.''
</P>
<P>
   Heading East
</P>
<P>
   Rolland Smith, who was an anchor on WCBS-TV and WWOR-TV before
he left for similar on-camera duty in San Diego, is switching
coasts again. Smith has joined the Regional News Network, which
provides newscasts seen on cable systems in the New York region.
The studios are 87 miles from Manhattan, in Kingston, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   No problem, said Smith, who will anchor three nightly newscasts
from Kingston. ``Where you are based, it really doesn't matter
these days. You can get and disseminate information from almost
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Musical Lawyers
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Duff has new lawyers in her custody fight against her
former husband, the Revlon titan Ronald Perelman.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, lawyers for another former Perelman wife, the gossip
reporter Claudia Cohen, complained of conflict of interest. The
issue: that Ms. Duff's lawyers _ Ken Warner and Rita Warner _ had
represented Ms. Cohen briefly in 1995 and '96.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Warner called the complaint ``a tactical ploy'' that
benefited Perelman.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Franklin Weisberg said the Warners could not
continue on Ms. Duff's team. (Ms. Cohen did not return a call for
comment.)
</P>
<P>
   Then Ms. Duff discharged her other lawyer, William Beslow. Her
spokesman issued a statement saying that Beslow had had only ``a
limited role'' in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Duff's next move was to hire three other lawyers _ Harriet
Cohen, Patricia Hennessey and Bonnie Rabin. On Monday, Weisberg
adjourned the proceedings until Feb. 8 so they could familiarize
themselves with the case.
</P>
<P>
   Ivana at Home
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Welcome to my home,'' a line on Ivana Trump's new
magazine said, and that was exactly what she did Monday. More than
20 photographers stood on the thick red carpet and took picture
after picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``How to look great in photos,'' another line on the cover
promised. She kept smiling as flash after blinding flash lit the
room for a fraction of a second in her town house on the Upper East
Side .
</P>
<P>
   It did not seem to matter that her name is not on the masthead
of Ivana's Living in Style magazine, which she said will be
distributed by the company that publishes the supermarket tabloid
The Globe. Between facing the photographers and sipping champagne,
Ms. Trump said that being involved with a magazine was easier than
appearing on cable-television shopping channels. ``I can be on the
air nine hours a day, and have to talk all that time,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
