<HEADER>
A8361 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-PHILLIPS-COLUMN-L     01-26 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PHILLIPS-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO FANTASTIC FINISH HERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someday, perhaps, the Kings and Mighty Ducks will meet in a
postseason series that will ignite their neighborhood rivalry and
generate hockey interest in an area that usually yawns at the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, perhaps, but not this season.
</P>
<P>
   As the two locals prepare to resume play following the All-Star
break, the Ducks are lodged in one of the Western Conference's
nether playoff berths, and the Kings are in danger of falling out
of the race altogether.
</P>
<P>
   One of the two locals probably will make the playoffs but not
both, and neither team's postseason prospects create much reason
for excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they have been virtually free of major injuries,
even though Paul Kariya leads the NHL in scoring, and even though
Teemu Selanne is poised for a strong second half, the Mighty Ducks
are two games below .500.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Kings, they've suffered one major injury after
another, are weeks from regaining key winger Glen Murray, and begin
a trip Wednesday in Dallas that could deepen the hole they've dug
for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers tell a gloomy tale: The Kings are 0-12 when trailing
after one period, 8-13-3 at home, have no one other than Luc
Robitaille and Murray with more than eight goals, and are 3-7-4
this year when they are tied after the second period. This dismal
legacy seems far too great for them to overcome in a 37-game sprint
to the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks, at least, appear to have an immediate upside in the
double-threat of Kariya and Selanne, but who can predict? The only
thing predictable about the two Southern California teams in recent
years has been their unpredictability.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Ducks had 85 points and made the playoffs,
the Kings had 67 and missed. Last year, the Kings had 87 points and
made the playoffs, the Ducks had 65 and missed. This year, the
teams have flip-flopped once again.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is clear, though: Another half-season of hockey has
passed and both teams remain several notches below where they need
to be to raise any hopes of contention for a Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   __ Eye for an eye: Florida's Dino Ciccarelli was irate last week
after receiving a two-game suspension from the NHL for slashing
Buffalo's Jason Woolley, who was uninjured on the play.
</P>
<P>
   What angered Ciccarelli was that the Sabres' Alexei Zhitnik did
not receive discipline for a cross check that left his left eye
almost entirely shut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand the logic here,'' Ciccarelli said. ``My eye
is three-quarters closed because some guy cross checks me in the
head, and they don't do anything. They're acting like this was
premeditated and I did it intentionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said I was trying to (retaliate) for my eye, but Jason
Woolley would be the last guy I'd try to hurt. If I wanted to get
anybody back, I would have got the guy that almost cut my eyeball
open.''
</P>
<P>
   Ciccarelli also was angry because he says referee Don Van
Massenhoven asked him for a hockey stick after the game, and upon
receiving it, Ciccarelli says Van Massenhoven promised he would not
report the slash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The referee wants hockey sticks,'' Ciccarelli said. ``He said,
`Don't worry, they won't review this. I know you didn't mean to
hurt him. It was an accident and we know he's not hurt. We're not
going to report this, but can I have one of your hockey sticks?' So
I signed a hockey stick for him. Is that unbelievable?''
</P>
<P>
   __ Chelios for sale?: The New York Post reported that Chicago is
preparing to shop veteran defenseman Chris Chelios to the highest
bidder, a report Blackhawks management denied. Chelios, 37,
insisted he wants to remain with the lowly Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swear on the heads of my four kids that I have no interest
in being traded,'' Chelios said. ``As bad as things are going here,
I don't want to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the kind of player who asks to be traded. When things
turn around here, I want to be leading the charge. I want to stay
in Chicago. I don't know how to put it any simpler. Things aren't
going good now, but I'm not a quitter. I'm going to fight through
this with these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia, Detroit and Phoenix are among the teams believed
to have interest if the Blackhawks decide to trade Chelios.
</P>
<P>
   __ Demanding coach: Though the Dallas Stars have the NHL's best
record, the players aren't exactly wild about coach Ken Hitchcock's
tactics. Last week, after a loss to Vancouver, Hitchcock skated his
players through 20 punishing minutes of starts and stops, saying he
did so because he felt the team was ``gliding'' into the All-Star
break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what kind of message he wants,'' veteran Guy
Carbonneau said. ``If it's because he's mad at us, I don't know if
the timing was good. The last I looked, we're still in first place,
and there's not much that we don't do right.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Mike Modano: ``I'd hate to see it if we were 7-27.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Loose pucks: Vancouver GM Brian Burke got rid of Pavel Bure
one week and coach Mike Keenan the next. You can almost see a giant
headache vacating Burke's cranium. . . . New Jersey's Scott Stevens
apologized to San Jose's Brantt Myhres for recent comments about
the latter's bout with alcoholism. Nonetheless, Stevens was booed
every time he touched the puck during a recent visit to San Jose,
and during a celebrity look-alikes segment on the scoreboard,
Stevens' photo was displayed next to a picture of the rear end of a
horse. . . . Former Detroit defenseman Vladimir Konstantinov, whose
career was ruined when he suffered massive head injuries in a
limousine accident after the Red Wings won the Stanley Cup in 1997,
is not expected to accompany his former teammates Thursday when
they visit the White House. ``I think his understanding of the
event is very limited,'' said Konstantinov's wife, Irina. ``He
can't put together why he is in the White House. It's not like when
he was on the ice in Washington after they won the Cup last spring,
he understood what was going on then because he recognized the
experience.'' &QL; 
BLUE LINES
</P>
<P>
   __ Any takers?: How badly does Philadelphia GM Bob Clarke want
to unload disappointing center Alexandre Daigle and his $1.9
million salary?
</P>
<P>
   ``We sent a fax out to all the teams to see if there was any
interest in him and a few teams called,'' Clarke said. ``I wouldn't
say there's anything imminent right now. But if we can get somebody
back that can help us, we'll trade him.''
</P>
<P>
   Kings GM Dave Taylor denied reports of a deal that would send
struggling defenseman Steve Duchesne to Philadelphia for Daigle, a
one-time first overall draft choice and a one-time boyfriend of
``Baywatch'' 's Pamela Lee.!dlim!You gotta have heart!dlim!
</P>
<P>
   Red Wings legend Ted Lindsay was quoted as saying that if Sergei
Fedorov had half the heart of teammate Steve Yzerman, he'd be the
best player in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Fedorov replied: ``Steve Yzerman should keep his heart. I've got
my own. And I've got one that's as big as anyone in this room.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
