<HEADER>
A8362 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-1STLD-W     01-26 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVILITY REIGNS, EVEN AS BIPARTISAN ENDGAME ELUDES SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs last graf for updating) (See related stories: IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-PUBLIC, IMPEACH-CONVICT,
IMPEACH-SESSIONS, IMPEACH-LEWINSKY, IMPEACH-TRIAL,
IMPEACH-DEFENSE) 
(nk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Upstairs, the impeachment trial was going through
serial delays as the Senate once more struggled to hold off
partisan meltdown. But downstairs, at least, at the head of an
escalator, the senior senator from Iowa politely yielded basement
debating time to the senior senator from Montana.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did your caucus conclude?'' asked Max Baucus, D-Mont., of
Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, when his colleague recognized him for an
impromptu two-lawmaker debate on a free fall of a day in President
Clinton's impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my understanding,'' replied Grassley over the escalator
hum, ``that there's something going on between some very senior
respected senators on both sides that could bring something
about.''
</P>
<P>
   It was as if Webster's timeless question of ``Neighbor, how
stands the Union?'' were being put once more in the very bowels of
the Senate as the president's fate was being settled. The jury was
not yet out, but rather out and about, trying to figure out what
was going on as they met in hallway encounters.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of tourists, staffers and reporters gathered around the
two, as they discussed witnesses and other issues in the day's
private leadership attempt at striking a deal to speed the trial to
conclusion. If nothing else the exchange demonstrated the senators'
civility had hardly eroded to the levels of the House impeachment
debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't your concern that you want to make sure this doesn't go
on for a long time?'' Grassley politely asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right,'' responded Baucus as other pedestrians brushed past to
the Capitol's underground tunnels and lunchrooms. ``And, basically,
I'm trying to find a way to let people on your side who feel they
have to cast at least one vote to satisfy certain political
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange was a microcosm of the caucus struggles through
much of the day centering on the question of ending the trial
fairly without yielding the House Republican managers a
time-consuming license to search for fresh witness evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't forget we're supposed to be running the show, not the
lawyers,'' Grassley stressed, yielding back the basement corridor
floor to his colleague.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our hope,'' replied Baucus with evident doubt, and the
two parted in search of the latest word on their leaders'
differences.
</P>
<P>
   In the corridors outside the caucuses, senators hurriedly passed
to and fro. The high hope in the Democrats' morning sound bites
fell flat by midday. But fresh attempts at reviving a deal were
quickly under way, driven by constitutional duty but also more
mundane factors as time consumption and the impatience of
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the chamber, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist was being
treated to the Senate's ultimate fallback tactic _ a slow quorum
roll call of the members to mark time while assorted negotiations
were under way off the floor. Rehnquist obviously came prepared. He
calmly became engrossed in some private reading matter as the clerk
slowly, ever so slowly, intoned each senator's name in a dirge-like
ritual of time killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to the operations of the United States Senate, Mr.
Chief Justice,'' majority leader Trent Lott of Mississippi
smilingly apologized as the Senate went through start-and-stop
motions and trial debate finally arrived, nearly two hours late.
</P>
<P>
   The senators settled in. A considerate John McCain of Arizona
got a backslap of gratitude when he jerry-built a footrest to ease
the infirmity of his fellow Republican, Jesse Helms of North
Carolina. The Senate mood seemed to be relaxed, for all the
off-the-floor contention. Lott genially worked the Democratic side
of the floor, then nonchalantly hand-edited a word in a procedural
resolution to end a complaint and get the trial back on track.
</P>
<P>
   For two hours the Senate court sat silent, still far from their
showdown impeachment votes, but listening to debate by the
prosecution and defense on a proposed preliminary dismissal of the
charges against the  &QR; 
president.
</P>
<P>
   This seemed certain to fail in a vote expected in a day or two,
after the conclusion of the Senate's own private deliberations. But
after the long day of political caucussing and confusion, this
debate, even if facing a foregone conclusion, suddenly brought the
Senate back to the gravity of the case to banish the president.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors flatly termed Clinton a ``criminal'' and pleaded
with the Senate not to seek an easy way out by dismissal. ``You'll
guarantee contention,'' warned Rep. Henry Hyde of Illinois, the
chief prosecutor. ``You'll never get it behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   At nightfall, there came a simple, stark reminder of the
enormous stakes for the nation. The 100-member court was sealed in
the Senate to begin its own closed debate on the merits of the
proposal to end the trial now rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a little while for all of us to adjust our ears to a
forum without amplification,'' Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman, D-Conn.,,
said afterward of a four-hour session in which the galleries were
empty and the floor microphones turned off as the senators
experienced jury-like isolation. He said Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va.,
had told the closed gathering, ``This is the way it was 30 years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ```I was there!''' responded Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., the South
Carolina Republican with the longevity record, Lieberman said,
adding, ``Once again in this ordeal, we've been through something
together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
