<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCANDAL-SYDNEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC OFFICIALS TO SCRUTINIZE SYDNEY BID
</HEADLINE>
   (See also OLY-SCANDAL, EDIT-OLY-SAMARANCH) 
(nk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The International Olympic Committee will
send one of its vice presidents, Jacques Rogge, and its director
general, Francois Carrard, here next month to investigate the offer
of $70,000 in sports aid that was made to committee members from
Africa by a key figure of the Sydney bidding team on the eve of the
vote for the 2000 Summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, Australian Olympic officials denied that Sydney
was now under the same level of scrutiny as Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ``My overall impression is that the IOC is interested in tying
up any loose ends,'' said Sandy Hollway, the chief executive
officer of the Sydney Organizing Committee, which still needs to
raise $139 million to balance its $442 million sponsorship goal.
``There is no suggestion I'm aware of that Sydney did anything in
the same league as Salt Lake City.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollway said he had been reassured by Kevan Gosper, an IOC vice
president from Australia, that the visit of the Olympic envoys did
not represent a full-blown inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The international committee has said that all cities that had
bid for the 1996 through 2006 Olympics will be asked to provide
information about irregularities in the process. But Sydney has
already provided some information and, according to IOC President
Juan Antonio Samaranch, Carrard and Rogge are visiting ``to know
what exactly is going on and what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch expressed surprise at the promised payments and their
timing and said that if Rogge and Carrard found wrongdoing, a wider
investigation would be started. Rogge, as chairman of the
coordination commission for the 2000 Games, has visited Sydney
frequently.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, John Coates, president of the Australian Olympic
Committee, released documents that showed he had offered $35,000
each to IOC members Charles Mukora of Kenya and Maj. Gen. Francis
Nyangweso of Uganda for sports programs in their countries. The
offer was made on Sept. 22, 1993, at a Monaco hotel. The next day
Sydney defeated Beijing, 45-43, on the final ballot. The voting was
by secret ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Coates has acknowledged that he made the final-hour offers,
which included payments staggered over seven years, because he felt
Sydney's support was faltering in Africa. But he said the
inducements, which were made in the name of the Australian Olympic
Committee, did not constitute bribery or break IOC rules because
they were between national Olympic committees and not individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Australian officials have argued that the payments were an
extension of an audited program that had already committed about
$1.2 million to 11 African nations for their athletes to train in
the Australian capital of Canberra.
</P>
<P>
   IOC regulations do not prohibit sports exchanges between
national Olympic committees, but the question is whether Mukora or
Nyangweso benefited personally from the payments. Mukora, president
of the Kenyan Olympic Committee, is one of the six IOC members who
were expelled on Sunday. In its report on the Salt Lake City
inquiry, the IOC commission concluded that Mukora accepted direct
payments totaling $34,650 ``for his personal benefit.'' Mukora
maintained that the payments were for sports activities in Kenya
and that the money was put into a trust, but the committee
concluded that the trust benefited Mukora.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 0025EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8366 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-COL-GRAFFITI-NYT &LR;      01-26 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-COL-GRAFFITI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: NEW VANDALS SCRATCHING UP THE SUBWAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You have to admire New York City Transit for the
speed it generally shows in covering up graffiti whenever it pops
up on buses and subway trains. It almost makes one wish that he had
the agency's paint concession.
</P>
<P>
   Around New Year's Day, for example, some mindless vandal who no
doubt refers to himself as an urban artiste spray-painted an
indecipherable scrawl on every column of the 86th Street station on
the No. 1 line. It was hideous. But within a few days, just as the
transit agency's rules require, the mess was wiped away with a
fresh coat of blue paint.
</P>
<P>
   What this suggests, of course, is that this subway defiler and
his many colleagues never disappeared. But they have been kept in
check, and some may have been permanently discouraged, by the
official policy of erasing their gibberish almost as soon as it
appears.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 10 years have passed since the last graffiti-covered
train was taken out of service. To give you an idea of the
importance of that final journey, the agency's Web site
(http://www.mta.nyc.ny.us) lists the moment _ May 12, 1989, on the
C line _ as a ``key event'' in New York subway history, along with
the debut of the token in 1953 and the demise of the Third Avenue
el in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, the same upbeat words cannot be written about the form of
vandalism that replaced graffiti as the bane of the subway system.
Transit officials have not only been unable to stop it, but many
riders are also convinced that the problem is worse than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Some call it scratchiti, a word that lends it an air of
near-dignity it hardly deserves. It is the etching of nicknames
into subway-car windows and walls, usually by teen-agers armed with
keys, coins, razor blades and, if you can believe this, super-sharp
rocks formed from lava, to be found in many hardware stores.
</P>
<P>
   The window scratchings are about as brainless as you can get.
Nobody pretends that they qualify as art, not even the likes of
Norman Mailer, who used to celebrate graffiti (and who was rarely
to be found on the IRT).
</P>
<P>
   True, subway riders are not as menaced by the etched graffiti as
they were by heavy sprays of black paint. Many say in interviews
that they have come to ignore it. But just as many say that it
sometimes makes them feel as if no one is in control.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the system's 5,800-plus cars are scratched up. Many
have not a single unscarred window. To this daily rider, it came as
a jolt while watching ``You've Got Mail,'' a cinematic love poem to
New York, to see Meg Ryan in a car free of blemishes.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Rappaport, coordinator for the riders advocacy group
known as the Straphangers Campaign, noticed some months ago that
the transit agency had stopped measuring scratched graffiti, while
continuing to rate subway litter and grime in its ``passenger
environment surveys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 100 percent every time,'' Rappaport said. ``Every car
had scratchiti. If you're not rating it, you're admitting that at
least for the short term there's not going to be any change.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, scratched subway windows have not received the intense
quality-of-life attention that City Hall has managed to give other
nuisances. Surely, with millions riding the subway each day, more
people are affected by this problem than were ever bothered by
squeegee men. Then again, the mayor is not to be found on the IRT
any more than Norman Mailer.
</P>
<P>
   But Joseph Hofmann is. Hofmann is the transit agency's subways
chief, and he says he has been meeting with police to figure out
how to crack down on scratchiti offenders, as they did with
graffiti spray painters. Beyond that, he said, he is looking to
protect the hundreds of new subway cars scheduled to join the
fleet, starting later this year.
</P>
<P>
   It would cost $65 million or more a year, a prohibitive expense,
to replace windows on a steady basis. Instead, Hofmann said, he
hopes to coat the windows of new cars with a polyester that might
not be scratchproof but would serve as a ``sacrificial barrier''
that protects the far more expensive glass.
</P>
<P>
   Solutions are not easy, Hofmann acknowledged. ``I don't think
it's something we're going to do overnight,'' he said. But he added
with determination, ``We're going to keep at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Encouraging words. Meanwhile, maybe some vandals will break
their arms and be knocked out of commission. If you think that
sounds mean-spirited, you, too, have not ridden the subways lately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
