<SLUG> BC-TIMES-CRITIC-GOURMET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMES CRITIC WILL BECOME EDITOR OF GOURMET
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ruth Reichl has resigned her post as restaurant
critic of The New York Times and will join Gourmet magazine as
editor in chief starting at the end of April. Ms. Reichl will
replace Gail Zweigenthal, who will leave the magazine after 34
years.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Reichl, who in the interest of fair reviewing and
nonpreferential treatment has been known to visit restaurants
cloaked in elaborate disguises, wrote a weekly review, along with
articles and essays, since joining the Times in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved every minute of this job,'' Ms. Reichl said. ``But it
is not a job that anyone can do forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Gourmet, which is owned by Conde Nast, a unit of Advance
Publications, has faced increasing competition in recent years as
general-interest magazines devote space to cuisine _ like Martha
Stewart's Living, which is published by Martha Stewart Living
Omnimedia _ and publishers have introduced new magazines devoted to
food, like Time Inc.'s Cooking Light, which has a circulation of
1.4 million. Gourmet has a circulation of about 880,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many other magazines taking little pieces of what
should be its franchises,'' Ms. Reichl said. ``I don't want to read
the best food writing in The New Yorker, or about the best kitchens
in House &AMP; Garden. I want to bring new voices to Gourmet.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1990 to 1993, Ms. Reichl was both restaurant critic and
food editor for The Los Angeles Times. She is the author of
``Tender at the Bone: Growing Up at the Table,'' a memoir published
by Random House last year.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lelyveld, the executive editor of the Times, said of Ms.
Reichl: ``She's a wonderful spirit and a wonderful critic and we
view this as a great loss. The search for her successor starts
today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
