<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8371 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     01-26 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS NEED ATTITUDE FIX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ Like besieged IOC president Juan Antonio
Samaranch, the beleaguered Lakers have at their fingertips the
answers to hard questions that first cropped up in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   All they have to do is pick up a hand mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Team magician Jerry West could produce an elite power forward
out of thin air tomorrow and it wouldn't improve the Lakers'
chances of winning an NBA title any more than the expulsion of a
few IOC members is going to purify the foul air at the top of the
Olympic hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is this: Whether you're the Lords of the Rings
or the lords-in-waiting for a championship ring, the gears of
change are yours alone to shift.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC's image is going to suffer until Samaranch takes
personal responsibility for the fact the fiefdom he runs has come
to stand for Interagents Of Corruption. The same goes for the
Lakers, who have to look inward if they're to put distance between
themselves and Utah.
</P>
<P>
   It says here the Olympic movement is worth saving as long as
Samaranch steps down. And the current Lakers roster is worth
preserving as long as everyone agrees to step it up.
</P>
<P>
   With the Lakers last spring, it wasn't the leadership at the top
that stank, it was the attitude in the trenches. You had Nick Van
Exel with his creaky knees and cranky attitude making vacation
plans, Shaquille O'Neal sneering more at his teammates than
opponents and everybody else snoozing and no one really digging in
to do the dirty work that wins games.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers grew so lackadaisical after their second-round
playoff dismantling of Seattle, it sometimes seemed as though coach
Del Harris was the only one who cared that the Utah Jazz proceeded
to thoroughly embarrass them in the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about Harris' uncertain future (he is in the final year
of his contract). He remains the right coach to guide the Lakers to
the NBA Finals if you believe, as we unequivocally do, that there
are a lot of good coaches out there; what's really important is to
have a group of interested athletes.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers didn't have enough attentive players when they went
up against the Jazz with an NBA Finals berth at stake. Eddie Jones
and Kobe Bryant and Van Exel saw their shooting percentages swoon
and the Lakers were swept in four games on the strength of the
Jazz's tenacity and teamwork, not its superior talent.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth noting that the Lakers return almost intact the squad
that produced the NBA's highest-scoring offense in 1997-98. And
they've added two proven ancillary players in Travis Knight and
Derek Harper.
</P>
<P>
   In the shortened season that begins next week, a deep bench
driven by high-octane, low-mileage legs will be a decided
advantage. The Lakers have all that and someone to override their
cruise control, too. That someone is the 37-year-old Harper, who
brings 15 years of experience to his latest mentoring assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Count on him to be every bit as dependable as Chick Hearn. And
just as passionate.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, Harper has come a long way since dribbling out the
clock during Dallas' Game 4 conference semifinal loss to the Lakers
in 1984 (the Mavericks would bow out in five). He was the best
guard you never heard of during his first decade in Dallas, his
numbers good but never gaudy enough for him to divert the spotlight
from Magic Johnson and John Stockton and Clyde Drexler.
</P>
<P>
   He played a wonderful leading man during the 1994 NBA Finals
between his New York Knicks and the Houston Rockets but was
outshone, if not outplayed, by Houston's Hakeem Olajuwon in the
Rockets' seventh-game victory.
</P>
<P>
   Harper played in Orlando in 1997-98. It was a mediocre season
for the Magic but certainly not a mundane one for Harper. In
February he had to be removed from the court on a stretcher after
being hammered on his way to the basket during a game against
Minnesota. Less than two months later, his daughter, now 2, spent a
day in the hospital on life support and another two in intensive
care after nearly drowning in the family pool.
</P>
<P>
   After 15 seasons, Harper could have quietly retired with no
regrets. But he's got the same bug that Lakers forward Rick Fox
can't seem to shake. He wants to win an NBA title before he's
through.
</P>
<P>
   Harper and Fox have a passion that's contagious. You'd have to
have built up an immunity to greatness not to catch their fever.
The Lakers should consider themselves lucky. Unlike Samaranch, they
have a chance to nip their apathy in the bud before it has a chance
to destroy them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
