<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PLAYOFFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS SEEM A SHOO-IN FOR PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Contrary to popular perception, the National Hockey
League's playoff formula is not so inclusive. Only 16 teams qualify
for the tournament, and 11 do not make the cut. Six divisions this
season _ instead of four _ means two more automatic berths for
division winners.
</P>
<P>
   The scramble for the next 10 slots will leave a few respectable
teams idle when the regular season ends on April 18.
</P>
<P>
   Among the teams from the New York area, the Devils seem certain
to qualify. The Islanders almost certainly will not, and the
Rangers have only a poor-to-fair chance. With the All-Star Game
break over, the final 12 weeks should be intriguing, beginning
Tuesday night with the Rangers at Washington, Ottawa at the Devils
and Boston at the Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   Under their new coach, Robbie Ftorek, the Devils are more
exciting and less predictable. If they make a trade or two before
the March 23 deadline, it will be as much for fresh energy and
personality as for filling roster holes. Fourteen teams have given
up fewer goals, but that does not mean goalie Martin Brodeur is
having a bad year.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur, Scott Niedermayer, Scott Stevens and Bobby Holik
constitute a strong backbone. Should General Manager Lou Lamoriello
sprinkle a little pepper into his well-mixed stew, the Devils
should go beyond last spring's first-round ouster.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who balked at the price for Pavel Bure, will face a
difficult decision as the trade deadline approaches. If close to a
playoff berth, the Rangers can offer spare parts or draft choices
for offensive forwards like Calgary's Theo Fleury or Montreal's
Mark Recchi. Due for unrestricted free agency in July, players such
as these could be short-term rentals for short-term goals.
</P>
<P>
   But should the Rangers fade, they might instead trade their own
players who are due to become unrestricted free agents, guys who
could help other contenders in a 90-day fling. These include Adam
Graves, Ulf Samuelsson and, yes, even Brian Leetch. In return, the
Rangers might get prospects or draft choices necessary for
rebuilding. Come summer, they could buy back their traded veterans
on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   With Bill Stewart as their new coach, the Islanders should
improve while Mike Milbury limits himself to his general manager's
role. But this franchise remains unsettled at most levels,
including ownership, arena and player personnel. As he demonstrated
with his trade of Bryan Berard for Felix Potvin, Milbury still has
much to prove as an executive.
</P>
<P>
   In the Eastern Conference, the surprise of the first half is
Toronto. The Maple Leafs are leading the Northeast Division under
the leadership of their president, Ken Dryden, the associate
general manager, Mike Smith, Coach Pat Quinn and Captain Mats
Sundin. But Toronto will leave Maple Leaf Gardens next month for
the Air Canada Center. Such changes usually disorient home teams.
The better teams in this division might be the Senators and the
Buffalo Sabres, young and hungry after a taste of playoff success
last spring.
</P>
<P>
   In the Atlantic Division, the Philadelphia Flyers seem settled
in goal with John Vanbiesbrouck. On offense, there is no duo more
dynamic than Eric Lindros and John LeClair, both among the leading
goal scorers.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the Devils, the Pittsburgh Penguins should stay
close. The Penguins' general manager, Craig Patrick, always plays
the hand he is dealt well. This season, the joker card is
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The Carolina Hurricanes barely lead the Southeast, which might
send only one team to the post-season. Now that the Panthers have
Pavel Bure, Florida might be that team. The Capitals, who slipped
into the Stanley Cup finals last season, can be thankful that the
Tampa Bay Lightning will keep them out of the cellar.
</P>
<P>
   Defending the last two Stanley Cup championships, the Detroit
Red Wings are either complacent or wearing out in the Western
Conference. They may coast to the Central title with a record
barely above .500. Names heard in trade rumors include Brendan
Shanahan and Sergei Fedorov. With Nashville and Chicago struggling,
only mediocre St. Louis could make things even lukewarm for the
Wings.
</P>
<P>
   In the Northwest, Colorado's division lead is much like
Detroit's: unimpressive. But the Avalanche improved in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Mark Crawford has replaced Mike Keenan as the Vancouver
coach, the Canucks might give Edmonton a run for second place _ or
better. Crawford gets to coach twice against his former team, the
Avalanche. Could Mark Messier, in his second season with the
Canucks, be the next to go in Brian Burke's midseason
housecleaning?
</P>
<P>
   The city of Dallas is far from the Pacific Ocean, but its hockey
team leads the division of that name. The Stars also lead the whole
league. The eyes of hockey are upon them. The Stars have shown they
can win in Detroit this season and they gave the Wings a major
challenge in the Western finals last spring. Brett Hull is only the
newest of several shooting stars on a balanced offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix Coyotes, who faded slightly in the second quarter,
are still robust.
</P>
<P>
   With Paul Kariya healthy and leading the league in points, the
Mighty Ducks of Anaheim are fun to watch. And so are also-rans like
the San Jose Sharks and the Los Angeles Kings. Team for team, this
may be the NHL's most entertaining division. Thanks to late-night
telecasts on ESPN2, Eastern fans can keep up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 0038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
