u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-TAXCUT-PROPOSAL-N     01-26 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-TAXCUT-PROPOSAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS CLAIM FLAWS IN TAX CUT PROPOSED BY GOP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Del.)  (mk) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Republican proposal to cut income taxes by 10 percent across
the board means that millions of middle-class families would get
only part of the tax break and taxes would increase for large
middle-income families by as much as 14 percent, House Democrats
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is how the income tax system interacts with two other
laws, the alternative minimum tax and the child credit for
middle-class families that took effect last year. When tax rates
are cut more people become subject to the alternative tax, which
was originally adopted 30 years ago to make sure that no person
could avoid income taxes. Under the alternative tax system,
deductions for dependent children, as well as the child tax credit,
are cut or eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a family with six children making $71,000 would see
its federal income tax bill this year rise by $600, to $4,900 from
$4,300, a 14 percent increase, said John Buckley, minority chief of
staff for the House Ways and Means Committee. However, families
making more than $300,000 would get the full value of the 10
percent cut regardless of family size, Buckley said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rate cut's main sponsor, Sen. Rod Grams, R-Minn.,
said on the Republican's weekly radio address last week that ``the
across-the-board tax cut is simple.'' He continued: ``You don't
have to be a tax lawyer or an accountant to understand it. The
across-the-board tax cut is fair, because we're not pitting one
group of taxpayers against the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Grams ``will make any changes needed to insure that no one's tax
goes up and everyone gets a 10 percent cut,'' his spokesman, Steve
Behm, said Monday, adding, ``Assuming the Democrats are right, and
that's a big leap of faith, then he would solve the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William Roth Jr., R-Del., the Senate Finance Committee
chairman, said that reforming the alternative minimum tax to exempt
middle-class families should be part of this year's tax
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican bill would lower each tax bracket by 10 percent.
The 15 percent bracket would fall to 13.5 percent; the 28 percent
bracket to 25.2 percent; the 31 percent bracket to 27.9 percent;
the 36 percent bracket to 32.4 percent, and the 39.6 percent
bracket to 35.64 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Republican plan, the bottom 60 percent of families,
those making $38,000 or less, would get an average $99 tax cut
while those in the top 1 percent income group, who make more than
$301,000, would save an average of $20,700 each, according to
Citizens for Tax Justice, a Washington nonprofit organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 0038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 00:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8376 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      01-26 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMARANCH ROOT OF OLYMPIC DECAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After he pulled the rope on the trap door under a
half-dozen International Olympic Committee members that he helped
appoint, Juan Antonio Samaranch said something scary about the
IOC's growing bribery scandal, which almost daily takes a fresh
bite out of the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the beginning,'' he said, ``not the end, of our
work.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC president probably first said similar words 40-plus
years ago while doing the work of Franco, the fascist dictator who
placed a few trap doors of his own under his Spanish subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Insofar as the scandal is in its infancy, Samaranch is right.
This thing is a lingering sore, destined to erupt regularly because
the virus is so deeply rooted.
</P>
<P>
   But for him to consider any reforms ``our work,'' meaning his
idea, is a stinging insult to anyone involved in the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   It is Samaranch and his fellow IOC members who indulged the
universal atmosphere in which competing cities hoisted their civic
skirts in a fashion that would embarrass the Folies Bergere. Almost
by definition, it becomes impossible for him or any of his cronies
to pass fair judgment about who among them is clean or tainted.
</P>
<P>
   One of the dirty half-dozen, Jean-Claude Ganga of the Congo,
said he is convinced he is being singled out because of IOC
politics, not because he abused his privileges. It is no stretch to
assume that those members who see themselves as victims will be
more than happy to tattle on their fellow miscreants, creating in
the coming months a figurative food fight to rival ``Animal
House.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the scandal broke, Samaranch inadvertently acknowledged
the institutionalized nature of the graft. In an interview with
``60 Minutes'' that was broadcast on the final Sunday of the Winter
Games in Nagano, Samaranch was told of a $25 million ``donation''
that the Japanese bidders made to an Olympic museum, among many
other contributions offered for a favorable vote in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether any city had hope of securing an Olympics without
resorting to such means, Samaranch said, ``Well, it wouldn't be
easy _ it would be quite difficult _ but if they're getting the
Games, they would receive a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Samaranch didn't get it then _ or now. The ease with
which votes can be bartered on such a large matter leads to
suspicion on every decision rendered by the IOC and its staff,
including drug testing, Olympic eligibility and distribution of
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   In light of public awareness of how the Olympics are brokered,
how does an IOC official look the next Ben Johnson in his yellow
eyes and say, ``You're dirty, so get out''?
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch later tried to pull strings with CBS to get the
interview killed, claiming he was ambushed and that English was
only his fourth-best language. CBS resisted. That might seem like a
rare stand for journalistic integrity until it's realized that NBC
had bought up the telecast rights for the next half-dozen Olympics.
With nothing to lose, CBS could afford to take a stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were many questions like this,'' Samaranch said later of
the unexpectedly tough interview. ``I think it was not fair because
I was a businessman thinking it was my obligation to be kind to
CBS, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch was disturbed because he rarely has to deal with tough
questions, especially from a network that once paid $375 million to
act as what amounts to the Olympics' propaganda organ. Like all
American networks, CBS was supposed to make nice.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there are no more Mr. Nice Guys. Newspaper editorialists
around the world Monday called for Samaranch's resignation after
his expulsion of the six despoilers, calling the measures
scapegoating. Samaranch held a press conference at Olympic
headquarters in Lausanne, Switzerland, to fire back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased with myself, what I have done these 18 years,''
he said. ``I am not thinking of any kind of resignation.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch claimed no laws were broken in the Salt Lake City
scandal, which is true so far. It also is true that the IOC is a
private organization, and most of the money thrown at it by
competing cities was raised from private funds.
</P>
<P>
   But Samaranch and his cronies have created a worldwide emotional
colossus _ not to mention their own gravy train of privilege _ out
of the Olympics partly by appealing to humanity's desire for fair
play, noble conduct and dreams fulfilled. That huggable image is
part of why networks pay billions to tell its irresistible stories.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of growing cynicism toward sports, the Olympics'
opening ceremony and torch lighting remain a moment of exhilaration
and hope unsurpassed in human relations. But the people who helped
create the moment now are a threat to it because they have betrayed
the idealism that, however naively, was at its heart.
</P>
<P>
   For the Olympics, it isn't enough to say no laws were broken.
Samaranch, of all people, should know that. And as the man who
presided over the abuses, he is in no position to make credible
reforms. Nor are his cronies among the IOC membership.
</P>
<P>
   As he said, the work has only begun. Samaranch's trap door needs
to flap ceaselessly until he and his disingenuous way of doing
business no longer erode what is left of the Olympics' credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 0039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8377 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHILIPPINE-EATERIES-L     01-26 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIPPINE-EATERIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILIPINO CHAIN SET TO EXPAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A tickling taste of the Philippines is coming to
the Southland, and for Amalia Saravia and other local Filipinos
it's not a moment too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Manila-based fast-food chain Jollibee International plans to
open about a dozen restaurants in California, including eight in
Southern California, officials said Monday. Glendale, the San
Fernando Valley and downtown Los Angeles will each get their own
Jollibee.
</P>
<P>
   Saravia, who came to the United States from Manila in 1996,
still has fond memories of the seasoned burgers, succulent chicken
and other dishes that have made the Jollibee name one of the most
familiar in her homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of Filipinos here and they miss those Filipino
tastes,'' said Saravia, a bookkeeper for the Los Angeles-based
social services agency Filipino American Service Group.
</P>
<P>
   Special spices mixed directly into the burgers and other
techniques give Jollibee's offerings an ``Asian and tropical
twist'' that makes the chain so popular in the Philippines, said
Arnie Balague, general manager of the chain's California expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The chain was founded in Manila in 1978 by Tony Pan, now the
company's president. Since then, it has grown to 325 stores in
Asia, the Pacific Islands and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Jollibee made it's first United States appearance last May in
Daly City, just outside of San Francisco, Balague said. The chain
expects to add 12 California outlets over the next two years, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Southern California, Jollibee will open restaurants in areas
including Los Angeles, San Diego, Long Beach, Carson, Glendale,
Cerritos, West Covina and the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley location has not yet been determined, but the chain
is focusing on sites around Panorama City, Balague said.
</P>
<P>
   In Northern California, the company will open restaurants in San
Jose, San Francisco, Union City and Vallejo.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,000- to 3,000-square-foot restaurants will each employ
about 50 full- and part-time workers.
</P>
<P>
   California offers fertile ground for the chain's growth in the
United States, said Balague.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jollibee is the No.1 fast-food chain in the Philippines. We
(carry) a certain national pride in the Philippines and we would
like to capitalize on that,'' he said. ``If you think of any state
in the United States where there's a good number of Filipinos, it
would be California.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the 1990 census, there were 219,653 Filipinos in
Los Angeles County, said Saravia. There are most likely many more
by now, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The chain's expansion is good news, Saravia said, because it
should mean more employment opportunities for area Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, she's happy Jollibee is coming for other reasons
beside national pride. ``I will be a customer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
