<HEADLINE>
NEW INTERNET RETAIL TIE BOOSTS MATTHEW SHARES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Stock of Matthews Studio Equipment Group received
a jolt, rising as much as 54 &UR;  &LR; percent after the rental-equipment
specialist announced an affiliation with Internet retail giant
Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   The stock jumped as high as $7.125 Monday before falling back to
$5 for a gain of 37.5 cents, or 8 percent, during the session. More
than 936,000 shares changed hands, 18 times the average volume
during the past month.
</P>
<P>
   The stock price has more than doubled since late December, when
Matthews announced strong quarterly results with revenues up 19
percent to $17.8 million. It hit $5.125 on Jan. 13 after the
company announced plans for full launch of ShowbizMart.com this
spring as a one-stop resource for suppliers, crew and equipment,
then fell back to less than $5 as Internet fever cooled.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive officer of Burbank-based Matthews said the
affiliation will make it easy for ShowbizMart.com customers to buy
Amazon.com's books, videos, CDs and other merchandise.
ShowbizMart.com will earn referral fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This exciting new association with Amazon.com will allow
ShowbizMart.com to further its goal of becoming the entertainment
industry's true single resource for industry insiders as well as
consumers and collectors of show business-related items and
merchandise,'' said Carlos D. DeMattos, chairman and chief
executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, Matthews has been buying rivals to become the
industry's leader in rental equipment, and it has grown from three
locations with 150 employees to 14 sites with 300. It recently sold
off its manufacturing subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
