<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-BESTWEST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST PREPS IN THE WEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With 36 players from four states, the 1999 edition of the annual
Best in the West football team, compiled by the Long Beach
Press-Telegram, is the third largest in the 23 years of the team.
</P>
<P>
   And it is the deepest.
</P>
<P>
   Not only because of the exceptional talent in this class or the
record five players from one high school but because no team in BIW
history has had such a high concentration of votes as this one.
</P>
<P>
   There were more players on the teams in 1988 (38) and 1993 (37),
but the standards for making the first team weren't as high as they
are today.
</P>
<P>
   The Best in the West team is determined by votes from 10 college
head coaches and recruiting coordinators. Until 1994, it took only
six votes to make the first team. Beginning with the '94 team, it
took seven votes to make the first team.
</P>
<P>
   Where eliminating the players with six votes from the teams in
'88 and '93 would reduce those lists to 23 players, adding those
with six votes this year would swell the '99 team to an amazing 46
players. Thus, the deepest group of prospects yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids who are good this year are very good,'' said Dick
Lascola of the Scouting Evaluation Association. ``They are as good
as any year. But once you get through the first wave, it gets
really thin.''
</P>
<P>
   To receive a vote, the panel must believe the player will make
an impact by his sophomore year in college. If the panel is correct
_ and it is more often than not _ get used to hearing these names.
</P>
<P>
   There are four unanimous choices (10 votes each): tight end Mike
Seidman of Westlake, receiver Kareem Kelly of Long Beach Poly,
defensive lineman Bernard Riley of Los Alamitos and running back
Paul Arnold of Burien (Wash.) Kennedy. Last year, there were eight
10s but only 20 players on the first team.
</P>
<P>
   A record five players _ Kelly, quarterback Chris Lewis, running
back Larry Croom, receiver Samie Parker and cornerback Darrell
Rideaux _ are from Long Beach Poly. The old standard was also held
by Poly, when Mark Carrier, Stacy Elliot, Brian Tuliau and Chris
Roscoe made the team in 1986. This year's Poly contingent, by the
way, would have grown to six if linebacker Dennis Link's six votes
were enough to earn first-team honors.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good year for teammates as, in addition to Poly, Los
Alamitos placed three on the team (Riley, Sagan Atuatasi, Keenan
Howry) and Westchester (Charles Drake, Courtney Morgan) and Hart
(Kyle Boller, Jerry Owens) two each.
</P>
<P>
   The overall 1999 first team is comprised of seven offensive
linemen, five running backs, five receivers, two tight ends, four
quarterbacks, three defensive linemen, three linebackers, three
defensive backs, a receiver-defensive back, a running
back-defensive back, a fullback-linebacker and even a player (Shaun
McDonald of Phoenix Shadow Mountain) who specializes in returning
kicks. Thirty-one players are from California, two each from Oregon
and Washington and one from Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The four prime prospects, according to the votes, are Arnold,
Kelly, Riley and Seidman.
</P>
<P>
   Seidman, a tight end already with NFL size, has yet to decide on
where he will play college, but he has the list sliced to UCLA and
USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``He literally could have gone to any school in the country,''
said Westlake coach Jim Benkert of his 6-foot-5, 245-pound star.
``Colleges love it that he's a big guy but still has the speed to
go vertical.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold is considered by some longtime Seattle observers as
possibly the best prep running back in Washington history. The
speedy 6-foot-1, 205-pounder, who is choosing between the hometown
Huskies, Notre Dame and UCLA, became coach Rick Neuheisel's first
priority when he took over at the University of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Riley is 6-foot-2, 300 pounds but has run a 4.9 40-yard dash.
Kelly is the defending state 200-meter champion.
</P>
<P>
   But this team is much more than the four unanimous choices.
</P>
<P>
   There are four outstanding quarterbacks (Lewis, Boller, Venice's
J.P. Losman, and Orinda Miramonte's Ken Dorsey), tremendous skill
players (Charter Oak receiver Steve Stevenson, Hart's Owens,
Monrovia running back Akil Harris, St. Paul receiver/defensive back
Marcell Allmond) and plenty of depth throughout. &QL; 
BEST IN THE WEST SQUAD &QL; 
(led by votes) &QL; 
10 __ Kareem Kelly/Long Beach Poly __ WR __ 6-2 __ 190 &QL; 
10 __ Bernard Riley/Los Alamitos __ DL __ 6-2 __ 300 &QL; 
10 __ Mike Seidman/Westlake __ TE __ 6-5 __ 245 &QL; 
10 __ Paul Arnold/Burien, Wash. Kennedy __ RB __ 6-1 __ 205 &QL; 
9 __ Joe Weber/San Bernardino Pacific __ RB __ 6-2 __ 230 &QL; 
9 __ J.P. Losman/Venice __ QB __ 6-3 __ 185 &QL; 
8 __ Bryce Bohlander/Salem, Ore. McNary __ OL __ 6-7 __ 270 &QL; 
