<SLUG> BC-STEALTHPAY-ARIZONA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTORNEY GENERAL WON'T REVIEW POLICY ON LAWMAKERS' PER DIEM PAY. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The Arizona Attorney General's Office has refused to
review a House policy that gave a former state House speaker
thousands of dollars in a daily allowance even though he was no
longer eligible for the extra money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a legislative branch issue that the legislative
branch needs to look at, rather than the executive branch,'' said
Tim Delaney, Attorney General Janet Napolitano's chief deputy.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Napolitano's own ruling, requested by House Speaker
Jeff Groscost and Senate President Brenda Burns, that allowed
legislators to continue to collect thousands of dollars in daily
allowances that voters had rejected at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, voters approved Proposition 302 by a 56 percent
to 44 percent margin. It increased legislative pay to $24,000 but
reduced per diem payments.
</P>
<P>
   The question was put on the ballot by the Commission on Salaries
for Elected State Officers. In her Jan. 7 ruling, Napolitano said
the commission had no authority to tinker with the daily allowance
for expenses, only salaries. The Attorney General's Office
intervened to rule on that constitution question, a representative
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   That ruling meant lawmakers were able to keep the $9,000 raise
and still have access to the old per diem system, which paid some
lawmakers as much as an additional $20,000 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Napolitano argued in her opinion that lawmakers were eligible to
take both the pay raise and per diem because the publicity pamphlet
for Proposition 302 ``focused exclusively on the salary increase,
not the per diem limitation.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to that opinion, the pamphlet stated twice within the
first 20 lines that Proposition 302 would change per diem
reimbursement as well as increase lawmakers' salaries.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Phoenix attorney Barry Dale said he will challenge
Napolitano's ruling in a lawsuit to be filed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a Jan. 22 letter, Dale urged Napolitano to reconsider her
decision. He said he would seek to recover the money ``illegally
paid to the legislators,'' plus 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they would find it upsetting to be named in a lawsuit
due to their acceptance of monies in reliance on your erroneous
opinion,'' Dale wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate indignity, Dale said, ``is having a ballot
proposition overruled by the attorney general. It takes away the
rights from the voters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Arizona Republic'' reported Sunday that former Rep. Don
Aldridge was able to collect thousands of dollars in extra per diem
money even though he had lost his leadership post and was no longer
eligible for the money.
</P>
<P>
   Those extra days account for $5,160 of the $13,080 Aldridge
collected in per diem payments. He also received $6,438 for mileage
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   On some days, even when the Legislature was not in session,
Aldridge signed for his $60 in per diem pay, then went home,
according to House sources.
</P>
<P>
   Through a ``special dispensation'' from Groscost, Aldridge was
able to collect more money than any other member of the House.
</P>
<P>
   And there were other discrepancies in the House policy. Rep.
Debra Brimhall, R-Snowflake, was allowed to claim mileage when she
traveled her district while other members, like Rep. John Verkamp,
R-Flagstaff, were not.
</P>
<P>
   During the Legislative session, Maricopa County legislators
receive $35 a day, while legislators from other counties get a $60
allowance.
</P>
<P>
   When the Legislature is out of session, House and Senate members
are eligible for a day a week of per diem pay, plus the days they
attend committee meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative leaders qualify for additional money because they
generally have to spend more time at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Senate leaders qualify for six days of per diem payments each
two-week period, while House leaders can get the money anytime they
work at the Capitol. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Chris Moeser can be reached at chris.moeser(at)pni.com via
e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
