<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-SPORTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENJOY SUPER BOWL FROM COMFORTS OF HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Tex. _ To enjoy the atmosphere of Super Bowl XXXIII,
you don't have to be in balmy Miami, Fla., soaking up the ocean
spray in a rented sports car while speeding down Biscayne
Boulevard.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Heck, simply pull up a seat in the den, boot up the computer and
watch it unfold on the 'Net.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of big-media sites give Super Bowl XXXIII a big presence
online. These resource-rich sites all have the components of a
quality site: updated content, easy navigation and interactivity.
</P>
<P>
   And they all have unique features.
</P>
<P>
   Here is one Web surfer's guide to the best of the Super Bowl
sites:
</P>
<P>
   Best preview: CBS SportsLine
(www.sportsline.com/u/football/nfl/superbowl/xxxiii) has lots of
cool features that the other sites have, but none has EA SPORTS'
video-game simulation of this year's Super Bowl. Using Madden NFL
'99, the Denver Broncos won, but not before the Atlanta Falcons
bolted to a 22-0 lead. CBS SportsLine has a breakdown of the
simulated game, complete with still images and statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Best editorial content: CNN/SI
(cnnsi.com/football/nfl/1998/playoffs) taps the resources of Sports
Illustrated and CNN correspondents. If you like to read, this is
the place to go. And if you like the magazine's dynamic photos, the
site has a high-resolution image gallery loaded with Super
Bowl-related photos. Users can zoom into the images _ as if they
have an online magnifying glass _ for closer looks.
</P>
<P>
   Best fantasy games: ESPN.com
(espn.go.com/nfl/playoffs98/superbowl) gets fantasy football
enthusiasts back online with its Fantasy Super Bowl Tournament and
Super Bowl Over/Under features.
</P>
<P>
   For the tournament, ESPN.com editors selected an all-time roster
for each franchise from all the players who ever wore its uniform
in a Super Bowl. Eight teams were seeded based on their Super Bowl
records. The San Francisco 49ers, who are 5-0 in Super Bowls, are
the No. 1 seed and the Cowboys, 5-3, the No. 2 seed. Votes cast by
ESPN.com users will decide a champion this week. It's a good way
for Cowboys fans to make some noise during Super Bowl week.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN.com's Over/Under is a free mini-fantasy game in which users
guess the frequency with which certain activities occur during the
game. Example: What quarter will be the first Dirty Bird dance
happen? Winner gets a TV.
</P>
<P>
   Best interaction: Superbowl.com (actually, superbowl.lycos.com)
has QB1, where online players test their play-calling skills during
the Super Bowl. Players must guess the offensive play and result
before each snap. Winners earn tickets to next year's Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Best video/audio: Since most are sitting at home this season,
Cowboys fans yearning for a little nostalgia will love NFL.com's
Super Bowl section (www.nfl.com/sb33), which has video and audio of
memorable moments from past Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Best polls: ESPN.com will be polling online visitors after the
game about their favorite and least-favorite Super Bowl
commercials. For the sake of some imagination, let's get those
Budweiser lizards out of here, please.
</P>
<P>
   Best place to learn how to do the Dirty Bird: Jamal Anderson's
site on America Online (keyword: jamal) has step-by-step
instructions. The Falcons running back also relates his theory on
the Dirty Bird on his site, which hawks official Dirty Bird
merchandise at a 10-percent discount this week.
</P>
<P>
   Best chamber-of-commerce-like site: SoFla.com's Super Bowl site
(www.sofla.com/FEATURES/superbowl) has it all: where to stay, where
to eat, where to celebrate, etc. It also has tips on where to rent
a car _ in case you decide to go to Miami and not sit in the den
and call up Web sites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
