</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-COL-REEVES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU'S ANGER PROBLEM NOT LIMITED TO NAILON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
It was almost exactly a year ago, give or take a couple of weeks,
that talented TCU center Lee Nailon was ordered to undergo anger
counseling after a one-sided fight with his girlfriend in his
campus dorm room.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yesterday, the Western Athletic Conference decided to give him a
24-hour refresher course.
</P>
<P>
   Nailon was handed a one-game suspension, taking him out of
uniform for TCU's 72-62 loss at Tulsa last night.
</P>
<P>
   It was exactly the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   You probably won't get head coach Billy Tubbs to admit that. He
spent much of the afternoon trying to convince WAC supervisor of
officials Bobby Dibler that a suspension wasn't merited, which,
from Dibler's point of view, must have been like being locked in a
room with a hyperventilating used-car salesman.
</P>
<P>
   But what's a head coach supposed to do when his star player's
availability for a key conference game is on the line?
</P>
<P>
   The question, in fact, wasn't so much whether Nailon deserved a
suspension, which is the NCAA-mandated penalty automatically meted
out to players who have been ejected for fighting. The real debate
is whether Tubbs deserves one, too.
</P>
<P>
   He probably does.
</P>
<P>
   Brash Billy made a crass bully of himself again once he lost
Nailon just 34 seconds into Saturday night's home game with
Nevada-Las Vegas. Tubbs must have known what was coming.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a heroic effort from Marquise Gainous, who scored 41
points, the Frogs lost in overtime to the Runnin' Rebels, who took
advantage of TCU's many defensive lapses.
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs spent the game on his feet, spewing venom any time a
hapless official was forced into earshot. After the game, referee
Bill Gracey reported that Tubbs came to the officials' dressing
room, cursed at them and kicked the door.
</P>
<P>
   Not our Saint Billy, surely. Brother Bill was probably just
checking on the officials' postgame buffet and was perhaps mildly
upset that the roast duck was a tad cold or the caviar too salty.
He may have kicked the door as a way of calling the chef's
attention to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Billy throw a tantrum? Why, what a preposterous suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   Around here, we just call that personality and try to slip decaf
into his coffee cup whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs had apparently hoped to convince Dibler that Nailon's
reaction when UNLV guard Mark Dickel _ about half Nailon's size _
tried to rip the ball out of his hands while Nailon was standing
out of bounds with the clock stopped should be expected. Nailon
basically fired an open-handed hook to the side of Dickel's face.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, if I'd been Nailon, already irritated and frustrated at
being pushed out of bounds by muscular UNLV center Kasbars Kambala
(now there's the match I'd pay to see), that might have been my
instant reaction, too. Dickel had no business trying to snatch the
ball away. The referee has to handle the ball after that call.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason there wasn't a fight, however, was because
Dickel didn't swing back, which saved him from being tossed, too,
and most of the other players missed the exchange because they were
already on their way to the opposite end of the court.
</P>
<P>
   To Nailon's credit, he has spent much of this season holding his
temper in check while being double-teamed, fouled, hacked and
mangled. Opponents have done about everything but clip his toenails
for him.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, he becomes an open target for anyone trying to
bait him. If he's ejected for fighting, even in self-defense, again
this season, he'll face another NCAA-mandated suspension _ this
time for the rest of the year, including the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, without Nailon, TCU can forget about the NCAA
Tournament anyway.
</P>
<P>
   One more fight of any kind and he's gone.
</P>
<P>
   At least Nailon hasn't bitten anybody's ear off yet.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad we can't say the same _ figuratively speaking, of course
_ for Tubbs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
