<HEADLINE>
TOP QUARTERBACK PICKS TEXAS OVER TENNESSEE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN MILLER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Tex. _ A week ago, Texas lost the recruiting battle for
Duncanville defensive end Kevin Young when he withdrew his
commitment from the Longhorns and committed to Tennessee.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Longhorns paid the Volunteers back in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Chris Simms from Ramapo High School in Franklin
Lakes, N.J., withdrew his commitment from Tennessee and committed
to Texas, his mother, Diana Simms, and his high school coach, Mike
Miello, confirmed yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is he had some time to think about it,''
Miello said. ``After doing so, he felt like Texas was a much better
fit for him. He liked everything about the coaches and players and
he came to a point where he wanted to change his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Simms, the son of former NFL quarterback Phil Simms, was
unavailable for comment yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5, 210-pound Chris Simms is regarded by many as the
top quarterback prospect in the country. He is the second highly
touted recruit to commit to the Longhorns in less than a week.
Galena Park North Shore linebacker Cory Redding committed to Texas
on Thursday. Eight members of the Star-Telegram's National Top 100
recruits have committed to the Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a possibility after getting a commitment
from Redding, Texas might end up with the No. 1 class in the
country,'' said Bobby Burton, editor-in-chief of The National
Recruiting Advisor. ``Now, with the addition of Simms, it does not
make them just a contender; it makes them the leader. They are the
team to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   During his four years at Ramapo, Simms played in every game and
broke every passing record at the high school. He completed 381 of
640 passes for 7,055 yards with 63 touchdowns and 13 interceptions.
He also ran for 324 yards and four touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Simms originally announced his decision to commit to Tennessee
on Dec. 15, then picking the Volunteers over Texas and Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   Commitments are not binding. Signing day is Feb. 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
