<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVS-NASH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS SIGN NASH TO A SIX-YEAR DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
DALLAS _ For the fourth time in three years, the Mavericks have put
the ball in the hands of a new ``cornerstone point guard of the
future.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest candidate _ despite having only 11 NBA starts on his
resume _ could have an All-Star career. His assistant coach says
he'll have the same positive effect on games as Phoenix Suns star
and former Mavericks standout Jason Kidd. And his head coach
compares him favorably to a young John Stockton, the Utah Jazz's
future Hall-of-Famer.
</P>
<P>
   Psst, meet Steve Nash, one of the NBA's best-kept secrets, the
owner of a new six-year contract extension worth $36 million, and
the new owner of a Mavericks leadership burden that proved too
cumbersome for Kidd and Sam Cassell in 1996-97, and Robert Pack in
'97-98.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand fans have questions about me or there are some
saying `Who is this guy?' and that's okay,'' said Nash, who
yesterday was named co-captain along with Michael Finley and signed
the extension that will begin paying him $4 million next season.
``I'm not promising I'll make the All-Star team because that can be
political. But if I'm not playing at an All-Star level in three
years, come to me because there won't be anybody else to blame.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, yes there will.
</P>
<P>
   Though it was general manager Don Nelson who pulled the trigger
on the draft-day acquisition of Nash from the Suns for the
Mavericks' 1999 first-round draft pick, it's assistant Donnie
Nelson who admits to holding the gun. Donnie Nelson says that while
he was a Suns assistant he struggled to muzzle his enthusiasm about
a third-team guard as he watched Nash outplay Kidd and Kevin
Johnson daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may sound crazy to a lot of people because Steve's still
relatively unknown, but in a different way he'll be just as
effective as Jason,'' Donnie Nelson said. ``He's like Jason, though
a little more under control. My rear end's on the line with this
one, and I'm very comfortable with that. This is just finally time
for Steve. He's paid his dues, and he's ready to break out.''
</P>
<P>
   Armed with the new contract that will team him with Finley for
at least the next three seasons and the pressure of being a
co-captain, Nash's time in the spotlight has arrived. The 15th pick
by Phoenix in the '96 draft, Nash has played in relative obscurity
behind Kidd and Johnson the past two seasons. In 141 career games,
he has averaged nine points and three assists. In 76 games under
coach Danny Ainge last season, Nash was used in up-tempo,
three-guard sets and as a defensive stopper on opposing point
guards, like Avery Johnson of the San Antonio Spurs in last
spring's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are going to learn who he is, and they're
going to like what they see,'' Nelson said. ``He can shoot, he's
hard-nosed and he's a winner. I'd compare him to a Stockton when he
was younger, but Steve is much more aggressive as a shooter and a
scorer. With a guy like him there's no risk unless there's an
injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Stockton arrived in the NBA from tiny Gonzaga to become the
NBA's all-time leader in assists and steals. Nash, 24, played at
Santa Clara and does have a reputation around the league for taking
charges and key shots late in the game, and playing bigger than his
6-foot-3, 195-pound frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little chance here because he's so young, but it's a
good risk,'' said Finley, who signed a similar extension worth $42
million over five years in October 1997. ``We're doing the same
thing Utah did with Stockton and Cleveland did with \RKevin\S
Johnson. As far as leadership and respect, Steve's already probably
the most responsible guy on the team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
