<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-MATCH1-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALCONS' 1-2 PUNCH TESTS BRONCOS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
MIAMI _ When the Atlanta Falcons upset the Minnesota Vikings in the
NFC Championship Game on Jan. 17, that didn't leave the league's
most prolific receiving duo in terms of yards per catch out of the
Super Bowl.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Minnesota's Randy Moss and Cris Carter, are in fact, second in
that category.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's T-N-T combo of Terance Mathis and Tony Martin is
first.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis and Martin combined to average a league-high 17.82 yards
per catch and to score 17 touchdowns in the regular season. Before
the playoffs, Mathis had 19 receptions of 20 yards or longer,
including five of 49 yards or longer. Martin had 16 receptions of
20 yards or longer, four receptions of 40 yards or longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are very surprised about us,'' Mathis said.
``When the magazines came out, the media makes all of their
superstars before the games are played.''
</P>
<P>
   Charged with stopping the Falcons' superstars are Broncos
cornerbacks Ray Crockett and Darrien Gordon. Crockett is better in
man-to-man coverage than Gordon and will probably be locked up on
Mathis for much of the game. However, both have shown an ability to
make plays. Each returned an interception for a touchdown during
the regular season. And Gordon had two interceptions against the
Jets in the AFC Championship Game. Nickle cornerback Darrius
Johnson also has three interceptions for the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   The key for the Broncos will be to mix up their coverages, and
disguise blitz packages against Falcons quarterback Chris Chandler
so that he won't have time to look to his second, third, and fourth
wide receivers. Chandler said the Broncos do that as well as any
team in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're real experienced on defense,'' Chandler said. ``They
do a nice mixture of playing you straight up, all-out blitz, the
zone blitz, the tricky stuff. They mix it up as well as anybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
