<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-ROBINSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALCONS HEAR A `PROPHET'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
MIAMI _ They will crowd around Falcons safety Eugene Robinson all
week here at the Super Bowl as if he were preaching gospel.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And to his teammates he is. The Falcons have followed the word
the 35-year-old Robinson is spreading, whether it be advice on
religion, family life or defensive schemes.
</P>
<P>
   They know that listening to the 14-year-veteran, who signed with
the Falcons as a free-agent in the off-season after two years with
the Packers, has brought them to this promised land.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talks non-stop,'' safety Randy Fuller said. ``And you want
to listen carefully, because if you don't you probably will miss
something important. He is our spiritual leader and everyone
gravitates toward him.''
</P>
<P>
   Said linebacker Jessie Tuggle: ``The minute I met Gene, I knew
he was a leader. He has that glow and magic about him. He talks
constantly, has endless energy and gives guys advice on everything
from zone coverages to family life to movie reviews.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed ``the Prophet'' by his teammates, Robinson simply
says, ``I'm real vocal. I'm always in their ears, always in their
ears.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Robinson is making his third consecutive trip the Super
Bowl _ he was there with the Packers the past two years _ his
teammates are bracing for an earful this week in preparation for
Sunday's battle against the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, he brought along a visual aid _ his 1996
Super Bowl ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to make it tangible for the other guys,'' Robinson
said. ``A lot of guys look at the ring and want to put it on and
look at it up close. I tell them that we can have our own rings. We
can do this. I try to make it real for them and not be mesmerized
by the Super Bowl. We can go out there and win a football game and
get our own rings.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, however, has done more than talk. He started every
game for the Falcons, recording 94 tackles and four interceptions.
He has been even better in the playoffs. He sparked the divisional
playoff victory against the 49ers with a 77-yard interception
return and helped contain the Vikings' big-play offense with a key
deflection against receiver Randy Moss in the NFC championship
game.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons coach Dan Reeves, who acquired Robinson in the
off-season to bring leadership and playmaking ability to the
secondary, said the crafty veteran has been everything he hoped for
and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a take-charge kind of guy who is willing to stick his
neck out,'' Reeves said. ``He loves responsibility. The more
responsibility, the better. He is a vocal leader who has been a
great addition and inspiration for this team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
