<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COACHES-SALARIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACHES CROSS THE GOLD LINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Tex. _ College football's Millionaire Coaches Club
doubled in membership during the past month, making ``salary
inflation'' a hot topic among smiling coaches and frowning athletic
directors.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Florida's Steve Spurrier (estimated salary: $2 million) and
Florida State's Bobby Bowden (estimated salary: $1 million) have
been joined by Tennessee's Phillip Fulmer and Washington's Rick
Neuheisel. Both have million-dollar deals; Fulmer's contract was
renegotiated, and Neuheisel made his money by leaving Colorado for
his new job.
</P>
<P>
   TCU's Dennis Franchione, meanwhile, had his contract reworked,
going from around $450,000 a year to $800,000.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a bottom line to these salary bottom lines, it's
this: If you want to win, you have to pay. The best coaches _ or
the ones perceived as the best coaches _ get paid for their
expertise. And those athletic directors who can pay, often do.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this: In 1982, Texas A&AMP;M hired Jackie Sherrill to
resurrect its football program. Sherrill's contract was a shocking
$240,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska athletic director Bill Byrne calls the upwardly mobile
salaries ``madness.'' He pointed out that most athletic departments
are operating in the red.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, an NCAA study of revenues and expenses released in
October indicated that Division I-A average expenses increased 21
percent from 1995 to 1997 while average revenues increased 15
percent over the two-year period. ``There just seems to be more
money than good sense on some of these issues,'' Byrne said.
</P>
<P>
   At least 17 I-A schools will have new coaches for the 1999
season. Last season, that number was 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think schools are understanding that coaches make a big
difference,'' Texas athletic director DeLoss Dodds said. ``As one
school pays more, it starts a domino effect that impacts everybody.
Schools that are generating revenue can pay the big salaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington, for instance, reported an athletic department profit
of approximately $6.6 million for 1998 with about $10 million more
in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione turned the Horned Frogs around from a 1-10 season in
1997 to a 7-5 record in 1998 that included a Sun Bowl victory
against Southern California. To fend off schools with coaching
openings, TCU reworked his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these salary increases, they're market driven,''
Franchione said. ``The standard gets set by what people are willing
to pay. And for coaches, contracts like these provide some
insurance. It's a short distance from the penthouse to the
outhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel was earning $635,000 a year at Colorado. Gary Barnett,
Neuheisel's successor at Colorado, saw his salary rise over 50
percent. He was earning an estimated $460,000 a year at
Northwestern and accepted Colorado's offer of $710,000.
</P>
<P>
   In recommending Barnett's deal to the Colorado board of regents,
school chancellor Richard L. Byyny said Barnett's compensation was
``necessary . . . in light of the prevailing market conditions and
competitive employment practices nationwide for head football
coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma is paying a reported $775,000 a year for the next five
years to Bob Stoops, a first-time head coach at the Division I-A
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a line between sensible and irrational, and I felt
comfortable that I was operating with a clear understanding of the
marketplace,'' Oklahoma athletic director Joe Castiglione said.
``But I do have concerns as the packages start to escalate. You're
constantly asking yourself, `What are the resources available to us
to fulfill our \Rcontractual\S obligations?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Salary escalation has been particularly evident in the
Pacific-10 Conference. In 1995, Stanford hired Tyrone Willingham at
a reported $500,000 a year. Last year, Southern California topped
that by paying Paul Hackett $640,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Neuheisel's million-dollar deal shortly after Arizona
State reworked Bruce Snyder's deal to $700,000 and Arizona upped
Dick Tomey's contract to $500,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Pac-10 assistant commissioner Jim Muldoon says that the
conference doesn't keep track of coaching contracts, but his guess
is that five years ago, the average salary for Pac-10 football
coaches was $200,000. For 1999, that average is expected to be
approximately $545,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the bar was raised, but certainly a few
eyebrows were raised,'' Oregon athletic director Bill Moos said of
Washington's big-money deal with Neuheisel. ``If you're hiring a
coach now, you have to pay attention to what's going on at places
like Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Scholarship restrictions have spread the talent and made more
programs competitive. Now there is concern that the playing field
is being tilted by coaching salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to lie and say it's easy for us to be a player
in this type of game,'' said Oregon State athletic director Mitch
Barnhart, who signed new coach Dennis Erickson to a
$300,000-a-year-deal. ``But we'll pay market value, whatever that
is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
