<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COL-GALLOWAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS ASSISTANTS GET NO NFL RESPECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Tex. _ I'm still asking. Somebody tell me. Please. In
the new world order of football coaching, how did it happen that
TCU's Dennis Franchione is now better paid than the head coach of
the Cowboys?
<TEXT>
<P>
   And for anyone coming up with that answer, don't stop there. Get
right to work on this stumper:
</P>
<P>
   Why did the NFL fill a record nine head coaching vacancies over
the past month, and not one Cowboys' assistant even receive a
courtesy phone call inquiring about possible interest?
</P>
<P>
   Let's see _ figure nine teams looking for a head coach, and each
had around five candidates. Even with overlaps, there had to be 30
names on those interview lists.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Valley Ranch had the same number of head
coaching interviews as Linda Tripp does new best friends.
</P>
<P>
   What does this tell us?
</P>
<P>
   If you say it's a weak staff, I'd say wrong. It's not.
</P>
<P>
   But in trying to gauge how far the Cowboys have fallen in
league-wide prestige, this is about as good a measuring stick as
you'll find.
</P>
<P>
   The cycle comes and goes. At the moment, it's gone at Valley
Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   How is Green Bay's quarterback coach _ somebody named Andy Reid
_ hired at Philadelphia? OK, idiots are in charge at Philadelphia.
But still.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for instance, Dave Campo, who has put in 10 quality
seasons as an NFL and Cowboys assistant, the past four in total
charge of an overachieving defense.
</P>
<P>
   Everything the Cowboys have done defensively in that span, which
has always been more than expected, is a credit to Campo. The
previous head coach had nothing to offer, and when Chan Gailey took
over he made it clear he would be totally consumed with offense.
</P>
<P>
   At least on the defensive side of the ball, Campo has been an
NFL head coach for four years, and with great results. But nine
vacancies this off-season, and not even a telephone call. Don't
tell me Dave Campo hasn't been more involved with winning football
games in the NFL than an Andy Reid.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the ``offensive trend'' in the league, it doesn't make
sense. That was the defensive coordinator of the Jaguars, Dick
Jauron, who was hired last weekend by the Bears. Then again, based
on how Bears' management handled the search, Campo came out ahead
not being involved.
</P>
<P>
   Another defensive coordinator, Arizona's Dave McGinnis, was
announced as the head coach on Friday, except it was before he had
agreed to the terms. McGinnis ended up walking away, and good for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Go back a year ago, and Jerry Jones' coaching search looks
totally organized compared to the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine new coaches, four are defensive guys. But George
Seifert went to Carolina on track record, and rightfully so. Plus,
Ray Rhodes had a Green Bay background, while Kansas City stayed at
home in promoting defensive coordinator Gunther Cunningham. But
Jauron? Well, Jacksonville is simply an organization that has
passed up the Cowboys in prestige. The Jaguars' offensive
coordinator, Chris Palmer, got the Cleveland job. ``Two very, very
good men and coaches, right there,'' Campo said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that long ago when the Cowboys had three assistants
hired as head coaches within two years _ Dave Wannstedt in Chicago,
Norv Turner in Washington and Butch Davis at the University of
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   These days, however, the phone lines are down. And while Campo
should have been a leading candidate somewhere, it's also
surprising the snub extends to special teams' coach Joe Avezzano,
assistant head coach/defensive line coach Jim Bates, and offensive
line coach Hudson Houck. All have qualifications.
</P>
<P>
   For Campo, the long-standing inside joke, even with him, is he
doesn't ``look'' the head coaching part. But it may not be a joke
to NFL owners.
</P>
<P>
   In a crowd, Campo could be your favorite computer technician. Or
a former shortstop, which he once was in college, and a good one,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very handsome, but I'm short,'' Campo said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, what is the ``look'' of a head coach in the NFL?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say there's no disappointment in this,'' Campo added.
``Mainly because I don't know how much merit is considered in some
of these hires. What you've done, doesn't necessarily seem to
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, I have a good job and have the respect of a
good organization. That's the most important part. My philosophy is
centered around having patience, and hopefully good things will
happen when there's an opening in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the Cowboys gain this time by not losing Campo.
But with nine jobs open, it's hard to believe they didn't, based,
of course, on merit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
