<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 03:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8459 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-SFCHRO     01-26 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS CLOSE DOORS FOR DEBATE  
  
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC SANDALOW  
   
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Washington _ With President Clinton's acquittal viewed as a near
certainty, senators met late into Monday night in a rare
closed-door session to debate a Democratic motion to dismiss the
impeachment proceedings.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before the public and the media were ordered out of the chamber,
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said there was enough
Republican opposition to defeat the motion when it comes up for a
vote Tuesday or Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, its introduction was widely viewed as the
beginning of the end for Republican hopes that the trial might
somehow transform public opinion and result in Clinton's removal
from office. Even as House prosecutors prepared a list of witnesses
they would like to see testify, senators from both parties spent
much of the day scrambling to reach an agreement to bring a quick
end to the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only a matter of time before the American people get
their fervently held wish'' that the matter be finished, said Vice
President Al Gore during a stop in San Francisco. ``I think we're
close to the end now.''
</P>
<P>
   As the ninth day of Clinton's impeachment trial came to an end,
the road map toward its conclusion was still a matter of partisan
debate. Democrats offered a plan early in the day to forgo both the
motion to dismiss and the debate over witnesses and proceed
directly to a vote on the two articles of impeachment. The idea was
quickly rebuffed by Republicans, who insisted that even with
witnesses the trial would be over within a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations became so disjointed and frantic that the trial
began an hour late and was twice interrupted by unscheduled
recesses known as ``quorum calls.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to the operations of the United States Senate,'' Lott
said, laughing, as he called the second recess.
</P>
<P>
   Senators adjourned their closed-door meeting nearly five hours
after it began. Citing Senate rules, they refused to discuss what
had transpired inside and whether any new compromises had been
reached.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's procedure for the remainder of the trial _ still
subject to change _ grew so complicated as the day wore on that
even veteran Congress-watchers had difficulty keeping it straight.
</P>
<P>
   As of late last night, the schedule called for the Senate to
proceed Tuesday at 9 a.m. PST with a motion from House managers to
call witnesses. The managers are expected to seek approval to call
Monica Lewinsky, Clinton's secretary Betty Currie and Clinton
confidant Vernon Jordan, among others. White House attorneys are
opposed to witnesses, but may decide to call their own if the
Senate gives prosecutors permission to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Each side will be provided three hours to make its case, which
will be followed by another closed-door meeting of the senators to
discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Votes will then be held _ probably tomorrow, according to Senate
leaders _ on both the motion to dismiss and the motion to call
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Senate is expected to reject the Democratic effort
to dismiss the charges on a mostly party-line vote, the motion to
call witnesses is expected to be close. If it passes, witnesses
will be deposed in private. Then the Senate would be asked to vote
again on whether each individual witness would be called for live
testimony on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   If the motion to bring witnesses fails, the Senate will move
immediately to the two articles of impeachment, starting with
another closed-door debate and ending in a public vote.
</P>
<P>
   Senate rules require impeachment deliberations to be held in
private meetings, although two Democratic senators, Tom Harkin of
Iowa and Paul Wellstone of Minnesota, offered a motion to overturn
that rule Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The motion was defeated by a 57-to-43 count, the first vote of
the impeachment trial. Both California senators, Dianne Feinstein
and Barbara Boxer, voted in favor of the open debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on dangerous, dangerous ground,'' Harkin told reporters
at an impromptu news conference in front of the main doors of the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame the public's not invited. The microphones in the
chamber were paid for by the American people, to paraphrase Ronald
Reagan,'' said Harkin, referring to a comment Reagan made during a
1980 primary debate in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The motion to dismiss was offered by Byrd, widely regarded as
the Senate's pre-eminent guardian of protocol and tradition and a
senator who Republicans had hoped might vote in favor of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In their argument against the motion, Republicans noted that in
the history of the Senate, no impeachment charge against a
president or judge has ever been dismissed without a vote on the
articles themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me assure you that I want this to be over,'' said
Representative Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark. ``As (Clinton adviser) Bruce
Lindsey sitting over here will probably attest, this is bad for me
politically.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we do have our responsibilities,'' Hutchinson said,
echoing a view repeated by numerous House prosecutors. ``And I
happen to believe that we should follow the process which is
dictated by the Constitution and the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Those facts, Republican managers argued in what may be one of
their final chances to persuade senators, include evidence that
Clinton lied under oath and obstructed justice. It was not just to
save his family embarrassment, they asserted. Clinton chose to
break the law because he knew he was in legal jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're sued for ... sexually harassing somebody, and
they're on to the fact that you can't control yourself enough to
stop it four, five years after you're sued, and you're doing it in
the White House with somebody half your age, I think that would
matter,'' said Representative Lindsey Graham, R-S.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that's the difference between getting bamboozled in
court and having to pay $850,000,'' Graham said, referring to
Clinton's out-of-court settlement with Paula Jones, whose sexual
harassment lawsuit touched off the entire controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers also attacked the notion advanced by White
House lawyers that the alleged crimes do not amount to high crimes
and misdemeanors or pose any threat to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the standard urged by the president's lawyers, the
misdeeds of Richard Nixon would not meet the threshold for
impeachment and removal,'' said Representative Charles Canady,
R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The White House countered that nothing in the case warrants the
removal of the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment has arrived where the best interests of the nation,
the wise prescription of the framers, and the failure of the
managers all point to dismissal,'' said Nicole Seligman, one of
Clinton's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have listened. You have heard. The case cannot be made. It
is time to end it,'' she said on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Seligman reiterated the White House defense made over more than
a dozen hours of testimony last week _ that the facts do not prove
crimes, and even if they did, they do not constitute ``high crimes
and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   She suggested that Clinton is aware of his misdeeds and is
already paying an appropriate penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Punishment will be found elsewhere,'' she said. ``Judgment
will be found elsewhere. Legacies will be written elsewhere. None
of that will be dismissed. None of that can ever be dismissed.''
</P>
<P>
   And she appealed to the Senate to drop the matter and return to
its lawmaking responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also ask you to end this case now so that the poisonous
arrows of partisanship can be buried and the will of the people can
be done, allowing all of you to spend your full days on the most
pressing issues of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle political reporter Carla Marinucci contributed to this
report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
