<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8596 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-WISDOM-NYTSF &LR;      01-26 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WISDOM-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T BE TOO SURE OF A `MARRED' LEGACY FOR CLINTON -- THE
UN-REAGAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)  
 &HT;    
 By JIM CASTELLI  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The conventional wisdom -- the consensus among politicians and
media personalities -- has been consistently wrong about the
scandal surrounding President Clinton's relationship with Monica
Lewinsky.
 &HT;    Those who create such ``wisdom'' have been more concerned with
what they want to happen, or what they think is supposed to happen,
rather than what is actually happening.
 &HT;    That's more than enough reason to question the confident
statements that Bill Clinton has been weakened anddisgraced and his
legacy permanently marred.
 &HT;    Put another way, there is reason to believe that Clinton has, in
fact, been strengthened by the scandal and that his legacy will be
far more positive than anyone now imagines.
 &HT;    To be sure, future historians are hardly likely to talk about
Clinton without referring to his impeachment following a full year
of headlines about a sexual scandal. But that won't be the whole
story.
 &HT;    Andrew Johnson was impeached, but historians now generally agree
that his impeachment was highly partisan and that it was Congress,
not Johnson, who was disgraced.
 &HT;    Historians also generally agree that Richard Nixon would have
been impeached and convicted over Watergate-related offenses, and
would have deserved to be, if he had not resigned.
 &HT;    But Nixon's legacy is far bigger than Watergate. His conduct of
the Vietnam War, detente with the Soviet Union, opening of
relations with Communist China, and his domestic policies -- many
of which would be regarded as dismayingly liberal by today's House
Republicans -- are also part of a very mixed legacy.
 &HT;    Bill Clinton was impeached on virtually a straight party-line
vote in the House, but no one beyond a handful of anti-Clinton true
believers think that the Senate trial will result in conviction. At
worst Clinton will receive a censure, at best (for him), nothing
more than impeachment by the House. If Clinton is still president
when all this is over, he will have won.
 &HT;    The notion that he has been weakened by the scandal ignores
public opinion, which has been consistent and resistant for a year.
The more Republicans attack Clinton, the more the public thinks
positively of Clinton and negatively of the Republicans.
 &HT;    In polls taken after the State of the Union address, anywhere
from 66 percent to 76 percent of Americans approved of Clinton's
job performance -- three times the approval rating Nixon had when
he resigned. The president is the most admired man in America and
his wife the most admired woman.
 &HT;    Clinton's party is fresh from a surprisingly strong showing in
the mid-term elections, and while the Republicans still control
Congress, Clinton is within reach of what Nixon used to callan
ideological majority. The Republicans have already lost two
speakers of the House over the Lewinsky affair, and the Republican
Party has its lowest approval rating in a generation.
 &HT;    The claims that the public won't trust Clinton on other issues
because he lied about Lewinsky don't hold up. Even amid all the
references to ``Wag the Dog,'' the public overwhelmingly believed
that Clinton ordered the bombing of Iraq for the right reasons, not
as a distraction from impeachment.
 &HT;    The public doesn't believe Clinton when he talks about things
they don't want to hear about, but they trust him when it comes to
doing his job.
 &HT;    The public also seems to trust Clinton and the Democrats more
than the Republicans on the issues likely to occupy Congress for
the next two years -- Social Security, Medicare, Medicaid, HMOs and
education.
 &HT;    And that is the irony behind the likelihood that Clinton's
legacy will be positive: Because of Bill Clinton, the American
people once again want government to work for them.
 &HT;    Clinton is the un-Reagan. Ronald Reagan spent eight years in
office downgrading government. He left the sense that government
shouldn't try to do anything, and he left a gigantic deficit that
made it almost impossible to think about government doing anything
new.
 &HT;    George Bush was somewhat less opposed than Reagan to government
trying to do things for people, but he lamented in his Inaugural
Address that America had more will than wallet.He never tried to
find either will or wallet, and the result -- in the face of a
recession -- was a feeling of national despair and 62 percent of
voters throwing Bush out of office.
 &HT;    Clinton came in arguing that there was nothing wrong with
America that couldn't be fixed by what's right with America.He
believed, in effect, that America could find both will and wallet;
he balanced the federal budget while adding new social programs.
 &HT;    Clinton's push for one big program -- a massive health-care
reform -- failed, but he has made major changes in America through
dozens of smaller changes.
 &HT;    Today, people can't lose health insurance because they change
jobs or have pre-existing conditions, and millions more children
have access to health care. Clinton has succeeded in his goal of
making two years of college or technical school affordable for
virtually every American. The controversial welfare reform bill he
signed has -- so far, at least -- moved people from welfare to work
without forcing people into the streets.
 &HT;    Clinton made it intellectually and financially possible, even
desirable, for Americans to once again look to government to do
good things for people. That's why so many conservatives loathe
him. But it's a heck of a legacy.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    Jim Castelli is the author of ``A Plea for Common Sense:
Resolving the Clash Between Religion and Politics'' (Harper &AMP; Row).
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1999 Jim Castelli
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 1021EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8625 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-PATROL-TIPS27-COX     01-26 0191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-PATROL-TIPS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Road problem tips
 &HT;    (EDS: Runs with TEXAS-PATROL)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Courtesy patrol officer Bruce Murphy, a 22-year
police veteran, offers a few tips for dealing with roadside
problems:
</P>
<P>
   _ Avoid leaving the car, if possible. It can be dangerous to
walk along the shoulder. In the age of cellular phones, someone is
likely to call the police to assist you.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you have a flat tire, don't stop on the road. Drive until
you can get your car safely onto a shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   _ Park on the shoulder, not on the grass. A hot engine can
ignite the grass, and soft surfaces make it dangerous to change a
tire.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you've replaced the tire with a ``doughnut,'' or spare,
drive immediately to a gas station and fill the replacement with
air. They can leak while sitting in the trunk.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you're in a minor accident and there are no injuries, move
your car out of traffic. State law requires motorists to move a car
if it can be moved and there are no injuries in the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
