u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-JOBS27-COX     01-26 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-JOBS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Think tank to help conservatives find work
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas Public Policy Foundation, a
conservative think tank based in San Antonio, has set up a job bank
to help conservatives find work in state government now that
Republicans have taken over statewide offices.
</P>
<P>
   Offering advice on everything from writing cover letters to how
to dress for an interview _ men: wear black or dark blue suits and
leave the Rush Limbaugh tie at home; women: stick to simple jewelry
and skirts at or below the knee _ the foundation promises to
``recruit and help place conservative job seekers in suitable
positions'' at no charge.
</P>
<P>
   `` 'Staff is policy' as the old saying goes,'' the foundation
says in the introduction to the job bank section of its web site
(www.tppf.org). ``The challenge for our new conservative elected
leaders is to replace the liberal and patronage employees of their
predecessors with qualified, dedicated and loyal conservatives.''
</P>
<P>
   The job bank is under attack by the foundation's political
nemesis, the Texas Freedom Network, which has scheduled a press
conference today to denounce what it calls a ``far right
ideological litmus test'' for state jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The site asks applicants to circle their political ideology,
from Libertarian to Liberal, and includes a lengthy questionnaire
probing their feelings on everything from gays in the military to
labor unions to decriminalizing marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Judson, the foundation's president, said ten people have
filled out the questionnaires since the job bank went up about two
weeks ago. The foundation will send completed applications to
interested agencies, he said, but they will not recommend any
particular applicant.
</P>
<P>
   No agencies have requested the information or pledged to use the
job bank, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, he said, is to encourage conservatives to interrupt
their private sector jobs for a ``tour of duty'' in state
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been concerned about building the kind of infrastructure
in Texas that the Left has had for 100 years,'' Judson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Freedom Network, founded by Cecile Richards _ former
Gov. Ann Richards' daughter _ to counter religious conservative
influence in state government, has been keeping a close eye on the
political activities of the foundation and its founder, Dr. James
Leininger, who has emerged as one of the state's top contributors
to conservative causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's outrageous, actually,'' Kathy Miller, the group's
deputy director, said of the job bank. ``It raises some very
interesting questions about an individual's power over state
agencies, state policy, who gets hired, who gets fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Judson said Leininger, who is on the foundation's board of
directors and is one of its financial backers, doesn't delve into
the details of the foundation's work: ``Jim probably couldn't tell
you much about (the job bank) at all.''
</P>
<P>
   While Miller said she plans to get a legal opinion about whether
state agencies can hire someone based on answers to political
questions, William Hale, executive director of the Texas Commission
on Human Rights _ the agency that enforces employment
discrimination laws in the state _ said there's nothing in state or
federal law prohibiting questions about a job applicant's politics.
</P>
<P>
   Judson told a San Antonio newspaper columnist earlier this month
that he met with Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander and her staff,
who gave the foundation strong encouragement. Judson said Monday
that a Rylander staffer expressed vague interest in the job bank
but made no commitment to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Elkins, spokesman for the comptroller's office, said
Rylander has been told about the job bank in passing, but ``she has
never endorsed it or indicated in any way that she was going to use
it, and she has not used it.''
</P>
<P>
   That isn't likely to reassure Miller, who noted that Rylander
and several other Republican officeholders are listed as guest
speakers tonight when the Texas Public Policy Foundation holds its
10th Anniversary dinner in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   But from Judson's perspective, the liberals, who have dominated
state government for so long, need to start getting used to
conservatives running things.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Texas Freedom Network and all the candidates they
supported lost, and they just need to buck it up and stop being
sore losers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Harmon writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
