<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPIELBERG-HOLOCAUST27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spielberg's CD-ROM to instruct students on Holocaust
 &HT;    By Sonja Isger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Palm Beach County high school students
will be the first in the country to get their Holocaust lessons
courtesy of Steven Spielberg and have their teachers trained by the
former director of the research institute of the Holocaust Museum
in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg's Shoah Visual History Foundation, based in Los
Angeles, has spent three years documenting the stories of 50,000
Holocaust survivors, including 289 in Palm Beach, Martin, St. Lucie
and Indian River counties in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In March, three teachers from each high school in the county
will gather to learn how to incorporate an educational CD-ROM
produced by Spielberg into their lesson plans. Their teacher will
be Michael Berenbaum, president of Shoah and the former director of
the Holocaust Research Institute of the U.S. Holocaust Museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully we'll be doing this in other school systems, but
this is the first,'' said Janet Keller, Shoah's media relations
manager.
</P>
<P>
   The school district can thank the non-profit Boca Raton,
Fla.-based League for Educational Awareness of the Holocaust for
being at the top of Shoah's list, Keller said. The group's support
of Holocaust education and its persistence in pushing for a Palm
Beach County training session landed a commitment before the
CD-ROM's scheduled release in March, Keller said.
</P>
<P>
   The CD-ROM, which premiered in a New York high school in
October, allows students to see and hear the stories of four
survivors from New York and Los Angeles in their own words, with
photographs of the survivors and their families before, during and
after the war. With the click of a mouse, students can veer from
the testimony to check out timelines of world events and other
information.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with state law, Palm Beach County's students have
learned about the Holocaust for four years. Some have even talked
with local survivors who come to the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a speaker's bureau. And every time we impart this
information, we share it with someone new, we give them a better
understanding,'' said Eileen Shapiro, who heads the district's
Holocaust education. ``Unfortunately, the average age of a survivor
is 76.''
</P>
<P>
   That was part of the reason Spielberg, who directed the Academy
Award-winning Schindler's List, wanted to create such a massive
archive of recollections, Keller said. The $69 CD-ROM that each
Palm Beach County high school will receive is just one of the
educational materials Shoah produces that are available not just to
schools but other institutions, Keller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holocaust education is about to be revolutionized,'' Keller
said. ``We are making it possible for them to speak to future
generations forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The tab to train the head of each school's library, social
studies and English departments and supply the CD-ROMs comes to
$20,000. That will be split between the district and LEAH, Shapiro
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Steven Spielberg knows how to get his audience,'' Shapiro
said. ``The CD-ROM is narrated by Winona Ryder and Leonardo
DiCaprio. Kids will want to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sonja Isger writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
