<HEADER>
A8630 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-PATROL27-COX     01-26 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-PATROL27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Little known service offers big help for motorists in need
 &HT;    (EDS: Runs with TEX-PATROL-TIPS.)
 &HT;    By Debbie Hiott
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Matthew MacMorran was struggling with an
uncooperative lug nut on the right-front wheel of his Ford pickup
when Bruce Murphy pulled up behind him in the inside breakdown lane
of MoPac Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes before, MacMorran had been trying to avoid being hit by
cars that whizzed by only feet away as he tried to change a flat
tire in the middle of heavy traffic. Even after police officer
Bruce Spence closed off the nearest lane of traffic, the work was
still taking time and slowing traffic. Frustrated drivers had begun
honking their horns.
</P>
<P>
   So when Murphy offered to help, MacMorran gladly wiped his
tire-greased hands and watched as Murphy finished the job in less
than 10 minutes with an air gun.
</P>
<P>
   MacMorran didn't know who Murphy was or why he was helping, but
it turns out the help didn't come from the average good Samaritan.
Murphy's job is to roam area highways and help stranded motorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never knew they had this courtesy patrol thing,'' MacMorran
said after thanking Murphy. ``I know I would have been out here a
lot longer if he hadn't come along.''
</P>
<P>
   Spence was also grateful Murphy came along. ``It's definitely a
whole lot simpler when you've got the right tools,'' Spence said.
``A lot of times (the courtesy patrol) can get things moving a
whole lot faster.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the idea behind the state Transportation Department's
2-year-old program. The courtesy patrol, made up of four drivers
and a supervisor, scans area highways for anything that will
slowtraffic, whether it's a stranded motorist or a pile of wood in
the road. It's not just about courtesy. The goal of the $250,000 a
year program is to improve traffic flow in congested areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know, because of limited funds and different problems
building new roads, that we have to make the best of what we
have,'' said Sam Cox, the former Austin police sergeant who now
heads up the courtesy patrol. ``We're trying to keep the roadways
running more efficiently.''
</P>
<P>
   Population growth in the region has led to major traffic
increases. For example, the average daily traffic on Interstate 35
near U.S. 183 increased almost 40 percent between 1990 and 1997.
Travis County averages more than 12,500 traffic accidents a year,
and when those occur on major highways, they can tie up traffic for
hours. Smaller incidents, such as vehicles with flat tires or those
that have stalled, can also slow the flow.
</P>
<P>
   While MacMorran's truck was disabled, one lane of MoPac was
closed to traffic, and gawkers slowed things even more, creating
lines of cars, bumper to bumper, from just north of 45th Street all
the way south of the 35th Street exit. But within minutes after the
pickup was on its way, traffic flowed smoothly again.
</P>
<P>
   Unsung hero
</P>
<P>
   Cox said many people don't know about the service, although the
courtesy patrollers help thousands of motorists in a year.
</P>
<P>
   From Sept. 1 to Dec. 31, the patrol members handled 1,721 calls.
In that time, they changed 285 flat tires, refueled 103 cars,
removed debris from the roads 247 times, assisted in clearing 125
accidents, gave mechanical assistance to stranded drivers 249 times
and pushed stalled cars from the road 79 times.
</P>
<P>
   The program is modeled after similar patrols in Fort Worth and
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said the department hopes to expand the patrol to put more
vehicles on the streets and has asked the Austin Police Department
to help pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every stalled car we take off the expressway is a stalled car
the police don't have to deal with,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, a 22-year veteran of the New York Police Department who
moved to the Austin area two years ago, says the reaction of the
people he helps is the best part of the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the few jobs where people are glad to see you,''
Murphy said. ``Usually when they see the state, someone's holding
them up working on a road.''
</P>
<P>
   Beating the streets
</P>
<P>
   Murphy's work day begins when the morning is still dark and the
streets are almost empty, as he checks over the patrol truck loaded
with everything from heavy tools to kitty litter for oil spills to
duct tape, which Murphy dubs ``the all-American cure-all.''
</P>
<P>
   Around 6 a.m. he pulls out of the statedistrict office near U.S.
183 and I-35 to begin scanning the roads for drivers who need help.
During rush hour, the courtesy patrol focuses on I-35, where on the
average day there are more than enough stalled cars and accidents
to keep the two courtesy trucks busy. The patrol divides the city
into two parts, north and south, with the boundary at 51st Street,
and after rush hour, they branch out onto other state roads such as
RM 620 and Loop 1.
</P>
<P>
   The calls vary from day to day. There are the mundane stops to
fix a flat or fill an empty gas tank. There are times when police
need help managing an accident scene. And then there are times when
the courtesy patrol arrives first to determine what's wrong: a man
who has had a heart attack, a woman who is crippled by a migraine.
</P>
<P>
   One day, it was a van full of Bible school students and a
teacher. They had watched car after car pass their van with a flat
tire on I-35 near U.S. 183. The teacher later told Murphy that she
turned to higher intervention when even a police car passed without
stopping. But the police officer had called for the courtesy
patrol, and moments later Murphy rolled up to relieved faces. The
teacher greeted him eagerly.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `We just finished our prayer and you pulled up,' ''
Murphy said. ``She told the children it worked.'' One of the
hardest parts of the job, Murphy said, is convincing the drivers he
helps that he can't accept a tip and there is no fee for the
program, which is supported with taxpayer money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing we're out here for is safety,'' Murphy said.
``Courtesy patrol is what I want on the road when my wife's car
breaks down.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
