<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-NYC-ADULT27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio city looks to Big Apple for guidance on X-rated business
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Dayton is studying whether it can enact a New
York City-style ordinance that limits where adult-oriented
businesses can operate.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court this month upheld New York City's law
that forced many X-rated businesses out of Times Square. Mayor Mike
Turner hailed the court's decision and would like to see a similar
ordinance here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very exciting the U.S. Supreme Court has finally given
us the tools to deal with this,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   New York decided to challenge the businesses as neighborhood
blights instead of focusing on obscenity. The law required
adult-oriented theaters, bookstores and dance bars to be at least
500 feet from each other, homes, churches or certain businesses. It
gave the businesses a year to move.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton has had see-saw battles against adult businesses for
decades and has unsuccessfully charged bookstore operators for
pandering obscenity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will not totally prohibit operation of these businesses
in the city but it would require their closure and relocation away
from neighborhoods and commercial districts,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton's effort comes as Ohio's Troy, Franklin, Washington Twps.
and other communities seek to limit where adult businesses can
operate.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Sirkin, a Cincinnati attorney who represents the owners of
Total Xposure in Troy and Diamonds Cabaret in Washington Twp., said
Ohio law might prohibit Dayton from enacting a New York-style law.
</P>
<P>
   New York allowed businesses one year to pay off the debts they
incurred in opening before they had to shut down and move. Ohio law
does not allow for so-called amortization, Sirkin said, and has
allowed adult-oriented businesses to stay open on the same property
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Any attempt to alter that would be challenged in court, Sirkin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton already uses zoning laws to restrict where new adult
businesses can operate, Sirkin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have not been any increase in adult uses for a very long
time (in Dayton),'' Sirkin said. ``The stores on Third Street and
the stores on Fifth Street have been there for a very long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bebbington writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
