<HEADER>
A8633 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINTER-FARMING27-COX     01-26 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINTER-FARMING27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Winter weather doubles farmers' workloads
 &HT;    By Scott Elliott
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Cows aren't any better at walking on a sheet of
ice than people, which is why Casstown, Ohio farmer Clyde Musser
cringed every time he checked on his cattle during the winter
storms this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The barnyard was covered with ice and the cows were sliding
around like they were wearing roller skates,'' he said. ``It hasn't
been a very healthy situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Musser's 30 cows are important to his livelihood, and caring for
them through the extremes of winter is hard work. Jeff Layman, Ohio
State extension agent for agriculture in Miami County, said winter
months present several challenges for farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ups and downs of winter cause a lot of problems _ whether
it's keeping animals healthy, making sure water supplies don't
freeze, watching for moisture in grain storage or even just
starting a diesel engine,'' Layman said.
</P>
<P>
   David Demmitt cares for 100 full-grown cows and 75 calves at his
farm near Troy, Ohio. Snow, ice and mud mean long hours, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really doubles our workload with the cows,'' Demmitt said.
``Our two main goals are keeping the cows warm and dry and keeping
them clean to protect milk quality.''
</P>
<P>
   When the animals are wet and cold they can become ill, he said,
and frozen surfaces can cause cows to slip and be injured. An extra
35 to 40 bales of straw must be brought to the barns each day so
cows don't have to feed in the field.
</P>
<P>
   The storm that hit around New Year's Day came from the east,
creating extra complications for farms with buildings that are
constructed to protect against Ohio storms that generally come from
the west or north, said Jerry Mahan, Ohio State extension agent for
agriculture in Greene County.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a different kind of storm,'' Mahan said. ``Those are
usually the worst ones. The snow drifted in ways you wouldn't
normally expect.''
</P>
<P>
   During a major storm, farmers must keep a constant watch on the
delicate systems that are vital to their operations. Demmitt heats
the farm's water pipes to them prevent freezing, but malfunctions
or ice still pose potential problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to keep water from freezing and keep everything
working,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller farms with less technology often suffer most during
winter storms, Mahan said. In Greene County, Mahan heard from
several farmers who were saddled with frozen pipes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating for those guys to have to dig them up and
repair them,'' he said. ``But the animals must have something to
drink.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who grow crops, selling their corn or grain is always
a guessing game. To get a better price, farmers may store some of
their products through the winter. For them, blowing snow can be
devastating.
</P>
<P>
   If snow blows in through vents and piles on top of stored grain,
the snow must be removed before it melts. Water dripping down into
the grain can cause mold and spoil the entire supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to keep constantly monitoring it,'' Casstown farmer
Carl Shoup said. ``I take a load out every once in a while just to
check it. If it gets out of condition, nobody wants it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoup, who farms 1,150 acres, has about 35,000 bushels of corn
and grain stored while he waits for a good opportunity to sell.
</P>
<P>
   He also worries about floodwater that flowed around his farm
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have so much water, you have some erosion,'' he said.
``It's too early to tell if there has been any damage. We'll just
have to get out there in the spring and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Elliott writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
