</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High-fee DRIPs not much of a bargain
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DRIPs _ dividend reinvestment plans _ have been unbeatable
bargains for small-time stock buyers like you and me for years.
Many of them still are.
</P>
<P>
   But some companies are doing the all-American thing: tacking on
new services and raising their fees. You may or may not want the
services, but you can't avoid the fees.
</P>
<P>
   At worst, a company may charge you $5, plus 5 cents or more per
share, to add to your DRIP account. That's unbearable if you want
to invest, say, $50 a month in the company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, it's no longer enough to be a willing buyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You also have to be a more careful shopper now,'' said Billy
Williams, president of the Atlanta area organization of private
investment clubs. ``You have to ask whether it's worth the premium.
And a lot of people are saying, `No.'''
</P>
<P>
   A DRIP is a way to buy stock directly from the issuing company,
without going through a broker and paying a sales fee. Dividends
are automatically used to buy more shares, and investors also can
make cash payments to buy yet more shares.
</P>
<P>
   DRIPs have become popular with low-dollar investors _ people who
can afford to invest perhaps $25 or $50 a month and want to watch
their investments grow steadily.
</P>
<P>
   The fees are changing things, however. They can include purchase
fees, annual account maintenance fees and even fees for selling
your shares.
</P>
<P>
   One explanation for such fees is that companies, and the
transfer agents they hire to handle the accounts, are entitled to
make a buck wherever they can. A more charitable explanation is
they are simply covering their costs.
</P>
<P>
   Charles B. Carlson, editor of the DRIP Investor newsletter in
Hammond, Ind., estimates that the cost of administering an account
runs $12 to $16 a year. ``This is a cost-conscious corporate
America we have today,'' he said. ``They're looking for ways to
defray the cost of servicing these shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all companies have high charges for the DRIPs, however. Vita
Nelson, who edits The DRP Authority, another newsletter in the
field, estimates that 200 have notable fees. Well over 1,000
companies have DRIPs.
</P>
<P>
   The fees usually are accompanied by extra services. Companies
may offer opportunities to buy shares daily or weekly. You may be
able to sell shares over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies will set up an individual retirement account, and
some allow investors to borrow against shares in their accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Two Web sites, one associated with each of the newsletters
mentioned above, will give conscientious shoppers a start. They are
http://www.netstockdirect.com and http://www.moneypaper.com.
</P>
<P>
   You will find links to many companies with DRIPs and assistance
in buying shares in some of those companies. The Moneypaper site
also pitches a new mutual fund restricted to a set of companies
that offer low-cost DRIPs. Note that the expense ratio can go as
high as 1.25 percent. That may well come down as the fund matures,
but it is high for bargain-hungry stock buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Also note that since those Web sites don't always have all the
details about DRIPs, serious shoppers may need to ask the companies
for further information.
</P>
<P>
   Among low-cost DRIPs, Carlson lists these favorites: Regions
Financial, Exxon, Johnson Controls, Finova Group and Philadelphia
Suburban.
</P>
<P>
   Among higher-fee companies, Nelson points to Aetna, Air
Products, Dayton Hudson and McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   There are some ways to lower the impact of DRIP fees:
</P>
<P>
   _ Shop carefully and switch to companies that don't charge high
fees.
</P>
<P>
   How much is too much? ``I would think that when it's more than
10 percent, that's getting pretty high,'' said Williams. A $5 fee
on a $50 purchase would be out of limits for him.
</P>
<P>
   _ Consider quarterly rather than monthly investments. Reducing
the number of purchases also reduces the cost.
</P>
<P>
   _ Go to automatic investments, which means authorizing the
company to take a given amount from your checking account each
month. The purchase fee is usually lower, typically falling from $5
to $2 per transaction.
</P>
<P>
   _ Consider dumping the whole idea and buying instead through a
discount broker.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga. E-mail:hezell(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
