<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Potty training vs. life training
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ My 31-year-old son called this afternoon for
a check-up and a chat - we chat while he checks up on me. He thinks
I don't know what he's up to. Hesitantly, I ask how things are
going for him. Terrific, he says. Couldn't be better, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Not true, I say. ``You just think you're all right,'' I warn,
``but the truth of it is, you're immature and will probably develop
behavior problems later in life because I didn't assert myself when
I was potty training you.'' A split-second of silence is quickly
followed by hilarity as he asks what kind of a book I've gotten
into this time. This kid knows me too well.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, I've been reading an article by a psychologist who
insists that wishy-washy mommys who are unable to give up their
role as caretaker (changing diapers) to assume that of an authority
figure (potty training) have wrecked their kids. ``Thanks to me,''
I whimper apologetically, ``you're probably constipated and suffer
from bladder-control problems. Hell, I may even be responsible for
your morning breath.''
</P>
<P>
   He tells me to relax. ``I think you did just fine, Mom. I have
none of the symptoms you mentioned and don't forget how much fun
you have telling large gatherings of people about my toilet
training.''
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, my cerebral approach to housebreaking the child was
a little odd, but I liked the nonconfrontational idea of having a
meeting of the minds as opposed to two people spending tense hours
in the bathroom while the taller of the pair tries to convince the
shorter one he has to pee.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how we did it: First we shopped for a potty chair. He
chose a streamlined model with a lid. We put it in his bathroom
next to the real thing. He was tickled pink with it. He stuck his
head in it, put the cat in it, and stored his Matchbox cars in it.
But never considered sitting on it.
</P>
<P>
   It was time, I decided, for an intellectual meeting of the minds
(bribery). ``Kristofor, how'd you like some underpants like
Papa's?'' Yep, he'd like that. ``It means you'd have to use the
toilet.'' Nope, he wouldn't like that. I told him to let me know
when it was time to shop for his ``Big boy'' pants. He agreed and
continued to use his potty chair as a garage.
</P>
<P>
   One morning, a couple of months later, he rousted me out of bed
at sun-up and gleefully announced he was pretty sure it was time to
ditch the diapers. ``But first,'' he said, ``my gots to see
sumpin', OK?''
</P>
<P>
   OK. We filed down the hall to his bathroom where he asked me to
take off his diapers so he could measure. Measure what, I asked as
I unpinned. ``Gots to see if I can reach.'' Now I understood what
he'd been waiting for. He wasn't going to do it at all until he
could do it right. The little potty was cool for trucks and Siamese
cats, but it was the big potty that was going to make him a man
like his papa.
</P>
<P>
   The good doctor says what makes such an antiquated approach to
toilet training (mine) so silly is the fact that it could be a snap
if moms would heed his ``naked and $75'' technique. That's where
you take off the kid's diaper, put a potty within reach and wait
for the inevitable accident to happen. When it does you put the kid
on the pot and use the 75 bucks to have the carpet cleaned. ``Kids
that age hate to have `it' running down their legs,'' he explains,
so they train themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Baloney! Two-year-olds will wallow in mud and wail when Mom
washes it off. And hasn't the Doc ever seen a kid who's been eating
waffles refuse to wash his hands because he likes having his
fingers stuck to his palm?
</P>
<P>
   Kristofor reassures me that he is functioning normally and
seldom has the urge to suck his thumb or rob a bank. That's good
enough for me.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Address mail: 320
West Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email:
eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
