</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wonderful idea spawns event that has hooked thousands
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Vinnie's fish was loose. The little boy in the
high-backed wheelchair had, literally, a lap full of trout for a
moment.
</P>
<P>
   What sensations were going through that mind: Of droplets
spritzed from a wiggling tail to his cheeks. Of that
never-to-mistake, current-fresh smell.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteer David Dover picked the 6-incher up from off the floor
and held it thrashing to Vinnie's cupped hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to keep it? Or put it back?''
</P>
<P>
   A nod and a smile are Vinnie's chief means of expression. He
nodded more vigorously at ``put it back.'' Dover returned it to the
tank.
</P>
<P>
   At the Really Big Fishing Event for Really Special People,
bringing home a trophy, or frying-pan fodder, was way down the list
of prizes.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake. A lot of those fish were going to get eaten. A
crack team of fish cleaners from Baylor's KOT fraternity did
nothing but clean from start to finish. Talk about service above
and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   That's been the theme of this event since its inception _ of
good people stepping forward to do right by fellow human beings
they've never met, and who they wouldn't meet otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday close to 1,000 disabled people fished, while 525
volunteers helped. The fisherpersons came from as far away as Tyler
and Georgetown for the special moments this event provides. The
idea was hatched 11 years ago as a lone fishing tank in the corner
of a room. Now it's an extravaganza with karaoke, dancing, a photo
studio with a grab-bag of disguises, and food, food, food.
</P>
<P>
   Waco resident Gary Beeson and Baylor student Sarah Borum were
talking with their mouths full. Beeson is deaf. Borum is studying
sign language at Baylor. She came just to be a part of what fellow
Kappas were doing to help out. She ended up escorting Beeson
through the event as they engaged in lively conversation
unencumbered by chili dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Fabian is blind, in Waco for computer training at the VA
Medical Center. Minnesota is home. As such, he clearly was
relishing the sinking of a line in January without having to bore
through ice. He also was enjoying jawing with anyone and everyone,
in the great fisherman's tradition.
</P>
<P>
   McLennan County Constable Travis Bailey and Butch Shaw, who runs
Heart of Texas Industries for the Texas Department of Mental-Health
Mental Retardation, can claim shares of responsibility for the
runaway success of this event.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, a fishing fanatic, was at the first such fishing event
in 1988 sponsored by the Governor's Committee for the Disabled. It
was an inspired notion, to give people who never get such chances
their first taste of a cherished sport. When the idea didn't get
picked up for a second year, Bailey stepped up. He ended up, with
the hard work of many key players like the Optimist Club of Waco,
managing the whole kettle of fish.
</P>
<P>
   But the story Saturday wasn't about fish. It was about human
contact, and mist on cheeks, and feelings that, once felt, are
forever, like the first pull on a line.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is editorial page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald,
Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
