<HEADER>
A8637 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PEPPER27-COX     01-26 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PEPPER27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pepper is golf's Mrs. October
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Dottie Pepper was steamed. For weeks,
she had been looking forward to watching the Presidents Cup. She
had even planned her daily schedule around when the action in
Australia would be televised back to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But the most successful woman in international golf competition
was soon wishing she had made alternate plans. It wasn't just that
the International team trashed the favored Americans, 20.5-11.5; it
was the ease with which the Americans seemed to take the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a lot of uninspired play,'' Pepper said. ``It just
seemed like they didn't have much flair. I don't know if you get
that from your captain or from something you read before the match
or it's just sort of in-bred. I was just real disappointed with
what I saw.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepper, who recently moved to Jupiter, Fla., is the LPGA's
version of Mr. October _ saving her A game for the Solheim Cup. She
has won 14 LPGA events (but none since 1996), was Player of the
Year in 1992 and is sixth in career earnings ($4.51 million). But
she has earned greater notoriety in recent years for her emotional
_ and sometimes controversial _ play in the Solheim.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper went 4-0 last year while leading the Americans to a 16-12
victory over the Europeans, making the 33-year-old the winningest
player in Solheim competition (12-4-1). With her qualifications
(and history of saying what's on her mind), Pepper was asked why
the American men keep getting upset in the Presidents and Ryder
cups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're a little spoiled to begin with,'' she said.
``When you can go out and not win a tournament and still make $1
million, I think that makes you pretty comfortable. It's also hard
when you walk in with 12 of the best players in the world ... there
are egos involved and there's no room for that. They (the U.S.
team) needed something to get them going.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a punching bag, perhaps? That's what Pepper was being used
as by the Europeans at the Solheim. The fiery New York native
angered the Europeans for allegedly inciting the pro-American
gallery to root against her opponents at a key moment late in the
second day. Afterward, in the European team's locker room, Laura
Davies and Annika Sorenstam took turns pummeling an inflatable
punching bag, with Sorenstam imploring her teammates to join her in
imagining it was Pepper's face on the bag.
</P>
<P>
   Four months later, Pepper still shakes her head and wonders what
she did wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up Sunday morning and I glanced at the paper and said,
`Gee, do I have an evil twin or what?' '' Pepper said. ``All I know
is this: When you're getting beat, you're going to find something
to get your team turned around. They went looking. When the English
media comes up to me and apologizes to me for what was drummed up,
that tells me a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's Pepper, too _ telling a lot. With a demeanor every
bit as saucy as her name, Pepper has become one of the LPGA's most
outspoken and talented players.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who watches her this week in The Office Depot at Ibis
Golf &AMP; Country Club will see she talks the way she plays golf, with
bulldog-type tenacity, sometimes filling the air with a ``Dang it,
Dottie,'' after a mediocre shot. When she gets in contention, her
stare could rival Raymond Floyd's.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a very intense player and sometimes that rubs people the
wrong way,'' said Juli Inkster, Pepper's closest friend on tour.
``She takes her golf very seriously, and there's nothing wrong with
that. I think she's great for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepper's husband, Ralph Scarinzi, who caddied for her for about
three years before they got married, said Dottie's competitive
exuberance isn't really out of place in sports. It's just that
she's looked at differently because of her gender.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at Tiger (Woods), and some of what he does when he
executes a good shot or makes a putt, throwing his fist up in the
air, it's no different. But Dottie not's supposed to do that
because she's a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Scarinzi said he stopped caddying for his wife last summer
because they needed separation of work and home life. Sort of the
worlds-colliding theory.
</P>
<P>
   Having seen Pepper's personality from all angles, he knows it
might help if she were to lighten up. But he knows that's not about
to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'd like to see her have a little more fun on the golf
course and not take everything as life and death,'' he said. ``But
I don't know how successful she'll be if she changed. But how long
a career can you have this way?''
</P>
<P>
   Pepper and Scarinzi moved their residence from South Carolina to
the Loxahatchee Club last December, buying a house owned by Jackie
Nicklaus. Pepper says one of the main reasons she headed south was
to try to make sure her game didn't follow the same direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're trying to prepare in a place where the average
temperature is 50 degrees, I don't think that's real conducive to
being ready to play in January,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she has anything to apologize for. Although she hasn't
won since a torrid stretch in 1996 (four victories in a 10-week
span), last year she was 10th on the money list and second in
scoring (70.46, which was a third of a stroke lower than when she
won Player of the Year honors in '92).
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't see a problem with how I've played the last two
years,'' she said. ``I may not have played well in 1997 by my
standards, but I had a lot going on.''
</P>
<P>
   In May '95 Pepper was divorced from Doug Mochrie, whom she had
known since she was 13, and married while attending Furman. By '97,
Pepper was romantically involved with Ralph Scarinzi, who had been
her caddy for three years. They married last January, and Scarinzi
stopped carrying her bag last summer. (To the delight of headline
writers, Pepper is back using her maiden name.)
</P>
<P>
   Pepper's preparations for this year were slowed, however, when
she had minor surgery on two toes on her right foot and the index
finger on her left hand. She's been practicing for only two weeks,
so it might be another slow start.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'll win again soon,'' Inkster says. ``I think she's settled
in now, getting married. I think she's more at ease with herself.''
</P>
<P>
   But this Pepper will never be bland on the golf course. She may
play her grand piano at home, spend time in her garden, walk her
pet dog named Furman and sip from her wine collection. But this is
not a sign she's changing and mellowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm comfortable with my reputation,'' she said. ``I think it
takes people to be outspoken because this tour can be a lot better,
but it takes people really caring about it to make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Dolch writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
