<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8638 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-ORR-BURE27-COX     01-26 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ORR-BURE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Orr a Bure admirer
 &HT;    By Al Tays
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ There's no mistaking the emotion in
Bobby Orr's voice, even through a telephone line. Whether he's
talking about his admiration for new Florida Panther Pavel Bure,
his fond memories of playing junior hockey or his opposition to
those who say hockey has become too violent, the former NHL
superstar and Tequesta resident speaks with joyous passion about
his favorite game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our game,'' he repeatedly calls it, and you know he isn't
about to let go of it.
</P>
<P>
   Orr, 50, spoke with reporters last week as part of a promotion
for Canadian junior hockey. When he wasn't reminiscing about his
days as a teenager playing for the Oshawa Generals, he talked about
being a Palm Beach County resident watching the Florida Panthers on
TV and going to the occasional game at the National Car Rental
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, he's been very excited about what he's seen, especially
from the Panthers' new superstar, Bure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Florida made a great deal (with Vancouver to acquire
Bure),'' Orr said. ``Pavel . . . he's not even in shape yet, so you
haven't seen a thing yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are going to love this kid. He's a heck of a player and
he's a great young man. He's going to be great not only on the ice
but in the community with the kids and with the fans.''
   Orr marveled at Bure's debut last Wednesday, in which he scored
two goals against the New York Islanders after a 10-hour flight
from Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a pretty good start,'' Orr said with a laugh, ``for a
kid that just flew over from Russia right to New York and gets on
the ice and scores two. But he's a special, special player. He's up
there with all the best players in the league. I think Bill
(Panthers president Bill Torrey) and his crew made a great deal.
</P>
<P>
   Orr agrees with Panthers coach Terry Murray that Bure's mere
presence will elevate the play of his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question,'' he said. ``Wayne Gretzky makes everybody better
around him. So do Mario (Lemieux) and all the great players.
There's no question Pavel Bure will make everybody better around
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know you're going to get a goal or two a night from him _
on an average _ so it makes you feel pretty good. Florida's having
a little trouble scoring, but he's going to score plenty and you'll
see other players start to put it in also.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the NHL style of play that resulted in nearly two
dozen player suspensions the first half of the season, Orr was
quick to differentiate between rough play and dirty play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some things do happen in our game that we don't like to see,''
he said, ``the hitting from behind, the high sticking . . . but
overall, I don't look at our game as being violent. There's some
stupidity, which we must get out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot get our game to the point where nobody wants to hit.
Hitting is a very, very important part of the game _ good, clean
bodychecks. I played with Johnny Bucyk in Boston, and 'Chief' won
the Lady Byng Trophy for gentlemanly play. Yet he hit guys harder
than anybody I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Orr said the solution to eliminating dirty play is simple,
consistent enforcement of the rules. ``The high-sticking, the
hitting from behind, the kicking the skates out _ there's no place
in our game for that,'' he said. ``And that's what we've got to be
working on. We have rules in the rule book _ enforce them. If we
enforce them, players are going to know, 'Hey, I can't do that.'
But one night (the officials) might let it go and the next night
they don't, so players, they don't know what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think our game is violent. I don't think that at all.
Hockey is a tough game. There are big men out there. In the old
days you might get a big player or two on a team, but they weren't
very fast and they couldn't catch you. Today they're all big and
they can all catch you.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Tays writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
