<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8639 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-PIPPEN-ROCKETS27-     01-26 1366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PIPPEN-ROCKETS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pippen opens second act
 &HT;    By Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The National Basketball Association's greatest sideman
might have an opportunity to command a more prominent part of the
stage, but Scottie Pippen said he is satisfied to blend in with the
Houston Rockets, just as he did for most of his 11 years in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   As Pippen moves to the next phase of his career after a trade to
the Rockets, inquiring minds want to know if will emerge from the
engulfing shadow of Michael Jordan only to run beside one cast by
Hakeem Olajuwon. Will Pippen drive the Houston Rockets to a third
NBA championship, or does he prefer to ride shotgun, the more
familiar position? Maybe the two players will take turns steering.
</P>
<P>
   The early indications are that Pippen is deferential.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team revolves around Hakeem,'' Pippen said. ``This is his
team. I'm not putting any pressure on myself to carry the team. If
it's going to happen, it will happen naturally. This is an
established team with some great players. There's no reason to go
out and disrupt the chemistry they've worked so hard for.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen, 33, has made a nice career as a complementary player,
one judged in 1996 by a panel of voters to be among the top 50 in
NBA history, a status shared by his new teammates Olajuwon and
Charles Barkley. Pippen has been more than some functional role
player, someone to be replaced when a younger part came along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel we have the most complete player in basketball playing
for us now,'' Rockets Coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``There isn't
anything on a basketball court Scottie can't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen's career averages for 11 years of 18 points, 6.8 rebounds
and 5.3 assists do not tell his story adequately. A slender,
long-limbed athletic forward/guard, the 6-foot-7-inch Pippen has
been named to the NBA's all-defensive first team seven times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there's a better defensive player in
understanding visualization of what the opponent's about,''
Pippen's coach with the Bulls, Phil Jackson said. ``He's a one-man
wrecking crew.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics judging Pippen have often pointed out that he failed to
win a championship when Jordan was retired during the 1993-94
season and after Jordan returned in time for the playoffs in
1994-95. But one of their former teammates, Steve Kerr, is not sure
how Jordan would have fared without Pippen, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``As great as Michael was, there's no question without Scottie,
he wouldn't have been able to win six titles,'' said Kerr, now with
the San Antonio Spurs. ``He might have been able to pull off one or
two, I don't know, but Scottie was the key to our team defensively.
He was really our point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Scottie,'' Kerr said. ``He's one of my favorite
teammates of all time. He's so unselfish. I think a lot of players
down there will be pretty happy to have him.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when word came to the Rockets that Pippen will joint
them, veteran Eddie Johnson said, ``Scottie's definitely the best
all-around player in the league now. He hasn't gotten his just due
because he's had to play with Jordan all this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, who helped recruit Pippen to the Rockets said,
``Scottie can take over games. He did it for the Bulls a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen was not always cast in the subordinate role. He averaged
career-highs in scoring (22 points) and rebounds (8.7) when Jordan
was off chasing curve balls in 1993-94. But the Bulls lost to New
York in the second round of the playoffs, a series that included
the most embarrassing moment of Pippen's career. In the third game
of the Eastern Conference semifinals, he refused to return to the
court with 1.8 seconds left when Coach Phil Jackson designed a play
for Toni Kukoc instead of Pippen, the kind of decision that can
scar an athlete for life. With Pippen on the bench, Kukoc made the
game-winning shot.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen later acknowledged that he made a ``stupid mistake.''
Asked last season if he fears that less than two seconds of his
career might leave a disproportionately-sized mark on his legacy,
Pippen said, ``I don't care if they forget it or not. I think I've
had a great career overall.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident is one of several calamities on Pippen's resume
along with the points, rebounds, assists and accolades. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   _In the 1990 Eastern Conference finals, he suffered a migraine
headache that caused blurred vision. He played 40 minutes during a
defeat for the Bulls, but some labeled him a quitter.
</P>
<P>
   _He criticized Bulls management for pursuing Kukoc, a star in
Europe, during the early 1990s, offering him more money that Pippen
was getting paid. Pippen was so fixated on Kukoc that he asked for
the job of guarding him during the 1992 Olympics when the U.S. team
faced Yugoslavia. Pippen wanted to ``get at him because I couldn't
get at (Bulls' general manager Jerry) Krause,'' he told the Chicago
Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   _While he was out of the lineup for the first 35 games last
season after undergoing surgery on his left foot, Pippen said he
had no intention of ever playing for the Bulls again because the
organization did not show him the proper respect. Pippen went so
far as to imply he was faking the injury because he was angry with
the Bulls' management.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen has been justifiably upset with his relatively meager
pay. He earned $2.8 million last season, only fifth-highest on his
team and 122nd in the league. But critics, while acknowledging that
slight, suggested Pippen reacted immaturely. It was perhaps
Pippen's mistake to sign a contract in 1991for less money than he
deserved and his misfortune that Bulls' owner Jerry Reinsdorf has a
policy not to renegotiate.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen finally has a large contract _ $67 million over five
years with another possible $15 million through incentive clauses.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen worked long and hard for this reward, but then he has had
to fight for everything. He might be the biggest success story in
the NBA. Pippen was 6-1 and 135 pounds when he graduated from
Hamburg (Ark.) High. No one offered him an athletic scholarship.
When his high school coach called the University of Central
Arkansas and said he had this kid with potential, the college
offered him a work-study grant under the condition that he would
become the team's manager. Pippen swept the gym floor, washed
uniforms, averaged 4 points and 3 rebounds a game.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, he had grown to 6-7 though still thin. He
averaged 24 points and 10 rebounds and impressed pro scouts at NBA
camps, where he competed against more prominent college players
from bigger schools. Seattle selected Pippen with the fifth pick of
the 1987 draft and sent him to the Bulls in exchange for the rights
to the No. 8 pick, Olden Polynice, and future draft considerations.
</P>
<P>
   Since joining the league, Pippen's highlights have far
superceded his mistakes in judgement. Case in point:
</P>
<P>
   _He contributed 32 points, 13 rebounds, seven assists and five
steals in the last game of the 1991 NBA Finals against the Los
Angeles Lakers, helping Chicago secure its first of six
championships.
</P>
<P>
   _His averages of 18.1 points and 7.7 rebounds in the playoffs
and 19 points and 8.3 rebounds in the NBA Finals are higher than
for the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   _He displayed great versatility by effectively guarding Indiana
point guard Mark Jackson during the Eastern Conference finals last
season.
</P>
<P>
   For an encore, Pippen played in the finals against Utah with
unbearable pain from a back injury that would require off-season
surgery. He could barely move during the decisive sixth game.
Pippen, whose courage was questioned early in his career, was now
considered tough and brave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real measurement of Scottie was against Utah,'' former
Bulls center Bill Cartwright later said. ``Most players would have
just stayed in the locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was the star, of course, the one who stole the ball from
Karl Malone and then made the winning shot. But Pippen was right
there, too, the game's greatest sideman.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rosner writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
