<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Impeachment, Super Bowl, it's all the same
 &HT;    By Frank Cerrabino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ For the first time in its 33-year
history, the Super Bowl will be played while an impeached American
president is on trial in the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   You may think this is coincidental. You may even imagine that
the two events, each of them grand spectacles on the American
stage, have no connections or similarities.
</P>
<P>
   But you probably haven't given this as much thought as I have.
</P>
<P>
   If you did, you'd see that the connection between these two
pageants might seem tenuous at first. But not when you take a
deeper look.
</P>
<P>
   Starr. . .
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl: Bart
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment: Ken
</P>
<P>
   Balding Former-Player-Turned Pundit. . .
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl: Terry Bradshaw
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment: James Carville
</P>
<P>
   Up with People. . .
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl: perennial half-time show.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment: Clinton's poll numbers
</P>
<P>
   Tough on Patriots. . .
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl: New England is 0-2 in Super Bowls, losing by a
combined score of 81-31.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment: Hypocrisy makes country a laughingstock abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The Importance of Rush Defense. . .
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl: In Super Bowl XXVI, the Washington Redskins held
Buffalo's Thurman Thomas, the AFC's best runner, to 13 yards
rushing in 10 carries.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment: Limbaugh's radio talk-show, a daily forum for
pro-impeachment forces, is blunted by Clinton's allies who are
given ``talking points'' to refute the talk-host's views.
</P>
<P>
   Trick Play. . .
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl: Defensive lineman William ``the Refrigerator'' Perry
becomes running back in Super Bowl XX.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment: Monica Lewinsky doesn't launder XX-rated stains
from dress.
</P>
<P>
   A forum for the blind. . .
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl: Stevie Wonder performs this year at halftime show.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment: What justice allegedly is.
</P>
<P>
   Taking his word for it. . .
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl: Joe Namath ``guarantees'' victory for New York Jets
in Super Bowl III.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment: Clinton guarantees he ``did not have sexual
relations with that woman, Ms. Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   Famous Trip(p)s. . .
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl: Miami kicker Garo Yepremian in Super Bowl VII
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment: Linda
</P>
<P>
   Frustrating for Bills. . .
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl: Buffalo lost four Super Bowls in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment: Clinton repeatedly lost key evidentiary rulings in
Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   Washington out of touch. . .
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl: Redskins fail to make playoffs again.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment: Most Americans disapprove of trial.
</P>
<P>
   Strange behavior from people wearing stripes. . .
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl: Referees under the microscope due to many blown
calls all year.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment: Chief Justice William Rehnquist raises eyebrows at
Senate trial when he shows up wearing yellow stripes on his robe in
order to emulate a fictional character in a Gilbert &AMP; Sullivan
opera.
</P>
<P>
   Commentators who ought to calm down. . .
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl: John Madden
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment: Geraldo
</P>
<P>
   Hearing from the President. . .
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl: President calls winning team's locker room after
game.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment: Republicans want president to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring. . .
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl: the idea
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment: the problem
</P>
<P>
   Frank Cerrabino writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
