<HEADER>
A8641 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NAMATH-GUARANTEE2     01-26 1701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NAMATH-GUARANTEE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Broadway's Legend _ Namath's best call
 &HT;    By Ethan J. Skolnick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Broadway Joe was well fortified when he addressed the
Miami Touchdown Club.
</P>
<P>
   Broadway Joe had two stewardesses waiting in another room at the
Miami Springs Villas . . . or that may have been another night. He
had four, or five, or six Johnnie Walker Reds before he took to the
dais . . . or maybe it wasn't that many. He had come to be honored
by the Miami Touchdown Club on Jan. 9, 1969, three nights before
Super Bowl III, against the wishes of his coach, Weeb Ewbank . . .
or perhaps Joe Namath had been the reluctant one.
</P>
<P>
   Can't guarantee any of it.
</P>
<P>
   It's been 30 years since the quarterback, dressed in a soft
green suit, grabbed food and a beer at the New York Jets' poolside
barbecue at the Galt Ocean Mile Hotel in Fort Lauderdale, and
entered a limousine headed for Miami Springs. Details of the next
four hours have been colored by three decades of interpretation and
exaggeration, by the several hundred who came to Dade County's
primo spot to crown Namath ``the Outstanding Professional Football
Player of 1968.''
</P>
<P>
   But this can be guaranteed:
</P>
<P>
   Namath made sport's most famous guarantee that night, predicting
the Jets, at the time 19-point underdogs, would upset the Baltimore
Colts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was typical Joe,'' said New York Times columnist Dave
Anderson, who chronicled the Jets' week in the 1969 book Countdown
to Super Bowl. ``You knew he might say anything. He had been saying
things like that all week, he just didn't use the word guarantee.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Miami Touchdown Club voted to honor Namath, it didn't
know the Jets would be preparing for a Super Bowl that January
week. The honor was significant, as Namath was an American Football
League player receiving a ``professional football award'' when
National Football League stars were far more respected.
</P>
<P>
   The site was significant too: the Miami Springs Villas, on the
Glenn Curtiss estate. The Villas were part of 21 acres owned by the
jet-setting Arthur Bruns, host or dining partner to Mickey Mantle,
Adlai Stevenson, Arnold Palmer, Nikita Khrushchev and Dwight
Eisenhower. The Villas are gone, replaced by economy hotels, and
Bruns died in 1996. But then, Bruns was a showman and, according to
Mary Ann Taylor, curator of the Miami Springs Historic Preservation
Society, the Villas were ``quite a showplace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the place to be,'' says Joe Walker, an original member
of the Miami Touchdown Club.
</P>
<P>
   The Touchdown Club was founded in 1960, primarily to support the
University of Miami. ``The Club was the thing to do, especially for
us ex-half-assed athletes,'' says Buster Ziegler, a longtime
member. ``By the time we got to the Club, we were always better
athletes than we ever were.''
</P>
<P>
   The Club was generally all-male, and often off-color, but women
were allowed to attend the banquet on Jan. 9, and many did.
</P>
<P>
   The question was: Would Namath? And would Ewbank let him?
</P>
<P>
   There is some dispute about who made sure Namath showed. Bill
Bruce, the emcee that night, says former player Tom Kelleher got
Ewbank's permission early in the week. Joe Hirsch _ Namath's New
York roommate and a longtime columnist for the Daily Racing Form _
says he called Ewbank, who asked that Namath return to the hotel by
midnight. Norris Anderson, a Club founder, says Hirsch ``lured
Namath with a couple of stewardesses; he could be had, you know,''
though Hirsch says only that he and Namath had ``two dates after
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Ramos, then and now the Jets' media relations director,
says he urged Namath to go. ``He was talking about not going to it,
because a lot of things were going on during Super Bowl week,''
Ramos says. ``It was the day off, and I said, `Joe, the only thing
about that _ if you told these people you are going to be there,
and they sold all these tickets to this event, and this is a great
honor because it was the first time they had an AFL player of the
year, you should go.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank Ramos is the one who twisted my arm and made me go,''
says Namath, who has a home in Tequesta. ``I would have rather
stayed at the hotel. It was a tremendous honor, it was an important
situation. I was probably wishing I was back in Fort Lauderdale
instead of south Miami, although I did get along well in south
Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the attraction of Namath's appearance: his flamboyance,
his unpredictability. With whom would he arrive? Flirt? Whom would
he praise? Insult? He had already perturbed many NFLers by stating
that Colts quarterback Earl Morrall wasn't as good as Daryle
Lamonica of the AFL's Oakland Raiders. On Sunday, he nearly got
into a barroom brawl with Colts kicker Lou Michaels . . . then
ended the night by dropping off Michaels at the Statler Hilton, the
Colts' hotel. On Monday, he slept through Photo Day, and was fined
$50.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, shortly after 6 p.m., the limousine arrived at Oakland
Park Boulevard and State Road A1A. The Galt Ocean Mile Hotel would
shut down in 1986, serve as a set for Revenge of the Nerds II in
1987 and as a fortress for FBI swat teams to practice raids, before
it was razed in 1993. In the 1970s, it was a hotspot, where Sid
Caesar and Guy Lombardo would perform, and the Yankees stayed
during spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Anderson accompanied Namath on the ride to the Villas, and
notes in Countdown to Super Bowl that the quarterback ``was sipping
Johnnie Walker Red out of a paper cup in the front seat of a
turquoise Cadillac sedan.''
</P>
<P>
   Namath was to share the spotlight that night with O.J. Simpson,
who had been named college football's best player. But Simpson was
on the West Coast and didn't show. Bruce says that during the next
year's banquet, he picked up the phone, pretending Simpson had
called, and said, ``No, O.J., you dumb SOB, that was last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The most famous dining room at the Villas was King Arthur's
Court, named for Bruns and decorated with a medieval theme
including eight elaborate murals. Anderson and others have reported
that the banquet was held there, but most of the Touchdown Club
members remember it being in the larger Playhouse, with cocktails
in the adjacent Florida Room.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner: prime rib. Of course. ``We would have prime ribs
that were bigger than the plate,'' Walker says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest prime rib you ever saw,'' Bruce says.
</P>
<P>
   For a big event. ``It was packed,'' Norris Anderson says.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were in the lounge, and some outside on the patio,''
says Bernie Rosen, then a cameraman for Miami's WTJV-4. ``(The
room) was set up for someone to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   Namath would receive the award from Milt Woodward, the AFL
president who had suggested he shave and cut his hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be the usual, `Thank you for this lovely
trophy,' '' Hirsch says. ``I guess everybody else did, too.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems everybody was watching him eat, and drink. ``You never
saw a more affable guy in your life,'' Bruce says. ``The woman who
was the head waiter, Nancy, asked for an autograph. He was putting
a piece of meat in his mouth, and put it back down. This guy was
such a charmer.''
</P>
<P>
   Others lived vicariously through his exploits and excesses.
Norris Anderson says he sat beside Namath, who ``had three Johnnie
Walker Reds.'' Walker says ``they were bringing him Johnnie Walker
Reds as fast as he could down them.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Anderson wrote that ``Namath leaned down every so often and
sipped Scotch out of a napkin-wrapped old-fashioned glass.'' Yet
Anderson says: ``He wasn't drunk. He was Joe. He had had a drink or
two. He wasn't drunk before or after. There were no women around
him that night. When he got back, we watched some film.''
</P>
<P>
   Namath espoused film work _ ``The one-eyed monster doesn't
lie.'' The monster convinced him he could attack the left side of
the Colts' defense, and his receivers could outrun their
cornerbacks. Especially if Baltimore was complacent. Says Colts
tight end John Mackey: ``We just believed we had to show up. We
announced a victory party Wednesday before the game, and we cut up
the playoff share at the pre-game meal.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Colts frolicked with their families and spoke of adding
extensions to their houses, Namath studied. ``He was very confident
that they were going to win that game,'' Dave Anderson says.
</P>
<P>
   And so he said so Thursday night, helping make the Miami
Touchdown Club one of the most famous clubs in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Versions differ on his words.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce says he told Namath that night his ``remarks so far have
been as welcome as a hernia at a weight-lifter's convention, but
it's about time you came up and defended yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Bruce, Namath said: ``I don't like banquets
usually, but tonight I'm having a lot of fun. You people are all
great, and I'm going to offer you this. I want you to sell your
car, cash in your insurance policies, take your money out of the
bank, and bet it on the Jets.'' Then, after an interruption, Joe
continued: ``Hey, wait, we're going to beat the Colts on Sunday. I
guarantee it.''
</P>
<P>
   Countdown to Super Bowl recalls the sequence and sentence a bit
differently: ``We're going to win Sunday, I guarantee you.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it was exciting, especially to the media. ``Most of
the other sportswriters had already left when Namath made his
guarantee,'' says Deborah Evans, widow of Luther, whose story under
a banner Miami Herald headline appeared Friday morning, upsetting
Ewbank's breakfast. ``He came home and told me about it. He thought
he had a hold of something pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was Namath,'' Rosen says. ``The Broadway Joe fit him
perfectly. He was just a cocky, cocky, cocky individual.''
</P>
<P>
   And a prescient one.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we did was laugh,'' Mackey says. ``We thought it was a
joke. And that was the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By halftime, I can remember thinking back, `That crazy bastard
knew what he was talking about,' '' Walker says. ``I think they
might beat the Colts.''
</P>
<P>
   They did, 16-7. Guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Ethan J. Skolnick writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
