<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8677 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILITARY-SPENDING-$AD     01-26 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-SPENDING-$ADV31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS MONEY FLOWS TO MILITARY, REFORMERS SAY CUT WASTE FIRST
 &HT;    With MILITARY-DATA. For release Sunday, Jan. 31.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton unveils his plans Monday for a
six-year, $110 billion budget increase to close a ``readiness gap''
in the military, some defense experts say much of the money could
be found by correcting mismanagement and waste.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been hearing clamoring in this town for more money for
defense,'' said Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, as he chaired a
hearing last fall to examine how Air Force personnel created phony
invoices and paid themselves nearly $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we put adequate controls on the money we have, there should
be no need for more defense spending,'' Grassley said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Peter DeFazio, a Democrat who monitors military spending,
said he fears the push for higher defense spending will relax the
demand for reform. ``Those of us who would like to see the Pentagon
live within its means are undercut by the president's proffer'' of
spending hikes, the California lawmaker said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   One private watchdog group warns that the influx of new dollars
into the Pentagon after a decade of cutbacks invites a new wave of
fraud, because the government has dramatically reduced its force of
auditors and investigators who monitor contracts and spending.
``Further cuts in oversight personnel must be halted,'' said Marcus
Corbin, defense specialist at the Project on Government Oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Among the money-saving reforms being urged:
</P>
<P>
   _ Close more military bases. This could cut costs by $2 billion
to $3 billion a year. The military chiefs are lobbying hard to cull
unneeded bases to fit a force that has shrunk to one-third of its
Cold War level, and the White House has said Clinton will propose
new rounds of closings for 2001 and 2005.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea of shutting down bases meets strong resistance in
Congress, where members want to preserve civilian support jobs in
their home districts. Republican members also bitterly remember the
last round of base closings in 1995, when Clinton made a campaign
promise to protect jobs at two of the bases listed for closure, in
the vote-rich states of California and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A federal study has predicted that the next major targets would
probably be maintenance depots, especially in Texas and California.
Earlier base closings shut down more than 70 installations, and the
new rounds could add 40 more to the list.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fiscal management. The Defense Department keeps such poor
track of where its money goes that last year it reported $22
billion in so-called ``problem disbursements,'' payments made
without proper documentation. The amount was only slightly less
than prior years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we pay for goods and services, we sometimes have no idea
if we got what we paid for,'' Grassley said as he described the
Defense Department's huge bill-paying operations, which sends out
checks at a rate of $1.1 billion each day.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many signs of missing safeguards, the Defense
bill-paying center at Kettering, Ohio, gave Air Force Staff Sgt.
Robert L. Miller Jr. authority over billions of dollars, even after
an investigation tied him to missing checks. Over two years, Miller
faked invoices and paid himself $435,000 before he was caught.
</P>
<P>
   The case was one of several in which military employees have set
up phony companies and siphoned off millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. General Accounting Office, the investigating arm of
Congress, last week listed the military's contracting payment
system as well as most of its fiscal oversight as ``high-risk''
areas for fraud and waste.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scale back new weaponry. ``The Pentagon has confused the need
to re-equip the force with buying the fanciest gadgets,'' said
Michael O'Hanlon, a defense budget expert and author of ``How to Be
a Cheap Hawk.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Hanlon is advising that the Pentagon develop weapons already
on the drawing boards, but buy fewer of them. He cites the F-22, an
advanced fighter plane, which was first envisioned when the Soviet
Union was still a threat. Now that no foreign-built fighter can
come close to rivaling the F-22, O'Hanlon suggests buying far fewer
than the planned 339 aircraft, to be built by Lockheed Martin at an
estimated at $110 million apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Others point to Trident submarines, which patrol the world's
oceans carrying intercontinental nuclear missiles. The United
States could save $500 million a year by decommissioning four of
the 18 submarines, as called for in the SALT II treaty with Russia,
an idea that the Navy has embraced. Unless the four oldest Tridents
are scrapped, they will be soon be due for costly refurbishing.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Russian legislature has yet to ratify the treaty,
so the full Cold War complement of Tridents continues in service,
because the Clinton administration and many in Congress have been
unwilling to move until Russia does.
</P>
<P>
   Other defense experts, led by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., focus
on weaponry that members of Congress force the Pentagon to buy. He
cites the C-130J transport plane, long a favorite of lawmakers and
their local National Guard units.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three years, former House Speaker Newt Gingrich,
R-Ga., cleared the way to buy 20 of the transports, which are built
at a cost of $50 million apiece by Lockheed Martin in his home town
of Marietta. The Pentagon made no request for the transports.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Lockheed defends the C-130J's as ``a matter of
cost-effectiveness and readiness,'' since they are replacing 30- to
35-year-old models that cost more to fly and maintain. The new
planes can be flown by two pilots instead of four and carry more
cargo at a higher speed, said Lockheed spokesman Doug Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   As for the flashy F-22 ``Raptor,'' the manufacturer argues that
the per-plane cost will rise if fewer are built. And despite the
lack of a foreign rival for the high-tech fighter, Lockheed
spokesman Jim Fetig said, ``The F-22 gives the Air Force
unparalleled advantage against a range of threats that includes
airplanes and surface-to-air missiles.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Privatizing support services. The Defense Department should
make ``revolutionary'' changes to save nearly $30 billion a year by
privatizing non-defense work such as payroll, property disposal,
housing and medical care, according to Business Executives for
National Security.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Defense Department has embraced the idea of
finding business partners to help resolve its enormous housing
problem. Two-thirds of the military's 300,000 family housing units
are in need of repair or replacement at a cost estimated at $20
billion.
</P>
<P>
   But after several attempts to forge partnerships with private
developers, only two projects have been finished, one in Corpus
Christi, Texas, and another in Everett, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been slow,'' acknowledged Glenn Flood, a Pentagon
spokesman. He said the Defense Department would continue the effort
to work with private developers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cutting inventory. As of 1997, the military had about $41
billion worth of spare parts, medical supplies, and clothing _ even
sneakers _ that were obsolete or rarely used, all stockpiled in 164
warehouses worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Although the military has gradually disposed of the excess
materiel, the effort has been a money-loser. In recent efforts, the
department got only about 2.7 cents per each dollar of the original
price, although other government surplus sales earn more than
double that amount. Reformers have called on the Pentagon to hire
private contractors to clear out the stockpiles.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
