<P>
   &UR; WHAT SHOULD WE DO WITH THE MOON? &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FOUR COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By FRED GUTERL &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six years after man last set foot on the moon, a
grassroots movement is now under way to go back. Alan Binder, a
planetary scientist turned entrepreneur, wants to start factories
on the moon, churning out hydrogen or basalt bricks: the moon as
industrial park. David Gump, the former publisher of a
space-industry newsletter who has founded LunaCorp, wants to build
a moon rover with ``telepresence,'' which would be controlled from
Earth via joystick _ preferably by an adolescent in an arcade in an
amusement park somewhere. Should we study the moon, strip-mine it
or turn it into a theme park? Fred Guterl, a senior editor of
Discover magazine, reports.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-MOON-AS-TOURIST-ATTRACTION-NYTSF. Sent to category
codes ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BODY BAZAAR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ONE COLOR SLIDE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By SHANTI MENON &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Advances in medical technology have created a marketplace for
everything from organs and tissues to genes and sex cells. Prices
vary: $300 for a pint of plasma, $50 for a sample of sperm, $10,000
for a nine-month lease on a surrogate mother's womb. Blood was the
first commodity on the market, and it is still the most commonly
sold body product. Paid blood donors typically earn from $50 to
$500 per pint; those with rare blood types or components may get
more. Think of it as a commodities market for the 21st century,
reports free-lance writer and editor Karen Wright.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-SELLING-BODY-PARTS-NYTSF. Sent to category codes
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A BLOW TO THE BRAIN: A STROKE VICTIM'S DIARY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ONE PHOTO ILLUSTRATION IS AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,100 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By JILL BOLTE TAYLOR &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``On the morning of Dec. 10, 1996, I awoke with a pulsing pain
behind my left eye,'' writes neuroscientist Jill Bolte Taylor. ``I
got up to begin my morning routine and jumped onto my
cardio-glider. The exercise, I thought, would banish the throbbing
inside my head.'' But when she stopped exercising, she knew
something was wrong. ``When I held my hands up in front of my face,
I felt as though my consciousness was suspended somewhere between
normal reality and some esoteric space ... Time seemed to stand
still. I was disturbingly aware that the intricate networks that
operate the different functions of my mind were shutting down. I
tried to visualize myself driving to work, and in the next instant
my right arm went totally dead. In that moment I knew I was having
a stroke.'' Bolte Taylor describes in detail the events of that day
-- and how her life had changed.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-TO-EXPERIENCE-A-STROKE-NYTSF. Sent to category codes
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you.
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
