<HEADER>
A8724 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOON-AS-TOURIST-ATTRA     01-26 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOON-AS-TOURIST-ATTRACTION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT SHOULD WE DO WITH THE MOON?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    FOUR EYE-CATCHING COLOR SLIDES showing what man might be doing
on the moon in the near future are available FREE OF CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. The art can be sent by mail or
overnight delivery, using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number.
Please specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 By FRED GUTERL  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Shortly after the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
was formed in 1958, its engineers began visiting elementary schools
in the leafy suburbs of Washington, D.C., to practice inspirational
speeches in front of kids.
</P>
<P>
   The space program hadn't yet hardened into a race against the
Soviets. It was still pictured as a journey of exploration, one
that would eventually lead to colonizing first the moon, then Mars
and the rest of the solar system. At least, that's the way Gregory
Bennett remembers the message the NASA guy gave to his third-grade
class.
</P>
<P>
   From that day on, Bennett was wedded to the space program.
</P>
<P>
   Now in his late 40s, Bennett is an employee of Boeing, NASA's
primary contractor for the International Space Station. On evenings
and weekends, Bennett is one of the leaders of what you might call
a lunar underground, a group called the Artemis Society, which is
bent on circumventing the politics and bureaucracy of NASA and
striking out on its own for the moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure we can put a man on the moon for about $1.5
billion,'' he says matter-of-factly. After an awkward silence, he
adds: ``We're going to do it. We are going to the moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett and his cohorts are not the only ones packing their
bags. Suddenly just about everybody is trying to get to the moon,
including a motley collection of entrepreneurs and dreamers in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone, that is, except NASA: They have their hands full with
the space station, and their eyes cast in the direction of Mars.
</P>
<P>
   With NASA on the sidelines, and with no Cold War in sight, those
listening to Bennett's pitch could be forgiven for wondering how a
new lunar program might be structured and who, in this day of
budget cuts and belt-tightening, would be willing to pay for it.
And why?
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Mendell attended the Twenty-Ninth Lunar and Planetary
Science Conference last March at the Johnson Space Center, as he
has attended just about every moon conference since the mid-1960s,
when he was a planetary scientist for the Apollo missions.
</P>
<P>
   Mendell still works for JSC's Planetary Science Branch, and he
is one of the leading advocates for putting people on the moon. He
also knows firsthand how difficult it is to get the lunar bandwagon
rolling.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the early 1980s, Mendell and his colleagues spurred
NASA-affiliated engineers and scientists to think about and plan a
return mission to the moon. The result was the first Lunar Base
Symposium in Washington in 1984. Momentum flagged after the
Challenger explosion in 1986 but picked up again in 1989 when
President Bush made a Kennedyesque speech challenging NASA to go to
Mars.
</P>
<P>
   NASA responded with a 30-year plan that used the space station
and the moon as starting points. Unfortunately, the price tag _
$500 billion to $600 billion _ triggered the gag reflex in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But Mendell has quietly continued to plug the moon, writing
articles such as ``Lunar Base _ Why Ask Why?'' He wants to go not
for national pride but for another equally old-fashioned reason:
knowledge. The moon has much to teach us, he says, about the
origins of the solar system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moon is a geologic time machine,'' he says. ``It underwent
some of the processes that Earth underwent, but then it just
stopped. It is a record of the early days of the solar system, just
waiting to be read.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in January, only weeks before the Lunar and Planetary
Science Conference convened, the Lunar Prospector orbiter had
arrived in lunar orbit and started making detailed maps of the
surface. The biggest jewel in a treasure trove of scientific data
was the first incontrovertible evidence of water on the moon _
about a billion tons of it.
</P>
<P>
   Water on the moon has given the lunar underground a fillip.
``Primarily, the existence of water opens people's minds to going
to the moon,'' Alan Binder says. ``It's like finding gold.
California could have been settled without the gold rush, but it
sure helped.''
</P>
<P>
   A planetary scientist turned entrepreneur, Binder was the
driving force behind the scrappy, 650-pound Prospector orbiter.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Binder wants to start factories on the moon,
churning out hydrogen or basalt bricks. He's not talking about a
moon base but a whole industrial infrastructure in space _ the moon
as industrial park.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's LunaCorp, a private firm cofounded by David Gump,
the former publisher of a space-industry newsletter, who wants to
build a moon rover with ``telepresence,'' which would be controlled
from Earth via joystick _ preferably by an adolescent in an arcade
in an amusement park somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody thinks bigger than Greg Bennett, though, when it comes to
mining the moon's entertainment resources. In his vision, tourism
is the sine qua non of the development of the moon, and the entire
solar system for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting people up there would cost, oh, maybe $100,000 per
person,'' Bennett says. ``It'd be like a luxury capital tour of
Europe. It's about what you'd spend to go to Mount Everest. If you
had a resort on the northeast corner of Mare Crisium, there's a
place called Angus Bay where you could go spelunking.'' Bennett
envisions a network of gondola chairs that would take people around
to the most interesting sights.
</P>
<P>
   Which way will prevail on the moon? Mining or tourism?
Production or consumption? Although nobody is even close to leaving
Earth, already it seems clear that the final arbiter of what we
should do with the moon will most likely be the free market. If the
coming decades are anything like this one, don't count
entertainment out.
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Fred Guterl is a senior editor of Discover.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC; 
