</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8757 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SHARPE-COX     01-26 1454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SHARPE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FBN-SHARPE-COX
 &HT;    Talkin' tall
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The goal is to find out what Denver Broncos tight end Shannon
Sharpe was like before he got to the NFL, before he had the nerve
to call Dan Marino ``a loser,'' before he baited Kansas City's
Derrick Thomas into a Monday Night meltdown, before he left a trail
of angry fans on the road to Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   You start with calls to Savannah State, the Division II school
where Sharpe played college football. The people there decide to
play a practical joke on you. They tell you that you should talk to
his roommate for the final three years of college. They say his
name is Mike Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right. Mike Wallace. That's a good one. And who did he
room with freshman year? Morley Safer?
</P>
<P>
   Only it turns out to be true. This Mike Wallace now is offensive
coordinator at Savannah State. Back in the late '80s, he played
free safety and lived with Sharpe.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a great roommate,'' Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   You wonder what Wallace's reaction was last Sunday when he
turned on the TV and saw his college buddy, the guy who grew up in
a rural Georgia town, wearing the Denver version of a Cheesehead _
a Bronco-head _ and mimicking a Bronx accent as he delivered a
post-game message to the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fuggetaboudit.''
</P>
<P>
   Was Wallace shaking his head, amazed at how fame can take a
small-town kid and turn him into The Mouth That Scored?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Shannon,'' Wallace said with a laugh. ``He never was
shy for words.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it turns out that fame hasn't changed Sharpe. It has
only turned him up a notch.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch Glicken, executive sports producer at WTOC-Channel 11 in
Savannah, recalls getting a call from the Denver CBS affiliate the
day the Broncos made Sharpe a seventh-round pick _ 192nd overall _
in the 1990 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `Do you have any video of this kid?' '' Glicken
said.
</P>
<P>
   Once he stopped laughing, Glicken said, ``Do I have video? I've
got tons of it. I'll make you a deal. I'll send you some now if you
send me some on the first day of training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal was struck. Then the first day of training camp came
and, Glicken says, the Denver affiliate said there was a problem.
They had spent their time at practice making sure to get shots of
other rookies. They hadn't gotten anything of Sharpe.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `He's not even going to make the team,' '' Glicken
said. ``I told them I'd call them back when he made the Pro Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   It took three years, but he made it. And he has been making it
every year since. Next month, he will make trip No. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers back up his talk
</P>
<P>
   He might be the best tight end in the NFL, a mix of speed and
size that gives defenses fits. But he might be best known for what
comes out of his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't your Flutie-is-short variety of trash talking. It's
as if Sharpe is trying to mix in a little something from one of his
favorite TV shows: Jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Geography for 100. What did Sharpe say moments after the Broncos
eliminated Pittsburgh from the playoffs last season?
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay away from the Allegheny, the Ohio and the Monongahela. I
hope they freeze those three rivers tonight, because I'd hate to
see anybody plunging to the bottom of them.''
</P>
<P>
   History for 200. What did Sharpe say a couple of years ago when,
after the Broncos took a 34-8 lead at New England, he picked up the
red telephone sitting behind the Denver bench in Foxboro?
</P>
<P>
   ``President! We need the National Guard! We need as many men as
you can spare, because we are killing the Patriots!''
</P>
<P>
   Travel plans for 300. What did Sharpe say following a 38-3
victory that eliminated the Dolphins and moved the Broncos within
one game of the Super Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   ``How does it feel to have the Super Bowl at your house, and
you're not invited?'' he said, adding a message for Dolphins coach
Jimmy Johnson. ``Tell Jimmy to have his office ready because we're
going to need to break down film.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Super Bowl week is here. Sharpe and his teammates arrive
today. And, guess what, they will be staying in Fort Lauderdale and
using the Dolphins' training facility in Davie.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what kind of reception he expects, Sharpe told
reporters in Denver: ``I don't really think I'll be getting many
free meals.''
</P>
<P>
   The people who know Sharpe _ friends and family from Georgia _
worry that the rest of the nation is getting the wrong impression.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe might be the Super Bowl's brashest talker since Michael
Irvin, but please don't lump the two together.
</P>
<P>
   A quiet family? Say what?
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe's life doesn't read like an episode of Cops. His mother
made sure of that. She sent him and two older siblings _ Sterling
and Sherra _ away from the streets of Chicago to live with their
grandparents in a farmhouse a half mile from the nearest neighbor
in Glennville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good family,'' said William Hall, track coach at Tattnall
County (Ga.) High School.
</P>
<P>
   Hall should know. He has been coaching football and track in the
area for 38 years. He coached Shannon's older brother, Sterling. He
coached four of his uncles. And when asked if they all were as
talkative as Shannon, Hall laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``Everyone else was quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the rest of the Sharpe family seems to try to avoid
attention. Sterling didn't talk to the media during his career with
Green Bay. And although he now is part of the media as a
broadcaster for ESPN, he didn't return calls for this story. And
their grandmother, who raised them after their grandfather died,
has an unlisted telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, there even is a quiet side to Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't drink. He doesn't smoke. He doesn't even go out that
much. When he does, he often chooses to sit in a dark theater and
watch a movie. And when he really wants to go crazy, well, he
watches more than one movie. He once sat through six in a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``People see me and say, `This is the guy that everyone says is
so funny and so talkative?' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That side comes out on the football field. Or in the weight
room. Or the locker room. Or seemingly anytime a microphone is
within shouting range.
</P>
<P>
   Hall recalls Sharpe once saying to him, ``You better hope
nothing happens to me, because if it does, the show stops.'' Hall
didn't get mad. He laughed, partly because he knew there was some
truth to it, but mainly because he knew Sharpe.
</P>
<P>
   He also knew Sharpe as a hard-working student who would end up
at Savannah State only because his test scores were low. Who was at
church every Sunday. Who never was in trouble. Who thought about
becoming a lawyer if football hadn't panned out. Who after winning
Super Bowl XXXII would take his ring and give it to his idol _
Sterling _ saying: ``Seeing my brother wear a Super Bowl ring means
more to me than having it on my own finger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's typical Shannon,'' said Bill Davis, his college coach
who now is at Johnson C. Smith University in Charlotte, N.C. ``Some
people try to distance themselves from their brothers. Not Shannon.
He wanted to be like Sterling. I can't say enough about him. He was
a joy to coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is Davis who should be blamed for Sharpe's constant
chatter. He always told his players that to succeed in life, they
had to be able to talk. Of course, he also told them they had to
think before they talked _ something Sharpe admits he doesn't do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just say what comes into my head,'' he said. ``It's not
planned.''
</P>
<P>
   A vocal leader
</P>
<P>
   Although some of those things make old friends cringe _ the
Marino comment, in particular _ his old friends don't want fame to
change him. For instance, Davis says he wishes he could clone that
personality and fill his team with it. He recalls asking Sharpe to
play quarterback for the scout team _ then scrapping the idea when
the scout team got so riled up that he feared the field would be
littered with injured players.
</P>
<P>
   That's the thing about Sharpe's talking. It might infuriate
others but it inspires those around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone feeds off him,'' Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   Now Sharpe is bringing his feeding frenzy to Miami, a place he
almost ended up at 10 years ago. After his sophomore year at
Savannah State, he was offered a chance to jump ship, to play for a
national powerhouse at the University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Think about that. Was there ever a player who seems like he
should have been a 1980s Hurricane?
</P>
<P>
   He thought about it but eventually decided to listen to advice
from Davis: ``Son, if you're good, they'll find you.''
</P>
<P>
   They did.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe made sure of that.
</P>
<P>
   (endit)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
