<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CASE FOR AN ALTERNATIVE SHAKESPEARE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   People tell me I must see ``Shakespeare in Love,'' and maybe I
will; but I've resisted it, confident that if I watch a
much-praised, well-scripted, well-photographed, well-acted movie, I
still won't believe a word of it.
</P>
<P>
   That's because I'm in the growing army of disbelievers in the
beloved Bard of Avon. I'll endeavor to chart the origin and
development of my disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   First, I must protest that I am not by nature a conspiracy
theorist. I believe Lee Harvey Oswald acted alone in the
assassination of President John F. Kennedy, and I tend to dismiss
most other well-exploited conspiracy notions. Having said that, I
believe a conspiracy existed between one William Shakespeare, an
actor, and Edward de Vere, the 17th Earl of Oxford and the true
author of the plays attributed to Shakespeare. So here goes.
</P>
<P>
   When I was enrolled in an upper-division undergraduate course in
Shakespeare at UCLA, I was shocked and appalled when the professor
_ a solidly credentialed Paul Jorgenson _ expressed belief that
Shakespeare was not the creator of Hamlet and Portia and Falstaff,
or of some of the loveliest sonnets in our language.
</P>
<P>
   As years passed, I grew ever more fascinated by the question of
authorship, read books and articles on the subject, became familiar
with claims for Francis Bacon, Christopher Marlowe, even Queen
Elizabeth I herself, all the while remaining faithful to the man
from Stratford. It seemed like petty snobbery that some people
believed Shakespeare incapable of writing the plays because of his
limited education and knowledge of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Oxford theory was gaining momentum. Dr. Jorgenson had
mentioned him as a possibility, although the earl was a late
starter in the authorship sweepstakes. Early in this century, a
scholar with the unfortunate surname of Looney proposed Oxford as
the authentic poet-dramatist. The basis of his claim was language,
and the argument is solid.
</P>
<P>
   In Shakespeare's time, there was no stability to the English
language _ Samuel Johnson's first great dictionary was almost two
centuries in the distance _ and there were hundreds of English
dialects and contrasting vocabularies. Stratford talk was far
removed from London talk, and it was unlikely that one come to
London as recently as Shakespeare would have had mastery of the
most elevated English speech, informed by the language of court.
</P>
<P>
   So I joined the opposition camp, a doubter of Shakespeare, but
also a doubter of Bacon, because Baconian language is not
Shakespearean. Nor is Marlovian language; and the theory of Marlowe
authorship is delightfully wild, with sure appeal for conspiracy
buffs. The notion is that Kit Marlowe _ Shakespeare's great
contemporary _ wasn't really killed in a tavern brawl at age 29,
but went into hiding with a price on his head and proceeded to
write plays that he slipped to Shakespeare surreptitiously.
</P>
<P>
   Charlton Ogburn's massive ``The Mysterious William
Shakespeare,'' published in the early 1980s, may be the nearest
thing to proof that Shakespeare couldn't and didn't write those
plays or any plays, any poems. Ogburn advanced the likelihood that
Shakespeare was illiterate, and that the four extant signatures
were made with a template. There is no witness to Shakespeare
having ever had pen or quill in hand.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatist who ``never blotted a line'' delivered plays
regularly to the Lord Chamberlain's Men for performance; and in his
leisure, Shakespeare lifted a glass with Ben Jonson and others at
the Mermaid Tavern, deceiving them all while playing his greatest
role.
</P>
<P>
   Ogburn's case against Shakespeare is stronger than his case for
Oxford _ which, however, is strong enough. I'm just getting warmed
up and will have more to say on this matter; meanwhile, if you've
been made curious, seek out Charlton Ogburn's ``The Mysterious
William Shakespeare'' and have some fun.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7731. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
