<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8776 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIRLS-ESTEEM-LIFEBEAT     01-26 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRLS-ESTEEM-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT HAPPENS TO SMART LITTLE GIRLS?
</HEADLINE>
  Includes a 100-word sidebar and a horizontal color illustration, in
JPEG format, of a girl and two boys raising their hands at their
school desks. Call Joe Applegate at 212-499-3342 for e-mail
delivery within minutes. 
 By BEN STEELMAN 
 c.1999 New York Times Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Statistics tell the story, but teachers have known the plot for
a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Until age 9 or so, girls and boys make about the same scores on
science tests, according to data from the National Center for
Education Statistics. By age 13, however, the boys are outscoring
the girls.
</P>
<P>
   A similar gap in math scores has closed somewhat in recent
years, but still exists.
</P>
<P>
   Until the middle-school grades, girls and boys use home
computers for roughly equal amounts of time. Then, girls' computer
use drops off, while boys' use increases.
</P>
<P>
   In seventh grade, about as many girls say they enjoy science as
boys. By 12th grade, however, the boys who enjoy science far
outnumber the girls.
</P>
<P>
   And as early as the eighth grade, according to the National
Coalition of Girls' Schools, more boys than girls are considering
careers in science and engineering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be a challenge, being the only girl in half your
classes,'' said Tameka Smith, a freshman at North Carolina State
University, who is aiming for an engineering degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls feel pretty good about themselves until age 10 or so,''
said Grace Mae Burton, chairman of the department of curricular
studies in the Watson School of Education at the University of
North Carolina at Wilmington. ``Then something happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The gap was documented in a 1991 survey, Shortchanging Girls,
Shortchanging America, commissioned by the American Association of
University Women. As girls reach adolescence, the survey found,
they suffer a loss of self-esteem _ and a loss of interest in
science and mathematics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has a handle on why this happens,'' Burton said, but
clues abound.
</P>
<P>
   Follow-up studies funded by the AAUW found that curricula
stereotyped girls, that teachers called on boys more often for
answers or discussions, and that school counselors often seemed to
channel girls into traditionally ``feminine'' courses. For
African-American girls, the difficulties seemed particularly acute.
</P>
<P>
   Some studies suggest that girls may be more hampered than boys
by a fear of failure. On standardized tests, for instance, girls
are far more likely to respond ``I don't know,'' rather than try to
make an educated guess.
</P>
<P>
   How can the trend be countered?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to help young women see that they can do lots of
things,'' said Burton, ``that they don't have to stifle their
intelligence. We have to teach them to say, `Yes I can.'''
</P>
<P>
   This can be done partly by steering girls toward after-school
programs that stress sports, computers, math or manual skills, such
as Girls Inc.'s national SMART (Science, Math and Relevant
Technology) program, encouraging their competition in science fairs
and trade shows, and exposing them to a variety of careers,
including those occupied largely by men.
</P>
<P>
   In the SMART program, girls join in such projects as building
batteries from cups, kitchen bleach and other simple materials to
rigging electric switches or taking a radio apart to see how it
works.
</P>
<P>
   Recreational programs, including basketball, soccer and
softball, can have values beyond fitness. Studies show that girls
in organized athletics are less likely to become pregnant as
teen-agers or to get involved in drug abuse. Sports may also build
girls' confidence in dealing with competition.
</P>
<P>
   Burton, a specialist in math education, suggested that
traditional boys' games _ for instance, kicking and throwing balls
_ can hone skills in spatial perception, a key tool in dealing with
math. Girls' games on the other hand, promote communication skills.
This might explain why many girls excel in language arts but lag in
geometry and higher mathematics.
</P>
<P>
   Parents and families can do a lot to give girls confidence,
especially the confidence to tackle difficult subjects.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom always told us, if it's worth having, it's worth
working for,'' said Smith, the N.C. State freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   (Ben Steelman writes for the Morning Star in Wilmington, N.C.)
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR: EXPERT ADVICE FOR PARENTS:
</P>
<P>
   _ Introduce books that help girls find role models beyond rock
singers and movie stars. Burton remembers as a young person,
reading biographies of scientists: ``What fascinated me was that
they didn't get their right answer the first time, but they kept
trying.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Helping girls learn about astronauts Sally Ride and Mae
Jemison, about Marie Curie, Rachel Carson, Jane Goodall and Amelia
Earhart, can give them positive examples.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you have a home computer, make sure daughters have as much
access as sons.
</P>
<P>
   _ Instill a spirit of independence. Allow children to make
choices, face consequences and learn to live with their
responsibilities. Problem-solving is a skill best mastered while
young.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call New York Times
Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480 or
fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
