<HEADER>
A8777 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINTERCAMP-LIFEBEAT-A     01-26 1329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINTERCAMP-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIGHTFUL, DELIGHTFUL WINTERTIME CAMPING
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Bela Vadasz is cq.) 
 Includes a horizontal color photo of a campsite on a snowy
mountainside. In JPEG format, available in minutes by e-mail. Call
Joe Applegate at 212-499-3342. 
 By KEN MCALPINE 
 c.1999 Ken McAlpine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I told friends I was planning to go winter camping in the
High Sierra between California and Nevada, everyone was quick to
weigh in. I would freeze. People died in the back country in
winter. They got lost, took a misstep, were buried alive.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, winter camping raised lots of questions. But it also
resonated a simple thought. If everybody was inside waiting for
spring, outside it would be empty...
</P>
<P>
   That and curiosity were the main reasons I signed up for a
two-day snow camping and winter survival course. And how I came to
be sitting in a tidy bunkhouse high in the mountains above Lake
Tahoe, a 50-mile drive from Reno, listening to our mountain guide
make a point he would repeat again and again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about being prepared,'' said Brian Biega, a
26-year-old instructor with Alpine Skills International, a local
outfitter. ``A lot of staying comfortable in the winter is always
keeping on top of things and always thinking ahead. Otherwise all
of the sudden you wake up and you have a big frozen cube in your
pod.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that cube might be your tentmate, Biega didn't say. Like
many experienced outdoor folk, Biega addressed the obvious and let
implication speak for itself. It would be his job to shepherd us
through two days and an overnight, while tutoring us in the bare
bones basics of avalanche detection, navigation, building a snow
cave and keeping our toes and fingers from turning into senseless
blocks.
</P>
<P>
   There were five of us in the group: the oldest was 51 and the
most experienced had done some back-country skiing. Just behind the
lodge a pine-pocked spine of the Sierra swept up to blue March sky.
Halfway up the slope behind the lodge two thick thumbs of snow
jutted out, between them a gap that dropped off into space. Two
weeks earlier the cornice had been punched away by the weight of a
snowboarder, burying and killing him probably in the same instant.
</P>
<P>
   As Bela Vadasz, ASI's founder and an alpinist of twenty-plus
years would tell me later, such accidents could often be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like most winter accidents usually occur for some
basic reason,'' Vadasz said. ``It's not like a whole bunch of
little things went wrong. Often it's just some basic precautions
that were ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in the hut, Biega began his instruction by having everyone
empty his backpack and spread its contents out on the floor.
Biega's consisted of six tiny stuff sacks, each organized so that
he could put his hands on things quickly. An emergency sack
contained a space blanket, duct tape, energy bars, parachute cord
and a candle and waterproof matches. There was an alarm clock for
quick catnaps.
</P>
<P>
   Biega sorted quickly through our piles, thinning our loads
substantially. Then he turned an eye on our nattily layered selves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the biggest mistake people make is not dressing
adequately,'' he said. ``So if anyone has anything that's cotton,
you should leave it behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has worked up a sweat knows that few things absorb,
and hold, moisture better than cotton. And you don't need to be a
MIT graduate to know that wet plus cold equals miserable.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the hut, we crossed the road, scaled an eight-foot
snowbank, put on snowshoes and shouldered our packs. Biega gave a
brief directional overview, pointing to the north, south, east and
west. We would be heading northeast, said Biega. So if we got lost,
which way would we go?
</P>
<P>
   ``Right. Southwest until you hit the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Off we strode single file, the snow firm and squeaky clean
beneath our feet. Our goal for the afternoon was to find a place to
set up camp. A good winter campsite must be low and out of the
wind, but not too low because cold dense air settles.
</P>
<P>
   We hiked for about twenty minutes, until we came to a small glen
clumped with pines. On the exposed ridges just up the slope, the
wind had pinched our faces. Down here it was nearly still, the
boughs of the pines bobbing languidly. The pines showed no evidence
of branches ripped away or bent in the direction of a rushing
avalanche of snow.
</P>
<P>
   Finally Biega spoke. ``It all looks good to me.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time we started setting up camp it was mid-afternoon.
Blue sky had given way to gray clouds that scudded overhead under
full sail. As we used our snow shovels to flatten out a spot for
our tents, I noticed that the distant ranges had disappeared in a
foggy-white whorl. Looking up again a few minutes later, I watched
the whorl swallow a nearby slope, blurring the trees fuzzy gray. A
brief bout of hail pocked down on us.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless a general air of optimism prevailed. We had been out
in winter for half a day and we were all surprisingly comfortable.
And now, to ensure further comfort, we were creating our shelter
for the night, flattening out the ground, staking down our tents,
using our snow shovels to hack out square cubes of snow, then
setting them neatly on top of each other to build a wall to block
the wind.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Biega was sculpting a winter home. Beneath the roof
formed by his cone-shaped tent, he'd dug out a standing-room deep
trench-cum-living room, complete with two snow benches and hollowed
out shelves where he could stash supplies.
</P>
<P>
   When you stepped down inside it was cozy and quiet, and
whitewashed walls of snow crystal blinked back at you. That night
as the wind roared far overhead, the six of us enjoyed freeze dried
Wild Time Turkey washed down with hot cocoa, our silences filled by
the propane hiss of Biega's stove.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't warm. I was still wearing three layers of clothing,
and tendrils of steam smoked up through my gloves like vapors off a
bog. But we were dry and comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   For me the biggest surprise came later that night, when I awoke
with a jolt and realized I would have to face what I had feared.
Hydration, Biega had repeatedly told us, is essential to staying
warm. I'd heeded his advice, and now I had to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Managing to unzip the damn tent flap, I stumbled out into a
strange and lovely world. Rather than the black of night, the world
was gray, illuminated by a landscape as smooth and taut as fresh
sheets. The snow fell steadily, and made no sound. I felt wrapped
in a serenity I'd never felt before.
</P>
<P>
   I stood in the snow enthralled, until my bare feet started to
burn.
</P>
<P>
   The next day I paid close attention as Biega showed us why any
smart back-country traveler carries at least a snow shovel and
space blanket, and how to use these items to make a cozy, and
potentially lifesaving snow cave. Find firm snowpack, put a slight
arch in the roof -- a flat roof could collapse -- and if you're in
trouble make the cave no bigger than a snug coffin; senseless to
waste energy, and the close confines, plus the space blanket wrap,
will help keep you warmer.
</P>
<P>
   And when we returned to the lodge late that afternoon, I
listened intently as Bela waxed on about the joys of winter; the
challenge, beauty and emptiness.
</P>
<P>
   When he finished, he smiled pleasantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``These experiences, they leave you with a piece of magic,'' he
said. ``Why not live as much magic in this lifetime, find as much
of it as you can?''
</P>
<P>
   Wonderful treat that we have wintertime to search it out.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ken McAlpine is a free-lance writer based in Ventura, Calif.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call New York Times
Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480 or
fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 1216EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
