<HEADER>
A8779 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUALITY-LIFEBEAT-ART-     01-26 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUALITY-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDEFINING QUALITY TIME
</HEADLINE>
  By FRANCES LA BARRE 
 c.1998 Child magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's Sunday night, and you're looking at a packed calendar,
wondering when and how you'll spend more time with your kids in the
upcoming week.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of ``quality time'' is meant to be reassuring to busy
parents. It suggests that even if your time with your children is
limited, when you use it wisely you can make up for a lack of
``quantity time.''
</P>
<P>
   But you have never been certain what is quality time, really?
Look at the following four scenarios. Can you figure out which ones
represent quality time?
</P>
<P>
   1. You and your spouse take Megan, 4, and Robby, 6, to the zoo.
You have a fine day, topped off with ice-cream cones. On the way
home, you tell the kids that later on Mom and Dad have to tackle
chores that were put aside to make time for the family outing. Soon
you hear fighting break out in the backseat.
</P>
<P>
   2. You've planned a treat for yourself and your 2-year-old,
Annie. She loves to go to the indoor play space nearby, so you've
rearranged your schedule to take her there. When it's time to go,
you expect to see an eager little face but find instead a balky
child who refuses to go. You can barely contain your dismay.
</P>
<P>
   3. You are watching James, 5, and Tanya, 7, play Chinese
checkers. Both kids are excited that each has jumped over four
marbles in a row. Tanya doesn't even mind when James wins. You have
to get dinner started, but they don't complain. They agree to play
another round in the kitchen while you cook and keep them company.
</P>
<P>
   4. It's a typical weekday morning. Dressing and breakfast are on
a tight schedule so that you can spend a little time over cereal
with Samantha, 3, before taking her to preschool. Samantha's been
trying to master new skills. As she pours her juice, she spills it
all over the floor, splashing some on her tights. Despite knowing
better, you become unglued and yell at her. Samantha begins to
wail.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a closer look at each situation; prepare to be surprised.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kids Need Help to Shift Gears &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A trip to the zoo is, of course, classic quality time, an outing
the whole family can enjoy. But you might think that the trip was
spoiled by the kids' fussing at the end of the day. In fact quality
time includes dealing with difficult transitions and endings. With
your help, your children can learn how to hold onto the good
feelings despite the hard parts.
</P>
<P>
   If you plan to tackle jobs around the house later, let your
children know at the start of the trip so they won't be so startled
by the prospect of separation. The younger they are, the more they
need you to help them see the outing and the ending as a whole, to
help them think through what they will do next. Ease the transition
by encouraging them to draw pictures of the zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Notice whether great outings are too often the focus of your
time together. Perhaps you tend to think that your presence is not
enough and that you must fill the time spent with your children
with something special. Don't forget that they might love simply to
pounce on you for a Saturday-morning wrestling session.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Accept Your Toddlers' Emotions &LR;
</P>
<P>
   You had thought a special trip to the indoor play space would be
fun. Instead, you feel discouraged and wonder, ``Why bother?'' But
your plan is a good one--children do need their parents to share
their favorite activities. It's just that a 2-year-old is so young
she has barely begun to learn about planning and following through.
</P>
<P>
   Your flexibility about this is one of the most important
elements of quality time with a toddler. So relax; let go of your
ideas of quality time and work it out with her. Quality time isn't
just a fun, upbeat time. It's an opportunity to build a
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be fooled by your child's apparent rejection of you or the
outing. Sit close to her and help her find words for her feelings
without trying to control her emotions. She could be at odds with
herself _ completely normal for a 2-year-old-and want a cozier time
with you as well as the exciting outing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Acknowledge Their Needs_ Out Loud &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If you recognized only the Chinese checkers game scenario as
quality time, you're laboring under the unnecessary burden of
thinking that quality time is something that occurs only when
everyone is happy.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you've forgotten a recent evening when both kids flew at
you as you entered the house after a stressful day at work. Your
oldest was complaining that her brother had wrecked her block
tower, and your son was howling because his sister refused to play
with him.
</P>
<P>
   To create quality time in this situation is undeniably
challenging, but it' helpful to remember that a little can go a
long way. Taking care not to add your burdens to your children's,
you might say, ``You know, right before dinner is a hard time for
everybody _ we're all hungry and tired. I bet that's part of why
you two are having trouble. Help me hang up my coat and come with
me while I make a note about a phone call I forgot to return; then
we'll see to these problems together.''
</P>
<P>
   The value of this time together lies not only in the resolution
of the problems but also in your being able to work on them
together. Even after a pressure-filled day, try to remember the
importance of connection.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Keep Your Cool &LR;
</P>
<P>
   You may think the situation with Samantha is an out-and-out
disaster, but little household accidents can be valuable
experiences. First, reassure your preschooler that this kind of
thing happens to everyone. Next, why not apologize for losing it?
Tell her it's like spilling juice: We don't mean to, but it
happens.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's a plus if you can keep your cool. Take a moment
to ease your child's frustration. You might call in the ``911
emergency paper-towel squad,'' and zoom from there to toothbrushing
and changing her tights. This gives your child a way to help right
things and supports her growing sense of mastery.
</P>
<P>
   Quality time is time you spend with your children having fun.
But it's also time you spend dealing with beginnings and endings,
downtime, squabbles and battles, disappointments, upsets, and the
stew of emotions _ yours and theirs _ that these circumstances stir
up.
</P>
<P>
   Quality time is any time you achieve an intimate connection with
your children.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Frances La Barre is a clinical psychologist practicing in New
York City.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call New York Times
Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480 or
fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
