<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8794 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANCER-TEST-HNS &LR;      01-26 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-TEST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIALISTS DIVIDED OVER VALUE OF BLOOD TEST FOR WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Time Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Martha Borgeson was planning a trip to Italy when
she saw her gynecologist for a routine exam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was all excited about the trip and I felt great,'' she said.
``My doctor gave me the exam and then a change came over his face.
He said, `You're not going to Italy.'''
</P>
<P>
   Several tests later, Borgeson received the news: She had ovarian
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't two tumors, it was three. I was in a state of shock,
obviously,'' said Borgeson, of North Greenbush, N.Y. That was
almost 10 years ago. Since then, Borgeson, 64, has had two major
surgeries at the Albany Medical Center Hospital, including a
complete hysterectomy, and regular infusions of chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   And every three months, she has a controversial blood test,
known as CA-125, to monitor her cancer. Dawn, Borgeson's healthy
38-year-old daughter, also gets the test twice a year, but as a
screening tool to pick up on any early signs of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Healthy women, even those without a family history of the
disease, are increasingly turning to the CA-125 test as a
diagnostic tool against a cancer that has for years been dubbed
``the silent killer.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 14,500 American women will die from ovarian cancer
this year and more than 25,000 new cases will be diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   Some specialists are advocating the test become as routine as
the pap smear, an annual exam to detect cervical cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet health specialists are cautious about the blood test, which
determines levels of a tumor marker known as CA-125. In the past,
the test has mostly been used as a way to monitor the recurrence of
disease by detecting high levels of CA-125 in the blood.
</P>
<P>
   Though effective as a monitoring tool, physicians say the CA-125
tests falls short of being a good diagnostic test.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may have an elevated test and you may not have ovarian
cancer at all,'' said Dr. Cora Bonatsos, a medical oncologist at
the Albany Regional Cancer Center.
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors fear that the inappropriate use of the test may
lead to unnecessary medical treatments and a lot of anxiety for
many women. ``The trouble with it is, you'll get a lot of false
positives,'' said Dr. Bruce Clark, an obstetrician and gynecologist
in nearby Latham.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians attribute the surge of interest in such an
unpredictable test to women's frustration with the disease. More
than half the women diagnosed with ovarian cancer die from it
within five years.
</P>
<P>
   Such grim statistics are blamed on the fact ovarian cancer is
notoriously difficult to diagnose in its earliest, most curable,
stages. By the time many doctors are able to detect the tumors
during a physical exam, many women have developed full-blown
disease.
</P>
<P>
   The standard treatment is surgery, followed by chemotherapy.
While there is no cure, ``we're keeping people alive longer,
feeling better,'' said Dr. John Malfetano, a professor of
obstetrics and gynecology at the Albany Medical College.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Kwong, who lives near Albany, had noticed only a little
spotting after a step aerobics class. Since it was unusual for her,
she called her doctor.
</P>
<P>
   At 34, five months after her wedding and after a series of
tests, Kwong was diagnosed with ovarian cancer and had a complete
hysterectomy. Now, four years later, she's challenged by weekly
chemotherapy treatments and some nagging questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I visited the gynecologist nine months before I had my
hysterectomy,'' she said. ``If they had drawn my CA-125 then, would
we have known earlier?''
</P>
<P>
   Malfetano said he understands women's fear of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``The symptoms are vague,'' he said. Sometimes, women will
notice pelvic or abdominal discomfort. Or they will experience
persistent gastrointestinal symptoms, like gas and bloating. Often,
as in the case with Borgeson, there are no complaints at all.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Malfetano still believes that the best use of the CA-125
test is for women already diagnosed with ovarian cancer as a way to
monitor tumor activity. An elevated level of CA-125 suggests that
tumors are reforming. He sees a lesser role for it in screening
only those women with a strong family history of breast or ovarian
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody else should make sure they get their annual
gynecological exam, he said. ``That's the best thing they can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Borgeson, meanwhile, has come up with her own strategy to beat
the odds.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, she finally toured Italy. And this spring, she and
three friends are celebrating their 65th birthdays with a
Mediterranean cruise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a lot of fun and a lot of laughs,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
