<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD AIR DAY IN THE CLINTON CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Look at what the tornado blew in, and then tell
me there isn't some kind of conspiracy to get President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton was speaking Sunday to tornado survivors in Beebe,
Ark., Paula Jones was in the crowd snapping a big piece of gum.
</P>
<P>
   She told reporters that she didn't come to her native Arkansas
from her home in Long Beach, Calif., to see Clinton, but ``to see
what they're going to do about the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones must be running for president of the Red Cross, now that
Elizabeth Dole is running for president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It sure looked like a case of political stalking. Jones once
said she was so traumatized by a proposition supposedly made by
Clinton that she suffered from an antipathy toward sex. Yet she
managed to blithely chew gum and walk into her alleged tormentor's
photo-op.
</P>
<P>
   You had to wonder who put her up to it.
</P>
<P>
   Jones can hardly afford to jet-set around to presidential
appearances like an anti-Clinton Alec Baldwin. She received
$850,000 in a settlement of her suit against Clinton, but
squabbling lawyers have claimed more than that in legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Jones has a lot of frequent-flier miles. Or maybe some
right-wingers gave this persistent plaintiff frequent-filer miles.
</P>
<P>
   Then Hurricane Monica was brought back by unpopular demand by
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr and the windbag House impeachment
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the same day the paths of Jones and Clinton
intersected with that of a tornado, every newspaper in America had
a photo of an unhappy Monica Lewinsky escorted to an interrogation
by the House prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting took place in a $5,000-a-night suite donated by a
Washington hotel _ called the ``Presidential Suite.'' At least
someone in Washington has a sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how big the right-wing conspiracy against Clinton
is. It's hard to tell, because our randy word-splitter of a
president has been his own biggest co-conspirator against himself.
</P>
<P>
   But it sure looks like there's been an effort to drag out all
the president's women, or at least two of them.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Senate voted to close its doors so we can't hear
them debating the dismissal of charges against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Let me see if I have this right. The senators are closing the
doors so taxpayers won't see them performing their highest duty,
yet the same senators will consider opening their doors so we can
see Monica Lewinsky? Is the Senate working for taxpayers or the
National Enquirer?
</P>
<P>
   As Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., said afterward: ``The vote in
the Senate said to the people, `We're cutting you out.'''
</P>
<P>
   You can be sure the Republicans wouldn't vote to cut us out if
Lewinsky testified.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
