<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMEONE'S HANGING ONTO ALL THOSE 50-CENT PIECES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Is the government making 50-cent coins anymore? It has been
over two years since I have seen a half-dollar coin in circulation.
</P>
<P>
   _ R.E.S., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: More than 30.7 million Kennedy half-dollars were produced in
1998, according to figures published by the U.S. Mint.
</P>
<P>
   This makes the 50-cent piece the least-circulated piece of U.S.
coinage _ 7.2 billion coins of other denominations were produced
during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   The scarcity of the coin is attributed to two things: the lack
of vending machines that accept 50-cent coins and the large number
of people who hang onto them after receiving the coins.
</P>
<P>
   Full coinage production figures are available on the U.S. Mint's
World Wide Web site at www.usmint.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I buy Kismet, a dice game that is similar to
Yahtzee?
</P>
<P>
   _ D.S., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Kismet is one of several classic games that is being
re-released by Endless Games as part of a ``retro games'' line of
products.
</P>
<P>
   Others include Concentration, Family Feud, Jotto, Password and
The Tickle Bee. Two more will be introduced in 1999: Beat the Clock
and the Price is Right.
</P>
<P>
   Password, the subject of another reader's question, has national
distribution and is being sold by Toys R Us, K-Mart, Target and
other chain stores.
</P>
<P>
   A company representative said that Kismet may be harder to find.
If you can't locate a copy, call Endless Games at (201) 386-9465 or
visit the World Wide Web site www.endlessgames.com for product
availability information.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to Dan Quayle?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.P.D., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Send letters to Vice President Quayle in care of his
political action committee, Campaign America, at 6263 N. Scottsdale
Road, Suite 292, Scottsdale, AZ 85250.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle told reporters earlier this month that he will probably
enter the 2000 presidential race. The Arizona Republic reported
that in February, Quayle is likely to file with the Federal
Election Committee to create a presidential exploratory campaign
committee.
</P>
<P>
   You can send e-mail to Quayle by visiting the Campaign America
World Wide Web site at www.quayle.org.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
