<HEADLINE>
GORE COURTS CALIFORNIA WITH CASH AND PROMISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 and MACKENZIE WARREN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Vice President Al Gore has become a regular
fixture in California, delivering federal largess and apparently
sending the message to fellow Democrats that when it comes to
votes, he owns the state.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who is preparing to run for the presidency in 2000, has
visited vote-rich California at least 52 times since he took office
six years ago, including two trips this month in which he again
brought promises of cash from Uncle Sam.
</P>
<P>
   In events Monday in San Francisco and Sacramento, Gore announced
the Clinton administration's intent to restore $1.3 billion in
health and welfare benefits cut off to legal immigrants in 1996.
Gore also promised $400 million to modernize a network of global
positioning satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Gore announced federal aid to help California
orange farmers harmed by freezing weather, and in a Sacramento
event Monday, the vice president announced $43 million to help
crime victims pay medical bills and other costs.
</P>
<P>
   In a September trip to the state, Gore announced $1.9 million in
grants to help the police fight domestic violence. Also last year,
he toured a San Francisco airport hanger earlier and announced $100
million for new bomb detectors at the nation's airports.
</P>
<P>
   By making showing up in California to announce the federal
largess, Gore can travel at taxpayer expense. He visited Los
Angeles on Sunday, announcing $366 million in federal funding for
information technology research, and a tax credit for research and
development.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, it boosts Gore's profile in a state that holds an
awesome 54 electoral votes in presidential elections. With the
California primary 14 months away, Gore is attempting to claim his
turf against other potential Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the state party is sending a discouraging message to
other possible Democratic presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're looking at a tight squeeze here,'' said Art Torres, the
state Democratic Party chairman. ``I think it's going to be
absolutely impossible for another candidate to get to where Gore is
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was scoring points Monday with Hispanics, who were livid at
the welfare cuts to legal immigrants and emerged as a crucial
voting bloc in the state's general election last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton and I made a solemn promise to this nation
that we would remove these harmful provisions,'' Gore said. ``We
are following through on that promise.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a center for senior citizens in San Francisco's
Chinatown, Gore said the administration would seek disability,
health and nutrition benefits in the budget the president submits
to Congress on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Among the provisions the administration is seeking is a
restoration of Supplemental Security Income and Medicaid
eligibility to more than 50,000 legal immigrants who entered the
United States after Aug. 22, 1996, the date when welfare reform
legislation became law _ and shut out hundreds of thousands of
legal immigrants from various social benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the $930 million proposal would allow people who
arrived after the deadline to be eligible once again as early as
2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``No child should be forced to suffer when their parents came
here seeking a better life,'' Gore said in a news conference at the
Chinatown center.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., said she thought the proposals
would be approved by the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a fight,'' Pelosi said. ``But I'm optimistic. I
think we'll be successful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
