<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8860 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-26 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN IDEAL DECADE FOR ZERO TOLERANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's probably harder than you think to come up with an original
complaint about language. You're maddened by less when it should be
fewer, it's instead of its, and sportscasters saying ``they played
aggressive''? Join the club; millions of others feel your pain.
</P>
<P>
   But Thor Kirleis has a gripe I'd call almost unique, if that
weren't a forbidden phrase: The locution that drives him nuts is
our near-universal habit of saying oh (or O) for zero in dates and
other strings of numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather was born in nineteen eight,'' he writes, not in
``nineteen, oh, eight. . . . My Zip code is not oh, eighteen,
sixty-four, but zero, eighteen, sixty-four.'' (Most people would
say oh-one-eight-six-four, in my experience, but that's another
question.)
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the history behind this terribly misused word?''
Kirleis asks.
</P>
<P>
   Well, to abbreviate the history considerably, the answer is that
the ``misuse'' has been there from the start. No doubt because the
figure 0 and the letter O look so similar, zero was called oh by
the time of their earliest recorded citations: The first example of
zero in the Oxford English Dictionary is dated 1604, and the first
example of O to mean zero, nothing, a cipher, is from ``King
Lear,'' 1605.
</P>
<P>
   Zero as a concept had come late to Europe _ around 1200 _ and
its tardiness is one reason for our current millennium-dating
confusion: The sixth-century designer of the Christian calendar
went directly from 1 BC to AD 1, with no year zero in between.
Hence the year 2000 is the last of the second millennium, not the
first of the third millennium.
</P>
<P>
   But while England was adapting to the new math, it already had
naught (or nought) as a word for nothing, and that too was used to
mean zero, the Arabic numeral. Naught is now little used, but it
survives in noughts-and-crosses, the British name for tick-tack-toe
_ evidence that the mark we think of as the letter O is perceived
as a zero by English speakers across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   So there's not much historical support for purism on the
zero-vs.-oh question _ and the decade that's hurtling our way will
be an especially difficult time for defenders of the faith. There's
been a lot of playful speculation about what we're going to call
the zero-laden years of the next decade, but nobody's predicting
that we'll say two-zero-zero-five; it's going to be either two
thousand (and) five or twenty-oh-five, and probably both.
</P>
<P>
   I had figured that 2001, at least, was locked in as ``Two
thousand and one,'' the usual rendition of the movie title ``2001:
A Space Odyssey,'' but just days ago I heard someone call it
``Twenty-oh-one.'' So I anticipate a lot of variations during the
oh-years, and the decade will probably be past before we reach a
consensus.
</P>
<P>
   Another sore point is likely to be that and in two thousand and
one. A kindergarten teacher wrote to say that she teaches her
pupils to count one hundred one, one hundred two, but wonders
whether one hundred and one is equally acceptable. It is, though
adding and is more informal than omitting it, and more common in
speech, where the extra word can provide a pause that may help your
listener.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, earlier this month, when radio host Christopher Lydon
and wordsman Richard Lederer were batting around names for the next
decade on WBUR's ``The Connection,'' a listener phoned to suggest
``the andies'' _ on the grounds that we would all be saying ``two
thousand and one,'' and so on, through 2010 or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``The andies'' isn't likely to win this war _ too obscure, too
reminiscent of undies and the Archies. Oh for zero, on the other
hand, is solidly established. As we grope toward a name for the new
decade, we'll surely find better issues to debate than the merits
of these useful little words.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The Boston
Globe, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.
Please include a hometown and phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 1328EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
