<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-OBRIEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'BRIEN TURNS OHIO STATE INTO A SOLID WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ So you want to be a coach, eh?
</P>
<P>
   Barely 12 hours after his team has whomped Purdue by 29, Ohio
State coach Jim O'Brien is sitting at the wheel of his sport
utility vehicle with thoughts of Minnesota running through his
mind. Celebration time is over. A coach really inhabits only two
time frames _ the present and the future. His first thought is
seeing to it that his kids do not get carried away with the Purdue
game, and he must do so without breaking down their confidence. His
second thought concerns the immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried about how we're going to guard Quincy Lewis,'' he
says, alluding to the Gophers' smooth 21-points-per-game small
forward. ``That's a tough matchup for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The essentials of coaching never change. When he was at St.
Bonaventure, he'd be worried about some kid at Niagara. When he was
at Boston College, he'd be concerned about a Georgetown Hoya or
Connecticut Husky. But settings and circumstances can be very
different. O'Brien now finds himself plugged into a very different
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was hired,'' he says, ``they talked about winning the
national championship. They did it once before, and they believe
they can do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State won the NCAA championship in 1960, and made it to the
championship game in each of the next two seasons. You can look it
up. The names of Jerry Lucas, John Havlicek, Larry Siegfried, and
Joe Roberts still have resonance here.
</P>
<P>
   But something has been amiss. Eldon Miller, Gary Williams, and
Randy Ayers combined to produce a mere eight 20-win seasons since
the sainted Fred Taylor left in 1976. The last NCAA tournament
appearance was in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. People in Columbus believe there is no reason Ohio
State basketball cannot rise again, and let's make one thing very
clear: No one can come in here and bitch about the facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few professional arenas are comparable,'' says O'Brien,
and the man speaks the truth. The 18,000-seat Value Center Arena at
Schottenstein Center is drop-dead gorgeous and comfy. If it's not
the best campus arena in America, let's just say there are none
better.
</P>
<P>
   Many a school would be satisfied with Ohio State's discard. St.
John Arena seats 13,000 and it's not exactly falling down. But when
Jerome Schottenstein knocks on the door and you've got a chance for
those delectable luxury boxes and all the requisite modern
amenities, you don't turn him away.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're Jim O'Brien, you don't turn away from doing
commercials for Kroger, a mammoth grocery chain and longtime Ohio
State backer. You also have the obligatory coach's TV and radio
shows, the latter broadcast throughout the state via OSU's
56-affilate network. There is constant exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did more speaking, and was invited to more events in one
year than in 11 at BC,'' O'Brien says.
</P>
<P>
   It's pretty much a case of ``Gee, Toto, we're not in Chestnut
Hill anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Did someone mention BC?
</P>
<P>
   There are but three pieces of evidence in his office to suggest
that 48-year-old Jim O'Brien has had another coaching life before
this one.
</P>
<P>
   The first is a Big East Coach of the Year trophy.
</P>
<P>
   The second is a photo of Howard Eisley, Billy Curley, Malcolm
Huckaby, and Gerrod Abram, the four kids who went from a 1-15 Big
East record as freshmen to within two minutes of the Final Four
three years later. They are sitting in front of the bleachers and
the photo has the following inscription: ``We're Not Ones For
Words, So In A Nutshell Coach . . . Thanks For Everything. Howard,
Billy, Malcolm and Gerrod.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is a photo of O'Brien with his arm around a
disconsolate Eisley, who has lost his dribble, and, with it, the
last chance for BC to defeat Florida and advance to the 1994 Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``My favorite photo,'' O'Brien says. ``We are actually standing
on the playing floor while the game is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien's official, unswerving policy with regard to the events
that led to his being here in Columbus is to let others do the
talking. What went down at his alma mater was too public and too
painful. He knows he came out looking like the bad guy, and what's
done is done. He chooses to, as they say, move on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If anyone wonders whether or not Jim O'Brien can coach, consider
that, with the addition of just one 5-foot-9-inch guard, a team
that was 8-22 last year now stands at 15-5 and is a legitimate
candidate to become both Big 10 champion and a participant in the
NCAA tourney. Of course, that 5-9 guard is the indefatigtable James
``Scoonie'' Penn, one of 11 players who either left or declined to
come to BC when the administration detonated the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to provide leadership,'' says Penn. ``I'm not worried
about scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be something of an oversimplification, but the fact is
that Ohio State's primary offensive weapon is the explosive Michael
Redd, a devastating scorer who last week reached the 1,000-point
plateau in the shortest time since Lucas did it in the early '60.
</P>
<P>
   Redd, a slasher of the first order, is a very tough player to
defend.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the foul line in,'' says O'Brien, ``he's as good as any
player in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim O'Brien and Ohio State. It is tough on the ear, isn't it? He
found out it was equally tough on the psyche of the high school and
AAU coaches of Ohio when he and his staff first began to make the
rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like, `We don't know these guys from a hole in the
wall,' '' O'Brien explains. ```Who are these guys? You're not one
of us.'''
</P>
<P>
   The flip side is that Obie &AMP; Co. were now wearing the scarlet
and gray.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot imagine the magnitude of the long arms of Ohio
State,'' O'Brien points out. ``That carries unbelievable clout in
the state of Ohio. You're from Ohio State, so they are interested
in what you have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   It also helped that O'Brien was in the company of trusted
friends and associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The single most important thing for me was that all our guys
came with us,'' he explains. ``We were starting from scratch here,
but we all knew each other. I didn't have to worry about, `Can I
trust this guy? Can he do the job?' That was never a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   This may be the most intact staff in all of Division 1
basketball. Associate head coach Rick Boyages and assistants Paul
Biancardi and Dave Spiller have each been with O'Brien for at least
eight years. Then throw in Randy Shrout, who was at BC for 19 years
as athletic trainer and assistant athletic director and is now Ohio
State director of basketball operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I handle everything but basketball,'' says Shrout, who takes
care of scheduling, travel, and the budget (the basketball program
has its own). It sounds more like a management team than a coaching
staff, but that's life in the express lane of college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   One thing O'Brien will never forget is the summer of 1997. Here
he was, the new guy in town, eager to make a good impression. And
what was his first official act? He threw five players off the
team, three of them double-figure scorers. ``Even worse, most of
them were from Ohio,'' O'Brien points out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Academic problems, social problems, basketball problems,'' he
explains. ``There was a lot of turmoil. There were some talented
players involved, but it was all in the best interests of the
program. But you think that wasn't an issue, an outsider coming in
and throwing those Ohio kids off the team?''
</P>
<P>
   What O'Brien seeks are more players like Redd, who is not only
gifted but also happens to come from Columbus West High School.
Keeping the good Ohio kids home has been an issue at Ohio State.
O'Brien has tried to make nice with the very influential Ohio High
School Coaches Association, and he feels he's making inroads. One
of his three current commitments is Yugoslavian forward Slobodan
Ocokoljic, by way of Massillon's Washington High School.
</P>
<P>
   He laughs when he thinks of his career progression.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went from St. Bonaventure to BC, it was a no-brainer,''
he says. ``There were no contract issues. I was coming back to
coach at my school, and nothing else mattered. This time I had a
zillion questions. My first BC contract was a page and a half. This
contract is a couple of inches thick.''
</P>
<P>
   He remains fascinated with the impact Ohio State has on the
community of Columbus, and the importance of the program. He will
always be grateful to people who remained upbeat enough last year
throughout a 17-game losing streak to cheer the walk-ons when they
when they entered in garbage time.
</P>
<P>
   But he also knows that the only reason he is here is that Randy
Ayers couldn't get it done. He knows how fragile his guard-oriented
team is, and he can't help daydreaming about the help he should get
next year from 7-3 Juco student Aleksandar Radojevic. He coaches in
an unforgiving league, where every road game is a guarantee of a
packed house. The people won't be smiling through losing streaks in
a year or two. They'll be signing petitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a look at this place,'' he says. ``You know it's serious
business.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota game has come and gone, and now O'Brien has more
problems. His team ran all over the Gophers by the exact same
29-point margin (89-60). Quincy Lewis? Obie threw a
triangle-and-two at Lewis and guard Kevin Clark. Lewis had 23, but
it was all cosmetic. Ohio State led from wire to wire.
</P>
<P>
   The next game is at Michigan State Wednesday night. His kids may
be up in the ozone somewhere, but Jim O'Brien knows there's not
going to be any 29-point victory in East Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have to make something up,'' he says. ``I'm going
to have to come to the next practice with an attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   He's had back-to-back 29-point wins, and all he can think of is
what little fabrication he can spring on his team to snap it back
to reality. And you thought coaching was all about X's and O's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
