<HEADLINE>
SAMARANCH SHOWS HIS OLYMPIC METTLE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ ``And what do you think of Monsieur
Samaranch?,'' a taxi driver asked on the way to International
Olympic Committee headquarters Monday afternoon. ``Quelle salade,
n'est-ce pas?''
</P>
<P>
   The French have a word for the distasteful five-ringed tangle of
crudites that has evolved from the Salt Lake City payoff scandal.
The august IOC's honor has been blackened. Three members have
resigned, six more likely will be expelled and more may follow as
the investigation broadens to other cities and other years.
</P>
<P>
   And Juan Antonio Samaranch, the 78-year-old Spanish marquis who
has presided over the IOC for nearly two decades, has found himself
in the center of a global hurricane. Everyone outside the Olympic
``family,'' it seems, from Salt Lake committee officials to
newspapers, have been calling for his white-haired head, which they
charge has been buried in the sand for years while bribery and
graft swirled around him.
</P>
<P>
   Though Samaranch says he had been hearing whispers of corruption
for years, he said the IOC never had evidence to expel members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some names on the Salt Lake City list were always in the
rumors,'' he said Monday, sitting in his office at the lakeside
Chateau de Vidy here. ``But the first time in all the years that we
have proof is now.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday's front page, the Times of London called Samaranch
``monstrously self-aggrandizing,'' a ``pretend president'' who
practices ``passive corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Samaranch: How Long Can He Hang On?,'' the local weekly
L'Hebdo wondered recently amid the worst scandal in the IOC's 105
years.
</P>
<P>
   But Samaranch insisted again that he would hang on until his
term expires in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``To resign in this moment when the boat is in a storm, this is
not my style,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the family apparently wants Samaranch to stay at the
helm. The IOC's executive board gave him a unanimous vote of
confidence on Sunday, and Samaranch will ask the same from his 114
colleagues on the full committee when they meet here in special
session in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``My position is clear,'' he said. ``I am elected president by
the members of the IOC. I will ask the members if I have their
support or not. I do not depend on outsiders.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch is the only president that most of the Lords of the
Rings have ever known. He has nominated all but 23 of them and has
been a member longer than all but four. He has seen the Olympic
movement through two major boycotts, the breakup of the Eastern
bloc, and several doping scandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have a president who's brought you through the good
times and then get rid of him when the bad times come,'' said
executive board member Kevan Gosper of Australia. ``If ever we
needed a good president, an exeprienced president, it's now.''
</P>
<P>
   If Samaranch were to resign, the radical cleansing and reform
that members will vote on in March _ expelling six more members and
allowing a 15-member election committee to pick the site of the
2006 Winter Games _ might not happen, IOC officials warn.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you change presidents now,'' says marketing director
Michael Payne, ``we haven't got a chance of completing those
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the IOC were a multinational corporation like Coca-Cola or
McDonald's, Samaranch might have stepped down already.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can't take a corporate model and apply it to this
model,'' says Payne.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC is a nonprofit club whose members, from Algeria to
Zimbabwe, meet once a year. They are not elected, but in IOC-speak,
``co-opted.'' They serve without pay and they make their own rules.
When the executive board voted to expel six of them Sunday, it
wasn't because they were corrupt, Samaranch said. It was because
they had broken their sacred oath.
</P>
<P>
   And Samaranch, as president, is not so much a CEO as a global
ambassador whose mission is to preach the virtues of Olympism. He
has spent much of the past two decades jetting around the planet;
he hopes to visit all 200 member countries before he leaves office.
He consorts with kings and presidents. And wherever he goes,
Samaranch is treated like royalty.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1991 IOC session in England, where Nagano was named host
of the 1998 Winter Games, Samaranch reportedly stayed in a
$1,000-a-night penthouse suite with a fireplace, Jacuzzi, and baby
grand piano. Salt Lake City has set aside $60,000 for his lodgings
during the 2002 Games.
</P>
<P>
   But when questions of his lavish lifestyle come up, Samaranch
bristles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot understand about this lifestyle,'' he said. ``My
lifestyle is very simple. When I read in some newspapers that I
take a helicopter from Lausanne to Geneva (35 miles away), that's
crazy. It's much quicker to go by car.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch lives in a $200-a-day suite in the Lausanne Palace
Hotel. ``It is not a big suite, I assure you.'' He dresses in plain
gray or blue suits. ``I am a very normal man,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
