<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC GLORY AT MUCH TOO HIGH A PRICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So now we know one way to become a world class city: shower
greedy members of the International Olympic Committee with cash and
other lavish gifts.
</P>
<P>
   It happened in Salt Lake City, in Sydney, Australia, and who
knows where else? The participants in these go-for-the-gold schemes
are trying to wriggle around the obvious and say the money and
gifts bestowed upon IOC members were ``inducements,'' not bribes.
But the truth is clear and beyond euphemism.
</P>
<P>
   These cities cheated to win, using money as dishonorably as some
Olympic athletes use performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   It is a huge scandal and embarrassment for the IOC, which is
promising to reform the bidding process. Yet so far, the reform
effort seems minimal. Six IOC delegates have been expelled, three
have resigned, and one has been scolded.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC has a long way to go before it can hope to restore its
tarnished reputation. In the meantime, this scandal should make
civic leaders across the country rethink the current definition of
``world class'' urban greatness. As we draw closer to the
millennium, the definition has less and less to do with schools,
housing, the arts and sciences _ and more and more to do with the
construction of grandiose monuments to sports, spoiled, overpaid
athletes, and corporate sponsorships.
</P>
<P>
   Think about what is happening today in Boston. Stoked by a
strong economy and prodded by powerful development forces, this
city is on the verge of changing its look and feel forever. It is
tempted regularly to accept the new turn-of-the-century definition
of greatness _ stadium packages and the like. Anyone who resists is
taunted for being shortsighted and parochial.
</P>
<P>
   Yet those most intimately involved in the modern greatness chase
already know a dark potential downside almost always exists.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, a group of local business people tried hard to
stir some high-level corporate interest in the Olympics. Their goal
was to woo a summer Olympic games to the Athens of America. When
they could not get corporate sponsorship, the effort died. The
lethal blow came from the John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance
Company _ one of a dozen worldwide corporate sponsors of the
Olympic movement _ when executives there declined to jump on board
the Boston Olympic bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock chairman Stephen L. Brown offended local bigshots behind
Boston's nascent effort when he put his name to a newspaper opinion
piece headlined ``The Olympics will hurt Boston.'' Hancock, he
wrote then, knows ``enough about the Olympics to respect the
distinct advantages which accompany the Games. But those advantages
come at a very steep price and the reward will vary from one host
city to another.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Hancock's message was even blunter. Hancock president
David D'Alessandro says he told Boston's Olympic advocates ``there
is the potential for corruption. Be prepared to entertain lavishly.
Be prepared for what we described as an endless food chain of
people arriving and wanting things. The problem is, you don't dare
say no.''
</P>
<P>
   These warnings came long before the still-unfolding Olympic
scandal. Even without knowledge of specific corruption, a major
sponsor like Hancock knew other grim truths about hosting the
games. For instance: The interlocking Olympic rings bring a host
city a short burst of glory and then something much less desirable
_ too much debt for too much of the wrong kind of infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The highest point people have is not actually hosting the
games, but winning them,'' says D'Alessandro. ``There is very
little evidence of any longterm economic value, and there appears
to be very little evidence of continuing civic pride after they're
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   As details of the current scandal pour out, Hancock is taking a
strong stand, calling for a broad and tough investigation of
bidding irregularities. Beyond that, D'Alessandro also believes the
Olympic Committee should pick a permanent host site and be done
with future bidding wars and their potential for corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should a single city overbuild itself, extend its
taxpayers beyond their means and have unbelievable political
battles for an unimproved economy, if not a deteriorating economy,
and facilities that will never be used again?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   That is an excellent question.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps we are just too tempted by the notion of a quick and
easy fix, a pain-free way to pump new life into cities. So we fight
for the glamour of an Olympic extravaganza, a glitzy new stadium or
a massive convention center. We are so dazzled by the promise of a
giant pay day, we choose to ignore the simple truth.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Thomas M. Menino spoke it in a line in his recent State of
the City address: ``Stadiums do not revive cities, '' he said.
``People do.''
</P>
<P>
   The same can be said of an Olympic contest. A fleeting glory is
associated with all elements of this competition. But, as the
people of Salt Lake City now know _ at what a price!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
