<SLUG> BC-OLY-CONSULTANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EL FARNAWANI HAS BEEN HIRED BEFORE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (s, f and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Mahmoud El Farnawani, the Canadian middleman
identified by the International Olympic Committee Sunday as having
received $161,000 from Salt Lake City to ``influence'' North
Africans to support that city's bid for the 2002 Winter Games, also
worked over the years as a paid consultant for other cities seeking
to win the prestigious Games.
</P>
<P>
   According to acquaintances and news reports, the 65-year-old
Egyptian-born entrepreneur from Oakville, Ontario, was paid $60,000
by Sydney to help win the 2000 Summer Olympics and was hired by
Athens as a consultant in its successful bid for the 2004 games. He
has also worked for Toronto, Nagano (Japan), and Istanbul to lobby
North Africans on the Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Nagano was site of the 1998 Winter Games while Toronto, which
bid for the 1996 Summer Games, and Istanbul (2000 Summer Games)
failed in their efforts to be selected as Olympic cities.
</P>
<P>
   El Farnawani was named in this week's report by the executive
board of the IOC on the investigation that led to the recommended
expulsion of six committee members for accepting cash and other
gifts from organizers of the 2002 Winter Games in Salt Lake City.
Four of the officials are Africans, and one is from the North
African nation of Sudan. In addition, two of three IOC members who
have resigned in the scandal are African, one from Libya, the other
from Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic officials say there is no evidence that El Farnawani did
anything wrong in his efforts to convince Olympic Committee members
from North Africa that the Utah city was the best place for the
Games. He was hired by the Salt Lake organizing committee ``on the
basis . . . he might be able to influence North African members,''
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing illegal or improper about that, said El
Farawani's lawyer, David M. Goodman of Toronto, saying the report
exonerates his longtime client.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked as a lobbyist, as a middleman, as a protocol man,''
but not as a bagman, Goodman said. ``He has been on the periphery
of the Olympics for years and years.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, El Farnawani has worked on the edges of the Olympic
movement since the 1950s, first as a volleyball coach in his native
Egypt and later as a well-paid agent of influence for cities hoping
to snare the games.
</P>
<P>
   He emigrated to Canada in the early 1970s by way of Libya.
</P>
<P>
   ``My belief is I did nothing wrong,'' El Farnawani told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   As president of Trade &AMP; Sports Canada Inc., an Ontario firm that
specializes in sports souvenirs, El Farnawani won a merchandising
franchise for the 1988 Winter Games in Calgary, Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, El Farnawani has been able to sell his services
to Olympic organizing committees in North America, Asia, and
Australia ``because of his extensive friends and contacts in North
Africa,'' said Goodman. ``He knows a lot of people in that region.
He could be persuasive because he could say, `Hey, I'm a North
African, like you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Along with pitching for Salt Lake City and Sydney, El Farnawani
was able to advise Olympic Committee members about Islamic customs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe something as simple as telling them to be sure not to
serve pork to a Muslim, or that it would be a polite touch to make
sure there is a prayer rug in the hotel room,'' Goodman said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Toronto Star, he worked as an unpaid volunteer
for a Toronto group that tried unsucessfully to win the 1996
Olympics for that city, and more recently was briefly a paid
consultant for Toronto's effort to secure the 2008 Games.
</P>
</TEXT>
