<HEADER>
A8876 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-NEGOTIATORS-BOS &LR;      01-26 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NEGOTIATORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIAN AND WHITE PEACEMAKERS OF THE FRONTIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
INTO THE AMERICAN WOODS 
Negotiators on the Pennsylvania Frontier 
By James H. Merrell 
Norton, 463 pp., illustrated, $27.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In February 1744, a Pennsylvania fur trader named Jack Armstrong
and two companions were ambushed and killed by Mushemeelin, a
Delaware Indian whose horse Armstrong had seized in payment for a
long overdue debt. It was the kind of encounter that at other times
and places had triggered escalating acts of retaliation. In New
England, for example, such incidents had set off the Pequot War in
1637 and King Philip's War in 1676. But Pennsylvania was enjoying
``The Long Peace'' that was to last some 70 years, from the
colony's founding in 1681 to the eve of the French and Indian War.
</P>
<P>
   William Penn is historically _ and rightly _ given credit for
creating the conditions which allowed for so long a period of peace
on the Allegheny frontier. But as historian James H. Merrell shows
in this engaging account, it was a peace maintained and nourished
by a fascinating crew of Colonial and native ``go-betweens,''
skilled and knowledgeable negotiators who journeyed back and forth
between the wilderness and the settlements defusing incidents such
as the killing of Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Such go-betweens were not unknown in the other colonies _ among
them must be counted Concord lawyer John Hoar, who negotiated the
ransoming of Mary Rowlandson after she was taken captive in the
raid on Lancaster during King Philip's War. But the difference in
Pennsylvania was that the position of negotiator had been
institutionalized.
</P>
<P>
   As Merrell reconstructs the Armstrong incident, after the
killings became known, two veteran negotiators _ Shickellamy, an
Oneida Indian, and Conrad Weiser, a Pennsylvania farmer _ were
pressed into service. ``In coping with this crisis,'' Merrell
writes, Shickellamy ``had to make inquiries and sift rumors, send
and receive messages, sit with Delaware and colonial councils, and
explain things to Iroquois ambassadors and provincial officials.''
Mushemeelin was arrested and brought to Philadelphia _ by his own
Delawares _ and eventually executed.
</P>
<P>
   Merrell, a professor of history at Northwestern University and
author of the Bancroft Prize-winning ``The Indians' New World,''
would have made a valuable contribution to Colonial history had he
gone no further than recounting so much of the Armstrong incident
as could be found in the provincial records. But he has gone far
beyond that, to uncover and reveal the lives and skills of the
negotiators _ ``an elusive lot,'' he writes, ``as obscure as they
were diverse'' _ and thus greatly enlarge our understanding of life
on the Colonial frontier.
</P>
<P>
   There was a consensus, Merrell writes, on what made a good
go-between _ ``a true good man . . . (who) spoke their words and
our words, and not his own . . . (someone) hearty and sincere''
even if, as most did, he drank too much.
</P>
<P>
   An Indian negotiator was definitely not to go native on arriving
in Philadelphia, even if he had donned a hat and riding boots to
get there, but the Colonial negotiator was expected to do so when
arriving in an Indian village.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Merrell writes, the Indian go-betweens invariably
held the upper hand in negotiations, for even if they understood
English, they insisted on having them carried out in their language
and ``their diplomatic customs held sway.'' Even Shickellamy could
be ``curt'' with Weiser when ``he was slow to pick up the finer
points of Indian protocol.''
</P>
<P>
   Much as in today's shuttle diplomacy, Colonial negotiators spent
much of their time on the road. Weiser reported once responding to
an Indian welcome by saying that ``it was enough to kill a man to
come such a long and bad road over hills, rocks, old trees, and
rivers, and to fight through a cloud of vermin and all kinds of
poisoned worms and creeping things, besides being loaded with a
disagreeable message'' _ upon hearing which, he added, ``they
laughed.''
</P>
<P>
   The fortunes of geography had provided space for peace to
flourish on the Allegheny frontier _ something that was notably
lacking in New England. But as military pressure from French Canada
increased _ the ambush and defeat of Braddock's army at the forks
of the Susquehanna occurred in July 1754 _ there were a series of
Indian attacks on Pennsylvania's frontier settlements.
</P>
<P>
   The Colonists, writes Merrell, ``lost faith in the culture of
diplomacy,'' which they had been willing enough to accept when it
``promoted trade, kept peace (and) bought land.'' But now, Indian
raids were taking place even as peace talks were under way. And
that an Indian war party ``spoke German to their German victims''
at one frontier massacre suggests to Merrell that the killings were
``at once a legacy of negotiators and a repudiation of that
legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   That legacy would be repudiated again and again over the next
century and a half, but it is important to know what was possible _
and what might have been.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 1340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
