<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8877 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MITZVAH-RENEWAL-2ND &LR;  &UR;      01-26 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MITZVAH-RENEWAL-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... greeting guests.)  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Or maybe it's a function of the fact that rabbis and Jewish
educators _ deeply concerned about keeping Jewish families
religious in an assimilated world _ are becoming more vocal about
how to celebrate such events. Many, for example, are holding
workshops for bar and bat Mitzvah parents, suggesting ways to bring
more meaning and tradition into the synagogue ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   And they are not hesitating to talk about the parties.
</P>
<P>
   Says Rabbi Edgar Weinsberg of Temple Beth El in Swampscott,
Mass.: ``I feel very free in asking people to reconsider how much
they are going to lavish on this. I'll tell you that on one
occasion, about 10 years ago, we had here what is affectionately
known as a New York-style bar mitzvah. Everyone gathered in the
social hall, with wall-to-wall mirrors of reflective paper, with
strobe lights and an imported New York band. And then suddenly, the
curtains parted and a dancer leaped off the stage with a cape that
said, ``Captain Bar Mitzvah.''
</P>
<P>
   The downsizing trend is being noted even by party planners such
as Jane Haas of Hopple Popple in Newton, Mass., who has been
organizing custom bar and bat mitzvah celebrations for 21 years.
``I'm noticing that people are now taking a lot of things into
account, one of them being how to prioritize,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Of course not everyone is scaling down. And scaling down can
also be a matter of degree. As Bob Isaacs put it, ``going from
$60,000 to $40,000 is a step down. And so is going from $20,000 to
$5,000.'' And clearly party facilitators are in no danger of going
out of business. Business, in fact, has never been better for
Siagel Productions of Newton, the largest company in New England
offering bar and bat mitzvah disc jockey entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year is stronger than the last, there is no doubt about
it,'' says Cindy Siagel, who runs the business with her husband
Steven. Likewise, for Hopple Popple, business is ``the best it's
ever been,'' Haas says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's the big deal about bar mitzvahs, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   In his popular book ``Putting God on the Guest List: How to
Reclaim the Spiritual Meaning of Your Child's Bar or Bat Mitzvah,''
(Jewish Lights Publishing, 1996), Long Island, N.Y. Rabbi Jeffrey
K. Salkin writes the rituals have been American Judaism's spiritual
mirror, reflecting changing trends in the manner of observance.
</P>
<P>
   But they are also its sociological mirror. In the 1960s and
1970s, being able to pay for a big splash was, for many
recently-emigrated, socially-insecure Jewish families, ``a way of
demonstrating they'd made it,'' says Jonathan Sarna, professor of
American Jewish History at Brandeis University.
</P>
<P>
   The splashes started to get even splashier with the financial
good times of the 1980s. And in the child-centered 1990s, with
two-working-parent families, parties escalated to the point of what
may have been the ultimate over-the-top party, held recently in
Pittsburgh. Rumored to cost half a million dollars, it had a
``Titanic'' theme complete with phosphorescent artificial icebergs
and a huge photo of the bat mitzvah girl's face superimposed over
Kate Winslet's body.
</P>
<P>
   But the countering trend is gaining on several fronts:
</P>
<P>
   _ Growing numbers of families are having their ceremonies in
Israel. ``Every year the number increases,'' according to Ilene
Wallerstein of the Illinois-based Israel Discovery Tours, one of
several companies booking such trips. ``People are looking for a
meaningful family experience, rather than a party that is over in a
few hours.'' Robin Gross and her family, of Lakeville, Mass., chose
that option for her daughter. The ceremony took place atop the
historic mountain fortress Masada, followed by a reception in a Tel
Aviv hotel for about 60 family members and friends, many of whom
lived in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   _ A push by Jewish educators to encourage families to perform
(itals)mitzvot(unitals) during the Bar/Bat Mitzvah year. At Temple
Emanuel in Newton, for example, family educator Maxine Zarchan
holds seminars for families on ``how to make a difference in the
world'' and links children with volunteer opportunities that match
their skills and interests. Many parents are choosing to donate a
percentage of what a bar mitzvah costs to the Los Angeles-based
national organization Mazon: A Jewish Response to Hunger, which
makes grants to anti-hunger agencies, mostly in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   _ Many parents who do have festive celebrations are making
charity part of the theme. For example, they are doing away with
strictly decorative centerpieces and making centerpieces with
social value _ baskets filled with toys or books or art supplies
that they will then distribute to children at a hospital, or a
homeless shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get them on a very consistent basis,'' says Suzanne Graca,
child life specialist at Boston's Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   As for Robin Rouse, she is busy planning her daughter Sara's bat
mitzvah, scheduled for August. Sara has decided to make her own
table centerpieces using teddy bears her mother purchased at
after-Christmas sales, and donating them afterward an agency that
works with children. Each bear will be donated in the name of a
guest she wants to honor, each of whom will be presented with a
miniature bear that she's making from clay.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Sara's party will be themeless doesn't bother her
in the least. Nor, looking back, does her older brother Ryan have
any regrets about the simplicity of his bar mitzvah. ``I've been to
lots of bar mitzvahs; some of them were pretty decadent,'' he says.
``But I don't feel like I missed out on anything important.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
