<HEADLINE>
AH . . . AH . . . AHCHOO! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In America, we say ``Bless you'' after someone sneezes. In
Germany, of course, it's ``Gesundheit.'' But what do they say in
other places? Travel Holiday lets us in on a few expressions:
</P>
<P>
   --In France, ``A tes amours'' _ ``To your lovers.''
</P>
<P>
   --In Quebec _ ``A vos souhaits'' _ ``To your wishes.'' (Some
believe sneezes are lucky.)
</P>
<P>
   --In Lebanon _ ``Nasho!'' _ ``May you grow up healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   --In Japan _ They say nothing. You, however, are expected to
say, ``Shitsurei'' _ ``Excuse me.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: What time is it at the North and South poles?
(Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of time: The Time Museum at the Clock Tower Resort in
Rockford, Ill., is our Museum of the Month. The museum contains a
priceless collection of 1,200 watches, clocks, and other devices
illustrating technological developments in timekeeping. For more
information, call (815) 398-6000. Rockford is 60 miles northwest of
Chicago. &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: The petting zoo at Walt Disney World's new Animal
Kingdom theme park is known as the Affection Section. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``There is something about the momentum of travel that
makes you want to just keep moving, to never stop.'' _ Bill
Bryson. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? It is the same time as in Greenwich, England.
That's known as Universal Coordinated TIme. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
