r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTEL-PRIVACY-HNS &LR;      01-26 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-PRIVACY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL OFFERS COMPROMISE ON ID CHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Stung by an uproar from privacy groups, Intel
Corp. is changing a feature on its latest microprocessors that
would automatically identify an individual computer on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But privacy advocates expressed reservations about the
modification, while the Federal Trade Commission plans to meet with
Intel representatives later this week to discuss the change.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said last week that every new Pentium III chips would
transmit a unique serial number internally and across the Internet
to help identify computer users.
</P>
<P>
   According to the company, that feature would help electronic
commerce, enabling companies and customers more security with
personal data.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Tom Waldrup said the Santa Clara, Calif.-based chip
maker would change the software that came with the chips and
controlled this identification process.
</P>
<P>
   After the change, he said, a Pentium III-equipped computer will
be set so that the identification signal broadcast is disabled. A
user will have to manually change a software program in the
computer to allow the computer to send its identifying information
over a network.
</P>
<P>
   Waldrup said the change had been made Monday in response to
privacy groups advocating the boycott of the new chips, due out
this quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made this change out of concern for the least
sophisticated user,'' Waldrup said. ``That seems to be the group
that privacy advocates are concerned about.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the advocacy groups calling for the boycott said the
change was cosmetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is their little software patch,'' said Dave Banisar,
policy director of the Washington, D.C.-based Electronic Privacy
Information Center. ``It's not really changing the technology. It
doesn't solve the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still Big Brother inside instead of `Intel Inside,''' he
said, referring to Intel's corporate slogan.
</P>
<P>
   EPIC had organized the boycott of Pentium III chips along with
Junkbusters Corp. of Green Brook, N.J., a lobbying concern.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Catlett, president of Junkbusters, was less critical of
Intel's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a big improvement,'' said Catlett, who plans on meeting
with Intel Thursday. ``I need to look at the technical details, but
if the default setting is off, then that is a considerable
improvement in their position.''
</P>
<P>
   Waldrup said the chip manufacturer had consulted with privacy
groups, including EPIC, about the new technology before it was
announced last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognized early on this would be sensitive,'' Waldrup
said. ``That's why we contacted these privacy groups under our own
initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   Banisar, though, said Intel hadn't been frank with his
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came at us with this `we've got a secret' stuff, and
didn't really tell us the details of this new technology,'' Banisar
said.
</P>
<P>
   Waldrup said the identifying technology was going to be included
in the Pentium III chips released in the next two months. The
Pentium III chip is Intel's high-end desktop microprocessor.
</P>
<P>
   Waldrup said Intel would not include the technology in its
next-generation Celeron chips, which are used in cheaper machines.
</P>
<P>
   EPIC said it planned to meet this week with the FTC to discuss
the Intel situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's a very big concern,'' said Jodie Bernstein,
director of the FTC's bureau of consumer protection. ``But we'll
have to wait and see if this will really resolve the total privacy
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein said Intel representatives would brief the agency on
the new chips Thursday, and added that the FTC would take action if
there was any indication that Intel was engaging in any ``unfair or
deceptive'' business practices.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein said she was heartened by the quick response of Intel
to the privacy concerns. ``That's usually the fastest way to
resolve these controversies,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
