A8891 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     01-26 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOGLE SOUNDS OFF ON SOCIAL SECURITY REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Bogle thinks the debate over Social Security is surely
leading to the establishment of personal accounts invested at least
partly in the stock market, and he's got no problem with that.
</P>
<P>
   His one warning: Don't let the mutual fund industry get its
hands on the money.
</P>
<P>
   Bogle, the famous skinflint senior chairman of Vanguard Group,
does not think fund managers should be running Social Security
money and wouldn't choose their companies to administer the
accounts. That includes his own Valley Forge, Pa.-based mutual fund
company.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Bogle is returning to his favorite theme: expense
control. He argues that very small accounts are more likely to get
eaten alive by the management and administration expenses typically
charged by mutual fund companies today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cost is a powerful component,'' said Bogle.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over Social Security reform is far from settled,
though most people now seem to agree that some kind of stock market
investment should be part of any plan to ensure the program has
enough money to cover the retirement of the baby boom generation.
Democrats want one pool of Social Security reserve money invested
in the market, while Republicans are pressing for individual
accounts that would let taxpayers decide how to put some of their
money to work.
</P>
<P>
   One wild card: President Clinton's new idea of a Universal
Savings Account for low- to moderate-income workers, similar to an
employer-sponsored 401(k) plan. The government would use part of
the government's projected surplus to match money saved by workers,
within limits.
</P>
<P>
   Bogle sees something like Clinton's USA account being adapted to
the Social Security debate, creating individual accounts that would
be directed by worker-taxpayers. He thinks about 1 percent of
salary contributed to Social Security by employers and another 1
percent kicked in by employees would be available for the accounts
to invest.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that makes the idea intelligent is that it's
the way our pension plans are going in this country,'' said Bogle,
referring to the growth of 401(k) defined contribution plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``A typical pension plan funded with, say, 60 percent stocks and
40 percent bonds is a perfectly intelligent option for the average
employee. But it isn't intelligent for either person at the
extremes of the (age) average. There ought to be some way to
control for that in our national retirement program,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bogle's beef with mutual funds as managers or administrators of
individual Social Security accounts boils down to fees: investment
fees, transaction fees, and administration fees.
</P>
<P>
   Those costs don't raise much of a fuss among most mutual fund
customers today, despite Bogle's best efforts. But applied to very
small accounts, they could wipe out the long-term profit advantage
investors expect as a reward for taking risk in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could easily turn out with those kinds of costs that when
someone looks back 20 years from now, the individual (stock Social
Security) accounts run by this industry will underperform the bond
market,'' Bogle said.
</P>
<P>
   His solution: strip the accounts down to their bare-bones, index
stock market investing backed by no-frills service, and individual
accounts are much more likely to deliver some real benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Who should administer the accounts? The Social Security
bureaucracy can do it, Bogle thinks. Who actually handles the nuts
and bolts of investing new money into index stocks? The government
could do that, too. Running an index fund, especially one that
doesn't have to cope with unpredictable daily cash flow changes,
isn't rocket science. If that doesn't work, contract the job out to
any investment firm and demand rock-bottom pricing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not recreating the mutual fund industry,'' he said.
``We're creating a product that if the mutual fund industry had it,
it would be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's a model that looks a lot like a government
version of Vanguard, a giant investment management firm owned by
the people who buy its funds and managed to keep their expenses
low. Vanguard has popularized investing in index funds, which
mirror the components of benchmarks such as the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 or the Russell 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Bogle thinks the entire operation could be run for as little as
10 basis points, or 0.1 percent of assets, per year. That's even
lower than the fee charged by the Vanguard 500 Index fund, which
invests in Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index stocks and charges its
investors 0.18 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 10th of a percent ought to be plenty. If you looked at all
the money (in a Social Security stock program), you would wonder
where a 10th of a percent could even go.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
