<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MITZVAH-RENEWAL-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMING OF AGE, SIMPLY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robin Rouse and her family have been to many bar and bat mitzvah
celebrations in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   There was the one with the South Pacific theme: The room was
decorated in island colors, and the guests received leis and
maracas. There was the Miami Heat basketball theme party, the
Broadway production party, and the formal New York black tie event
where, for the grand finale, waiters wheeled out a lavish Viennese
pastry table and ``everyone oohed and aahed,'' Rouse recalled.
</P>
<P>
   So, when the time came four years ago to plan her own son's bar
mitzvah, young Ryan had a question for Rouse. ``What's the theme of
my bar mitzvah going to be?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theme of your bar mitzvah,'' she told him, ``is bar
mitzvah.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, (itals)duhhhh(unitals), as a seventh grader might say.
</P>
<P>
   You might think the focus of the bar or bat mitzvah would be on
its intended purpose _ the religious coming of age of a 13-year-old
Jewish boy or girl. And for a great many families, it is. But over
the last 15 years, some of these celebrations have _ in the view of
many in the Jewish community _ gone soaring over the top, with
their black-tie dinners, costly entertainers, and ``room
transformations'' in which hotels and temples alike are made over
into rain forests or circuses.
</P>
<P>
   But change is afoot. There is a growing movement to shift the
emphasis back onto the spiritual and religious aspects of the bar
or bat mitzvah, during which boys and girls read or chant in Hebrew
from the Torah and interpret sacred texts.
</P>
<P>
   Like big corporations, like early retirees, American bar and bat
mitzvahs are beginning to downsize.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen three clear trends,'' writes Rabbi Joshua Hammerman
of Stamford, Conn., in New York-based Jewish Week magazine. ``1)
the service is becoming more central, 2) the parties more modest,
and 3) those who still insist on `doing it up' are more
self-conscious.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbis and others involved in synagogue life in Massachusetts
echo his observation: from Temple Shalom in Newton, where executive
director Bob Isaacs reports seeing ``fewer monster parties'' and
``more focus on what goes on in the sanctuary than what goes on in
the party;'' to Temple Aliyah in Needham, where Rabbi Carl Perkins
says more parents are using the event as an opportunity not just to
celebrate but to ``enrich their family's Jewish life;'' to the
North Shore, where parents from such communities as Marblehead,
Peabody, Everett, Revere, and Malden have formed a ``Mitzvah coop''
to plan and prepare each other's parties, bypassing the expense of
caterers, decorators, even photographers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The downsizers include families like Robin Rouse's of West
Newton, Mass., who with her husband, Brian Gallagher, hosted a
simple lunch in a restaurant for about 50 family members and
friends, following their son's ceremony at Temple Emanuel, a
conservative congregation in Newton. A family friend who is a DJ
entertained the kids. And in lieu of table centerpieces, the family
took the money that would have been spent on table decorations and
made donations to several charities. Each donation was made in the
name of a particular guest whom the family wanted to honor. The
entire cost of the party came in ``well under $3,000,'' Rouse say,
substantially less than the $10,000 and $15,000 parties she has
attended.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one,'' maintains Rouse, ``should be spending 10, 15, or 18
thousand dollars on a child's religious ceremony.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that she hasn't enjoyed such costly parties. On the
contrary, ``I have such a great time when I go to them. I know
people are doing them because they can'' afford to, says Rouse, a
former teacher in the Jewish community who now works as a technical
writer at Lotus Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   She adds, ``But at some point along the way, you say to
yourself, ``Are these the values we are supposed to be passing on
to our children? For me, there is too big a chasm between the
meaning of the celebration and the method of celebrating. It's such
a dissonant way to mark a child's beginning a path into
(itals)mitzvot(unitals),'' performing good, ethical deeds.
</P>
<P>
   Some celebrations reflect deeper concerns. Emily Newberg, a
ninth-grader at Belmont (Mass.) High School, has always been
interested in the Holocaust, which she considers ``more compelling
than any other subject I've studied so far.'' So she decided to use
her bat mitzvah as an opportunity to honor the sacrifices made by
victims and heroes of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   In the months leading up to her bat mitzvah at Belmont's Beth El
Temple Center, she became involved with the Jewish Foundation for
the Righteous, a New York-based organization that provides
assistance to surviving Christians who rescued Jews during the
Holocaust. She also participated in a program that twins a bar or
bat mitzvah child with a Jewish boy or girl who died in the
Holocaust before turning 13.
</P>
<P>
   There are families like the Borgenichts of Dover, Mass., for
whom throwing a big party last August for their daughter Sarita's
Bat Mitzvah was, for them, simply out of the question, even though
they could have afforded it. Instead, they hosted a quiet buffet
luncheon for family and a few friends in their temple's social
hall. ``I personally do not like and don't support taking anything
away from the experience,'' Fred Borgenicht says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such simpler celebrations are increasingly common. Why now?
</P>
<P>
   Rabbis speculate it reflects a general return among Americans to
spiritualism and simplicity. And some rabbis see an increasing
self-consciousness among Jewish parents about much-publicized
displays of excess. (One that drew front-page coverage in Boston's
Jewish Advocate involved a ``fashion cafe'' party at a country
club, featuring a Cindy Crawford supermodel look-alike greeting
guests.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
