<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CHAFEE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAFEE, `NOT A WEATHERVANE,' DEFENDS HIS STANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARWICK, R.I. _ This is Chafee territory, home to descendants of
the founding Rhode Island family, where the mayor is a Chafee and
everyone knows someone with the last name. And these days, some
people have a dilemma: Senator John H. Chafee.
</P>
<P>
   The problem isn't what he's done. After 22 years in the Senate,
Chafee is as beloved as Republicans get in this overwhelmingly
Democratic state, a model moderate who supports everything from the
environment to abortion rights. The problem, instead, is what
Chafee hasn't done about impeachment _ and what some fear he might
do next.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Chafee, 76, said he would vote to hear
witnesses in President Clinton's impeachment trial and oppose a
swift up-or-down vote to dismiss the case. Democratic leaders,
mindful of Chafee's reelection looming in 2000, seized on this
stance and began plotting his demise around it. And longtime Chafee
supporters, like Phyllis Zito, are their prime target.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's done a good job,'' said Zito, 53, a former
schoolteacher, as she settled into a booth at the Newport Creamery
in Warwick over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as this thing goes on,'' added Zito, who voted for Chafee
in all four of his Senate races, ``I see he's more concerned with
party lines than what his constituents are saying. And that bothers
me. I think that I'd have to think long and hard about whether I'd
vote for him again.''
</P>
<P>
   Such opinions are a delight to Democratic leaders in Rhode
Island, who have salivated over Chafee's Senate seat since he first
won in 1976, and have long been irritated by his ability to secure
huge portions of the liberal vote. They have sprung into action.
Last week, Representative Patrick J. Kennedy took to the airwaves
with a string of blistering attacks, accusing Chafee of ``getting
rolled'' by conservatives. The People for the American Way also
launched a series of radio ads in Providence geared toward getting
voters to ask their senators to end the impeachment trial _ a
tactic clearly aimed at Chafee, since the other Rhode Island
senator, Jack Reed, is a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Bill Lynch, the state chairman of the
Democratic Party, all but announced his candidacy for Chafee's
seat, saying the senator's inaction would undoubtedly star in any
future campaign. Last Friday, the Providence branch of the NAACP
said it sent Chafee a letter pleading with him to alter his
position, and its president, Clifford R. Montiero, later said
campaign support would be contingent on what Chafee does next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I led Democrats for Governor Chafee in 1962. I would lead
Democrats against Senator Chafee in 2000 if he feels it is
important to crucify one of the greatest presidents this country
has ever had in terms of civil rights,'' Montiero said.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee defends his position tirelessly and unapologetically,
explaining to constituents that in impeachment, as in policy
making, he is an independent thinker, ``not a weathervane''
twisting in the winds of public opinion polls. If he votes for a
limited number of witnesses, as is expected, it is because he
believes witnesses are appropriate; if he votes against a motion to
dismiss the case, it is out of respect for the Constitution, not
the Republican Party's right wing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Rhode Island have always supported me in a very
generous fashion,'' Chafee said in an interview. ``They've said,
`We have confidence in you. You go down there and do what you think
is best.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Chafee has survived a number of unpopular policy moves in which
he voted against the state's Democratic grain, including supporting
Clarence Thomas's nomination to the Supreme Court. After the
upheaval over the Thomas hearings, Chafee bucked a liberal tidal
wave and cast an almost-deciding ballot: Thomas was confirmed by
just 52 to 48.
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton's impeachment trial, Chafee again is part of a
crucial bloc of swing votes, joining three other Republicans from
New England _ Senators Olympia Snowe and Susan M. Collins of Maine
and Senator James M. Jeffords of Vermont. All four are moderates,
and together they could help decide key questions, such as whether
to call witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   But Chafee shares a dilemma with a larger swath of his party:
the 12 other Republicans who are facing reelection in 2000 and must
at least wonder what effect their stand on impeachment will have on
voters in their home states.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them _ such as Senator Slade Gorton of Washington, where
65 percent of people polled oppose impeachment _ have made a
concerted effort to appear bipartisan during the trial. Others,
such as Pennsylvania Senator Rick Santorum, whose state opposed
impeachment by 63 percent, have toned down hard-core conservative
rhetoric that once brought them recognition.
</P>
<P>
   But Chafee has not changed his tune, not even after polls last
November showed a full 74 percent of people in Rhode Island wanted
to see the impeachment process end. Nor does he plan to.
</P>
<P>
   ``You listen to what your constituents' views are, you read the
letters, you read the e-mail, but in the final analysis, you have
to do what you believe is right,'' he said. ``I'm not going to
respond to polls _ 62 percent this way, 38 percent that way.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Democrats, he said: ``I've no problem if they want to
use this as an issue. Go to it. I've been perfectly happy to defend
any position.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, there is little for Chafee to defend. He has not
announced whether he will vote to convict Clinton. For some in
Warwick, whatever Chafee does will be fine. Alice Dunne, 81, a
Democrat from Warwick, said she would vote for him again _
especially because she believed Chafee would eventually ``try to
lead the way'' to end the impeachment trial. Dale Davenport, 53, a
Democrat from East Providence, agreed, saying Chafee's role in
impeachment is ``not going to influence what he does for Rhode
Island.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at what the president did _ he's still running the
country,'' Davenport said. Chafee ``can still work for us.''
</P>
<P>
   But for others, questions remained, and some said Chafee's
actions might well influence their vote in 2000. Tania Aguiar, 20,
who works at a mortgage company in Warwick, said ``it would be a
big deal'' for her if Chafee voted to oust Clinton. Sandra Andraee,
22, a sourcing analyst at Fleet, said, ``It should not be about
what he thinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Andraee said senators should consider the public's view, not
just their own. ``If they're not going to represent the people,
they shouldn't be in office,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But, she acknowledged, Chafee ``probably would get reelected
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very well known. He's an institution,'' she said. ``I
don't think the older people would let him go.''
</P>
<P>
   Darrell West, a political science professor at Brown University,
said the poll numbers support the claim that ``Chafee has a strong
reservoir of public support.'' In June 1997, Chafee's job approval
rating was 50 percent; by September 1998, it had shot up to 63
percent, according to West, who regularly polls Rhode Island
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a lot of personal credibility with Rhode Island
voters,'' West said. ``But the $64,000 question is whether this
time is going to be different, because this vote is far more
high-profile than anything he's done in the past. History may not
be the best guide.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
