<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8900 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SAMARANCH-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     01-26 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SAMARANCH-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 LAUSANNE, SWITZERLAND: ... he says.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The suites and the limousines and the baby grands are not
provided for Samaranch, his lieutenants say. They are provided for
the IOC president, who has achieved nearly papal status as the
Olympics have become universal in their reach.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch may have collected more plaques, medals, honorary
degrees, and Order of the Whatevers than any other man on earth. He
receives so many ex officio gifts that the IOC puts most of them in
the Olympic museum or in storage.
</P>
<P>
   When it was revealed recently that Salt Lake City had given him
a shotgun and a rifle worth nearly 10 times the IOC's gift limit,
his staffers made a point of unveiling ``The Samaranch Collection''
_ a global rummage basement stuffed with Dutch stamps, oil
portraits, statuettes, dolls, trays, and other commemorative
bric-a-brac that they say the president doesn't want but couldn't
refuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I receive hundreds of gifts,'' Samaranch says. ``I am also
giving gifts. That is the protocol of a normal visit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not that the president couldn't afford a Browning Gold
semiautomatic shotgun (about $475 retail) if he wanted one.
Samaranch grew up in a wealthy textile family and added to his
fortune by speculating in beachfront real estate and joining
corporate boards. (He is still a director of Spain's largest bank.)
</P>
<P>
   Though he developed a reputation as a youthful playboy,
Samaranch was both ambitious and shrewd, a political realist with
his finger always in the wind, a gifted adapter and survivor whom a
Catalan magazine once dubbed a ``clever chameleon.''
</P>
<P>
   He became a Franco loyalist, joining the Movimiento, wearing the
blue fascist shirt and saluting with upraised arm. Samaranch ended
up not only as Catalan regional councilor but Franco's sports
minister, which landed him a place on the IOC in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Though he had been a middling athlete (a featherweight boxer who
fought as ``Kid Samaranch'' and a roller hockey goalie),
Samaranch's obvious talent was for inside diplomacy. He quickly
became the IOC's head of protocol, made the powerful executive
board, and became a vice president in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   When Franco died three years later and Samaranch realized his
political and social life in Spain was finished, he asked to be
ambassador to the Soviet Union. Though Austria had been offered,
Vienna was not hosting the next Olympics, Samaranch understood.
Moscow was.
</P>
<P>
   When the Spanish government decided to join the US-led boycott
of the 1980 Games after the Afghanistan invasion, Samaranch
persuaded its Olympic committee to send a team anyway. And when
Lord Killanin decided not to stand for reelection that summer,
Samaranch ended up as president.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly set about revolutionizing the Olympic movement, which
was reeling after consecutive boycotts, bereft of host cities for
the Games and still stuck in founder Baron Pierre de Coubertin's
19th-century ideal of amateur sport as practiced by the English
upper classes.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch named women to the IOC's all-male club (there were a
dozen before Finland's Pirjo Haeggman resigned last week). He
broadened its Eurocentricity by nominating new members from Africa,
Asia, and Latin America, which now make up half of the committee.
He had the word ``amateur'' removed from the Olympic charter and
pushed to let professionals compete. And he created a marketing
machine with Horst Dassler, the Adidas sporting goods magnate that
has poured billions into the IOC coffers, more than 90 percent of
which has been passed on to international sports federations and
national Olympic committees.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1984 boycott of Los Angeles, Samaranch set about
drawing the Soviet bloc back into the fold by giving dictators such
as Romania's Nicolae Ceaucescu, East Germany's Erich Honecker, and
Bulgaria's Todor Zhivkov the IOC's highest honor: the golden
Olympic Order. The past three Olympiads have featured virtually
full attendance, with every country sending six athletes and two
officials to each Games at IOC expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``These 18 years have not been only the black days we are having
today, no?'' Samaranch mused Monday. ``We have also had very bright
days.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was the bright days, ironically, that spawned the black days.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sense, with certain footnotes and asterisks, Samaranch
has fulfilled the mandate and dream of Coubertin _ to make the
Games truly universal,'' says John Lucas, a Penn State professor
emeritus and Olympic historian. ``But at a great price.''
</P>
<P>
   The bigger and richer and more popular the Olympics became, the
more cities craved them _ and the more the IOC members found
themselves being offered, and sometimes asking for, cash and gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are able to meet people who are eager to do anything to
seduce you,'' IOC director general Francois Carrard says. ``A small
gesture becomes a big gesture. That is where the temptations begin.
Some members were not able to resist as they should have.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch was profoundly embarrassed that some of his colleagues
would betray their oath for cash and cosmetic surgery, for tuition
and jobs for their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very much surprised and disappointed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he realizes that the ongoing investigation into other bid
cities from other years, six Games in all, may lead to other
expulsions in March and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will keep cleaning,'' Samaranch vows.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake scandal has not soiled him personally, though if
his colleagues ask him to step down he will step down, Samaranch
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my duty now is to try to solve the problem and leave the
Olympic movement as strong as possible to the next president,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
