<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8901 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-CRACKDOWN-0127-     01-26 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CRACKDOWN-0127-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHINESE RESUME DISSIDENT CRACKDOWN, ACCUSE POLITICAL MAVERICK OF
SEEING PROSTITUTES
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ After nearly a month's lull, Chinese security
authorities have resumed their aggressive crackdown on maverick
thinkers, this time hauling in a Beijing factory
manager-turned-intellectual for allegedly consorting with
prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   Peng Ming, the irreverent founder of a discussion group called
China Development Union, was seized Monday by 10 policemen at the
Dayun Night Club on Beijing's southern outskirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a frame-up,'' protested Nie Ying, his wife and mother
of his two children. In a telephone interview, she said Tuesday
that an officer at the Tongzhou police station near the nightclub
had informed her that Peng had been ``subpoenaed for prosecution''
on sex-related charges.
</P>
<P>
   She said that at 11 p.m. Monday, police burst into a private
dining room where Peng and a male friend had been enjoying a
multi-course Chinese dinner. Later, when her husband failed to
return home, she tried to call him on his beeper. When he failed to
answer, she realized he was no longer ``at liberty'' and began
trying to find him, she said.
</P>
<P>
   By late Tuesday, Peng's wife and friends did not know where he
was. District police officials told inquiring reporters that they
had no information on Peng.
</P>
<P>
   Peng's case followed the pattern of four other political
dissidents whose opposition activities were cut short in the last
two months by morals charges that they also claimed were trumped
up.
</P>
<P>
   China Democracy Party activist Han Lifa, who tried to organize a
demonstration in Shanghai during President Clinton's visit to China
last summer, fell into a similar predicament when he went out
drinking with friends in Shanghai last Oct. 23.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, he awoke in police custody facing charges of
patronizing a prostitute, Han said later. In December, Shanghai
authorities sentenced Han to nine months of detention on
prostitution charges.
</P>
<P>
   Sentenced with Han was fellow Democracy Party activist Cai
Guihua, who contended that he was arrested on Oct. 30 while he was
dining with a business partner in a Shanghai hotel. Suddenly, he
said, two women entered the room and disrobed. Police immediately
burst in and arrested him.
</P>
<P>
   In another episode, the Chinese Foreign ministry acknowledged in
late December that two New York-based democracy campaigners who had
slipped back into southern China illegally were sentenced to three
years forced labor. They were charged not just with evading border
police but also with hiring prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   The two men, Zhang Lin and Wei Quanbao, both veterans of the
1989 Tiananmen Square uprising, were arrested Nov. 12 in a barber
shop that authorities insisted was a brothel.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Since Peng, the latest detainee, emerged from obscurity less
than a year ago, he has always claimed he is not a ``dissident''
since he isn't trying to form an opposition political party.
Instead, he said, he has just been tossing out reform ideas for
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Peng attracted Western media attention last summer when he began
holding weekly discussion sessions in Beijing on such topics as
human rights, democracy and environmental degradation. But last
fall, he told Western reporters he was curtailing his activities
``until things loosened up again.''
</P>
<P>
   His decision last October to suspend the activities of the China
Development Union was prompted by a raid on his home, in which
police confiscated fax machines, computer equipment and some files
on his tiny organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that's interesting about the new case against Peng
is that he has not been very active at all for the last few
months,'' said Liu Si Qing, director of the Hong Kong-based
Information Center of Human Rights and Democratic Movement in
China.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Chinese security agents have adopted
divide-and-rule tactics to keep the handful of dissidents still in
China off balance.
</P>
<P>
   While targeting some lesser-ranking protesters with tawdry sex
accusations, the government crashed down much harder late last
month on the three main leaders of the incipient China Democracy
Party. Chinese courts sent Xu Wenli, Qin Yongmin and Wang Youcai to
prison for at least 11 years each for such crimes as ``attempting
to overthrow state power.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came a pause in the pace of new prosecutions lasting almost
a month.
</P>
<P>
   The round-up resumed last week when a court in Shanghai imposed
a lighter sentence on cyberspace dissident Lin Hai, a 30-year-old
web page designer who was convicted of exchanging e-mail addresses
with a dissident group based in the United States. Lin got two
years.
</P>
<P>
   The scattered episodes of sex-related charges coincide with a
renewed campaign by Chinese authorities to stamp out prostitution,
which was virtually eliminated in the 1960s during the moralistic
days of Communist Party fanaticism. Since economic liberalization
began in 1979, small-scale prostitution has crept back into urban
life, coinciding with the spread of factory layoffs and the growing
gap between wealthy and impoverished Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, according to state media, a Chinese court
sentenced a 41-year-old woman to be executed for running a
prostitution ring while using a sauna and restaurant as a front.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
