<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZENGA HAS A ZEST FOR THE TASK AT HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ There is a great deal of evidence supporting
the observation that Walter Zenga has a winning touch. But Zenga
denies it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a winning touch, I have a hunger to win,'' Zenga
said Monday. ``There is a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga, 39, has returned to the Revolution as player-coach. He
seems rejuvenated, prepared for the challenge of elevating a team
that has the MLS' worst record after three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   There will be few roster changes and no major stars are expected
to be added, including Giuseppe Bergomi, who had been rumored to be
a Revolution candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' Zenga said of his former teammate at
Internazionale.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a different mentality within the team, though.
Zenga brings not only a desire to succeed, but also a great deal of
credibility. The trick will be for Zenga to translate his success
as a player to that of a player-coach.
</P>
<P>
   Two veteran defenders _ Brian Bliss and Dan Calichman _ should
help stabilize the Revolution defense. Ze Rodrigues, Giovanni
Savarese, and possibly Sierra Leone's Unisa Conteh could change the
offensive dynamic.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution also will be without the league's leading
scorer, Raul Diaz Arce, lost to San Jose in a trade. Missing from
training camp will be captain Mike Burns, who is on trial with
Hearts in Scotland; midfielder Shawn Medved, who is in a contract
dispute; Imad Baba, Jamar Beasley, and Joe-Max Moore (with national
teams); goalkeeper Ian Feuer, who is on loan to Rushden and
Diamonds in England; and Jeff Causey, Edwin Gorter, and Carlos
Rocha, who are also training in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga's task will be to tie this project together, setting the
tone from the first day of training, which will start indoors, then
move to Italy's Tirennian Coast, in preparation for the season
opener at Miami March 28.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Zenga displayed an alchemist's touch in transforming
a team that had split into cliques and had sunk to the bottom of
the league under Thomas Rongen. The Revolution surrendered two
quick goals to Miami in the first half of Zenga's first game as
coach, then quickly galvanized and set team defensive records with
three successive shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   In the 29 games Zenga has participated in as coach or player,
the Revolution have a 14-11-4 record and a 45-37 goal differential.
Without Zenga, the Revolution are 15-44-8 and have been outscored,
138-91.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures indicate that the Revolution also are hungry for
victories. But, so far, they have been unable to devise how to
acquire them.
</P>
<P>
   For Zenga, the formula for success is simple. You start by
organizing the defense, something that rarely has been emphasized
with the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean the Revolution will be playing for 0-0 ties,
a endgame that has been legislated out of fashion even in Italy by
FIFA's 3-points-for-a-win edict. They will, however, be playing by
the philosophy that if the other team doesn't score, you can't
lose. There is a difference, and Zenga hopes to transmit this to
the Revolution in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a place where soccer is No. 1 in the thoughts of the
people,'' Zenga said. ``You will not lose by going there to train.
We will train against Italian teams and when we return we will be
ready to play in MLS.''
</P>
<P>
   Several professional teams are based near Forte dei Marmi, the
Revolution's Tuscan base. Zenga has the connections not only to
secure accommodations and facilities at cut rates, but also to set
up exhibitions against top clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Revolution supporters likely would settle for a few rays of hope
after a dismal '98, when the team was eliminated from playoff
contention with a month left in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am always optimistic, in everything I do,'' Zenga said. ``I
want to give entertainment to the people who come to the stadium.
They appreciated what we did in the last six games last year. What
we did in the last part of the season was positive.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cap flap
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The MLS' salary cap is causing players to seek better offers
elsewhere, and some are succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   Former US national team captain John Harkes will leave D.C.
United for a three-month loan to Nottingham Forest in England's
Premier League. United already lost Tony Sanneh to Hertha Berlin
and Tampa Bay lost Frankie Hejduk to Bayer Leverkusen, both on
long-term contracts. San Jose's Eric Wynalda is on loan to Leon in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Burns and Feuer seem intent on leaving the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league has said take it or leave it,'' said Burns's agent,
Craig Sheron. ``For Mike Burns to walk away, (the offer) has to be
bad. Mike is not asking for a lot. He could ask for the maximum and
he is not asking for that. He is willing to play for New England
for a lot less money than he would earn overseas. He would love to
stay in New England, it's far and away his first choice. But he's
28, and this is possibly his last long-term contract, and he is not
prepared to accept what MLS is offering.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns has 76 national team appearances. He was among the first
to sign with the MLS in 1995, at a base pay of about $80,000. The
league has offered a 10 percent raise. Burns is requesting about
$150,000 in base pay, according to a source.
</P>
<P>
   Sheron believes the MLS is risking too much by allowing US
players to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league is dismantling its most credible asset,'' Sheron
said. ``They are being overly preoccupied with the bottom line on a
short-term basis. It's a given that they are not going to get the
big-name overseas players, and they need to invest in domestic
players and keep them. If they don't develop from within, keep the
Mike Burnses and Tony Sannehs, they are going to end up with a
bunch of no-names and people are not going to watch them.''
</P>
<P>
   The next to go could be last season's leading scorer, Stern John
of Columbus, who has an offer from Bayer Leverkusen.
</P>
<P>
   The MLS is taking steps to retain young talent by expanding its
Project 40 program to include foreigners. Candidates include South
African Stephen Armstrong of Butler University, Ukrainian Demo
Kovalenko of Indiana, Brazilian Maurizio Rocha of Connecticut, and
Ghanaian Duke Shamo of St. Francis. Armstrong, a striker, is
polished enough to bypass Project 40, which provides educational
funds and does not occupy a roster spot. One MLS team expressed
interest in selecting Armstrong as its fourth foreign player,
outside of Project 40 considerations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
