<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8904 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-26 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF LT GETS INTO HALL, HE WON'T BE SORRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (itals)``The only criteria for election to the Pro Football Hall
of Fame is a nominee's achievements and contributions as a player,
coach or contributor in professional football.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   _ Pro Football Hall of Fame bylaws, Section 3, Item C &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI _ To become a member of the Pro Football Hall of Fame,
Lawrence Taylor needs 29 out of 36 voters to interpret Section 3,
Item C literally.
</P>
<P>
   That might not happen.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was, and, is, a rogue. He did what he did and he does
what he does and he is eternally unrepentant. His laundry list of
drug offenses, tax problems, and transgressions such as leaving the
scene of an accident are not supposed to have anything to do with
his qualifications for the Hall of Fame, but they do. If only LT
would say what some people want to hear, he probably would be a
unanimous choice when the committee convenes Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He won't do it, and that's why he's LT. There will be no mea
culpas. ``I don't apologize for anything,'' he said via conference
call Monday. ``I live my life the way I live my life.'' He wants
people to understand that part of the reason he was such a
phenomenal player is that he had no inhibitions, on or off the
field. He is daring voters to take the whole package, rap sheet and
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the bylaws,'' he said, ``it should be a no-brainer.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on his talent, it may be the ultra no-brainer of all-time.
More than a few reputable people believe he was the greatest
defensive player ever, at any position. At the very least, he
redefined linebacking. On the basis of athletic merit, the Pro
Football Hall of Fame may never have been presented with a more
obvious candidate for enshrinement.
</P>
<P>
   But the sticky issue of the ``other'' Lawrence Taylor bothers
some people. Some people are morally troubled by the idea of his
bust being on display in Canton, Ohio, where grandmothers and kids
can see it. When they think of LT, they think of rehabs and drug
busts and ``You-have-the-right-to-remain-silents'' as much as they
do of quarterback sacks.
</P>
<P>
   And they are troubled by that, bylaws or no bylaws.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have a hard time with it,'' acknowledged voter Steve
Schoenfeld of the Arizona Republic, who says he is leaning toward a
no vote but has not made up his mind. ``This is a guy who talked
about rehabbing on the golf course. That's hard to take.''
</P>
<P>
   To which LT has a three-word (implied) reply: ``Get a life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to start going by off-the-field stuff, you
might have to kick out half the people in that Hall of Fame right
now,'' he sneered.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if everything is in the past tense with Taylor,
either. He's got a major legal situation pending. Sometimes it
seems he always does. If they put him in the Hall, who's to say he
won't do something to embarrass the place in the next couple of
years? Then again, O.J. has been in the Hall a long time, as I'm
sure LT would gladly point out.
</P>
<P>
   So what does all this mean to a guy like LT, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important, simply because it's a reward for the years you
put into the league,'' he conceded. ``It's the finest reward you
can get in football. It doesn't take much to make me happy, but I
have family and friends who would like to see me get in, and I
would like it to happen for them.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those friends is Bill Parcells. Throughout Taylor's
endless run-ins with the law and his long history of antisocial
behavior, The Tuna has remained completely loyal to his old
quarterback killer. Now here's a guy with a family who certainly
knows right from wrong. I've often wondered how Parcells could
defend such a recidivist slug. Last week I found out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will always stand by Lawrence Taylor,'' The Tuna said in a
TV interview. ``He made me what I am today.''
</P>
<P>
   That tells you all you need to know about LT the player, that a
coach not exactly known for his humility says a thing like that.
But talent is not the issue.
</P>
<P>
   No, the issue is that LT is a guy who always has bent the rules
and who, in his early 40s, really doesn't sound as if he's learned
anything. Americans are the most forgiving people on earth. All
anyone has to do is ask.
</P>
<P>
   LT won't ask us for anything, certainly not from mere
sportswriters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only one I have to answer to is God almighty,'' he
declared. ``I live my life the way I live my life. Yes, I have some
problems, but who doesn't?''
</P>
<P>
   He actually said all this in a reasonably good-natured way.
Asked, for example, if he felt a kinship with Bill Clinton, he
said, ``I can't see what the hoopla is all about. So he had a
run-in? Come on.''
</P>
<P>
   Understand that Taylor is not lobbying for the Hall. We asked
him to take time out from his acting duties (he's appearing in an
Oliver Stone movie, ``On Any Given Sunday,'' being shot in South
Florida), not the other way around. He knows he belongs in the Hall
of Fame on merit. He has no control over the process. Whatever
happens, happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't be sitting around by the phone,'' he asserted. ``And
if you're going to ask me to be remorseful for what I've done, I
can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nope. He's LT, and we can agree on one thing for sure: The man
is consistent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
