<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALCONS DEFENSE NO LONGER OFFENSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ So much is new about these Atlanta Falcons. Consider
this insight from Chuck Smith, a defensive lineman and most
articulate student of football: One of the main reasons the
Falcons' defense was for so long buried in the bilge of the NFL
cellar was the team's offense.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmmm. The defense was bad because of the offense? This
demanded some elaboration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough, just tough to go out there for practice because
we were so bad,'' said Smith, who grew in nearby Athens, Ga.
``Everybody wants to win in this league and we were losing. And it
was even tougher to understand because Georgia is a football state
_ we're down South and this is football country. I remember growing
up and before we'd get on the school bus in the morning, we'd be
playing football, everybody, even the girls.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Falcons were virtually ignored in Georgia, because they
were bad, and not bad in the good sense. They were very bad,
especially the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd go to the stadium on game day and you knew, on the
defense, that you didn't have a chance going into the game,'' Smith
went on.
</P>
<P>
   Smith searched his mind for explanations; heck, he thought,
Deion Sanders was playing corner, and he was the best corner in
football. Jessie Tuggle was at middle linebacker ``and what's
Jessie been?,'' asked Smith. ``An All-Pro five times and an
alternate four other years? Jessie'd be in the Hall of Fame already
if he'd been playing on a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   And still the Falcons defense was putrid.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a reason why we were playing such bad defense; we
were setting records we were so bad,'' Smith elaborated. ``It all
starts at the top; guys wanted to do well but they couldn't because
of certain reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   A major reason, Smith concluded, ``was because of the
run-and-shoot offense we had, and that's all we ever practiced
against on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The run-and-shoot was the offense of head coach June Jones, and
the offense was flashy and flamboyant and exciting and many things;
but, of course, the run-and-shoot has many receivers but no tight
ends. And, alas for the Atlanta defense, the opposing teams on
Sunday almost always lined up with a tight end or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to understand, I played all those years in the
league and I never even practiced against a tight end,'' said
Smith. ``That's why the Falcons were last in run defense. That's
why you play bad defense and you can't stop the run. No one else
puts five receivers out there. I mean, you might get it once in a
while in a game but we got it all the time in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Smith was wound up. He is an NFL history buff and has a vast
video library of the best pass rushers of all time, from Reggie
White and Lawrence Taylor and Bruce Smith and back to Wilber
Marshall and Carl Eller and even Dick Butkus. The defense Smith was
playing was not the defense he'd seen on all those tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember one year _ I'm sure none of you guys remember any
history about Atlanta because nobody cared then _ but I remember
one year we had seven (defensive) guys pull hamstrings in camp,''
said Smith. ``I mean, they've got 15 receivers there on the offense
and we only only have six or seven defensive linemen and we're
rushing every down. Those receivers are out there running a
thousand go-routes in practice but that didn't help me. Every day,
it seemed, there'd be a thousand pass rushes in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Smith could take no more. In the last week of the 1996
season, when the Falcons were 3-12, Smith told the Atlanta media
the team needed ``a defensive-minded man'' to lead them and the
team could not exist on ``gimmicks,'' such as the run-and-shoot.
Too much time already had been wasted, too much talent wasted, too,
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones promptly suspended Smith for Atlanta's last game of the
1996 season. Soon thereafter, Jones was fired and replaced by Dan
Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said then we needed a defensive-minded coach to come in here
and until that happened, we'd be losers,'' Smith went on. ``And I
believe that now, because you look at the two teams in this Super
Bowl and they both play defense.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Smith made pains to point out, ``I never said June Jones
should be fired. That was already in the books. That had nothing to
do with me.''
</P>
<P>
   So Smith met with team president Taylor Smith ``and we worked it
out.'' And when Reeves arrived in Atlanta, there were no whispers
or grudges or ``any reason for him to hold anything against me
since he didn't know me and I didn't know him. He just wanted
players out there who'd play.''
</P>
<P>
   And, it must be noted, the Falcons would not be in this Super
Bowl if it weren't for Chuck Smith. Minnesota was leading the
Falcons, 20-7, just before halftime in the NFC title game and the
Vikings again were moving when Smith made a move that freed him to
strip the ball from quarterback Randall Cunningham. Atlanta
recovered, Atlanta scored, and the game no longer was over.
</P>
<P>
   And the record should note that Smith made his move to the
outside of the Vikings left tackle and to the inside of _ you
guessed it _ the tight end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who knows anything about football,'' said Smith,
``knows defense wins championships.''
</P>
</TEXT>
