<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOWL-PROPLAYER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE-KNOWN FIRM HOPES SUPER BOWL WILL BRING IT FAME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUDSON, N.H. _ Pro Player, Inc., the sports clothing company, is
stuck at the rear of a nondescript industrial park here, off the
road to Nashua.
</P>
<P>
   But, on Sunday, in a broadcast that about one-out-of-two
Americans will watch, the name Pro Player will be featured
prominently, as Fox Broadcasting televises the Super Bowl from Pro
Player Stadium in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   If the past is any guide, Pat Summerall, the venerable
play-by-play announcer, and his colleague, John Madden, are likely
to say the words ``Pro Player Stadium'' at least a few times to an
audience that advertising executives project at about 130 million
viewers. In fact, Fox and its broadcast team have already come
through big for Pro Player, featuring the company's name
prominently last Sunday when Madden announced his annual
``All-Madden Team.''
</P>
<P>
   A mere mention may not be quite the same marketing tool as a
30-second commercial. But while advertising executives say
companies are shelling out $1.6 million for 30-second spots during
the Super Bowl, Pro Player's notices during the broadcast come
entirely from its naming rights deal.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Pro Player, Inc. _ formed from the remnants of
three small, largely unknown firms in 1994 _ say that sort of name
recognition is priceless. Marketing experts say that the 10-year,
$20 million agreement with the stadium owner, H. Wayne Huizenga,
which was struck almost by coincidence in 1995, has proven to be
among the most valuable naming-rights deals in American sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of think of ourselves, this little New England company
up here in New Hampshire, as that Little Mouse That Roared,'' said
Doug Kelly, president and chief operating officer of Pro Player,
Inc. ``And the stadium deal has been a big part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the fact that a company that is not well known was
looking for some recognition, and the fact that there has already
been a World Series there, and now you have the Super Bowl coming
up with all of that marketing power, word around the business is
that it was one of the best stadium-naming deals,'' said Greg Abel,
of Advantage International, the Virginia firm which is a world
power in sports marketing and management.
</P>
<P>
   Pro Player, Inc., a small subsidiary of the apparel giant Fruit
of the Loom, has evolved in five years from a screenprinted T-shirt
and fiber-fill jacket company to the second-largest producer of
licensed sportswear in the country, with sales of about $218
million, according to Sporting Goods Business and other analysts.
It trails only the industry kingpin, Starter, Corp., of New Haven,
Conn. with $300 million in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   In a business battered by a changing sense of fashion, Pro
Player has managed single-digit growth in sales in recent years
while many of its competitors struggle to maintain pace, according
to industry analysts and company officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people in the licensing business have kind of been
crying the blues,'' Kelly said during an interview as he sat in his
office amid an exurban design and manufacturing complex that feels
worlds away from the mega-media spotlight of the NFL's showcase
game. ``We're excited here about what we think are some great
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   In the space of 10 months beginning in late 1993, Fruit of the
Loom, acquired two small T-shirt screen printing companies, Salem
Sportswear and Artex, and the licensed outerwear company Pro
Player. It also hired Kelly away from Easton Corp., a California
manufacturer of aluminum bats and hockey sticks, where he was
president and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to develop a business plan to present to Fruit of the
Loom and their board of directors basically in a two-week time
frame,'' said the 45-year-old Kelly. ``I basically came up with a
plan that said we should put the majority of our dollars behind the
Pro Player brand, consolidating the operations in all of the
different labels they had in Salem, Artex and the old Pro Player.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advertising and the marketing dollars just don't spread,''
he said. ``We weren't going to get anywhere near the exposure we
were going to need to develop any one of the brands.''
</P>
<P>
   After Kelly's plan was in place, he and a group of Pro Player
vice presidents devised a strategy to grow the new company. Two
early thoughts were: striking a marketing deal with Jimmy Johnson,
a rising star among coaching ranks in the NFL; and another deal
with one of the more independent-minded owners in the league. With
Pro Player doing about 40 percent of its annual sales with NFL
products, the strategies appeared to make sense.
</P>
<P>
   Miami made sense, too, Kelly said, because if you cannot tap
into Manhattan or Los Angeles's influence on fashion _ in a world
looking away from the traditional sports look _ identifying with
South Beach is almost as good.
</P>
<P>
   Leveraging some of the contacts of an 800-pound gorilla, Fruit
of the Loom, Kelly soon found himself talking with Huizenga's
organization about a sponsorship deal, or maybe a deal with
Johnson, or with one of the coaches of Huizenga's other
Florida-based teams, the Marlins of Major League Baseball or the
Panthers of the National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the dialogue went on,'' Kelly recalled, ``the title
situation came up. American Airlines had approached them about
renaming Joe Robbie Stadium, and one of Huizenga's guys asked me if
Fruit of the Loom would be interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them no,'' Kelly chuckled, face still flushed at the
unexpected good fortune. ``I told them that we would be interested,
as Pro Player.''
</P>
<P>
   Pro Player's deal with Huizenga is at the high end of the range
of naming-rights deals struck in the mid-1990s according to
marketing sources who track the accords.
</P>
<P>
   ``These naming-rights deals can be tricky,'' said Dennis P.
Wilson, a sport economist at the University of Massachusetts,
Amherst. ``It's called the Winner's Curse. Just because you win the
auction doesn't mean you won _ you might have overpaid.''
</P>
<P>
   But those who have evaluated the deal point out that Pro Player
Stadium offers the exposure of both Major League Baseball and the
NFL, as well as a top flight college bowl game _ the Federal
Express Orange Bowl _ every other year.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins played in a World Series in 1997. The Super Bowl is
there this year. In 2002, the National Championship Game in college
football will be played at Pro Player Stadium. Even considering
that the Marlins luck has changed dramatically, with Huizenga
selling off key players and then the team to a new owner, John
Henry, observers say Pro Player is well ahead of the curve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you have somebody like Pro Player, a company that
almost no one could recognize . . . it obviously makes sense to use
some of the marketing budget to buy name recognition,'' said Rick
Burton, of the Warsaw Sports Marketing Center at the University of
Oregon in Eugene. ``They're getting some exposure every time
somebody says, `Live from Pro Player Stadium.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The $2 million annual fee represents about 17 percent of Kelly's
annual advertising budget. He says he spends much of his time
leveraging the stadium exposure _ using the stadium and the Super
Bowl as a backdrop for a current series of ads in Sports
Illustrated and ESPN The Magazine, inviting major accounts down to
the stadium for games and using the Dolphins' cheerleaders to model
a new season's line of clothes at a fashion show in the Dolphin's
locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to use a lot of the rest of the advertising
budget to tell people that we're not just a stadium _ we're an
apparel company,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   The naming-rights deal has paid measureable dividends, he said.
Shortly after the name first appeared on the stadium in Miami,
company research showed that name awareness increased 7 percent, he
said. After the World Series, it was up by 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have the Super Bowl,'' Kelly said, grinning a victor's
grin. ``We are hoping that after it the improvement of our brand
awareness is going to be up by something closer to the mid 30s or
40s.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
