   &UR; WHEELS: FORD RANGER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Its brash big brother, the F-150, may get the hype and media
attention, but the Ford Ranger pickup quietly continues to stretch
its utility with a four-door option that's definitely on the
cutting edge.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AT A GLANCE: A look at the Ford Ranger.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: THE MECHANIC: As automotive electrical systems become more
complex and computer-dependent, the once relatively simple role of
the battery takes on a whole new dimension. While this unobtrusive
component of the vehicle's electrical network has remained
basically unchanged since its debut, it has earned the dubious
position of being the most overlooked component under the hood.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY: AFRICAN-AMERICAN WEB SURFERS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The African-American Web surfer belongs to one of the
fastest-growing user groups on the Internet. By 2003, it's expected
that more than 14 million African-Americans will be on-line.
Blackfamilies.com, which launched Jan. 18, Martin Luther King Day,
is the newest Web site hoping to tap into this growing user group.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRENDS: Many alternative and mainstream cartoonists are
finding that the Web is a valuable tool for publishing and
promoting their work.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECH BRIEFS: Surfing the Web is getting to be a little
like living in a glass house_ much of what you do goes noticed.
Those who run Web sites use things called ``cookies'' and
``referrers'' to see what we search for, but a software product
from a Cambridge, Mass., company blocks cookies for you, without
limiting your access to different Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECH TOOLS: Computer programs and Web sites will provide
you with the correct date and time in any city, as well as the
longitude and latitude in case you are navigating.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECHNOBUDDY: Don't pay retail for a computer if you can
help it. First, identify the specifications for the machine you
want to buy. Then go shopping.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOKS: ``ELEGY FOR IRIS'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The well is dry, the brain atrophied. Iris Murdoch, the last of
the great 20th-century British writers, has Alzheimer's. And yet,
in ``Elegy for Iris,'' a beautifully rendered portrait by her
husband, John Bayley, we are allowed to glimpse the private
sanctuary of the artist's once vital mind. We get to peer through
the opaque windows of a marriage that wouldn't seem nearly so
remarkable had it not spawned such a monumental body of work: 26
novels that have the Protean grandeur, the intellectual richness,
the lyrical luster of Shakespeare or Proust.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: In ``American Beach,'' author Russ Rymer is too
intent on academically documenting the disintegration of
African-American businesses to let his characters take charge.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: ``Angels Flight'' may be author Michael Connelly's
darkest novel yet.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS: The biographer, like any artist, must
possess the intuition and moral imagination to breathe life into
his subject.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In dental chairs, doctors' offices and surgical wards, more
medical professionals are harnessing the power of light and lasers
to diagnose and treat everything from cancer to cavities.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: FOLIC ACID: Women should consume at least 400 micrograms
of folic acid daily. But most women get only half of that amount,
say health specialists.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEALTH BRIEFS: After years of holding steady, HIV
infection rates are rising among young gay men in Atlanta, possibly
because of recreational drug abuse, an AIDS advocacy group is
warning.
</P>
