<HEADER>
A8915 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELVIS-AUTHOR-SPI &LR;      01-26 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELVIS-AUTHOR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELVIS BIOGRAPHER BRINGS FRESHNESS TO LATEST WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eleven years of Peter Guralnick's life were devoted to
researching and recounting the life of Elvis Presley, someone whose
life so many people thought they already knew in intimate detail _
the unlikely rise, the agonizing fall.
</P>
<P>
   Guralnick did not care how much had been written about Elvis, or
how well people thought they knew him. His own intent as biographer
was clear, unshakable.
</P>
<P>
   ``My aim at the conclusion of the book was to have the reader
say, `Ya, that makes sense,' because I was trying to tell a
credible story and not prompt any more `Oh-my-God!' flashy
headlines,'' Guralnick said in an interview. ``My greatest
aspiration was to present a character and a world that come across
as fresh and make sense on their own terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Guralnick's two-volume account of the life of the King of Rock
'n' Roll is finally finished now, 1,139 pages in all. His acclaimed
1994 volume, ``Last Train to Memphis: The Rise of Elvis Presley,''
has just been joined by ``Careless Love: The Unmaking of Elvis
Presley'' (Little Brown, 651 pages, $27.95), already appearing on
best-seller lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Careless Love'' tracks Elvis from his 1958 Army service in
Germany to his 1977 death when the drugged and depressed singer was
stricken by a heart attack while sitting on the leather toilet seat
in his Graceland mansion in Memphis. This is a story of pathos and
excess and self-destruction, another sorry tale of how charisma and
celebrity and money cannot purchase happiness, familiar tabloid
fodder then and even now.
</P>
<P>
   But Guralnick's account of all this sensational stuff is much
like the 55-year-old biographer himself _ serious-minded,
non-judgmental, diligent, thorough, unassuming, scrupulous.
</P>
<P>
   Elvis' decline and fall into a bloated Las Vegas parody of
himself may have subjected him to widespread derision and ridicule.
But Guralnick strives, with great success, to elevate the
discussion of this seminal figure, bringing fresh insights into
Elvis' remarkable contributions to American music and culture and
his complex and often-contradictory personality, including what
would prove to be fatal flaws, his tendency toward depression,
isolation and idolatry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He constructed a shell to hide his aloneness, and it hardened
on his back,'' Guralnick writes. ``I know of no sadder story. But
if the last part of Elvis' life had to do with the price that is
paid for dreams, neither the dreams themselves, nor the aspiration
that fueled them, should be forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   As a Boston teen, Guralnick started his long-playing record
collection with an album by Elvis and he remains a great fan of the
man's music. Guralnick readily admits that his favorite Elvis song,
``Trying to Get to You,'' got to him when it was first released in
1955 on Sun Records and still gets to him today, whether in the
original version or many subsequent versions throughout Elvis'
life, the ballad's soaring spirituality always seeming to inspire
the singer and somehow reflect his aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Guralnick's appreciation for Elvis' music inspires some of the
most compelling writing in his massive account, especially in his
recounting of various all-night recording sessions. But it does not
prevent him from examining, often in day-by-day detail, the
downward spiral of a great, even revolutionary, talent too often
squandered on quickie movies, forgettable tunes and ill-prepared
performances.
</P>
<P>
   What Guralnick does not do much, by design, is analyze. He is
unstinting in his pursuit of what actually happened, what Elvis did
or said or what others around him did (although not much beyond
those principals). But the biographer is almost pathologically
opposed to deciding for readers why something happened or who was
responsible or what that all means. If that frustrates readers who
come to a biography expecting judgments in this rush-to-judgment
age, then so be it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such judgments only speak of the author of the judgment,''
Guralnick emphasized. ``It does not describe the person who is the
subject of the biography. What I'm trying to do is paint a portrait
of sufficient depth that different readers will take different
things from it. The portrait is mine and the framing of the
portrait is mine, but the challenge is to try to paint the portrait
in a way that it paints the person, not provide some pop psychology
one-liners.''
</P>
<P>
   Guralnick's relentless accumulation of detail can at times test
the patience and endurance of anyone who is not a fervent
card-carrying member of the Elvis fan club, especially since the
second portion of his life is almost as much of a downer as the
pills that held the singer in their grip. But there is no denying
that the Elvis who emerges in the pages of ``Careless Love'' is a
real human being, not some celebrity cardboard cutout.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a person of unassuming humility in the maelstrom of
fame, a performer who in the last days of his life was still
worrying over what will his fans think. Here is someone of
impulsive generosity who gave new cars to friends and acquaintances
as if they were boxes of chocolates. Here is someone who was
rigorous in his quest for answers to elemental questions of meaning
and faith, even when they led to unconventional sources that others
might deride, including one trip on LSD.
</P>
<P>
   And here is a person with enough quirks to fill a psychology
textbook: his refusal to have sex with women after they had had
children (including his wife, Priscilla); his infatuation with law
enforcement paraphernalia and personages; his near-mythic
connection to his mother, Gladys, even after her death in 1958; his
rationalizations that he was not a drug-user since what he took and
had administered to him was prescribed by willing doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Elvis' problems with drugs started in the Army when he was
introduced to amphetamines by fellow soldiers who used them to get
through the rigors of all-night field exercises. Then, once out of
the service, it all careened out of control in days of sleep and
nights of partying, with downers to finally knock Elvis out and
uppers to get him going and painkillers of ever-increasing strength
to combat ailments of one kind or another, until his body became a
kind of pharmaceutical lab experiment.
</P>
<P>
   Elvis did not turn blimp from an all-cheeseburger diet. Nor did
he die because he did not eat enough broccoli or oat bran. What
finally happened to Elvis is not that simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``What killed Elvis was a heart attack, but his health was
severely compromised by all the prescription drugs he took,
depressants, cancer drugs, painkillers,'' Guralnick said. ``His
health was undermined by drugs. You can see that in his appearance;
he was bloated from steroids. If you take away his medications,
Elvis might have been a normally overweight man without that
bloating.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what killed Elvis most of all was the death of his spirit.
He was on a course toward his death from late 1973 on; it is
impossible not to see what he was doing then as heading on a
one-way trip. To say that Elvis killed himself might be overstating
things. But he was so deeply self-destructive by then, having
fallen away from his ideals and aspirations and more and more using
drugs to block out reality. He was destroying himself. What Elvis
did was kill himself slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Guralnick, despite all he now knows about Elvis,
still finds himself often reflecting on ``thoughts of what might
have been.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
