<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GREECE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELPING GREECE CATCH ON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS _ As host of the 2004 Olympics, Greece automatically gets
to enter its baseball team in the competition, without having to
qualify. Which is fine, but Greece doesn't have a baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   Or a baseball stadium. Or a coach. Or bats. Or baseball fans,
for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Red Sox and the Baltimore Orioles are about to change
that.
</P>
<P>
   As a gesture of good will, the teams plan to send several
coaches and players to train Greek players when the 1999 season
ends in the United States. In addition, the Major League Baseball
Commissioner's office has offered to help refurbish several rutted,
rock-strewn baseball fields on an abandoned US military base
outside Athens.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to instill a love of baseball in the cradle of
Western thought. More immediately, everyone wants to form a team
that won't embarrass Greece as it holds the Games for the first
time since it hosted the debut of the modern Olympics in 1896.
</P>
<P>
   The idea came from US Ambassador R. Nicholas Burns, who is, to
put it undiplomatically, a nut about baseball. He may be the only
ambassador anywhere who displays Carl Yastrzemski and Carlton Fisk
baseball cards right by the requisite portraits of President
Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright.
</P>
<P>
   During a conversation last year with officials from Greek's
Ministry of Sports, Burns turned the conversation to baseball, as
he often does.
</P>
<P>
   Burns inquired about the preparations for baseball in 2004. The
government officials conceded that although Greece has
extraordinary soccer and basketball teams, it lacks baseball
players, particularly catchers, pitchers, outfielders, and anyone
who knows what ``batting stance'' means.
</P>
<P>
   Burns sought the assistance of Paul Beeston, president of Major
League Baseball, and Lou Gorman, Red Sox executive consultant and
former general manager. He also called Orioles owner Peter Angelos,
a Greek American. All agreed to contribute money, materials, and
advisers to help with baseball diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   In an oversight, perhaps, the ambassador from Wellesley, Mass.,
neglected to contact George Steinbrenner, the deep-pocketed owner
of the world champion Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe George would have been glad to help,'' Beeston
said last week from New York. ``Maybe the ambassador has too many
bad memories of Red Sox-Yankees games.''
</P>
<P>
   Beeston said baseball management is excited about the chance to
help Europe catch up to the United States, Latin America, and Japan
in baseball fever. The commissioner's office may send coaches and
trainers from minor league teams, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to promote baseball as much as we can,'' said Lou
Gorman, of the Red Sox. ``When it gets spread all over the whole
world, maybe we'll have a real World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns put out the word among Hellenic organizations about the
need for a few good ballplayers with Greek passports. Or, at the
very least, the heritage that would entitle them to play for
Greece.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got people coming out of the woodwork,'' he says as he
sits in his Athens residence, which is decorated with a model of
Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   At first, apparently, Greek officials assumed they would go to
the Major Leagues and recruit Greek-American players like, well,
what's-his-name. But Greek-Americans have not reached the
prominence in professional baseball that they have in politics, the
media, and the arts. The big leagues do not yet have a Michael
Dukakis, or Olympia Snowe, or George Stephanopolous, or Yanni, the
new age musician.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Burns's preliminary scouting report has identified
several up-and-coming Greek-American players on several campuses.
And the volunteers include Charles G. Samiotes and Bill Galatis,
who take part in the Red Sox Fantasy Camp in Fort Myers every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that we are pretty good ball players and would like to
be involved in the 2004 Olympics, as well as bringing baseball to
Greece,'' Samiotes, who is from Wayland, wrote in an e-mail to
Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Costas Bakouris, managing director of Athens 2004, which is
coordinating the Olympics in Greece, has watched with pleasure
while the ambassador works his Rolodex.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a Red Sox fan, you have a special relationship with
the team. . . . I don't know whether the word is fanatic, I don't
know if you're masochistic,'' Bakouris said at Athens 2004 Olympic
headquarters, which has plenty of pictures of swimmers and runners,
but none of outfielders or pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of full disclosure, Bakouris mentions that he
went to college in Chicago and is a White Sox fan. ``I actually
like the Cubs, too,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   At the embassy, Burns is busy monitoring violence in the Balkans
and trying to ease tensions between Greece and its enemy Turkey. He
asked an assistant, Dave Simons, who usually oversees housing for
embassy employees, to be his point man on baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Simons, of Salt Lake City, doesn't know how Burns chose him, but
he assumes it has something to do his background as a Red Sox fan.
</P>
<P>
   The Greek government is building baseball and softball stadiums
and practice fields, which should be ready shortly before the
Olympics. That leaves aspiring players _ if any appear _ with no
place to play for the next few seasons. So one of Simons' first
stops was the old Hellinikon Air Base near Athens, which the US Air
Force deserted five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   A pessimist would have seen four rusting backstops and rutted
baseball and softball diamonds that have been transformed to a
makeshift soccer field. That's exactly what Simons saw, and he's an
optimist.
</P>
<P>
   The only things holding the backstops together seem to be
weathered signs proclaiming that ``non-appropriated funds''
(donations, in layman's language) were used to build the baseball
emporium on the base.
</P>
<P>
   Still, like anyone who has cheered for the Red Sox at some
point, Simons is a believer. What he saw was not quite a field of
dreams, but a field of weeds with potential. ``It was kind of a
nostalgic experience,'' he says. ``It takes you back to the summers
when you were a kid buying Sno-Kones.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially if you were a kid on a military base blessed with
non-appropriated funds.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox have not decided which players to send over, and the
Orioles say they also will volunteer to help with training in the
off-season. Simons is working with the league management to
refurbish the fields, a project that is expected to start later
this year.
</P>
<P>
   One evening earlier this month, Simons looked out of his
apartment window and saw a sign, a harbinger, a message from
Spalding or Rawlings or Nike, the ancient gods of sport:
</P>
<P>
   In the fading, golden light of dusk, there stood three boys,
about 12 years old, laughing and playing catch with a baseball and
gloves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
