u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-26 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEGINNING OF THE ENDGAME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - When three members of the House prosecution team
told the media circus gathered around Monica Lewinsky that she
would be a good witness, they undercut their credibility with the
Senate one more time.
</P>
<P>
   Had the House Republican 3 _ Bill McCollum of Florida, Ed Bryant
of Tennessee, and Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas _ had the good sense
to say something neutral, Lewinsky's lawyer, Plato Cacheris, might
have let them off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   But as Cacheris watched them go beyond the facts once more, he
had no choice but to set the record straight. Nothing different
from her 22 previous appearances and sworn statements, Cacheris
said bluntly. There's nothing substantive to add, he said, so
please tell your superiors (a lovely insult) to lay off and let her
have a chance at a life.
</P>
<P>
   It was the beginning of the endgame, and Henry Hyde's minions
had once again stuck their necks out in public with a tale that
could be contradicted simply by the facts.
</P>
<P>
   The Monica incident was not the only one in town that evening.
House managers also spent time with the least credible practitioner
in the political game, former Clinton adviser Dick Morris, as they
attempted to cobble together a list of deposition witnesses that
might have a chance of Senate approval.
</P>
<P>
   In the trial presentations, however, the managers themselves had
already poisoned that well with their most astonishing
prevarication of all.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Bryant had been the offender, and his offense over the
weekend was to twist the facts. Bryant had supplied what appeared
to be a grand jury testimony-based narrative of a phone call
between President Clinton and Morris as the sex scandal was
breaking a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, once the US attorney for western Tennessee, informed the
Senate on Friday that Morris's testimony had been that Clinton told
him he was preparing to hold a press conference trashing Lewinsky
but that Morris had urged caution before taking such a dramatic and
irrevocable step.
</P>
<P>
   And then Bryant sat down at the managers' table, and no one said
a thing.
</P>
<P>
   At the other table, the presidential attorneys could not believe
their ears _ or their luck. The next day, White House counsel
Charles Ruff seized on another version of the ``trashing'' theory
from Representative Jim Rogan of California to pounce.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Bryant's narrative, Ruff simply read from Page 127
of Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's referral to the House,
describing Morris's account of his second chat with the president:
</P>
<P>
   ``When Mr. Morris was considering holding a press conference to
`blast Monica Lewinsky out of the water,' the president told Mr.
Morris to `be careful.' According to Mr. Morris, the president
warned him not to be too hard on (Miss Lewinsky).''
</P>
<P>
   ``One hundred eighty degrees off,'' deadpanned Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast this with Ruff's behavior when he got caught trying to
ignore unpleasant facts in his own presentation on the witness
tampering charge that is part of the obstruction of justice
impeachment article. The White House argument had not dealt either
with a second Clinton-Betty Currie meeting after his deposition in
the Paula Jones case or with the fact Currie had been subpoenaed as
a potential witness in the case after the scandal broke in the
press.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff immediately apologized for his effort to be too cute by
half and thus misleading. That confession, however, then gave him
standing to rebut the material _ noting that after the headlines
the Jones lawyers had in fact issued a blizzard of Lewinsky-related
motions (Currie's subpoena was No. 163) in the closing days of
discovery, and that eight days after the first story, the judge in
the case ruled all Lewinsky material immaterial to it.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the endgame melodrama is dominated by opinion
polls, fatigue, exasperation, scenarios _ in short, by politics.
But beneath the surface is the most important reason of all why
more than a few Republicans have edged toward a willingness to pull
the trial's plug.
</P>
<P>
   It was on vivid display still again last Saturday as Hutchinson
sought to paint presidential friend Vernon Jordan as a crook by
presenting ``evidence'' that Jordan had told the grand jury ``you
didn't have to be an Einstein'' to realize that once Lewinsky was
subpoenaed in the Jones case in mid-December 1997, that his job
search and her effort to avoid telling the truth were related.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton attorney David Kendall noted, this deliberately
misstated Jordan's repeated testimony that the subpoena caused him
to get (false) assurances from Clinton and Lewinsky that they had
no relationship and only then to continue with the job and other
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The problem here is called bad faith, and it has proved fatal to
the House case, as it should.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
