<SLUG> BC-BKW-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC MAY HAVE DESIGNATED A LANDMARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Jan. 16, 1995, the University of Connecticut beat Tennessee,
77-66, in a game televised around the country that gave the Huskies
their first No. 1 ranking and catapulted them toward an undefeated
season and the national championship. Although UConn had been good
for years, that one victory is often cited as putting the women's
basketball program on the map.
</P>
<P>
   Time will tell whether Boston College's 78-66 upset of those
Huskies last Saturday becomes the same kind of defining moment, but
this much is certain: On Sunday morning, a lot more people were
paying attention than had been 24 hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two people sent flowers today, fans calling, people I don't
even know leaving messages on the machine,'' said Eagles coach
Cathy Inglese Monday. ``It's been overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   When you look back over the past few seasons, the shocker over
UConn shocks a little less. In 1994-95 _ the year UConn went 35-0
in Geno Auriemma's 10th season at the helm _ Inglese was in her
second year at The Heights, and her team was 6-21. Since then, the
Eagles have finished 10-17, 18-10, and 17-11. Early last season
they easily handled Texas Tech, 82-68, when it was ranked No. 25,
and beat Notre Dame, 78-76, before the Irish went on to the Sweet
Sixteen.
</P>
<P>
   This season, they again beat Notre Dame, which was No. 7 at the
time, and the next week the Eagles made their first-ever appearance
in the national polls at No. 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year's been a steppingstone to get here,'' said Inglese,
whose team was No. 22 in the Associated Press poll that came out
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But beating No. 2 UConn, to which it had lost 16 straight games
going back to 1990, is more like a battering ram.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to open more doors for us,'' deadpanned
Inglese.
</P>
<P>
   Behind some of those doors will be media: ABC didn't even wait
for the end of the game before calling to put in dibs for an
interview with the soon-to-be victorious coach. And when's the last
time the BC women's basketball team took up two-thirds of the
Sunday Globe's sports front?
</P>
<P>
   Behind others will be fans, their interest finally piqued.
Monday, the BC ticket office got 30 orders for advance tickets,
which, said associate athletic director Jim O'Neill, was ``very
unusual for us. Outside of UConn, we'd be lucky to get a call a
week for advance tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Eagles have played most of their games at Conte
Forum in front of crowds not even a 10th the size of Saturday's
8,606.
</P>
<P>
   Behind still more will be recruits, newly impressed by all of
the above.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you a great phone call,'' said Mike Flynn, editor of
the Blue Star Report, a newsletter on recruiting. ``It helps you
with your mailing. It makes a statement to recruits. Maybe this
changes who they feel they can target. This gives BC the chance to
rise above the pack.''
</P>
<P>
   And with the game televised on Fox Sports New England and
selectively picked up around the country as the upset was brewing,
a lot of folks got their first glimpse of BC women's basketball on
a day when Conte Forum was filled to capacity and Alissa Murphy
played like Chamique Holdsclaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't ask for a better scenario,'' said Muffet McGraw,
coach of Notre Dame. ``All the recruits are watching. It sort of
legitimizes your program. As a coach, you're always saying, `We're
pretty good, come watch us.' This turns it from opinion to fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Because next year's freshman class is virtually set by now, any
long-term impact of the win won't be seen for a couple of years,
and even that isn't guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going on a losing streak and not making the NCAA tournament,
that would basically negate the effect of this game,'' warned
Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   Inglese pretty much agreed: ``If we make it to the NCAAs'' _
which BC has never done _ ``that's the step we need to get some of
those bigger players, not just one a year but maybe two or three a
year.''
</P>
<P>
   But that madness comes in March. For now, it's well-earned
hysteria at The Heights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
