<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPER BOWL TEAMS IGNORE THE ODDSMAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The Denver Broncos know what it's like to be the Atlanta
Falcons this week. They know what it means to have no chance in the
biggest football game of the year.
</P>
<P>
   They know it means nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Robinson knows what it's like to be the Denver Broncos
this week. He knows what it means to be told there is no way you
can lose the biggest football game of the year.
</P>
<P>
   He knows it means nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Broncos' team and the Falcons' safety know because just
12 months ago one was the team that had no chance to win and the
other played for the team that had no chance to lose. The Broncos
were believed to be the Denver Lambs then, a team sent to the
slaughter at Super Bowl XXXII at the hands of Robinson's mighty
Green Bay Packers. As 12-point underdogs, the Lambs were there
only, it was said, because Green Bay needed somebody to beat up on
and the Broncos had volunteered.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve months later, those same Broncos are back as defending
Super Bowl champions, conquerers of Robinson's Packers, and now
favorites themselves to do to Robinson's Falcons what Green Bay
could not do to them.
</P>
<P>
   Oddsmakers did not build Las Vegas out of desert sands by being
wrong very often about such matters, but no one is right all the
time, either, so as the madness of Super Bowl week began, that gave
hope to one team and served as cautionary note to the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one expects us to go out there and win,'' Robinson said of
his 16-2 Falcons. ``I'm pretty sure Denver is feeling pretty good
about themselves because they played marvelously throughout the
season. Some people expected them to finish 17-0, and that was
within their grasp. They're a great team.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't mind being the underdog. Being an underdog is
being in a position to surprise the other team. I like that.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't like it much last year, though, when his was the team
that was surprised. He didn't like it when the Broncos came out and
ran the ball on his defense until they had beaten it into
submission. He didn't much like learning that underdogs have teeth,
too, but a year later it is a lesson he can pass on to his
less-experienced teammates. A lesson about life and about football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wore my Super Bowl ring (from Super Bowl XXXI) leading into
the NFC Championship in Minnesota because I wanted to make it
tangible for the other guys here,'' Robinson said. ``A lot of guys
look at the ring and want to put it on and look at it up close, but
I tell them we can all have our own rings. We can do this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to make it real for them. Don't be mesmerized by the
Super Bowl. We can go out there and win a football game and get our
own rings. People said we had an advantage last year because the
Packers had been there the year before. People said the same thing
about the 49ers when we were getting ready for the divisional
playoffs a couple of weeks ago because they had more experience
than we did. Quite frankly, our guys don't care at all about that.
We've been accustomed to winning all season long. The theme all
year has been to win a game every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there is only one week _ and one game _ left, and though
Robinson's team is not expected to win, he knows it can. He knows
this not solely because he believes in the Falcons. He knows this
not solely because it was in this same city 30 years ago that the
New York Jets pulled off one of the biggest upsets in football
history.
</P>
<P>
   No, Robinson knows this because he has first-hand evidence that
is just 12 months old. It is the same evidence the Broncos believe
will insulate them from the arrogance they feel led to the Packers'
downfall a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta pretty much comes into the situation we came in last
year _ the underdog,'' said Broncos All-Pro tight end Shannon
Sharpe. ``I don't know how many people are giving them a chance but
I think we learned from the mistakes that Green Bay made. You have
to respect your opponent and you have to prepare. If you do that,
you at least give yourself an opportunity to win the ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get those 11 1/2-12 points (from the spread) on the
scoreboard. For us, 7 points doesn't mean anything because we know
that we have to go out there and play the ballgame. I think we
learned a valuable lesson in how Green Bay approached it.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question we respect them more than Green Bay respected us.
No one gave Atlanta a chance to go into Minnesota and beat that
team, and they did. We've got our hands full. We know that.''
</P>
<P>
   They know it now, but will they remember it Wednesday and
Thursday and Friday and Saturday and most of all Sunday? Will they
know it after a week of hearing and reading about how great they
are and how this is a bon voyage party for John Elway and a
showcase for the league's fourth 2,000-yard rusher, Terrell Davis?
</P>
<P>
   Will they still know it when they have been told over and over
about the sad history of the Falcons, who never have been even
close to a Super Bowl before?
</P>
<P>
   Will they still know it enough to think of Aretha Franklin when
they think of the Falcons and give them R-E-S-P-E-C-T and remember
to T-C-B or will they just think, as Aretha used to wail, that
they're going to ``sock it to 'em, sock it to 'em, sock it to 'em,
sock it to 'em YEAH just a little bit?''
</P>
<P>
   Until the game is played nobody can know that for sure, but
Broncos cornerback Ray Crockett believes if his team has a problem
come Sunday, it won't be because they didn't see it coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really worry about being the underdog or being picked
to win,'' Crockett said. ``That really doesn't matter to us. What
we have to do is go out and prepare the same way we did last year.
Last year we didn't feel like the underdogs. We thought we were
definitely as talented as any team out there and we feel the same
way about Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't look at them as an underdog. They have as much talent
as anyone. We're all here with an even battle. There are no
underdogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Not in this game there aren't. In this game there are only two
teams, both survivors of a long walk through minefields. They are
the champions and the future champions. If the Denver Broncos
intend to become both, they need to remember Ray Crockett's words
because you can bet on one thing this week for sure. Eugene
Robinson will.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
