<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8928 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-26 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEET FAST EDDIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; They are the most arresting commercials on television.
Desperate barkers hawk financial products along a darkened carnival
midway in a skyscraper canyon. A frog hops among the flotsam in a
flooded hall, seeking to avoid the alligators and sharks. One
astonishing image after another fills the screen, emphasizing the
ubiquity of fragility and deception in the financial world. ``This
is a world few know well,'' intones the announcer. Finally the
camera pans up to disclose a serene glass and steel presence far
above the turmoil. ``Come to the mountain called First Union,'' the
announcer continues. ``Or, if you prefer, the mountain will come to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   First Union Corp. says it has been around for 92 years. Why
haven't we heard of it before?
</P>
<P>
   Meet Edward E. Crutchfield, 57, known as ``Fast Eddie'' in the
banking community for the alactrity of his deals. A dozen years ago
he was the newly named chief executive of the third biggest bank in
North Carolina, after North Carolina National Bank and Wachovia
Bank. Today, he runs the sixth largest bank in America _ though
still only second biggest in Charlotte. Wachovia threw in with
First Atlanta shortly after a 1985 Supreme Court decision that
permitted banks to expand regionally, but NCNB changed its name to
NationsBank and went on a buying spree. Today it is the nation's
third largest bank, after Citibank and Chase. Hugh McColl built
NationsBank by buying distressed banks at sale prices. Crutchfield
built First Union through a whirlwind series of premium-priced
deals. (He's pledged, more than once, to seek a less dilutive
``merger of equals'' next time.) NationsBank went south and west
and the middle of the country. First Union went up the Eastern
seaboard _ from Florida to Connecticut, so far. In fact, the
present-day incarnation of First Union in the television
commercials is barely four years old. That was when, in a meeting
at the Greenbriar resort in West Virginia, Crutchfield and his
fellow executives decided to take on the mutual funds and brokerage
companies head to head. They bought Boston's Keystone Investments
Inc., a large manager of stock, bond, and money market funds, in
September 1996. ``We're trying to build a business that is about 50
percent traditional bank while the other needs to look like a
combination of Merrill Lynch, Fidelity, and Charles Schwab,''
Crutchfield told an interviewer in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   One tactic in the expansion drive is a single bankwide computer
system that is supposed to give First Union insurmountable
economies of scale; another is an aggressive customer friendliness
that sends ``calling officers'' into homes earning as little as
$75,000 annually, in a search for business beyond traditional bank
ing fees. (That's how the mountain comes to you.) The surreal
television advertising campaign is the brainchild of Crutchfield
and advertising legend Hal Riney, chairman of a San Francisco
agency. The idea was to somehow ``break above the clutter'' of
ordinary ads for financial services. Riney is best remembered for a
series of commercials for Bartles and Jaymes wine coolers (and
Ronald Reagan's ``Morning in America'' ad!). He enlisted Industrial
Light and Magic, the Hollywood spe cialeffects firm (it grew out of
the ``Star Wars'' films) to make his commercials. Four have aired
so far; a fifth is scheduled to be shown for the first time during
Sunday's Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In the advertising community, a spirited debate is underway
about the efficacy of the ads; there is always disagreement when an
image campaign is not tied directly to the product. But the more
interesting question has to do with whether it is possible to
establish a brand without a secure position in the marketplace.
That's the real riddle at the heart of First Union's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With the financial services industry poised for another great
wave of consolidation, First Union's strategy in the capital
markets, like that of other banks, must be one of keep ing its
stock price high _ all the while aggressively searching for
acquisitions among the remaining premium independent regional banks
_ Fleet Financial, for example, or BankBoston. That means behaving
more than a little like those carnival barkers and alligators in
its ads. It remains to be seen whether you can befriend the world's
frogs _ and eat them too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
