<HEADER>
A8976 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOT-BJT27-COX     01-26 2057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday, Jan. 27,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACHMENT TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate is to convene at noon EST
today and move to the impeachment trial of President Clinton. The
White House lawyers and House prosecutors each have two hours to
argue the case for calling witnesses to the trial. The senators are
then expected to move into a closed-door session to debate whether
the House prosecutors will be allowed to subpoena witnesses. Next
on the schedule is two votes: the vote on a motion to dismiss the
case offered by Sen. Robert Byrd, and the vote on calling
witnesses. These votes are likely to be held over until Wednesday.
(Foskett/Sherman/Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-MANAGERS _ WASHINGTON _ Not all the 13 House managers
had experience as prosecutors before leading the case for President
Clinton's impeachment, but several have records of success in
high-profile cases. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ Commentary on the impeachment. (Baxter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER WASHINGTON NEWS
</P>
<P>
   COX-AFFIRMATIVE _ WASHINGTON - The Center for Individual Rights,
which successfully fought affirmative action in education in Texas,
unveiled a new legal strategy Tuesday - a threat to seek personal
damages from trustees of public universities that use racial
preferences in admissions. ``Trustees are going to have to step up
to the plate,'' said CIR's senior counsel, Terence J. Pell.
(Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   BLUE-DOGS _ WASHINGTON _ The ``Blue Dogs'' or conservative
Democrats have increased in number and in clout in Congress. As a
result, unity in the Democratic party could depend greatly on
bringing together these younger conservatives with their
traditionally liberal collegues. Moderate Waco democrat Chet
Edwards realized this a while back. ``We were a disfunctional
family in 1994,'' he said. Now, Edwards has become a bridge between
conservatives and the Democratic leadership. He says conservative
Democrats are bringing the party back ``to the middle of the road''
and will be the key in regaining Democratic control of Congress in
2000. (Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BLUE-DEFINE _What is a blue dog? Short description of the origin
of the term. (Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   POPE _ ST. LOUIS _ Coverage and reaction to John Paul's address
to the Light of the World Papal Youth Gathering. What does it mean
so see the pope? (Lyles, Dayton Daily News). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Pope arrives at 6 p.m. EST
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POPE _ ST.LOUIS _ President Clinton welcomes Pope John
Paul II to St. Louis. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POPE _ MEXICO CITY _ This was likely Pope John Paul II's
final trip to the Americas. We examine the potential impact, both
on people and policy. Developing. (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in International (i) and Lifestyle (l) categories.
</P>
<P>
   JASPERDEATH-TRIAL _ JASPER, Texas _ On the second day of jury
selection in the murder trial of John William King, we look at what
attorneys are seeking in the perfect jury. Jury members must fill
out a questionnaire with 50 questions that ask such things as What
is the most important value we should teach our children and name
three heroes. We also provide some insight into what happens once a
jury is empaneled, such as daily escorts by law enforcment for each
juror to and from the courthouse. (Gamino, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   LYONS _ CLEARWATER _ Testimony begins in racketeering and fraud
trial of the Rev. Henry Lyons, president of the National Baptist
Convention USA. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constituton).
</P>
<P>
   EXTRATERRESTRIAL-LIFE _ LOS ANGELES _ For the first time in
human history, we now have the capability to move life beyond
Earth, and researchers in physics, chemistry, genetics and other
fields are pooling their knowledge to understand where terrestial
life may end up and how it may adapt or we change. (Seabrook,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-JOBS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas Public Policy Foundation,
a conservative think tank based in San Antonio, has set up a job
bank to help conservatives find work in state government now that
Republicans have taken over statewide offices. Offering advice on
everything from writing cover letters to how to dress for an
interview _ men: wear black or dark blue suits and leave the Rush
Limbaugh tie at home; women: stick to simple jewelry and skirts at
or below the knee _ the foundation promises to ``recruit and help
place conservative job seekers in suitable positions'' at no
charge. (Harmon, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-PATROL _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Matthew MacMorran was struggling
with an uncooperative lug nut on the right-front wheel of his Ford
pickup when Bruce Murphy pulled up behind him in the inside
breakdown lane of MoPac Boulevard. MacMorran had been trying to
avoid being hit by cars that whizzed by only feet away as he tried
to change a flat tire in the middle of heavy traffic. Even after
police officer Bruce Spence closed off the nearest lane of traffic,
the work was still taking time and slowing traffic. Frustrated
drivers had begun honking their horns. When Murphy offered to help,
MacMorran gladly wiped his tire-greased hands and watched as Murphy
finished the job in less than 10 minutes with an air gun. MacMorran
didn't know who Murphy was or why he was helping, but it turns out
the help didn't come from the average good Samaritan. Murphy's job
is to roam area highways and help stranded motorists. ``I never
knew they had this courtesy patrol thing,'' MacMorran said after
thanking Murphy. ``I know I would have been out here a lot longer
if he hadn't come along.'' Spence was also grateful Murphy came
along. ``It's definitely a whole lot simpler when you've got the
right tools,'' Spence said. ``A lot of times (the courtesy patrol)
can get things moving a whole lot faster.'' That's the idea behind
the state Transportation Department's 2-year-old program. (Hiott,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   with TEX-PATROL-TIPS _ (Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SPIELBERG-HOLOCAUST _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Palm Beach County
high school students will be the first in the country to get their
Holocaust lessons courtesy of Steven Spielberg and have their
teachers trained by the former director of the research institute
of the Holocaust Museum in Washington, D.C. Spielberg's Shoah
Visual History Foundation, based in Los Angeles, has spent three
years documenting the stories of 50,000 Holocaust survivors,
including 289 in Palm Beach, Martin, St. Lucie and Indian River
counties in Florida. In March, three teachers from each high school
in the county will gather to learn how to incorporate an
educational CD-ROM produced by Spielberg into their lesson plans.
Their teacher will be Michael Berenbaum, president of Shoah and the
former director of the Holocaust Research Institute of the U.S.
Holocaust Museum. (Isger, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WINTER-FARMING _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Cows aren't any better at
walking on a sheet of ice than people, which is why farmer Clyde
Musser cringed every time he checked on his cattle during the
winter storms this month. ``The barnyard was covered with ice and
the cows were sliding around like they were wearing roller
skates,'' he said. ``It hasn't been a very healthy situation.''
Musser's 30 cows are important to his livelihood, and caring for
them through the extremes of winter is hard work. Jeff Layman, Ohio
State extension agent for agriculture in Miami County, said winter
months present several challenges for farmers. ``The ups and downs
of winter cause a lot of problems _ whether it's keeping animals
healthy, making sure water supplies don't freeze, watching for
moisture in grain storage or even just starting a diesel engine,''
Layman said. (Elliott, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-NYC-ADULT _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Dayton is studying whether it
can enact a New York City-style ordinance that limits where
adult-oriented businesses can operate. The U.S. Supreme Court this
month upheld New York City's law that forced many X-rated
businesses out of Times Square. Mayor Mike Turner hailed the
court's decision and would like to see a similar ordinance here.
``It is very exciting the U.S. Supreme Court has finally given us
the tools to deal with this,'' Turner said. (Bebbington, Dayton
Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   STATE LEGISLATIVE NEWS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-STATEOFSTATE _ AUSTIN _ As Gov. Bush walks into the Texas
House chamber Wednesday to deliver his third state of the state
address, he is expected to be welcomed as a hero. Ironically, the
most unpredictable reaction in the chamber will come from his own
party. We examine Bush's relationship with the Legislature,
particularly those conservative Republicans who help derail his tax
plan last session and have a social agenda this session that goes
far beyond what Bush has promised. (Elizondo, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-STATESIDE _ Bush is expected to paint a rosy picture of the
state of the state. We offer our own assessment, with a graphic
heavy look at key indicators, such as employment rate, crime rate,
graduation rate, drop-out rate and other barometers. (Ward, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-CHAMBERS _ The state's eight largest chambers of commerce,
including Austin's, announce joint legislative goals in a press
conference. May be the first commom effort of its kind of these
groups. (Greenberger, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CRACKDOWN _ BEIJING _ After nearly a month's lull, Chinese
security authorities have resumed their aggressive crackdown on
maverick thinkers, this time hauling in a Beijing factory
manager-turned-intellectual for questioning about allegedly
consorting with prostitutes. Peng Ming, the irreverent founder of a
discussion group called China Development Union, was seized late
Monday by 10 policemen at the Dayun Night Club on Beijing's
southern outskirts. The police burst into a private dining room
where Peng and a male friend had been enjoying a many-course
Chinese dinner, according to Peng's wife. (Albright-Kunstel, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is a Cox EXCLUSIVE.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SYMPHONY _ BEIJING _ The National Symphony Orchestra,
based at the Kennedy Center, is opening an Asia tour on Wednesday
night with a concert at the Great Hall of the People. Developing.
(Kunstel-Albright, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in International (i) and Lifestyle (l) categories.
</P>
