<HEADLINE>
HAIL TO THE CHEAT: CLINTON'S FLAKY FANS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 1,025-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 23 January 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In rapturous waves, they stand and cheer, their ecstatic smiles
as wide and lingering as his, their eyes as joyful. What does it
matter that Bill Clinton is on trial for perjury and obstruction of
justice? Look at his supporters _ at his fans. He is a president at
the peak of his popularity.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 19 the president delivered his State-of-the-Union
message to Congress. He described a country in its best shape in
years, where almost every indicator ticks towards improvement.
</P>
<P>
   America is in its eighth year of economic boom. Both federal and
state budgets are in surplus, even awash with money. The
unemployment rate, at 4.3 percent, is the lowest for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   In the big cities, murder rates have fallen by a fifth; the
crack epidemic has faded; even abortion rates and rates of teenage
pregnancy are falling. Gasoline is as cheap as it was between the
world wars, and baseball home runs at their highest ever.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder, you might conclude, that Clinton's popularity
knows no bounds. According to the latest USA Today/CNN/Gallup poll,
81 percent of the public now judge his presidency a success, and 69
percent approve of his overall job performance.
</P>
<P>
   And yet these figures and are also surreal and bizarre. Before
they dutifully trooped over to the House of Representatives to hear
the president's speech, the senators had been engaged in quite
other business: sitting as a silent jury to consider whether
Clinton should be removed from office. And, the next day, they
returned there.
</P>
<P>
   Small forests have been felled in the effort to explain why,
despite the disgrace of impeachment, the president's party and the
public still cling to him with such devotion.
</P>
<P>
   It is as though the president's supporters and his attackers are
