<HEADER>
A8978 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GO-SLOW-KOSOVO-ECONOM     01-26 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GO-SLOW-KOSOVO-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST MUST GET MORE INVOLVED IN KOSOVO, BUT CAREFULLY  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 650-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 23 January 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another massacre, more denials and dissemblings, the usual
pitiful survivors' tales. This time it was 45 ethnic Albanians,
including old men and children, who had been shot dead, probably at
close range.
</P>
<P>
   The only new twist was the Serbian authorities' behavior after
the killings _ the expulsion of a senior international monitor, and
the spiriting away of the bodies.
</P>
<P>
   This was outrageous even by the standards of the region, and the
world is justified in holding Yugoslavia's President Slobodan
Milosevic responsible. So is it time for NATO's long-threatened air
strikes against the Serbs?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the ``verifiers'' of the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe have reported strong prima facie evidence
that the killings were carried out in cold blood by Serbs, probably
in uniform. (They had blamed many previous cease-fire violations on
ethnic Albanians.)
</P>
<P>
   And certainly NATO would make a fool of itself if Milosevic
refused to abide by last October's cease-fire agreement and the
alliance then failed to carry out its threat to bomb Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   If air strikes become the only way of averting a catastrophic
loss of western moral authority, they will have to be carried out.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, however, a bombing campaign would not in itself
be enough to meet all the challenges posed by Serb brutishness _
and the killings, kidnappings and intimidation by ethnic-Albanian
fighters _ in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   For a start, one consequence could be more deaths of old people
and children. Among the risks of a bombing campaign is that it
would trigger bloody fighting in Pristina, Kosovo's capital.
</P>
<P>
   If the western world crosses that Rubicon, and conducts an air
campaign against a sovereign country of nearly 11 million people,
it will have to acknowledge, more clearly than hitherto, its
responsibility for the future of the rump Yugoslav state,
consisting of Serbia (including Kosovo) and Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   This would mean not only deploying armed peacekeepers to police
whatever cease-fire agreement were eventually reached, but setting
out an internationally agreed formula for the political future of
the federation and then putting intense pressure on the parties to
accept it.
</P>
<P>
   That should be done in any event, even if Milosevic backs down
this time and a bombing campaign is averted. Recent diplomatic
efforts have shown that there is virtually no chance of Serbs and
Albanians freely reaching agreement by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   What should that internationally agreed formula be? It will
somehow have to accommodate two principles. The first is that nasty
microbes fester whenever large numbers of people are subjected to
rule they regard as illegitimate, alien and intolerable.
</P>
<P>
   One of the worst effects is the spawning of insurgencies in
which thugs terrorize their own communities and dabble heavily in
crime, as well as harassing the hated rulers.
</P>
<P>
   The other principle is that, especially after the 1975 Helsinki
agreement, sovereign states should not be broken up by force, even
when (as in Bosnia) many citizens have voted for parties committed
to terminating the state's existence.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing to prevent states breaking up by consensus, as
Czechoslovakia did in 1993, and that may eventually happen in
Yugoslavia. But to countenance the violent, non-consensual breakup
of Serbia would be to invite a similar fate for Macedonia, Albania,
Bosnia, possibly even Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
   How can those two principles be reconciled? First, by calling
immediately and unequivocally for the elevation of Kosovo to the
status of the third republic, coequal with Serbia and Montenegro,
in the Yugoslav federation.
</P>
<P>
   Then by offering international guarantees and, if necessary,
peacekeepers to protect enclaves in Kosovo that are either heavily
populated by Serbs (in the north, for example) or regarded as Serb
holy places.
</P>
<P>
   That would give the lie to the Serb nationalists' belief that
the outside world has some racist bias against them, and establish
the principle that Serbs do not need to commit massacres to protect
their people or their heritage. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
