<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8980 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DINOSAUR-TELEPHONES-E     01-26 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINOSAUR-TELEPHONES-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK, MA BELL, NO WIRES!: THE MOBILE PHONE REVOLUTION  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 650-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 23 January 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``a''
general news, ``f'' financial news and ``k'' commentary news
files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``He's just stepped away from his desk.'' The age-old
secretarial excuse for absent bosses depends for its shred of
credibility on a dying technology: the wired telephone.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt secretaries will continue to offer it. But the
mind-boggling price that the markets are putting on the new
Vodafone/AirTouch combination _ their capitalizations will create
the world's ninth-largest telecoms business _ is the clearest
signal yet of a switch of telecoms from land to air.
</P>
<P>
   The new Vodafone is worth three times as much as Yahoo!, that
darling of the Internet share bubble. Mobile telephones have
changed the lives of many more people than the much-hyped Internet
_ and equally radically.
</P>
<P>
   Stupendous as the growth of the Internet has been, it remains
mainly an American phenomenon. The United States accounts for more
than 90 percent of the most-visited Internet sites and about half
of all users.
</P>
<P>
   The boom in the mobile phone has been more of a European and
Asian phenomenon. American companies have been slow to sell digital
phones; slow to charge the caller, rather than the recipient of the
call; and slow to develop a single national network.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in Europe, mobile phones have been an island of
deregulation amid a sea of old monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   A common digital standard (its replacement is a bone of
contention between Europe and America) allows users to call home
from Shanghai and Sydney to Reykjavik and Rimini. Little surprise
that Europe is home to two of the world's biggest mobile-phone
makers _ and now to its largest mobile-communications firm.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, analysts are still struggling to explain where
the profits will come from. No need for that with mobile
telephones.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two years, more than half of new telephone
subscriptions have been to mobile phones. In Finland, indeed, 53
percent of all telephones are mobile.
</P>
<P>
   Youngsters, off to university or to a new apartment, see no
point in paying for a fixed line when their lives are mobile _ and
the habit, once learned, will stay.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet and data transmission may prolong the life of fixed
lines. But the future of talk will be mobile.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, new mobile markets are still emerging. The latest,
flourishing in Europe more than in America, is for prepaid
mobile-telephones, which now account for 80 percent of new sales
for some firms.
</P>
<P>
   Talk has become like chocolate: you can buy it in the
supermarket or give it (in rationed quantities) to your children,
and companies can offer it free with their products.
</P>
<P>
   Governments, still fixated by the goal of universal service,
have hardly begun to consider the implications of a world in which
telephone time is bought over the counter.
</P>
<P>
   Other innovations will follow. Wireless allows many products,
from cars to tamagotchi, to incorporate communications as
inconspicuously as they already do computer chips.
</P>
<P>
   But already, the growth of wireless is changing the way people
think about the telephone. For one thing, the mobile telephone is a
personal instrument, not a communal one.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the car freed people from the inconvenience of communal
transport, so the mobile is a liberation. That appeals especially
to the young. A mobile-telephone number is a piece of data about a
person, not a household.
</P>
<P>
   Its enormous value is something that _ for all the blather about
Internet ``portals'' _ telephone companies have barely started to
consider.
</P>
<P>
   Equally, wireless will change the significance of location.
Time-zone and cost now matter more than mere distance. Indeed, in
some ways, the mobile telephone dispenses with physical geography
even more effectively than does the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   To tap into their e-mail, most folk still have to plug in
somewhere in the world (although that too will change as new mobile
gadgets develop). But to take that call, they can be anywhere the
signal reaches. Including away from their desk. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 650-word article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or
212-499-3333, or fax us at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 1426EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
