<HEADLINE>
EUROPE'S DEMORALIZED RIGHT-WINGERS TAKE FLIGHT TO NATIONALISM  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 925-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 23 January 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``a''
general news, ``i'' international news and ``k'' commentary news
files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the start of the decade, with communism vanquished and
socialism reeling from a crushing sideways blow, it was tempting to
write off the left in Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The right was triumphantly entrenched in government in Germany
and Britain and, by 1993, in France, the other big European power,
too. Defeat for the right looked about as likely as the birth of a
single European currency.
</P>
<P>
   How times have changed. These days, European voters have almost
universally rejected parties of the right, turning instead to the
reinvigorated, reinvented left _ and not only in Germany, Britain
and France.
</P>
<P>
   Today in the EU, the right rules alone only in Spain (and, in a
special form, in Ireland).
</P>
<P>
   Across the Union, parties of the right look demoralized, divided
and lost.
</P>
<P>
   In scrambling about for a way out of the electoral wilderness,
one route has begun to catch the eye of the right: nationalism.
This direction may offer some promising ideas. It certainly
presents some grave dangers.
</P>
<P>
   The revival of a nationalist program for the right has its
temptations. Parties of the right in opposition face a basic
choice: whether to try to seize back the center ground that they
have ceded to the new left, or to look for a clear, bold message
that sets them quite apart.
</P>
<P>
   A nationalist message offers just such a distinction. It chimes
with popular insecurities about globalization. And it is all the
more compelling these days in the face of intensifying efforts at
European unification.
</P>
<P>
   Since the launch of Europe's single currency on Jan. 1, if not
before, it has become plain that EU leaders are pressing ahead with
political integration.
</P>
<P>
   Although some Europeans, notably Italians, may be quite pleased
by the prospect of being increasingly governed by foreigners, the
thought sends a shiver down the spine of others. In any event,
plans for European integration in the coming years will challenge
national sovereignty still further.
</P>
<P>
   Right or wrong, there is a respectable case against European
integration to be made, one that resonates with worries about
national identity. This is the case that William Hague, leader of
Britain's Conservative Party, drew on when he outlined on Jan. 19
his ``British Way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Transferring power from Westminster to Brussels,'' among other
pieces of ``constitutional vandalism,'' he declared, ``strikes at
the core of our national identity.''
</P>
<P>
   When, the previous day, France had ratified the Amsterdam
treaty, which pulls the European Union a bit closer together, a
less sophisticated version of the message had been thundered out by
Charles Pasqua, once a French right-wing interior minister: this
week's ratification, he recalled, symbolically took place on the
anniversary of the proclamation of the German empire in 1871.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so (reasonably) respectable. But flirting with
nationalism can be a dangerous game. It can encourage the sorts of
populist fears that give rise to a far more frightening variety:
the xenophobia of the extreme right.
</P>
<P>
   It would be absurd to suggest that all politicians who draw on
nationalist feeling to criticize European integration pander, by
definition, to racists. Most do not.
</P>
<P>
   But the danger nonetheless exists that by fanning the
nationalist fire, even with genuine concerns about, say, an influx
of job-seekers from Eastern Europe in an expanded EU, nationalists
stoke up the sort of populist xenophobia on which the far right
thrives.
</P>
<P>
   This is why it was worrying to see members of Germany's
center-right Christian Democratic Union, which held power in Bonn
for 16 years until last September, take to the streets this week.
</P>
<P>
   They, and their more right-wing Bavarian counterparts in the
Christian Social Union, were doing so to gather signatures for a
petition against proposed changes in Germany's nationality laws.
The new government wants to make it easier for foreigners, notably
Turks, born and brought up in Germany to get a German passport.
</P>
<P>
   The critics, uneasy about this, object in particular to plans to
allow dual citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   It may be that, up to a point, stern words from the moderate
right about racial issues and immigration can steal the thunder of
the far right.
</P>
<P>
   One reason, other than its first-past-the-post voting system,
that Britain has been spared the growth of an extreme-right party
is that the Conservative Party extends farther to the right than
most of its continental counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   If it panders to the fears that the far right plays upon,
however, the moderate right will lend these fears respectability.
It may encourage the xenophobes who attack black and brown
Europeans. And it will discredit itself in the eyes of decent
voters who want nothing to do with racist bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   Which way to deal with anti-immigrant prejudice is the choice
that the French right now faces, thanks to a split in the National
Front, France's nasty far-right party.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend one of the Front's two camps meets to decide its
future. Although many center-right French politicians refuse even
to dignify the Front with the term ``political party,'' there will
be others who see in its implosion a chance to mop up some of its
vote.
</P>
<P>
   The right has been battered across the European Union in recent
years, defeated and outflanked by the new left. It is desperate for
a program around which it could return to power.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is a respectable nationalist agenda, the right
would be wise to pay close attention to the difference between that
and the xenophobic brand. It plays unthinkingly with nationalism at
its peril. &QL; 
