<SLUG> BC-DOGGIE-DAYS-TURKEY-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT DO YOU GET WHEN YOU MIX A DOG AND TURKEY?...ISTANPOODLE  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This curious 400-word ``separate buy'' article is from the current
(week beginning 23 January 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``a''
general news, ``i'' international news and ``k'' commentary news
files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA _ Those who criticize Turkey's human-rights record can
take some comfort from the fact that Turks seem to be treating
animals better than they used to.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the story of a collie abandoned in the Aegean port of
Izmir was splashed on the front page of a mass-circulation
newspaper, Hurriyet. The dog apparently ``went on hunger strike
because of a broken heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of readers rang up, offering to adopt the unhappy
fellow. Dog-loving, it seems, is the latest fad.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of things this is odd because, despite Turkey's
government-enforced secularity, Islam has long frowned on dog
ownership. Orthodox Muslim teaching says that dogs are unhygienic:
they must not be nearby when Muslims pray.
</P>
<P>
   But that is just one reason for many Turks' recent dogginess:
actively secular Turks like to show off their dogs partly to
demonstrate how European they are.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, dogs were, at best, exotic. Some breeds were on
display alongside tigers and giraffes in Ankara's zoo. What changed
the canine status was the Soviet Union's collapse, and the ensuing
influx of Russian suitcase-traders, whose wares included pedigree
puppies going cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Well-bred spaniels, Dalmatians and Rottweilers started selling
fast, for as little as $5 a pooch. Enterprising Turks began to
trade in dogs, tripling the Russians' prices but still offering
furry bargains to middle-class Turks.
</P>
<P>
   Pet shops proliferated: there are now 40 or so in Ankara, the
capital, alone, plus 60 dog clinics and three ``dog hotels'' in
case owners have to go away.
</P>
<P>
   The sales boom has given a boost to animal-rights groups, and
politicians have also spotted the trend. New laws to make
maltreatment of animals a crime are going through parliament.
</P>
<P>
   There was a burst of public debate this month when it emerged
that fur trappers were using meat laced with arsenic to lure foxes
to their doom.
</P>
<P>
   The latest posters of Mesut Yilmaz, Turkey's recently deposed
prime minister, who hopes to get his job back after the election
due in April, display him alongside not just his family but also
his Great Dane, Daisy.
</P>
<P>
   A popular television program has even shown Turkey's would-be
``first dog'' going into labor and then basking with her new pups:
vote-catchers, so Yilmaz hopes, all seven of them. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 400-word article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or
212-499-3333, or fax us at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
