<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK REPORTEDLY PROBES ON-LINE AUCTION HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN SARACEVIC  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ eBay Inc., the high-flying Internet auction
house, is being investigated by New York officials based on
consumer allegations of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New York City Department of Consumer Affairs is actively
investigating complaints regarding alleged fraudulent sales at
on-line auction houses,'' Commissioner Jules Polonetsky said
Monday. A source in New York confirmed eBay was part of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   At question are a number of person-to-person transactions in
which dealers allegedly sold the same piece of sports memorabilia
to multiple buyers.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report published in the New York Post, the
Consumer Affairs agency was able to purchase a baseball autographed
by Hall of Fame pitcher Christy Mathewson that had allegedly been
sold to several different buyers at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   While eBay (www.ebay.com) officials would not confirm or deny
the allegations, they said their attorneys were in touch with New
York officials.
</P>
<P>
   eBay, which is based in San Jose, Calif., issued a statement
saying: ``It has always been eBay's practice to offer to fully
cooperate with any investigation involving improper items on the
site. eBay takes pride in its close working relationship with law
enforcement and regulatory agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 15, eBay announced an update of its on-line ``trust and
safety program.'' Among the security features offered to its
customers at that time were free insurance from Lloyd's of London,
a user-identification system, easy access to escrow and
``clarification of illegal items that are not permissible for
sale.''
</P>
<P>
   The company said that it receives an average of 27 complaints
about fraud for every 1 million auctions. It conducted about 9.5
million auctions in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement to customers, Meg Whitman, the president and
chief executive of eBay, said the company had ``zero tolerance for
fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have committed and will continue to commit resources to
have the most comprehensive programs in order to keep eBay a safe
harbor for on-line person-to-person trading,'' Whitman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
