<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9015 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARALYZED-OFFICER-ART     01-26 1305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARALYZED-OFFICER-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON OFFICER MISSES UNDERCOVER ROLE AFTER DEALER'S BULLET CUTS
ACT SHORT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Photos available on NYT database) 
 
By LEIGH HOPPER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Vonda Higgins could have earned an Academy Award for
her portrayal of a drug addict.
</P>
<P>
   Shuffling back and forth, almost dancing in place as she rubbed
her hands together, the undercover officer ``geeked'' _ acted like
a crackhead who needs the drug but has no money. Her hair stuck out
wild, and she wore house shoes with her ``crack clothes'' for a
convincing effect.
</P>
<P>
   Her partner, Ralph Chaison, was known to pooch out his belly and
ask a skeptical dope dealer, ``You ever seen law with a stomach
like this?'' Chaison could wisecrack his way through danger, but
Higgins tricked criminals with dead-on mimicry.
</P>
<P>
   In five years working narcotics for the Houston Police
Department, the duo fooled hundreds of crooks, leading to hundreds
of arrests. They played the roles of boyfriend/girlfriend or
prostitute/john so well, they cracked themselves up. They often
talked of putting together a curriculum for the police academy.
</P>
<P>
   But Higgins' make-believe guises put her in the path of
real-life violence. Her street-theater stardom abruptly ended last
Feb. 4 when she and Chaison encountered a dealer who didn't buy
their act. Now Higgins is in an unwanted role she'll play for the
rest of her life.
</P>
<P>
   Just before 11 a.m., the pair was starting a special effort to
stop overt drug activity at a far southwest Houston apartment
complex. Higgins waited in the truck as Chaison approached the iron
fence where the dealer waited.
</P>
<P>
   Chaison, 45, bought a $20 rock, the size of a Tic-Tac, and
turned to go. The 21-year-old dealer spoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put it in your mouth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chaison was startled. ``What?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not the law, put it in your mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaison paused.
</P>
<P>
   Crack is such a potent drug, a person's hand will go numb in the
spot where it touches the skin. Plus, dealers often hide rocks in
their mouth or anus. Real addicts don't care.
</P>
<P>
   Chaison made an excuse: ``It's for the girl in the truck, man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You the law.''
</P>
<P>
   The dealer pulled his pistol first; both started firing. Chaison
managed to get behind a tree. He glanced over and saw Higgins
calling for help on the radio &UR; . &LR;  When he turned back, the dealer
had disappeared from view. Chaison heard more gunfire, then a thud
_ a sound he instantly recognized after nearly two decades of
police work.
</P>
<P>
   It was the sound of Higgins' body hitting the street.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PROGRESS IS SLOW &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a year later, Higgins, 37, wears a neat little scar where
the bullet entered her neck below her left jaw. The 9 mm bullet
remains lodged next to her spine. She is considered a quadriplegic,
although she has regained some use of her hands and arms.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of a preacher, Higgins lives alone in her own home
_ her parents, who live in nearby Pearland, want her to be able to
make it without them _ but she requires 24-hour nursing. Visits and
calls from friends, co-workers and members of her large family fill
her time.
</P>
<P>
   She just got a dachshund puppy, which she named ``Latin'' after
a close friend on the police force. Twice a week, the puppy's
namesake, Officer O.J. Latin, picks Higgins up from her home and
drives her to The Institute for Rehabilitation and Research in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   After spending two weeks at Ben Taub Hospital immediately after
she was shot, Higgins went to TIRR for two months of inpatient
treatment during which she quickly recovered her sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins tormented her protective mother by pretending to choke
on a pickle, just to listen to her howl for help. On another
occasion, as Higgins' mother prayed, ``Lord, will you move my
daughter's leg?'' Higgins got an aide to move it and said, ``See,
Mom? My leg is moving.''
</P>
<P>
   The former star of undercover narcotics is now an outpatient at
TIRR. During a recent therapy session, she worked with physical
therapist Melisa Bennett to strengthen her arms and shoulders _ the
muscles she must rely on now for all of life's tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it seem easier, or just about as hard (as last time)?''
Bennett asked as Higgins, leaning forward, struggled to push
herself into a sitting-up position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about as hard,'' Higgins said, falling forward with a
groan.
</P>
<P>
   Progress is slow and measured in tiny increments. All this is so
she can return to the work she loves.
</P>
<P>
   She recently got a donated van that can transport her motorized
wheelchair. She's able to feed herself, brush her teeth and write
with the help of a special brace. But she also needs
catheterization every four hours. She is only now learning to keep
her balance sitting on the edge of her bed. She can't open a door
for herself.
</P>
<P>
   Her goal is ``to go back and do my job as a police officer,''
she said. ``I pray for a complete healing ... Until that time
comes, I'm going to continue with what I have.''
</P>
<P>
   In December, Higgins testified against the man who shot her,
finishing the job she started that day outside the apartment
complex. In court, Higgins politely referred to Robert Demond
Lavern as ``that gentleman.'' Lavern never looked at her, staring
at the table in front of him instead. (He was sentenced to 24 years
for aggravated assault of a public servant.)
</P>
<P>
   Chaison was the one who wept at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   He and Higgins had ``gelled'' in the field. It was like a good
marriage. They understood the nuances of each other's gestures and
tones of voice. When one sensed danger, the other caught on right
away. Chaison now rides with another officer who's not as easy to
read. He said he's getting better at interpreting his colleague's
actions, but Chaison still misses some cues.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins, he said, was ``one of the best, with the potential to
be the best.''
</P>
<P>
   The bullet stole other things, too. Chaison, a minister, had
been counseling Higgins and her boyfriend of five years, police
Officer Kenneth Wiltz, in preparation for marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Wiltz has remained at Higgins' side, learning some of the
procedures required for her care, but plans to marry have been
tabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of some issues I need to work out,'' Higgins
explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, I don't want to be anybody's bride being rolled
down the aisle. He may argue that point.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`IT REALLY CLEANED THIS PLACE UP' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The drug activity the undercover police were fighting a year ago
in far west Houston shocked Higgins with its openness. Young men
were dealing during daylight hours near single-family homes, a
Buddhist temple and places where children played.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the problem is nowhere in sight. Flags and balloons fly
in front of the landscaped entrance of The Arbor at Dairy Ashford.
A banner reads ``Come See Our New Look.''
</P>
<P>
   Property manager Gayle Kibble, whose company bought the former
rent-subsidized complex three days before the shooting, credits the
difference to the work done by undercover narcotics officers, HPD's
gang task force and off-duty Houston police officers she hired to
patrol the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally changed,'' said assistant manager Cindy Mata, who
was working the day Higgins was shot. ``It's sad, it was a tragedy,
but it really cleaned this place up.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only one corner in a city full of such places, but
Higgins relished even the small successes. She liked to joke,
``It's really not a bad job _ other than the fact you carry a gun
and could get shot at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   But the humor is a thin cover for the passion she felt for her
vocation. Undercover narcotics work was her calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't miss something until you can't do it, I guess,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss it. I really do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
