<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9017 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-26 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALTER'S VIBURNUM CAN GROW TO 12 TO 15 FEET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Would you please give me some information on Walter's
viburnum? I'm especially interested in the height and spread of
these beautiful spring bloomers.
</P>
<P>
   A: Walter's viburnum (``Viburnum obovata'') is an attractive,
dense shrub good for hedges or to use alone. The foliage is about 1
1/2 inches long, and glossy; the white flowers appear in clusters
about 2 inches across; and blue-black fruit is enjoyed by wildlife.
Mature height is 12 to 15 feet, and I understand the spread is in
the same range. Sun and a well-draining fertile soil are best.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When do I prune my climbing rose? It is an old rose.
</P>
<P>
   A: Prune repeat flowering roses while they are dormant. Prune
climbers that bloom only once a year after they have flowered.
</P>
<P>
   We plan to have more on pruning roses soon. Feb. 14 is the
traditional day to prune roses.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Recently, my corn plant bloomed. I have never seen one of
these flowers before. What do I do with the bloom?
</P>
<P>
   A: Corn plants (``Dracaena'') occasionally flower. Remove the
bloom when it has faded. Your best bet at propagation is air
layering, by removing a crown from a leggy cane and rooting, or by
rooting cane cuttings.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My succulent elephant foot plant has white flowers with
maroon centers and a gray trunk. It is huge, about 7 feet wide now,
and falling over. What is the best way to propagate?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sounds like you have a relative of the Madagascar palm,
``Pachypodium lamerei.'' Plants in this genus often have gray to
brown, spiny trunks and swollen bases. The flowers are followed by
twin-horned seedpods, and you can try propagating by sowing these
seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Q: From what I've seen through the years, one killer for fungus
is chlorine, and a prime source for chlorine is liquid bleach.
Builders and repairmen use bleach on siding and brick to kill
fungus. Bleach in the foot bath in locker rooms keeps down fungus.
So I gave it a shot on brown patch. I put a strong solution of
bleach in my hose-end sprayer and then sprayed the infected areas.
It worked like a charm.
</P>
<P>
   The bleach did not harm the grass. I can't remember, but I may
have added a few drops of liquid dish soap. But if I did, it was
just as a wetting agent. I'm wondering if the same treatment might
work for take-all patch as it, like brown patch, is a fungus.
</P>
<P>
   A: I know bleach is a common disinfectant and used to clean
garden tools to keep from spreading disease from plant to plant.
I've heard of gardeners using a 10 percent bleach solution (1 part
bleach to 9 parts water) as a dip for cuttings taken from a plant
that is showing signs of a disease. And a bleach dip, some believe,
helps prevent damping-off, a fungal disease, in seedling flats when
the soil is drenched with a 2 percent solution (2 1/2 tablespoons
bleach to a gallon of water). You can also just sterilize the flat
with a bleach solution to kill any fungi that would trigger
damping-off, and use a sterilized potting medium.
</P>
<P>
   I do use a diluted bleach solution to clean the outside of our
house, but I am careful to avoid much contact with nearby shrubs.
Bleach, a mix of sodium and calcium hypochlorite, may kill certain
fungi, but it also kills beneficials, as it is not selective.
Chlorine bleach may damage plants, especially if it hits the
foliage. In discussions on using gray water in the garden, some
caution against the use of such recycled water containing chlorine
on plants, especially edibles. I have read where a mixture of
household bleach and horticultural oil is used to combat the fungal
disease fusarium blight on cool-season grasses, but I have yet to
come across documentation _ verbal or written _ of using bleach on
St. Augustine, a warm-season grass. All this means is that while I
can't dispute your experiment, I can't confirm it yet either. Thank
you for writing, however, as your information is certainly
interesting. I would love to hear from anyone who has any knowledge
about bleach as a fungicide.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
