 Tuesday, Jan. 26, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following
stories for Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Susie
McBee or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in
all sluglines.)    (Recasts IMPEACH-WITNESSES skedline)
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-WITNESSES (Washington) _ House prosecutors in President
Clinton's impeachment trial urge the Senate to ask Clinton to give
another deposition, a move the White House immediately rejects. The
prosecutors also want permission to take new depositions from
Monica Lewinsky, Vernon Jordan and former White House aide Sidney
Blumenthal. And they ask the senators to consider sworn statements
from two minor figures in the case and records of phone
conversations between Clinton and Lewinsky. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ Democratic Senate leader Tom
Daschle predicts party-line votes Wednesday when the Senate decides
whether to dismiss the impeachment case against President Clinton
and whether to call witnesses. Daschle warns that the trial will be
delayed if new witnesses are brought in. By STEWART M. POWELL, JUDY
HOLLAND and JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Amazing what turns up in an
impeachment trial. Over and over, the Republican House prosecutors
stressed their deep concern that unless President Clinton is
removed from office, his actions will destroy all respect for civil
rights, equal rights for women and the sex harassment laws. Funny.
Until now, the GOP has had a history of opposing and trying to
weaken such laws. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
</TEXT>
