<HEADER>
A9033 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SAMARANCH-OPINION     01-26 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SAMARANCH-OPINION\ </SLUG>
 SAMARANCH SHOULD RESIGN IF HE CARES  
 Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ On the surface, this looks like a victimless
crime. So what if the International Olympic Committee takes
extravagant freebies from cities bidding to host the next Games?
Who really gets hurt?
</P>
<P>
   The cities that lay out the payola and don't end up with the
five-ring prize? The cities that don't have the resources to commit
world-class bribery? The corporate sponsors who attach their good
names to the Olympics?
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to work up much sympathy for any of them, isn't it?
And what about the athletes? Does back-room dealing really hurt
them? The Olympics are big business now, and they know that. How
can they complain when some of the business flows their way, when
commercialization has widened the stages on which they perform?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Jeff Rouse has no complaints. The Stanford University
graduate went to two Olympics, won three gold medals and a silver
in swimming, captained the 1996 American men's team in Atlanta. He
also was in Barcelona, where rooms in the steamy Olympic Village
lacked air conditioning. Some athletes objected.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was mostly Americans,'' he said. ``Because we're so
spoiled. In Spain, most people don't have air conditioning. It's a
cultural difference. Here, we're used to having it in every house.
... I don't expect to live in luxury when I'm at the Olympic
Village. That would make it too easy, in a way.''
</P>
<P>
   Rouse is not surprised by the bribery scandal. He is not naive.
He knows how the Olympics work, how the world works. He'd accept it
all, if it weren't for one thing. He's still a true believer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've ever seen `Chariots of Fire,' the beauty of that
movie, that's what the Olympics are about to me,'' he said. ``To
me, the IOC members should watch that movie over and over and over
again and then ask themselves if they are living up to the ideals
that movie espouses.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea seems almost corny, doesn't it? Rouse is a thoroughly
modern Olympic champion. He had a deal with Nike. He circulated
petitions to fight performance-enhancing drugs, pushing for more
comprehensive testing. He competed in a totally different arena
from the runners in the 1920 Olympics, the characters in ``Chariots
of Fire.'' But he still believes in the romance of the Games, that
they are more than a conduit to sell Coca-Cola and Big Macs.
</P>
<P>
   The bribery betrays that sentimental vision of the Olympics. In
a few weeks, IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch will convene an
international conference on performance-enhancing drugs. Can we
trust that he will make a sincere effort to combat doping when
covering up drug use is the best way to protect the prestige of his
fiefdom?
</P>
<P>
   Will the conference be just another token gesture, more
public-relations gloss, like this weekend's expulsion of six IOC
members who accepted gifts from bid cities?
</P>
<P>
   If Samaranch meant to clean house thoroughly, he would have
resigned. He should have been willing to give up everything for the
Games. That's what the athletes do.
</P>
<P>
   Rouse is now 28, retired from swimming, and living in
Fredericksburg, Va., his hometown. He is getting a real-estate
license, and he is engaged to be married in August. He serves on
the steering committee for U.S. Swimming, a commitment that runs
through the 2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   He is the perfect athlete representative. He is not rash or
unreasonable. He makes a point of saying that there are worthy,
uncorrupted IOC members. He concedes that a lot of Olympic funds
are used to create athletic facilities. But still, he believes that
the Olympics have been pulled too far away from the athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt that decisions are made based on the bottom
line rather than what's good for the athletes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He offers an example: In 2000, the swimming competition will
expand by two days to add semifinal heats for every event. The
semis were eliminated 20 years ago because they wore the swimmers
out. The meet was too long. But television apparently liked the
extra elimination round, and two more days of swimming meant more
ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no need for it,'' Rouse said. ``Technically, it's not
good for the swimmers.''
</P>
<P>
   The more the Games become divided from the athletes, the more
they will suffer. Bribe-takers on the IOC only widen the gap. Every
dime they take says that the Olympics are about the power-brokers,
not about the true believers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
