<P>
   Sports stories from The New York Times News Service for
 &UR; WEDNESDAY &LR; , Jan. 27:
</P>
<P>
   FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN (Miami) _ Sports of The Times Super Bowl
column on the Denver offensive line, which started off Super Bowl
week with a $1,800 dinner at Joe's Stone Crab, the immensely
popular Miami Beach restaurant where a wait for a table can last as
long as an actual football game. By Dave Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-DENVER (Miami) _ At the heart of the Denver defense is
linebacker Bill Romanowski, an extremely intense player who
sometimes goes over the line, as when he spit at San Franciso 49ers
receiver J.J. Stokes last season in an incident that took on racial
overtones. Romanowski already has three Super Bowl rings (one with
Denver and two with the 49ers) and is now going for a fourth, and
seems to be one of those players who is either loved or hated. By
Gerald Eskenazi.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-ATLANTA (Miami) _ Everyone knows who John Elway is, but what
about the quarterback for the Atlanta Falcons? Chris Chandler has
spent a decade in the NFL, playing for six teams, and only now are
people beginning to appreciate his value. By Mike Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-ATLANTA-VETS (Miami) _ An On Pro Football on two key Atlanta
veterans _ linebacker Jessie Tuggle and defensive back Eugene
Robinson. Tuggle has spent an entire career playing, for the most
part, on lousy Falcons teams. Robinson won a Super Bowl with the
Packers two years ago and arrived in Atlanta at just the right
time. By Thomas George.
</P>
<P>
   Other Super Bowl as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-AFRICA (Lausanne, Switzerland) _ With the bribery scandal
centering on gifts and payments sent to African IOC members,
Africa's sports programs may suffer as a result. By Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   Other Olympics as needed.
</P>
