<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of WEDNESDAY, Jan.
27.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING &LR;  (``d'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NAPA-BRANDY (Undated) _ The Napa Valley is fairly popping with
vineyards. On weekends, it turns into a playpen for yuppies. But
there is one intriguing wine-related activity that remains in its
infancy, little noticed by the thundering herds, in the Napa Valley
or elsewhere in California: distilling. Exactly five tenacious
enterprises in this state are engaged in the exacting business of
producing brandies or eaux-de-vies by traditional Continental
methods. All of them turn out products that can stand comparison
with their counterparts in Europe, where the custom of drinking a
digestif _ a small glass of dry spirits after dinner, perhaps with
a coffee and a cigar _ is far better established than in the United
States. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   MANDOLINE (Undated) _ It appears to be a simple sweet potato
gratin, a tall square stack, browned on top and sagging on the
edges. As you sink your fork into it, though, it reveals layer upon
fine layer, like a piece of puff pastry. Most chefs can dazzle home
cooks with their knife skills, but even they cannot exact such
precision on sweet potatoes and apples unaided. Their secret, the
tool that no chef would live without, is the mandoline. And this
slicing tool is perfectly suited to home cooking. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
