<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Jan. 27:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IMPEACH &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans a 5-page package of stories, including
2 pages of text, on the continuing Senate impeachment trial of
President Clinton and related developments.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RDP (Washington) _ Ledeall: The Senate trial resumes at
noon for four hours, split between White House and prosecutors,
over the issue of calling witnesses; more closed session expected;
votes planned Wednesday on a motion to dismiss and a motion to call
witnesses. By Eric Schmitt and Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ In the chamber: Speeches on
dismissal and witnesses. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ASSESS (Washington) _ Republicans in the Senate juggle
difficult choices for how to move to the next stage of the
proceedings. A news analysis by Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCENE (Washington) _ Scenes from the Hill. By Francis X.
Clines.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   Other impeachment as needed.
</P>
<P>
   HUBBELL-TAXES (Washington) _ Tax evasion charges against Webster
Hubbell, brought by Kenneth Starr and then dismissed, are
reinstated by a federal appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS (Washington) _ Folo on the Supreme Court ruling: Now that
the census is given no choice but to try to count everyone, how
does Census Bureau plan to do it? And what of the continuing
political battle over statistical sampling of the population for
uses other than apportioning House seats?
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE (Washington) _ With the deadline for its final report
just five weeks away, the federal advisory commission debates
proposals for radical changes in Medicare. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHWAY-SAFETY (Washington) _ Public service ads on highway
safety released today take a tough approach, with blood and guts
instead of jocular crash dummy characters, as the Transportation
Department tries harder to raise seatbelt use. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a' code)
</P>
<P>
   POPE-U.S. (St. Louis) _ Pope John Paul II visits St. Louis, is
met by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Related coverage as needed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.S. (Washington) _ More shooting incidents, in north and
south no-fly zones. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ The U.N. Special Commission charged
with disarming Iraq issues what could be its farewell report,
detailing Iraqi efforts to conceal its weapons programs from the
inspectors. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-HUSSEIN (Undated) _ Having anointed a new heir, King
Hussein abruptly flies back to the U.S. for urgent medical
treatment after his doctors concluded that there was reason for
concern that his cancer had not been cured. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   HOLBROOKE (Washington) _ Developments in negotiations between
the U.S. envoy and the Justice Department over accusations of
improper lobbying. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-RESIGN (Johannesburg) _ The head of the South African
election commission resigns. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S. (Moscow) _ Developments in U.S.-Russia talks with
Secretary Albright. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ The World Briefing column.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-RELIGION (Jerusalem) _ The religious councils bill is
approved by Parliament. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EXTREME-WEATHER (Undated) _ January has brought extreme
weather to the U.S.: record snowstorms in Chicago and record rain
in the East. Buffalo had 5 feet of snow, weird even for Buffalo.
More than 100 tornadoes have struck. Extremes in cold include
readings of 35 below in Indiana and 55 below in Maine. Now,
scientists are trying to find out why and are looking at the La
Nina phenomenon. By William K. Stevens. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HAND-SCOTT (Dateline to kum, N.J.) _ A profile of Matthew
David Scott, of Absecon, N.J., the recipient of the first hand
transplant in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Dateline to kum) _ Developments: Fitch downgrades
Brazil's debt, becoming the second agency, following S&AMP;P, to do so.
The currency, the real, continues to slide, drawing no support from
Monday's announcement by the central bank that it was changing a
pair of currency-trading rules in an effort to reduce demand for
dollars on the spot market. At midday, the local currency stood at
1.90 to the dollar, considerably weaker than Monday's late level of
1.79 to the dollar. But shares on the stock exchange were 5.7
percent higher. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Boeing's profit, before a tax
credit, increased 55 percent in the fourth quarter as easing
production bottlenecks and strong sales of military fighters offset
weak margins in the commercial-jet business. The earnings exceeded
expectations by 3 cents a share. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Merck's net income increased 13
percent in the fourth quarter, meeting expectations and aided by
sales of five new drugs, including the asthma medicine Singulair
and the baldness treatment Propecia. Schering-Plough's profit rose
22 percent, lifted by increased sales of the allergy drug Claritin
and the cancer and hepatitis drug Intron. Johnson &AMP; Johnson posts a
10 percent gain before a charge, helped by higher drug sales and
its acquisition of DePuy. American Home Products' profit before
extraordinaries rose 3.2 percent as sales of birth-control pills
and the estrogen drug Premarin offset revenue lost from the
withdrawal of its painkiller Duract. By David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Coca-Cola's net income fell 27 percent
in the fourth quarter as recessions and currency devaluations cut
into results in Latin America, Asia and Eastern Europe. The results
matched analysts' recently lowered expectations. By Constance L.
Hays.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ A second day of
cross-examination of the highest-ranking Microsoft executive to
testify at the antitrust trial. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   LOEHMANNS-SUIT (Undated) _ Forty Three Apparel, a small concern
that makes women's clothing, is suing Loehmann's, the discount
apparel retailer. Forty Three charges that it was pressured to hire
the wife of Loehmann's chairman and that when she subsequently left
to start her own company, she took corporate secrets of Forty Three
Apparel with her. Her new company became a major Loehmann's
supplier, forcing Forty Three into bankruptcy court, the suit
asserts. By Sharon R. King.
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ-ALTAVISTA (Undated) _ Compaq will sell Alta Vista to the
public. Also, shares of Inktomi fall as much as 16 percent because
Microsoft says it will replace the Internet search service as its
primary search technology with Alta Vista's service. By Saul
Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   MCDONALDS-EARNINGS (Chicago) _ McDonald's posts an 8.8 percent
increase in net income for the fourth quarter and says higher sales
in the United States and Europe outweighed reduced demand in Asia
and elsewhere. The company also splits its stock 2 for 1. By David
Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column.
</P>
<P>
   MAZDA-CREDIT (Tokyo) _ Moody's downgrades Mazda to below
investment grade, citing the continued deterioration of the
Japanese car market. The action had been expected, and the auto
maker says it expects little impact on its bottom line. By
Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-MIRROR (London) _ Mirror Group, which publishes the
Daily Mirror and the Sunday Mirror, says its chief executive, David
Montgomery, has resigned, clearing the way for Trinity to renew
takeover talks. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was up 33
points, or 0.4 percent, and the Nasdaq index was up 1.8 percent.
Elsewhere, prices rose 1.2 percent in Tokyo and 0.1 percent in Hong
Kong. They were up 0.2 percent in Frankfurt and down half a percent
in London. Brazil was up 5.7 percent and Mexico was flat. On the
American debt market, the long bond was up 3/32 point, with the
yield at 5.11 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   William Safire's ``Essay.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Herbert is on vacation.
</P>
