<HEADER>
A9075 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-26 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIMAGGIO CAUGHT THIS BOBBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one is immune from making mistakes, but NBC's doozy Sunday
night was made worse when Joe DiMaggio actually was watching at the
time NBC declared that he was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Morris Engelberg, DiMaggio's friend and lawyer, and the Yankee
Hall of Famer were watching a video of ``Gunfight at the OK
Corral'' at DiMaggio's home on Sunday night. They stopped the tape
to watch ``Dateline NBC,'' during which a crawl came on the bottom
of screen, stating, ``This is an NBC News Special Report. Baseball
legend Joe DiMaggio has died at his Florida home. He was 84 years
old and had.'' The crawl then ended abruptly.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 minutes later, NBC ran another crawl, correcting the
earlier one.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassed by the mishap, NBC quickly apologized to DiMaggio. A
network official explained that a technician in the New York
control room mistakenly aired the erroneous report.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio was released last week from Memorial Regional Hospital
in Hollywood, Fla., after spending 99 days in intensive care. He
suffers from lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The NBC error triggered an outpouring of criticism and medical
reports assessing DiMaggio's condition. His doctor, Earl Barron,
faxed a statement to the Associated Press Monday that said, ``He is
progressing nicely since his discharge from Memorial Regional
Hospital one week ago. Over the weekend, his physical therapy has
progressed to the point that he is walking. Reports of his
condition worsening are not true.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio's brother Dom, 82, who lives in Florida, told WBZ's Bob
Lobel in Boston that the erroneous report is another example of
media overzealousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media calls here every 30 minutes to see if my brother has
passed away,'' said Dom DiMaggio, the former Red Sox outfielder.
``I don't know why they continue to call. It causes so much anguish
not only to Joe and his family but also his fans around the world.
It's kind of ghoulish. They must get a medal or something if they
are the first ones to report that Joe has passed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Simpson makes list
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPN has O.J. Simpson ranked 49th on its list of the 100
greatest American athletes of the century, a selection bound to
generate a little criticism, but the choices are based strictly on
field performance.
</P>
<P>
   During a 30-minute profile Friday night, ESPN will mention the
fact that Simpson went on trial, and was acquitted, for the murder
of his wife and her friend, but the show will be about the Juice,
the football player.
</P>
<P>
   But even the panelists who made the selections are conflicted.
</P>
<P>
   Author George Plimpton said, ``It's a shame. I think he was
guilty, and you just can't get that out of your mind. If he were in
prison, actually serving out his term, I think one would begin to
think of him more as a football player. The fact that he's not
paying a penalty always sits up there as a barricade.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland Browns great Jim Brown was more direct.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's try to give some credit where credit is due,'' Brown
said. ``O.J. was a tremendous athlete. This man was a great
sprinter. This man was one of the greatest running backs that ever
lived.''
</P>
<P>
   Former NFL defensive end Deacon Jones echoed Brown's sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gonna take all your cheers back?'' Jones asked. ``Nothing
he did outside the game has anything to do with his contributions
to the sport. Not one iota. Now, if you hate him over here for what
he was accused of, you understand, then hate him over there, but
over here you have to give him his dues.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Measuring up
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Duke's overtime win over St. John's Sunday afternoon pulled a
respectable 3.5 rating in the overnight measure of 44 media
markets. The game received a 2.4 rating and 6 share in Boston . . .
Fox airs the first event in its National Thoroughbred Racing
Association series Saturday. Post time for the Donn Handicap is
4:40 p.m. The hour-long coverage starts at 4 p.m. The last two
Kentucky Derby winners, Silver Charm and Real Quiet, as well as
last year's Belmont winner, Victory Gallop, are competing for a
chance to earn a $5 million bonus . . . CBS opens its PGA Tour
coverage this weekend with the Phoenix Open.
</P>
</TEXT>
