<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CENSURE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR DRAFTS CLINTON CENSURE RESOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHRISTOPHER MATTHEWS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., said Tuesday that
she had drafted a resolution to censure President Clinton for
official misconduct in his intimate relationship with former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal condemns the president both for having the affair
and then concealing it from the nation, his cabinet and other
government officials.
</P>
<P>
   It does not deal with the legal question of perjury or
obstruction of justice _ the basis for the impeachment charges
approved by the House of Representatives _ but instead focuses on
presidential misconduct. The resolution neither clears the
president of criminal behavior nor implicates him.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said she had been given assurances by Senate leaders
that Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., will take up her
resolution following final Senate action on the two articles of
impeachment now being tried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trent Lott has agreed to the introduction of the censure
resolution,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the proposed measure would be considered as a simple
Senate resolution, one that does not require a vote by the House or
the president's signature. It would need a simple majority in the
Senate to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein, who has emerged as a quiet voice of conscience on the
year-long scandal, has been known to be preparing such a censure
resolution but had not made it public.
</P>
<P>
   The draft appeared ready for formal introduction to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein expressed hope that her draft proposal would attract
the support of both liberal and conservative senators as well as
those closer to the political center.
</P>
<P>
   Having Feinstein's name attached to the proposed censure
resolution is expected to carry weight with fellow senators. In the
past, she has publicly expressed her disappointment with the
president. When Clinton made his denial to the country a year ago
about his relations with ``that woman, Ms. Lewinsky,'' Feinstein
was sitting in the same White House meeting room.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., said Tuesday that the chances for
passage of a censure resolution would depend on the timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sooner this ends, the more likely there'd be a censure,''
she said. While attractive as an ``alternative'' to removing the
president from office, she said, a resolution of censure ``loses
its glamour if we get it as an afterthought.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
