<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-1969-NAMATH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DAY JOE NAMATH CHANGED THE FOOTBALL WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They don't make guarantees the way they used to.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it: Joe Namath ruined it for every subsequent athlete
who wanted to make a name with a bold promise or brash prediction.
</P>
<P>
   Because, really, who can ever come along and top the
show-stopping act of Namath? Who could approach the cool of Namath
lounging in front of a swimming pool at a Florida hotel in 1969,
days before the biggest game of his life, seemingly without a scare
in the world? Who could upstage Namath, the way he led a team of
sacrificial American Football League lambs _ known to next-of-kin
as the New York Jets _ into Super Bowl slaughterhouse III?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jets will win on Sunday. I guarantee it.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke those words three nights before the Super Bowl, at a
Miami Touchdown Club banquet honoring him as professional
football's player of the year. With the flourish of John Hancock
putting his name on the Declaration of Independence, Namath put his
signature on the American sporting scene in general and the Super
Bowl in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Talk _ and we do mean talk, which in those days was cheaper than
Jack Benny _ about handing your enemies a chain saw and then
climbing out on a limb. The Jets over the Baltimore Colts? When
pigs wear lipstick, and politicians make good on campaign promises.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts, befitting their status as the pride and joy of the
National Football League, were enjoying favored-franchise status.
The betting line started at 17 points, swelled to 19 and continued
to rise like Miami temperatures in July.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, Namath put his mouth where the betting money was
in a moment of weakness. Namath lost the cool he had been so
careful to put on display for the world to see. He certainly hadn't
bothered to consult first with his teammates, or his coaches, or a
battery of image consultants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks we were being told how we were going to lose the
game,'' Namath said. ``I don't care whether you're at the lower end
of Beaver Falls, Pennsylvania, or you're with the New York Jets.
When you keep hearing your team isn't going to win, you get angry
and frustrated. The anger festers. Anger is a good thing to have
when you're playing some sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Jets had plenty of anger. They were angry at being
taken more lightly than a blonde at a MENSA convention. They were
angry at their quarterback for taking the chance of awakening a
slumbering giant of a 15-1 team. They undoubtedly would have been
angry to know that three decades would pass without them getting to
the Super Bowl again.
</P>
<P>
   Jets coach Weeb Ewbank pulled Namath aside and asked, in effect,
``ARE YOU CRAZY?''
</P>
<P>
   Namath puts tackle Dave Herman in the category of Jets who
``wanted to choke me.'' Herman had the assignment of handling Bubba
Smith, the Colts' fire-breathing, quarterback-eating defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two or three times in the meetings during the week leading up
to it, it was expressed in there that, `You might want to shut this
off; we could get overconfident watching this,''' Herman said.
``But that was conversation inside the four walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then Joe went out and said quite innocently, `I guarantee
we're going to win.' I went up and said, `I've got a guy 6-8, 320
pounds. We don't need to excite him any more than he's going to
be.'''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the Colts took Namath and the Jets about as
seriously as a teen-ager takes a talk about the birds and the bees.
``All we did was laugh,'' Colts Hall-of-Fame tight end John Mackey
said. ``We thought it was a joke. And that was the problem. We had
the wrong attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colts considered themselves the substantive alternative to
Namath's style. Namath had the $400,000 contract and the white
cleats and the East Side penthouse with the llama rug. He liked
long-legged women and longer nights out on the town. He was the
leader of a new breed of athlete, and the establishment wasn't
ready to embrace him as a change for the better. Still, athletes
who prided themselves for being square enough to be divisible by
four soon found themselves on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy sex as much as Joe Namath,'' straight-arrow Roger
Staubach once said, in a sound-bite Hall of Fame moment. ``Only I
do it with one girl.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colts, for their part, had two quarterbacks who wore
crewcuts and black high tops. Their Hall-of-Fame-bound quarterback,
John Unitas, shredded his right elbow in the final game of the 1968
preseason. Coach Don Shula simply plugged in journeyman Earl
Morrall, who lit up opposing defenses for an NFL-leading 26
touchdown passes.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Colts were so overwhelming, they could make a league
Most Valuable Player out of a backup They sure weren't about to
worry themselves about a cocky 25-year-old quarterback with a mouth
big enough to stuff two feet into.
</P>
<P>
   Colts owner Carroll Rosenbloom arranged for the players'
families to make the trip to Miami. Super Bowl week had the feel of
a working vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the biggest mistake was that we believed we were a
19-point favorite,'' Mackey said. ``We just believed all we had to
do was show up. We had announced the victory party the Wednesday
before and cut up the winners' share at the pre-game meal. Now, can
you believe that?''
</P>
<P>
   Believe this: Morrall took the Colts on six first-half drives in
Super Bowl III. Two ended with missed field goals. Three ended with
interceptions inside the Jets' 15 yard-line. None ended with
points.
</P>
<P>
   The play that has the Colts and their fans shaking their heads
to this day came in the final minute of the half. With the score
7-0, Jets, and the ball on the Jets' 41, receiver Jimmy Orr got
wide open in the end zone on a flea-flicker. For some reason,
Morrall never spotted Orr. Safety Jim Hudson picked off a pass over
the middle intended for Jerry Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The desperation of a 13-0 deficit called for the measure of
Shula bringing a rusty, limp-armed Unitas into the game. Less than
four minutes of the third quarter remained. The score was 16-0
before Unitas got around to taking the Colts into the end zone.
Less than four minutes of the fourth quarter remained. The Colts
recovered an onside kick and drove inside the Jets' 20. The Jets'
defense held up one last time.
</P>
<P>
   It ended Jets 16, Colts 7. A crowd of 75,377 paid $12 a ticket
to see the game that announcer Curt Gowdy calls ``the most
financially important game that has ever been done in this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Namath foiled the Colts' blitz all day, completing 17-of-28
passes for 206 yards. Matt Snell ran through the Colts for 121
yards and scored the only Jets' touchdown. The Jets forced five
turnovers and didn't bother throwing a pass the entire fourth
quarter. Just like that, the AFL had credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``That changed the whole thinking of the sportsman's mind,''
said Gowdy, who did the Super Bowl III play-by-play for NBC. ``Most
guys were, `Ah, that AFL, who are they?' Like the AFL players came
from upper Slobovia and the NFL players came from the colleges. You
couldn't tell 'em the AFL was getting better every year until the
Jets beat Baltimore. The next year, Kansas City beat Minnesota
soundly (23-7 in Super Bowl IV). Suddenly, everybody was, `Hey,
it's all over now. The AFL is as good as the NFL.'''
</P>
<P>
   They don't make guarantees the way they used to. They can't. Joe
Namath guaranteed the impossible and delivered.
</P>
</TEXT>
