<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTATOES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMASHED, NOT MASHED, POTATOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MOLLY O'NEILL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Smashed potatoes, as opposed to mashed potatoes, could almost be
called a natural phenomenon. They appear to be hand-hewed and
unprocessed, seemingly at odds with a technological age. Yet,
smashed potatoes can also be viewed as a victory of the pro-lumpers
over the anti-lumpers, a triumph of the slap-dash over the careful.
</P>
<P>
   Smashing _ roughly mushing a baked or boiled potato with a fork
or wire masher _ reverses this country's 200-year trajectory toward
fluffy, creamy potatoes. Smashing generally leaves potato skin,
flakes and lumps intact and deploys olive oil or cooking juices as
often as it does butter or cream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, you give the potato a good kick in the pants and
send it to the plate,'' said Peter Hoffman, the chef and owner of
Savoy restaurant in Manhattan. The results? An innocent,
warts-and-all potato, nothing gussied up or airbrushed.
</P>
<P>
   Chefs like Hoffman like it that way, and they are not alone.
Smashed potatoes are chic and are appearing in some of the best
restaurants in town _ and in some of the finest homes.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Guarnaschelli, the editor of the 1997 revision of ``Joy of
Cooking,'' said the rising popularity of the smashed potato fits
the natural, unprocessed, healthy, low-fat style of eating in
America today. For the first time in its 65-year run, the current
edition of ``Joy'' contains a recipe for smashed potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   The starchy Idaho, Russet Burbank or large Yukon Gold potato are
great in mashed and smashed potatoes alike, but smashing allows the
use of waxier varieties like the tiny fingerling and also heirloom
varieties, which become gluey when subjected to a ricer or
hand-held mixer.
</P>
<P>
   Baking most varieties is the simplest way to get a good texture
and a toasty flavor. The fingerlings or heirloom varieties can be
baked, boiled or steamed in their skins.
</P>
<P>
   While a simple fork or the side of a heavy knife can smash
potatoes nicely, a beloved tool in professional kitchens is a thick
serpentine-shaped mashing wire with a heavy-gauge stainless steel
handle. This smasher, which looks like the hand mashers that were
popular in the early part of this century, is a perfectly balanced
tool that allows the cook to retain lumps or banish them as the
mood fits.
</P>
<P>
   Made by Best Manufacturers in Portland, Ore., it comes in 8-,
10- and 11-inch sizes; Broadway Panhandler (477 Broome Street, near
Wooster Street) has them for $6.95, $9.95 and $14.95. Dean &AMP; DeLuca
(560 Broadway, at Prince Street) has the 8-inch size for $7.50 and
the 11-inch for $15.
</P>
<P>
   But the story of smashed potatoes is not merely one of technique
and technology. How a given era treats its potatoes always reveals
current culinary ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   In charting the potato's progress in America, steadily rising
levels of butter, milk and cream separate the mashed from the
whipped, the creamed from the pureed. Technological innovation also
seems to point to ``fluffy'' as manifest destiny, said Karen Hess,
a scholar of Early American cookbooks and, with her husband, John,
the author of ``The Taste of America,'' (University of South
Carolina Press, 1989).
</P>
<P>
   The smooth, rich form reached its peak with the invention of the
hand-held electric mixer. A pamphlet issued by the Sunbeam-Oster
Co. in 1933 depicts mounds of whipped potatoes that look like
cumulus clouds. Whipped potatoes were also highest on the richness
scale, containing up to three tablespoons of milk or cream and one
tablespoon of butter per potato.
</P>
<P>
   Directly beneath whipped potatoes, creamed potatoes contain
three-quarters of a cup of milk and one tablespoon of butter per
potato. Mashed potatoes contain one tablespoon of cream and
one-half tablespoon of butter per potato.
</P>
<P>
   Smashed potatoes initially appear to be less decadent. They have
a lot of texture, and for this reason chefs tend to pair smashed
potatoes with rich meat dishes, while reserving the unctuous mashed
or whipped potato for seafood and more delicate meats.
</P>
<P>
   But the spare and humble versions served at the Union Square
Cafe and Le Bernardin are already giving way to more luxurious
forms. At Gramercy Tavern, Tom Colicchio smashes potatoes with
everything from foie gras to cod. Terrance Brennan at Picholine
serves a smashed potato with copious amounts of truffle butter,
topped with shaved truffle.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, no sooner does ``smashed'' become a code word
for ``healthy, pure and lean'' than the dish starts getting bigger,
richer and more expensive. The conceit is humble; the price tag is
another story. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SMASHED POTATOES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Peter Hoffman, Savoy &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces fingerling, Russian Banana or other waxy,
rich-flavored potatoes, washed
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Chopped fresh herbs (optional). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Place the potatoes in a large pot, and add enough cool water
to cover by one inch. Add 1 teaspoon of salt for each quart of
water. Cover, bring to a boil, and cook until tender when pierced
with a knife tip, 20 to 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Drain the potatoes, and remove them from the pot. Cool
slightly, about 5 minutes. On a flat work surface, whack each
potato once or twice with the flat- side of a large knife or the
back of a plate; the potatoes should pretty much retain their
original shape. Divide potatoes among four plates, and top with
butter, salt, and if desired, a few grinds of pepper and, if
desired, herbs. Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRUFFLED SMASHED POTATOES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Terrance Brennan, Picholine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces fingerling potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons finely chopped black truffle, plus 12 paper-thin
slices (about 2{ ounces in all)
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons unsalted butter, room temperature, cut into pieces
</P>
<P>
   Coarse sea salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat the oven to 375 degrees. Toss the fingerlings with
olive oil, place them on a baking sheet, and bake until they can be
easily pierced with a fork, about 22 minutes. Remove from the oven,
and cool.
</P>
<P>
   2. When the potatoes are cool enough to handle, remove the skins
with a paring knife. Transfer the potatoes to a bowl, and add the
chopped truffle and butter. Roughly crush the potatoes, using a
serpentine-style masher. Switch to a fork or a slotted spoon, and
continue to smash and fluff the potatoes until the butter and
chopped truffle are all incorporated, but they should retain a
rough texture. Add salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   3. Divide the potatoes among four plates, garnish with three
truffle slices each, and serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
