<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9163 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      01-26 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING THE HEAT LOW FOR POACHED FISH FILLETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thin fish fillets can be tricky, mostly because they fall apart
the instant they're overcooked. But the fact that
quarter-inch-thick fillets of flounder, sole and other flatfish
take so little time to cook can be turned to your advantage.
</P>
<P>
   By poaching them in barely hot liquid, you slow the process and
gain control. By flavoring the liquid first with a quick-cooking
aromatic vegetable, you create a comforting, warming dish that
needs only bread or rice to become a meal. By contrast to what
happens with broiling or sauteing, the fish never dries out.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional liquid for poaching fish is court-bouillon, a
stock made from scratch using fish bones, onions, carrots and
celery and enhanced with white wine and herbs. Assuming you don't
have any on hand _ and who does? _ the poaching liquid of choice is
chicken stock.
</P>
<P>
   The usually insipid canned variety is fine, because you're going
to add flavor to it, and quickly.
</P>
<P>
   This recipe requires 15 minutes or less from start to finish.
While the stock comes to a boil and reduces by about half, you
clean and chop some leeks, adding them to the liquid as they're
ready. A couple of minutes later, you season the broth and add the
fillets.
</P>
<P>
   The subsequent cooking time depends largely on your equipment.
If you have an electric stove, you can simply turn the heat off;
the element will remain warm enough to cook the fish. You may need
a low flame with a gas stove, but it should be the minimum. A
heavy-duty pan may retain enough heat to make even that
unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Poaching fish with this method presents dozens of options, all
of which are as simple as changing the seasonings. You can use
other aromatic vegetables, like shallots, onions, scallions,
garlic, carrots and celery, alone or in combination. (Cut carrots
into small pieces so they'll cook quickly.) Or try herbs,
especially parsley, chervil or dill, and spices, alone or in
combination.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a North African-style combination of a few
coriander seeds, a small piece of cinnamon and a little cumin is
easily assembled and appealing.
</P>
<P>
   You can also use this technique for thicker fillets, like red
snapper, sea bass or cod.
</P>
<P>
   After you cover the skillet, keep the heat on low and, after
about six minutes, check the fish every minute. When the tip of a
thin-blade knife inserted into the fish encounters no resistance,
the fish is done. If it begins to flake, it's overdone _ but only
slightly, and it will still be juicy. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FISH POACHED IN BROTH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 2 cups chicken stock (or 1 can containing 14 or 15 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   3 1-inch-thick leeks
</P>
<P>
   Coarse salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds flounder or other thin fillets. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Place the stock in a large skillet that can be covered, and
turn the heat to high. Let the stock boil and reduce by about half
while you prepare the leeks. Trim off leek roots and green ends;
cut the white part in half the long way, and rinse thoroughly. Chop
each half into semicircles [ to \ inch thick, adding them to the
boiling broth as you cut them.
</P>
<P>
   2. When all the leeks are added, cook a minute longer. Add salt
and pepper to taste, and stir; then add the fish. Cover, and turn
off the heat, or keep the heat at an absolute minimum. Uncover and
check the fish after 3 minutes; it is done when the tip of a
thin-blade knife inserted into the flesh encounters no resistance.
Continue to check every minute until the fish is done.
</P>
<P>
   3. Serve the fish with the leeks and some broth spooned over it;
top all with a sprinkling of coarse salt.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
