<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9183 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OTTER-OPERA-ART-NYT &LR;      01-26 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OTTER-OPERA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN A LACONIC, TALL, BLONDE SWEDE PLAY CARMEN? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Anne Sofie von Otter is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (HLW)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the Swedish mezzo-soprano Anne Sofie von Otter
was a young girl, she knew nothing about classical music and cared
less. ``I couldn't tell the difference between Bach and Mahler,''
Ms. von Otter said recently.
</P>
<P>
   She took the obligatory piano lessons that children from
comfortable homes are usually subjected to: her father was a
diplomat. But the music that spoke to her was pop and rock, the
Beatles, most of all, but also Cat Stevens, Judy Collins and
Crosby, Stills and Nash. It was ``the nice tidy'' pop, she
explained. ``The Rolling Stones were not for me.'' Later, a friend
introduced her to fusion jazz, which she thought very daring at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   She loved ballet, however, especially the Tchaikovsky ballets
she attended in Stockholm, her birthplace, and London, where her
father was the Swedish consul-general for five years during her
childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ardently wanted to a be a ballerina,'' she said. ``I took
dance classes and had dreams. I was terribly disappointed when I
realized that I could not do it.'' She wasn't drawn into singing
until her last two years of high school in Sweden, when a dashing
music teacher took over the chorus, and she just had to join up.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ms. von Otter's story of coming late to singing is not
uncommon, it is striking given her probing intelligence and
sensitive musicianship, qualities usually associated with singers
who have trained seriously from an early age. She clearly made up
for lost time, attending Stockholm Conservatory and later spending
a year at the Guildhall School of Music and Drama in London. But by
starting late, she at least did not prematurely push her naturally
warm, dusky-toned lyric voice.
</P>
<P>
   Now 43, she would seem to be at her peak, a compelling artist
who brings a wide range of colors and nuanced shadings to her
interpretations and who likes to explore unusual repertory. The
series she has been presenting at Alice Tully Hall with the Chamber
Music Society of Lincoln Center, a mix of songs with piano, songs
with instrumental accompaniment and chamber works, is typical of
repertory forays.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday's concert was devoted to music of Erich Wolfgang
Korngold, the Austrian composer, born in 1897, who jettisoned his
early modernism as he developed, eventually becoming an
award-winning composer of Hollywood film scores. On Sunday, the
program focused on French music, including Faure's sublime ``La
Bonne Chanson.'' Wednesday night's program presents mostly music
from Scandinavia, including a seldom-heard song cycle by Grieg,
``Haugtussa,'' plus songs by Swedish composers and by Sibelius, a
Finn.
</P>
<P>
   Through her perseverance and artistry, Ms. von Otter has won a
loyal following among song enthusiasts. She is also a sought-after
singer of the orchestral song repertory. But she has not had
equivalent opportunities in opera, she said. ``I'm not known as an
opera singer, an opera star,'' she said. ``I wish my repertory were
larger. But there is so little to choose from that is right for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. von Otter is being somewhat modest in describing her
repertory as limited. She has sung many roles memorably, including
Mozart's Cherubino, Dorabella and Sesto, Strauss' Octavian (one of
her notable achievements), as well as roles in works by Monteverdi,
Gluck, Handel and other Baroque composers.
</P>
<P>
   And although on one occasion she sang Rossini's ``Cenerentola,''
Cecilia Bartoli's signature role, Ms. von Otter has not been part
of the current bel canto boomlet, driven, it would seem, by a whole
contingent of mezzo-sopranos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rossini is not for me,'' she said. ``I can enjoy a Rossini
opera. But to stand there in my room, with a Rossini score in front
of me, with all those notes, and have to learn it: it doesn't do
anything for me.'' And, she added, there are other mezzos, like Ms.
Bartoli and Jennifer Larmore, who have the alchemy to turn those
Rossinian roulades into something exciting. So why should she
compete?
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ms. von Otter is considering one touchstone role for which
there is ample competition: Bizet's Carmen. She has sung the role
once in concert but not yet on the opera stage. ``I'm not an
obvious Carmen,'' she said. Carmen is a hot-blooded, willful
Spanish gypsy. Ms. von Otter is a laconic, 6-foot-tall, wholesomely
attractive blonde Scandinavian. ``I would have to be costumed
right,'' she added wryly.
</P>
<P>
   When she tried the role in concert, she wanted her portrayal to
be as far removed from the standard hip-swiveling, seductive
routine as possible. ``But you end up doing it anyway,'' she said,
shimmying a little bit in her chair. ``You can't help it. It's in
the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Ms. von Otter's repertory adventures have been suggested
to her by a longtime collaborator, the pianist Bengt Forsberg, the
artistic adviser for Ms. von Otter's current series with the
Chamber Music Society. ``We are real partners,'' she said of
Forsberg. ``I never say to Bengt, `This is what we are doing, go
home and learn it.' We spend hours reading through music,
suggesting things to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Forsberg is responsible for engaging Ms. von Otter's interest in
Korngold. The latest of their Deutsche Grammophon recordings is a
two-disk program of that composer's songs and chamber works. They
are both eager to talk about why Korngold has been so overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``There he was, a composer born over 25 years after
Schoenberg,'' Forsberg said. ``Yet the music sounds so Romantic,
lush and extravagant. But if you listen carefully, there is
dissonance, fantastic harmonies, a constant ebb and flow.'' And, he
added, Ms. von Otter sings it ideally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Korngold takes great technical finesse,'' Ms. von Otter
explained, ``but also great heart, and lots of schmaltz.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. von Otter's schmaltz is kept from being smothering by her
cool-headedness. Is this a stereotypical Swedish trait?
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think we Swedes are slightly more reserved,'' she said.
``There is great passion in us, but not on the surface, as with the
South Europeans. You have to look a little more to see the passion.
We show less.''
</P>
<P>
   In a field crowded with emotive prima donnas, Ms. von Otter's
self-containment is refreshing. She saves her passion for her music
making, and saves herself for her personal life, especially her
family: her husband, Benny Fredriksson, a theater director, and her
two sons, 10 and 7.
</P>
<P>
   This is one reason she has been largely absent from the opera
company in her hometown, the Royal Opera in Stockholm. After some
performances there as Octavian in 1988, she did not sing with the
company again until last year, when she participated in the
premiere of a new opera by a Swedish composer, Sven David
Sandstrom.
</P>
<P>
   She sings recitals in Sweden, and performs with the chamber
ensemble run by Forsberg. But ``when I'm home, I like to be home,
to be able to put my children to bed,'' she said. ``If I am not
singing in the evening, I never work past 4 p.m. I try be away from
Sweden no more than six months per year.''
</P>
<P>
   She gives some 50 performances a year. She could easily accept
twice that number of bookings if she wanted to. She doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``When young singers ask me for advice, I say: `Don't accept
everything. Spend time at home. Keep your friends.' Or, as you say
in American, `Get a life!'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
