<HEADLINE>
FOOD NOTES AND NEWS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Salted Soybean Pods Seek a Niche in the Home &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Edamame, salted soybeans that are the equivalent of cocktail
peanuts in Asian restaurants, will soon be moving into home
kitchens. Karan Hall, a spokeswoman for one importer, Seaside Farms
of Inglewood, Calif., says the demand for the fresh soybeans has
risen fivefold nationally in the last six months.
</P>
<P>
   Nobu Next Door, Mirezi, Bop and other restaurants serve the
snack warm with drinks. Edamame, fresh soybeans that are boiled and
salted, are bright green and slightly fuzzy pods that should be
popped open; each contains about three plump, slightly sweet
legume-like seeds.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Help for Fish Bones &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Fish bones are embarrassing to the cook and risky to the diner,
but now there is a cute gadget to help. Boneless Fish is basically
a bright plastic tweezer in the shape of a fish about four inches
long. Press the fins, and the mouth closes to seize a bone to be
pulled out. It will work on sauteed trout, smoked whitefish and
even on the annoying pin bones in fillets of raw salmon that are
supposed to be boneless.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dulce de Leche, Israeli Style &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Dulce de leche is the Hispanic milk caramel that enjoys
well-deserved mainstream popularity _ witness the skyrocketing
sales of Haagen-Dazs' dulce de leche ice cream. In Mexico it is
often called cajeta and may be made with goat's milk. Now, in an
odd example of culinary cross-pollination, a company in Israel is
producing and selling jars of creamy dulce de leche to spoon over
ice cream or to use as a cake filling. What's next? Mexican
falafel?
</P>
</TEXT>
