<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE OF THE WEEK  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Brajkovich Signature Series Kumeu River Chardonnay 1997, New
Zealand. About $15. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This is the least expensive of the Kumeu River chardonnays,
which makes it the ideal vehicle for getting acquainted with
chardonnays from New Zealand. At their best they are the antithesis
of the California style, which is big-bodied with lots of extract,
fruit and wood, not necessarily in that order. As befits their
chillier, maritime climate, the New Zealand chardonnays are no less
intense, but are often leaner bodied and a bit sharper on the
palate.
</P>
<P>
   This wine was made from purchased grapes grown in Kumeu, in the
Auckland region. The grapes were hand harvested rather than machine
picked and were fermented in oak barrels rather than in stainless
steel. The wine was bottled in December 1997 and has six months
more aging than a typical American chardonnay because of the
reversed seasons in the Southern Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   If you like this Kumeu chardonnay, you will love the winery's
estate-bottled Mate's Vineyard Chardonnay, named for Mate
Brajkovich, who founded Kumeu River in 1944. It is about $40.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
