<HEADER>
A9196 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-POPE-0127-COX     01-26 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POPE-0127-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POPE'S MESSAGE IN MEXICO COULD HAVE RADICAL EFFECT ON CLERGY
SERVING POOR
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ He was supremely diplomatic and didn't publicly
refer once to the conflict between Zapatista Indian rebels and the
Mexican government.
</P>
<P>
   But Pope John Paul II's visit to Mexico -- where he denounced
widening economic inequality in the Americas -- could have a
radical effect on Mexican and Latin American clergy, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the pope left Mexico Tuesday morning, some clergy
were already rejoicing over homilies the Catholic leader had
delivered. The pope was in Mexico to outline the Vatican's vision
for the church in this hemisphere at the dawn of a new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be off the wall to think that the pope would come
here and talk about the Zapatista National Liberation Army. But
it's another thing for him to talk about just causes in the
universal sense,'' said Bishop Samuel Ruiz, speaking to Mexican
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz is a controversial figure in Mexico who presides over a
diocese in Chiapas state, where the Zapatista rebels are based.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz, excited about the pope's exhortation to protect the poor,
held a press conference in Mexico City on Monday, the day before
the pope departed for St. Louis, Mo., to meet with U.S. President
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Ruiz has faced criticism from Catholic hierarchy
for his impassioned attacks on the Mexican government, which he
accuses of violating the rights of impoverished Indians.
</P>
<P>
   But the pope's speeches -- although mostly of a spiritual flavor
-- may benefit Ruiz and other like-minded clergy in Latin America,
said Oscar Aguilar, a Mexico City political consultant who has
studied the Catholic church.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope's condemnation of poverty will help priests like
Ruiz,'' Aguilar said. ``But if you read the church documents on the
Americas (that were released in Mexico) you see that he also warns
them not to exclude anyone from the church.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope,'' Aguilar added, ``is very careful not to align
himself with any one side.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Dolores Villagomez of Mexico City's Center for Ecumenical
Studies said the pope's messages were filled with enough spiritual
content to satisfy those who believe the church should stay out of
political life.
</P>
<P>
   But she agreed that some Catholics will feel they have the
pope's blessing to challenge government policies that are unjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that more priests will become involved in politics,''
Villagomez said. ``It's that priests will be encouraging lay people
to become involved in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it is losing members, the Catholic church remains a
powerful influence in Latin America, where most of the world's
Catholics live.
</P>
<P>
   The region also suffers from the biggest gap between rich and
poor on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the pope has become more outspoken about
inequality.
</P>
<P>
   During his five-day visit in Mexico the pontiff repeatedly
lashed out at new ``neo-liberal'' or free-market reforms that have
taken hold in Latin America and, he said, made some people poorer.
</P>
<P>
   While the pope avoided mentioning the Indian rebels in Chiapas,
he repeatedly expressed sympathy for Latin America's Indian
population.
</P>
<P>
   During the pope's visit, Mexicans were also surprised at the
tough speeches delivered by Cardinal Norberto Rivera of Mexico
City, who has a reputation for being conservative.
</P>
<P>
   At one public event, Rivera told the pope Mexico ``had been
deceived and invaded by poverty,'' words that made banner headlines
in newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were strong words because they came from him, not from
some union leader,'' said Aguilar.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
