<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Wednesday, Jan. 27. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IMPEACH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RDP (Washington) _ Ledeall: The Senate trial resumes at
noon for four hours, split between White House and prosecutors,
over the issue of calling witnesses; more closed session expected;
votes planned Wednesday on a motion to dismiss and a motion to call
witnesses. By Eric Schmitt and Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ In the chamber: In a surprise move,
House prosecutors asked the Senate today to ``request the
appearance'' of President Clinton at a deposition for his
impeachment trial. They also sought subpoenas to question Monica
Lewinsky, presidential friend Vernon Jordan and White House aide
Sidney Blumenthal. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ASSESS (Washington) _ Republicans in the Senate juggle
difficult choices for how to move to the next stage of the
proceedings. A news analysis by Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   HUBBELL-TAXES (Washington) _ Tax evasion charges against Webster
Hubbell, brought by Kenneth Starr and then dismissed, are
reinstated by a federal appeals court. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL  &LR;  (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   POPE-U.S. (St. Louis) _ Pope John Paul II visits St. Louis, is
met by President Clinton. By Alessandra Stanley. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-PILLS (Boston) _ The world of school nurses has changed
greatly. Nowadays, they strive to juggle the traditional triage of
sick-feeling students with a host of growing demands: handle drugs
for Attention Deficit Disorder and increasingly common asthma
inhalers; help medically fragile students with catheters or tube
feedings; teach children to wash their hands frequently or persuade
teenagers to quit smoking and consider celibacy; and much, much
more. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK REGION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DEBT (Albany) _ Gov. George E. Pataki said that for the next
five years, New York State should use 75 percent of its share of
the national tobacco lawsuit settlement, or $1.5 billion, to reduce
state debt, turning aside calls by health care advocates and
medical industries to use most of the money for health care. By
Richard Perez-Pena.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EXTREME-WEATHER (Undated) _ January has brought extreme
weather to the U.S.: record snowstorms in Chicago and record rain
in the East. Buffalo had 5 feet of snow, weird even for Buffalo.
More than 100 tornadoes have struck. Extremes in cold include
readings of 35 below in Indiana and 55 below in Maine. Now,
scientists are trying to find out why and are looking at the La
Nina phenomenon. By William K. Stevens. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL  &LR;  (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ The U.N. Special Commission charged
with disarming Iraq issues what could be its farewell report,
detailing Iraqi efforts to conceal its weapons programs from the
inspectors. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS  &LR;  (will move in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-AGENTS (Toronto) _ The unfolding international scandal
involving the selection of Olympic sites has focused attention on
middlemen who have promoted one city over another. To some people,
they are ``agents''. To others they are legitimate lobbyists, paid
consultants who use contacts and expertise to advise and assist
competing cities on how best to make their cases. By Raymond
Bonner.
</P>
