<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUPERBOWL-FOOD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TACKLING THESE BOWLS WILL SCORE SOUPER POINTS  
 (ADV: STORY INCLUDES TWO RECIPES) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Don't let a bad pun stop you from considering our
suggestion: Throw a Souper Bowl Party on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It's just familiar enough, and just different enough, that your
friends will love it. Last year, we invited a few people to bring
their favorite soups over and watch the game. Surprise! The game
was a really good one, and the soups were even better. Everybody
had a great time.
</P>
<P>
   For one of the most casual entertaining occasions on the year's
social calendar, you can't go wrong with soup. Consider it a
variant on the perennial favorite Super Bowl guy food, chili.
</P>
<P>
   Invite people to bring a soup, and let them know that it doesn't
need to be a huge amount, either, because if everybody brings
something, you'll have loads. Get a lot of sturdy plastic bowls and
spoons (disposable but recyclable), so everybody can have a fresh
bowl and spoon when they try a different soup.
</P>
<P>
   Hit the bakery for a bread assortment, make a batch of cornbread
and spread out some cheese and crackers.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to get really fancy, put out a variety of soup
condiments and let guests add their own embellishments: croutons,
oyster crackers, lemon or lime wedges, salsa, a bottle of hot
sauce, bacon bits, chopped chives, you name it.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Broncos Black Bean Chili recipe is the one we served
last year, to great acclaim. It's simple, it's vegetarian if you
want it to be, low in fat and high in fiber, and you can put it in
a slow cooker. The Broncos are back in the Big One, and so is our
recipe. Chopped green onions, salsa and cheese are great add-ons.
</P>
<P>
   In perfect creamy counterpoint is Shrimp and Corn Chowder, which
is from James Villas' ``My Mother's Southern Kitchen.'' It is rich,
and because it's from the Georgia and Carolina Low Country, makes
abundant use of fresh shrimp. If you don't have a freezer full, try
cutting the shrimp amount in half. (And if you don't have bacon
grease _ another Southern staple _ use any kind of oil.) Be careful
not to overheat the soup or let it do more than just come to a boil
at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the food! section we have sprinkled other soups for
your consideration. Tortilla Soup is always a favorite. You can
suggest these recipes to your guests, or ask them to bring their
own favorite soup.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be super. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Denver Broncos Black Bean Chili
</P>
<P>
   (From Kim MacEachern and Judy Walker)
</P>
<P>
   2 cans (15 ounces each) black beans
</P>
<P>
   2 cups pureed tomatoes (canned, or fresh ones pureed in the
blender or food processor)
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 cups chicken broth, water or vegetable broth
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Optional garnishes:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Your favorite salsa
</P>
<P>
   Chopped green onions
</P>
<P>
   Grated cheddar or longhorn cheese
</P>
<P>
   Combine beans with all ingredients except salt, pepper and
garnishes. Cover and simmer for 30 minutes to 1 hour or for up to 8
hours in a slow-cooker. Season to taste. Serve with salsa, chopped
onions and grated cheese, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about seven 8-ounce servings.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving without garnishes: 455 calories,
3 g fat, 1 mg cholesterol, 80 g carbohydrates, 20 g fiber, 30 g
protein, 696 mg sodium, 6 percent calories from fat. (Note: sodium
values will be much lower if using homemade chicken or vegetable
broth, or water.)
</P>
<P>
   Shrimp and Corn Chowder
</P>
<P>
   (From ``My Mother's Southern Kitchen'' )
</P>
<P>
   6 cups strong fresh chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds fresh shrimp, shelled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons bacon grease
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   1 medium-size onion, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 celery ribs, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 large green bell pepper, seeded and minced
</P>
<P>
   8 ears fresh corn (about 4 cups kernels)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons arrowroot dissolved in 1 cup cold milk
</P>
<P>
   Salt and black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Tabasco sauce to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   2 carrots, scraped and sliced paper thin
</P>
<P>
   1/2 red bell pepper, seeded and cut into small dice
</P>
<P>
   4 slices bacon, fried crisp and crumbled
</P>
<P>
   Bring half the chicken stock to a boil in a large, heavy
saucepan, add the shrimp, return to a boil, remove from the heat,
and let stand 3 minutes. Reserve 24 or more shrimp, place the
remainder in a blender with the remaining cold stock and process,
till almost pureed, then add the liquefied shrimp to the hot stock.
</P>
<P>
   In a skillet, heat the bacon grease and butter, add the onion,
celery and green pepper, and cook over low heat about 3 minutes,
stirring. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Slit the corn kernels by running the tip of a sharp knife down
each row of kernels. With the back of the knife, scrape the pulp
and juice into a bowl. Add the corn pulp and juice to the shrimp
mixture, and cook over moderate heat 1 minute, stirring. Add the
cooked vegetables and arrowroot mixture, stir, bring to a brisk
boil, and cook 2 minutes. Remove from the heat, add the salt,
pepper and Tabasco, cover and let stand 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to serve, bring the chowder to a boil, add the cream,
carrots and red pepper, and stir well. Do not let it continue to
boil. Pour into wide soup bowls and add 4 to 6 shrimp that were
reserved plus a sprinkling of crumbled bacon to each portion.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 851 calories, 37 g fat, 528 mg
cholesterol, 32 g carbohydrates, 3.8 mg fiber, 95 g protein, 724 mg
sodium, 40 percent calories from fat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
