<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      01-26 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WORTHY RHONE NEIGHBOR FOR HERMITAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's an American story, actually. A fellow becomes disillusioned
with the corporate grind and decides to change his life. He buys a
nice piece of ground, plants some vines and, presto change-o,
becomes a wine maker. In California, it seems that it happens every
other day.
</P>
<P>
   But Alain Graillot did it in France, where career changes are
considered subversive and midlife crises are often assuaged with a
new car or a girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Graillot was a 40-something salesman for an
agricultural business and had spent most of his working life on the
road. Some road _ one of his two sons was born in Guatemala and the
other in Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   He hated the life and he missed France. So he did what is almost
unthinkable there _ he chucked his job and went back to the Rhone
Valley, where he was born, to make wine. It was a courageous move.
It was also a smart one.
</P>
<P>
   He purchased some 50 acres in Crozes-Hermitage, most of it
planted 20 years earlier. Today he is one of the best known and
most respected winegrowers in the appellation _ and just when it is
beginning to gain a reputation for truly excellent Rhone wines.
</P>
<P>
   I say ``in the appellation'' because there is no community
called Crozes-Hermitage. It is a wine-producing region consisting
of 11 communes surrounding the town of Tain-l'Hermitage, which is
the source of a revered wine called simply Hermitage. One of those
11 communes, called Crozes, is where the Crozes-Hermitage
appellation was created in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   Until the 1980s, Crozes-Hermitage wines were decent but
unmemorable; better than most Cotes-du-Rhone, but not by much. In
the '60s, a drinkable Crozes-Hermitage sold in New York for $1.25
and it was a far cry from a great Hermitage.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the various communes in the Crozes-Hermitage
appellation display different soil and drainage characteristics.
The best locations are in the south _ east of the Rhone and north
of the Isere River. There, in the town of Pont-de-l'Isere, is the
Domaine les Chenes Verts (Green Oaks), Graillot's main vineyard and
his home.
</P>
<P>
   He also owns two small portions of a vineyard called Les
Greffieux, in Hermitage itself, and some four acres in St.-Joseph,
a large region across the river, on the west bank of the Rhone.
</P>
<P>
   All the communes I've mentioned are part of the Northern Rhone,
a wine region stretching about 60 miles from Ampuis (which is just
south of Lyons) to Valence. This is mostly red wine country, and
the grape, with few exceptions, is syrah. The white wines, which
can be surprisingly good, if a bit muscular compared with white
Burgundies, are made from the marsanne and roussanne grapes.
</P>
<P>
   I first met Graillot in late December, when he came to New York
to conduct a tasting of his wines at a dinner at the restaurant
Montrachet. In fact, he had to share the spotlight with wines from
one of his neighbors, Paul Jaboulet-Aine, one of the grand old
producers of the Rhone.
</P>
<P>
   A modest man, Graillot persists in downplaying his Hermitage: it
is not, he insisted, up to the quality he wants to display one day,
even though many of his vines are 80 years old. (A taste that
evening confirmed his judgement.) So that night, we drank his
favorite Crozes-Hermitage, wines he calls La Guiraude, from the
1994, 1992, 1990 and 1989 vintages.
</P>
<P>
   From a lack of a Graillot Hermitage, we drank La Chapelle, from
Paul Jaboulet-Aine from 1982 (in magnum), 1990, 1978 and 1961. By
the way, to provide a dinner to match these powerful wines,
Montrachet's chef, Remi Lauvand, created an all-truffle menu.
</P>
<P>
   The first wine called La Guiraude came from the 1985 vintage,
which was harvested just 15 days after Graillot took possession of
the place. La Guiraude is a blend with no particular geographic
orientation within the Graillot vineyards: it merely represents the
lots of wine that Graillot enjoys most from the year's crop. This
approach may explain why Remington Norman remarked in his book
``Rhone Renaissance'' (Wine Appreciation Guild, 1996) that in
outlook Graillot is ``more Bordelais than Rhone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He selects and blends to make his wine, the idea of `brand' or
`house wine' usurping that of terroir,'' Norman wrote. In other
words, he is more interested in making a wine that reflects his
taste than one that reflects the soil and weather that produced it.
</P>
<P>
   Being Bordelais in outlook does not, of course, mean that
Graillot makes Bordeaux-style wines. His are full-bodied Rhone
wines, with the depth, the power and the spice and raspberry
flavors that are characteristic of the syrah grape.
</P>
<P>
   Until the mid-1980s, just around the time that Graillot came
along, most of the Crozes-Hermitage growers sent their grapes to a
cooperative at Tain, where they were paid by weight. Now, the most
serious growers make their own wine, riskily leaving the grapes on
the vines longer and severely lowering crop levels to produce more
intense wines. At Domaine les Chenes Verts, the Guiraude is aged
entirely in wood, in barrels used once or twice by famous
Burgundian producers like Sauzet and Domaine Dujac. His other wines
are aged partially in wood and partially in stainless steel.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite among the Crozes-Hermitages served at Montrachet was
the 1989: it had both richness and elegance. Most of the younger
wines were not yet ready to drink. You can expect a Guiraude to be
in the $25-to-$30 range; the regular Alain Graillot
Crozes-Hermitage sells for about $18.
</P>
<P>
   (The big winner that night, for me, was La Chapelle Hermitage
1982. It was a wine to make one forget Burgundy for an entire
evening. That it was served with poached foie gras with truffles
didn't hurt.)
</P>
<P>
   Graillot wines are hardly supermarket items, but neither are
they as rare as some cult wines from the Cote Rotie, in the
northern Rhone _ or as some Napa Valley labels, for that matter.
Good shops will have them or can get them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
