<HEADER>
A9235 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MANAGERS27-CO     01-26 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MANAGERS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EXPERIENCED PROSECUTORS HEADLINE HOUSE TRIAL TEAM
 &HT;    850&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As a prosecutor, James Rogan has felt the courtroom
sting of having his case against a high-profile defendant summarily
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   As a deputy district attorney in Los Angeles a decade ago, Rogan
charged mortician David Sconce with using oleander poison to kill a
rival funeral director in the notorious Lamb Funeral Home case.
Although Sconce and other family members were imprisoned for
stealing and selling body organs and gold teeth from corpses,
forging organ donor cards, and conducting mass cremations at a
secret crematorium, the murder charge was thrown out for lack of
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Now Rogan is one of several seasoned former prosecutors who have
taken lead roles in presenting impeachment evidence against
President Clinton. Although all 13 of the House managers are
attorneys and members of the Judiciary Committee, some have little
trial experience and others have never prosecuted a criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some haven't done a lick of lawyering in 30 years,'' the
National Law Journal noted.
</P>
<P>
   Experienced or not, the managers are all anxiously awaiting a
decision by the Senate on whether to dismiss the case or to grant
the managers' request to hear witnesses. Votes are expected by
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like a real trial,'' said Rogan, R-Calif. ``We have
to play the hand we're dealt.''
</P>
<P>
   If witnesses are permitted, the former prosecutors among the
managers are expected to do most of the questioning. In addition to
Rogan, they include three former U.S. attorneys _ Reps. Ed Bryant
of Tennessee, Bob Barr of Georgia and Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas.
Reps. Lindsay Graham of South Carolina and Bill McCollum of Florida
have considerable experience as military prosecutors in the Judge
Advocate General (JAG) Corps.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson, whose down-home drawl has become familiar to TV talk
show viewers, has the most trial experience of all the House
managers. He has prosecuted or defended more than 100 jury cases.
As the U.S. attorney for western Arkansas, he directed the 1984
case in which Roger Clinton, brother of the then-Arkansas governor,
pleaded guilty to possession of cocaine with intent to distribute.
Roger Clinton was sentenced to serve two years in prison and later
testified against an Arkansas attorney involved in drug dealing
under the plea bargain.
</P>
<P>
   In other well-publicized cases, Hutchinson successfully
prosecuted five Arkansans who had hidden a tax protester before his
death in a shootout with federal marshal and sent a Republican
sheriff to jail for marijuana distribution.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Hutchinson recalled his days as an Arkansas defense
lawyer in urging the Senate to allow witnesses. He told of a case
where a witness against his client was not at all credible in
person but whose written deposition was powerfully persuasive when
read by a jury. ``The story needs to be told. The truth should be
determined. Justice should be accomplished,'' said Hutchinson.
``That is done not through lawyers up here talking, it's done not
through transcripts, but through witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, after teaching constitutional law at West Point as a JAG
officer, was named U.S. attorney for western Tennessee. There he
prosecuted the worst mass murder in the state's history. In an
isolated cabin, Dennis Harris lost $600 in a poker game and then
killed the six other players because he was afraid to tell his wife
about the loss. Harris shot one of his poker buddies in the head,
then tied up the others and burned them alive in the cabin. Bryant
prosecuted him on a federal arson charge, getting a sentence of
life plus 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant also directed the successful prosecution of then-Judge
David Lanier, who was convicted of sexual assaulting and harassing
women in his courtroom in a landmark decision later upheld by the
Supreme Court. However, Bryant resigned in protest after the
Justice Department sought to seat a new jury in his fraud case
against then-Rep. Harold E. Ford, D-Tenn. Ford was later acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   Barr, while earning his law degree from Georgetown University,
worked as a CIA analyst. Later, he was appointed U.S. attorney for
the northern district of Georgia and successfully prosecuted
then-Rep. Pat Swindall, R-Ga., for perjury. In a complicated case,
Swindall had backed out of financial deal with undercover agent who
had said he wanted to launder drug money. Summoned before a grand
jury, Swindall denied knowing the source of the funds and afterward
was indicted for perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's folksy courtroom manner has been widely acclaimed as
effective in the Senate case. As a JAG officer, Graham was the lead
prosecutor for U.S. Air Force in Europe from 1984 to 1988. His
cases included fraternization charges involving sexual relations
between military personnel.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell, as a JAG officer in the Naval reserves for 20 years,
served as prosecutor, defender and judge at various times. His last
prosecution was a drug case in Jacksonville about five years ago,
said an aide. Before his election to Congress in 1980, McCollum
handled insurance defense cases for a mid-sized law firm in
Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   TV viewers have seen less of the other House managers, most of
whom have limited courtroom experience.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Chris Cannon of Utah has never prosecuted a case, and has
served as lead courtroom attorney in only a couple of instances. As
an Interior Department attorney during the Reagan administration,
Cannon did negotiate settlements with mining companies, but the
Justice Department took over any cases that went to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Sensenbrenner of Wisconsin practiced only about six
months as private attorney before becoming a state assemblyman. His
last courtroom presentation came in a 1975 divorce case. However,
he did lead the House team in the impeachment trial of U.S.
District Judge Harry E. Claiborne. Or perhaps his colleagues
enlisted Sensenbrenner as a good luck charm: He won $250,000 in the
D.C. Lottery in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Another House manager with JAG experience is Stephen Buyer of
Indiana. Called to active duty in the Persian Gulf as a U.S. Army
Reserves captain in 1990, Buyer was a legal adviser during Desert
Storm. He served as a legal liaison to the International Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   A Cincinnati city councilman before his election to Congress,
Rep. Steve Chabot of Ohio handled mostly civil cases such as wills
and divorces rather than criminal defenses in his private law
practice. Before entering politics, Rep. Charles Canady of Florida
specialized in corporate litigation after graduating from Yale Law
School. Rep. George Gekas of Pennsylvania was a local prosecutor _
but more than 30 years ago, before his election to the state
legislature in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde of Illinois is
a practitioner of politics rather than courtroom law. Hyde has
served in Congress since 1974 and in the Illinois legislature for
eight years before that.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Rogan said he was not frustrated at the limitations
imposed upon the House managers by the Senate. Frustration was
being an overworked and under-staffed assistant district attorney
in Los Angeles, he recalled, and being called upon to prosecute a
rape case at a moment's notice and with no time for preparation.
</P>
<P>
   As a prosecutor, Rogan displayed a flair for drama. In a
vehicular homicide case _ where a drunk driver killed four people _
Rogan lined 10 glasses up on the jury box and slowly filled each
with beer to illustrate how much the defendant drank before hitting
his victims. Then he raised four fingers and snapped his fingers to
show how quickly four lives were lost.
</P>
<P>
   He won a conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
