<HEADER>
A9260 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      01-26 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERBOWL STEAKS WITH POTATO-GARLIC AND GRATIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (This is the last of eight columns by Alfred Portale, the executive
chef and an owner of Gotham Bar and Grill in Manhattan. His
collaborator on these columns was Dorie Greenspan. Next week: Rick
Moonen, the executive chef of Oceana in Manhattan.)  
 (HLW)  
 By ALFRED PORTALE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I take football seriously, and so do the people who
work with me, which is why I close the restaurant on Super Bowl
Sunday and invite my staff and their families to eat, drink and
cheer their favorites on big-screen televisions set up around the
dining room. I've always been a football fan (my hometown team is
the Buffalo Bills), I've always had friends in to watch the game
and I've always cooked something special _ but easy _ for halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Very often, that has been these pan-roasted steaks with garlicky
potato gratin.
</P>
<P>
   So that you don't miss a minute of Sunday's game, start cooking
the gratin before kickoff. It will be done before halftime, so when
there's a commercial, run into the kitchen and turn off the oven.
(The gratin can stay inside.) Take the steaks out of the
refrigerator then, to bring them up to room temperature so they
will cook perfectly. Then the minute the halftime whistle blows,
run back and start the steaks.
</P>
<P>
   I've chosen filets as much for their size as for their taste:
because they're small, three fit in a pan, leaving enough room for
each to get a ``steakhouse crust'' from a home stove's heat. After
I press cracked peppercorns into the steaks, I cook them in heavy
skillets for six minutes on a side, and they're just the way I like
them _ rare. To test for doneness, press the steaks. If the dent
you've made comes back slowly, they're rare; if it springs back
more quickly, they're medium, and if it doesn't give at all (like a
pigskin), they're well done.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need a sauce for the steaks because the gratin is so
creamy. I submerge thinly sliced potatoes in garlic-infused cream
and bake them until they absorb the cream and develop a golden
crust. You can dust the top with grated Gruyere if you like, or
next time, add mushrooms, butternut squash or even artichokes to
the potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Take it from one who knows: even if your team is behind at the
half, this combination is always a winner.
</P>
<P>
   PAN-ROASTED FILET MIGNON
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   6 teaspoons cracked white peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   6 8-ounce filets mignons, each about 1\ inches thick
</P>
<P>
   Coarse salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1. Press peppercorns evenly into steaks, using 1 teaspoon for
each filet. Then season to taste with salt.
</P>
<P>
   2. Pour 1 tablespoon oil into each of two heavy-bottomed 10-inch
skillets, and place over high heat. When oil just begins to smoke,
place 3 steaks in each pan. Cook steaks 6 minutes on each side for
rare, 7 minutes for medium-rare and 9 minutes for medium. If
necessary, turn heat down to keep them from burning.
</P>
<P>
   3. Transfer steaks to a plate, cover with foil and let them rest
5 minutes. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   POTATO-GARLIC GRATIN
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Butter for greasing baking dish
</P>
<P>
   4 pounds Yukon Gold or russet potatoes
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon freshly grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   2 small cloves garlic, peeled and minced
</P>
<P>
   2 cups (approximately) heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Butter a 9-by-11-inch baking
dish.
</P>
<P>
   2. Peel potatoes, placing them in a bowl of cold water. Using a
mandoline (which will keep the slices together so that they may be
fanned out later) or a sharp knife, cut potatoes lengthwise into
slices [ inch thick. Place potatoes in a single layer in the dish,
fanning each one out so that each slice slightly overlaps its
neighbor to cover the bottom of the dish. Sprinkle with salt and
pepper to taste, nutmeg, and some of the garlic. Make as many
layers as needed to use all potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Pour cream over potatoes half a cup at a time, pressing down
firmly on potatoes after each addition to distribute cream evenly.
When all cream is added, it should just cover potatoes when they
are pressed; a little more or a little less than 2 cups may be
needed.
</P>
<P>
   4. Cover dish with foil. Poke a few holes in the foil, and bake
1 hour. Remove foil, and bake until potatoes have absorbed cream
and top of gratin is golden, about 20 minutes more. Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 1711EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9270 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MANDOLINE-ART-3TAKES-     01-26 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANDOLINE-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TOOL THAT CHEFS LOVE, AND HOME COOKS BARELY KNOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It appears to be a simple gratin. It is a tall, square stack of
yams, browned on top and sagging on the edges. As you sink your
fork into it, though, it reveals layer upon fine layer, like a
piece of puff pastry. And when you bite into it, the layers,
separated by a smoky chipotle-scented cream, fall apart in your
mouth.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this gratin at Mesa Grill so exceptional? The precise
slicing of the yams.
</P>
<P>
   Consider another example, a familiar garnish on desserts around
the city: the wafer-thin, perfectly even cross section of apple,
dried to a sweet, brittle chip in the oven. It's so thin, it's
translucent. And if it weren't cut just so, it would simply be a
dopey, chewy slice of dried apple.
</P>
<P>
   Most chefs can dazzle home cooks with their knife skills, but
even they cannot perform such precision on yams and apples. Their
secret, the tool that no chef would live without, is the mandoline.
</P>
<P>
   With this slicing tool, they can cut carrots on an angle into
exactly one-sixteenth-inch slices. They can transform a zucchini
into julienne finer than matchsticks. They can reduce a firm,
starchy potato to sheets that fold like prosciutto.
</P>
<P>
   But even as home cooks rush to embrace every implement of the
professional kitchen, the mandoline remains one of the few to be
overlooked. That's at least partly because of their unwavering
devotion to another professional tool: the food processor.
</P>
<P>
   But the mandoline is in many ways more useful than a food
processor, which is cumbersome and offers little flexibility. With
the turn of a knob or the press of a lever, most mandoline blades
can be adjusted to the millimeter, so you can slice in the precise
thickness you want. You get consistency and, with practice, great
speed. A potato can be finely sliced in little more than a minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do everything on the mandoline,'' said Carol Peck, the
owner of the Good News Cafe in Woodbury, Conn. ``We use it a good
two or three hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   At Cena in the Flatiron district, it is considered so crucial
that the cooks are required to provide their own mandolines along
with their knives.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, it is really just a straightforward device _ a sharp
blade fixed between braces and set up on an angle, like a
washboard. It has but a single function: it cuts.
</P>
<P>
   You adjust the thickness of slices _ as fine as a millimeter or
as thick as a quarter inch _ and simply slide vegetables or fruits
down the mandoline and across the blade.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear exactly when the mandoline was invented, but an
early version was used in the 19th century in Alsace, France, for
shredding cabbage for choucroute. It was bigger and bulkier than
the mandoline of today, with a single straight blade set into wood.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, Bron of Thonon-les-Bains, France, came out with a
heavy-duty nickel-coated version, and in 53 years, the design has
barely changed.
</P>
<P>
   The gold standard of mandolines, the Bron is still expensive
(about $144), still clunky and still a beautiful, sculptural piece
of cookware. But cheaper varieties are now breathing down its neck.
Many professional kitchens depend on the cheap (about $24), plastic
Benriner, which can simply be tossed out when the blade goes dull.
</P>
<P>
   The mandoline is not for the faint of heart, however.
Practically everyone who has a mandoline has a mandoline story. And
few are pretty. The mandoline can be very dangerous. The exposed
blade is extremely sharp, and there is little protection for your
hands as you push fruits and vegetables against it. There are hand
guards on many mandolines, but it is still a fairly barbaric
contraption.
</P>
<P>
   Some dishes, though, cannot be made without it. The ubiquitous
gaufrette potato chips, with their lattice cut, for instance,
cannot be sliced with a knife. Some mandolines come equipped with a
crenulated blade, so you can run the potato over the blade, turning
it 90 degrees with each slice to produce the lattice pattern.
</P>
<P>
   The potato-wrapped sea bass at Daniel is another. Improbably
thin, long strips of potato are what make the dish. They cling like
gauze around the fillet and, when sauteed, crisp up and protect the
delicate fish within.
</P>
<P>
   Or beet chips. Few mortals could take a knife to a raw beet and
come up with anything that remotely resembles equally sized,
one-sixteenth-inch thick round circles.
</P>
<P>
   The mandoline is even more convincing, though, when it is used
to transform conventional dishes. Jean-Georges Vongerichten, the
chef at Jean Georges, uses it to make a typical fennel and apple
salad.
</P>
<P>
   But by slicing the fennel and apple as thinly as possible on a
mandoline, rather than having the usual texture of coleslaw, the
fennel and apple are more like tissue paper _ gossamer sheets that
melt on the tongue. The flavors blend more subtly and the salad
looks like a glistening tangle of opaque ribbon.
</P>
<P>
   Potato Maximes, or potato chips fried in clarified butter, can
also take on greater dimensions when sliced with a mandoline. In
his book, ``Great American Food'' (Random House, 1996), Charlie
Palmer alters the recipe slightly by making paper-thin slices of
potato on a mandoline, then sandwiching herbs between two slices
and baking them. The potato chips turn out like flower petals
pressed in glass.
</P>
<P>
   But what chefs find most desirable about the mandoline is its
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much quicker and much more accurate because you set the
spacing, so every cut will be the same,'' said Michael Romano, the
chef at Union Square Cafe. ``I couldn't imagine a professional
kitchen without one.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   GRATIN OF CHIPOTLE CREAM AND YAMS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Bobby Flay, chef at Mesa Grill &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1{ hours
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chipotle pepper puree
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds yams, peeled and cut into 1/16-inch thick slices on a
mandoline
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 375 degrees. In a bowl, whisk together the
cream and pepper puree until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   2. In an 8{-inch-by-4{-inch terrine or bread pan that is 2}
inches deep, arrange a thin layer of the yams. Season with a little
salt and pepper and spoon over a little of the cream mixture.
Repeat layering the remaining yams and cream mixture, seasoning
every other layer. Press firmly on the gratin to compact the yams.
</P>
<P>
   3. Cover the terrine with aluminum foil, and bake for 30
minutes. Remove the foil, and continue baking for 35 to 40 minutes,
or until most of the cream has been absorbed and the yams are
tender and browned. Remove from the oven, and let rest for 10
minutes before slicing. Cut into 4 rectangular pieces, and
carefully transfer to serving plates using a spatula and a fork.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   FENNEL AND APPLE SALAD WITH JUNIPER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Jean-Georges Vongerichten &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 fennel bulb
</P>
<P>
   1 Granny Smith apple
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   15 juniper berries.
</P>
<P>
   1. Trim the fennel, and then cut it in half through the core,
keeping some of the top feathery fronds for garnish. Cut the apple
into quarters, and then core it but do not peel it.
</P>
<P>
   2. Using a mandoline, cut the fennel against the grain as thinly
as possible. Also on the mandoline, cut the apple into the thinnest
possible slices. In a nonreactive bowl, toss together the fennel,
apple, lemon juice and olive oil. Season to taste with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   3. Crush the juniper berries with the side of a knife, and then
mince. Stir them into the salad, toss and let sit for 5 minutes
before serving.
</P>
<P>
   4. Just before serving, garnish with the minced feathery fennel
tops.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   HERB POTATO MAXIMES
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Great American Food'' (Random House, 1996) by
Charlie Palmer and Judith Choate &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: about 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   { cup unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 large Idaho potatoes
</P>
<P>
   20 1{-inch-long chive points
</P>
<P>
   20 fresh tarragon leaves
</P>
<P>
   20 small chervil sprigs
</P>
<P>
   Coarse salt.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place butter in a small saucepan over very low heat. Cook for
15 minutes. While it cooks, use a ladle to skim off the white
frothy matter, until the top of the melted fat is clear. Remove
from heat, and let stand for 10 minutes. Pour yellow fat into a
bowl, taking care not to let any of the solids at the bottom of the
pan get into the bowl.
</P>
<P>
   2. Heat the oven to 300 degrees. Brush a heavy nonstick baking
sheet with the clarified butter. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. Peel potatoes. Rinse them under cold running water, and pat
dry. Using a mandoline, slice one potato, lengthwise, into
paper-thin slices, discarding the end pieces. You should get 18 to
20 even slices from each potato.
</P>
<P>
   4. Working quickly, lay the potato slices out next to one
another, but not touching, on the prepared baking sheet. Place one
piece each of the chive, tarragon and chervil in a pattern in the
center of each potato slice, leaving a small border.
</P>
<P>
   5. Slice the second potato as described in Step 3. Dry the
slices slightly, and lay them evenly on top of the herb-topped
slices. Once all the potatoes are covered, firmly press each
``sandwich'' together to seal the edges. Brush with the remaining
butter, and season with salt to taste.
</P>
<P>
   6. Place in the oven, and bake, turning the baking sheet from
time to time, for 25 minutes, or until golden. Remove from oven,
and drain on paper towels. Serve at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 20 chips.
</P>
<P>
   SKATE WING WITH CRISP PARSNIP CRUST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Geoffrey Zakarian, chef at Patroon &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 large parsnip, peeled and trimmed
</P>
<P>
   4 skate wing fillets (about 6 ounces each), skinned and boned
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon canola oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   Juice of { lemon, for sprinkling
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped flat-leaf parsley.
</P>
<P>
   1. Cut parsnips into 4-inch lengths. On a mandoline, slice the
parsnips lengthwise into 1/16-inch slices. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Lightly brush the skate wings with the egg wash. Lay parsnip
slices on the skate in neat rows, touching one another. Season with
salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a 12-inch nonstick saute pan, heat the oil over medium
high heat. Using a spatula, carefully flip the skate wing into the
pan in a single motion, parsnip side down. Let the fish cook
undisturbed for 4 to 5 minutes. Carefully turn over, and cook about
2 minutes more, or until fish is lightly firm to the touch.
</P>
<P>
   4. Meanwhile, in a small saucepan, melt the butter over medium
heat. Cook until it smells nutty and browns lightly. Add the lemon
juice.
</P>
<P>
   5. To serve, arrange the fish on a platter, the parsnip side up.
Spoon the butter over the top. Sprinkle with parsley. Serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If used incorrectly, the mandoline, with its exposed blade, can
be an extremely dangerous tool. But with a little caution and
common sense, you can avoid losing fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, your mandoline will have a hand guard between your
fingers and the blade. On the Matfer mandoline, for instance, the
hand guard has stipples on the underside to grasp the food and a
handle on top to make it easy to slide the food over the blade,
keeping your fingers inches above.
</P>
<P>
   If the vegetables or fruits you are slicing are large, cut them
into sizes that can fit under the hand guard.
</P>
<P>
   Position the mandoline on a solid surface, and set the blade to
the desired thickness. Place the food under the hand guard. To
slice, begin at the top of the mandoline and slide down and over
the blade in a single fluid motion. Do not press too hard or the
food can slip. The more fluid your motions and the more evenly you
apply pressure, the safer the mandoline will be. Start slowly,
until you feel comfortable slicing.
</P>
<P>
   If the food you are slicing will not fit under the hand guard,
or if you choose not to use the guard, the best alternative is to
wrap the fruit or vegetable in a small kitchen towel and use it as
a protective layer between your fingers and the blade.
</P>
<P>
   As you get toward the end of slicing a potato or apple, do not
grab the towel with your fingers pointed downward. Instead, lay
your palm flat on top of it with your fingers extended so they stay
out of the blade's way.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important is that your mandoline's blade should be
sharp, so that there is less resistance when slicing. You are more
likely to slip if pushing too hard against a dull blade. If they
become dull, some blades may be replaced, others removed and
sharpened. The manufacturer's instructions will tell you which to
do.
</P>
<P>
   Four Variations on the Mandoline
</P>
<P>
   Whether you are paying $24 or $159, every mandoline requires a
little compromise. I tested the four brands most commonly found in
cookware stores: V-Slicer Plus, Benriner, Bron and Matfer.
</P>
<P>
   The most intimidating and possibly least effective is the
V-Slicer. The blade, shaped in a ``V,'' cuts through most
vegetables with little effort. But each slice requires sliding your
hand between the blades _ and if you're making a julienne cut, over
8 or 24 little blades set in the center of the ``V'' that stick up
like shark fins. It is simply frightening to use.
</P>
<P>
   It also offers little flexibility: it only cuts foods thick (a
quarter inch) or thin (one-sixteenth of an inch). There are wide
and narrow julienne attachments but no crenulated blade _ so no
gaufrettes. It is $39.95 at Broadway Panhandler, 477 Broome Street
(Wooster Street); (212) 966-3434.
</P>
<P>
   The Benriner, made in Japan, is the darling of chefs, who
consider it disposable when the blades dull. It's kitschy in
design, constructed of plastic imprinted with wood grain. It does
have a serious, razor-sharp blade, positioned at an angle in the
center of the mandoline, but that does not mean it is paired with a
decent hand guard. This one is so small and difficult to hold that
it is practically useless. Be careful.
</P>
<P>
   The instruction booklet, which reads as if it were written by a
first-year English student, is not much help. Thankfully, it is an
easy mechanism to figure out. The thickness of slices can be finely
adjusted from an eighth of an inch to a barely detectable width by
turning a knob, and the three julienne blades can be installed and
secured with large screws.
</P>
<P>
   As with the V-Slicer, though, there is no crenulated blade. For
$23.98 at Zabar's, 2245 Broadway (80th Street); (212) 787-2000,
it's worth considering.
</P>
<P>
   If you must have gaufrettes, then you will have to lay down the
cash. The Bron mandoline has a crenulated blade built into the base
frame. You simply raise the blade to put it into action. In fact,
the most appealing part of this classic mandoline is that all the
blades are built in.
</P>
<P>
   The only loose part is the hand guard, which slides on and off;
it was the most stable and protective of all the hand guards I
tried. Its flat blade is not quite as sharp as the one on the
Benriner, but it can be sharpened. Its blades can be finely
adjusted, to a maximum of three-eighths of an inch.
</P>
<P>
   And a heavy, sturdy frame and top-quality construction make it
worth the $143.95 it costs at A Cook's Companion, 152 Atlantic
Avenue (Clinton Street) in Brooklyn; (718) 852-6641.
</P>
<P>
   The Matfer mandoline also turns out a nice gaufrette cut and
with zucchini, potato and celery root, perfect julienne, gratings
and paper thin slices. It can produce slices as thick as
three-sixteenths of an inch. Though the julienne blades are not
built in, as with the Bron, they are easy to slip in and out. This
mandoline can be ordered for $159 from Williams-Sonoma, (800)
541-2233.
</P>
</TEXT>
