<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPA-BRANDY-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW GAUNTLET: COGNAC, MADE IN AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors` recipes at end of article)  
 (bl)  
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UKIAH, Calif. _ When I first visited the Napa Valley, in 1965,
it was still the bucolic place pictured in Frank Loesser's musical
``The Most Happy Fella.'' There was no wine train. There were no
restaurants with gastronomic pretensions, and no fancy-pants
grocery stores or shops. Only a half-dozen vineyards caught your
eye as you drove up sleepy Route 29.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, it's fairly popping with vineyards. On weekends,
it turns into a playpen for yuppies. But there is one intriguing
wine-related activity still in its infancy, little noticed by the
thundering herds: distilling.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly five tenacious enterprises in California are engaged in
the exacting business of producing brandies or eaux de vie by
traditional Continental methods _ two in the Napa Valley; two here
in Mendocino County, two hours north of San Francisco, and one in a
warehouse in Alameda, across the bay from San Francisco. They have
a formidable competitor in Portland, Ore. _ Steve McCarthy of Clear
Creek Distillery, whose eau de vie made from Bartlett pears is
quite spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   All the Californians turn out products that can stand comparison
with their counterparts in Europe, where the custom of drinking a
digestif _ a small glass of dry spirits after dinner, perhaps with
a coffee and a cigar _ is far better established than in America.
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose Bierce, an American, once called brandy ``a cordial
composed of one part thunder-and-lightning, one part remorse, two
parts bloody murder ... and four parts Holy Moses.'' He obviously
never tasted these.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, all the producers struggle to sell their wares, and none of
them turn up very often in your corner liquor store. Some of the
best California digestifs, like Germain-Robin and St. George, can
be found in fine wine shops and at deluxe restaurants around the
country, but others, like Jepson, are harder to come by.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best batches of each year's output at Alambic, made
in the hills above Ukiah by Hubert Germain-Robin, whose family made
cognac in the Charente region of southwestern France for 175 years,
is reserved for the White House. It is mellow and satisfying, with
an aroma compounded of fruit, spice and vanilla-tinged wood. Its
taste lingers long after the liquid is gone _ what the professional
tasters call a ``long finish.'' Classic stuff.
</P>
<P>
   At St. George Spirits in Alameda, Joerg Rupf, Alsatian-born,
makes the same kinds of clear, dry, fruit-based digestifs that are
produced in his homeland (and in Austria, Germany and Switzerland).
In recent years, he has submitted many of these ``white alcohols''
to an annual competition sponsored by Destillata, an Austrian
magazine, including poire; kirsch, made from cherries, and grappa,
distilled from the grape pomace left over from winemaking.
</P>
<P>
   Competing against Europe's best, they have all won gold medals,
and in 1997, Rupf and Lance Winters, his fellow distiller at St.
George, won the trophy for best in show.
</P>
<P>
   To get to Ansley J. Coale Jr.'s 2,000-acre sheep ranch, 1,100
feet above sea level, you have to negotiate a potholed one-lane
road that would challenge a panzer. When I visited him in November,
the trees were encrusted with moss and lichen engendered by 90
inches of rain in five months. Unadorned frame buildings popped in
and out of the fog, visible one minute, hidden the next.
``Brigadoon,'' my stepson said.
</P>
<P>
   Coale, 56, once taught at Berkeley. He met Germain-Robin, 48,
when he picked him up as a hitchhiker almost 20 years ago. Until
they sold out to the giant Martell, Germain-Robin's family had been
cognac distillers since 1782; 200 years later, he and Coale picked
up that thread in the New World.
</P>
<P>
   They built their distillery themselves _ a one-room shed the
size of an icehouse; a small pot still from the old country, fired
by propane, with shiny brass valves and the traditional swan's-neck
tube leading to a condenser; a Wisconsin dairy tank. They added an
aging cellar in 1983. The whole operation cost $85,000.
</P>
<P>
   As in cognac, Germain-Robin brandy is distilled twice. Each pass
takes 11 to 12 hours, and Germain-Robin does two a day, for six
months a year. What comes out is near-brandy, not yet drinkable.
The distilled liquid is pumped into 92-gallon French oak barrels,
allowed to rest for a year, then blended with brandies from other
vintages and brandies made from other types of grapes, then aged
further.
</P>
<P>
   The process is exactly the same as that used for cognac, but
only brandy made in designated zones in Charente can be called
that.
</P>
<P>
   What is different here is the wine from which the brandy is
made. In southwestern France, the traditional grapes are folle
blanche and colombard, supplemented starting early in this century
with ugni blanc, a varietal more appreciated for quantity than
quality. In France, many of the old-timers still tell you, ``The
thinner the wine, the richer the cognac.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost by accident, Coale and Germain-Robin found otherwise. In
the early days, they experimented, buying what came to hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more sun than Cognac does, so we get better, riper
grapes,'' Coale insisted. ``The right sugar content. Plenty of
acidity. That's what makes the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Germain-Robin added: ``They don't have a choice. I do.'' He buys
grapes and wine from Roederer Estate and Clos du Val, among others,
mostly in Mendocino County. I tasted one-year-old unblended
brandies from seven varietals, including muscat, which had exactly
the flowery aroma of Muscat de Baumes de Venise, a sweet wine from
the Rhone Valley; viognier, which had a touch of muskmelon in the
flavor; pinot noir, underdeveloped but robust, and zinfandel,
pleasantly peppery on the nose as well as the palate.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Oak, blending skill and time in the maturing shed will do
wonders for all of them. Some brandies will stay for a long time,
up to 50 years, perhaps. At the moment, Germain-Robin is producing
7,000 cases a year and selling 4,000; for a while, the firm sold
only 2,000 from an annual production of 5,000. Good for the
blending stock; bad for the balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Germain-Robin's standard product, labeled Fine, retails for $32;
it has overtones of clove and contains brandies up to five years
old. Its creamy XO, 13{ years old, costs $100. And if that doesn't
satisfy you, next month Coale plans to begin shipping Anno Domini
2000, a miraculously dense and complex brandy designed for
millionaires' millennium celebrations. It is made mostly from pinot
noir, harvested and distilled in 1983 and 1984, with a bit of
palomino, the grape of sherry, thrown in. Price: $350. Quality,
when I tasted it, a month after bottling: superior to Paradis and
other deluxe French blends, and equal to the best very old
single-vintage, small-producer cognacs.
</P>
<P>
   Jepson, the other Mendocino producer, is not nearly as
ambitious, but to say that is not at all to dismiss its brandies, a
7-to-8-year-old blend labeled ``rare'' ($34) and a
13-to-14-year-old Signature Reserve ($100). Both are made from
colombard grapes grown on the Jepson Estate, along the Russian
River near Hop-land, which also produces worthy white table wines.
</P>
<P>
   I found the lower-priced brandy round and notably spicy in
flavor, with hints of nutmeg, cinnamon and hazelnuts, if somewhat
too sharply alcoholic in attack. The Signature was not made
available for tasting.
</P>
<P>
   Miles Karakasevic is a fierce, combative, handsome Serb,
complete with mustache, who lives on a Napa mountaintop. There he,
too, follows family tradition, producing distillates of all sorts:
Grappa di Marko, named for his son, made from pomace still moist
with merlot rather than dry, as is usual; Calvad'or, a
calvados-like eau de vie, bursting with flavor, made from
Gravenstein apples, and Pachanga, an eau de vie made from Jerusalem
artichokes, with a resemblance to cactus-based mescal. It does
wonders for a Bloody Mary.
</P>
<P>
   There are other things, too: ``No fruit is safe from Miles,''
says his good-humored wife, Susan.
</P>
<P>
   Karakasevic (the name is pronounced kah-rah-KAH-shah-vitch) has
developed a method of flavoring vodka with California's
distinctively delicious Meyer lemons. He makes a wicked pastis. He
even makes port. All are sold under the name Domaine Charbay,
chiefly at the distillery, on Spring Mountain Road above St.
Helena, and served at local restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, Betsey; my stepson, John Brown, and I tried them all
one sunny morning just after Thanksgiving, and liked every one.
Well, tried almost all. We didn't get to taste Karakasevic's
long-promised brandy, distilled in 1983, he says, from folle
blanche grapes. He keeps postponing its release.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's shooting for ``the turn of the century.'' But his
wife, who has heard it all before, said, ``I'm not sure he'll come
through.''
</P>
<P>
   RMS is the opposite of Domaine Charbay, a big corporate
operation with a flossy, banner-bedecked visitor center down in the
Carneros section of the Napa Valley, a distillery with no fewer
than eight highly automated alambic stills and a barrel house that
holds a consequential asset: 4,000 casks of brandy, from the
vintages of 1982 through 1998, slowly mellowing. A black fungus
grows on the roof tiles of the barrel house, a curious sign of
authenticity; the brandy evaporating through the pores of the wood
_ ``the angel's share,'' the distillers call it _ feeds the fungus.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, RMS stood for Remy-Martin-Schramsberg, a joint
venture of the French cognac house and the California champagne
house. Schramsberg dropped out 12 years ago, and the initials are
now said to stand for ``rare-mature-special.'' David Key, who
showed us around, stated the obvious: ``This place was made to
distill a lot more than it does.'' The alambics are fired up only
eight weeks a year.
</P>
<P>
   RMS, like Germain-Robin, blends a range of brandies: SR, a
minimum of seven years old, $30 retail; QE, 14 years minimum, $116
in a lovely flagon; and Folle Blanche, ``a nod to history,'' a
brandy made only from folle blanche grapes from old vines at the
Louis M. Martini vineyards, 10 years old, $65. I particularly liked
the austere, delicate taste of the folle blanche (though I must
note in all honesty that most people disagree, preferring the SR
and QE).
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, RMS released no new product, even though
it was distilling the equivalent of up to 10,000 cases a year.
Almost all the sales took place at the visitor center; the rest
went into inventory. This year, the French owners are finally
making their first national sales push. It's a high-quality
product, and RMS finally has people out singing its praises.
</P>
<P>
   At their best, eaux de vie offer miraculously concentrated
flavors. Nothing tastes quite so much like fresh raspberries _ not
even fresh raspberries _ as a glass of well-chilled framboise. The
trick is to avoid the chemical or medicinal flavor that often
creeps into the distillation. And that Rupf of St. George certainly
does. Nor do his products have any of the coarse bite of alcohol
that mars down-market European brands.
</P>
<P>
   His methods are proven ones _ fruit is crushed at the peak of
ripeness, fermented without added sugar, distilled in pot stills
made by Arnold Holstein at Markdorf on the Bodensee in Bavaria,
probably the best in the world; the ``heads'' and ``tails,'' the
beginning and end of the two-hour distilling run, are cut
drastically, to eliminate the harsher flavors concentrated therein.
</P>
<P>
   I recently tasted St. George poire and framboise against poire
and framboise produced by Miclo and Massenez, two of the best
houses in Alsace, and by Brana, in the Pyrenees. I put St. George's
poire first, with Brana's just behind; Miclo's framboise came
first, with St. George's just behind. The differences were
minuscule.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When it came to kirsch, I much preferred St. George's spirit,
which is made from Montmorency cherries from Michigan and
Washington, the kind traditionally baked in pies, rather than from
Alsatian black cherries.
</P>
<P>
   Better than half of St. George's total output, about 5,000 cases
a year, goes to clients in Germany, Austria and Switzerland. Like
Coale, Rupf says that it is the consistently high quality of the
fruit available in the United States _ it takes up to 30 pounds for
a single bottle _ that gives him a competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
   Under his own label, Rupf also makes several agreeably
smoky-tasting grappas, and he does contract distilling, too,
turning out a grappa for Eisele Vineyard in the Napa Valley, for
example, and a chardonnay brandy for Acacia. And Winters is
tinkering obsessively with a single-malt whiskey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joerg is legendary for his lack of marketing zeal,'' Winters
said, pointing to the dark recesses of the warehouse. ``There are
tanks of things back there that will never see the light of day
because he doesn't think they're good enough. He's not focused on
the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL RECIPES FOLLOW)
</P>
<P>
   POIRE WILLIAM ICE CREAM  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Charlene Reis, pastry chef, Chez Panisse, Berkeley,
Calif.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes, plus chilling and freezing  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6 large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 cup half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons poire William eau de vie.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a small bowl, whisk the egg yolks just enough to break
them up. Set aside. Place the cream in a medium mixing bowl, and
set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a small nonaluminum saucepan, combine the half-and-half
and sugar. Place over medium heat, stirring occasionally, just
until steam rises; do not boil. Slowly add about { cup of the hot
mixture to the egg yolks, whisking vigorously to combine well. Pour
the mixture into the saucepan, and simmer over low heat until it
forms a custard thick enough to coat the back of a metal spoon,
about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Strain the custard into the bowl of cream. Add the poire
William, and stir to mix well. Refrigerate until well chilled,
about a half-hour. Freeze in an ice cream maker according to
manufacturer's instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1{ quarts (6 servings)
</P>
<P>
   MAGIE NOIRE (BLACK MAGIC CAKE)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Carole Germain-Robin &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 15 minutes, plus 1 hour chilling and resting  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   \ cup blanched slivered almonds
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces semisweet chocolate
</P>
<P>
   14 tablespoons (1} sticks) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   Butter and flour for pan
</P>
<P>
   8 large eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2{ tablespoons Germain-Robin brandy
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons heavy cream.
</P>
<P>
   1. Using a food processor or blender, chop the almonds very
finely, but do not allow to form a paste; set aside. In a
microwave-safe bowl or the top half of a double boiler, combine 8
ounces of the chocolate and 10 tablespoons of the butter. Use the
microwave oven or double boiler to melt the chocolate mixture, and
set aside. Butter a 9-inch springform pan, dust with flour and tap
out the excess flour.
</P>
<P>
   2. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. In the bowl of an electric
mixer, combine the egg yolks and sugar. Mix well until very smooth.
Add the melted chocolate mixture, and mix to blend. Add the ground
almonds and brandy, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a clean bowl, whisk the egg whites until stiff but not
dry. Add about { cup of the beaten whites to the chocolate batter,
and stir to thin and loosen it. Carefully fold in the remaining
whites until smooth. Pour the batter into the prepared pan. Bake
until a toothpick inserted into the center of the cake comes out
dry, 35 to 40 minutes. Transfer to a rack, and allow to cool in the
pan; the center of the cake will sink slightly when cooled.
</P>
<P>
   4. When the cake is cool, remove from pan and transfer to a
serving plate. In a small pan over low heat, combine the remaining
chocolate, butter and cream. Stir with a wooden spoon until smooth
and glossy. Slowly pour the mixture over the cake, starting with a
pool in the center and letting it run down the sides. Allow to
cool, then chill in the refrigerator for { hour. Remove, and let
sit at room temperature for 20 to 30 minutes before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: one 9-inch cake (8 to 10 servings).
</P>
</TEXT>
