<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: AN OFFICE DRONE BECOMES A STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hits just keep coming this winter in television's midseason:
this week even lowly UPN got into the act.
</P>
<P>
   Proving that the network might have life after all, ``Dilbert,''
UPN's new animated version of the popular comic strip, scored the
best number of the season for that struggling would-be network.
Overnight ratings from the nation's 44 biggest cities show that
``Dilbert'' posted a 7.3 rating, which more than tripled what UPN
had been doing on Monday nights at 8.
</P>
<P>
   The rating was good enough to beat the overnight number for
well-established shows on two networks, ``Melrose Place'' on Fox,
which scored a 6.2, and ``Suddenly Susan'' on NBC, which had a 7
rating. (Each rating point in the overnight measurement represents
623,882 homes.)
</P>
<P>
   And though it was not good enough to beat the rating for
``Seventh Heaven,'' the growing hit on UPN's big rival WB, UPN can
still claim bragging rights of a sort because the premiere of
``Dilbert'' beat the overnight rating for the September premiere of
WB's highly promoted new drama, ``Felicity.'' After receiving more
attention than any other new series on any network last fall
``Felicity'' opened with a 6.5 rating in the overnight measurement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dilbert'' certainly got every ounce of promotion that UPN
could muster, but it was not helped by all the magazine covers and
other free publicity surrounding ``Felicity.''
</P>
<P>
   UPN was also happy to point out that ``Dilbert'' more than
doubled the rating of the premiere of WB's big midseason comedy
hope, ``Zoe, Duncan, Jack and Jane,'' which scored an 3.2 rating.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune of `Providence'
</P>
<P>
   Despite getting ratings that dwarfed any comedy previously on
UPN, ``Dilbert'' will not be considered the salvation of the
network until it proves it can bring the viewer back next week and
every week thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   But the record of the shows that have been introduced this
winter after heavy promotion is exceptionally good. On Fox, ``The
PJ's,'' which turned up during every timeout on two football games
and then scored the best ratings of any new comedy on Fox, has held
up well, more than doubling Fox's performance at 8:30 on Tuesday
nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``60 Minutes II'' won a similar barrage of promotion on CBS and
opened with hitlike numbers on Wednesday at 9 p.m. The ratings
diminished only slightly in the second week and the show made an
impressive jump in the rating over the weak comedies that preceded
it at 8 and 8:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest story of the midseason continues to be NBC's
``Providence,'' which has now had three weeks to demonstrate how
strong it is: all three weeks it has dominated its Friday 8 p.m.
time slot.
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps the most eye-catching comparison, ``Providence'' is
the only new drama to win its time period in total viewers and
young adult viewers its first three weeks since ``E.R.'' went on
NBC five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The next new potential midseason hit on the horizon is Fox's
``Family Guy,'' yet another animated comedy. It will get perhaps
the best promotion of all on Sunday night when the show's pilot
follows what is sure to be the highest- rated show this year: the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The staying power of ``Family Guy'' will remain a mystery for
some time, however, because new episodes will not appear until
March.
</P>
<P>
   Golden Globes Golden
</P>
<P>
   Last year when ``Titanic'' was a phenomenon the movie industry
had not seen for decades, if ever, NBC rode the interest in the
film to the best showing ever by the Golden Globe Awards ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   No movie this year had anything like the following of
``Titanic'' and so the even better performance of the Golden Globes
ceremony on Sunday night has NBC executives more convinced than
ever that the show has become second only to the Academy Awards _
and possibly the Grammy Awards _ as an awards show attraction on
television.
</P>
<P>
   The telecast of the ``Golden Globes'' set another record for
NBC, climbing from a 15.9 rating last year to a 16.1 this year.
(Each national rating point represents 994,000 homes.) That left
every other award show this season in the dust including the Emmy
Awards and ``The People's Choice Awards.''
</P>
<P>
   It may also be hard for the Grammy Awards presentation next
month to beat that figure, though last year that show had a 17
rating. But that was up considerably from recent Grammy ratings.
</P>
<P>
   What is more remarkable is the growth in interest in the Golden
Globes in the four years the show has been on NBC. Each year, more
people have watched the presentation, resulting in more stars
turning up for the event, which, of course, has increased the
ratings further.
</P>
<P>
   Five year ago the Golden Globes presentation was still a
small-time awards with a small-time audience on cable television.
The last year the show was televised on the TBS cable channel it
scored only a 2.5 rating. That means almost eight times as many
people watched the show this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
