writes about Denver's controversial tight end Shannon Sharpe.
(Archdeacon, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   FBN-CERRABINO-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ For the first
time in its 33-year history, the Super Bowl will be played while an
impeached American president is on trial in the U.S. Senate. You
may think this is coincidental. You may even imagine that the two
events, each of them grand spectacles on the American stage, have
no connections or similarities. But you probably haven't given this
as much thought as I have. If you did, you'd see that the
connection between these two pageants might seem tenuous at first.
But not when you take a deeper look. (Cerrabino, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SHARPE-COX _ The goal is to find out what Denver Broncos
tight end Shannon Sharpe was like before he got to the NFL, before
he had the nerve to call Dan Marino ``a loser,'' before he baited
Kansas City's Derrick Thomas into a Monday Night meltdown, before
he left a trail of angry fans on the road to Super Bowl XXXIII.
(Woods, Palm Beach Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NAMATH-GUARANTEE _ MIAMI _ It's been 30 years since the
quarterback, dressed in a soft green suit, grabbed food and a beer
at the New York Jets' poolside barbecue at the Galt Ocean Mile
Hotel in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., and entered a limousine headed for
Miami Springs. Details of the next four hours have been colored by
three decades of interpretation and exaggeration, by the several
hundred who came to Dade County's primo spot to crown Namath ``the
Outstanding Professional Football Player of 1968.'' But this can be
guaranteed: Namath made sport's most famous guarantee that night,
predicting the Jets, at the time 19-point underdogs, would upset
the Baltimore Colts. ``It was typical Joe,'' said New York Times
columnist Dave Anderson, who chronicled the Jets' week in the 1969
book Countdown to Super Bowl. ``You knew he might say anything. He
had been saying things like that all week, he just didn't use the
word guarantee.'' (Skolnick, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
