<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9304 &Cx1f; kan-z
a f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRUMP-MIDWEST-TWOTAKE     01-26 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUMP-MIDWEST-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY HAS A LOT RIDING ON TRUMP BID FOR FLAMINGO HILTON
CASINO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Name a building in New York City. There's a
fair chance Donald Trump owns it.
</P>
<P>
   Name a casino in Atlantic City. Ditto.
</P>
<P>
   Now The Donald's real estate empire is poised to expand again,
and for the first time into Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Gaming Commission meets Wednesday in Kansas City,
and the agenda includes the first public discussion of Trump's
surprise bid earlier this month to buy the troubled Flamingo Hilton
Casino in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers expect the flamboyant New York real estate
tycoon's $15 million, bargain-basement offer for the casino and his
application for a state gaming license to be approved later this
year with little dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly traded Trump Hotel &AMP; Casino Resorts Inc. already is
licensed by gaming authorities in New Jersey and Indiana, where the
companies have experienced few regulatory problems.
</P>
<P>
   Trump is regarded as a good corporate citizen in Gary, Ind., his
other riverboat market, and universally as a tough, even brutal,
competitor who sometimes wins the admiration of his adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   Trump executives are reluctant at this point to say how they
intend to upgrade and change the Kansas City operation, or whether
a trademark Trump hotel might be in the offing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know much about the Kansas City market yet,'' said
Joseph A. D'Amato, chief operating officer of Trump's riverboat and
300-room hotel in Gary. D'Amato is expected to play a supporting
role in establishing the Trump label in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   But the company makes it clear that Trump-flavored changes will
come.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone conference last week with gambling industry stock
analysts, Trump chief executive Nicholas Ribis hinted that the
Kansas City deal was the first of several casino acquisitions the
company hoped to announce this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This property has been beleaguered for some time,'' Ribis said
in reference to troubles that have threatened the Hilton Hotels
Corp. gambling license since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton _ the hospitality and gambling industry giant based in
Beverly Hills, Calif. _ has been troubled by the long-running
Kansas City Port Authority bribery scandal and the indictment last
month of former Hilton executive Markland Rousseau.
</P>
<P>
   The final chapter in that regulatory saga opens Wednesday when
Missouri Gaming Commission members could decide whether to sanction
Hilton or let the company walk away from its Missouri troubles.
</P>
<P>
   If the sale is approved, it will be Trump's second purchase of a
troubled Hilton casino. In the mid-1980s, Trump bought what now is
Trump Marina in Atlantic City when Hilton ran into licensing
problems in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   For Hilton, Ribis said, the Kansas City casino ``is a very small
asset to a very large company. But for us it's a major move to a
new jurisdiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Ribis also told analysts last week that the casino's general
manager would be Bruce McKee, a former Trump gaming executive who
left the company last year but is back and moving to Kansas City
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Trump officials also said they intended to offer employment to
most of Hilton's 800 current workers.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan McKenzie, the Flamingo Hilton's current general manager,
will move to Gulfport, Miss., where he is to head the recently
acquired Grand Casino under Hilton's spinoff Park Place
Entertainment Inc.
</P>
<P>
   While there are no firm development plans for Kansas City yet,
Trump spokesman Kenneth M. Ciancimino said the Trump name on the
door should be welcome news to gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Trump is adamant about providing the leading technology
and the best product in the marketplace,'' he said. ``Kansas City
will benefit from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump would assume ownership of a Kansas City casino that offers
players some of the area's highest slot machine payback
percentages, plus the area's most generous ``slot club,'' which
accumulates frequent-flier-type points for cash rebates and other
gifts.
</P>
<P>
   But the Trump organization also knows how to compete for
players.
</P>
<P>
   According to Casino Player magazine, Trump's riverboat in Gary
often is in contention for that Greater Chicago market's monthly
``loosest slots'' title, while Trump's Atlantic City casinos rank
in the middle of the pack among that city's 12 fiercely competitive
casino hotels.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Trump's solidly East Coast operation appears to be a
good fit in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I'd be giving Donald Trump a reference,'' said
Gary City Hall spokeswoman Sandy Cogan. ``But so far the Trump
organization has been an excellent corporate citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Williams, executive director of the Gary Chamber of
Commerce, agreed: ``The Trump organization has made a significant
impact on this town in more ways than one. They're involved in
many, many, many city and civic organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The casinos contribute hefty contributions to the city's
coffers. They've been a real shot in the arm.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also has awarded hundreds of thousands of dollars in
local scholarships and charitable grants since opening in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Trump officials say Kansas Citians can expect the same pattern
of civic involvement, and perhaps much more.
</P>
<P>
   Trump also is a partner in the revival of a long-abandoned hotel
in downtown Gary. Trump, who built his financial empire on real
estate deals, could take a similar interest in Kansas City real
estate.
</P>
<P>
   MORE...MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 1729EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9305 &Cx1f; kan-z
a f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRUMP-MIDWEST-2NDTAKE     01-26 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUMP-MIDWEST-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Kansas City, Mo.: take a similar interest in Kansas City real
estate.)
</P>
<P>
   If so, the property at the top of that list quite likely would
be Richard L. Berkley Riverfront Park, next door to the casino and
developed almost entirely with Flamingo riverboat lease payments,
which Trump will continue to make.
</P>
<P>
   The newly opened public park abuts the Missouri River along a
milelong promenade. An estimated 50 acres on the south side are
being aggressively marketed by the city for development of an
upscale riverview district that would include commercial, retail
and residential projects.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, another company in Trump's web of corporate
entities is developing a remarkably similar property, Trump Place,
on 100 acres along New York's Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Authority's executive director, Brian Collins, said
Monday that he was aware of the Trump Place project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting connection,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he expected to meet with Trump executives next week
for an introductory session. And he expects that Kansas City's
riverside project will come up in the conversation. ``We're
interested in whatever opportunities this new arrangement might
provide,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Will Trump and his traveling entourage become a common sight in
Kansas City?
</P>
<P>
   Don't bet on it, said Allen Kress, a former city planner for
Gary who recently moved to the same post in neighboring Hammond,
Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Trump attended the riverboat's grand opening in 1996, Kress
said, but ``I don't believe he's been back to the boat since.''
</P>
<P>
   Kress said Trump's partner in that twin casino complex, which
shares a dining and entertainment pavilion on Lake Michigan, was a
far more visible and hands-on executive in dealing with the city.
</P>
<P>
   New York City newsman Timothy L. O'Brien, in his 1998 book Bad
Bet, quoted Atlantic City consultant Al Glasgow on the Trump style:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Donald has the patience, or the interest, or the
attention span to be a hands-on operator,'' Glasgow told the
writer. ``He's just a deal maker. He blows in and then he moves on
to the next deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But other East Coast observers say Trump sometimes is seen in
his Atlantic City casinos.
</P>
<P>
   And the effect can be electrifying, said Marvin B. Roffman, now
a Philadelphia investment counselor and stock analyst whose claim
to fame is that he once sued Trump _ and won.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has tremendous charisma,'' Roffman said. ``He will walk
through the casino floor, and people will jump up and try to touch
him.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Roffman lost his job of 17 years with a New York
brokerage after Trump threatened legal action over Roffman's
bearish forecasts for Trump's Taj Mahal casino resort in Atlantic
City.
</P>
<P>
   Roffman's downbeat analysis proved to be correct; the casino
collapsed into early bankruptcy but has since recovered. Roffman
said he sued over his forced dismissal and won confidential
out-of-court settlement payments from both his former employer and
Trump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must have hit a raw nerve,'' Roffman said recently. ``I hope
I never have to go through that again. ... When you go to battle
against rich and powerful people who have very deep pockets, what
they do is wear you down.''
</P>
<P>
   William Gormley, a New Jersey senator long regarded as a Trump
ally, is another who unexpectedly found himself on the deal maker's
wrong side when he supported legislation for a casino rival.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the GOP incumbent was challenged by an unusually
well-financed political unknown who, The Press of Atlantic City
later reported, had received more than $100,000 in contributions
from contractors and others with close ties to Trump.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey bars casinos and gaming executives from making
political contributions to candidates for state office.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley handily won re-election. And Trump survived a
post-election inquiry by the New Jersey Casino Control Commission
into the questionable campaign donations.
</P>
<P>
   Soon thereafter, the state's rules were changed to close the
loophole that appeared to wink at casino officials' influencing of
the political contributions of others.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley said the experience taught him a valuable lesson about
Trump: ``All the measures I had supported over the years to benefit
Mr. Trump didn't count.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gormley has a grudging admiration for the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Donald is a brilliant businessperson. He's very tough,''
Gormley said. ``He is not your average foe in the political arena.
He has a keen understanding of the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you'd better realize Donald works 18 hours a day. ... If
you're going to disagree with him, you should be well prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Another longtime Trump watcher in New Jersey asked not to be
identified because of his sensitive role in the gambling industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give Donald a lot of credit for being able to push
financial, legal and regulatory matters to their absolute breaking
points but without actually breaking them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hires lawyers better than anyone. While he may be seen as
crafty, shrewd, audacious, deceptive, less than truthful and maybe
even underhanded, he's smart enough to stay clean.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
