<SLUG> BC-WORKING-WOMEN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKS ARE READY TO HELP WOMEN IN BUSINESSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether you're launching a new business or expanding an existing
one, the big question remains the same: How do you get capital?
</P>
<P>
   Women traditionally have avoided loan officers. We'll deplete
our savings accounts, borrow from relatives or max out our credit
cards rather than walk into a bank for a loan. As a result, many of
us miss opportunities because we're undercapitalized.
</P>
<P>
   But as Marlene Abbey of Oz Accommodations knows, banks _
especially small ones _ are in the business of making loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of banks, and they want your business,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Abbey received several small loans before choosing her current
banker. She encourages other consumers to shop around so they can
find someone they feel comfortable with. You need to act out of
strength and realize you can take your business to another bank,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Like many business owners, Abbey also knows from experience that
you can't get a loan without a detailed business plan. A good idea
is not enough. You need to know the market, know how much money you
will need to borrow and know how you will use and repay those
funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never prepare too much,'' agreed Mary Valentine, a
vice president at First National Bank of Olathe. ``Do your
research. Go to small-business workshops. Don't go to a banker
until you're armed with everything you need to pitch your point.''
</P>
<P>
   Numerous resources for writing business plans are available. The
library is a great place to start. Colleges have business centers.
</P>
<P>
   One misconception potential borrowers have is that they can
borrow the entire amount they need.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a lot of people coming to the bank wanting us to put in
100 percent, and they're not prepared with their share of the
capital injection,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   She said consumers are expected to provide 25 percent to 30
percent of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Another common mistake women make is maxing their credit cards
to finance a business. While that is tempting, loan officers warn
that carrying a lot of debt can be detrimental when you apply for a
bank loan.
</P>
<P>
   Architect Dixie Junk didn't apply for a loan until after her
business was established. But she encouraged other business owners
to get to know a banker long before they need to borrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets down to who believes in you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And someone who knows you and your track record is more likely
to believe in you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
