<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9312 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-TURKEY-CRUISE-     01-26 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-TURKEY-CRUISE-2NDTAKE-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: known places.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the days passed, we found another force breezing through our
group along with the warm trade winds. Our enthusiasm for
exploration, climbing and hiking slowly ebbed as the warm water and
hours of unalloyed relaxation worked their seductive power.
</P>
<P>
   While it is fine to begin such trips with a determination to
trek and discover, such resolve is likely to weaken as days pass.
But we had not turned completely indolent, and in Kas were the
beneficiary of new inspiration in the form of John Ash, a
British-born poet and Byzantine historian whom we had prevailed
upon to fly down from his home in Istanbul to guide us for a couple
of days.
</P>
<P>
   He took us first to an idyllic seaside village called Ucagiz,
formerly known as Theimiussa. There we dined at a fine seafood
restaurant with a view so enchanting that it moved two Turkish
members of our group, mother and daughter, to ask for folk music on
the cassette player; they then proceeded to demonstrate their
mastery of belly dancing.
</P>
<P>
   After lunch we hiked past the edge of town to a Lycian
necropolis. The Lycians built their tombs above ground, some of
them carved into the sides of cliffs and others as free-standing
granite structures. Some are carved with elaborate inscriptions,
and on one we distinctly made out the words ``Hey Boy,'' leading us
to dub it the Hey Boy Sarcophagus.
</P>
<P>
   On our way back to the boat we stopped at the ruins of what had
once been a grand home or palace, its imposing doorway arch intact.
</P>
<P>
   A short boat ride from Ucagiz lies the village of Simena, where
the most prominent landmark is a handsome Lycian sarcophagus that
was built on land but now, with changes in the water level, rises
from the shallow harbor about 50 feet from shore. After anchoring
near it, we climbed a steep hill to a well-preserved Byzantine
fortress built on the ruins of one from Lycian times.
</P>
<P>
   From the summit there was a spectacular view of wooded islands
dotting the multicolored sea. On the way down we stopped to admire
the smallest ancient theater I have ever seen, carved from rock in
a neat semicircle and big enough for about 250 people. Perhaps it
was an Off Broadway tryout center where stand-up bards honed their
skills for the big time at Phaselis and Aspendos.
</P>
<P>
   During our numerous swimming breaks we saw submerged remains of
several ancient towns, but resisted the temptation to join a trip
in a glass-bottom boat or, even more adventurous, a scuba diving
tour. We were, however, intrigued by Ash's assurance that there are
dozens of magnificent sites in this area that are not mentioned in
any guidebook, and challenged him to prove it. He did so most
impressively.
</P>
<P>
   When the minibus he chartered arrived at the Kas harbor the next
morning, we voted unanimously to postpone our trip because the heat
was already intense. The bus returned late in the afternoon, and we
proceeded to a spot about 35 miles north, near the village of
Dirgenler. We parked at the foot of a deep canyon, which Ash said
was the only pass in a chain of mountains near the Tarsus range.
</P>
<P>
   Lycian villagers moved inland to this region to escape seafaring
raiders beginning in the eighth century A.D. To defend their homes
they built an imposing fortress overlooking the chasm below. We did
not climb to the fortress, but walked about a mile along the cliff
on a road cut by Romans.
</P>
<P>
   Near this Roman road, in the middle of a verdant valley, Ash led
us through a farmer's yard and past a herd of grazing goats to the
glorious ruin of a very large Byzantine church. Towers and walls
are still standing, along with two octagonal chambers on opposite
corners. We were told that they are all but unique in Turkey and
that their purpose remains obscure.
</P>
<P>
   The size and dignity of the structure, the rich colors of the
surrounding landscape, and the sense that very few outsiders have
seen this place in recent centuries combined to make the experience
deeply moving.
</P>
<P>
   By this time the last remnants of pollution and stress were
purged from the psyches of everyone aboard. We still had a couple
of days left, and we stopped at several small coves. There we swam
and viewed a few more ancient sites, among them a Roman bath that
is now half-submerged and thus once again available for bathing.
</P>
<P>
   Several times we were visited by a skiff carrying a local man
and his son who peddle ice cream to passengers on visiting boats.
His prices were double those ashore, but we were willing buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Before ending our voyage we stopped at the town of Fethiye,
which in ancient times was famous for soothsayers. I didn't find
one, but if I had, I suspect he or she would have predicted that
most of my companions and I would sooner or later be drawn back to
Blue Anatolia. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you go &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many companies have sprung up to offer versions of the blue
cruise, either as brokers or actual vessel operators. Some charge
exorbitant prices, such as one based in London with which I first
negotiated. The best way to organize trips is through an American
travel agency that regularly sends clients to Turkey _ try Pasha
Tours at (212) 764-4080 _ or directly with cruise operators in
southern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   The company from which my friends and I rented our gulet,
Fantezi, may be telephoned in Antalya beginning in the spring at
(90-242) 814-6233. Other reliable operators based in Bodrum include
Aegean Yacht Services, (90-252) 316-1517, fax (90-252) 316-5749,
and Alesta Yachting and Travel, (90-252) 612-3054, fax (90-252)
614-2571; and Dolphin, (90-242) 248-4040, fax (90-242) 248-4538, in
Antalya.
</P>
<P>
   Prices vary widely according to the month, length of trip and
size and type of vessel. Aegean's prices range from $200 daily for
a modest six-cabin vessel with crew in April or November to $6,500
daily for a deluxe 18-cabin vessel in July and August. Alesta's
range from $280 daily for a four-cabin gulet in May or October to
$1,440 daily for a 10-cabin ketch at peak season.
</P>
<P>
   The crew normally includes a cook who buys food and prepares all
meals, but prices do not include the cost of food or drinks. It's
customary to tip crewmen at the end of a trip; we gave each of our
three crewmen $100.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
