<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9318 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CLASSES-ART-NY     01-26 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CLASSES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAR TURNS BY STAR TEACHERS: CLASSES IN THE CALLAS TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (HLW)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Every once in a while, the performing arts come up
with a whole new category. Music, having explored the concert, the
opera and the liederabend, now brings us the master class: the solo
recital with a difference. Thomas Hampson and Marilyn Horne starred
in their own master class productions just recently at the
Juilliard Theater. Leontyne Price, Roberta Peters, Regine Crespin,
Joan Sutherland and Elly Ameling had preceded them, and Sherrill
Milnes takes the boards next week.
</P>
<P>
   The raging success of Terrence McNally's ``Master Class'' on
Broadway a few years back, with Zoe Caldwell as McNally's version
of Maria Callas, has made the real thing more attractive to
everyone concerned: organizers able to win new audiences, the
audiences themselves hoping to bask in insider wisdom, and the
teachers, too. Hampson is in his prime as a singer, but most of his
colleagues in this highly public educational endeavor are not.
Retired or retiring divas quite naturally miss their old ardent
following, and through the master class the public is made to
remember and show respect.
</P>
<P>
   Should we worry that McNally's entertainment had little to do
with teaching and almost nothing to do with music? I think not.
Playwrights deal with people's heads and insides, not breath
support. The private soul of Callas was turned inside out in the
quasi-fantasy of ``Master Class,'' with self-absorption as public
rant and daydreams said out loud.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Master Class'' exaggerates the facts, it does get close to
uncomfortable truths: that the true exercise of its subject matter
is more about the teacher than the taught, that its format assures
that even with the best of intentions the student is the least
important element involved.
</P>
<P>
   Callas aficionados probably remember every recorded word she
uttered during her famous master classes at the Juilliard School in
1972, but I don't think any of them know who her momentary pupils
were, nor do they really care. Maybe they were not much good and
not worth remembering, but in name at least this event was about
them.
</P>
<P>
   For the uninitiated, the musical master class is an odd
combination of show business and personal tutoring whereby a series
of students _ singers, pianists, violinists, for example _ play or
sing briefly over the course of a few hours and receive brief words
of wisdom from the master in attendance. He or she is customarily a
performer of stature, though occasionally a star teacher. The
transaction takes place before an audience, often a paying one.
</P>
<P>
   Promised is a win-win-win situation. The student learns. The
master shows not only depth of learning but also compassion for
one's inferiors. The music lover in the seats sees a bit of music
from the inside out and learns the tips and tidbits that apparently
turn dross into gold. There is also the flattering feeling among
audience members that they are in on the teaching. After specific
ministrations to a singer, Hampson often turned to the orchestra
seats, asking, ``Do you hear the difference?'' En masse, listeners
beamed in complicity even if they didn't hear it.
</P>
<P>
   It is the audience that changes everything. Whom are they there
to pay attention to? If you say the student and the music, I don't
think you are being honest. The master class is first of all about
an audience and a star. The equation goes something like this:
Performing artist is to song what master class teacher is to
student. The singer interprets the song; the master class singing
teacher interprets the student.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the purpose is to stimulate a public. Not that
teachers don't care about what or whom they are teaching; not that
students don't sometimes learn. Good things happen: secrets are
passed, changes made.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the exceptional sound will disrupt the normal process.
One young woman at Ms. Horne's morning session sang with a quality
that made me forget everything else. But students in this situation
will always be props in another, more prominent show going on
beside them.
</P>
<P>
   Hampson and Ms. Horne were very different teachers. He a general
principles man, she a line-by-line editor. In matters of posture
and mental preparation, Hampson often repeated himself. This is
less interesting for an audience always wanting something new, but
it spoke of basic values that students can call upon when no
teacher is around. I liked a lot of them, especially the formula
for overly aggressive interpreters: ``Don't go looking for passion;
make it come to you.'' This is an image as valuable to pianists or
violinists as it is to singers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Horne was concerned with the song at hand: how to phrase
each line, alter tempos, place accents, extend breaths. She tells
students that these are her private decisions and not necessarily
those of others, but it is very clear that she expects to get what
she wants. If I were a singer preparing Wolf's ``Kennst du das
Land'' or ``In dem Schatten Meiner Locken'' for the public, I would
make a beeline for Ms. Horne. If I were looking for broader values
that would fit in my pocket anywhere I went, I think I'd talk to
Hampson.
</P>
<P>
   McNally's Broadway success happily tossed music aside, isolated
the master class' element of stardom and let it run wild. With road
shows and translations beckoning, stars like Faye Dunaway leaped at
the opportunity to play the part; and where more easily could one
give legitimate vent to one's own natural imperiousness? Audiences
love to watch a big ego ignite, and divalike actresses have had the
chance to play themselves without fear of embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   McNally's theatrical students were real singers, but
dramaturgically they were the movable walls off which the diva
bounced her speeches. In the theater we expect hyperbole, and we
got it. A musician will find very little recognizable in the
teacher of ``Master Class,'' but the students portrayed are another
matter. They, and the way they are used, are often dead on.
</P>
<P>
   The teaching process is customarily binary. The teacher teaches,
and the student learns. (In the healthiest situations both teach
and both learn.) Master classes dilute the transaction by
introducing outsiders. For what was previously an exchange of
information becomes a three-way dance. It is the students who play
and sing, but make no mistake, it is the masters of these master
classes who are ``on.'' The audience rules. Every role is played
out for its benefit.
</P>
<P>
   As public stimulation, the master class is first-rate
entertainment. As a learning device, it is seriously compromised.
For the teacher is sending out beams in two directions
simultaneously: toward the student and toward those watching the
teacher and the student. There is simply not enough energy to
sustain both beams.
</P>
<P>
   Master classes are fun. We should go to them, buy our tickets
and have a good time. But be careful, lest you confuse them with
higher education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
