<SLUG> BC-SHOOTER-BOOK-REVIEW-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MR. DARWIN'S SHOOTER': A DARWIN ASSISTANT WITH HINTS OF INDIANA
JONES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(lb) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scattered here and there in the copious diaries and letters of
Charles Darwin are mentions of a certain Syms Covington. ``My
servant,'' Darwin called him, continuing in one reference, ``I do
not very much like him; but he is, perhaps from his very oddity,
very well adapted to all my purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Covington, who was born to a laboring family in Bedford,
England, and died in Australia not long after the publication of
Darwin's ``Origin of Species'' in 1859, is the inspiration for
Roger McDonald's new novel, ``Mr. Darwin's Shooter,'' a
high-spirited, adventuresome, idiosyncratic ramble through the
history of science that certainly captures the ``oddity'' that
Darwin spoke of.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Darwin's Shooter'' is, in other words, a fictionalized
biography of a figure about whom the available historical
documentation would probably not permit a full-scale nonfiction
treatment. At the heart of McDonald's book is a picaresque
novelization of the years that Covington spent with Darwin in South
America during the famed voyage of the Beagle in the 1830s.
</P>
<P>
   The Covington of McDonald's novel collected specimens for
Darwin. He roamed Patagonia and other places in search of animals
and birds, and along the way he got involved in Indiana Jones-like
scrapes and romances: Indiana Jones with a briny 19th-century
flavor and a lack of scholarly understanding.
</P>
<P>
   The Covington of ``Mr. Darwin's Shooter'' is distinguished by an
understandable failure to realize that he is working for one of the
greatest scientific thinkers of his century; his religious beliefs
also lead him to be troubled by the thrust of his master's
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   As McDonald shapes Covington's semi-imaginary life, he rubs up
against the Big Questions that Darwin's theory raised, expressed by
McDonald in an earthily poetic vernacular.
</P>
<P>
   Stumbling over the ``black lava'' of the Galapagos Islands,
where ``the most old-fashioned antediluvian animals'' can be found,
Darwin and Covington are startled by what they see: ``proof that
God's hand sizzled here with one thing, there with another, and the
chambers of his gallery were infinite in their on-going.''
</P>
<P>
   Darwin himself is a powerful figure who fills up the background
space of McDonald's book, but it is the rough-and-tumble, querulous
figure of Covington who dominates the foreground.
</P>
<P>
   We first meet him when he is a teen-ager in Bedford in 1828,
leaving home in the company of a kind of seagoing, born-again
Congregationalist named John Phipps. Later we see him near the end
of his life, living as a prosperous agricultural entrepreneur in
Australia, raising a brood of children and anxiously awaiting a
copy of ``Origin of Species,'' wondering if he will be mentioned in
the acknowledgments.
</P>
<P>
   Covington becomes friends with a doctor-adventurer named
MacCracken, originally from Boston, and it is through MacCracken's
often astonished eyes that we view Covington: physically scarred,
nearly deaf, furiously righteous, and raging against the
theological implications of Darwin's theory.
</P>
<P>
   ```Non-creation,' said Covington, `is the idea that the Garden
of Eden and the Flood of Noah are merely stories men tell each
other .... Non-creation is the notion that there's been more time
on earth than any mortal is able to calculate, and that those who
love the Bible are fools. One such a fool stands before you,
MacCracken.'''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald alternates between the later Covington and the youthful
one of the Darwin years, with both periods well grounded in
historical detail. We experience Covington as a member of a family
of horse butchers in England, then follow him on board ships to
South America in the company of the evangelizing Phipps, and in his
job as bird-shooter in Argentina, where he explains to his paramour
the method of skinning a winged specimen so that the feathers
remain undisturbed.
</P>
<P>
   Covington's relationship with Darwin is cleverly imagined, seen
mostly from Covington's point of view, but always comically
marinated in the deep differences between the two men: one an
advantaged, understated genius, the other a coarser, more desperate
figure caught between the need to please and the need to assert his
self-respect.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Darwin complains at one point of some samples Covington brought
him from the fields and skies of Argentina: ``But you have too many
of the same kind. What is this?''
</P>
<P>
   Covington replies, ``It came skimmin' along the water.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is half shot away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A pinch is better than a peck, ain't that right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not in the case of birds, I am afraid,'' Darwin says.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald, who is an Australian writer of poems, travel essays
and screenplays as well as several novels, shows a knack not only
for a pungent sort of historical reconstruction but also for
characters of craggy fragility.
</P>
<P>
   His MacCracken _ a man who recognized ``that a point in his life
had arrived when he was tired of who he was, and had come to feel a
flimsiness of character running right through to the physical'' _
would be a good candidate for best literary supporting character of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   And Covington's alternation between a self-protective obedience
and brash independence of spirit makes for a spicy study in
19th-century class awareness.
</P>
<P>
   By the time we see him late in his life in Australia, a crusty,
monied paterfamilias with a penchant for absolutist gestures, we
feel we understand the origin of the species known as Covington.
And when, thinking about John Phipps and Charles Darwin and a
certain Mrs. Fitzpatrick whom he met on the pampas, Covington faces
his end, it is with an elegiac courage that seems to be the sum of
all of the man's many parts and experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no words in Covington's lexicon to pin himself
down,'' McDonald writes. ``He was a man of action _ yet strangled
by philosophy you might say.'' Fortunately, McDonald's lexicon was
equal to the task of summoning up out of facts and admiration a
character you are not likely soon to forget.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MR. DARWIN'S SHOOTER'
</P>
<P>
   By Roger McDonald
</P>
<P>
   365 pages. Atlantic Monthly Press. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
