<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9336 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POPE27-COX     01-26 1421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POPE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POPE CHALLENGES AMERICAN POLICIES ON ABORTION, ASSISTED DEATH
 &HT;    540&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By Bob Deans
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ His own legacy tainted by scandal, President Clinton
on Tuesday paid tribute to the moral heroism of one of the most
towering spiritual figures of the 20th Century, praising Pope John
Paul II for his ''limitless faith,'' and his role in the
''revolution of values and spirit'' that helped end the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   The Pope, in his seventh visit to the United States, responded
with a direct challenge to American policies on some of the most
divisive political dilemmas of the age, including abortion,
euthanasia and racial equality.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving here from Mexico for a two-day visit to this hub of
heartland Catholicism, the pontiff summoned the echoes of American
slavery, saying that ''After untold suffering, and with enormous
effort, that situation has, at least in part, been reversed.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the country now stands at the brink of a new social
divide that pits the interests of spiritually-centered Americans
against groups that lack ''a higher moral vision.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Today the conflict is between a culture that affirms,
cherishes and celebrates the gift of life, and a culture that seeks
to declare entire groups of human beings _ the unborn, the
terminally ill, the handicapped, and others considered unuseful _
to be outside the boundaries of legal protection,'' the Pope said.
''Only a higher moral vision can motivate the choice for life.''
</P>
<P>
   His remarks were met with cheers and applause from an audience
of several thousand people who turned out at the Lambert St. Louis
International Airport, chanting at many times, ''We love you, John
Paul two.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who journeyed here on a day when the fate of his office
continued to hang in the balance as the Senate presided over his
impeachment trial hundreds of miles away, did not respond directly
to the Pope's message, delivered in a hangar normally reserved for
F-15 warplanes flown by the Missouri Air National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the president looked on as the aging pontiff spoke,
slowly and deliberately, his head bowed toward his text, in
heavily-accented English.
</P>
<P>
   Retiring to a small room for a private, 20-minute meeting with
the Pope afterward, Clinton told reporters it was ''a great joy,''
to meet with the spiritual leader of the world's 1 billion Roman
Catholics - half of all Christians on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ''He reminds us to think of the people, not just the governments
of other countries, but the people of other countries,'' Clinton
said. ''That's an important thing for an American president to keep
in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   During the private meeting, the Pope raised a host of American
policy issues over which the White House and the Vatican are split.
</P>
<P>
   Among those was the U.S. policy of containing Iraq, using
military force and economic sanctions the Pope has criticized as
harmful to Iraqi citizens.
</P>
<P>
   They also spoke of Cuba - where the Pope visited last year in an
effort to spotlight continuing human rights abuses and poverty
under more than three decades of rule by Communist leader Fidel
Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ''They both agreed that the progress to date has been very hard
fought and very small,'' P.J. Crowley, press spokesman for the
National Security Council, told reporters here after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In the two men's fourth meeting, the Pope also raised the
abortion issue, though Crowley insisted the matter was tangential
to the broader discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ''The pontiff's views on the respect for dignity and human life
are well-known,'' Crowley said. ''It did come up in passing.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidently weary from his travels, the Pope, 78, cut out a long
paragraph from the prepared text of his public remarks, eliminating
a powerful plea for global peace and economic equality, as well as
a bid for an international land-mine ban that Clinton has declined
to sign.
</P>
<P>
   He extended his blessings to all of the country's 61 million
Catholics, as well as to ''people of all religions and for every
person of good will.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hailed the life and work of the Pope, a native of Poland
who became supreme pontiff in 1978, has championed human rights
around the world, lent spiritual inertia to the Polish worker's
movement that helped usher in the demise of the Soviet Union, and
survived a gunshot wound by a would-be assassin in 1981 and an
attempted knifing the following year.
</P>
<P>
   ''For 20 years, you have lifted our spirits and touched our
hearts,'' Clinton said. ''Through it all you have given of yourself
with a boundless physical energy, which can only find its source in
limitless faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton praised the pontiff's efforts to bring about the end of
the Cold War, and for ''standing for human dignity, human rights
and religious freedom'' around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ''We honor you for helping to lead a revolution of values and
spirit in Central Europe and the former Soviet Union, freeing
millions to live by conscience, not coercion, and freeing all of us
from the constant fear of nuclear war,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''People still need to hear your message that all are God's
children, all have fallen short of His glory,'' Clinton said, and
''all the injustices of yesterday cannot excuse a single injustice
today.''
</P>
<P>
   As strong as the public words of either man, however, was the
stark symbolism inherent in the meeting between Clinton, the
scandal-tarnished 42nd president of the world's last remaining
superpower, and the aging Vicar of Christ, the 264th supreme
pontiff in a line stretching back nearly 2,000 years to the
disciple of Jesus, St. Peter.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to emerge from a year of political purgatory, Clinton
journeyed here in what was, in some respect, the ultimate stop
along the road to redemption he embarked upon publicly last
September with his White House admission that ''I have sinned.''
</P>
<P>
   And, while administration aides insisted that Tuesday's brief
private meeting was focused on such policy matters as Iraq, Kosovo
and world poverty, the president's admitted personal failings
couldn't have been far from each leader's mind.
</P>
<P>
   The Pope, after all, has put the need for morally-based
governance at the heart of his mission throughout a career that has
spanned half a century of global turmoil and suffering at the hands
of misguided political and military leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''Against the delusion that has made such a mess of the 20th
Century - mainly that politics and economics is what runs the world
- the Pope has insisted that what really motors history is culture,
is moral conviction, in particular, religiously-influenced moral
conviction,'' said the Bethesda, Md.-based theologian George
Weigel, author of a biography of the Pope, entitled ''Witness to
Hope,'' due out later this year. ''He can only be understood as a
thoroughly convinced Christian disciple.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's public reception was clearly the Pope's event, as
evidenced by the response of the several thousand people who came
bearing tickets distributed by local parish administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she was more excited about seeing Clinton or the
pontiff, Deborah Dell responded ''The Pope - but it's kind of an
added extra seeing the president.''
</P>
<P>
   She said her family hadn't been able to avoid speculation about
the unique circumstances of Clinton's meeting with the Pope, their
first meeting since the Monica Lewinsky scandal broke a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''My husband and I joked a little bit about it,'' said Dell, who
brought her two daughters, Melissa, 14, and Kristen, 10, to
Tuesday's event. ''We'd kind of like to know what the Pope would
say to the president about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she paused, added that her family supports the president,
and shrugged, ''We all make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no mixed emotions, either, for Lisa Portilla, who, in
shades of Biblical stories of the infirm being taken to Jesus,
braved crowds to bring her son Gregory, 3, who is wheelchair-bound
due to a development disorder.
</P>
<P>
   She was rewarded for her faith when Clinton led the Pope to the
young boy, whom the pontiff leaned over and blessed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't tell you what it meant when the Pope touched his
head,'' Portilla gushed afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you're looking for divine intervention, this is the place
to be,'' she said. ''I'm not necessarily expecting a miracle, but
I'm sure hoping for one.''
</P>
<P>
   end
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
