A9338 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-IMPEACH-AZR &LR;      01-26 0371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IMPEACH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE SHOULD LIMIT TIME FOR WITNESSES  
 (ADV: THIS EDITORIAL WILL APPEAR IN THE JAN. 27 ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Democrats are clamoring to dismiss the case against
President Clinton. Even most Americans who believe Clinton is
guilty think he should stay in office. With the impeachment trial
now in its third week, many Republicans are looking for ways to
bring it to a close without short-circuiting the process and
violating constitutional procedures.
</P>
<P>
   We applaud those efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions the Senate makes today on whether it takes
depositions from witnesses, requires them to take the stand in the
Senate chamber or hears no witnesses at all will be crucial in
deciding when and how this trial ends.
</P>
<P>
   Even some conservative Republicans are urging closure. Said Sen.
Richard Shelby of Alabama: ``Let's close this thing out. Let's vote
on it, up or down.''
</P>
<P>
   But if enough senators disagree with Shelby to prolong the
trial, as seems likely, we offer another suggestion: Give each side
time to call witnesses, but make the time limited and then enforce
the limits.
</P>
<P>
   This would follow the pattern set when the Senate limited each
side's opening arguments. Give the House managers, say, two days to
put on their best witnesses. Then give the White House two days to
put on theirs. Both sides know going in what the time frame is and
can plan their strategies accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   The important thing is that the trial not be allowed to drag on
for weeks. Nobody - especially not Republicans - has anything to
gain from prolonging the process. Witnesses from both sides could
be heard in a week.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the value in guiding the process to closure is the
public's disinterest. The public is disengaged - so disengaged, in
fact, that the Senate meeting in secret sessions on Monday and
Tuesday drew a big yawn. That's a shame. The forum should have be
open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   We are disappointed that Arizona Sens. John McCain and Jon Kyl
supported secret deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   It's the public's business the Senate is conducting, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Senators would be wise to remember that. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
