<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The following text accompanies the weather map for Wednesday,
Jan. 27, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Record to near-record low temperatures will chill parts of
central California early Wednesday morning in the wake of a Pacific
disturbance that brought rain, snow and thunderstorms to the state
on Tuesday. Because the system merely brushed the California coast
early Tuesday when weather balloons were launched over land, a
reliable gauge of its maximum strength was not possible. However,
based on the shape and texture of the system's clouds on satellite
imagery, the system was and will be rather formidable.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the sluggish but potent disturbance will bring snow
to the mountains of Arizona and western New Mexico as it presses
eastward. Later Wednesday night or Thursday, rain and thunderstorms
will develop across parts of Texas as the east-bound system draws
increasingly moist air northward from the Gulf of Mexico. Strong
thunderstorms are possible.
</P>
<P>
   The storm system that produced three inches of snow at
Bakersfield, Calif., on Monday (which marked only the third
measurable snow in the city's history) will weaken as it crosses
the upper Middle West. A stripe of light to moderate snow will fall
from Michigan's upper peninsula across parts of northern Minnesota
into North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   Across the central Gulf Coast and Southeast States, a trend
toward record warmth will begin Wednesday as a warm high-pressure
system expands northward from Florida. Warmth will spread to the
Middle Atlantic States, but it will not be able to reach New
England as Canadian air builds into the region later Wednesday and
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Winter Spouts
</P>
<P>
   Rotating motions detected by radar in thunderstorm clouds led
forecasters to alert mariners for possible waterspouts off the
southern California coast on Monday. Though there were no confirmed
reports, winter is the season for offshore twisters in California.
Waterspouts form when cold air overlies relatively warm water.
These unstable conditions encourage fast-rising currents of air
that, given a weak spin in the atmosphere, can lead to the
formation of a waterspout. With air temperatures at 20,000 feet
near 20 degrees and sea temperatures near 60 degrees, conditions
were ripe for waterspouts.
</P>
</TEXT>
