<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Wednesday, Jan. 27. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
AMWEST (Phoenix) - Phoenix Mayor Skip Rimsza is scrambling to see
what Phoenix can to do keep America West Airlines here. He's
reminding airline officials of the $466 million the city's poured
into airport improvements - many of them to directly benefit the
hometown airline. He's trying to get the mayors of Columbus, Ohio
and Las Vegas to join with him in ensuring the three hub cities
speak with one voice on America West's fortunes, and on Tuesday he
reminded federal Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater of the
city's concern about keeping the airline here. Slater's opinion is
vital in any anti-trust review of airline mergers by the Department
of Justice. And the mayor talked to Southwest Airlines about his
strategy. Rimsza said he was blindsided by United's announcement
last week that it was looking at buying America West. Just six days
earlier, the mayor said, AmWest officials were in his office,
pushing him to speed up airport-expansion projects that would aid
the airline. By MARY JO PITZL. Story will move in the ``F''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SOMMER-OBIT (Undated) - Frederick Sommer died Saturday in Prescott,
Ariz. He was 94. Sommer was the most important artist living in
Arizona, with a world-wide reputation (he had a one-man show at the
Getty a few years ago) and was friends with such important names as
Max Ernst, Edward Weston and Charles Sheeler. He was not an artist
that the public knew widely, but was revered by other artists, and
was one of those highly innovative people who generate ideas that
others later feed off of. By RICHARD NILSEN. Story will move in the
``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AIRPORT-GOLF (Phoenix) - The rich, as you may have heard, are not
like you and me. For one thing, they are rich while the rest of us
are not. For another thing, they do not travel like you and me.
They travel in corporate jets or private jets. Jets that cost more
than your house. Jets that are nicer than your house. And this week
for the Phoenix Open, every corporate or private jet in the world
that isn't in Miami for the Super Bowl is cooling its jets at the
Scottsdale Airport. By CLAY THOMPSON. Story will move in the ``S''
and ``L'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AZNOTES (Phoenix) - What Arizonans are thinking about the Senate
impeachment trial. By JULIE AMPARANO. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SOUPERBOWL-FOOD (Phoenix) - Don't let the bad pun stop you from
considering our suggestion: Throw a Souper Bowl Party on Sunday.
It's just familiar enough, and just different enough, that your
friends will love it. Last year, we invited a few people to bring
their favorite soups over and watch the game. Surprise! The game
was a really good one, and the soups were even better. With two
recipes. By JUDY WALKER. Story moved in the ``D'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
EDIT-IMPEACH (Phoenix) - If President Clinton's impeachment trial
is extended,as seems likely, we offer a suggestion: Give each side
time to call witnesses, but make the time limited and then enforce
the limits. Story moved in the ``K'' category. &QL;
