<HEADER>
A9357 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-MYSTERY-SWAMP-     01-26 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MYSTERY-SWAMP-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKULKING AROUND IN THE SWAMP 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Jan. 31) 
(JT) 
 By MARILYN STASIO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whisper the words ``Key Largo'' in my ear and I am suddenly
tanned and barefoot, toes curled around the rung of a bar stool,
nodding at the tall tales of marlin fishermen and watching a fat
red sun sinking into the bay. When two guys in baggy linen suits
push through the screen door and put a round into the jukebox, the
bartender, who is a friend of mine, casually advises me to slip out
the back. A drug bust? A movie conference? I just laugh and toss
another beefsteak to the big bull alligator who lives at the far
end of the dock. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute _ this scene feels familiar. Didn't I read it
somewhere? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Let's put it this way: my brain has been soaked in so many crime
novels set in southern Florida that I have a hard time separating
life from fiction. If I'm in Miami, I expect to see Charles
Willeford's burned-out homicide detective Hoke Moseley slouching by
on his way home to El Pelicano Arms, the seedy apartment house he
manages on Singer Island. In Fort Lauderdale, there's always a
party in progress on slip F-18 in Bahia Mar, the yacht basin where
John D. MacDonald's beach-bum hero Travis McGee moors the Busted
Flush, the snazzy houseboat he won in a poker game. And if we're
down in the Keys, the private eyes and adventurer sleuths are
thicker than palm fronds on the sidewalks after a hurricane. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's just something about this place that makes criminals,
crime writers and sensation seekers out of people who would never
make a moral ripple anywhere else on the planet. Susan Orlean gets
it so right, in ``The Orchid Thief'' (Random House), when she
writes that ``the state of Florida does incite people. It gives
them big ideas ... Florida seems like the kind of place where you
can try anything.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Orlean found her real-life role model for this buccaneering
spirit in one John Laroche, a criminal entrepreneur who went into
business with the Seminoles on a horticultural enterprise that
involved poaching wild orchids from the Fakahatchee Strand, a
wilderness preserve just south of Naples. You couldn't get me into
this primordial bog _ a place teeming with cottonmouths and
diamondback rattlers and sundry other creatures that bite your
flesh and drink your blood _ if you put a gun to my head. But I,
too, am a sucker for eccentric locals like Laroche, brazen rogues
who seem to self-propagate, like certain gaudy species of poisonous
flower, in the almost indecently fertile climate of southern
Florida. Luckily for me, Carl Hiaasen, James W. Hall, Elmore
Leonard and like-minded novelists can't get enough of these
characters, either. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hiaasen's villains run to greedy land developers with visionary
schemes for turning the state into a theme park, the crooked
politicians in cahoots with these despoilers, and the freelance
scavengers who swoop down to pick over their leavings. But his
heroes _ eco-terrorists who launch crackpot crusades to stop the
rampant exploitation of the environment _ are just as bizarre. In
``Tourist Season'' one of these unhinged folk heroes thinks he can
discourage the land-grabbers by ritualistically tossing tourists to
the alligators. (A nice idea that almost works.) Another crusader,
a former governor named Skink who dropped out to live in the swamps
on a diet of road kill, periodically emerges from seclusion to
exercise his righteous rage. ``Don't you love this place!'' he
exults, during one rampage of violent retribution in ``Stormy
Weather'' (Knopf). ``Don't it bring out the beast in your soul!'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Skink may be crazy, but he's got a point. People do tend to lose
their inhibitions in Florida crime novels. Even hardened killers
aspire to new styles of decadence when they feel that hot sun at
their backs and the warm sand between their toes. Cundo Rey, a
Cuban hit man in Elmore Leonard's ``La Brava'' (Arbor House),
pursues a second career as a go-go dancer in a South Beach disco. A
serial killer who calls himself Butler Jack hijacks a cruise ship
out of Miami in James W. Hall's ``Buzz Cut'' (Delacorte) and
initiates a reign of high-seas terror as brilliant as it is
perverted. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In this sultry climate and under the influence of the let-it-be
natives, your average law-abiding citizen can also run amok.
Charles Willeford captured that ineluctable impulse in
``Sideswipe'' (St. Martin's) with a retired auto worker named
Stanley Sinkiewicz. After a lifetime of painting the racing stripes
on cars, Stanley now saunters out from his Riviera Beach home each
morning with a full day's supply of cyanide pills in the
hollowed-out shaft of his wooden cane. ``Thanks to Stanley's
skill,'' we learn, ``the neighborhood was shy one boxer, one
Doberman, and one Pekingese.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the temperate climate and lackadaisical life
have had a distinctly ennobling effect on the over-the-hill
mobsters who go native in Laurence -Shames' stories. ``One visitor
in a thousand ... probably more like one in 10 thousand, was not a
tourist but a refugee,'' according to a real estate agent who spots
one of these rare birds in ``Tropical Depression.'' Sooner or
later, they all cross paths with Bert the Shirt d'Ambrosia, an aged
Mafia don who sits by the sea in his splendid shirts, stroking his
ancient chihuahua (how'd he ever escape Stanley Sinkiewicz?) and
dispensing sage advice to hot-blooded young gangsters who come
roaring down from New Jersey in fast cars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With all the unstable characters who come to town in these
books, the local sleuths are searching for ways to maintain their
own sanity. James W. Hall's hero, a moody guy named Thorn, lives in
Thoreauvian seclusion in a stilt house on Key Largo, pondering the
decline of civilization and constructing bonefish lures as
intricate and pretty as poems. Doc Ford, the marine biologist who
lives on Sanibel Island in Randy Wayne White's novels, likes to
jump into his boat and push off for some private healing place. His
destination is usually one of the barrier islands off Florida's
west coast, those isolated outposts that exude ``their own odor,
their own feel,'' he tells us in ``The Mangrove Coast'' (Putnam), a
heady mixture of ``sea water, sulfur muck, white sand, Gulf Stream
allusions and a wind that blows salt-heavy out of the Yucatan.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while somebody tries to escape before her own limbs
petrify like underwater tree roots. Alison Kerry, a young drug
runner from Key West, gets all the way to Seattle in Jenny Siler's
``Easy Money'' (Holt), but the tug of home keeps yanking her back.
The hard-boiled Allie holds no romantic illusions about the Florida
Keys. ``The outlaws' outpost,'' she calls the islands, where
``smuggling has always been a kind of family business, like farming
in the Midwest.'' But her cynicism is a fierce kind of affection,
and in the end she decides she can never untangle herself from her
roots. ``Everything in the Keys is formed by plunder,'' she says,
``even the house I grew up in, built from the timbers of a wrecked
ship, a schooner lured to the jagged reef by a phony beacon.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't look now, but Allie just walked into the bar. She's
packing her Walther in her jeans and her '69 Mustang is idling out
front. If you're up for a bet, I'd say she's waiting for John
Laroche to show up with a pillowcase full of hot orchids.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 1806EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
