<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9358 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      01-26 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FACE-TIME &QL; 
 &UR; Erik Tarloff (Crown, $23)
</P>
<P>
   Here's a novel that's also a primer on life in Washington, D.C.,
and it might explain a few things about the tawdry, real-life mess
that has played itself out over the past year despite a weary
public and the humiliation of one political figure after another.
Ben Krause fell in love with his girlfriend, Gretchen, while both
were working on Charles Sheffield's presidential campaign. Now,
Sheffield has been elected, Ben is his speech writer, and Gretchen
works in the White House social office. Things are going swimmingly
_ they have good jobs, good sex and good access (known as face
time) to the most powerful man in the world. Then, Ben discovers
that Gretchen is getting better face time than he is: She's having
an affair with Sheffield. When Ben confronts her, she swears she
does not want to break up but refuses to stop sleeping with the
president. It's too flattering, she says. A man in his position
could have any woman he wants. ``Yeah,'' a wounded Ben replies.
``It's too bad Golda Meir is dead. Without her around, I don't have
much chance for revenge, do I?'' Tarloff (he is married to Laura
Tyson, former head of Bill Clinton's Council of Economic Advisors)
has written a funny book about power, status and the sort of
calculated schmoozing that tosses moral standards into the Potomac.
Ben is a tad too earnest (he loves Gretchen with a tenacity that
probably wouldn't have survived the campaign, let alone the White
House), and Tarloff's writing is sometimes stiff. But his
descriptions of political life are eye-opening. One thing seems
certain: If Clinton had taken up with a pragmatic woman like
Gretchen instead of Monica Lewinsky, we'd be blissfully ignorant
today. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; RETURN TO MODESTY &QL; 
 &UR; Wendy Shalit (Free Press, $24)
</P>
<P>
   Here's an interesting argument from a 23-year-old author. Shalit
laments the fact that modesty today is associated with sexual
repression and suggests that many of the woes besetting modern
young women reflect a society that ``has lost its respect for
female modesty.'' Children know too much too soon. ``They end up,
in some fundamental way, (begin itals) not (end itals) knowing _
stunted and cut off from all they could be,'' she writes. ``If you
are not taught that you `really' want just sex, you end up seeking
much more.'' Virginity is a good thing. So is embarrassment _
rather than something to overcome, it is a valuable signal ``that
something very strange or very significant is going on, that some
boundary is being threatened either by you or by others.''
Furthermore, she says, a return to female modesty will inspire a
return to male honor. As we said, she's very young. But there is
truth in her perception of a collective yearning for bygone values
and in her premise that women are made to feel abnormal because of
it. ``We're not flocking to Jane Austen movies because we want the
facts,'' she writes, ``but because we're sick of having the facts
shoved in our faces all the time.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE EMPERORS OF CHOCOLATE &QL; 
 &UR; Joel Glenn Brenner (Random House, $25.95)
</P>
<P>
   When Forrest Mars' children were young, they were not allowed to
eat M&AMP;Ms. Their father was so driven to make money on the candy
that he would not spare any for his own kids. He was, as Brenner
points out, ``the Howard Hughes of candy,'' a demanding but
brilliant entrepreneur who built his family company into the
largest candy manufacturer in the world. Contrast him with Milton
Hershey, the first to make milk chocolate in America, a man who
hated financial matters and was devoted instead to the experiment
of making new products. Hershey sold his first company in midcareer
and set out to create an industrial utopia, a factory and town in
rural Pennsylvania where everything would be perfect, where almost
all of the residents would work for him and life in Hershey would
be the ultimate employee benefit. In later years, he became an
extraordinary philanthropist _ he had enough money, he said, and
saw no reason to wait to give the rest of it away. These two very
different men are at the heart of Brenner's exploration of the
candy business, a fiercely secretive, competitive, even cutthroat
industry fueled by invention and paranoia. Brenner takes us inside
the factories and boardrooms to see what has happened since others
succeeded the candy pioneers. Milton Hershey died in 1945 with only
the shirt on his back and the cash in his pocket. And Forest Mars?
According to Brenner, he came out of retirement in 1980 (at age 76)
to build another company, Ethel M. Chocolates. He lives in a
penthouse above the factory, she says, and spies on his workers
through one-way mirrors. Employees call him the ``phantom of the
candy factory.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SLAVES IN THE FAMILY &QL; 
 &UR; Edward Ball (Ballantine, $15.95)
</P>
<P>
   ``There are five things we don't talk about in the Ball
family,'' Edward Ball's father would say. ``Religion, sex, death,
money and the Negroes.'' Ball comes from a family that owned some
of the oldest plantations in the American South, more than 20 of
them along the Cooper River in South Carolina. This book, new in
paperback, is his National Book Award-winning exploration of his
family's history as slave owners. As part of his research, he
tracked down descendants of Ball slaves, unnerving some of his
relatives. ``Within the Ball family,'' he writes, ``the plantation
stories functioned like a giant self-portrait. I was making a new
painting that might change the look of the past.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Correspondent Anne Stephenson can be reached at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net via e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
