<HEADER>
A9367 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CRUISE-WEBSITE     01-26 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CRUISE-WEBSITES-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROUGH DATA PORTS OF CALL ON THE WEB  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 31) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ADAM BRYANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The building boom in the cruise industry has been matched by the
proliferation of cruise-related Web sites. And while navigating the
Internet is often called surfing, the term does not quite capture
the spirit of trying to work through all the cruise-related sites
available.
</P>
<P>
   There is, after all, a lot of territory to cover _ the Yahoo
search engine found 43 categories and 2,373 sites for ``cruises.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, there is certainly some entertainment value to
seeing through the Internet just how splintered the industry has
become, with cruises to match every taste, or mix of tastes. The
Norway is sailing on Feb. 13, for example, on a Bluegrass Music
Caribbean Celebration (www.cruise-eta.com).
</P>
<P>
   And what better reason for a floating vacation than to get a
jump on New Year's Eve celebrations with a Pre-Millennium Caribbean
Cruise in March (www.cruise-eta.com/millen.html)? Or wait until
next year for what will presumably be called the Post-Millennium
Caribbean Cruise.
</P>
<P>
   If your interests tend to be more conventional, the Internet can
offer some help in guiding you through myriad choices, though the
limitations of the medium may eventually prompt a call to a trusted
travel agent or friend who has sampled life aboard a few different
ships.
</P>
<P>
   Most cruise lines have Web sites that offer details you would
typically find in a glossy brochure, and a bit more. You can often
call up a detailed map for each deck of a ship, for example.
</P>
<P>
   The sites also contain information about destinations,
itineraries and special deals. Some try to help find a trip that
suits your needs and desires. The Cunard site, www.cunardline.com,
has an online ``cruise consultant.'' Instead of the flowery
greeting-card language that is found so many cruise sites, this
electronic Cunard consultant is all business: ``I am the virtual
cruise consultant,'' it states. ``I will find all cruises which
meet your criteria.''
</P>
<P>
   Some sites offer virtual tours of their ships, but these often
require software that must be downloaded from the Internet. That
can take time, and if your computer is at all temperamental, it may
not be worth all the trouble.
</P>
<P>
   For more guidance and suggestions, try Fielding's Cruisefinder,
www.fieldingtravel.com. It offers ratings of ships _ 12 receive its
highest rating, six stars _ and summary descriptions of the
experience. From the site you can learn about their judgment of the
popular Carnival Cruise Lines: ``While they're not to our own
particular cruising taste _ we find it hard to spend more than
three or four days aboard before the color, lights and pinging slot
machines get to us _ most Carnival passengers think they've died
and gone to heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of places to find passengers' comments,
though many complaints sound as if they resulted from a mismatch of
expectations. And glowing reviews sometimes sound as if they were
submitted by loyal ship employees.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer volume on these sites can be overwhelming, but they
are worth a look, and in some cases you can seek opinions on cruise
ships from other Web browsers. Some of these sites include
www.cruiseopinion.com, www.stutt.com/rtc/home.htm, and
www.travelpage.com.
</P>
<P>
   For a more official opinion on a cruise ship, you can go to the
Web site for the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, at
www.cdc.gov/nceh/programs/sanit/vsp/scores/scores.htm.
</P>
<P>
   The agency regularly conducts sanitation tests of the ships, and
makes available its database of scores. It even offers photographs
showing an inspector conducting tests aboard a ship, in case you
were curious about what sausages resting in a kitchen pan looked
like.
</P>
<P>
   After many hours with your hand on the electronic tiller of your
computer, you may decide that you want to talk to someone in person
and see some glossy brochures. The Cruise Lines International
Association (www.cruising.org) has a search service for travel
agents who specialize in cruises.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
