<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9368 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFFIRMATIVE27-COX     01-26 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFFIRMATIVE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLLEGE TRUSTEES MAY BE LIABLE FOR RACE POLICIES, GROUP SAYS
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Center for Individual Rights, the conservative
legal group that successfully challenged affirmative action in
Texas law school admissions, unveiled a new legal strategy Tuesday
of threatening to seek personal damages from trustees of
universities that give admission preference to minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think that trustees would be well advised to get on
this problem now and start reforming these practices now, so CIR
does not have potential clients come to us down the road,'' said
Terence Pell, senior counsel at CIR. ``Trustees need to step up to
the plate or they're going to have real problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Pell spoke at a news conference held Tuesday to publicize two
new CIR brochures, one advising students how to challenge school
admission polices and the other advising trustees of public schools
of their personal liability in racial discrimination cases. That
brochure argues that trustees of private schools are similarly
liable if their schools receive federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   Former Education Secretary William Bennett, joining Pell at the
news conference, said affirmative action programs that give
preference to minorities are ``a serious social and moral problem''
on par with the legal barriers to African Americans prior to the
1964 Civil Rights Act.
</P>
<P>
   Janelle Byrd, the lead NAACP Legal Defense Fund lawyer who faced
CIR attorneys in the Hopwood case in Texas, responded with
accusations that CIR is ``trying to create an atmosphere to
frighten trustees into dismantling legal affirmative action
programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd said she hoped that lawyers for public universities would
counsel their trustees that ``Bakke is still the law of the land,
not Hopwood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bakke'' is the famous 1978 Supreme Court ruling that struck
down racial quotas in higher education admissions, but which also
held that colleges and universities could consider an applicant's
race as one factor in determining admission. ``Hopwood'' is the
1996 ruling by the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which the
Supreme Court let stand, striking down ``diversity'' as a rationale
for considering race in college admissions.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference, Pell charged that affirmative action
programs similar or identical to those struck down at the
University of Texas are widespread in public universities
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   And while he insisted that CIR is ``not looking for more
lawsuits'' to file _ it is set to go to trial in Ann Arbor in May
on a suit challenging the University of Michigan's affirmative
action policies _ ``if potential clients find their way to our
door, we'll consider that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to expose red-neckism wherever it is, whether it's
in Mississippi or it's in Cambridge, Massachusetts,'' Bennett
vowed.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   CIR's news conference also coincided with its placement of
full-page ads in student newspapers at 15 colleges and universities
with the headline ``Guilty by Admission,' and, in bold print,
``Nearly Every Elite College in America Violates the Law. Does
Yours?''
</P>
<P>
   The targeted schools are: the University of Chicago, Columbia,
Dartmouth, Duke, James Madison, North Carolina, Pennsylvania,
Pittsburgh, Rutgers, Stanford, Virginia, Wake Forest, George
Washington, Washington University in St. Louis and William and
Mary.
</P>
<P>
   The targeting of Virginia, James Madison and William and Mary,
along with a report to be released Wednesday by the conservative
Center for Equal Opportunity (CEO) critical of ``preferential
treatment'' of blacks in admissions to 10 Virginia institutions,
suggest Virginia may be the next legal battleground in the fight
over affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence is very strong that several Virginia schools
discriminate in favor of black applicants,'' said Linda Chavez, a
former Reagan administration official who heads CEO.
</P>
<P>
   But if Virginia is the next legal battleground, Michigan is the
next state in which affirmative action foes are planning a
political fight. Ward Connerly, the architect of successful voter
initiatives in California and Washington to outlaw affirmative
action, has said Michigan is at the top of his list of target
states for the next election.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like they've got a plan,'' said Byrd. ``And I don't
think it bodes well for those of us who believe that diversity is
in the best interest of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bennett countered, ``The law says you can't treat college
applicants differently by race in order to achieve a particular
racial mix of students. Unfortunately, many of America's leading
colleges and universities break that law every year.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
