A9373 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-EARNINGS-COX     01-26 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Global economy helps Coke profits fall
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co. profits tumbled 27 percent in the fourth
quarter and 14 percent for 1998 as global economic troubles took
their toll.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterly profit decline was the biggest in years for the
Atlanta-based beverage company, which does 70 percent of its
business outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola warned last month about lackluster results, which were
in line with analysts' revised forecasts. Fourth quarter profit was
$597 million, or 24 cents a share, versus $817 million, or 33 cents
a share, a year earlier. Revenue dropped 5 percent to $4.46 billion
versus $4.70 a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock dropped nearly $2.50 a share in early
trading Tuesday but recovered to close at $62.62 1/2, down 31 1/4
cents.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman and Chief Executive M. Douglas Ivester, the native
Georgian promoted to the top job in late 1997, called his first
year at the helm ``a challenging period.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the economic environment became more uncertain and
volatile in the later part of 1998,'' Ivester added in a statement,
``we strongly believe our fundamental opportunities for long-term
growth have not changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say their near-term outlook remains clouded by sluggish
sales and currency devaluations in various Latin American, Asian
and European nations. Such devaluations can reduce profits when the
local currencies are translated into U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coke is so strong they can withstand a country or two, or even
five or six, having problems,'' said Martin Romm of Credit Suisse
First Boston. ``But when you have them slowing down en masse, it's
going to hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The next two quarters will continue to be challenging,'' said
Andrew Conway of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. Conway said currency
problems were the biggest drag on earnings in 1998, depriving the
company of almost $450 million in operating profit.
</P>
<P>
   Conway added currency woes go hand in hand with slow sales, as
reflected in Coca-Cola's numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide case volume declined 1 percent in the fourth quarter
-- in part because of fewer shipping days . For all of 1998, case
volume rose 6 percent. That figure fell short of a 7 percent goal
and was bouyed by big gains early in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Annual profit fell to $3.53 billion, or $1.42 a share, versus
$4.13 billion, or $1.64 a share in 1997. Revenue was flat at $18.81
billion versus $18.87 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Conway predicted no major strategy shifts but added Coca-Cola
``may be more resourceful in its marketing spending.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Conway and Romm said the profit downdraft shouldn't reflect
on Ivester's early tenure as successor to the late Roberto
Goizueta.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has faced a tough international situation, and under the
circumstances I think he's done an outstanding job,'' Romm said.
``I see no sign the company has lost its resolve or long-term
focus,'' he added, citing continuing acquisitions and investments.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
