A9374 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCI-INTERNET-COX     01-26 0270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCI-INTERNET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MCI makes accounts accessible on Net
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's a kind of self-service for telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom this week trotted out a new feature aimed at
letting business customers use the Internet to tinker with their
accounts, making changes on the fly without talking to any company
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Known as MCIWC Interact, the innovation and its marketing come
out of the company's large Atlanta operations, according to
spokeswoman Colleen Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we made a long-term strategic commitment to move
many of our key business processes and customer applications to the
Web,'' Cotter said. ``Our customers have been clamoring for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Interact lets a customer change network configurations and
allocate bandwidth as needed, she said. The customer may also order
new products and services, including pagers, phone lines, and
calling cards.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom, which unveiled the service at a Washington, D.C.,
trade show, charges nothing extra for the service, Cotter said.
</P>
<P>
   It will save money for both the company and its customers, she
said. ``It streamlines the entire process of how telecom invoices
are reviewed, analyzed and paid.''
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom's business markets unit, which was all MCI before
the recent merger with WorldCom, is based in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The company has about 4,000 employees in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 1817EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
