<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9376 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURNER-INTRANET-COX     01-26 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURNER-INTRANET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner, other large companies fine-tune intranetsBy Charles
Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Turner Broadcasting executives are wielding the
Internet as a scalpel, shaving business expenses while cutting new
paths to reach its 10,000 employees in Atlanta and worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   They do so through creating an expanded intranet, an online
interactive repository of information and services about their
company. The Atlanta-based company's employee directory, for
example, is now published online rather than printed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're saving $10,000 a year through our intranet,'' says
Ronnie Gunnerson, the company's vice president of corporate
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting, of course, is not alone. Nearly every big
company in town has an intranet page, including such giants as
BellSouth Corp. and First Union bank.
</P>
<P>
   But Turner Broadcasting's intranet was one of the first, and the
company is still considered a local leader in this new and growing
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of companies have tried to catch up but Turner is still
ahead of the pack,'' says Tillman Douglas, manager of sales at
ThinkAtlanta. It designs and maintains all kinds of Web sites for
companies throughout the Southeast. ThinkAltanta, for example, was
hired to redesign Turner's intranet.
</P>
<P>
   Intranets are Web sites created for internal use by a company,
school or church. Typically, only members of those organizations
can access an intranet.
</P>
<P>
   What appeals to companies about the intranet is that it can be a
low-cost way to publish and continually update corporate material
such as policy manuals, benefit plans and companywide memos or
announcements.
</P>
<P>
   Publishing online saves companies tens of thousands of dollars
in printing and updating costs annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intranet is a way that companies can make money by saving
money,'' says Scott Shamp, director of the University of Georgia's
Dowden Center New Media studies. He has also served as a consultant
on Turner's intranet efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But saving money is just the beginning, adds Shamp. He sees
intranets as a way to open two-communication among a company's top
executives and the rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next step is using the intranet to let employees tell the
company what they want,'' says Shamp.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting shares Shamp's vision for its intranet.
``The intranet opens the company up more to employees and that's a
key part of our strategy,'' says Gunnerson.
</P>
<P>
   She and her intranet manager, Molly Chase, envision the day when
the company's top executives can discuss breaking developments
about Turner Broadcasting live with employees through the intranet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could do an internal `talk back live' about, say, the
impact of Digital TV on the company's programming,'' says Chase,
referring to a CNN show.
</P>
<P>
   That day is not here yet, but the company's intranet is proving
increasingly popular among employees. The number of annual hits, a
common, if imperfect, measure of use, has grown tenfold in the past
two years to 4.2 million. That represents an average of 3,500
employee visits daily to the intranet or 25,000 a week.
</P>
<P>
   Chase says company research shows that employees have found a
wide variety of uses for the intranet. ``People are using it (for
everything from) finding in-house recommendations for a plumber to
signing up for volunteer work,'' says Chase.
</P>
<P>
   Gunnerson and Chase didn't create the company's intranet. They
inherited a strong effort already in progress, begun several years
ago by the human resources department.
</P>
<P>
   But Gunnerson has greatly expanded on the original work, adding
new services and a uniformity to the look and use of all pages.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best new features Gunnerson has added is an
electronic clipping service. Turner Broadcasting, like many media
giants, closely monitors press coverage of its many cable TV
channels.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, that work was done with scissors, paste and
photocopying. ``The PR department prepared 200 sets of clips daily
for key executives,'' says Gunnerson.
</P>
<P>
   Now that work is done online, its results open to every employee
of the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only has that helped open up the company to everyone, but
it's saved us a fortune in paper and man hours,'' says Gunnerson.
To her, that's what the intranet is all about.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
