<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barnes outlines Y2K efforts
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gov. Roy Barnes will unveil the outlines of a
broad-based Y2K program for state and local government, for
businesses and the public this Friday at the Georgia Year 2000
Utilities Forum. ``The governor sees this as an opportunity to
inform the public about the level of effort and strategy the state
will use to responsibly manage the Y2K problem,'' said spokesman
Jim Flowers.
</P>
<P>
   The forum will be held at at the Georgia International
Convention Center in College Park from 8 a.m. until 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Some 700 people have signed up for the event which also features
information on Y2K readiness and updates from representatives of
major utilities doing business in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone can attend. Reservations can be made on the Web at
(http://www.bytewise
</P>
<P>
   .com/atlyear2000) or by calling 770-641-2223.
</P>
<P>
   What to do when bug bites
</P>
<P>
   Much has been written on how to prepare for Y2K, but little has
appeared on what to do when the computer bug bites.
</P>
<P>
   That gap has been partially filled by consultant Ian S. Hayes
who spoke at the Hyatt Regency Atlanta last week.
</P>
<P>
   For businesses, the key is a crisis management organization, ``a
command and control structure that supports a company through the
transition period by capturing, directing and tracking responses to
all problems,'' Hayes explained.
</P>
<P>
   A fully staffed crisis management team, according to Hayes, is
divided into four areas. These include a crisis response team in
overall charge of the Y2K effort and a crisis help desk ``that is
the focal point for receiving and tracking all incoming issues.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are emergency teams, each with an area of expertise,
that actually performs the damage control.
</P>
<P>
   Not least, the fourth area is a legal support team that tracks
compliance and flags legal problems _ potential legal liability is
the great Y2K wild card.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes and co-author William M. Ulrich, another expert in the Y2K
arena, have collected their thoughts in a paper, ``Six Steps to
Crisis Management.'' CD-ROM copies of this work are being
distributed free. For the steps to obtain your own go to
(http://www.y2k.com) where a banner at the top of the screen will
link you to the appropriate Web site (which has a long URL).
</P>
<P>
   Rob Chambers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
