<SLUG> BC-FBC-RECRUIT27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Johnson makes commitment to UGA
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia got a much-needed commitment from a wide
receiver, but it wasn't from the one most Bulldog fans were hoping
for.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Johnson, a 6-foot-4, 215-pound receiver from Union High
School in Tulsa, Okla., committed to the Bulldogs at a news
conference Tuesday. Johnson chose Georgia over Miami, Tennessee,
Missouri, Texas Christian and Tulsa.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, wide receiver Reggie Brown of Carrollton, the No. 1
receiver prospect in the South, did not show up for his scheduled
official visit in Athens. When reached by telephone on Tuesday,
Brown's mother said her son was not available to take calls.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is losing its top two receivers from the 1998 season,
Champ Bailey to the NFL and Tony Small to graduation. The Bulldogs
also are pursuing wide receiver Durrell Robinson of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson gives the Bulldogs 22 verbal commitments. National
signing day is Feb. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia gets a player who could play several positions in
additon to wide receiver. Johnson caught 54 passes in the fall for
916 yards and 13 touchdowns. But he also started at free safety
and, because of his body type, could beef up and play tight end or
linebacker, if needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a big kid that can play,'' said Union High coach
Bill Blakenship, whose team finished 13-1 as state runner-up in
Oklahoma's highest classification. ``His heart is at receiver, but,
as a recruiter, it's a no-brainer that this kid could play wherever
you needed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Chip Towers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
