A9381 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-26 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 THE GOP DISCOVERS THE LADIES   (For use by New York Times News
Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's impeachment trial in the Senate
is so rich in irony, hypocrisy and vacuousness that after it is
over months will be needed to reflect on the folly of it all.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most immediately apparent and amazing developments,
however, is the sudden urgency the Republican House prosecutors see
in protecting civil rights, equal rights for women and the sexual
harassment laws. Over and over they stressed their deep fears that
if President Clinton is not removed from office, the lack of
punishment for his sexual irresponsibility will destroy all respect
for the rights of minorities and women.
</P>
<P>
   This is truly a remarkable advancement. Until now, House
Republicans have had a history of opposing and trying to weaken
laws meant to enforce those very concepts.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tim Johnson, D-S.D, observed wryly that there was ``a bit
of eye rolling'' among Democrats as the GOP team piously wrapped
itself and its party in an unfamiliar mantle of concern for
minority and gender rights.
</P>
<P>
   The political gender gap, reflecting the fact that women back
Democratic candidates in a greater proportion than they support GOP
candidates, opened a decade ago because women perceived the
Democrats to be more friendly toward their rights and interests
than the GOP. That party has taken up the cudgels against
affirmative action, family medical leave, minimum wage increases,
expanded funding and powers for the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission, sex education in the schools, family planning
subsidies, tougher sexual harassment measures and abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, when Clarence Thomas was confirmed as a Supreme
Court justice by mostly Republican votes despite Anita Hill's
charges of sexual harassment, public awareness of the issue has
risen dramatically. Congress and the courts constantly grapple with
definitions of just which actions constitute sexual harassment,
with somewhat mixed results.
</P>
<P>
   It was disingenuous of the Republican prosecutors to try to
transform the president's sins into a women's rights case. The
impeachment articles do not ask for a vote on whether he sexually
harassed anybody but instead accuse him of perjury and obstruction
of justice, totally separate offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying the charges are the allegations that the president
lied about his consentual sexual adventures with Monica Lewinsky.
But she initiated and encouraged their relationship and was
rewarded with gifts and the president's backing in her efforts to
find a good job in New York. Portraying her as an abused victim of
his power is silly.
</P>
<P>
   The sexual harassment issue arises only in the lawsuit filed by
Paula Jones, in which she charged that he humiliated her by
exposing himself to her in a Little Rock hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   That suit was thrown out of court by U.S. District Judge Susan
Webber Wright, who ruled that the alleged single instance of
exposing himself _ even if true _ was an insufficiently severe and
pervasive act to create a hostile environment and a cause of
action. Following the supposed incident, Jones received regular pay
raises.
</P>
<P>
   After she appealed the decision, the president settled the suit
for $850,000 without apologizing or admitting anything, a fact the
House prosecutors suggested demonstrated his guilt rather than a
desire to end the litigation hassle. They offered no evidence to
support their sinister supposition.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee originally proposed four articles
of impeachment, one of which accused the president of lying under
oath in the Jones civil case. A narrow majority of the House
rejected that article as legally unsubstantiated and inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jones case loomed large in the prosecutors' oratory in
the Senate anyway. It was their way of trying to undermine the
president's support, particularly among women who feel that backing
his overall female-friendly policies is more in their interest than
rejecting him over the issue of sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   And it was inherently dishonest. Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif.,
claimed that if the president is not dumped, it will ``send a
message ... that you might as well just keep quiet about it
(improper sexual advances) because the person can lie in court and
suffer no recrimination.'' The notion that the president has not
suffered during all this is cruel and outlandish.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, the House Judiciary Committee chairman and
leading prosecutor, bemoaned ``the damage to sexual harassment
laws'' and said that ``those are serious consequences.'' His
anguish on behalf of female victims would be more effective were he
not a leading champion of criminalizing an abortion of a fertilized
egg that could to save the life of a pregnant woman or prevent a
birth resulting from forcible rape.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy White House Counsel Cheryl Mills took on the GOP
prosecutors for dragging imaginary threats to civil rights and
female equality into the debate. She pointed out that Jones had her
day in court and that the president's overall civil rights record
is ``unimpeachable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The house of civil rights is strong because its foundation is
strong,'' she declared. ``It was never at the core of the Jones
case.'' Well said, indeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 1821EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9382 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-DESIGN31-COX     01-26 1334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-DESIGN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW DESIGN IDEAS MAKE SCHOOLS WORK BETTER FOR KIDS, COMMUNITY
 &HT;    750&AMP;add. For release Sunday, Jan. 31. With SCHOOL-POLITICS and
SCHOOL-GRAPHIC.
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ With its colorful geometric patterns, soaring
skylights and blooming gardens, Gateway Elementary, Middle and
Michael School is an oasis in a neighborhood of dilapidated homes
and crumbling factories.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-year-old public magnet school for science and technology
has won raves from parents and national leaders for delivering a
fun, quality education to even the most stubborn learners.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, classrooms are filled with a variety of animals,
hallways feature museum-quality science displays and even preschool
children are taught to work on computers.
</P>
<P>
   As politicians debate federal support for school construction
and renovation,
</P>
<P>
   Missouri is just one of several states creating a new generation
of improved learning environments for students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are what most schools want to be,'' Gateway Elementary
Principal Richard Sirna said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Education agrees. It cited Gateway in
1998 as a model school for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most noticeable differences between this school and
antiquated ones is the design of individual classrooms and overall
layout of buildings. It's actually three schools in one.
</P>
<P>
   As teaching styles evolve and technology plays an increasing
role in instruction, teachers need larger classrooms to better
accommodate computers and cooperative learning, said Richard
Passantino, the recent past chair of the American Institute of
Architects' Committee on Architecture for Education.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of cramming a room with rows of desks, Gateway
classrooms have open areas that allow students to gather in groups
or use the floor to work on projects.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say such open classrooms are better for students
because they encourage children to work together and allow teachers
to move more freely among students to assist them with their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gone from the sage on the stage to a guide on the side,''
Passantino said. ``Before, the instructor stood at the front of the
classroom and imparted wisdom onto students. Now, the instruction
is much more modified to do student research, work in groups and in
pairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Gateway has received national recognition for using all of its
available space for learning. The hallways and outdoor play areas
are filled with science stations where students can conduct
experiments. The school library has an exposed ceiling with colored
pipes to teach children which ducts carry air, water and heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's really good because they have more stuff to help
you learn,'' said 9-year-old Sarah Schofield. The hallway science
displays are ``neat, because anytime you want you can read them,''
she added.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollment steadily increases
</P>
<P>
   Overall school layout also has changed in modern schools, as
school crowding becomes a critical problem. During the next five
years, enrollment at public elementary and secondary schools is
expected to grow by 1.3 million, according to the U.S. Department
of Education.
</P>
<P>
   When planning new schools, architects and educators often must
decide how to accommodate the most students without compromising
instructional quality.
</P>
<P>
   To tackle this problem, many new schools use the ``house''
concept to create a sense of smallness among a large student body.
The school is subdivided into groups, or houses, each with its own
student body, faculty and administrator.
</P>
<P>
   At Gateway, the elementary and middle schools are combined into
one 19-acre complex. The campus also includes the Michael School
for orthopedically disabled children. While each school is
autonomous and has its own principal, they all share a common
cafeteria, library and science courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   For security reasons, schools also have moved away from designs
that create niches, nooks and crannies where students can find
hiding places for graffiti and mischief.
</P>
<P>
   Although school crime has slightly decreased in recent years,
students are more fearful than before and believe gang activity has
increased, according to a report released in October by the federal
justice and education departments.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway's youngest children play in a schoolyard surrounded by
classrooms, keeping them sheltered from the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   In some schools, administrative offices' walls are made of glass
so adults can supervise children walking through the hallway at all
times. At Gateway, most classroom doors are see-through.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   School as a community center
</P>
<P>
   The modern amenities come at a high cost. Taxpayers spent $25
million on Gateway's three schools. Still, that amount was less
than the national average cost to build three separate schools.
</P>
<P>
   The average new elementary school costs $6 million, and middle
and high schools cost about $15 million each, according to the U.S.
General Accounting Office (GAO), the auditing arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government needs to have some involvement because
voters aren't going to keep voting to raise their taxes,''
principal Sirna said.
</P>
<P>
   To gain support from taxpayers, many districts have built
schools that can be used for community programs after hours, said
Janet Stork, an educational design consultant for Project Zero, a
research institute affiliated with the Harvard University Graduate
School of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers often are more willing to pay for a school if its
theater is large enough to accommodate a community production or if
the classrooms have enough computers and other equipment to support
adult education programs at night, Stork said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our country, we need those places because lots of people
are disenfranchised,'' Stork said. ``Sometimes people don't see why
they should invest in schools because it doesn't impact them
directly. By making schools more like a community center, maybe it
gets kids feeling like the community cares about them and the
community feels like people are getting involved.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Stanley M. Makowski Early Childhood Center in
Buffalo, N.Y., includes a community day care center, and the
nurse's office is a public clinic staffed with a nurse practitioner
licensed to prescribe medication.
</P>
<P>
   Details and planning are key
</P>
<P>
   School districts often underestimate the importance of aesthetic
details when building a new school, Passantino said.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway planners used natural wood, windows and skylights to
help make the school appeal to children.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to avoiding drab colors, some schools have replaced
fluorescent lights with softer incandescent lights or larger
windows. Studies have shown that students learn better when exposed
to natural and incandescent light. A 1996 GAO report on the
condition of America's schools showed that most states report
lighting as a key problem in schools.
</P>
<P>
   But Stork warned that in their hurry to build schools quickly
and save as much money as possible, school officials need to be
especially mindful of planning.
</P>
<P>
   When planning a school, architects and educators should do a
better job of communicating with each other, Stork said. The best
schools are the result of architects listening to teachers about
their needs and teachers being open-minded about a school's budget
limitations, Stork said.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers praise a well-designed school, but acknowledge that
learning requires more than a fancy building.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best resources are the administrative resources because
they are supportive of the teachers when we try something new,''
Gateway first-grade teacher Janet Kyger said. ``It's the first time
in this district that I feel like I'm treated like a professional,
and that really makes me want to come to school and do a better
job.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
