<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9384 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-POLITICS31-COX     01-26 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-POLITICS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW BATTLE OVER SCHOOL CONSTRUCTION FUNDS EXPECTED IN CONGRESS
 &HT;    580&AMP;add. For release Sunday, Jan. 31. With SCHOOL-DESIGN and
SCHOOL-GRAPHIC.
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a move expected to spark a new partisan battle
in Congress, President Clinton wants the federal government to
authorize $22 billion in bonds to build new schools and repair old
ones, issuing tax credits to those who buy them.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Treasury department estimates the tax credits will cost
the government $3.7 billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is more ambitious than the $19.4 billion bill
backed last year by Clinton, which never made it out of a House
committee and was killed in the Senate by a 56-42 vote.
</P>
<P>
   But with many Republicans eager to get back to policy at a time
when impeachment proceedings have dragged down their poll ratings,
``We think there is a fair amount of support in the Congress,
enough to create enough pressure to get it passed,'' White House
spokesman Barry Toiv said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studies that have been done show that classrooms need
renovation or that schools need to be replaced entirely,'' Toiv
said. ``The president believes the federal government has a
responsibility to help.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate on school construction also is being fueled by a 1996
federal report that showed 60 percent of American schools need
significant repairs. The report estimated that schools need $112
billion more for renovations and to comply with federal
requirements such as access for the disabled and cleanup of
environmental hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Under Clinton's proposal, the government would offer tax credits
to companies or individuals who buy school construction bonds from
school districts or states. Bond buyers could claim the credit when
they annually file their tax return, instead of receiving interest
payments from the schools.
</P>
<P>
   With the government offering a tax incentive to cover the
interest payments, school districts would have more money to spend
on actual renovation costs, proponents say.
</P>
<P>
   About $11 billion would be used by 125 school districts with the
largest proportion of poor children, said Julie Green, spokeswoman
for the U.S. Department of Education. These districts include
Atlanta city schools; Dayton (Ohio) County schools; Broward, Dade
and Palm Beach counties in Florida; Austin Independent School
District in Texas; and cities in North Carolina and Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The government would provide another $11 billion to states, with
an emphasis on those with a disproportionate number of poor
children.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for the federal money, states, territories and school
districts would have to submit a study of their construction and
renovation needs, list safeguards to ensure the money is spent
properly, and describe how the money would be divided fairly,
especially between rural and high-growth areas.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say improving schools is among their top priorities,
which also include revamping Social Security, cutting income taxes
and fortifying national defense, said Pete Jeffries, communications
director for House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than back Clinton's plan, Republicans are likely to
devise their own, said Trent Duffy, spokesman for the House Ways
and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Duffy criticized Clinton's proposal as temporary because it
provides money only for 2000 and 2001. Because the proposal targets
the poorest districts, it may unfairly exclude other districts that
may also need help, Duffy added.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, House Republicans approved a bill that would have
provided $2.7 billion to school districts every five years. Under
that proposal, the money would have been slated to build or
renovate schools, but also could have been used for other needs,
Duffy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans supported this with overwhelming margins in the
past, so I think that's an indication that Republicans will support
such a bill,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   School construction proposals are also likely in the Senate,
where Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., has introduced a measure
similar to one he co-sponsored last year. That bill is being
considered by the Labor and Human Resources committee.
</P>
<P>
   Past congressional efforts to aid school construction have been
limited.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Congress passed the Education Infrastructure Act, which
allocated $100 million for school officials to repair, renovate,
alter or construct schools. However, the program was eliminated in
1995 by legislative efforts to balance the budget, and none of the
$100 million made it to schools, Green said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Congress passed a bill providing $2.4 billion in tax
credits to certain school-business partnerships to pay for a
variety of expenses, including building renovation.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Anderson, superintendent of the Dublin city schools in
Ohio, said politicians should do whatever is necessary to reach a
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care whether (the money) comes from federal, state or
local,'' Anderson said. ``At least give us the money to provide our
kids with as much possibility for success. Anything short of that,
in my opinion, is another excuse to do nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
