<HEADER>
A9393 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRADLEY-COLUMN27-     01-26 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRADLEY-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The voice of experience
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Cornelius Bennett addressed the Falcons on Monday. His
topic: How not to lose the Super Bowl. On this subject, Bennett is
an unchallenged expert.
</P>
<P>
   This is Bennett's fifth Super Bowl. He hasn't won one yet. Only
one player has been been part of five losing Super Bowl teams, and
that one _ Buffalo and San Diego backup quarterback Gale Gilbert _
should carry an asterisk. Bennett is the real deal, four times a
loser with Buffalo. ``I hoping the fifth time is the charm,'' he
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, he lent his new team the benefit of his old
club's experience. Put simply, it was this:
</P>
<P>
   Get some sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back, I wish (the Bills) hadn't hung out the way we
did,'' Bennett said. ``I'm not going to attribute losing to that.
But when guys ask me, `What's it like?' and `What's going to make
the difference?', I've got to tell them something different.
Because what we did didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Bennett described the Bills as ``the party team of
the 1990s.'' Realizing that it raised the ire of long-suffering
Buffalo fans, he backed off a bit. ``We did care about the game.
... We didn't do it intentionally to go out and lose. ... But
that's just what I'd have to do different, and I can't just say I
was out there by myself (as a socializing Bill). Of course, had we
won, I'd be saying, 'Hang out 'til 5 in the morning.'''
</P>
<P>
   Since leaving the Bills for Atlanta in 1996, Bennett has
undergone all manner of growth. He has become a Christian. He
served 36 days in jail last summer after pleading guilty to sexual
misconduct. After being prodded by Dan Reeves to play like the
All-Pro linebacker he was in his Buffalo days, he has become a
vital force in what is being called the best front seven in
football. And this carouser of renown has dubbed himself the
Falcons' voice of reason.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills ``hung out a little less each year,'' Bennett said.
``But Buffalo's a small town, and we had a lot of single guys. You
remember how it was when you were 21. It's hard to tell a young guy
to stay in and chill. I'm just trying to tell our guys, 'Don't get
caught up in the hype.' ``
</P>
<P>
   This is not to confuse moderation with monasticism. South Beach
is but a 15-minute limo ride from Falcons HQ, and Bennett himself
has made the trek twice. ``I'm not saying just to stay in the
room,'' he said. ``But there's a difference between staying out
past 1 or 2 in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bills' first Super Bowl loss, by one point to the Giants,
was honorable enough. The three thereafter seem, at least in
retrospect, the work of an easily distracted team. Thurman Thomas
missed the first two plays of Super Bowl XXVI because he couldn't
find his helmet. The Bills led Dallas at halftime of Super XXVIII
but crumbled via turnovers. ``I tried to tell (the Falcons) how not
to get caught up in the moment,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   Has he seen any evidence that his new temmates, most of them
Super novices, have taken his counsel? ``We have (midnight) curfew
starting tonight,'' Bennett said. ``With Buffalo, we didn't have a
lot of that. I'm hoping they take heed. If this works, I'll be a
genius.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bradley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
