</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HUMMER-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spotlight shines on QB Chandler
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Walk down Chris Chandler's perilous career path, and
you'd get pretty good at the ol' duck-and-cover, too. But here is
today's amazing Super Bowl twist. Now, he's defending himself
against charges that he is the better of the quarterbacks left
standing.
</P>
<P>
   He must appear before the pearls of sports journalism and
declare: C'mon, I'm not all that. Give this Elway fellow some
credit.
</P>
<P>
   I've considered the heretical notion that the Falcons have the
advantage at quarterback here at Armageddon XXXIII. A fellow wretch
from Miami wrote as much Tuesday morning. Chandler believes none of
this wisdom pertinent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't do anything for me,'' he said. ``I think it's an
absurd thing to say that anybody is going to play better than John
Elway. I've been playing really good football for the last two
years. (But) most people really don't know this game well. For the
general person to say I'm playing better than John Elway, I think
that's stretching it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler's got the numbers over Elway this season. The passing
yardage is greater, the touchdowns more, the rating higher. More
significantly, the Falcons found themselves a quarterback with the
Elwayian ability to construct victory from the chaos of a game's
final moments. A couple of drives 10 days ago in Minneapolis, and
suddenly the quarterback nobody wanted is being bronzed.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever ``it'' is that marks the accomplished two-minute
quarterbacks, Chandler is in the process of acquiring it. After
what happened against Vikings in the NFC Championship, your teeth
could rot from all the sweetness thrown Chandler's way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This organization has put five stars on my shoulder and made
me the general,'' Chandler said. And the fellow foot soldiers seem
well pleased.
</P>
<P>
   They will speak in terms usually reserved for the established
winners of the position. ``Guys like that, they have competitive
spirits,'' receiver Terance Mathis said. ``And then you've got some
guys who just go through the motions and say, `All right, let's
just get this game over with.' Chris is a guy who wants to win.
He's going to do almost everything right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He exhibits the patience of Joe Montana,'' Eugene Robinson
said. ``Guys would be in his face and he'd go, `Excuse me, I've got
to complete this pass.' That's the same thing Chris does. You've
got to be a cool dude in the pocket, and he's just cool.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He understands the position. His mechanics. His footwork. His
vision. He has conveyed more to me than any quarterback I've been
associated with,'' said Steve DeBerg, who has been associated with
nearly all of them.
</P>
<P>
   From kicking around on six teams in 10 seasons to becoming the
anchor of a Super Bowl team, an amazing transformation completes
itself Sunday. At the time of his defining performance in
Minnesota, Chandler had no time to appreciate what was happening.
Now, though, ``I look back and feel a little more satisfaction than
maybe someone else would. Being given up on so much, having so many
teams say I couldn't do it for them . . . '' So amazing that when
some say he is no John Elway, it almost comes out like a
compliment.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hummer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
