A9400 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-MIRROR-NYT &LR;      01-26 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-MIRROR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAD OF BRITAIN'S MIRROR GROUP RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ After a remarkably public showdown with board members
and stockholders, David Montgomery resigned Tuesday as chief
executive of Mirror Group PLC, opening the way for a takeover
battle for one of Britain's oldest tabloid newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery, 50, is one of the most contentious figures in the
British newspaper industry. He was initially lauded by investors
for rescuing Mirror Group after the depredations of its former
owner, Robert Maxwell; then he was reviled by many journalists who
lost their jobs to his cost-cutting, and was ultimately forced out
by people who depicted him as a hindrance to shareholders'
fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   His resignation came after he failed to persuade institutional
investors holding 31 percent of Mirror stock to back him in a
bitter, personal feud with Sir Victor Blank, the former investment
banker who is the company's nonexecutive chairman. Sir Victor had
threatened to call a no-confidence vote at a board meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The boardroom battle was propelled by takeover approaches from
two regional newspaper groups that have pushed Mirror stock to 207
pence, or $3.41, from a low of 136 pence in October.
</P>
<P>
   The two suitors are Trinity PLC, Britain's biggest regional
newspaper group, which made an all-stock offer valuing Mirror
shares at 160 pence, or $2.65, and Regional Independent Media,
owned by Candover Investment Trust, which is backed by the
financier George Soros and a Deutsche Bank unit. Last week, the
Mirror board rejected Candover's offer of 200 pence, which would
have valued the company at 913 million pounds, or $1.51 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Neither suitor gave a clear indication Tuesday of its intentions
after the news of Montgomery's departure. Both Sir Victor, the
chairman, and investors such as Phillips &AMP; Drew, with a 21 percent
stake in Mirror Group, had held Montgomery responsible for blocking
takeover moves, accusing him of putting his own position in the
company ahead of shareholders' interests.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the daily tabloid The Mirror, the company publishes
The Sunday Mirror and several Scottish and regional newspapers. It
also owns a cable television channel, Live TV.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery, a former newspaper editor, was brought into the
Mirror Group in 1992 after Maxwell, the entrepreneur whose
plundering of the group's pension fund had left the company in
disarray, drowned at sea in 1991.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
