<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9401 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-PLANNING-COX     01-26 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-PLANNING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    NATURAL FAMILY PLANNING
 &HT;    PHOTOS AVAILABLE
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Anntoinette Moore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW _ When Deya Stavinoha's husband first suggested they
use natural family planning as birth control, she was very
skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   It was soon after Stavinoha, who is Presbyterian, had married
her husband, Jerome, who is Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   He finally persuaded her to attend a natural family planning
class.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to argue with the teachers. I was going to give
them a hard time,'' Stavinoha said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she was converted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they started explaining how your body's signs tell you
when you're fertile, it made sense,'' Stavinoha said.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband now teach classes in natural family planning
under the auspices of the Couple-to-Couple League in Gregg County
Texas. They have three children, all of whom were planned, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   They teach a method developed by the Couple-to-Couple League, an
interdenominational nonprofit organization based in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``Natural family planning is the awareness of a woman's
fertility cycle. You can manage your fertility easily by being
aware of these changing signs and symptoms,'' Stavinoha said,
adding that the signs are not hard to detect.
</P>
<P>
   By using natural family planning, a couple can time their sexual
intercourse to either increase the woman's chances of becoming
pregnant or to avoid pregnancy, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The couples at these classes learn to detect (the woman's)
cervical mucous flow, which is one of the signs of the fertile
phase, and they monitor her daily basal temperature,'' Stavinoha
said.
</P>
<P>
   This ``sympto-thermal method'' _ charting a woman's basal body
temperature and her Z through her monthly menstrual cycle _ is very
effective, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women who use this method actually take better care of
themselves. It's like looking at yourself in the mirror every
day,'' Stavinoha said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This method can be adapted and used easily with irregular
menstrual periods because the rules still apply. Every woman is
different. Every woman has a different cycle,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It is a far cry from the rhythm method of birth control,
Stavinoha said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the rhythm method, you had to be like a little clock. It
didn't work for women who had irregular cycles,'' Stavinoha said.
``Rhythm is like the Model T of natural family planning.''
</P>
<P>
   Father Mark Kusmirek, of Christ the King Catholic Church in
Kilgore, Texas, said natural family planning is approved by the
Catholic church.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church asks that in everything we do, we cooperate with
God's plan for nature. The church calls that the natural law,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   While birth control pills or IUDs circumvent nature, natural
family planning enables individuals to cooperate with nature,
Kusmirek said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really calls for a husband and wife to understand each
other's bodies and the cycle of fertility. Couples choose to have
intercourse during times when they know they have a good chance to
conceive or not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The couples that I know who have used natural family planning,
it helps them know each other better,'' Kusmirek said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It opens up couples to understanding . . . that love is more
than just having intercourse, it's the whole gamut of things that
bring people together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stavinoha said natural family planning ``is not a Catholic
thing, just like breast-feeding is not a Catholic thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Conservative Jews and many Protestant churches don't condone
artificial forms of birth control,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Couples in the class ``are from all denominations. They come for
many different reasons. Many women cannot take birth-control
pills,'' Stavinoha said. ``Many women believe that it's wrong to
pollute a woman's body with drugs that are not necessary, with
drugs that have dangerous side effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you use contraception . . . it is an anti-procreative
act, whereas abstinence (from sex) during the fertile times is not
an anti-procreative act. It's just abstaining.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples who abstain from sex while the woman is fertile are not
doing anything to destroy the potential consequences of that sex _
a fertilized egg or fetus, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fertility is not a disease. Fertility is a gift from God. It
is not a pathological condition or disease that you have to treat
or cure. It is not a burden. It is a blessing,'' Stavinoha said.
</P>
<P>
   Women's health-care nurse practitioner Linda Boggs said
effective natural family planning depends on accurate tracking of a
woman's fertile periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to keep an actual chart of their periods for about
six months before they know what that fertile period is,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have many people who ask me about it. Usually they're
pretty attuned to their bodies even before they ask,'' said Boggs,
who works at Women's Health Care Clinic, a satellite of Diagnostic
Clinic of Longview, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always tell them that this is a way that you can not get
pregnant if you don't want to be. But most people are more
interested in other methods of contraception, like birth-control
pills,'' or contraceptive injections, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many women use natural family planning while they're
breast-feeding, said Boggs, who has been a nurse for 20 years and
learned about the method during her medical training.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no side-effects to their baby that they're
breast-feeding at
</P>
<P>
   all,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage is the method's low cost, basically limited to
the cost of a basal thermometer, charts and perhaps a natural
family planning class, Boggs said.
</P>
<P>
   For a typical woman using natural family planning, the method is
80 percent effective in preventing contraception during the first
year, she said. For the ``perfect user,'' it is 91 to 99 percent
effective, Boggs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not bad. But it has to be somebody who's willing to put
that much effort into it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One disadvantage is that it offers no protection against
sexually transmitted diseases or HIV, Boggs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another disadvantage is that the woman will have to abstain
from sex when her libido is highest,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Natural family planning is a real good method for the right
individual. Like any method of birth control, it's not for
everybody. With the right counseling and the right individual it
could be an effective method,'' Boggs said.
</P>
<P>
   Stavinoha said remembering to take your temperature before you
get up every day, monitoring your cervical mucous flow and charting
the changes was not difficult to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We brush our teeth every day. We take a shower every day. It's
just another hygiene habit. It's not a big deal,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the classes, both husband and wife are involved in the
process, Stavinoha said. For example, the wife takes her
temperature but her husband records it on the chart, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both are aware of where she is on her cycle. It is the
business of the couple, not just the woman,'' Stavinoha said.
</P>
<P>
   Natural family planning strengthens marriages because the
husband and wife have to talk to each other, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both decide together when to have sex. This method helps you
build those virtues that help you have a long, faithful marriage,
virtues such as patience, kindness and self-control,'' Stavinoha
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wife and the husband do not take each other for granted.
The couple works together as a team. The rough spots are worked out
mutually and become a bond,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stavinohas' class consists of four, two-hour sessions, set
one month apart. Couples' confidentiality is protected and the
Stavinohas also will teach individual couples natural family
planning, she said. Classes are held in English and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The next round of classes begins Feb. 21. A $50 fee pays for a
basal thermometer, charts, a natural family planning textbook and a
one-year subscription to the Couple-to-Couple League's newsletter,
Family Foundations, Stavinoha said, adding that she and her husband
are not paid for teaching the course.
</P>
<P>
   The league's World Wide Web site is www.ccli.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
