<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9402 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GIBBS-COX     01-26 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIBBS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coach Gibbs gets to players through criticismBy Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ For 20 minutes this afternoon, during the Denver
Broncos' only practice in pads before Super Bowl XXXIII, the
offense will gear up for its weekly nine-on-seven drill, a physical
session in which every play is a run and every run is between the
tackles.
</P>
<P>
   And then for hours tonight, dreading the weekly critique from
Alex Gibbs, several of the offensive linemen will find it
impossible to sleep because they are worrying about how the
Broncos' assistant head coach might embarrass them during video
review on Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The skull session, in which head coach Mike Shanahan basically
turns the team over to Gibbs, is a Broncos tradition in which the
lights go out, the videotape machine goes on, and the anxiety level
of every Denver offensive player goes up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just waiting for it is bad enough, especially if you had a bad
practice the day before,'' Broncos guard Mark Schlereth said. ``I
think the intensity of everyone in that room picks up when Alex
starts picking us apart. You sit there in your chair squirming and
thinking to yourself, 'Oh, man, don't let me be the brunt of his
jokes.' It gets pretty heated.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, Gibbs employed a laser pointer to edify the
troops on their mistakes. He would point to the screen and tell
John Elway the quarterback's right foot had been five inches too
far outside on a handoff. He would point it again and show tailback
Terrell Davis exactly where the cutback lane would be on the
outside toss and then scold the league's premier runner on having
missed it by a foot. He would flick it on the celluloid image of a
tackle and insist that his hand placement was too high on the
defensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   The laser pointer is history now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was replaced by his mouth,'' right tackle Harry Swayne
said. ``Nobody, and I do mean absolutely nobody, is immune. In that
room, on that drill, everyone is fair game.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs is one of the most brilliant but also one of the most
anonymous coaches in the NFL. He earned a master's degree in
European history, has a doctorate in education and has been known
to read 25 books in the offseason. He received his Ph.D. in
offensive-line blocking techniques long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah, Gibbs, 57, is also a cross between the boogie man and
a CIA undercover agent, the guy lurking at the end of the dimly lit
alley who makes you take the long detour to get home. He is a man
of mystery who disdains the media, operates with great stealth and
speaks at the Super Bowl only because the NFL would fine him
$10,000 if he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the season he is off-limits and on-guard, insisting
that his charges follow his lead in ignoring anybody carrying a
notepad or a mini-cam. The linemen dined at the legendary Joe's
Stone Crab here Monday night with the $5,500 in kangaroo court
fines collected in 1998. Little of that money, claimed center Tom
Nalen, was the result of violating Gibbs' gag order ``He scares you
(into) silence,'' Nalen said.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Gibbs conducted his news conference Tuesday
from behind a pair of Oakley sunglasses. He could tell you why the
Broncos undersized offensive line ranks among the best in the NFL _
but then he'd have to kill you.
</P>
<P>
   A master motivator, Gibbs prepped under some of the game's
finest teachers and to this day considers himself more educator
than coach. He brags about having worked for Vince Dooley at
Georgia and pointed out Tuesday that one of his former bosses,
Woody Hayes, taught freshman English at Ohio State for 26 years and
never had a student fail.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it is his fear of failure that drives Gibbs and which
he has cultivated carefully in his offensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paranoia is a great thing, under control,'' Gibbs said, biting
off each of those words. ``I love insecure linemen because I know
that they're all afraid of failing. The momentum of failure is one
of the most powerful elements I know. Truly, it is a positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he insisted on Tuesday that his strength is not as a
game-planner, Gibbs will design a blocking scheme around his
weakest link. The entire plan, every single play, Swayne agreed,
will revolve around protecting the most overmatched blocker. ``He
is obsessed with that,'' Swayne said. ``It's like, 'Who do we
double(team) to help someone out?' He doesn't want any
breakdowns.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs, who doesn't plan ever to be a head coach at any level, is
a grunt and knows it. He wants his linemen in his image. Of the
nine offensive linemen on the roster, just three began their
careers with the Broncos. The others were plucked from the league's
scrap heap or, in the case of left tackle Tony Jones, acquired in a
trade.
</P>
<P>
   The higher the draft round, the more worthy a lineman is to play
for Gibbs, who has told Denver officials he never wants them to
draft a blocker in the first two rounds. And he spends hours in the
videotape room, scanning other teams and perusing World League game
film. Already he has targeted a couple of linemen he figures will
be released soon by their current teams and whom he plans to claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let somebody else get them through their growing pains,''
Gibbs said. ``I don't want the job of doing that. I relish taking a
guy who's been beaten up a little bit. The guys who have been down
on their luck at some point _ those are my guys. Those kinds of
guys know about loyalty. Those kinds of guys will work their tails
off for you. Those kinds of guys want to show the world somebody
was wrong about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
