<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9403 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICS-CHRIST-COX     01-26 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-CHRIST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    HOW CAN CHRISTIANS BE CHRIST-LIKE IN POLITICS?
 &HT;    FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Robin Galiano
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ Though Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. was able to
maintain his nonviolent commitment to a righteous cause some 30
years ago, some observers say that Christians and politics today
make for a stormier brew.
</P>
<P>
   Some say the two just don't mix, that it's difficult for people
with strong Bible-based convictions to operate within a realm that
requires compromise to work. Others say believers have an
obligation to be ``salt and light'' to their communities and to
influence the nation for moral good.
</P>
<P>
   Since the rise of Jerry Falwell's Moral Majority in the 1980s
and Pat Robertson's 1988 bid for the presidency, Christians have
become increasingly active politically. It's not unusual today for
groups like the Christian Coalition to be tapped for their
responses to issues such as President Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In East Texas, Christians have gotten their foot in the
political door by being elected to school boards, and many with
pro-life sentiments have made significant inroads in the Gregg
County Texas Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   But some would argue there's an ongoing conflict with Christians
in politics: that some participants, especially those on the far
right end of the spectrum, are often unwilling to compromise, and
thus the political process itself comes to a standstill.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Christians have been known to pursue political
goals with tunnel vision, unwilling to back down on a single issue.
For instance, 1995 school board sessions in White Oak, Texas,
caused some Christians to stumble on ``hot button'' words, such as
``outcome-based education'' and ``multi-age classes'' in
discussions about education. And delegates to state political
conventions have argued vehemently about whether all abortion
should be illegal or whether instances of rape and incest should be
the exception.
</P>
<P>
   And some religious conservatives have been accused of being
mean-spirited and even vindictive in the midst of heated political
discussions _ all in the name of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   In the Jan. 11, 1999, issue of Christianity Today, Daniel Taylor
asks, ``How can we affirm Christian morality, unapologetically
rooted in the Bible, without becoming rhetorical bomb throwers?''
</P>
<P>
   Some would say it's difficult. And that perception seems to be
growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seen as the pit bulls of the culture wars _ small
brains, big teeth, strong jaws, and no interest in compromise,''
Taylor writes. ``Is this indictment fair? Often not.
Understandable? Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paul Kubricht, professor of history at LeTourneau University
in Longview, said it's the clash of values that often makes it
difficult to be ``Christ-like'' in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rise of the Christian right was a response to increasing
secularism and what is perceived as antibiblical values,'' he said.
``Christian values were being challenged in the political arena,
and so they thought, 'We have to do battle.' And the history of
fundamentalism shows that they do battle. They'll take on Darwin or
whoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Keith Rothra, pastor of Judson Community Baptist Church in
Longview, said he entered the political realm because that's where
people had introduced ideas that were ``repulsive'' to his
religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's foolish for them to think that they can bring things like
abortion into the political realm and expect me not to respond,''
he said. ``I think abortion doesn't belong in the political forum _
it's a spiritual and moral issue. I'm just using the forum they've
chosen. In the American system, everyone has a right to press their
views.''
</P>
<P>
   Rothra, who has been a delegate to the state Texas Republican
Party convention, acknowledged that he had problems with the
``radical Religious Right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as I oppose abortion, I don't agree with those who say
all the way or no way. There has to be an element of compromise in
the political
</P>
<P>
   process. Those who hold out for the whole pie or none are going
to starve to death. Morally, I understand their position. But I
think their tactic is foolish.''
</P>
<P>
   The use of inflammatory words is another way Christians get into
trouble, Rothra said.
</P>
<P>
   On the national scene, for instance, members of an
ultra-conservative Baptist church showed up at the funeral of
Wyoming homosexual Matthew Shepard, carrying placards that read,
``God Hates Fags'' and ``Matt in Hell.'' And they quoted Scripture
verses to justify their stance.
</P>
<P>
   But while the actions of a few extremists may cause political
opponents to unfairly label all Christians as part of the Religious
Right or as ``fundamentalists,'' Christians are not as monolithic a
voting bloc as might be perceived, said Kubricht.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the conservative Christian community there are great
differences in how people respond,'' he said. ``Those coming from a
more evangelical framework, such as Evangelicals for Social Action,
see things much differently, but you hardly ever see other views on
the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media tend to focus on a few extreme examples, and ignore
the complexity of responses in the Christian community to these
issues. You don't see coverage of churches who have a significant
ministry to AIDS patients. Those who do things in a quiet way are
overlooked.''
</P>
<P>
   How can Christians maintain their heartfelt convictions without
tuning out those with whom they disagree?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every religious group needs to tread lightly if they
want to be taken seriously in politics,'' said Dr. James Joseph,
assistant professor of political science at the University of Texas
at Tyler. This is especially true for conservative Christians, whom
he said are frequently perceived as ``wild-eyed, radical and
breathing fire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any candidate from the religious right won't have much of a
chance, but they can still be influential,'' Joseph said. ``If
you're coming from the Judeo-Christian, it might be better to focus
on God being forgiving rather than talk about fire and damnation.
It's those kinds of groups that, even if you agree with their
views, they'll turn you off as a voter.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Herb Spady, pastor of South Longview Bible Fellowship,
said Christians who are willing to tackle political areas such as
race relations and abortion must first take an honest look at their
own lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of wielding the Bible as an object of judgment and
reproof, Christians need to read it and access the power that can
transform their own lives, families and this nation. 2 Chronicles
7:14 says that God's people have some wicked ways themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at someone like President Clinton and say, 'Look what
he did.' But who are we, as sinners ourselves, to judge? We do have
to pay the consequences of our sin, and for Clinton, that may mean
impeachment and removal from office. But to say he didn't really
mean it when he apologized, that he's not really sorry, that's
wrong. We're to love the sinner and not condemn him. We need to
stop judging him and start praying for our leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Spady, who was a speaker at the recent World AIDS Day gathering
in Longview, insisted that it is possible to hate the sin but love
the sinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing that all of us are supposed to do,'' he said.
``As Christians, we don't do that very well. Some of us hate the
sin and hate the sinner, too. We kill off the wounded, like people
with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are Christians who are able to hate the drugs and
the homosexuality that brings on AIDS, yet they still love the AIDS
patients.
</P>
<P>
   That's the bottom line of Christianity. That's what God did when
He came to die for our sin.''
</P>
<P>
   As Daniel Taylor concludes in his magazine article, perhaps
Christians need to go beyond mere tolerance and become truly
loving, which he says is ``a far greater challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Love is not incompatible with judgment but it is incompatible
with our not properly valuing all that God has created, including
those who offend us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
