<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9404 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROLIFE-FLAGS-COX     01-26 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROLIFE-FLAGS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   VISION PROMPTS PRO-LIVE CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOS AVAILABLE
</P>
<P>
   By Robin Galiano
</P>
<P>
   c. 199 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ Rex and Georgie Willcox have taken a pro-life
stand, and they're not afraid to let their neighbors know it.
</P>
<P>
   Their Longview home bears a banner that simply and unashamedly
reads, ``I Choose Life.'' But what's unusual is that the flag
carries an original design drawn up by Rex. It shows a baby in the
womb, surrounded by heart-shaped concentric circles of different
colors that represent racial diversity, and a flag of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Rex, who is a former evangelist, pastor and retired post office
worker, but not an artist, said he drew the design two years ago
after he experienced what he described as a spiritual prompting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord gave me a vision, and I saw banners in front of
homes. I'm looking down on the United States, and everywhere
there's a banner, there's a connection. And all the time, the Lord
is saying, 'You're part of My people becoming one.' I came home and
asked Georgie, 'Do we have any colored pencils?' I drew it, and we
had it copyrighted.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgie Willcox, who taught at LeTourneau University in Longview
for more than 30 years and served as director of continuing
education, said some people told Rex the flag should say, ``Choose
Life.'' The couple, however, insisted the banners were to carry a
more personal message. ``This is not us telling you what to do.
It's just saying where we stand,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we can all do,'' her husband added. ``People
see them and stop and say, 'Thank you for being a standard bearer.
I'm one, too.'''
</P>
<P>
   And it's catching on across the country. After putting an
advertisement in a national right-to-life publication, requests
came in so strong that the Willcoxes have installed a new computer
system to maintain a database for distribution of the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have requested one are Eagle Forum director
Phyllis Schlafly, Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., Rep. Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., and Family Research Council president Gary Bauer. And
they've learned that the international director of Priests for Life
took one of the flags to Rome to be blessed by Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wonderful,'' Right to Life of East Texas director
Joe Dudas said of the banner. ``They're spreading the pro-life
cause in a very unique way. We've encouraged our members to
purchase a flag, and we have them available at our booth at the
Gregg County Fair.''
</P>
<P>
   For the flag's designer, however, it's more than a pro-life
statement _ it's symbolic of the way Rex Willcox believes
Christians should express the
</P>
<P>
   unity they have at heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue above this one is that God's people are one
people. Jesus prayed in John 17 that the Father would make us one
as He and the Father are one, and this prayer is to be answered
before we go to heaven. We are to see eye to eye and be perfectly
one. After all, the Father and the Son don't have any arguments.
Satan's biggest tool is to keep division in the body of Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   Willcox said when he realized the Lord might be speaking to him
about helping the church become unified, he was ``aghast.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was prejudiced myself. Everyone wants to hold onto truths
that are precious to them. I saw that we were in prison walls of
our own making. We just can't put people down or condemn them.''
</P>
<P>
   Willcox said the cause of ``stopping the killing'' might be the
thing to bring Christians together. ``It's for God's people to come
together who have been reticent, apathetic or indifferent. I myself
had to repent of that. This is not to scorn or rebuke. Years ago, I
could say the harshest thing about abortion, but I was still
indifferent about doing what I could about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The soft-spoken 72-year-old tears up easily as he describes his
passion for the unborn. ``We need a deep understanding of Jesus'
words, 'Inasmuch as you've done it to the least of these, you've
done it to Me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``When you begin to study the Scriptures about when life begins,
the plain naked Scripture, it's so clear that life begins in the
womb. Psalm 127 says the fruit of the womb is the Lord's treasure.
We are the product of God Almighty. Man's value diminishes as his
value of life in the womb diminishes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Willcoxes are so committed to making the banners available
that they've used a significant chunk of their retirement money to
produce them and have set up the nonprofit Sacred Heart Ministries
to distribute them. They sell them at cost to churches that can
resell them and use the proceeds for pro-life projects such as
establishing homes for unwed mothers.
</P>
<P>
   The Willcoxes' goal is to see 40 million homes in the United
States bearing the banner, sort of a silent and continual ``chain
of life'' that can be seen seven days a week, 24 hours a day, 365
days a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot stop abortion by marching on clinics and shooting
abortionists,'' Georgie Willcox said. ``You have to do it by
changing people.''
</P>
<P>
   She admitted it takes courage for people to put a banner on
their home and that folks who do so are ``standard bearers'' for
the unborn. ``Your home is the most personal thing you have, more
so than a car bumper. We live here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
