<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9405 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-WITNESSES-HNS     01-26 1545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-WITNESSES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PROSECUTORS WANT TO TALK WITH CLINTON, THREE WITNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN and ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House prosecutors issued a surprise invitation
Tuesday to President Clinton to testify in a deposition for his own
Senate impeachment trial and said they also want to question three
others: Monica Lewinsky, presidential confidant Vernon Jordan and
White House aide Sidney Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors also asked the Senate to accept sworn statements
not already admitted into evidence from two minor players: Barry
Ward, a law clerk to the Arkansas federal judge in the Paula Jones
sexual harassment lawsuit, Susan Webber Wright; and T. Wesley
Holmes, one of Jones' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The move by the prosecutors on witnesses set the stage for a
Senate vote Wednesday on whether to approve the requests, which
represent scaled-back versions of earlier plans for live testimony
from some of the key players on the Senate floor. Some Republican
senators such as Richard Shelby of Alabama were signaling their
reluctance to approve such a step.'
</P>
<P>
   The Republican prosecutors also appeared hopeful of convincing
senators that the impeachment trial would not be unduly prolonged
by the depositions, which are interviews under oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two people who know the most about this are Monica
Lewinsky and William Jefferson Clinton,'' Rep. Bill McCollum,
R-Fla., one of 13 House prosecutors. ``We think it is exceedingly
important ... for you to examine (Clinton) and these other
witnesses to get at the truth of this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been impeached for alleged perjury and obstruction
of justice in connection with the coverup of his affair with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors said they were inviting him to give a deposition
because he was ``the one person who possesses direct and personal
knowledge'' of all the events surrounding the perjury and
obstruction of justice charges against him. ``His credibility is
critical in order for the Senate to resolve different inferences
from the factual record in his favor.'' The White House rejected
the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what House prosecutors hope to obtain from the other
witnesses:
</P>
<P>
   MONICA LEWINSKY
</P>
<P>
   McCollum called Lewinsky ``the one witness you and the American
people honestly do need to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's testimony roughly would cover the period from Nov. 5,
1997, when she first met Jordan to discuss his help in getting her
a job in New York, to Jan. 21, 1998, when her name first surfaced
in news reports.
</P>
<P>
   The House prosecutors believe Lewinsky's testimony would bolster
the version of events they have laid out in the Senate trial:
Clinton and Jordan intensified efforts to help Lewinsky find a job
after her name appeared on the Jones witness list, Clinton
encouraged Lewinsky to file a false affidavit denying a sexual
relationship with Clinton, and Clinton sent his secretary Betty
Currie to Lewinsky's apartment to retrieve gifts subpoenaed by
Jones' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   In her grand jury testimony in August 1998, Lewinsky denied that
anyone had promised her a job for her silence or asked her to lie.
She also testified that Clinton said ``I don't know'' or ``let me
think about that'' when she suggested in their final meeting Dec.
28, 1997, that Currie retrieve the gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, prosecutors argued, Currie called Lewinsky, told
her ``I understand you have something to give me,'' and then drove
to Lewinsky's apartment to pick up the gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky also would be asked about a Dec. 17, 1998, phone
conversation when Clinton informed Lewinsky she was on the Jones
witness list. In that conversation, Clinton suggested Lewinsky
could avoid testifying by signing an affidavit and ``you can always
say you were coming to see Betty (Currie) or that you were bringing
me letters.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House position on this scenario is that Lewinsky said
on other occasions that Clinton said nothing when she broached the
subject of retrieving gifts; that since he never had sexual
intercourse with Lewinsky and that she could sign a
limited-but-truthful affidavit in the Jones case that they never
had sex; to avoid testifying.
</P>
<P>
   VERNON JORDAN
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors believe Jordan's testimony will prove that Clinton
encouraged Lewinsky to file the false Jones affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan at the time was in communication with both Lewinsky and
Clinton, and he was helping her get legal help in preparation for
the Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In her grand jury testimony, Lewinsky admitted her affidavit was
false and that she and Clinton in fact did have a sexual
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's testimony also will shed light on Clinton's role in
helping obtain employment for Lewinsky in New York in exchange for
false testimony in the Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, through Jordan, intensified efforts to find Lewinsky a
job after the appearance of her name on the Jones lawsuit witness
list, prosecutors assert.
</P>
<P>
   The job ``was intended to ensure Ms. Lewinsky's gratitude and
thereby discourage her from providing any damaging information
about her relationship with the president to the Jones attorneys,''
the prosecutors argued.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers have insisted the job search was an
innocent, routine effort to help a Clinton friend find employment
outside of government, and was unconnected to Clinton's efforts to
buy her silence.
</P>
<P>
   SIDNEY BLUMENTHAL
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors want to question Blumenthal, a presidential
aide, to prove that Clinton obstructed justice by lying to
Blumenthal about his relationship with Lewinsky, knowing that
Blumenthal would repeat the lie to the grand jury. That constitutes
obstruction, the prosecutors argue.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told Blumenthal _ and Blumenthal told the grand jury _
that Lewinsky was a ``stalker.'' Clinton told Blumenthal that
Lewinsky had repeatedly made sexual advances and that he had
rebuffed them. Clinton denied to Blumenthal that he had a sexual
relationship with Lewinsky, adding that Lewinsky threatened to tell
people just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors assert that the testimony from the aide will
prove that Clinton sought to attack Lewinsky's character in an
effort to exculpate himself, which they contend supports the
obstruction charge.
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall, Clinton's private lawyer, last week defended
Clinton on this charge by claiming that the president's statements
to Blumenthal and other aides was no different from what he told
the American people on national television.
</P>
<P>
   BARRY WARD
</P>
<P>
   A law clerk to Judge Susan Webber Wright, Ward was present at
Clinton's Jan. 17, 1998, deposition in the Jones case. At one point
during a debate over Lewinsky's affidavit, Clinton's lawyer Robert
Bennett pointed out the document said ``there is absolutely no sex
of any kind, of any manner, shape or form with President Clinton''
and asked the president to confirm it. ``That is absolutely true,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors accuse Clinton of perjury in that statement because
he failed to repudiate falsehoods in his deposition in his Aug. 17,
1998, grand jury testimony. He said that at the time, he was not
focused on what Bennett was saying. House prosecutors say Ward
could confirm that Clinton did, in fact, appear to be paying close
attention.
</P>
<P>
   T. WESLEY HOLMES
</P>
<P>
   One of Jones' lawyers, Holmes would be asked about the
circumstances leading up to Clinton's talk with Currie on Jan. 18,
1998, the day after Clinton was asked repeated questions about
Lewinsky in his Jones deposition.
</P>
<P>
   According to the prosecutors, Clinton tried to enlist Currie's
support for his false version of the Lewinsky relationship, trying
to get Currie to agree with him that he and Lewinsky were never
alone, and that she wanted to have sex with him but he refused.
House prosecutors have argued that this amounts to obstruction
since Currie was a likely witness in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   In his deposition, Clinton denied a sexual relationship with
Lewinsky and suggested Currie could back up his version of events.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say Holmes could confirm that based on Clinton's
testimony about Currie, the Jones lawyers zeroed in on the
secretary as a key witness and issued a subpoena to her on Jan. 22.
For that reason, prosecutors argue, Clinton must have known Currie
would be a witness and his attempts to sway her testimony amounted
to obstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not Currie was to be a witness is crucial because an
element of the law on obstruction requires prosecutors to show
interference with an actual witness in a legal proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   The White House legal team has argued Clinton had no idea Currie
would be a witness, and that he was concerned with the potential of
a media ``firestorm'' growing out of the Jones lawyers' questions
about Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   TELEPHONE RECORDS
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors want to submit records of a Dec. 6, 1997, phone
conversation between Clinton and Lewinsky that lasted 56 minutes.
On that day, Clinton learned for the first time that Lewinsky was
on the Jones lawyers' witness list. Later that same day, Clinton
intensified his effort to win Lewinsky's silence with a job,
according to the prosecutor's theory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
