<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Pinochet Appeal Continues
</P>
<P>
   A House of Lords hearing into whether Gen. Augusto Pinochet of
Chile is immune from arrest and extradition to Spain was told that
charges of torture and hostage-taking against him are not
internationally recognized crimes and not within the jurisdiction
of any tribunal outside Chile. Clare Montgomery, a lawyer for the
former Chilean dictator, who is 83, said only genocide, war crimes
and crimes against humanity are covered by international
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Opera as Holocaust Remembrance
</P>
<P>
   On the annual Remembrance Day for the Victims of Nazism,
children in Berlin staged the opera ``Brundibar,'' which was
written by a concentration camp prisoner who was later killed at
Auschwitz. The production offers a new way of teaching youths about
the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Hint of Carlos Salinas' Return
</P>
<P>
   Ana Paula Gerard, the wife of the former President Carlos
Salinas de Gortari, returned to Mexico from Cuba, the newspaper La
Jornada reported, prompting speculation that her husband may end
his exile. Ms. Gerard and Salinas, who have lived mostly in Ireland
since 1995, visited Cuba to meet lawyers for Salinas' brother,
Raul, who was convicted last week of murdering a Mexican
politician.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   India: 20 Members of Lower Castes Killed
</P>
<P>
   The police said more than 20 lower-caste men, women and children
were killed in a remote village in Bihar state by about 100
rampaging men who are thought to belong to a private army organized
by upper-caste landlords. Such armies have killed peasants in
revenge for Maoist guerrilla violence.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe: Protest Against Reported Torture
</P>
<P>
   A protest march by journalists and lawyers against torture was
broken up by officers firing tear-gas canisters. Two journalists
for an independent Sunday newspaper said they were tortured by
soldiers after they reported that some officers planned a coup. The
250 marchers carried placards calling on President Robert Mugabe to
resign.
</P>
<P>
   Congo: U.N. Rights Monitor to Return
</P>
<P>
   A Chilean lawyer serving as a monitor for the U.N. high
commissioner for human rights is to visit Congo next month. The
lawyer, Roberto Garreton, had been collecting evidence of
human-rights abuses by troops loyal to President Laurent Kabila
until Kabila banned him. The ban has been reversed by Kabila, who
blames Rwanda, his former ally, for the abuses.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: Peace Talks for Natal Rejected
</P>
<P>
   The governing African National Congress has rejected requests by
the opposition United Democratic Movement to hold high-level talks
to prevent a return of political violence in KwaZulu/Natal. Sifiso
Nkabinde, secretary general of the UDM and a former Congress
guerrilla, was shot dead on Saturday, setting off a spate of
revenge killings.
</P>
</TEXT>
