<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: SHORT-STORY READINGS; A PROGRAM CHANGE; NEW MUSIC
SITE; TICKETS FOR STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The lineup includes Jane Alexander, Alec Baldwin,
Barbara Feldon, William Hurt, Anthony LaPaglia, Jerry Orbach, Meryl
Streep and Joanne Woodward. And Bertolt Brecht, Langston Hughes,
Dorothy Parker and Oscar Wilde.
</P>
<P>
   This is ``Selected Shorts: A Celebration of the Short Story.''
The 10-program series of readings begins its 15th-anniversary
season at 6:30 Wednesday night and continues through June 2 at
Symphony Space, Broadway at 95th Street. Wednesday night's readers
are Beverly D'Angelo, Michael Keck and John Shea; the authors are
Nico Orengo, Amy Bloom and D.H. Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch Hitter
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The baritone Thomas Hampson is out. The mezzo-soprano
Michelle DeYoung is in. That's the word from Carnegie Hall, where
Hampson was to sing Thursday night with the Orchestra of St.
Luke's, led by Sir Charles Mackerras.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the three arias on Hampson's program, Ms. DeYoung
will perform ``Arianna a Naxos'' in an all-Haydn concert, part of
the orchestra's yearlong Haydn Festival. Hampson did not return
telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Music in Motion
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After 20 years of presenting more than 2,000
experimental and avant-garde concerts in its 74-seat loft at 228
West Broadway in TriBeCa, Roulette is moving to Alice Tully Hall,
en route to a new and larger home at a site to be selected.
</P>
<P>
   The temporary stop at Lincoln Center at 8 p.m. on Saturday takes
the form of a 20th-anniversary benefit concert, featuring musical
innovators like Steve Reich, Shelley Hirsch, John Zorn, Meredith
Monk and William Parker and the Little Huey Creative Music
Orchestra, along with surprise guests.
</P>
<P>
   A postconcert party will take place at the New York Society for
Ethical Culture at 2 West 64th St. Roulette's spring season begins
in TriBeCa in early March.
</P>
<P>
   Right This Way
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Psst, want a ticket? The price is no higher than $5
on weekends and two for $5 Monday through Thursday. The proceedings
begin with an all-Strauss program by the New York Philharmonic at
Lincoln Center on Feb. 2 and end some 450 events later with Dance
Africa at the Brooklyn Academy of Music on May 29.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's a catch. The ticket buyer must be a high
school junior or senior. More than 6,500 such tickets to
off-Broadway theater, ballet and contemporary dance, classical
music, opera, jazz, performance art and museum exhibitions in the
five boroughs of the city go on sale Friday. They are made
available by High 5 Tickets to the Arts, a year-round program that
makes the arts affordable.
</P>
<P>
   The free High 5 spring catalog is available at participating
Ticketmaster outlets, public libraries, some Barnes &AMP; Noble and
Borders stores, and Coliseum Books, and in High 5's offices at 1
East 53rd St. The catalog may also be viewed at www.high5tix.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
