<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITNESSES MAY HAVE NO CHOICE BUT TO TESTIFY BEFORE SENATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, who knows well the perils of
testifying under oath, can rely on constitutional doctrine to avoid
testifying before the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But other potential Senate witnesses _ his former paramour, a
long-standing confidant and a trusted aide _ could face the risk of
perjury if they fail to tell senators the truth. They might have no
legal recourse but to testify before the Senate in the president's
impeachment trial, a Houston law professor and a criminal defense
attorney said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors, aware of the president's constitutional
protection against testifying before Congress, have urged the
Senate to request, but not compel, Clinton to give testimony in his
impeachment trial. In contrast, the prosecutors, or ``managers'' in
impeachment trial vernacular, have pressed the Senate to order
Monica Lewinsky, Vernon Jordan and Sidney Blumenthal to testify.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate could vote as early as Wednesday on the prosecutors'
request.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional separation of powers between the president
and Congress affords Clinton legal footing to ignore a
congressional demand that he give testimony, said University of
Houston professor David Crump.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Kent Schaffer, by contrast, said Lewinsky, Jordan and
Blumenthal would have little constitutional protection against
testifying about the president's allegedly illegal efforts to
conceal his extramarital affair with Lewinsky. These efforts, as
argued by the 13 House prosecutors, include lying before a federal
grand jury and obstructing justice.
</P>
<P>
   The separation of powers doctrine, while not expressly mentioned
in the Constitution, has long been interpreted to mean that
Congress, short of passing a law, cannot compel the president to
act, Crump said. The only price Clinton would pay for refusing to
comply with the Senate's request for testimony would be the wrath
of senators who regard his silence as an admission of guilt and
vote for his conviction and expulsion from office, the professor
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The separation of powers protects the president from being at
the beck and call of Congress,'' said Crump, a constitutional law
expert. ``The president could come to the Senate voluntarily.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate could in theory take Clinton to court for refusing to
testify, arguing that the separation of powers doctrine does not
protect the president from having to appear at his impeachment
trial. The Constitution, while containing an implied separation of
powers, also gives the Senate the ``sole'' power to try
impeachments. Therefore, it might allow the legislative body to
compel the president's testimony, Crump said.
</P>
<P>
   But no federal court would have authority to settle the dispute.
The Supreme Court has held that the Senate's singular authority
over impeachment trials prohibits courts from ruling on matters
regarding how senators conduct the proceeding, the professor said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the other potential witnesses, Schaffer said that
Lewinsky would be barred from citing the Constitution's Fifth
Amendment privilege against self incrimination. The reason is that
she has signed an agreement with independent counsel Kenneth Starr
immunizing her from prosecution in return for her truthful
testimony about her relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Because she will not be prosecuted as long as she tells the
truth, Lewinsky has no fear that her testimony would incriminate
her and would therefore be ``stuck'' with having to testify, said
Schaffer, president of the Texas Criminal Defense Lawyers
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, Clinton's close friend, and Blumenthal, an aide to the
president, have not signed immunity agreements but may have waived
their Fifth Amendment rights by testifying before a federal grand
jury investigating the Lewinsky scandal. Having already spoken
under oath about what Clinton told them about his relationship with
Lewinsky and what they did in response, the two men may now be
prevented from remaining silent about their actions and those of
the president, Schaffer said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jordan and Blumenthal would be able to cite the Fifth
Amendment if House prosecutors seek testimony on matters the two
did not discuss before the grand jury, the attorney said. The
prosecutors, in urging the Senate to allow them to question
witnesses, said they would seek new testimony but were not
specific.
</P>
<P>
   However, Schaffer seemed unconvinced, noting that Starr and his
assistants relentlessly quizzed Jordan and Blumenthal before the
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you ask Vernon Jordan that he didn't already say?''
Schaffer said, noting that Jordan appeared before the grand jury
for five days. ``What in the world are the Republican congressmen
going to come up with?''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan and Blumenthal, if House prosecutors ask the same
questions, could urge the Senate trial's presiding judge to excuse
them as witnesses because their testimony would be a mere
repetition of what they already told the grand jury, Schaffer said.
Jordan and Blumenthal could argue that the effort to get them to
testify amounts to ``pure political harassment'' and would not add
to the trial, an argument that Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist,
the presiding judge and a stickler for procedure, might accept,
Schaffer said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Senate would retain the final word on whether
Jordan and Blumenthal would have to testify. Under Senate
impeachment trial rules, senators can overturn the chief justice's
rulings by a simple majority vote taken at the request of a single
senator.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
