<SLUG> BC-MAZDA-CREDIT-255&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOODY'S DOWNGRADES MAZDA DEBT
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Moody's Investors Service, the credit rating agency,
lowered its ratings on Mazda Motor Corp.'s long-term unsecured debt
to below investment grade Tuesday, citing continued deterioration
in the Japanese car market.
</P>
<P>
   The company, in which Ford Motor Co. holds a 33.4 percent stake,
had expected the downgrade and said it would have little effect on
its bottom line this fiscal year, which ends March 31, largely
because Mazda has no need to borrow money before then.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman declined to comment on the company's plans for the
next fiscal year. The company has been working hard to cut its
costs, in part by keeping its borrowing to a minimum, and it
expects to post its first profit on a consolidated basis in six
years this fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Moody's said the senior unsecured debt rating for Mazda was
lowered to ``Ba1'' from ``Baa3,'' moving the company's rating below
investment grade. The agency also characterized the rating outlook
for Mazda as negative. Lower ratings signal more risk for investors
and tend to increase a company's borrowing costs.
</P>
<P>
   The downgrade, which affects about $2.8 billion worth of
securities, could have negative implications for the troubled
Nissan Motor Co., analysts said. Nissan, which has nearly $24
billion in debt, still enjoys an investment-grade rating, and most
analysts regard Mazda as a much better credit risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Mazda's rating down, there's really no reason for Nissan
not to be downgraded further,'' said Koji Endo, an auto analyst at
Schroders Japan Ltd.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Moody's said it was concerned about how a stronger yen and
rising interest rates would affect Mazda. The strengthening of the
yen makes Mazda's cars more expensive overseas, thus making it
harder for the company to make up for sales drops in the domestic
market.
</P>
<P>
   And rising interest rates will push up the cost of existing debt
for Mazda and for its domestic dealership networks, the ratings
agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Mazda's president James Miller said at a news conference Friday
that Moody's decision to put Mazda's debt under review last
December ``shouldn't come as a surprise to anyone'' given its
actions related to other Japanese companies, including Toyota Motor
Corp. Toyota, which is widely regarded as one of the world's most
financially sound companies, lost its ``AAA'' credit rating last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Miller noted at the meeting that Mazda had managed to cut its
debts in half since Ford took control in 1996 and imposed strict
cost-cutting measures. ``We have a clear vision of what we must do,
and we believe we will regain the confidence of the ratings
agencies by our future performance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Mazda said the company planned to redeem and
refinance 105 billion yen worth of bonds, or almost $930 million,
before the end of the fiscal year. The company plans to refinance
35 billion yen and use 33 billion yen of cash flow and 37 billion
yen withdrawn from cash and time deposits.
</P>
<P>
   Mazda's largest market is Japan, where sales of cars have
declined for the last 21 months. Last week, Miller said that the
company expected the market to shrink 3 percent next year, to fewer
than 5.7 million units, of which 1.6 million units will be
lower-margin minicars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect 1999 to be a very, very challenging year,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
