</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUE-DEFINE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHAT IS A 'BLUE DOG?'
 &HT;    With BLUE-DOGS.
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A ``Blue Dog'' refers to a conservative or moderate Democratic
member of Congress. In fact, 29 members belong to a Blue Dog
Coalition that focuses mostly on fiscal issues, such as pursuing a
balanced budget.
</P>
<P>
   Even members, however, are not sure about the origins of the
term. Some say Louisiana has had Blue Dog Democrats going back as
far as the one-party days of the 1920s and '30s, with Blue Dogs the
conservative Democrats, and Yellow Dogs the ultra-conservative
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But the modern Blue Dogs can be traced back to the early 1980s,
according to Rep. Billy Tauzin of Louisiana, a former conservative
Democrat who has become a Republican. Tauzin said Louisiana
Democrats came up with the name ''Blue Dogs'' as an alternative to
''Boll Weevils,'' a group of more than three dozen mostly Southern
House Democrats who banded together to support Ronald Reagan's
economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, when a new group of conservative Democrats was
searching for a name for a coalition, Rep. Jimmy Hayes, another
Louisiana Democrat who later switched parties, showed up at one of
the group's meetings with some of his old Blue Dog lapel pins from
the 1980s. And the rest is history.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one more Louisiana connection. Hayes happened to be
a friend of Louisiana artist George Rodrigue, who has become famous
for his paintings of a wide-eyed Blue Dog. Hayes arranged for each
member to receive a print of one of the paintings, which has led to
a common belief that the ``Blue Dog'' label came from Rodrigue's
painting. The truth is that the artist was creating a tribute to
his departed pet, Tiffany.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
