<HEADER>
A9419 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLUE-DOGS27-COX     01-26 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUE-DOGS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    w/BLUE-DEFINE-0127
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Waco Democratic Rep. Chet Edwards realized a while
back that his party needed some mending.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a dysfunctional family in 1994,'' he said. ``The first
step was to rebuild some trust and respect within our own caucus.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards' solution: socialize. Together with Reps. John Lewis,
D-Ga. and Vic Fazio, D-Ca., Edwards organized a series of dinners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fascinating,'' he said of the meals that brought
together traditional Democratic liberals with their often ignored
conservative Democratic colleagues. ``People who had been here six
and eight years (had) never gotten to know each other.''
</P>
<P>
   In the years since, Edwards has become a conduit between
moderates and conservative Democrats and their party leaders _ a
role that could become increasingly vital as the party moves to the
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to continue to be a bridge builder,'' he said. It's a
position that could result in big political payback if Democrats
take over the House in 2000 on the strength of conservative
districts.
</P>
<P>
   It is obvious things are already changing for conservative
Democrats, known as ``Blue Dogs.'' Just a few years ago, they
rarely got floor time or a good committee assignment. Now, they are
increasing in number and in clout.
</P>
<P>
   It can be seen in plans for a Leadership Council, which would
serve as a key policy-making arm under House Minority Leader
Richard Gephardt (D-Mo.). The group, comprised of representatives
from the five key caucus coalitions, will include one member from
the conservative Blue Dogs and another from the moderate New
Democrat Coalition, which has 50 members and is now the largest
sub-group in the caucus.
</P>
<P>
   In a further sign of the conservatives' new status, Gephardt
plans to include a member from the Blue Dogs in his routine Tuesday
morning meetings of top leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Max Sandlin, D-Marshall, is a ``Blue Dog'' who thinks
conservatives are the key to a Democratic majority in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious that the Democratic party has become more
moderate and has moved to the middle,'' Sandlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Working for a balanced budget and education issues resonates
with the public, he said. ``The party more accurately reflects
middle America today.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandlin, in his second term, is part of a batch of somewhat
recent arrivals who are finding strength in numbers. With such a
slim GOP majority in the House, moderates and conservative
Democrats are critical to passing any meaningful legislation, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us in the middle can often times control the vote and
that puts us in a very important position.''
</P>
<P>
   In November, 23 newly elected Democrats came to Washington. Of
those, 15 have joined one of the two right-leaning groups, and
Sandlin said he expects a few more to join. In the previous
election, Blue Dogs recruited and financed candidates for the first
time. Six of the 13 candidates endorsed by the group were elected.
</P>
<P>
   The New Democrat Network, the outside political arm of the NDC,
won 26 of the
</P>
<P>
   34 races it targeted in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said he will continue to make sure the voice of
moderates and conservative Democrats is heard in the policy-making
arena. Unlike the GOP, he added, the Democratic party has learned
from its mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are letting the most extreme factions within their party
dictate public policy, just as Democrats let the most extreme
liberals do that for many years,'' he said. ``They are being pulled
so far to the right that they are getting outside of the mainstream
of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
