<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9425 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      01-26 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS BRACE FOR DEFEAT IN FIRST IMPEACHMENT TRIAL SHOWDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL, JUDY HOLLAND And JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Democratic leader Tom Daschle, conceding
defeat on the eve of showdown votes in President Clinton's Senate
impeachment trial, said Tuesday the Republican-led Senate will
admit witnesses and rebuff a White House effort to win dismissal of
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle, who leads the Senate's 45 Democrats, conceded that the
Senate will vote Wednesday to approve the House prosecutors' plan
to summon former White House intern Monica Lewsinky, Clinton
confidante Vernon Jordan and White House staffer Sidney Blumenthal
for sworn testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors said they wanted to take the depositions to
resolve disputes that have arisen in the three-week Senate
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Senators said a decision on the procedures for the witnesses
would await Senate action Wednesday on the proposal to admit
witnesses to the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle, referring to witnesses, said they were ``inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., echoed Democrats' resignation. ``I
feel there shouldn't be witnesses, but if we are going to have
witnesses, everybody ought to have all the witnesses they want,''
Leahy said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., said House prosecutors' decision to
narrow their witness list to three made Senate approval more
likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``My instincts say that will pass,'' Coverdell said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., scheduled Senate
votes on Wednesday beginning at 1 p.m. EST on a motion to dismiss
the case offered by Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., and the request by
the House prosecutors to have the Senate subpoena Lewinsky, Jordan
and Blumenthal and Clinton to give a deposition.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials reiterated that Clinton will not submit to
questioning by the Senate _ in person or in writing. ``It's time to
wrap this up,'' said White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   After debating the proposal to call witnesses, the Senate
retreated into a closed-door session to deliberate before emerging
for public votes on the two motions on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle warned that the first substantive Senate vote of the
impeachment trial may shatter the bipartisanship that has generally
prevailed at the trial. Daschle said 45 Senate Democrats will vote
to dismiss the impeachment case and against admission of witnesses
while the Senate's 55 Republicans will vote against dismissal and
for the admission of witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been able to largely avoid partisan votes until now, but
I'm skeptical,'' Daschle said. ``I think on the vote on dismissal
and on the vote on witnesses, it sounds as if the lines may be
drawn.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, predicted that some Democrats will
break ranks Wednesday to join Republicans to reject dismissal of
the case and to support the admission of witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow will be a red letter day for the Constitution,'' said
Gramm. ``I do not believe (Democrats) can be a solid united group
of people who are going to oppose the constitutional process to get
to a verdict,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials expressed concern that they may suffer
defections by Sens. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., Bob Graham, D-Fla.,
and possibly John Edwards, D-N.C.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)  &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said the decision by House prosecutors to cut the
proposed witness list from upwards of 15 witnesses to only three
witnesses helped cement the support of GOP moderates for having
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, said he was more inclined to vote
in favor of calling witnesses in light of the smaller witness list.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said the Senate may set a deadline for depositions to be
complete from the three witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is we'll set a date certain, like Monday, that this
all has to be done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said the pared-down list may persuade other Republicans
_ and even a few Democrats _ to vote to depose witnesses. Several
Republicans, including Sen. Ted Stevens of Alaska, said they want
to have witnesses deposed but do not want to see anyone testify
publicly on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   With Democrats bowing to defeat on the question of witnesses,
some senators shifted their focus to the procedures that would be
used. Some Republicans urged that the depositions be videotaped to
permit the witnesses' testimony to later be shown to senators on
the floor of the Senate without calling the witnesses themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I., circulated proposed ground rules for
deposing witnesses that called for each witness to be interviewed
for four hours _ split equally between the House prosecutors and
Clinton's lawyers. Chafee suggested videotaping the private
sessions for senators to view.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James E. Rogan, R-Calif., said House prosecutors decided to
limit their witness request to three because the lawmakers had been
``picking up lots of intelligence'' that narrowing the request to
three witnesses would garner the support of at least 51 senators.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan said House prosecutors went back and forth selecting the
witness list to ``politically strategize'' on the best balance for
making the case against Clinton without alienating a wavering
senator on calling witnesses at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 1853EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9427 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PERSPECT-COX     01-26 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PERSPECT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Though not illegal, nutrition products supplied to players a
touchy subject with NFL
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Most of the Broncos admit it. They play with a 13th man.
He lives in a suburb of Denver and the NFL has grown weary of his
act.
</P>
<P>
   He is EAS, Experimental and Applied Sciences, a small company
located in Golden, Colo., that produces a line of sports-related
nutrition products, some of which cross the lines of the NFL's drug
policy. EAS supplies the creatine that flows freely in the locker
room; even team owner Pat Bowlen and coach Mike Shanahan use it.
Players so frequently wear EAS-adorned clothing that the league
resorted to fining them for promoting a product not licensed by the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   And while none of the Broncos has been punished by the league
for using the EAS product Andro-6, the NFL was suspicious enough
last summer that it warned about illicit use of androstenedione,
after the Mark McGwire flap in baseball. EAS was the only firm
mentioned in the league's letter.
</P>
<P>
   To the Broncos, EAS is a large component of the team's success.
To the NFL, the company is a pain in the corporate rear.
</P>
<P>
   ``With EAS, you know it's a nutrient,'' said wide receiver Rod
Smith, a big client. ``It makes your body perform at it's maximum.
So why not use it? It can't hurt you. That's the thing. It can't
hurt you.''
</P>
<P>
   Then why is the NFL so spooked by EAS?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really want to comment on the league about EAS,''
Smith replied. ``I don't want to get myself in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   It might be too late for that. The league has been on the
Broncos about EAS for more than a year. Linebacker Bill Romanowski,
quarterback John Elway, running back Terrell Davis and tight end
Shannon Sharpe are paid endorsers for the company. Romanowski is
believed to receive a six-figure fee as a spokesman. The company's
name and logo were displayed conspicuously by Broncos players
during the 1997 championship drive, and today, paunchy Denverites
wear EAS apparel with no idea what the company is. Some still
believe EAS stands for ``Elway And Sharpe.''
</P>
<P>
   The league has gone to battle about such blatant logo display,
threatening to fine players after the first round of the playoffs,
when many players wore EAS hats and turtlenecks in post-game media
sessions, in disregard of the closely monitored licencing policy.
The league threatened to levy $10,000 fines and double them for
future violations. The team was in complete compliance for
Tuesday's media day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue came up last summer about the rules on (non-licenced
apparel on) game day,'' said Greg Aiello, the NFL's vice president
for public relations. ``Do those (uniform) rules apply to the
locker room after the game? And the answer is yes. I think what's
happened is they now understand the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   But the EAS flap is about performance enhancers, not clothing.
The creatine issue and long-term effects of the widely used
supplement, which develops muscle mass, are still unknown. Yet EAS
uses the highest-profile players on one of the NFL's high-profile
team to promote it.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that 75 percent of the Broncos use EAS products,
most of them creatine. More than half of the Falcons also use
dietary supplements, including creatine, amino acids and various
protein drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very beneficial to athletes when taken correctly,'' Sharpe has
said. ``Should be for highly skilled athletes, not to be toyed
with, not to be played with. . . . Carefully supervised. Very
misunderstood.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the federal Food and Drug Administration approved the
substance, creatine has come under increasing criticism for side
effects, including a potential for causing dehydration, which
prompts cramping. It is commonly found now in high-school locker
rooms, but some NFL teams -- Tampa Bay, Washington and Cincinnati
among them -- have banned its use.
</P>
<P>
   Andro-6 is a far more serious matter. It is on the NFL's banned
substances list. After the McGwire publicity, the NFL reiterated
its stance against steroid use. Androstenedione and
dehydroepiandrosterone both are banned substances, and both are in
Andro-6, which increases testosterone levels in the bloodstream to
promote muscle growth. McGwire, of the St. Louis Cardinals, used
Andro while breaking baseball's single-season home-run record last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Both substances also can mask steroids in a player's system.
Results from NFL drug-testing are confidential, and it is unknown
if any Broncos have tested positive for Andro-6. Bill Phillips,
EAS's chief executive officer, no longer takes calls from the
media, but he told the Rocky Mountain News last year, ``I would
never recommend to any Olympic athletes I coach or pro athletes to
use Andro-6. It can increase the testosterone levels enough to give
a false positive on a drug test.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is an unsavory aspect to the performance-enhancing
industry, the Broncos seen to be oblivious to it. Romanowski
reports that he is stronger and faster in his 11th pro season,
because of a grueling conditioning program and Phillips' input. It
was Romanowksi who first exposed the rest of the team to EAS.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got with Bill Phillips two years ago, he put together a
nutritional program for me that's helped me considerably,''
Romanowski said. ``With how I train and how I take care of myself,
I've been able to improve myself every year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If it makes a guy feel he has the extra energy or whatever it
takes,'' Smith said, ``hey, you're going to use it. If I'm training
and someone says you can be the caliber athlete of Michael Jordan
if you take this powder, you think they're not going to take it?''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
