<HEADER>
A9428 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PICTUREDAY-COX     01-26 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PICTUREDAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All walks of media life meet Super Bowl participants
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ He was dressed to the canines. Silver britches. Black
No. 34 Falcons jersey. A silver diamond hoop earring dangling from
each ear. And around his neck, Ray Buchanan wore a studded dog
collar.
</P>
<P>
   A thick, black leather dog collar, covered with silver studs
that glistened in the South Florida morning sun. Some guys just
know how to accessorize.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing it for fun, for the media,'' said Buchanan, the
Falcons Pro Bowl cornerback. ``They got us as a seven-point
underdog. So I thought I'd wear my dog collar.''
</P>
<P>
   So he dressed for excess for Tuesday's Super Bowl XXXIII Media
Day. What did teammate Bob Whitfield think of Buchanan's neckwear?
``I think he needs to wear it on his hips,'' Whitfield said. ``Ray
Buchanan looks like a Teletubby.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Media Day, the NFL's hour of babble, the photo op
where a picture is worth 1,000 wordsmiths and TV crews from ESPN to
Japan to ``Comedy Central'' converge. On Tuesday morning at Pro
Player Stadium, the Falcons underwent their Media Day baptism. The
fun began at 8:45 a.m., with the scoreboard clock set at 60:00. The
highlight clock is running:
</P>
<P>
   59:31 _ While walking across the field, Jamal Anderson filmed
the stadium and assembled media with a digital video camera.
Sitting down at one of 10 podiums reserved for coach Dan Reeves and
nine talkative Falcons, Anderson switches to a 35-mm. camera and
snaps four group shots of the media in front of him while advising,
``Be natural. Smile. Don't look posed.''
</P>
<P>
   When a man asks, ``Can you send one to my mother?'' Anderson
replies, ``For 10 bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   53:42 _ Beth Littleford, a correspondent for ``The Daily Show'',
is grilling backup safety Chris Bayne: ``The Dirty Birds is a
professional nickname. Does it apply to your personal life?'' Uh,
no. Then this: ``You're on special teams. How special is special
teams?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Real special,'' Bayne said. ``That's why they call them
special teams.''
</P>
<P>
   49:18 _ Keith Brooking is preserving the festivities with his
camcorder. It's the rookie's second Media Day in Pro Player. Last
season, Brooking and Georgia Tech played here in the Carquest Bowl.
``This is a little different, believe me,'' Brooking said. Total
Carquest media? ``Probably 100.'' None from German TV.
</P>
<P>
   42:20 _ Cornelius Bennett, the linebacker who lost four Super
Bowls in a row with Buffalo, is momentarily startled by a question:
``Who was more responsible for making you lose all those games, Jim
Kelly or James Lofton?'' Then Bennett spies the interrogator:
Lofton, standing beside Kelly, both ex-Bills now working in TV.
</P>
<P>
   36:37 _ Sometimes Whitfield can be reserved. Not now. Not even
when asked about being blind in his left eye. ``Who said that?''
Whitfield asked, covering his right eye. ``I can't see you.''
Pointing to his artificial eye, he said, ``It's big, ain't it? I'm
Cyclops.''
</P>
<P>
   29:51 _ Lesley Visser, the ABC sportscaster, finishes an
interview with O.J. Santiago, then asks the tight end, ``Can I
borrow your earrings?''
</P>
<P>
   24:31 _ More Whitfield, when asked to compare Anderson and
Denver's Terrell Davis: ``There's Jamal . . . .'' Long pause. ``And
there's everybody else.'' Three, four, five times he repeats it.
Later, when asked about Bronco quarterback John Elway, Whitfield
says, ``There's Jamal . . . .'' Long pause. ``And there's everybody
else.''
</P>
<P>
   19:22 _ Morten Andersen is one of several Falcons seated in
their own sections in the stands. The place-kicker from Denmark
answers in his native tongue to TV2 Sporten, of Danish television,
when Dom Irerra of ``Comedy Central'' follows up in Brooklynese:
``Oh, Morten, you don't really believe that, do you?'' Anderson
laughs. More Dom: ``Why do you think you're going to be the MVP?
Are you going to have sex before the game? Wait 'til halftime?''
</P>
<P>
   15:51 _ In section 139, team president Taylor Smith speaks
fondly of his late father, Rankin, when he's interrupted by a guy
with a cell phone: ``Mr. Smith? The Fabulous Sports Babe would like
to talk to you.'' Far more courteous than any TV type, Smith says,
``OK, now. I've got some other people here I'm talking to.''
</P>
<P>
   12:04 _ Several Falcons rookies and backups, ignored, lean on a
rolled-up baseball tarpaulin. Others sit in the Marlins dugout. Not
Robbie Tobeck. The center poses in the stands with the flag of
Wales wrapped around him. The Falcons have a sister city in Wales;
if they win Sunday, they'll donate $50,000 to a Welsh charity.
</P>
<P>
   9:22 _ ``Dan,'' asks a TV guy, ``can you spell your last name?''
Dan Stryzinski smiles for the camera: ``S-T-R-Y-Z-I-N-S-K-I.'' The
punter earlier declined a Japanese TV crew's offer to wear a white
headband adorned with Japanese characters. ``We'll be fined
$100,000 if we wear unlicensed NFL stuff,'' he said,
straight-faced.
</P>
<P>
   5:25 _ And yet more Whitfield, on what it's like to block for
Anderson: ``You know what it's like to run naked on the beach in
Rio de Janeiro with the rain hitting your butt? It's not like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   0:00 _ Time's up. The Falcons depart. The media reassembles
upstairs in Pro Player for brunch before descending on Denver. A
woman videotapes a closeup of granola, then a sweeping panorama of
grazing media. And one sports writer wonders what the rest of Media
Day will be like: ``You think Elway will have a dog collar on?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
