<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9429 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONSPASS-FEATU     01-26 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONSPASS-FEATURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Broncos want to get to Chandler through pressure from quick
front
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It isn't often that a team wins two Super Bowls in a row
with only one defensive lineman in the same position he played the
previous year. But that's what the Denver Broncos will attempt to
do Sunday night against the Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   One of the several keys for the Broncos, however, will be just
how well their retooled defensive front pressures Falcons
quarterback Chris Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   ``They build a pretty good wall around (Chandler),'' defensive
end Neil Smith said. ``What they've been doing lately is using max
protection, and they do it pretty well. You have to keep fighting
your way through those layers of protection to get to the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Falcons reshuffled the front group, coordinator
Greg Robinson's defense recorded 47 sacks this season, No. 7 in the
league. The Falcons surrendered 53 sacks, sixth-most in the NFL.
The perception is that the Falcons offensive line improved in
December, but it still allowed 12 sacks over the final four
regular-season contests.
</P>
<P>
   Much like the Falcons defense, the Broncos front creates
pressure with quickness and relentless desire. Robinson likes to
send linebacker Bill Romanowski on a third-down blitz from the
outside. In last year's Super Bowl, however, Robinson also designed
some blitzes for linebacker John Mobley, the quickest of the
Broncos' front seven. Denver also likes to blitz a nickel defender
out of the slot, but some of the Falcons formations might preclude
that move. What the Broncos might attempt to do is take advantage
of fullback Brian Kozlowski, the former tight end filling in for
Bob Christian. Some of the Broncos noted privately Tuesday that the
Atlanta running backs aren't solid pass-blockers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, we have to bring as much heat as we can
with our front-four guys,'' defensive end Maa Tanuvasa said. ``We
have to take it on ourselves to get to Chandler as often as
possible. Hopefully, our quickness will help us.''
</P>
<P>
   The new-look line clearly is quicker than the Broncos unit of a
year ago and evolved in part because of Robinson's need for speed.
Injuries also played a role in forcing some of the switches. The
lone lineman starting in the same position as he did in last year's
Super Bowl is right tackle Keith Traylor.
</P>
<P>
   Tanuvasa, a former tackle, moved to end when Alfred Williams had
biceps surgery early in the year. Harald Hasselbach replaced Smith
at left end. Trevor Pryce, a second-year veteran from Clemson, was
promoted to starter at left tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Williams usually play in the nickel defense, and
Tanuvasa sometimes moves back inside, where his ability to wiggle
through the gaps is advantageous. Of his 8 1/2 sacks this year,
five came when he moved from end to tackle.
</P>
<P>
   It is Pryce, though, who has proved to be right for the Broncos
pass rush. In his first season as a starter, he recorded 8 1/2
sacks. When he lines up in the gap he can be dangerous, especially
when Traylor occupies two blockers. At 285 pounds, Pryce lacks the
usual bulk of a tackle, but at 6 feet 5 he has natural leverage,
and he has learned to use his hands well.
</P>
<P>
   Only a year ago, some Denver insiders were suggesting that Pryce
was a flop.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has probably grown up as fast in one year as any player
we've had,'' Broncos coach Mike Shanahan said. ``His improvement
has been tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
