<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9442 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-SPORTS-ON-THE-NET     01-26 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SPORTS-ON-THE-NET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENJOY SUPER BOWL FROM COMFORTS OF HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To enjoy the atmosphere of Super Bowl XXXIII, you don't have to
be in balmy Miami, Fla., soaking up the ocean spray in a rented
sports car while speeding down Biscayne Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, simply pull up a seat in the den, boot up the computer and
watch it unfold on the 'Net.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of big-media sites give Super Bowl XXXIII a big presence
online. These resource-rich sites all have the components of a
quality site: updated content, easy navigation and interactivity.
</P>
<P>
   And they all have unique features.
</P>
<P>
   Here is one Web surfer's guide to the best of the Super Bowl
sites:
</P>
<P>
   BEST PREVIEW: CBS SportsLine
(www.sportsline.com/u/football/nfl/superbowl/xxxiii) has lots of
cool features that the other sites have, but none has EA SPORTS'
video-game simulation of this year's Super Bowl. Using Madden NFL
'99, the Denver Broncos won, but not before the Atlanta Falcons
bolted to a 22-0 lead. CBS SportsLine has a breakdown of the
simulated game, complete with still images and statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Best editorial content: CNN/SI
(cnnsi.com/football/nfl/1998/playoffs) taps the resources of Sports
Illustrated and CNN correspondents. If you like to read, this is
the place to go. And if you like the magazine's dynamic photos, the
site has a high-resolution image gallery loaded with Super
Bowl-related photos. Users can zoom into the images _ as if they
have an online magnifying glass _ for closer looks.
</P>
<P>
   BEST FANTASY GAMES: ESPN.com
(espn.go.com/nfl/playoffs98/superbowl) gets fantasy football
enthusiasts back online with its Fantasy Super Bowl Tournament and
Super Bowl Over/Under features.
</P>
<P>
   For the tournament, ESPN.com editors selected an all-time roster
for each franchise from all the players who ever wore its uniform
in a Super Bowl. Eight teams were seeded based on their Super Bowl
records. The San Francisco 49ers, who are 5-0 in Super Bowls, are
the No. 1 seed and the Cowboys, 5-3, the No. 2 seed. Votes cast by
ESPN.com users will decide a champion this week. It's a good way
for Cowboys fans to make some noise during Super Bowl week.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN.com's Over/Under is a free mini-fantasy game in which users
guess the frequency with which certain activities occur during the
game. Example: What quarter will be the first Dirty Bird dance
happen? Winner gets a TV.
</P>
<P>
   BEST INTERACTION: Superbowl.com (actually, superbowl.lycos.com)
has QB1, where online players test their play-calling skills during
the Super Bowl. Players must guess the offensive play and result
before each snap. Winners earn tickets to next year's Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   BEST VIDEO/AUDIO: Since most are sitting at home this season,
Cowboys fans yearning for a little nostalgia will love NFL.com's
Super Bowl section (www.nfl.com/sb33), which has video and audio of
memorable moments from past Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   BEST POLLS: ESPN.com will be polling online visitors after the
game about their favorite and least-favorite Super Bowl
commercials. For the sake of some imagination, let's get those
Budweiser lizards out of here, please.
</P>
<P>
   BEST PLACE TO LEARN HOW TO DO THE DIRTY BIRD: Jamal Anderson's
site on America Online (keyword: jamal) has step-by-step
instructions. The Falcons running back also relates his theory on
the Dirty Bird on his site, which hawks official Dirty Bird
merchandise at a 10-percent discount this week.
</P>
<P>
   BEST CHAMBER-OF-COMMERCE-LIKE SITE: SoFla.com's Super Bowl site
(www.sofla.com/FEATURES/superbowl) has it all: where to stay, where
to eat, where to celebrate, etc. It also has tips on where to rent
a car _ in case you decide to go to Miami and not sit in the den
and call up Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   (Tommy Cummings writes about the Internet for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7397. E-mail:
dragon(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 1909EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9443 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CARLREINER-TEX     01-26 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CARLREINER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE WORLD OF TV, EXPERIENCE IS SOMETHING THAT COUNTS AGAINST
YOU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Carl Reiner is speaking of writing, of comedic
composing, of being in the zone. He has felt this before when no
one was around, when it was late and dark and there was just him
and his words, which seemed to gush like oil from a busted pipe.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers the feeling vividly, back when he was the living
mechanism fueling ``The Dick Van Dyke Show,'' back when his calls
were returned and TV executives waited patiently on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's pushing 70 and wouldn't be shocked if the pimple-faced
programmers asked if ``that's Reiner with an `e', sir?'' and could
he please fax over his credits?
</P>
<P>
   He knows how the business works; after all, he worked it for
years. But it doesn't matter when it comes to the words. They've
been flowing, just like in the old times, for this television pilot
he's written, and it has made him excited and intrigued, if also
somewhat nervous about facing a world that's changing right under
his feet.
</P>
<P>
   He knew he had to come see the pimple faces, to hear their
thoughts, and he did. He made a couple references to major actors
to play major parts and they frowned and chuckled and asked
``Who?'' which made him realize there's a problem selling something
to anybody who's not riding the same vibe.
</P>
<P>
   Seems his concept had to be a high-concept ``Friends'' or a
low-concept ``Seinfeld'' or something that would put them in the
mind-frame of something else. What is it? they begged.
</P>
<P>
   He walked out wondering if he has fallen too many steps behind
the game, whether the language of the day is no longer his own. He
talks of the ``classic language,'' which still buzzes within him
with so much force that he has written a book of short stories that
will be published this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Writers have to write,'' he says. ``I'm not going to ever stop
writing. I'll find some way to write, even here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here'' is television, a medium where the more experience you
have, the less useful you are. A place where surgical knives carve
out fountains of exterior youth. A place where writers near or over
50 are virtually shut out and shut down because they're considered
too old and too out of touch and too unhip to write anything for
viewers 18-to-34.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the latest Writer's Guild report and see how the rate of
employment decreases after age 30. Last season, 77 weekly series
had no writers over 50. Few over 40. No wonder older writers cut
off their 1970s credits. No wonder 32-year-old Riley Weston duped
The WB into thinking she was 19 just to get a writing gig. No
wonder the older guys sit around dazed and confused and questioning
why series TV today require an army of producers when they were the
lone wolves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty names,'' Reiner says. ``Four executive producers, each
executive producer has his personal executive producer, and each
story editor has a story editor to produce the story. I've never
seen so many names needed to put out a 22-minute show.''
</P>
<P>
   So the pimple faces look for kindred souls and graze in their
own splendor of naivete, cross-pollinating and socializing like
killer bees, which is how it has always been done. Reiner knows.
His kindred souls know. The twist is that back then, the older,
more experienced writers got the gigs and younger folks waited in
the line forming at the rear. Stand there and learn, kid, and be
the better for it.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Lear, he of ``All in the Family'' and ``The Jeffersons,''
thinks his writers could tear it up today because the comedy has
held up like Super Glue. Ask TV Land. Ask Nick at Night. ``But so
many of the executives that are buying the ideas, passing on the
ideas, at all the networks and cable stations, are very young
(people) whose greatest theatrical or entertainment involvement was
with the television tube _ not with the stage and film and
literature,'' Lear says.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the way kids behave on television through the years of
their growth is the way they think kids behave. So that's why
you've got so many (smart-aleck) kids on television that have no
relationship to the children you have in your home. And everything
works that way. If their involvement is with the tube, they're
thinking about ideas that work in that context today.''
</P>
<P>
   Lear wonders whether they are capable now of thinking outside
the box, if it's too late. Will network television as we know it
die under the weight of cable? If not, will it simply become a
victim of sameness?
</P>
<P>
   Meryl Marshall, president of the Academy of Television Arts and
Sciences, which will induct Reiner into its Hall of Fame next month
figures there's room, too, for the golden agers to make a return,
but with more savvy and less ego.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work with people with whom we're most familiar and most
comfortable,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``But also, if the music that we listen to is not the same music
that the audience, the young audience, is listening to, and a buyer
is looking to meet that young audience, we have to ask ourselves
whether we're operating in a context that's appropriate and whether
we have the language, the mannerisms, the stories that they need
and want to be able to hear and enjoy. So we have to accept some
responsibility for crossing that bridge ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Reiner knows this and understands this, but it has nothing to
with the flow, the gushing of words, the zone. He's back, at least
in his mind, when he's sitting down and ``I feel exactly the same
way as I did when I was doing `Van Dyke Show.'''
</P>
<P>
   So he'll sit and he'll write and he'll wait. The words will
flow. Or ``fly'' as he calls it. And he'll feel the way he used to.
Alive.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 1909EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
