<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9444 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RETAILING-INTERNET-TE     01-26 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETAILING-INTERNET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETAILERS TRYING HARDER TO SELL WARES ON WEB, BUT FUTURE IS
ANYBODY'S GUESS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by RETAILING-WEB SITES) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LILA LAHOOD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a growing belief among traditional retailers regarding
online shopping: No one knows how big it could get, but in the
meantime, more are unwilling to risk the wait unwired.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping on the Web still accounts for a small fraction of U.S.
retail sales. But the segment is growing quickly, as more Net
surfers scrap the drive to the mall for a seat in front of the
computer at home. During the 1998 holiday season, consumers spent
about $115 billion in all, $2.3 billion of which was spent online,
double what was spent during the 1997 holidays, according to
Jupiter Communications, a New York research firm.
</P>
<P>
   And even though many retailers say they have low expectations at
this point for Internet sales, stores ranging from J.C. Penney to
Pier 1 Imports are stepping up efforts to get established on the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your competition goes online, it becomes imperative that
you go online,'' said David Szymanski, associate director of the
Center for Retailing Studies at Texas A&AMP;M University. The emergence
of online bookseller Amazon.com, for example, prompted retailer
Barnes &AMP; Noble to launch a Web site in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   It's not hard to find retailers on the Web. They have used it as
a way to draw customers into the stores, announce events,
test-market, and track customer buying habits.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart, a giant discounter, offers 175,000-250,000 items
online at any given time, more than you'd find in a Wal-Mart store.
Pier 1 and Tandy Corp., operator of Radio Shack stores, plan to
sell products online this year. J.C. Penney, which launched its Web
site four years ago, plans other sites directed at targeted
audiences beginning this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Wal-Mart example aside, retailers typically limit the
merchandise they offer online to a smaller selection of what they
carry in their stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``If nothing else, the retailers are using it as advertising
more than to sell products on the Web,'' with the main objective
being to draw shoppers into the real store, said George Gillen, a
Dallas partner with the PricewaterhouseCoopers consulting and
auditing firm.
</P>
<P>
   That is Pier 1's strategy, says chairman and chief executive
Marvin Girouard.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to create a $15 million business on the
Internet and lose $15 million with your store sales,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pier 1, based in Fort Worth, sells gift certificates and offers
bridal gift registry services on its Web site. It plans to start
selling merchandise online in May and will offer about 400 items
online, compared with about 4,500 in an average Pier 1 store.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to go gently into it,'' Girouard said.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth-based Tandy, which operates 7,000 Radio Shack stores
nationwide, has similiar views.
</P>
<P>
   The company uses its Web site to display products and provide
store location information, and it expects to start selling online
this year. Tandy does not expect online sales to cut into store
revenues, spokesman Ron Trumbla said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talk about hits,'' Trumbla said, referring to the
number of visitors to a Web site. ``We get, every day, 1 million
living, breathing people who walk into our stores.''
</P>
<P>
   The growth of online retailing has started becoming evident
within the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   Among traditional retailers, Penney was an early entrant to the
field, posting its Web site in 1995 and launching sales the
following year. Since then, the company has refined its strategy,
viewing the Web as a logical extension of its stores and catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Its first site aimed at a specialized audience _ this one for
full-figured women, a group that has been ``historically
underserved,'' spokesman Michael Ponder said _ will be launched in
the spring.
</P>
<P>
   The site will let customers build rotating ``models'' of
themselves, including choices for size, hair and skin tone, and
then use the models to try on clothing and solicit advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes a catalog for one,'' Ponder said.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out what consumers will buy online is a key challenge
facing the traditional stores.
</P>
<P>
   Books, compact discs, computers and electronics, tickets and
services have shown the most success in online sales because they
``are easy for the customer to evaluate without touching or trying
on,'' Szymanski said.
</P>
<P>
   Also high on the list are what Al Meyers, director of retail
strategy for the Senn-Delaney unit of Arthur Andersen in Dallas,
calls destination and repeat purchases _ items the consumer already
is familiar with: ``Anything that's a model number, a particular
brand that can be compared and cross-shopped,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many other challenges of online retailing mirror those of the
catalog business. Sizes are not uniform, and colors displayed in a
2-inch graphic will look different on a full-scale product. Returns
are inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers that don't have catalog experience might have
difficulty building the internal structure to deliver orders
efficiently, Gillen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start to disappoint people because you can't get the
product there, you could lose customers,'' Gillen said.
</P>
<P>
   How successful online retailing will eventually be is anybody's
guess.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts predict online services that browse the Web and
identify sites with the lowest prices. ``That could dramatically
lower margins in the business on brand-name products,'' Meyers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gillen expects online sales to net between 5 percent and 8
percent of the retail market within a few years. It's harder to
tell how long it will take for retailers to establish a profitable
Internet business.
</P>
<P>
   That depends on how long it takes for consumers to fully embrace
online shopping. ``There's still something about going and touching
a lot of products that's important to people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
