<P>
   The New York plans 5 pages of coverage, including 2 pages of
text, on the continuing Senate trial of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans a 5-page package of stories, including
2 pages of text, on the continuing Senate impeachment trial of
President Clinton and related developments.
</P>
<P>
   Moving at  &UR; 7:30 p.m. Eastern time &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TWO-STEP (Washington) _ Searching for a graceful ending
to the impeachment trial, Sen. Trent Lott, the Republican leader,
today named a six-Senator working group to examine how the Senate
could vote to find President Clinton culpable for perjury and
obstruction of justice without removing him from office. By David
E. Rosenbaum. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SESSIONS (Washington) _ What it was like in the
closed-door sessions. By Frank Bruni and Katharine Q. Seelye. (900
wds)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LEWINSKY (Washington) _ Declining to wait for a Senate
subpoena, Monica S. Lewinsky checked out of the Mayflower Hotel
here today and returned home to Los Angeles. Her lawyer, Plato
Cacheris, said that the former White House intern wanted to get out
of town. ``She's been cooped up in the hotel,'' Cacheris told
reporters. ``She's not able to leave and she wants to get on with
her life.'' By Don Van Natta. (200 words)
</P>
<P>
   Moving by  &UR; 8:00 p.m. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HUBBELL-TAXES (Washington) _ In a striking victory for Ken
Starr, a Federal appeals court reinstates a tax fraud case against
Webster Hubbell, saying a lower-court judge was wrong to say that
the independent counsel overreached in bringing the case. By Neil
A. Lewis. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ASSESS (Washington) _ Senate Republican leaders are now
gambling that they can open the door to witnesses and yet still
somehow bring the trial of President Clinton to a relatively quick,
dignified and non-confrontational conclusion. A news analysis by
Alison Mitchell. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCENE (Washington) _ Scenes from the Hill. By Francis X.
Clines. (850 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moving by 8:30 p.m. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The ledeall:
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RDP (Washington) _ Ledeall: Even as House prosecutors
today offered a short list of witnesses to appease skittish Senate
Republicans, outside the chamber Democrats angrily countered that
summoning witnesses was unnecessary and would significantly prolong
President Clinton's impeachment trial. The skirmishing came on the
eve of two crucial votes. Senators on Wednesday will likely vote
against dismissing the case, along party lines. But a vote on
whether to depose the three witnesses House managers want to call,
is too close to predict, senators said, although both sides said
the momentum was moving toward passage. By Eric Schmitt and Lizette
Alvarez. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   Moving by  &UR; 9:00 p.m. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ In the chamber: In a surprise move,
House prosecutors asked the Senate today to ``request the
appearance'' of President Clinton at a deposition for his
impeachment trial. They also sought subpoenas to question Monica
Lewinsky, presidential friend Vernon Jordan and White House aide
Sidney Blumenthal. By R.W. Apple Jr. (1550 words)
</P>
<P>
   STARR-LEAKS (Washington) _ U.S. District Court Judge Johnson
releases new documents in the investigation of possible leaks from
Kenneth Starr's office. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-REPUBS (Washington) _ Many Republican strategists see
the desire to maintain decent relations with The House as a key
reason why the Senate won't just shut the trial down. By Richard L.
Berke. (800 words)
</P>
