<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-HUSSEIN-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING HUSSEIN RETURNS TO U.S. FOR MEDICAL TREATMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ Only hours after anointing a new heir, King
Hussein flew back to the United States on Tuesday for urgent
medical treatment prompted by what his doctors said were
indications that his cancer might be recurring.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors said the king, 63, had suffered fevers and
blood-count abnormalities since returning to Jordan on Jan. 19. He
was heading directly to the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn., where
he had spent six months in treatment for non-Hodgkins lymphoma.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday morning the new crown prince, Abdullah, 36, was sworn
in at the airport to run the country in his father's absence. He
replaces Hussein's brother, Prince Hassan, who was crown prince for
34 years.
</P>
<P>
   The king's abrupt leave-taking added to a sense of unease
evident in Jordan, whose residents are still digesting the
surprising news that Abdullah, a career soldier with little
experience of politics, now stands next in line for the throne.
</P>
<P>
   And now Jordan faces once again the prospect that the king, who
has had diagnoses of cancer twice in the last six years, may be
sicker than anyone knows.
</P>
<P>
   Official photographs taken at a ceremony on Monday night, when
Hassan handed his portfolio to Crown Prince Abdullah, showed the
king leaning on a walking stick. Although he piloted his own plane
back to Jordan last week from London, where he had been recovering,
Jordanian officials said he was a passenger on the flight to
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very unfortunate development,'' said Mustafa
Hamarneh, director of the Center for Strategic Studies at the
University of Jordan. ``In my view the country needs the king more
than ever. Crown Prince Abdullah is very new at this, and it's
extremely critical that the king be around for a number of years in
order to give the young prince a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Before returning to Jordan, the king told his subjects that he
was ``fully recovered'' from his latest illness.
</P>
<P>
   He underwent six sessions of chemotherapy and a bone-marrow
transplant during his stay at the Mayo Clinic and had not been
scheduled to return for a follow-up examination until March. As he
left the clinic on Dec. 29, doctors there pronounced him in good
health.
</P>
<P>
   But the king's personal doctor, Lt. Gen. Samir Farraj, told
reporters in the Jordanian capital Tuesday that because of the
nature of the king's symptoms, ``I, as well as doctors from the
Mayo Clinic, thought it best to send him back to the clinic for
checkups and treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   An official statement reported that ``after his majesty's
blessed return,'' his doctors had noticed ``an occasional increase
in his temperature and, they feared, as a result of initial tests,
a lack of blood cells produced by the bone marrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement noted that the king had stood in an open car in
wintry rain for hours last Tuesday to acknowledge the hundreds of
thousands of people who lined his route to welcome him home.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the decision that he should return to the United States
so quickly suggested that this was being treated as more than a
passing episode.
</P>
<P>
   The events of the last week have also raised the question of
whether the king's apparent haste in altering the line of
succession in favor of his son had been motivated by a knowledge
that he remained ill. That is a question to which no one in a
position to know has volunteered an answer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The king has battled illness successfully before: In 1992 he
underwent surgery to remove a kidney after the discovery of
cancerous cells. In 1997 he had prostate and lymph-node surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The news of his abrupt departure seems to have affected many
Jordanians and to have intensified a critical focus on Abdullah, an
army major general who heads Jordan's special forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``The king has been here so long I don't know what Jordan would
do without him,'' said Jamal Khader, 32, a shopkeeper on a downtown
Amman street. ``They say Abdullah is a good man, but we don't
really know him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rami Khouri, a Jordanian political columnist, said, ``Some
people will no doubt express legitimate concerns over his capacity
to run affairs of state, primarily because Abdullah is untested.''
</P>
<P>
   The air of uncertainty was heightened, Jordanians said, by the
public release of a letter from the king to Hassan that offered an
uncommon glimpse into tensions within the royal family.
</P>
<P>
   In it, the king told his brother that he had been stripped of
his title of crown prince in part because Hassan and his supporters
had been acting as if the king was already out of the picture.
</P>
<P>
   The king wrote that he had been forced to intervene ``from the
sickbed'' to halt a shakeup of top army officers under Hassan that
he said would have amounted to ``a settling of scores.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On top of my personal suffering, I was for the first time
pained in my own life,'' the king said of the episode. He said he
had also been deeply hurt by what he labeled a vicious whispering
campaign that he said Hassan's supporters had directed against
Hussein's American-born wife, Queen Noor, and their four children.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most critically, the king also suggested that Hassan had
stood in the way of his own plans to establish a family council
that might have ruled that power should pass first to Hassan and
then to one of Hussein's sons.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, the king disclosed for the first time that he had
considered abdicating in his brother's favor in 1992, after his
cancer diagnosis that year. But he said he had decided against that
course, and suggested strongly that the reason had been a belief
that Hassan would have been determined to appoint his own son as
his heir.
</P>
<P>
   In a reply, Hassan was contrite. ``I put myself in your hands
and abide by your honorable order,'' he said of the decree that
designated Abdullah as crown prince.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
