<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9459 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-HUSSEIN-BOS &LR;      01-26 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-HUSSEIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING HUSSEIN RETURNS TO US; OLDEST SON IN CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Jordan's cancer-stricken King Hussein has returned
to the United States for emergency medical care, leaving his oldest
son, and newly anointed successor, holding the reins of power in
his absence.
</P>
<P>
   The king's suddenly deteriorating health and rapid departure
Tuesday came only 12 hours after he had stunned Jordan and the
world with the announcement that the throne would not pass to his
brother, Prince Hassan, but to new Crown Prince Abdullah.
</P>
<P>
   The developments within the monarchy have reverberated
throughout the Middle East, where the king has come to play an
indispensible role as a strong moral voice and a peace maker with
neighboring Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is made more dramatic by the fact that it comes
just one week after a homecoming in which the nation poured out its
heart to the monarch and celebrated what the palace said was his
``good health'' after six months of cancer treatments in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Upon his return home Jan. 19, Hussein, 63, piloted his own plane
and enthusiastically greeted hundreds of thousands of Jordanians
who lined the streets to welcome him on a raw, rainy day. The
popular monarch, poked his head _ bald from chemotherapy but
wrapped in a red-and-white-checked kaffiyeh _ through a sunroof of
his limo and waved to his subjects.
</P>
<P>
   The gesture was classic Hussein _ warm and vibrant and of the
people. Critics might say it was also characteristically
egotistical. Now, like some tragic Shakespearean figure it could
sadly lead to the undoing of his fragile health.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two hours of driving in the open-topped limousine through
the cold and rain, palace sources fear, brought on the recurrent
fevers and low blood count. His failing condition has concerned
doctors enough to send him back to Minnesota's Mayo Clinic for
tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``His majesty is leaving after suffering from exhaustion,'' a
palace statement said. ``He is going for medical tests.''
</P>
<P>
   His departure came amid palace infighting surrounding his
decision on succession _ made official early Tuesday by royal
decree _ was reportedly intense and at times ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein has ruled over the Hashemite kingdom of Jordan for
nearly a half century, taking the crown at age 17 in 1952 after his
father abdicated due to mental illness and only one year after he
stood next to his grandfather as he was assasinated in Jerusalem.
He is a beloved figure in his country. Eighty percent of Jordanians
have known no other ruler.
</P>
<P>
   The ousting of his younger brother, Prince Hassan, who served as
crown prince and heir to the throne for 34 years, shocked the
nation and caused some concern about the stability of the
monarchical government.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter published in the Jordan Times that did not mince
words, King Hussein publicly rebuked Hassan for meddling in the
army and opposing the king's plans for the succession.
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal of Hassan, who many palace observers say never had
the charisma of his older brother, has given sudden rise to
prominence of the 36-year-old Abdullah, Hussein's oldest son and
the product or his second marriage. Some believed that the crown
would go to Prince Hamzeh, 18, the king's eldest son by his current
wife, the American-born Queen Noor.
</P>
<P>
   But amid the family squabbling it seemed the king deferred to
tradition, opting to pass the crown to his eldest son.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah is a respected senior military officer but a political
novice who inherits the daunting task of guiding a land
precariously positioned between Iraq and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Like his father, Abdullah is considered down-to-earth and
trusted by the leaders of the Bedouin clans _ unlike Hassan, who
was viewed as too erudite and arrogant.
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage for Abdullah is his marriage to a Palestinian
woman. This, palace watchers believe, will put him in good standing
with the majority of Jordan's population _ Palestinian refugees
displaced from the West Bank and welcomed on the other side of the
Jordan River after the Arab-Israeli wars of 1948 and 1967.
</P>
<P>
   He will need all of the support he can get as he faces the
challenges of balancing a growing income gap and a potentially
restive underclass in a land with few natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   But by far the most difficult _ and crucial _ issue the Crown
Prince will face is preserving the tenuous 1994 peace accord with
Israel. King Hussein was given time by his people to give peace a
chance, analysts say; it is unclear that his successor will be
afforded that luxury.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
