<HEADER>
A9460 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIORAMA-TEXAS-TEX     01-26 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIORAMA-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE DABS FROM 25,297 TEXANS DOT DIORAMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY BINGHAM 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Only in Texas ... will you find the nation's
largest paint-by-numbers picture.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Brenham artist Jim Campbell brings to Fort Worth his
48-foot-long diorama painted by _ hold your breath _ 25,297 Texans,
including 1,362 from Fort Worth-Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Y'all take a moment and pat y'allselves on the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, it's really impressive that that many people did
such a good job,'' Campbell said. The painting, ``A Little Dab of
Texas,'' is on display starting Tuesday at Suitable for Framing in
west Fort Worth. The exhibit ends Saturday with a reception for
Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   The painting was Campbell's idea, so the cowboys, longhorns, log
cabins and wagons are his drawings. The roadrunner, rattler, wild
pig and cows he hid in the collage are his, too. The vibrant
purple, yellow, orange and turquoise colors are his take on the Old
West.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, who is a contemporary western artist, was looking for
publicity. He hauled his 12 panels to more than 80 locations
statewide, from a Victoria rodeo to a ranch outside Weatherford,
from a Dallas Texaco station to Arbor Day in Euless.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the 12 pieces of wood is a stand-alone picture that
measures 4 feet by 8 feet. When put together, they form the
diorama. Campbell drew them in pencil, then asked his amateur
artists to match color paint to the small dots of color he used to
code his drawings. He went through a surprisingly small amount of
paint: six gallons.
</P>
<P>
   The project took him three years and four months, but now that
it's done, it will be displayed in 30 Texas cities. It has already
been on display in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Look closely, and you can see where some painters took artistic
license. One wise guy painted a cream-colored shingle green;
another gave a longhorn steer a smile, a pair of eyelashes and a
brand shaped like the state itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knew I hid stuff, so the people who painted got back
at me and they started hiding things in the painting themselves,''
Campbell said. He painted over any initials, names or slogans he
found. But he's still finding dots turned into hearts, hands bigger
than he drew them, and other surprises.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest Texan to paint was 14 days old; the oldest 92
years. One boy spit in his paint to make it go further, and one
cowboy dipped his brush in a can of Bud Light for the same reason.
It's rumored that a wiener dog in Abilene took some strokes, but
Campbell didn't count him.
</P>
<P>
   No telling what he hid in the painting.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``A Little Dab of Texas''
</P>
<P>
   Through Saturday: 10 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. through Friday, 10 a.m.
to 4 p.m. Saturday at Suitable for Framing, 6323 Camp Bowie Blvd.,
Fort Worth. Artist reception is 1-7 p.m. Saturday and is open to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   Admission: Free
</P>
<P>
   Information: (817) 735-9558
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
