<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-HUBBELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT REINSTATES CASE AGAINST HUBBELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal appeals court handed a victory to
independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr Tuesday, reinstating a tax
evasion case against former Associate Attorney General Webster
Hubbell. But the court also raised questions about the way Starr
handled the case, suggesting it may be difficult to successfully
prosecute the charges.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate impact of the decision is that Hubbell, a former
mayor of Little Rock, Ark., and one of President Clinton's closest
friends, now faces a criminal trial on charges that he evaded
taxes. The case also is significant because it may prompt Starr to
delve once again into the Whitewater matter, which has dogged the
president for years.
</P>
<P>
   But the 2-1 ruling by the US Court of Appeals in the District of
Columbia contained enough questions about Starr's treatment of the
case that the Hubbell legal team wound up praising part of the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell attorney John Nields said he is ``very gratified'' that
the court questioned whether Starr violated Hubbell's Fifth
Amendment rights by relying on documents provided by Hubbell under
a limited grant of immunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides have something to cheer about,'' said former
federal prosecutor Robert Ullmann of Boston, noting that the
reinstatement of the case is tempered by questions about whether
key evidence will be deemed admissable.
</P>
<P>
   The Hubbell case is being closely watched in Washington because
Starr has suggested that Hubbell knows more about Clinton's
involvement in the Whitewater land development project than he has
said. Hubbell, in turn, has said Starr brought the case against him
in an effort to intimidate him into lying about the president and
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're innocent, not only myself but my wife and my friends of
any of the underlying charges,'' Hubbell said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling overturns a decision last July by US District Judge
James Robertson that resulted in the tax case being thrown out.
Robertson ruled that Starr violated Hubbell's Fifth Amendment
rights by basing the tax case on records supplied by Hubbell under
a grant of limited immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the appeals court said that while Starr's case against
Hubbell may be sound, Starr's methods may be questionable.
</P>
<P>
   The case may be sound, the court said, because it is
``reasonable'' for Starr to theorize that Hubbell was paid hundreds
of thousands of dollars in ``hush money'' from Clinton friends who
wanted to ensure that Hubbell wouldn't talk about the president's
involvement in Whitewater.
</P>
<P>
   But the court questioned whether Starr based his case on records
that Hubbell supplied under the limited immunity grant. Those
documents included 13,120 pages of Hubbell's financial records.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave me immunity to get the documents and then they used
those documents to later indict,'' Hubbell said Tuesday. ``That's
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In the tax case, Starr alleged that Hubbell owes about $900,000
in taxes and penalties. Starr also alleged that Hubbell performed
little or no work for hundreds of thousands of dollars in
consulting fees, much of it from Clinton friends.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court Tuesday did not rule on whether the payments
were intended to keep Hubbell quiet, but said the theory is
sufficient reason to bring the case against Hubbell. ``The timing,
sources, and extent of the payments make the belief that they were
hush money reasonable,'' the ruling said.
</P>
<P>
   But the appeals court warned Starr that he must show he learned
about the key facts of the case without relying on the documents
provided by Hubbell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government labors under `a heavy burden of proving that
all evidence it seeks to introduce is untainted by the immunized
act of production,' '' the court said, quoting a prior case.
``Accordingly, should the Independent Counsel prove unable to meet
the requisite evidentiary burden, the contents of those documents
will be inadmissible.''
</P>
<P>
   That raised comparisons to the way the former White House aide,
Lieutenant Colonel Oliver North, initially was found guilty in the
Iran-contra affair, but then had the verdict overturned after a
federal appeals ruled he was improperly convicted partly on the
basis of testimony he provided under a congressional grant of
immunity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
