<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LEWINSKY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY DECIDES TO GET OUT OF TOWN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (See related stories: IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-TRIAL,
IMPEACH-TWO-STEP, IMPEACH-SESSIONS, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-REPUBS,
HUBBELL-TAXES, STARR-LEAKS) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Declining to wait for a Senate subpoena, Monica S.
Lewinsky checked out of the Mayflower Hotel here Tuesday and
returned home to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   While House managers argued for the necessity of calling her as
a witness, Ms. Lewinsky, 25, hurried past a phalanx of reporters
and TV cameras that had been parked outside the hotel since her
arrival on Saturday and stepped into a limousine.
</P>
<P>
   Her lawyer, Plato Cacheris, said that the former White House
intern wanted to get out of town. ``She's been cooped up in the
hotel,'' Cacheris said. ``She wants to get on with her life.''
</P>
<P>
   For the third consecutive day, Cacheris announced that Ms.
Lewinsky had absolutely no interest in testifying at the Senate
impeachment trial of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It took a court order to summon Ms. Lewinsky to Washington on
Saturday. And it would take a Senate subpoena to bring her back
over the next few days, her lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she's needed, if they issue a proper document to get her
back here, she will return,'' Cacheris said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
