<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the business news stories the Los Angeles Daily News
plans to move for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs
of Wednesday, Jan. 27 and thereafter. The stories will carry the
``f'' financial news category code unless otherwise noted. For
questions about stories, contact James Laurin at the Daily News,
(818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-BAD-QUARTER (Los Angeles) _ Wall Street trackers
following The Walt Disney Co. are bracing for the entertainment
giant to post one of its worst quarters in memory due to continued
poor performance at ABC and home video operations. By Dave McNary.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRONIC-YEARBOOK (Los Angeles) _ Yeardisc Systems Inc. has
released a do-it-yourself yearbook software package that lets
schools bypass the traditional paper-and-binding approach by going
straight to an electronic format. Sounds good, especially for
schools on a budget, but where are your friends going to sign? By
Ben Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   KTEL-CUSTOM-CD (Los Angeles) _ K-Tel International has announced
an online custom CD store, sending the company's shares up 10
percent. Users can customize their CDs, picking from K-Tel's
collection of thousands of songs to put together their own. By Ben
Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   MRV-STOCK-JUMP (Los Angeles) _ Shares of telecommunications
equipment specialist MRV Communications Inc. surged more than 20
percent for their biggest gain since the stock melted down five
months ago. By Dave McNary.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
