<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-RESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA'S ELECTIONS CHIEF ABRUPTLY QUITS
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ After months of fighting over the
way South Africa's second post-apartheid election should be run,
the chairman of the country's Independent Election Commission
resigned suddenly Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman, Johann Kriegler, had repeatedly complained of a
lack of financing for his agency and criticized the government's
decision to require voters to get new identity documents before
registering.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts believe that the identity document decision could
discourage millions from voting _ particularly whites and those in
deep rural areas _ and cause other problems as well. Two opposition
parties are challenging the rule in court.
</P>
<P>
   Only last month, Kriegler warned of ``the ominous specter of
tens of thousands of black youths arriving at voting stations on
election day _ but having to be turned away'' because of the
government insistence on new bar-coded identification books.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1994 elections, voters had only to go to the polls
carrying identification. But this time the country is trying to
enforce stricter controls.
</P>
<P>
   The voter registration process has, however, been plagued with
difficulties and Kriegler's departure just months before the
election is due only increased the fear here that the vote could be
delayed.
</P>
<P>
   According to South Africa's constitution, elections must be held
before the end of July, but the vote has been expected in May or
June. The constitution also says that President Nelson Mandela can
fix the date only after Parliament has adjourned, probably at the
end of March.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela announced Kriegler's resignation at a hastily convened
news conference at his home here. He did not say why Kriegler had
resigned, but denied it had to do with a shortage of financing or
the new registration procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was with great regret that I accepted the resignation today
of Judge Johann Kriegler as commissioner and as chairperson of the
IEC,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kriegler, 66, is an outspoken and independent-minded man who
guided the nation through its first free election in 1994, which
ended white minority rule and put the African National Congress in
control of the government.
</P>
<P>
   After Mandela's announcement, Kriegler held his own news
conference and rejected the idea that his departure could delay the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had found ``the load'' of being both the chairman of
the commission and a member of the nation's highest court, the
Constitutional Court, ``increasingly heavy.'' At the same time, he
said, ``persisting differences of opinion about the role and
function of the commission'' had added to the burden.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to enumerate his differences with the Mandela
administration, saying: ``You know what they are. They have been
reported. It would be unfair of me to highlight any one now.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela said he had appointed Kriegler's deputy, Brigalia Bam,
to replace him in the interim.
</P>
<P>
   Kriegler first threatened to resign last July if the agency did
not get more financing to conduct the elections. It received about
$90 million, about half the amount requested. Instead, it abandoned
its voter education efforts and then drastically curtailed its
registration drives. Only after a public uproar did the government
make army personnel available to help.
</P>
<P>
   Kriegler has also repeatedly objected to the government's
insistence on the bar-coded identification books, a requirement
that is expected to hurt the opposition parties. Three parties, two
largely supported by whites and the Inkatha Freedom Party, the
country's second-largest black party, have called on the government
to revoke the requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Inkatha was particularly concerned that its rural supporters
would have a hard time getting the new identification.
</P>
<P>
   The rule is also likely to affect white voters. While blacks
were quick to get rid of the apartheid-era documents, many whites
have not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
