<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9478 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TWO-STEP-560&AMP;     01-26 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TWO-STEP-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE GROUP NAMED TO STUDY BEST WAY TO END TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine, N.M., Mo., Ky., Va.)  (See related stories: IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-TRIAL,
IMPEACH-SESSIONS, IMPEACH-LEWINSKY, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-REPUBS,
HUBBELL-TAXES, STARR-LEAKS) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Searching for a graceful ending to the impeachment
trial, Sen. Trent Lott, the Republican leader, on Tuesday named a
six-senator working group to examine how the Senate could vote to
express its view that President Clinton committed perjury and
obstruction of justice without removing him from office.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's problem is one of numbers: A majority of senators _ most
Republicans and possibly some Democrats _ believe that the
president committed the offenses described in the articles of
impeachment, and they do not want to end the trial with only a vote
to acquit. But far fewer than the two-thirds of senators required
by the Constitution are prepared to vote the president out of
office.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, opinion polls show that most people agree that
Clinton is culpable but do not want him expelled from office.
</P>
<P>
   The latest device under consideration by the senators would be a
preliminary vote on ``findings of fact,'' in which senators could
affirm the truth of the charges in the articles of impeachment.
Presumably a majority would vote in favor.
</P>
<P>
   A second vote would then be taken on removing the president from
office. Presumably it would fail for lack of a two-thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
   This seems to pass constitutional muster. The first vote would
be like a sense of the Senate resolution and would not involve
punishment. In many respects, it would be hardly different from the
censure resolution that some Democrats have advocated as an
alternative to impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, some senators considered a constitutional
interpretation advanced by Joseph Isenbergh of the University of
Chicago Law School that while the Constitution requires removal for
conviction of high crimes and misdemeanors, it permits lesser
punishment for impeachment for lesser offenses. Under that
interpretation, the Senate could vote to convict Clinton but then
vote to allow him to stay in office.
</P>
<P>
   But few authorities on the Constitution agree with Isenbergh,
and his proposal has basically been set aside. Sen. Olympia Snowe
of Maine, co-chairwoman of Lott's working group, said she had been
advised by the Senate legal counsel, Thomas Griffith, that the
Senate could not vote to convict Clinton without removing him from
office.
</P>
<P>
   Laurence Tribe, a constitutional law professor at Harvard Law
School, said in an interview that conviction required removal from
office and that the Isenbergh approach was clearly
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   But Tribe said it would be perfectly permissible for the Senate
to vote to express its official opinion that the president had
committed the offenses with which he was charged but to forgo
conviction on the ground that the offenses were not the high crimes
necessary for removal from offices.
</P>
<P>
   In three instances in the 19th and early 20th centuries, the
Senate voted to convict judges and then took separate votes to
remove them from office. But authorities who have reviewed the
records say there was never any thought that those judges could
remain in office once they were convicted of the articles of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The working grou named by Lott consists entirely of
Republicans. In addition to Snowe, the members are Sen. Pete
Domenici of New Mexico, the co-chairman, and Sens. John Ashcroft of
Missouri, Susan Collins of Maine, Mitch McConnell of Kentucky and
John Warner of Virginia.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In an interview on Sunday on the CBS News program ``Face the
Nation,'' Collins said that a separate vote on the facts would
``give a lot of senators who are very concerned about the
president's actions, who believe that he did commit obstruction of
justice, for example, the opportunity to distinguish between those
offenses and the question of removal.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats might oppose a preliminary vote on findings of
fact. Many Democrats want the Senate to acquit Clinton of the
impeachment charges first and end the trial. They have said they
would then be receptive to a resolution to reprimand or censure the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Senate's rules, the findings of fact could be brought
up by a majority vote, and it would require only a majority to
approve the measure. Republicans, who have a 55-45 seat advantage
over Democrats, presumably could assemble a majority for the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   But if it passed on a party-line vote, Clinton and his
Democratic allies could continue to argue that impeachment was no
more than a partisan drive by Republicans against a popular
Democratic president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
