<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-ALTAVISTA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALTAVISTA TO BECOME COMPAQ SUBSIDIARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a time when leading Internet search services have run up
stock market valuations in the billions, Compaq Computer Corp.'s
AltaVista site has remained on the sidelines _ until now.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq Tuesday said it will turn AltaVista into a wholly owned
subsidiary and offer shares of AltaVista to the public, possibly by
year end. The new company will also seek major strategic
investments from other firms, although Compaq says it will remain
the majority owner.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq hopes to benefit from the dramatic run-up in Internet
stocks, and the eagerness of major media companies to make large
investments in Internet firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to be a multibillion revenue company by the end of
the year 2002,'' said Rod Schrock, the president and chief
executive of Palo Alto, Calif-based AltaVista Co., and former
Compaq senior vice president of consumer products. Schrock expects
to achieve most of this growth through sales of merchandise at the
AltaVista site. Compaq recently acquired the Internet shopping
company Shopping.com, and this service will be added to the
AltaVista site.
</P>
<P>
   Many other Internet search services, like Waltham-based Lycos
Inc. are transforming themselves into ``portal sites,'' which offer
a wide range of features intended to keep visitors at the site for
as long as possible.
</P>
<P>
   But Schrock said AltaVista will get visitors in and out quickly
by providing the fastest Internet search service available.
Visitors will spend less time at the site, Schrock said, but he
believes that faster searches will make them visit more often. In
addition, Schrock aims to make the AltaVista shopping experience as
fast and simple as possible.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista was created in 1995 by Digital Equipment Corp., which
was purchased by Compaq last year. AltaVista was started to
demonstrate the speed of computers that used Digital's powerful
Alpha microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
   But the site soon became far more than a marketing gimmick,
establishing itself as one of the Internet's most popular search
services.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it never achieved the popularity of other Internet
services like Yahoo. And as part of a larger company, AltaVista
couldn't take advantage of the soaring stock valuations of rival
Internet firms. ``It's sort of like locking up your prettiest
daughter,'' said Melissa Bane, analyst for the Yankee Group in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista ranked number twelve among Web sites last month,
lagging Yahoo, Excite, Lycos and other top destinations, according
to the Media Metrix research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Digital planned to spin off AltaVista back in 1996, but later
shelved the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Paris Burstyn, an Internet watcher with International Data Corp.
in Framingham, Mass., said Compaq could earn back a large chunk of
the $9.6 billion it paid for Digital simply by selling a piece of
the new AltaVista unit.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Burstyn noted the deal could resolve an awkward
conflict of interest problem. Compaq hopes to sell computers to
other Internet companies, but they might hesitate to buy while
Compaq also runs a rival Internet service. ``Compaq wants a big
piece of this market,'' Burstyn said, ``and it doesn't want to give
the appearance of AltaVista competing with its customers.''
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, Compaq struck a deal with Microsoft
Corp. to license Microsoft's Hotmail technology to provide free
electronic mail services on the AltaVista site. At the same time,
Microsoft agreed to use AltaVista as the primary search service on
Microsoft's MSN Web site. Microsoft will terminate its existing
agreement to use a search engine created by Inktomi Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq closed at 49 1/4, up 2 9/16 on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
