u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-BOS &LR;      01-26 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US-RUSSIA RELATIONS FROSTY AFTER ALBRIGHT VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Alexander Shokhin is not your average knee-jerk
anti-American. A moderate politician who has been associated with
Russia's pro-Western governments in the past, Shokhin occasionally
can be found at receptions at the US embassy in Moscow, trading
jokes in English with Americans.
</P>
<P>
   To get an idea of the state of US-Russian relations as Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright ended a 48-hour visit here Tuesday,
consider Shokhin's reaction to reports of an American missile
attack against Iraq Monday that Baghdad says killed innocent
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a US attempt to put pressure on Russia,'' Ekho Moskvy
radio quoted Shokhin as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Misgivings and mistrust were the rule among Russian commentators
on Albright's visit, which came at a time when the United States
and Russia agree on little and relations are as cool as they have
been since the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Russia differ on how to deal with Iraq and
Kosovo. The United States accuses Russia of secretly helping Iraq
develop its missile program; Russia is upset over an American plan
to build a new anti-missile defense system that it says would
scuttle a fundamental arms control treaty. As a result, Russia says
it will not ratify the 1993 START 2 treaty on reducing nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Russia needs cash. The United States thinks Russia needs a
clearer economic plan if it expects financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   But what really irks Russians is the thought that the United
States is exploiting Russia's current weakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``America should not demonstrate that it is much stronger and
that it can order Russia around,'' said Mintemir Shaimiyev,
governor of the Volga region of Tatarstan. ``We remember all those
years when the Soviet Union was the equal of the United
States....This is not popular among Russians.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright and Ivanov Tuesday promised to keep the vital
relationship between the world's two nuclear superpowers on track.
However, Albright exchanged verbal blows with two men with good
chances to become Russia's next president, Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov and Moscow Mayor Yury Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   She also heard criticism from President Boris N. Yeltsin.
Hospitalized with a bleeding ulcer, Yeltsin voiced concern about
the missile-defense question and told Albright that unilateral US
military action in Iraq or Kosovo ``is impermissible,'' according
to his press service.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's words were overshadowed at home by reports suggesting
that Primakov was negotiating with the Russian parliament to
undermine the ailing Russian leader's authority. Both Primakov and
Yeltsin's chief of administration denied the reports, although
Yeltsin issued a statement expressing his disdain for attempts to
pry away his powers.
</P>
<P>
   Albright and Ivanov did issue a joint statement condemning the
masscre of 40 villagers in Kosovo. They also signed an agreement
that Albright said would allow the United States to resume
cooperation with Russia over the launching of satellites.
</P>
<P>
   But Albright said the deal depended on Russia's ability to halt
its support of Iran's missile program. Ivanov protested what he
called attempts to ``pressure'' Russia. He was referring to the
sanctions Washington imposed on three Russian research institutes
this month for allegedly aiding Iran. Russia says the aid never
happened and the sanctions are humiliating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sanctions against Russian institutions is a slap in the
face,'' said Alexei Venediktov, news editor of Ekho Moskvy.
``Research institutes, this is a blow against Russian science ,
something we are proud of. The Americans are not paying attention
to us, and that hurts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 1936EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
