<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9499 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE-STLOUIS-BOS &LR;      01-26 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-STLOUIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE CHALLENGES AMERICANS TO RAISE MORAL STANDARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Journeying to America's heartland amid a wrenching
national political and moral debate, Pope John Paul II met
President Clinton Tuesday and challenged all Americans to ``a
higher moral vision.''
</P>
<P>
   In public remarks, John Paul made no direct reference to
President Clinton's fight for his political life as the Senate
continues its impeachment proceedings, but he did say that
``America faces a time of trial'' and a test of national character.
</P>
<P>
   While praising the United States for advancing the cause of
freedom in the world, John Paul chastized America for being
indifferent to the plight of society's weakest _ the poor, the
unborn and minorities and he exhorted the country to ``reaffirm the
genuine truths and values of the American experience.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of his strongest statements on one of the most explosive
issues roiling the United States, the pope compared the aborting of
babies to last century's infamous Dred Scott case, argued in St.
Louis, that declared slaves to be private property.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the pope said, ``after untold sufferring and with
enormous effort,'' the struggle by blacks to win their legal rights
has been largely successful.
</P>
<P>
   But the conflict, John Paul added, now is ``between a culture
that affirms, cherishes, and celibrates the gift of life, and a
culture that seeks to declare entire groups of human beings _ the
unborn, the terminally ill, the handicapped, and others considered
`unuseful' _ to be outside the boundaries of legal protection.''
</P>
<P>
   US Catholic leaders have been outspoken in their support of
legislation that would outlaw late-term abortions, a controversial
procedure that has become one of the newest and hottest
battlegrounds in the national abortion debate.
</P>
<P>
   In a private 20-minute meeting between Clinton and the pope,
abortion only ``came up in passing'' and the Monica Lewinsky affair
not at all, White House officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Lewinsky) topic was not included,'' agreed Vatican
spokesman Joaquin Navarro-Valls. The Vatican media have given scant
attention to the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The two men did talk about Cuba and Iraq, Navarro-Valls said,
two areas on which Clinton and the pontiff disagree. The pope
strongly opposes the US economic embargo against Cuba and Iraq,
arguing that it punishes children, the sick and the poor. On
Monday, the Vatican harshly criticized the United States latest air
strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iraq was a topic of conversation for a while, but the
positions on both sides were so clear that a real dialogue did not
develop,'' Navarro-Valls said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside an Air National Guard hangar at Lambert-St. Louis
International Airport, where a crowd of 2,500 had been waiting, the
pope received a much more boisterous welcome than Clinton, who was
accompanied by his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   During his speech, Clinton hailed John Paul for his role in
bringing down Communism but said that ``people still need to hear
your message that all are God's children, all have fallen short of
his glory. All of the injustices of yesterday cannot excuse a
single injustice today.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope arrived after a triumphant five-day visit to Mexico,
where he delivered a blueprint for the future of the church in the
Americas.
</P>
<P>
   On his seventh visit to US soil, John Paul was expected to
exhort his flock, particularly young Catholics, to build a more
moral and just society as the church prepares to enter the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   He called on America to ``open wide your hearts to the ever
increasing plight and urgent needs of our less fortunate brothers
and sisters throughout the world.''
</P>
<P>
   John Paul's first major event Tuesday was a raucous rally with
20,000 young people, giving the pontiff the chance to celebrate
with a demographic group he has particular affection for and from
which he always receives a strong spiritual boost.
</P>
<P>
   Showing he was in touch with youth culture, John Paul referred
to last year's record-breaking baseball season much to the delight
of the teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am told that there was much excitement in St. Louis during
the recent baseball season, when two great players (Mark McGwire
and Sammy Sosa), were competing to break the home-run record,'' the
pope said. ``You can feel the same great enthusiasm as you train
for a different goal: the goal of following Christ, the goal of
bringing his message to the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the youths had traveled for hours from Ohio, Illinois,
Kentucky and other states to cheer on one of the world's most
admired men.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most awesome thing I've ever been to,'' said Chris
Nelson, 15, who with about 40 classmates rode a bus for four hours
from Notre Dame High School in Peoria, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   For small Midwestern city on the banks of the Mississippi River,
built by French Catholics, the visit of the leader of the world's 1
billion Roman Catholics is one of the biggest events in its,
bringing to St. Louis unprecedented international media attention.
</P>
<P>
   The pope literally brought the city to a standstill as downtown
streets were closed and many people sneaked out of work to get a
peep at John Paul as he rode by in his now-familiar ``popemobile.''
</P>
<P>
   About 1 million people, the biggest crowd St. Louis has drawn
since the 1904 world's fair, are expected to flood the city for the
30-hour papal visit.
</P>
<P>
   Banners, some in Polish, welcoming the pontiff were hung across
the city, from hotels, apartment buildings and pawnshops. One rock
'n roll station took advantage of the visit to depict the pope on a
billboard wearing headphones. The caption read: ``Father Knows
Best.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an incredible honor for this city and a wonderful
opportunity for it to shine,'' said Alex Volansky. ``It's all
anybody has been talking about for weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Volansky, along with his 20-year-old daughter, Julie, was won a
ticket to attend the welcoming ceremony inside the Missouri
National Guard hangar and rub shoulders with politicians, diplomats
and church leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The trip here, which culminates Wednesday with a Mass for over
100,000 people inside the TWA Dome, is a tip of the pope's skullcap
to John Paul's close friend, St. Louis Archbishop Justin Rigali,
who worked in the Vatican for many years and was a key adviser to
the pontiff during the early years of his 20-year pontificate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
