<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9502 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-DAVIS-ART-2TAKE     01-26 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-DAVIS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A.'S LEADING DOOMSAYER IGNORES CRITICS (AND, SOME SAY, THE
FACTS) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Davis is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On a winter Sunday morning of the sort that only
Southern California seems to produce, under a brilliant blue sky
scoured clean of clouds and smog, a crowd of upper-middle-class
Angelenos filed into the Skirball Cultural Center and plunked down
$10 each to hear a conversation with their city's reigning prophet
of doom.
</P>
<P>
   In two best-selling books, ``City of Quartz'' published in 1990,
and ``Ecology of Fear,'' issued last fall, that man, Mike Davis,
has portrayed Los Angeles as a false paradise ruled by malign
elites who have stifled the poor, built a fortress downtown
surrounded by a growing ring of dying suburbs, and courted
environmental disaster by heedlessly encroaching on canyons and
cliffsides never meant for mass habitation.
</P>
<P>
   For this Davis, a one-time meat-cutter and now full-time Marxist
urbanologist, has been hailed as something like a hero, not only by
the coast-to-coast school of critics who have long looked askance
Los Angeles, but by his fellow Southern Californians whose
unrelenting misery he presumes to celebrate. The winner of a
$315,000 MacArthur Foundation ``genius'' grant, he has also won an
unquestioned place on the short list of serious thinkers about a
city whose prevailing culture has long been a blend of oligarchical
boosterism and noir self-loathing.
</P>
<P>
   When a questioner at the Skirball Center gestured to the sunny
splendor of the Sepulveda Pass outside and asked if L.A. was really
so bad, Davis, 52, acknowledged with a rueful laugh, ``I wake up in
the morning and look at the San Gabriel Mountains in incredible
January _ even if it may be a symptom of global warming _ and I ask
myself, `Are you crazy?'''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, a growing chorus of Californians is
effectively answering, ``Yes!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ecology of Fear'' (Metropolitan Books), with its thesis that
the modern megalopolis of L.A. has no business existing in the
earthquake-ridden Southern California desert, has unleashed a
pent-up firestorm of criticism over Davis' methods after 16 weeks
on the local best-seller list (``City of Quartz'' is No. 5 on the
paperback list).
</P>
<P>
   Critics have cast grave doubt on many of the obscure and
startling factoids that are Davis' stock-in-trade, calling into
question his broader argument that Los Angeles is a hopelessly
damned creature of unchecked real estate speculation and the
mercenary folly of its ruling class.
</P>
<P>
   The debate has pitted rival camps of the city's interpreters
against each other in a fight more typical of New York or Paris
than of laid-back L.A. Academics, alternative weeklies, business
journals and The Los Angeles Times have all weighed in, with
everything from Davis' birthplace (the desert suburb of Fontana,
not Los Angeles, as the book jacket of ``Ecology'' says) to his
marriages (he is on his fifth) grist for the mill. As a topic of
collective conversation, he is not quite on a par with the Dodgers
or the latest movie grosses, but he is gaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, it is a significant development in the
intellectual history of Los Angeles _ and don't gasp, there is such
a thing,'' said Kevin Starr, the state librarian whose own
histories of the Golden State, like ``Inventing the Dream,'' have
been hailed as authoritative. ``The decade of the 90s began with
`City of Quartz' and its elegantly presented noir vision of Los
Angeles as a repressive conspiracy, and sure enough, all these noir
aspects came out, beginning with the riots in '92.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the decade,'' Starr continued, ``there's a
different situation. Immigrant groups have revitalized the Los
Angeles economy, the mood is better, and here comes a book that
really makes us think about earthquakes and the epicycle of
climatological reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Davis' offering of an unmitigatedly apocalyptic point of view
is now meeting with resistance. There's going to be some bad
manners, some fighting back and forth. But you've got people caring
about L.A. and the theory of L.A., and I think that's very
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, whose unruly shock of white hair and soft, half-swallowed
speaking voice convey an aura about as threatening as Linus in
``Peanuts,'' has been caught in some embarrassing mistakes. For
starters, he has acknowledged fabricating an entire conversation
with a local environmentalist, Lewis McAdams, for a cover story he
wrote for the L.A. Weekly a decade ago; he defends it as an early
attempt at journalistic scene-setting.
</P>
<P>
   In ``City of Quartz,'' discussing the power divisions between
the city's old and new elites, he misidentified the late Howard
Ahmanson, the founder of the giant Home Savings empire and a
conservative Christian, as Jewish, and he also described Hancock
Park, one of the city's oldest WASP enclaves, as a Jewish
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   He also acknowledges that he cannot find the source for his
claim in ``Ecology of Fear'' that as many as 30 bodies a year have
been found in drug-plagued MacArthur Park near downtown, a claim
the police dismiss as wildly off-base.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book is a, you know, polemic, with a lot of irony and
humor in it,'' Davis said in a two-hour interview at a pub near his
home in Pasadena. ``It has sailed over the heads of some people.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel Kotkin, a fellow at the Pepperdine Institute for Public
Policy in Malibu and one of Davis' most vociferous critics, said
that he welcomes a debate over the meaning of Los Angeles, but that
Davis has so twisted the facts as to make honest debate impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The latest critique of Davis, for example, in the weekly New
Times L.A., leaves little doubt that the portrait of suburban
Pomona, as described in ``Ecology of Fear,'' as a deserted husk is
at best outdated, ignoring a decade of revival.
</P>
<P>
   ``What bothers me even as a person who was trained as a Marxist
is that somebody would so bastardize Marxist theory to the point of
making things up,'' Kotkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' particular calling card has been his unearthing of
obscure, even fantastic, facts about Los Angeles' experience with
natural and scientific phenomena, from monsoon-intensity rain to
little-noticed tornados to mountain lions that prowl the city's
suburban fringe. One chapter in ``Ecology of Fear,'' on wildfires,
is titled, ``The Case for Letting Malibu Burn.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brady Westwater, a Malibu real estate agent and amateur
local historian who has appointed himself Davis' one-man truth
squad, has produced reams of material, circulated on the Internet
and among publications here and in New York, questioning almost
every claim he makes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something pathological about it,'' said Westwater, who
cites, as just one example among dozens, Davis' claim that the
local media has long downplayed Southern California's experience
with tornado-like storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I checked the L.A. Times article he actually cites as evidence
of this reluctance, and it uses the words `tornado' or `twister' 13
times,'' Westwater said. ``You don't even have to check other
sources to prove he's lying. He does it himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis calmly contends that any book of such length and ambition
(it is 461 pages, including footnotes) is bound to contain errors.
``The thing you have to understand about these books is I'm a
Socialist,'' he said. ``This book has an utterly radical political
agenda, no holds barred.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Davis, who has taught at the Southern California Institute of
Architecture and is now on the verge of accepting a three-year
appointment to teach history ``deep in the faux-Colonial
architecture of Suffolk County,'' at the State University of New
York at Stony Brook, seems to slide reflexively into hyperbole.
</P>
<P>
   He referred to a friend, William Deverell, a respected professor
in his late 30s at the California Institute of Technology, as ``the
dean of L.A. historians.'' He mused of his recent visit to a Times
Square seemingly devoid of homeless people: ``What's Giuliani done?
Built gas chambers in Queens or something?''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Dutton, who owns the respected independent bookstore in
Brentwood that bears his name, had a long list of orders for
``Ecology'' before it was even published. He said Davis has ``an
enormous following'' among his upscale customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't help but think to a certain extent that if you agree
with his theories, you'll like the book, and if you don't, you
won't,'' Dutton said. ``It's a kind of analysis that's very
personal, almost a grand unified theory for Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis insists he loves the city, which is why he is so hard on
it, and says he is trying to inspire a new generation of labor
activists, environmentalists and academics to carry on the battles
for social justice that he himself fought as a civil rights
protester and Students for a Democratic Society member in the 60s.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged: ``Some people like the book because they
like the glamor of decay and apocalypse. Those people aren't the
people I write for, although they probably help sell the book.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
