<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9505 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT     01-26 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: FREQUENT-FLIER LINKS; BUSINESS TRAVEL COSTS;
BUDGETEL
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: also moving in `t' travel category; with DELTA-SURCHARGE) 
(bl) 
 By JANET PIORKO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Starting Monday, five airlines in a marketing alliance called
One World are linking their frequent-flier programs so that members
using one of the carriers can earn and redeem miles on any of the
others.
</P>
<P>
   The group, which includes American Airlines, British Airways,
Canadian Airlines, Cathay Pacific Airways and Qantas Airways, also
aims to give reciprocal perks such as priority check-in to
high-level members of the airlines' frequent-flier programs.
</P>
<P>
   Members will be able to use miles accrued on flights on various
alliance members to achieve higher levels of status in the
frequent-flier program of their choice.
</P>
<P>
   Because the frequent-flier programs all have different names for
various tiers of membership, One World has established a set of
symbols _ Emerald, Sapphire and Ruby _ so that members' levels will
be recognized across the board.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the airlines' tiered frequent-flier programs (those
above entry level) will get new cards with the appropriate symbol,
or stickers to affix to their old cards, from the individual
frequent-flier programs, according to Mark Stitt, an American
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   There is one exception to the reciprocity: Passengers on British
Airways' direct routes between Europe and the Americas cannot earn
or redeem miles on American Airlines on those flights, and vice
versa. Existing aviation agreements between the United States and
Britain preclude such a link, according to John Lampl, a spokesman
for British Airways. Meanwhile, the two carriers are awaiting a new
aviation accord between the two countries that would pave the way
for them to pursue their own separate alliance in addition to One
World, he added.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to priority check-in, the One World alliance will
give eligible members access to some 220 airport clubs and lounges,
along with priority standby and wait listing.
</P>
<P>
   Finnair, which joined One World after the original alliance was
announced, will begin participating in the program later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Costs Rising at Slower Pace
</P>
<P>
   Though business travel costs will rise in 1999, the increase
will be only about half as much as last year's, according to an
annual study by American Express.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the company's 1999 forecast prices will go up 4 to 5
percent this year, compared with an estimate of nearly 9 percent
for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate hotel rates in the 25 top business cities will climb 7
to 8 percent, the study said. Car rental costs will go up 4 to 5
percent; air fares used by business travelers, 3 to 4 percent, and
restaurant meal prices, 2 to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Budgetel Becomes Baymont
</P>
<P>
   It was nearly a year in coming, but the former Budgetel Inns,
which has operated under that name for 25 years, is now Baymont
Inns and Suites. The change, which had been announced last February
and took effect earlier this month, reflects the upgrading of the
properties, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The limited-service chain, with more than 160 locations in more
than 30 states, is a subsidiary of Marcus Corp. in Milwaukee. About
10 percent of the chain's rooms are business-class rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Work and Play
</P>
<P>
   ``All work and no play'' is not a slogan that fits the 501
business travelers surveyed recently by Cahners Corporate Research.
Three-quarters of them turned at least one business trip into a
partial vacation over the last year by extending their stay and
inviting a family member or friend to join them. Most of the hybrid
trips were taken in spring or summer, with travelers spending an
average of four days on business and three on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular destinations for extending a business trip were
San Francisco; Las Vegas; New York; Phoenix, and Orlando, Fla. The
survey was conducted for Hotels magazine in a questionnaire sent in
June to 2,000 subscribers to the North American Pocket Flight
Guide.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 1949EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
