<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Wednesday, Jan. 20, and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Bob Schenet at 206-448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-EARNS (Seattle) _ Boeing reports fourth-quarter net
income of $465 million vs. a net loss of $498 million in the same
period a year earlier. The Seattle company, which for 14 months had
disappointed investors, reversed the trend by reporting quarterly
earnings per share of 48 cents, ahead of the First Call analysts'
consensus of 42 cents per share and rising from a 51-cent-per-share
net loss in the same period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   ELVIS-AUTHOR (Undated) _ Interview with Peter Guralnick, who's
touring behind the second and concluding volume in his much-praised
bio of Elvis Presley.
</P>
<P>
   By John Marshall. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-ROBINSON (Miami) _ Eugene Robinson, now playing for the
Atlanta Falcons, is making his third straight Super Bowl
appearance. The gregarious former Seahawk safety presided over
Tuesday's media day in Miami like a potentate.
</P>
<P>
   By Clare Farnsworth. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN (Miami) _ The Broncos are last year's team.
The interest has turned to the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   By Laura Vecsey. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
