<SLUG> BC-POPE-MEXICO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAITHFUL GATHER TO CATCH GLIMPSE OF DEPARTING POPE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The sun hadn't yet risen above the skyscrapers
Tuesday, but hundreds of people, fearing they were too late,
scurried down the wide boulevard toward the compound where Pope
John Paul II had slept four nights.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the pope's two escort helicopters were making wide
circles over the neighborhood, indicating that John Paul would soon
depart in a motorcade for Mexico City's airport and fly to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of people pressed against the metal barriers set up
across the normally busy intersection a block from the papal
envoy's residence where John Paul was staying. Still more people
lined the streets that the pontiff would travel on his way to the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   Those arriving after sunrise had little chance of getting a good
view of the 78-year-old pope, because the best spots had already
been taken. But people packed in anyway, many of them knowing this
would likely be their final chance to see John Paul in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the fourth time he has come, and we know it will
probably be his last,'' said Jorge Ocampo, a 47-year-old architect
who stood immobile toward the back of the crowd. ``God bless him,
he's gotten old. But it's important _ it's impressive _ to see the
faith of our people.''
</P>
<P>
   On the flight to Mexico from Rome on Friday, the pontiff had
joked with reporters that Mexicans hadn't let him sleep on his
three previous trips to the country, waking him with song on many
mornings.
</P>
<P>
   During this papal visit, barricades manned by police and
plainclothes security officers kept everyone away from the papal
envoy's compound except people who live in the leafy, middle-class
neighborhood on the south side of the Mexican capital. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Thank you for your fervor,'' read a banner draped from palm
trees on the boulevard in front of the compound. ``Thank you for
respecting the rest of the Holy Father.''
</P>
<P>
   But on the last day of John Paul's stay in Mexico _ the first
country he visited as pope before making 84 other foreign trips _
people were determined to give him a send-off.
</P>
<P>
   Estela Garcia de Leon, 61, and her friend Concepcion Santos, 50,
arrived at the corner near the papal envoy's compound at 4 a.m.
after traveling by bus from a distant corner of the city. Both
women said they saw John Paul twice over the weekend but wanted to
catch a glimpse of him one more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are interested in everything he says, in all that he
does,'' said a giggling Garcia de Leon. ``It's worth all the hours
we have to wait, all the trouble we have to take to get here.''
</P>
<P>
   Preceded by phalanxes of motorcycle police and stony-faced
security officers in sport utility vehicles, John Paul finally
whisked by the corner about 8:30 a.m., his face impassive but one
hand waving slightly.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd roared a final time. ``The pope! The pope! The pope!''
</P>
<P>
   Then it was over.
</P>
<P>
   Children headed to school, businessmen hurried to their
officers, homemakers went home. The security men took down the
barricades, and the usual morning traffic jams formed almost
instantly along the neighborhood's boulevards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at all these people,'' said Angela Lucas de Mateos, 60,
as she watched the crowd disperse. ``We are here for faith, for
Christianity. People wouldn't do this for a president, for any
corrupt politician.''
</P>
<P>
   A few people gathered in front of the papal envoy's gate, hands
dismantling the elaborate tapestry made of artificial flowers that
adorned the entrance. Young men climbed the display as high as they
could and passed pieces of the colorful plastic mosaic to those who
wanted them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a final memory,'' Maria Ponce, a middle-aged woman from
an indigenous village outside of Mexico City, said of the red and
yellow plastic she held to her breast. ``We want just a little
something.''
</P>
<P>
   A small crowd gathered at a small sandwich shop across the
street from the envoy's compound, eyes fixed on the small
television that showed the pope's departure ceremony at the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   The sounds of meat sizzling on the griddle and people calling
out orders for sandwiches drowned some of the speeches delivered by
President Ernesto Zedillo and John Paul. But the knot of people in
the shop didn't seem to care.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks so tired,'' Josefina Arguelles said of the pope, as
she and a daughter sipped black coffee from plastic cups. ``Time
changes. I don't know how he can manage all of this.''
</P>
<P>
   As the pope spoke, one woman said a prayer, her lips moving
slightly as she murmured.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
