<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA, U.S. SEEK COMMON GROUND IN KOSOVO SETTLEMENT  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia and the United States Tuesday called on both
sides that are fighting in Kosovo to hold talks toward achieving a
political settlement in the Serbian province, while the United
States spoke more openly of using force to compel the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Russia remains firmly opposed to using force. But a joint
statement, issued on the second day of a visit by Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, would be helpful in showing the Yugoslav
leader, Slobodan Milosevic, that he cannot automatically count on
the Russians for support, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time Tuesday, Albright refused to rule out
using American ground troops as part of a peacekeeping mission in
Kosovo, saying, ``We would examine that among other options.''
</P>
<P>
   An administration official said that the United States had
``moved further along'' toward possible use of ground troops in
Kosovo, an option that appeared virtually unthinkable last week.
</P>
<P>
   In the statement Tuesday, the Russians went further than they
had before in calling on Milosevic to restrain his police and
military units in Kosovo, which is a province of Serbia, but where
more than 90 percent of the population is ethnic Albanian. The
ethnic Albanians are calling for independence.
</P>
<P>
   In calling for a political settlement, both the United States
and Russia said that both sides in the Kosovo conflict must accept
``substantial autonomy'' for the Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting of NATO ambassadors in Brussels Tuesday, the United
States continued to push for an ultimatum to be issued to both
sides that threatened air strikes if they did not agree to a
political settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has traditionally been more sympathetic to the
nationalism of fellow Slavs in Serbia than many Western countries.
Serbia is one of two republics remaining in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In the joint statement on Kosovo issued by Albright and Ivanov,
the Russians also agreed for the first time to push Milosevic to
accept investigators from the war crimes tribunal in the Hague to
investigate the killings of 45 ethnic Albanians this month in the
village of Racak.
</P>
<P>
   The statement between Russia and the United States on Kosovo was
the most immediate result of the Moscow meetings, which covered a
gamut of strategic and economic issues at the most troubled time in
American and Russian relations since the breakup of the Soviet
Union. Despite the paucity of specific agreements, Albright and
Ivanov tried to put the best face on the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Asked at their joint news conference whether the United States
has been ignoring Russia, Albright, who stood beside Ivanov on a
stage at a press center here, replied: ``The proof is in the
pudding _ or me. I am here because we are neither ignoring nor
avoiding or dismissing Russia and its views.''
</P>
<P>
   A more defensive Ivanov said that Albright had explained the
Clinton administration's plans for a new missile defense system and
its effect on the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty, which the
Russians believe is sacred to nuclear arms control. The new
position of the Americans is ``being studied very thoroughly,''
Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
   But he made clear that the Russians resent what they consider
the hardball tactics of the United States on the nonproliferation
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Albright pressed the Russians again to stop what the
administration asserts is help to Iran with nuclear missile
technology.
</P>
<P>
   In a recognition of the volatile political landscape in Russia,
Albright reached out to some of the people who are likely to run in
next year's presidential election. She met Monday with Yuri Luzkov,
the mayor of Moscow, and Tuesday with Alexander Lebed, the former
general who is now governor of a region in Siberia. She also met
with Grigory Yavlinsky, leader of a liberal party.
</P>
<P>
   The encounter with Luzkov was quite fiery, according to accounts
from American officials. Luzkov vigorously attacked U.S. policy
toward Iraq and Kosovo and expressed concern that the United States
wanted to kill the Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty.
</P>
<P>
   She spoke by telephone with President Boris Yeltsin, who remains
in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion of possible ground troops in Kosovo was an
inevitable outcome of the increasing talk at NATO about possible
air strikes against Serbian targets in Kosovo. If air strikes
occurred, some kind of peacekeeping force would have to be deployed
in Kosovo afterward.
</P>
<P>
   As the NATO ambassadors met in Brussels Tuesday, there were
talks with NATO military commanders about limited air strikes or a
longer phased air campaign, a Western diplomat said. The diplomat
said they also were discussing the context in which an ultimatum
would be issued.
</P>
<P>
   But there was still disagreement among the NATO allies about
which diplomatic channels to use and in what order to use them,
Administration officials said. Before issuing a NATO ultimatum, the
French and British want to hold a meeting of the so-called Contact
Group, which includes Russia, and is dedicated to resolving issues
of the countries that once made up a larger Yugoslavia, an
administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   But Albright, who was so irritated after attending a meeting of
the Contact Group last year that she dismissed it as the ``lowest
common denominator of diplomacy,'' was not anxious to attend a
Contact Group meeting, the officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
