<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9530 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-REPUBS-NYT &LR;      01-26 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTY UNITY, DEFERENCE TO HOUSE FUELING GOP SENATORS' RESOLVE
</HEADLINE>
   (See related stories: IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-TRIAL,
IMPEACH-TWO-STEP, IMPEACH-SESSIONS, IMPEACH-LEWINSKY,
IMPEACH-SCENE, HUBBELL-TAXES, STARR-LEAKS) 
(nk) 
 By Richard L. Berke  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In pressing forward with a call for witnesses,
Republican Senators often cite the Constitution or their
disapproval of President Clinton. But there is a more political
explanation: Senators may see it in their own best interest to
maintain cordial relations with Republicans in the House.
</P>
<P>
   This may seem surprising given that historically, Republicans
and Democrats in the Senate are known for bonding more with one
another than with their counterparts _ even from the same party _
across the Capitol Rotunda.
</P>
<P>
   Republican strategists and politicians concede that Senators
face great pressure from the party's conservative base to move
ahead with the trial. But they also said there was a growing
recognition among Republican Senators that the more united their
party is on impeachment, the better positioned it would be to
tackle their legislative agenda.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, while they may have qualms about pressing ahead
with witnesses, many Senators are reluctant to do anything to
discredit what they think has been a good faith effort by House
impeachment managers to make their case. Several senators said in
interviews that they feel particularly inclined to cooperate after
House members pared down their list of witnesses to three on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been immersed in this case, they know it well,'' said
Sen. John H. Chafee, R-R.I. ``They say they need discovery. OK,
let's give them discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying he was pleased that the House managers limited their
witness list, Chafee added, ``Frankly, I was stunned when they came
back with only three. Three cheers.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah, said, ``They've only asked for
three witnesses. That's a very reasonable request. Let's at least
let them depose them.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason that the Senate seems deferential to the House is
that the Senate seems in some ways to be becoming more like the
more populist House. Many senators who are pressing hardest
behind-the-scenes for moving forward with the trial at a deliberate
pace are former House members themselves: Don Nickles and James M.
Inhofe of Oklahoma, Jon Kyl of Arizona, Rick Santorum of
Pennsylvania and Connie Mack of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republicans with an eye to the presidential race next
year also said the last thing they want are Republicans running
against the party's congressional wing. That is what Bill Clinton
did in 1992 when he essentially campaigned against his own party in
Congress. He won the White House, but Democrats lost seats in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we move beyond this trial, we have to get to things like
Social Security reform and tax cuts and health care reform and
education,'' said Ed Gillespie, a strategist with close ties to
Republican leaders in Congress. ``And the House and Senate
Republicans have to be together in the next six months because if
they're not, you're going to create an environment where even the
most ardent Republican presidential candidate will seek to define
himself or herself in contrast to Republicans in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillespie said Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott was taking his
time to try to accommodate all sides. ``It's a matter of letting
the cake bake all the way through,'' he said. ``It is not quite
done yet. It doesn't quite bounce back when you put your fork
through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to the elections in 2000, Mickey Edwards, a former
Republican House leader from Oklahoma who now teaches government at
Harvard University, said: ``Senators are a little afraid of doing
anything that makes House Republicans look even worse. If we lost
control of the House, the effectiveness of the Senate Republicans
is much reduced. They're marginalized.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Edwards asserted that Senate Republicans should be more
worried about the potential damage to the party from the
impeachment trial than about relations with the House. He said of
senators pressing for witnesses: ``It's like people running head on
to an incoming train and, for whatever reason, not getting off the
track.''
</P>
<P>
   Rich Galen, a strategist who is close to former Speaker Newt
Gingrich, said many senators who had been furious at their House
counterparts for sticking them with the trial have since become
impressed with how House managers have handled themselves. ``There
is a strong desire on the part of most Senate Republicans that the
House proceeding not be characterized as being fraudulent,'' Galen
said. ``They will not do things that will allow the White House to
turn around and say, `It was a witch hunt.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But some Republicans scoffed at the notion that Senate
Republicans need to preserve relations with House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't given five seconds thought to that!'' said one
House Republican, speaking on the condition of anonymity. ``The
Senate looks down at the House. They say, `You're in the pea soup.'
They say, `You need us more than we need you.' They're the
patricians and we're the common thieves who happened to get
elected.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
