<HEADER>
A9533 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-FEATURE27     01-26 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-FEATURE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jamal Anderson: Not one bit shy
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It was the entertainment portion of the afternoon. An
audience awaited his arrival. But the lead performer was up in his
room, stalling.
</P>
<P>
   What do you want? He was only 7 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was the last time I got stage fright,'' Jamal
Anderson said. ``My parents used to have these huge barbecues for
these people, and they used to ask me and my brothers to do these
huge performances. But I didn't want to do it....It was one of
those `New Edition' songs or something. But I was nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has been a lot of things this week. Nervous is not one
of them. From his first news conference, when he jokingly scolded
one media member for having a cheap tape recorder, to telling
another, ``Man, I know you can't dance _ you look like both your
knees are broken,'' to describing the Dirty Bird dance as ``Gregory
Hines meets Baryshnikov,'' it's clear he has been on stage.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has hungered for attention since being buried deep in
the 1994 NFL draft, in the seventh round. He grew up taking
graduate courses in media relations and marketing from the various
celebrities who were clients of his father, James Anderson, a
personal security guard. And what better time to launch your
publicity campaign than on stage of the planet's biggest media
event?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to be natural,'' Anderson said. ``People say
I'm a ham. I'm not a ham. I'm just doing my thing.... Seriously,
any time you can do something like this, you have to think about
that. Maybe that's from being around those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Note pads and cameras have been five deep around Anderson. On
Monday, he said he got a facial to prepare for Tuesday's photo day.
Some suspected he actually wore makeup Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way _ does my skin look that good?'' Anderson said.
``Europeans have shown us the way. Look at you guys. I know a good
place down in South Beach you should go to.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Anderson mugs for a photographer. ``Did you get a
good angle?'' he said. ``You should come around the front. I don't
like that side of my face.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson hopes to mug on several occasions after this game. The
Falcons have opened negotiations for a deal that could rival the
nine-year, $51.9 million contract of the Broncos' Terrell Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest difference between me and Terrell,'' Anderson
said, ``is his contract, for now, and about 30 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Off the field, his glibness should help him on Madison Avenue,
particularly if the Falcons pull an upset in the Super Bowl.
Anderson currently has modest deals with Nike and Zero Tolerance.
``I wanted to make sure I looked good today. Is my hair tight?''
</P>
<P>
   He smiled. He talked about being ignored by major recruiters.
``Some coaches said I wouldn't make it to the NFL if didn't sign
with them. I may have to get them one day in my book.'' He talked
about the depressing draft day. ``I was listening to all the other
names going ahead of me, taking mental notes.'' He talked about
growing up with celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to watch Muhammad (Ali) and Ray (Leonard) at their
press conferences. They showed me how you can still be in your
element even when you're not in your athletic field.''
</P>
<P>
   He jokingly complained about the ``100 unauthorized'' versions
of Dirty Bird songs, then teased the media about unveiling a new
version Sunday: ``The all-around-the-world Bird.'' He wouldn't
demonstrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't sneak backstage to see the showgirls before the
show,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Anderson continued to bask in the spotlight. ``I figured it
like this,'' he said. ``I used to hate public speaking. But I
figured if I was going to have to do all these press conferences
one day, I might as well get used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   A postscript: As a 7-year-old, Anderson finally came out to
sing.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox _ the best mark in the NFL since the Oakland
Raiders averaged 16.3 in 1989. Unlike the West Coast-style passing
games that are prevalent in the league, the Falcons will stretch
the secondary down the field. Just as with his running game, Reeves
wants the pass going ahead, not sideways.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves likes strong-armed passers with touch on the deep ball.
One of the reasons he did not re-sign popular Bobby Hebert in 1997
was that Hebert lacked the arm strength to play in his offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play ball possession with the running game, not with the
pass,'' New Orleans Saints defensive coordinator Zaven Yaralian
said. ``When the Falcons throw, they're looking for the big play
downfield. They want something substantial from it. Their approach
is to draw you in with the run, make you commit another body to the
line of scrimmage and then bomb you deep. It's been very effective
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons ranked fourth in the NFL in 1998 in pass completions
of 25 yards or more. Chandler led the league in yards-per-attempt
at 9.65. Most NFL teams regard the yards-per-attempt statistic as
the most significant on offense and are happy with anything around
7 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's passing attack does not appear to be complex. But the
system is effective, creating openings into which the wide
receivers run. Many times, if wide receivers Terance Mathis and
Tony Martin beat the initial hit at the line, they encounter little
traffic downfield because zones have been cleared.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, it is a two-wide-receiver set. Chandler's passer rating
with two wideouts on the field this season was significantly better
than with three wide receivers. One of the ironies of Atlanta's
victory against Minnesota in the NFC Championship Game was the
29-yard catch by slot receiver Ronnie Harris on the late drive that
tied the game. Like the Broncos, the Falcons got little production
from their third wideout; slot receivers Todd Kinchen, Tim Dwight
and Harris combined for 16 catches.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons also don't throw often to theias lost a half-step
but still is fast enough to run through some double coverages. He
will force Atwater to check him deep.
</P>
<P>
   For the Broncos, the riddle is how to pressure Chandler. By
nature, Denver is not a big blitzing team on the early downs. But
because the Falcons will use maximum protection to insulate
Chandler, sometimes sending only two receivers out on routes, the
Broncos might have to come at him more aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   EDGE: FALCONS
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
