<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-UNIFORM-STYLE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    City matchups: Fashion for the Super Bowl
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pro sports teams often agonize over their uniforms, switching
styles and colors every few years _ thereby compelling
souvenir-shoppers to follow suit. The Falcons and Broncos have each
undergone makeovers during the '90s. A state-of-the-jerseys report:
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA
</P>
<P>
   True to the NFC's hard-nosed style of play, the conference
champion Falcons sport a no-frills look. Their jerseys, pants and
accessories are in not-so-adventurous shades: red, pale gray and
black. If the Falcons were supermodels, they could appear in
Reebok's show.
</P>
<P>
   As the home team in the Super Bowl, the Falcons likely will wear
their black jerseys and their customary gray pants with
black-and-red stripes. It's a color scheme that reeks of
masculinity, but the contrast between the tops and bottoms is
flattering only on the Falcons with the most streamlined of
physiques. Everyone on the team looks more chiseled when the
Falcons wear white jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   Also in keeping with the Falcons' no-nonsense approach to the
game, their jerseys' numbers are in the traditional block style.
Overall, the Falcons' uniforms contribute to the illusion that
they're bulkier, slower and more boring than they actually are. If
the Broncos aren't careful, the Falcons' style of dress could lure
them into a false sense of superiority.
</P>
<P>
   DENVER
</P>
<P>
   The reigning Super Bowl champions are disciples of West
Coast-style offenses. If they make fashion faux-pas, they do so
unabashedly. How else to explain their enduring crush on orange,
which clashes with the team's other colors: blue and white?
</P>
<P>
   When Broncos players with taste get ready to suit up, they must
grit their teeth and adhere to the ''Just Do It'' motto of their
outfitter, Nike.
</P>
<P>
   As the away team, Denver is expected to show up for the game in
a mostly monochromatic color scheme. That means white jerseys,
white pants. Nike's nudging is noticeable in that there are odd,
orange Swooshes on the Broncos' rib cages and outer thighs.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos also are up to some numerical shennanigans this
season. Their numbers are a stylistic mix of angles and curves. The
Falcons must caution against being dazzled by Denver's haberdashery
and focus on the mission at hand.
</P>
<P>
   _ A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
