<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9540 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-HNS &LR;      01-26 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL SULLIVAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS _ There's no use fighting it anymore, and they know it.
</P>
<P>
   They were the talk of the first half and the buzz at the
All-Star Game. Now, as the second half of the NHL season gets under
way, they are the odds-on favorite to win the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a little ahead of ourselves, you say?
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, Brian Skrudland and friends seem to welcome the
talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see why not,'' the Dallas Stars center said after
Tuesday's practice for tonight's game with the Los Angeles Kings.
``If people want to put us there, we set ourselves to that
standard, so let's not disappoint anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's a guy in this dressing room who doesn't
believe we can win the Stanley Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   After a hot first half, the Stars were left with plenty of
reasons to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Their 61 points led the NHL, leaving them three better than East
leader Philadelphia and six ahead of Pacific Division and Western
Conference runner-up Phoenix. The 27 wins were matched only by
Toronto. In 43 games, Dallas lost just nine times, a league low.
</P>
<P>
   Four players _ center Mike Modano, defensemen Darryl Sydor and
Sergei Zubov, and goaltender Ed Belfour _ played in Sunday's
All-Star Game. Ken Hitchcock coached the North American team to the
win.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   Now, back to business.
</P>
<P>
   ``For our older players, it was really beneficial,'' Hitchcock
said of the break. ``Toward the end, quite frankly, I think some of
our older guys were worn down a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was fatigue or merely an overdue slump, Dallas
finished the first half on a sour note, going 2-4-1 over its last
seven games. The first five of those were on a grueling Western
road trip, but home losses to Vancouver and Toronto gave cause for
a little soul-searching during the weekend off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't playing our game, and that starts in our own
zone,'' said Sydor. ``We've got to get stronger and simplify our
game more and not get into a run-and-gun style.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Stars' game begins with aggressive checking and a
tight defense that has helped Belfour and backup Roman Turek
compile a 2.04 goals-against average, tied for third in the league
with Phoenix and trailing only Philadelphia and Buffalo. Despite
the offseason addition of winger Brett Hull (16 goals and 16
assists despite missing 10 games because of injury), this remains a
blue-collar, grind-it-out sort of team _ albeit it one with enough
Star power to smooth over a few rough edges.
</P>
<P>
   Sydor, enjoying a breakout season, leads all NHL defensemen in
scoring (36 points, including 24 assists, 21 of those on power
plays). The team's power play is the league's best, with a
22.8-percent success rate.
</P>
<P>
   Modano, the franchise golden boy who is earning a reputation as
a two-way player, is tied for seventh in assists with 31. Hull,
despite limited ice time, already has five game-winning goals.
Belfour's 2.05 goals-against average ranks fifth among goalies with
the required 720 minutes, and backup Turek (1.96) has been even
better.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of balance and consistency produced a 15-game unbeaten
steak between Dec. 6 and Jan. 6, during which Dallas won 12 times.
It also resulted in a road record (13-5-5) that has been almost as
good as the team's showing at Reunion Arena (14-4-2), where it has
played to capacity crowds almost every night.
</P>
<P>
   Not that this is a sudden turnaround, mind you. A year ago, the
Stars won the President's Trophy (awarded to the club with the best
regular-season record), finishing with franchise records in wins
(49) and points (109), but they would not add the more coveted
hardware. After losing center Joe Nieuwendyk to a torn anterior
cruciate ligament in the opening playoff game against San Jose,
Dallas took eventual Stanley Cup champion Detroit to six games in
the Western Conference finals before bowing out.
</P>
<P>
   With the offseason addition of Hull from St. Louis and the
return of Nieuwendyk (who actually had both ACLs repaired), the
Stars seemed to have bridged the gap with the two-time champion Red
Wings. Detroit's struggles with injuries and inconsistency only
appeared to further pry open the window of opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite the impressive first half, not everything has
gone exactly to plan.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk sat out the final five games with tendinitis in his
right knee. Voted Most Valuable Player by his teammates a year ago
despite the truncated playoff run, his health for the second half
is critical to a team that leans on him for scoring and leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt we're looking for some added scoring punch
from another line or a group of lines,'' he said. ``We all have a
responsibility. Certainly, I'm one of those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock, who watched his team's offense grind to a halt
against Detroit in Nieuwendyk's absence, is anxious to see if those
knees will hold up after some rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that position, that No. 2 hole, we need a good player at
center ice,'' Hitchcock said. ``Joe's the guy we want in that
position. He's going to have to be a good player for us, a strong
player night in, night out, if we want to go to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano, Hull and Jere Lehtinen are the team's top three scorers,
and all play on the No. 1 line. Finding punch from the left wing
remains a concern as well.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder, then, that the coach with the league's best record
still calls his team ``a work in progress.''
</P>
<P>
   The work resumes tonight as the second half begins and the
stakes continue to rise. With all the talk of a spring celebration
comes a level of expectation the Stars have yet to experience since
moving to Dallas before the 1993-94 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second half of the season, it goes up another level,''
Hitchcock said. ``All the players here recognize that. If we stay
the same level we were at the first half, we're just going to be a
middle-rung hockey club.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to need some of our younger players stepping their
games up, and we're going to need a strong emotional content to our
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do that, we'll be good.''
</P>
<P>
   Better than last year's near miss against the Red Wings?
</P>
<P>
   That's the hope, at least.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the clock is running.
</P>
<P>
   Hull is 34 years old, and Belfour will turn 34 in April. Wingers
Pat Verbeek and Dave Reid will be 35 in May. Skrudland will be 36
this summer, while defenseman Craig Ludwig will be 38 in March, the
same month center Guy Carbonneau turns 39.
</P>
<P>
   For the Stars, then, the future is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intensity, the talk around here, is starting to focus
itself on the playoffs,'' Skrudland said. ``We know it's a ways
down the road yet, but we want to talk Stanley Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not?
</P>
<P>
   Everyone else is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
