<SLUG> BC-DELTA-SURCHARGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING RESISTANCE, DELTA AIR WITHDRAWS FARE SURCHARGE
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By JANET PIORKO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines has withdrawn the $1 surcharge it imposed
earlier this month on one-way domestic flights purchased anywhere
but on its own Web site.
</P>
<P>
   An airline spokesman, Todd Clay, said Tuesday that the change
had been put into Delta's reservations system overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the airline had withdrawn the fee, he said, ``The
marketplace spoke, and we responded.''
</P>
<P>
   The fee had provoked an intense response from travel agents, who
book the vast majority of airline tickets and who contended that
its purpose was to entice customers away from them.
</P>
<P>
   In imposing the surcharge, Delta had cited increased costs of
distributing tickets. ``Consumers and consumer groups reacted very
negatively,'' said Dina Long, a spokeswoman for the American
Society of Travel Agents in Alexandria, Va. ``It was certainly seen
by us as being discriminatory against travelers, favoring one group
of travelers over another, and forcing consumers into purchasing
tickets in the way that is most convenient for Delta.''
</P>
<P>
   But a bigger reason for Tuesday's withdrawal may have been the
reluctance of any other airline to follow Delta's lead, thereby
putting Delta at a competitive disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Hanmer, a travel agent in Bartlesville, Okla., who had
criticized the surcharge when Delta imposed it two weeks ago, was
surprised but happy when she heard the news Tuesday. ``I'm pleased
that they listened to the public,'' she said, ``because Lord knows,
they don't listen to travel agents.'' Ms. Hanmer added that
passengers who had already paid the surcharge would not be be able
to obtain a refund. ``There's no chance,'' she said. ``Airlines
don't give back money easily.''
</P>
<P>
   AAA, the auto club and travel service, praised Delta's move.
``We believe that Delta has done the right thing,'' said Jack
Mannix, the organization's managing director for marketing and
industry relations. ``This demonstrates that they can and do listen
and respond to the concerns of others in the travel industry.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Murphy, an airline analyst with Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, remarked: ``Somebody the other day made a very good comment
that Delta should have done it in reverse _ put in a discount on
the Web site rather than a penalty'' on other bookings. ``Putting a
surcharge in is offensive to customers, whereas a discount would
be, I think, welcome,'' he added
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
