<HEADER>
A9544 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-ART-365     01-26 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-ART-365&AMP;ADDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS TALK TURNS TO CALLING LEWINSKY, SENATORS BECOME APPREHENSIVE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Texas, Ark., Ill., Ariz.)  (See related stories: IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-TRIAL,
IMPEACH-TWO-STEP, IMPEACH-SESSIONS, IMPEACH-LEWINSKY,
IMPEACH-REPUBS, HUBBELL-TAXES, STARR-LEAKS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``Senators, she does have a story to tell,'' the
impeachment manager said politely, uttering one of the classic
understatements of the nation's past year of scandal overdrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't you at least like to see and hear from her?'' asked
the prosecutor, Rep. Ed Bryant, R-Tenn., his gentle drawl inviting
as he urged the Senate court to not be shy and to call Monica
Lewinsky as the key witness in the case against President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   With the request for the much interrogated former intern at last
put before the court, House impeachment managers faced a Senate
very anxious about its own dignity. Instantly, repeatedly, the
managers promised it would be a bowdlerized, expurgated Ms.
Lewinsky summoned to testify, hardly the furtively tape-recorded,
uninhibited storyteller already making some senators cringe in
anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   ``At no point,'' the managers emphasized, would questions about
``explicit sexual relations with the president'' be asked or
answered in the august chamber. No sex, no way, they vowed.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate court only listened, as silent as ever, its dignity
intact for Tuesday at least, as the members went into closed
session to consider the request. Before that, as the president's
lawyers argued the issue with the House managers for four hours,
the Senate's attentiveness level certainly seemed to increase at
each utterance of Ms. Lewinsky's name and the prosecution claim
that she still had some story left to tell.
</P>
<P>
   The trial was approaching the heart of the matter, whether to
venture in search of fresh revelations from the famously talkative
young woman with whom the president misbehaved. Senators did not
quite brace themselves in unison, but some could be seen variously
fighting smiles and grimaces during the debate.
</P>
<P>
   There was a stir as the impeachment managers reminded the Senate
of the early cover story that Clinton was only ``ministering to a
troubled person'' in his dealings with Ms. Lewinsky. This brought
openly mirthful glances of disbelief on the Republican side, as if
in nostalgia at recalling one of the oldie-goldie tabloid show
stoppers of the scandal story.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Democrats tended to wax glum across the way, especially when
``the genie of discovery'' was invoked as a force likely to follow
into the chamber close upon any appearance by Ms. Lewinsky. As on
most trial days, Minority Leader Tom Daschle had a look of brooding
watchfulness as he took all this in.
</P>
<P>
   The senator seemed a match for the poker-faced stoicism of Bruce
Lindsey over at the defense counsel table _ the White House lawyer
who has yet to address the trial and, so, is doubly fascinating for
his silence. For he is Clinton's closest friend and confidant, the
president's midnight card-playing crony, a sought after witness
himself in the early impeachment sparring. As he takes notes and
confers at the defense table, Lindsey is widely assumed to be the
president's alter ego at the trial, the premier source of what
Clinton needs to know after each day's session.
</P>
<P>
   As the senators sat mutely through their eleventh day in
judgment of the president, the chamber's level of focus remained
noteworthy. Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, could be seen leaning and
staring in laser-like delight at the prosecutor's performance of
Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark. The senator nodded emphatically and
slapped his chair arm as Hutchinson drove home contentions about
Clinton's impeachability. At the end, Gramm could not help breaking
his rule of silence, sending a popping sound about the chamber as
he enthusiastically slapped his right fist into his left palm, as
if he had just witnessed a flawless baseball pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimate verdicts aside, many senators clearly are savoring the
sheer performance level of the vying attorneys. Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., leans back and grins appreciatively at the poor-mouth
strategems of the chief prosecutor, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sort of think we have fallen short in the respect side,''
Hyde told the Senate on Monday, fairly bowing and scraping as he
spoke as a humble visitor from the House, ``the other body, kind of
blue collar people.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tuesday, David Kendall, the president's personal lawyer, scored
points in senators' smiles of appreciation as he turned several of
the prosecutors' own past words against them in having previously
assured the House there was no need for witnesses. He belittled the
impeachment managers in quick order as desperate blackjack players,
a programmed barbershop chorus fruitlessly hoping for something
fresh to turn up. Kendall triggered a bipartisan guffaw when he
quickly added, beaming in all insincerity : ``I don't want to be
uncharitable to the House managers.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde closed out the public debate by complaining that Kendall's
side has a ``positive allergy'' to fact witnesses, preferring
professional academics by the polished tablefuls. ``You know what
an intellectual is,'' said Hyde, his trial shtik well honed by now.
``It's someone who's educated beyond his intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Various senators appreciated the chance to smile, even leer
before they once more were sealed within the chamber for their own
less amusing deliberations about summoning Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
