<HEADER>
A9546 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-DAVIS-COX     01-26 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-DAVIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The matchup: Davis and the Falcons D
 &HT;    By Andy Clendennen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ This is the matchup everyone is waiting
to see.
</P>
<P>
   No, Dan Reeves and Mike Shanahan aren't going to lace up the
gloves and go a few rounds.
</P>
<P>
   But NFL Most Valuable Player Terrell Davis vs. the heralded run
defense of the Falcons could be just as entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons allowed an average of 75 rushing yards a game this
season. Atlanta has also held 12 teams under 100 rushing yards this
year, and the Falcons ranked fourth in fewest points allowed with
289, or 18.1 per game.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, meanwhile, rushed for 2,008 yards, had 11 100-yard games
and scored 21 touchdowns. He also averaged 5.1 yards per carry, and
his rushing touchdowns are more than every single team in the NFL
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Something will give, but Davis isn't taking a different approach
just because the Falcons have one of the best defenses in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel pressure, to be honest with you,'' Davis said.
``I try to keep things simple. Going through a game with me is
playing as hard as I can, doing what the coaches ask me to and
keeping things simple. Doing those things, I think good things
happen and that's been my key as long as I've been playing and so
far it's been working.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what kind of game it is. It could be a
championship game or a regular-season game, I tend to just stick
with the same thing and it seems to get me through, so we'll stick
with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Chances are that the Falcons will stick with what got them here
_ a defensive line that is small but quick, a solid corps of
linebackers and an extremely strong secondary.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis is mainly concerned with the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are just very quick up front,'' Davis said. ``They don't
have particularly big players up front. They remind me a lot of our
defense. They have a lot of speed on the front and they are very
talented in what they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play their gaps well and are very disciplined, and people
like that are very hard to run against. The teams that I have faced
throughout the years, those are the teams that are very hard to run
against.''
</P>
<P>
   And a strong defense is what Broncos coach Mike Shanahan calls
the highest accolade one can give a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at their rushing defense, and they're ranked second
in the NFL,'' Shanahan said. ``To me, the biggest compliment you
can give a team is say they have a (good) rushing defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this game you have two great defensive teams who have the
opportunity to shut down anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   A big key to the success of Davis and the rushing offense may be
the play of fullback Howard Griffith.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't catch a lot of passes, he doesn't get many carries,
but he may play the most important role on Super Bowl Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Howard Griffith is a guy who is an unsung hero,'' Shanahan
said. ``He doesn't carry the ball many times, he doesn't catch the
ball many times, therefore a lot of people don't know him. But our
football players all know him and he's one of those guys that comes
to play every week, and he's just had an exceptional year.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's OK with his role on the team, a role overshadowed by
such offensive stars as John Elway, Shannon Sharpe, Rod Smith, Ed
McCaffrey and Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very comfortable with it,'' Griffith said. ``Lead blocking
is something that I've become accustomed to and I take a lot of
pride in. It's one of the things I have to do if I want to make
this team go, so it's something I take a lot of pride in doing for
the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously a challenge, going against a defense like we're
going against. It's going to be a challenge going out and executing
our gameplan to the best of our ability. They're going to make some
plays, but as long as we can stay on schedule and not get caught in
a 2nd and 10, we'll be fine. We have to choose our opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Clendennen writes for the Daily Sentinel, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
