A9552 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DENVER-NOTES27-CO     01-26 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DENVER-NOTES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chop-block technique common, linemen say
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Much has been made of the ``seal-blocking'' techniques
taught by Denver Broncos offensive line coach Alex Gibbs and
responsible, many observers feel, for the success of tailback
Terrell Davis. One national magazine recently detailed the manner
in which the frontside blockers rotate opposing defensive linemen
sideways, much like setting a ``pick'' in basketball. The backside
blockers allow the defense to pursue the play laterally, then use
their momentum to cut down would-be tacklers.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, the Denver linemen insisted there is nothing
revolutionary about the tactics employed by Gibbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing new under the sun in the NFL,'' right tackle
Harry Swayne said. ``We do what good offensive lines do. We come
off the ball hard. We try to punch you under the chin. We try to
get away with as much as they'll let us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos have been accused by some teams of using the same
cut-block techniques taught by San Francisco line coach Bobb
McKittrick. Those schemes have made McKittrick a despised coach in
several NFL cities.
</P>
<P>
   Center Tom Nalen stressed that the Broncos emphasize some
techniques in which the defenders are lured away from the play,
then legally chopped when they turn back to pursue the
misdirection. Guard Mark Schlereth politely noted that everyone is
seeking a reason why the NFL's lightest line unit (average 286
pounds) is so good. ``Instead of looking for all these reasons for
our success, people should acknowledge we're pretty good,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   They also block . . .
</P>
<P>
   The Denver offensive linemen splurged at Joe's Stone Crab on
Monday night and it turns out the group invited a couple hangers-on
to attend. Both fullbacks, starter Howard Griffith and backup
Detron Smith, accompanied the blockers. ``For just one night, they
had linemen status bestowed on them,'' tackle Tony Jones said.
``But the expiration date has expired now. They're back to being
just fullbacks.'' In postscript to the dinner, paid for with the
kangaroo court fines the linemen collect during the season, backup
center K.C. Jones was penalized $500 for revealing the plans in
advance to the media. ``Because of him, the place was crawling with
TV cameras,'' guard Dan Neil said.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for work
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Greg Robinson is sympathetic to the plight
of minority coaches, who have had problems securing head coach
opportunities. But Robinson made it clear he someday wants to be a
head coach, and said all hires should be made on merit. ``I
understand perfectly what the league and commissioner (Paul)
Tagliabue are trying to do in calling attention to the minority
problem. It's something that desperately needs to be addressed. But
I feel like I've earned consideration, too.'' In each of the last
two seasons, Robinson's name has been mentioned on the grapevine.
</P>
<P>
   Piece of the action
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback John Elway continues to leave the door open, just
barely, on his possible return in 1999. But when Elway does retire,
speculation is that Broncos owner Patrick Bowlen might invite him
to become a minority partner in the franchise. ``I know he does not
want to be a coach,'' Bowlen said. ``But I think he wants to work
here. I think that he probably wants to be a part of the ownership
group and I would welcome him.'' Elway certainly has the financial
wherewithal to buy into the Broncos. Last year he sold his six
Denver area car dealerships to Miami Dolphins owner Wayne Huizenga
for more than $87 million.
</P>
<P>
   The homeboy
</P>
<P>
   Broncos kicker Jason Elam, the former Brookwood High School star
from Snellville, allowed on Tuesday that it's ``a little strange''
facing the Falcons in the Super Bowl. ``I grew up a Falcons fan as
far back as I can remember,'' Elam said. ``I used to live and die
by what those guys did. Tim Mazzetti, Mick Luckhurst, Greg Davis,
Steve Bartkowski _ I remember them all. It's going to be tough to
root against them. It's going to be pretty special when we kick off
against them.''
</P>
<P>
   Inquiring minds
</P>
<P>
   Ever wonder if ``Barrel Man,'' the guy who comes to every
Broncos game dressed in a huge orange-and-blue barrel, has anything
on underneath? The Denver mascot, real name Tim McKernan, has
always claimed he was naked except for the barrel. But a curious
scribe who does not work for the Journal-Constitution caught a
sneak peek on Tuesday and issued this report: Bermuda shorts.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy system
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Ed McCaffrey, who was selected to the AFC Pro Bowl
squad, felt partner Rod Smith should have made the team as well. So
he's paying for Smith to accompany him to Hawaii for the game.
``The way I see it, he's one of the biggest reasons I made the
team,'' McCaffrey said. ``It's the least I could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Stat of the day
</P>
<P>
   There have been over 300 punts in Super Bowl history but none
has ever been returned for a touchdown. ``Let's keep it that way,''
Denver punter Tom Rouen said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos did not practice Tuesday because the the Media Day
activities, but will resume workouts this afternoon... Coach Mike
Shanahan imposed a 12:30 a.m. curfew on Tuesday for the next few
nights.
</P>
<P>
   The last word(s)
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe, who played at Savannah State, when asked what it might
be like to be covered Sunday by Falcons free safety Eugene
Robinson, a Colgate graduate: ``He can't out-talk me and he can't
cover me. Just because he went to Colgate, doesn't mean anything to
me. I don't have a degree from Harvard, but I can count to a
million.''
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
