<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: CAUGHT IN CROSS CURRENTS, LOTT SEEKS MIDDLE GROUND
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to correct hed)   (Eds.: The second take is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET) 
(See related stories: IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-TWO-STEP,
IMPEACH-SESSIONS, IMPEACH-LEWINSKY, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-REPUBS,
HUBBELL-TAXES, STARR-LEAKS) 
(sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Republican leaders on Tuesday took the
gamble that they can open the door to witnesses and yet still
somehow bring the trial of President Clinton to a relatively quick,
dignified and non-confrontational conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, Sen. Trent Lott, the majority leader, and his
deputies have struggled to find a footing in the midst of powerful
political cross currents: the general public overwhelmingly wants
the impeachment drive to end, but the party's conservative base
demands that it move forward.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans have wondered just what loyalty they owe to
their colleagues in the House, who pulled them over the cliff once
before during the government shutdown of 1995-1996. And they wonder
what kind of precedents they are creating for history.
</P>
<P>
   With all these conflicting impulses in mind, Lott has now
arranged a middle ground for his party: to approve subpoenas for
just three witnesses (aside from a House request, which may be
ignored, that the Senate invite Clinton to testify), with sharply
limited questioning time that could bring the Senate to an end to
the trial by mid-February. Although some Republicans were still
wavering, Lott seemed likely to win when the Senate votes Wednesday
on whether to depose witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just trying to have a fair process here,'' the
Mississippi Republican said this week, ``but one that gets us to a
conclusion, as soon as possible, without rushing to judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott has been navigating his way through a caucus of many views,
not always following predictable ideological predilections.
Conservatives like James M. Inhofe of Oklahoma, Wayne Allard of
Colorado and Don Nickles, the majority whip from Oklahoma, or
former House members like Rick Santorum of Pennsylvania have pushed
to support the House with a full trial and as many witnesses as the
prosecutors wanted, Republicans say.
</P>
<P>
   But moderates like Susan M. Collins of Maine and John H. Chafee
of Rhode Island have also argued for witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Shelby of Alabama, a usual ally of Lott's has been one
of the Republicans most skeptical about witnesses. And Richard
Lugar of Indiana, usually a centrist, has been mostly quiet in
caucus, Republicans say, but sounded fierce on Tuesday when he
blamed the White House for any partisanship developing in the
Senate. ``The White House has stonewalled almost every opportunity
to inquire about the president's activities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To hold this group together and win a majority for witnesses,
Lott has steadily reined in the House prosecutors. They once wanted
to call 15 witnesses instead of the three they ultimately settled
for on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He thus has played almost the opposite role as the leadership in
the House. There Rep. Tom DeLay, the majority whip, aggressively
pushed impeachment forward, by cleverly pushing moderates to vote
for impeachment, by not allowing them an easy out through a censure
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The House prosecutors made it clear on Tuesday they were less
than delighted. ``We have always believed and we still do believe
that 10 or 12 witnesses are what we should have, and should have
been permitted to call to prove our case,'' Rep. Bill McCollum,
R-Fla., said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
