<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BARNHOUSE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACH'S PREPARATION MEETS OPPORTUNITY AT ARIZONA STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
TEMPE, Ariz. _ In baseball, it's the trade that helps both teams.
In this particular college basketball story, it's the hire that
helped both schools.
<TEXT>
<P>
   About a year ago, when it was apparent that Texas A&AMP;M would
dismiss coach Tony Barone, the leading candidate was quickly
apparent. Rob Evans, the Mississippi coach who had been an
assistant at Texas Tech and Oklahoma State, seemed to be the
perfect fit.
</P>
<P>
   But, as often happens with the Aggies, ``negotiations broke
down.'' Instead of Evans, A&AMP;M wound up hiring Melvin Watkins of
North Carolina-Charlotte. Evans was hired at Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for Melvin and he's fabulous for Texas A&AMP;M,'' Evans
said after a recent Arizona State practice. ``It's something where
it really worked out for both of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have always worked out for me. I've always felt like
when I recruit a kid and I don't get him, the one I wind up with is
better. The man upstairs is looking out for me because this is a
great situation.''
</P>
<P>
   If you say so, Mr. Positive. Arizona State is recovering from a
point-shaving scandal that forced the resignation of coach Bill
Frieder two years ago. Don Newman, Frieder's interim replacement,
lasted one season before the school decided to hire a New Sheriff
to come in and clean up the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view, Rob is someone who is very straightforward, a
stand-up professional,'' Arizona State athletic director Kevin
White said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State's last conference championship came in 1973. The
Sun Devils have made two NCAA Tournament appearances in the past 17
seasons. The school's basketball tradition is as arid as the
climate.
</P>
<P>
   And that's another reason why Evans is a good fit here. He knows
all about winning at a school where the basketball history fits on
an index card. Compared with his former school, Arizona State is a
veritable North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   After a quarter of a century as an assistant coach, Evans got
his chance to be a head coach. He was handed the keys to
Mississippi's program in 1993. Few expected Evans to be seen or
heard from again.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got to Mississippi, that might have been the bleakest
situation I've seen,'' said Evans, 52. ``I took a pay cut. I was
making $70,000 and I was making more at Oklahoma State as an
assistant. The facilities were awful. Attendance was awful.''
</P>
<P>
   What Evans doesn't say is that he is a black man who was taking
over as coach at a school that has displayed a Confederate flag as
its symbol and has played ``Dixie'' as a ``fight'' song. Try to
recruit African-American players to a school with ``that'' baggage.
</P>
<P>
   In his final two seasons the Rebels won 42 games and twice
finished on top of the Southeastern Conference West Division. Evans
proved that he could build something out of very little.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils are 11-8 overall and 3-4 in the Pacific-10. Evans
is trying to build his program's foundation by emphasizing defense
and discipline. Arizona State's gambling scandal, he said, ``was no
factor'' as the Sun Devils signed an impressive recruiting class in
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Arizona State is one of the few schools, probably one
of 20, that has the chance to win the national championship,''
Evans said. ``It may never happen. But you've got the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the A&AMP;M job was a good situation and possibility for
me. The new facility, the location ... I thought there were three
or four jobs in the country that were ones I would leave Ole Miss
for, and A&AMP;M was one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State, it turned out, was also on that list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
