A9558 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-RELIGION-ART-N     01-26 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-RELIGION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORTHODOX WIN KEY RULING KEEPING MORE LIBERAL SECTS OFF RELIGIOUS
COUNCILS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Efforts by the conservative and reform Jewish
movements to gain official recognition in Israel suffered a setback
Tuesday when the Israeli Parliament passed a bill intended to bar
non-orthodox Jews from the country's powerful religious councils.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bill's practical effect is still to be tested, it
has fueled the debate on religious pluralism in Israel and on the
role of religion in the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the small conservative and reform movements here, who
have been been chipping away at the orthodox control of religious
affairs in Israel, warned that the legislation would cause a rift
with Jews abroad, most of whom are not orthodox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am deeply concerned that this legislation will alienate
diaspora Jewry, two-thirds of the Jewish people, from the state of
Israel,'' said Rabbi Ehud Bandel, president of the conservative
movement in Israel. ``The Parliament has said that there is only
one legitimate Judaism in Israel: Orthodox Judaism.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Sephardic chief rabbi lashed out at the Reform
movement, saying it had led to the loss of more Jews by
assimilation than in the Holocaust. ``We know that the one-way
street sanctioning assimilation is the Reform system, the Reform
conversion, the Reform synagogue,'' said the rabbi, Eliahu
Bakshi-Doron.
</P>
<P>
   The government-sponsored bill was proposed by the strictly
orthodox United Torah Judaism party to counter Supreme Court
rulings that conservative and reform Jews should be included in
religious councils, traditionally an orthodox preserve.
</P>
<P>
   The state-financed councils in cities and towns serve both
religious and secular Israelis, running marriage bureaus and burial
societies, maintaining synagogues and ritual baths and supervising
kosher inspections at restaurants and shops.
</P>
<P>
   Facing the prospect that strictly orthodox lawmakers would block
approval of the state budget if the councils bill was not passed,
the governing coalition of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
mustered just enough votes to pass the bill 50 to 49, with one
abstention. Suspended budget discussions resumed after the vote,
which followed a stormy debate that lasted late into Monday night
and ended Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   A crucial yes vote was cast by Yitzhak Mordechai, the former
Israeli defense minister, who was recently dismissed by Netanyahu.
Running for prime minister at the helm of a new centrist party,
Mordechai is courting orthodox support in the Israeli elections set
for May.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Uri Regev, a leader of the Reform movement in Israel,
called the legislation ``a slap in the face.'' As head of the
movement's Israel Religious Action Center, Regev has waged a decade
of court battles to seat reform and conservative Jews on the
councils.
</P>
<P>
   Designed to exclude non-orthodox Jews, the bill passed Tuesday
requires council members to pledge that they will abide by rulings
of the Chief Rabbinate and of local rabbinates.
</P>
<P>
   But reform and conservative representatives say that they are
willing to acknowledge the Chief Rabbinate's authority in matters
of Jewish law, and are prepared to make the pledge in order to
serve on the councils.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will make the pledge required by law, though our
interpretation of it might be different that that intended by the
lawmakers,'' said Bandel, who is a designated member of the
Jerusalem religious council.
</P>
<P>
   But Bandel and his colleagues are sure to run into resistance
from orthodox council members, who have boycotted recent council
meetings in the cities of Haifa and Tel Aviv to avoid having to sit
with conservative and reform representatives. The religious council
in Jerusalem has not even been called into session, and the
conservative and reform movements have gone to court to demand that
it be convened.
</P>
<P>
   The interior and religious affairs minister, Eliahu Suissa, a
member of the strictly orthodox Sephardic Shas party, is leading
the resistance to the court-ordered integration of the councils. He
warned on Monday that he would resign rather than violate Jewish
law or the injunctions of the chref rabbis. He has also ordered the
appointment next month of new religious councils with fewer members
in an effort to restrict he number of non-orthodox representatives.
Bakshi-Doron has called for the abolition of the religious councils
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Defiance of court orders to integrate the councils is a
religious imperative, argued Avraham Laserson, a lawmaker from
United Torah Judaism. ``Matters that are sacrosanct in Judaism are
not subject at all to the authority of the court,'' he told
Parliament Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
