u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WITNESS-COX     01-26 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WITNESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Republicans cut potential witness list to 3; Currie not
includedBy Mark Sherman and Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republican prosecutors whittled their
proposed witness list to three Tuesday to focus on obstruction of
justice charges against President Clinton and to coax a reluctant
Senate to extend the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors also ``made a rather gentle request,'' in the
words of prosecutor Rep. Asa Hutchinson (R-Ark.) that senators
invite Clinton to submit, under oath, to another round of questions
about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky and attempts to conceal
it. White House aides quickly ruled out an appearance by the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Under a measure that the Senate will vote on today, Lewinsky,
Clinton friend Vernon Jordan and presidential aide Sidney
Blumenthal would answer questions from prosecutors and Clinton's
defense team in the presence of a senator from both parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Witnesses help you. They won't help me,'' Rep. Henry Hyde
(R-Ill.) told senators. ``I'm satisfied a compelling case is here
for the removal of the president.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise was that Oval Office secretary Betty
Currie, who plays a critical role in two of the seven obstruction
of justice counts, was not included on the list. Hyde, the lead
prosecutor, said there is already enough from her in the record.
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall, Clinton's personal lawyer, scoffed at the need
for witnesses in a presentation to the Senate that was laced with
sarcasm. ``We know what they're going to say,'' Kendall said of the
proposed witnesses, ``because it's all right there in the volumes
before you.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparing the prosecutors to Mr. Micawber in David Copperfield,
Kendall said that they keep hoping something new will turn up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't know what it is, but they believe they'll know it
when they see it,'' Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
   He also warned senators that if they let the ``genie'' out of
the bottle, White House lawyers would need ample time to examine
evidence they have not yet seen and prepare for witnesses they
might call in Clinton's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall sparred with the House team during an afternoon session
that at times resembled a ``did too, did not'' spat.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said the White House is afraid of witnesses. We are
not, Kendall said. Are too, Rep. Bill McCollum (R-Fla.) said in
closing the debate.
</P>
<P>
   In arguing for witnesses, the prosecutors acknowledged that they
had wanted to ask for more witnesses _ up to 18, according to Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they were settling for ``a pitiful three,'' Hyde said,
because senators left little doubt that they would reject a lengthy
list of witnesses and seek to end the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we made such a request, it would not be approved,''
McCollum said.
</P>
<P>
   The prospective witnesses, and the issues prosecutors said they
would explore, indicate that they will emphasize the article of
impeachment charging Clinton with obstructing justice over the
article that alleges the president testified falsely to a federal
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cover six of the elements of obstruction,'' Hutchinson
said, explaining how prosecutors decided which names to include.
</P>
<P>
   At least two Republican senators, Susan Collins of Maine and
Gordon Smith of Oregon, and two Democrats, Bob Graham of Florida
and Russell Feingold of Wisconsin, have said that they consider the
obstruction charge the stronger of the two. Conviction on either
article, which requires a two-thirds vote in the Senate, would be
sufficient to remove Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   The House prosecutors argued that the witnesses would remove any
doubts that the senators might have about the case against Clinton
by injecting live voices into the case, which has so far been told
by depositions and video and audio tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Today's vote, if successful, still would defer a decision on
whether to call any of the witnesses to the floor of the Senate for
live testimony. One possibility under discussion would involve
videotaping the witnesses' testimony in private sessions with the
lawyers, then making the tapes available to senators.
</P>
<P>
   The House prosecutors also asked permission to introduce three
pieces of evidence that weren't in the official House impeachment
record used so far during the trial:
</P>
<P>
   _ An affidavit from Barry Ward, the clerk for U.S. District
Judge Susan Webber Wright who oversaw the Paula Jones sexual
harassment lawsuit against the president. Prosecutors said Ward
attended Clinton's deposition in the Jones case and observed a key
moment in the testimony in which presidential lawyers contend
Clinton was not paying attention. Ward testified the president was
attentive, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   _ An affidavit from T. Wesley Holmes, a lawyer for Mrs. Jones,
who testified that the Jones lawyers had subpoenaed Oval Office
secretary Betty Currie as a witness in their case in January 1998,
around the time Clinton had summoned his secretary to his office
and gone over his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky. Clinton has said
he wasn't tampering with Ms. Currie because he had no reason to
believe she would be a witness in any proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   _ Records of telephone calls between Ms. Lewinsky and the
president, including a Dec. 6, 1997, call that lasted 56 minutes.
The call occurred around the time Ms. Lewinsky was emerging as a
possible witness in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman and Rebecca Carr write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
