A9563 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-TRIAL-COX     01-26 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Three qualify as potential jurors in dragging death case
 &HT;    By Zach Maxwell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Prosecutors and defense attorneys in the capital
murder trial of John William King interviewed 10 potential jurors
Tuesday, but qualified only three for a final pool from which they
will select the 12 jurors and two alternates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three out of 10 won't get us there,'' Jasper County District
Attorney Guy James Gray said after the third session of questioning
Tuesday. He said simply finding a jury to decide the fate of King,
accused in the June 1998 dragging death of James Byrd Jr., ``has
always been a concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the seven excused from jury duty, four were steadfastly
against the death penalty, one had a prior conviction for
shoplifting and another said their opinion in the matter was
already set.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential juror revealed he was related to Michelle
Chapman, who received letters from King while he was in jail and
has been subpoenaed to testify in the trial. The DA's office filed
a list of 48 subpoenas last week, including a man from Diboll,
Steven Potter. Potter's relation to the case was not known.
</P>
<P>
   Gray showed confidence that a jury of Jasper County residents
would be set, even if it becomes necessary to dip into jury pools
from other county court jury lists.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning session, one of three people from the 122-member
jury pool _ a black woman whose husband is a Jasper County
sheriff's deputy _ made the cut.
</P>
<P>
   James Byrd Sr., the father of the 49-year-old killed in a
possibly racially-motivated hate crime, attended the morning
session.
</P>
<P>
   Five people were interviewed in an early afternoon session.
Three were dispatched within 10 minutes for their qualms against
the death penalty. The fourth was subjected to lengthy
back-and-forth questioning from Gray and defense attorney Brack
Jones. He and a postal worker, both white men, completed the day's
qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
   Two more men were excused from duty in a short 3 p.m. session,
again for their stands on the death penalty. One of the men quoted
the Bible (``Thou shalt not kill.'') on a lengthy questionnaire
distributed to potential jurors Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're moving faster than expected,'' Gray said. ``Six were
disqualified in a heartbeat. That speeds things up.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the anti-death penalty theme of the day was to be
expected in Jasper, a deeply religious town of 8,000 in the East
Texas piney woods, but called the disqualifications a ``statistical
blurp.''
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Joe Bob Golden issued an order to the jury
pool to steer clear of a cable television special on the killing
that aired Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Potential jurors were interviewed one-by-one, with an audience
of mostly news media in the courthouse gallery. King wore an
untucked black and white checkered shirt concealing a stun belt,
occasionally laughed at banter with his attorneys, and made a point
to scan the gallery before taking his seat at the start of the
day's final session.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell writes for the Lufkin Daily News, Texas
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
