<HEADER>
A9569 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH27-COX     01-26 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth releases plans for office complex
 &HT;    By Sallye Salter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth's estimated $750 million program to build
three large office centers in Midtown and Buckhead will relocate
most of its metro Atlanta employees to within walking distance of
MARTA transit stations. At the same time, the project will deal a
blow to the suburban office space market. The company will vacate 2
million square feet in the suburbs while it builds 3 million square
feet in the city.
</P>
<P>
   In Midtown, BellSouth plans to build three buildings of 350,000
square feet each on the seven-acre site of the vacant First Baptist
Church at Fourth and Peachtree. The telecommunications company has
offered to give the sanctuary building to the Atlanta Symphony
Orchestra for a concert hall. The new BellSouth office would be
near the North Avenue MARTA station and a block from the 1
million-square-foot BellSouth Center at 675 West Peachtree.
</P>
<P>
   The Midtown land was part of several blocks assembled by a
Swedish investor in the 1980s for a massive high-density
development. It is now owned by a Swedish lender of the developer
who went bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   At Lenox Park in Buckhead, north of the Lenox MARTA station,
BellSouth will buy 12 acres. The company will build three office
buildings containing a total of 640,000 square feet alongside three
existing office buildings containing 360,000 square feet. The site
is zoned for one additional building.
</P>
<P>
   At the Lindbergh MARTA station, BellSouth will construct two
500,000-square-foot office buildings that will be developed by
Carter &AMP; Associates as part of a retail-office-residential-hotel
complex on land leased from MARTA. Carter is also developing
BellSouth's other two centers.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's consolidation, which will put 17,000 of its 19,000
employees within I-285 by 2003, is the second such plan unveiled by
Atlanta-based corporate giants this month. Two weeks ago, Coca-Cola
Co. said it is working on a consolidation plan to relocate 2,500
employees from the suburbs and Midtown to sites near its
4,500-employee North Avenue headquarters in the western sector of
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congestion has turned on the suburbs,'' said Gregg Logan, who
heads the Atlanta office of Robert Charles Lesser Co., a national
consulting firm. ``It is not surprising that companies are looking
back in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given Atlanta's inability to build highways in the suburbs,
BellSouth seems to be betting that the situation is going to get
worse before it gets better,'' said Logan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's validation of the notion that development demand by
corporate users is gravitating intown,'' said Tom Watson, executive
vice president of Jamison Research Inc., a major provider of
information on commercial real estate here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a warning flag to the suburbs that it's time for smart
growth,'' Watson said. ``It is going to say a lot to north Fulton,
Cobb and Gwinnett that have been attracting these technology
companies. ``
</P>
<P>
   While Midtown development is more expensive than the suburbs,
BellSouth will be able to achieve costs comparable to those for
suburban office space in the Buckhead locations, Logan said.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth officials indicated the buildings will be functional
and not landmark towers.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its off-Peachtree location, Lenox Park is closer in
price to the suburbs, and at Lindbergh ``BellSouth will have
transportation and almost suburban land prices in an area that's
about to take off,'' Logan said.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Stevenson, Carter executive vice president of
development, said BellSouth's addition to the complex ``gives
instant credibility to the site.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's plan, developed over the past 14 months, ``is
cheaper and gives more flexibility'' than the company's current
leases, expected renewal costs and growth projected for five to
seven years, according to Inge Waddle, vice president of property
at BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still exploring the financial alternatives,'' Waddle
said, and the company has not determined if it will own the
facilities or lease them, perhaps in a sale-leaseback transaction.
Construction is expected to be started later this year and
buildings will be completed between 2001 and 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The suburban space to be vacated is in 75 locations. The larger
locations are at Century Center in DeKalb County, Perimeter Center
in Sandy Springs and Executive Park in northeast Atlanta. All of
the large spaces are leased by BellSouth, with the exception of one
building at Perimeter Center and another at Executive Park. Both of
those will be placed up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Neither BellSouth Center nor the 600,000 square feet of space
the company occupies in the Campanile building and the 1100
Peachtree Building will be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Sallye Salter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
