u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXERCISE-BENEFITS-BOS     01-26 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXERCISE-BENEFITS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY EQUATES BENEFITS OF LIFESTYLE, GYM EXERCISE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Science has come to the rescue of all who can't imagine
themselves wearing Spandex and sweating in a gym. Two studies
published Wednesday show that no-sweat, no-equipment activities
squeezed into busy everyday lives produce equal health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Improvements in fitness, blood pressure, cholesterol, weight
loss, amount of body fat, and mood were no greater among
individuals randomly assigned to vigorous aerobic programs than
among comparable people who engaged in dribs and drabs of
moderate-intensity ``lifestyle'' exercise such as brisk walking,
taking the stairs instead of elevators, and doing household chores.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is good news for people who don't enjoy traditional
exercise programs or are not able to do it,'' said Ross E.
Anderson, a Johns Hopkins University researcher who led a study
comparing the two exercise approaches among 40 obese women.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to go to the gym unless you want to,'' added
Andrea L. Dunn of the Cooper Institute for Aerobic Research in
Dallas, an author of a second study comparing the two strategies
among 235 previously sedentary men and women.
</P>
<P>
   Exercise experts said the new studies, published in this week's
Journal of the American Medical Association, provide some of the
strongest evidence so far on the health benefits of moderate
activities that can be worked into daily life.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence ``substantially bolsters the case for lifestyle
physical activity and has important public health implications,''
said Dr. Michael Pratt of the US Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention in Atlanta. ``Modest amounts of physical activity,
within the reach of most people, will improve health.''
</P>
<P>
   Research over the past five years has pointed in this direction,
but until now the evidence has been largely epidemiological _ based
on statistical associations in large populations. The Dallas and
Baltimore groups documented the effects on individuals randomly
assigned to one or the other type of exercise program.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt said the studies were ``noteworthy'' because they
monitored the exercise effects for two years, in the case of the
Dallas study, and 68 weeks, in the Baltimore project. ``Long-term
health benefits require long-term behavioral changes,'' Pratt noted
in a journal editorial accompanying the studies.
</P>
<P>
   The results may surprise many Americans who remember the
oft-repeated maxim that it takes at least 20 minutes of daily
vigorous exercise three times a week _ running, swimming, cycling
and the like _ to achieve meaningful health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The great majority of Americans have found that prescription
beyond their reach. Only about one-fifth of the population is
active enough to derive health benefits from exercise of any kind,
according to a 1996 report of the US Surgeon General.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gym-based programs probably help about 12 to 20 percent of
people,'' Dunn said, ``and that hasn't changed since the mid-1980s,
when the fitness boom occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   Even for those motivated to hit the gym, the conventional
exercise wisdom has actually worked against long-term adherence
because many people think it's no use if they can't keep up the
thrice-weekly routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people think `Oh, I've missed a week of exercise, I might
as well give up,' '' Dunn said. ``What these studies say is that
even these moderate activities can help maintain fitness during
those times, such as business trips, when they can't get to the
gym.''
</P>
<P>
   The new results do not imply that more intensive exercise
doesn't provide additional benefits, but both sets of researchers
agreed that the major gain comes from moving from being sedentary
to moderately active.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most encouraging results come from the study of
obese women, a collaboration of researchers at Johns Hopkins, the
University of Pennsylvania, and Cabrini College in Radnor, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers assigned 40 middle-aged women, obese since
adolescence and weighing an average of 192 pounds, to a vigorous,
16-week aerobics program or a four-month series of classes to teach
them how to be more active in their daily lives. All were asked to
stick to a 1,200-calorie daily diet _ a the American Heart
Association's standard weight-loss regimen.
</P>
<P>
   The aerobics program used stepping platforms and low-impact
movements choreographed especially for obese women; each 45-minute
session was designed to expend 450 to 500 calories _ a considerable
workout.
</P>
<P>
   The ``lifestyle'' group was quizzed regularly about how often
and how far they walked briskly, how often they climbed stairs, and
other activities. But researchers checked their answers against a
wearable computerized device to record their movements.
</P>
<P>
   Women in the lifestyle group increased their total activity
level by 28 percent, according to the devices. They lost the same
amount of weight as the aerobics group (about 17 pounds), but the
``lifestyle'' group actually did better in keeping weight off in
the year after the formal instruction ended.
</P>
<P>
   Other improvements, such as reduced body fat, lower blood
pressure, and better cholesterol and blood fat readings, were
comparable between the two groups. Both had substantial
improvements in mood too.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas study had a similar design, with 235 men and women
randomly assigned either to six months of intensive instruction in
gym workouts on their choice of treadmills, bicycles,
stairclimbers, and other equipment; or to classes that helped them
work out ways to accumulate at least 30 minutes of brisk walking
and other moderate exercise each day.
</P>
<P>
   The ``novel finding,'' the Texas researchers said, is that the
``lifestyle'' approach ``is as effective in producing beneficial
changes in physical activity, cardio-respiratory fitness, blood
pressure, and body composition as the traditional structured
approach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
