<HEADER>
A9572 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SESSIONS-1STL     01-26 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SESSIONS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS ADAPT TO CLOSED SESSIONS
</HEADLINE>
 
(replaces last 5 grafs with 9 new grafs, for rewriting and
additional information) 
(ATTN: Neb., Utah, Tenn., N.J., Texas, Ore., W.Va.)  (See related stories: IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-TRIAL,
IMPEACH-TWO-STEP, IMPEACH-LEWINSKY, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-REPUBS,
HUBBELL-TAXES, STARR-LEAKS) 
(bl) 
 By FRANK BRUNI and KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When their gazes drifted upward, toward a
four-sided gallery recently packed with reporters, foreign tourists
and even the stray Hollywood celebrity or two, senators saw only
empty seats and, behind those vacant rows, something that had been
invisible to them for the last few hectic weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You sat there looking up at the busts of the vice
presidents,'' said Sen. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., referring to the
marble statues lining the outer, upper rim of the Senate chamber.
``Usually, they are camouflaged with thousands of people teeming
around.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since the impeachment trial of President
Clinton began, Frist and other senators noted, there was relative
stillness: no revolving groups of spectators streaming in and out,
no aides scurrying to and fro.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a greater hush, especially Monday night, when
senators addressed one another without benefit of microphones. If
the colleague speaking was disinclined to shout, other senators
sometimes left their seats, strayed informally toward the well of
the chamber and leaned in close to listen.
</P>
<P>
   It was ``more intimate, more personal,'' Sen. John Kerry,
D-Mass., said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., agreed. ``We stripped away the
theater,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual closed-door debates that the Senate held Monday
night and again Tuesday afternoon and evening did not yield
agreement among senators on a number of points, including whether
they were proper and whether they were helpful.
</P>
<P>
   But there was almost unanimous consensus, in interviews with
more than a dozen senators Tuesday, that the atmosphere of these
sessions was rare and extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, this is a new process for almost everyone in the
Senate,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, saying that the only other
closed sessions he and many other senators had ever participated in
were national security briefings from outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very specific, and very limited in time,'' Gramm
said. ``Nothing like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday evening, the doors to the chamber closed for more than
four hours for a debate on a Democratic motion to dismiss the
charges against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday afternoon, the doors closed again for a debate on a
Republican motion to depose three witnesses. Suddenly, the hundreds
of spectators were asked to leave, and for several
movement-crippling minutes, they packed the third-floor hallways
outside the chamber, a startling reminder of the abrupt transition
inside from public proceeding to private conference.
</P>
<P>
   On both days, the television cameras in the chamber were turned
off, the reporters sent away. Senators could not summon aides to
their sides and, on Monday, could not use microphones.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, although the main audio system was again shut off and
senators could not use the microphones at their desks, a portable
microphone attached to two loudspeakers was made available to them.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the senators were bound to a code of secrecy
about the content of their discussions. Any violation could, under
Rule 29 of the Standing Rules of the Senate, lead to ``expulsion
from the body.''
</P>
<P>
   Several senators, seemingly relishing this aura of mystery,
joked that the penalty could be even worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I tell you anything,'' Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, said
late Monday, ``they'll hang me by my thumbs.''
</P>
<P>
   A majority of Democrats had voted not to close these debates,
while a majority of Republicans wanted them held in secrecy, so
assessments of how useful the sessions were often split along party
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans said the sessions promoted candor and comfort.
``If the public could see it, they would demand that we do it more,
not less,'' said Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would see people talking to each other instead of at each
other,'' Smith said. ``It's really remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Without television cameras, Smith added, ``people assume a
different posture.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., had apparently observed an
entirely different proceeding Monday night, after which he said he
concluded that ``senators are theatrical even in the privacy of
their home showers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't detect any noticeable change in demeanor,''
Torricelli said Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., said many senators seemed confused by
the sudden isolation. Imitating them in a mocking fashion, he said:
``Where do I look? Who do I talk to? What about these cards I want
to use? Where is my staff to tell me what to say?''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., one of the few Democrats who
voted to shut the chamber's doors, said that the measure was indeed
proving helpful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you about a closed debate,'' Byrd said Tuesday
morning. ``If the Constitutional Convention of 1787 had not closed
its doors, we would not have the Constitution we have today.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained that the Constitution's framers could speak bluntly
and fearlessly, and he said that that held true when the Senate's
doors closed this time.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., had voted to keep the
debate open, he said during a break in this evening's session that
closing it did have some positive effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Members are talking to one another,'' Schumer said, ``instead
of the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Senators said that the tone of discussion on both nights
remained civil. One senator, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said that Tuesday evening's discussion was much more
intense and animated than Monday's, because the upcoming vote on
witnesses would be closer than the one on dismissing the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Another person who was in the chamber Tuesday night and who also
spoke on the condition of anonymity said that there were private
negotiations going on constantly in the back of the room. Up front,
this observer said, most senators spoke for five minutes each, with
Democrats and Republicans taking alternate turns speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Senators moved around more freely, sometimes drifting into small
clutches of private conversation, sometimes stretching their legs
or backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a remarkable thing,'' said Smith or Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Or, in the words of Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, ``very strange.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
