<HEADLINE>
AT SITE OF INDONESIA RIOTS, FEW SIGNS OF LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TELAGAKODOK, Indonesia _ The hands on the broken white plastic
wall clock show 10 minutes past 11, almost the exact time that an
enraged Muslim mob entered this village Wednesday and began killing
Christian residents, sending the entire population fleeing for
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The clock lies outside the ruins of a house, one of more than 40
set afire in this once bustling hillside village 20 miles northeast
of the town of Ambon, in the Spice Islands or Moluccas. Local
officials had originally reported that the attacks were on
Thursday. But they have concluded that the attacks were on
Wednesday, after clashes that began Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of life are few. A lone dog guarding the burned ruins of
his house barked at a stranger. On a neatly tended hedge
uncollected clothes had been set out to dry. A few goats, some
ducks and chickens foraged among the ruins, the only other signs of
life.
</P>
<P>
   Under police escort, a reporter visited the site, but the
officers were not eager to linger. They said many of the attackers
were from a Muslim community 300 yards down the road.
</P>
<P>
   The situation remains tense.
</P>
<P>
   A parish priest from a nearby village supervised the burial of
12 victims of the attack. But with many villagers unaccounted for,
several senior government and church officials said they believed
that the final death toll would be at least 40.
</P>
<P>
   The killings followed five days of rioting, looting and arson
that destroyed Muslim and Christian villages in the region and much
of the waterfront commercial district of Ambon.
</P>
</TEXT>
