<HEADER>
A9576 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AGL-SETTLE-COX     01-26 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGL-SETTLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Regulators hope for settlement on gas prices
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ State regulators hope the settlement of Atlanta Gas
Light Co.'s rate debacle will now clear the way for Georgia's
natural gas deregulation to proceed with promised savings for
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Service Commission voted 4-0 Tuesday to accept a
settlement worked out between the utility and commission staff. The
pact should go a long way toward ending customer confusion over
AGL's bills.
</P>
<P>
   The utility agreed to refund $14.5 million in the form of checks
and bill credits to its customers, with most of the relief going to
those hurt the most by December's rate shock. Refunds for those
custromers will vary, but average about $23.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, AGL abandoned its controversial new rate structure
that resulted in many consumers' getting socked with hefty bills
when they used little or no gas in December because of built-in
charges for interstate pipeline capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The utility will return to a system that bases all gas charges
on the amount of gas actually consumed by a home or business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers have spoken loud and clear,'' said Paula Rosput,
president and chief operating officer of AGL, referring to the the
outcry.
</P>
<P>
   The flap over AGL's rates, a controversy unprecedented in the
utility's 143-year-old history, was anticipated by few in the
utility industry. But it's been credited by many observers as being
a critical factor in a larger-than-anticipated migration of AGL
customers to marketers that began selling gas in the state Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   At last count, 284,000 of AGL's 1.5 million customers -- or 19
percent -- had switched to marketers, a much higher rate than in
other deregulation programs around the country at this stage in the
process. Once 33 percent have switched, the rest will be assigned
at random to marketers, and AGL will exit the gas sales business.
</P>
<P>
   PSC Chairman Stan Wise said he doubted that bringing AGL's
prices into line would stem the migration to marketers. ``The
momentum is there,'' he said. ``Over time and once market forces
are in control, prices will come down. ''
</P>
<P>
   The general sentiment at Tuesday's PSC meeting was, as state
utility counsel Jim Hurt put it, the settlement is not perfect.
``But we think it's in the best interest of everyone to move on,''
Hurt said.
</P>
<P>
   PSC member Robert Durden called the controversy a ``horrendous
experience'' that he blamed on AGL's ``failure to communicate'' and
hoped would not happen again.
</P>
<P>
   A sour note was sounded by Lynn R. Westergaard, president of
Resource Service Mininistries, an Atlanta activist group that is
active in PSC proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a mean-spirited and evil way, AGL has taken money from the
ratepaying public that borders on extortion, if not out-and-out
stealing,'' Westergaard said in a letter to the commission.
``Refunds should be made on a formula that matches
dollar-for-dollar for each household from whom money was
overcollected.''
</P>
<P>
   AGL said its new rate for gas usage that will show up in
February bills is 40 cents per therm, based on normal weather. Last
February, before deregulation, AGL's rate was 37 cents though the
utility undercharged consumers by $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   The new rate, however, is subject to change due to the weather.
Mark D. Caudill, vice president/rates and regulatory affairs at AGL
Resources Inc., parent of Atlanta Gas Light, said if weather is 50
percent warmer than usual, the rate could go as high as 52 cents
per therm. If it's 50 percent colder than usual, the AGL rate could
go as low as 35 cents per therm, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But at least, consumers will be able to figure out their bill
based on how many therms they use in a given billing period, AGL
officials said, instead of trying to figure out hoplessly
complicated pipeline capacity charges.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, customers will only be charged based on what they
use. ``If they use zero gas, they won't see gas charges on their
bill as in the last few months,'' said Terri Reichert, AGL's rates
manager.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of January rates offered by marketers found that gas
charges ranged from 37 cents per therm to 47 cents per therm, in
addition to fixed monthly delivery charges not affected by the
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Some marketers offer to lock in rates for up to three years,
others change rates monthly.
</P>
<P>
   Several marketing executives said the settlement would not cause
them to lower their rates to be more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we're below AGL, we'll be fine,'' said Warren
Darby, senior vice president of South Carolina-based SCANA Energy,
which is believed to have a leading share of customners who have
switched to marketers. SCANA's current rate is 37 cents per therm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our pricing is not going to be affected,'' said A. Clifton
Payne, vice president for marketing at Georgia Natural Gas
Services, AGL's marketing affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew C. Quinn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
