<HEADER>
A9581 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE-CLINTON-650&AMP;ADD-     01-26 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-CLINTON-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGAIN, CLINTON CREATES HIS OWN POLITICAL AURA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also POPE-U.S., POPE-EXORCISM, POPE-JEWS) 
(lb) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ With Pope John Paul II at his side, Bill Clinton
declared Tuesday that the United States was striving to be ``an
example of justice and civic virtues'' _ as he once again adroitly
harnessed the presidency to save his situation.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, Clinton took President Nelson Mandela's hand to help
him down from a podium, and on Tuesday, again playing the admiring
protege, he did the same with the pope; but while he may have been
offering his support each time, Clinton clearly got at least as
good as he gave.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Washington, the House prosecutors were declaiming about
witnesses to the crimes of perjury and obstruction of justice that
they say Clinton committed in covering up his affair with Monica
Lewinsky. But as the president demonstrated again Tuesday, his most
potent cover-up is the political one he has conducted, all year, in
plain sight.
</P>
<P>
   By never mentioning Ms. Lewinsky or the trial while performing
the duties of his office and commanding its majesty, Clinton
essentially creates his own political atmosphere; through the
press, he pulls the country in.
</P>
<P>
   The thousands of Roman Catholics gathered in a shadowy, stuffy
airplane terminal here warmly greeted Clinton. They may not have
been applauding the Southern Baptist who has confessed his
infidelity to the world, but they most certainly applauded the
president of the United States, repeatedly punctuating his words of
welcome, on behalf of the country. There were no cries of ``God
bless you!'' as there were for the pope, but there were no cries of
protest, either.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the pope, ``You have never let those of us who
enjoy the blessings of prosperity, freedom and peace forget our
responsibilities.'' He said the pope would see ``an America working
harder to be what you have asked us to be: an example of justice
and civic virtues, freedom fulfilled and goodness at home and
abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, the chairman of the House Judiciary Committee
who is the lead prosecutor in the president's impeachment trial,
and David Schippers, the committee's chief counsel, are both papal
knights, an honor granted to several hundred Roman Catholics who
promote the church's interests. Hyde and Schippers were in
Washington working to remove Clinton from office as the pope
clasped the president's hands in both of his and smiled up at him
on the podium.
</P>
<P>
   The pope brought no hint of the storm in Washington to Clinton's
self-created political atmosphere. He thanked Clinton for his
courtesy, and did not say a word about Ms. Lewinsky. The pope stuck
with policy, the arena the president prefers, making his profound
policy differences with Clinton clear by declaring that the United
States must outlaw abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a higher moral vision can motivate the choice for life,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who did not publicly address the issue Tuesday,
supports abortion rights, saying abortion should be ``safe, legal
and rare.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, his aides say over and over, is just doing the job that
he loves the way that he loves to do it. And that is true. It is a
classic bit of Clinton luck, however, that the job is now, as the
trial is under way, supplying him with extraordinary opportunities
to switch subjects.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago he delivered his State of the Union address, resting
his arms on the lectern and leaning toward his hostile audience in
a folksy, friendly, initiative-packed appeal that shot right over
their heads. On Tuesday he descended the stairs of Air Force One
holding the hand of his wife, Hillary, before sharing the world's
spotlight with the pope. And on Monday, Clinton will unveil his
budget _ part intricate policy statement, part political broadside,
and a certain attention-getter.
</P>
<P>
   A less skilled politician or policy-maker, or perhaps a more
easily abashed man, could not pull it off. But Clinton makes it
look easy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In December, Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the House majority whip,
said, ``I'm suggesting that the president of the United States
cannot be believed, and I think it's reflected in his foreign
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in anchoring Clinton's defense to the Senate, former
Sen. Dale Bumpers of Arkansas countered with a list of foreign
leaders _ from Mandela to President Carlos Menem of Argentina to
King Hussein of Jordan _ who have praised Clinton's leadership in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   But the president seems to make the debate over his credibility
irrelevant by ignoring it and simply showing up for his job. On
Tuesday he met with the pope for about 20 minutes and covered a
broad range of subjects, from Iraq to Cuba to Mexico. The pope
urged the United States to remain engaged in the world, and Clinton
asked him to repeat that message to the American people. Mrs.
Clinton had a meeting with 15 cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton landed in the blue-and-white presidential 747, he
left it to his aides to handle the matters in Washington. In a
trailer by the runway, Joe Lockhart, his press secretary,
criticized the House prosecutors as ``falling back on their old
habit of playing politics.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Clinton gave no hint of concern. He was relaxed and
cheerful, even joking with the pope, whom he has met three times
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Church should buy the company producing the
film,'' he said, as photographers' shutters chattered madly, ``and
you could fund all the Catholic charities all over the world with
it. We could sell all the film the photographers use.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was any doubt that by virtue of his position, Clinton
occupied as lofty a plane as the pope on Tuesday _ or that the
pope, by virtue of being human, had some of the same needs as
Clinton _ it was erased by the sign marking a restroom near their
meeting room: ``President or Holy Father Only,'' it read.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
