<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEADS GIVE WILLIAMS A HEADACHE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE _ To bead or not to bead?
</P>
<P>
   If that is the question for Venus Williams, the answer is that
the headstrong young lady is not amused by any suggestion that she
change her hairstyle. Even though, extraordinarily, it cost her a
critical game and, admittedly, her poise as she faded from
prominent view at the Australian Open. She will continue with the
baubles and beads, but she may have to tighten up the act.
</P>
<P>
   Hoist by her own beads _ and the petard-like explosive strokes
of Lindsay Davenport _ Williams was victimized by perhaps the most
curious penalty point ruling in the game's annals. Surely a
coiffure had never caused its owner to be officially disciplined,
and trimmed of a point, but she head-bumped into the so-called
``hindrance rule.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as Williams has often said, ``I'm new and different.''
</P>
<P>
   Beads flew like birds from her renowned braids in the second set
of the long-awaited all-American quarterfinal clash Tuesday with
the game's newly anointed No. 1, Davenport, and an audience of
15,000 were themselves amused. At first.
</P>
<P>
   Clicking and spilling across the green asphalt floor as Williams
launched a serve, they were a rolling rainbow of pink, blue, green,
yellow, but mostly white, interrupting the point. Bead eruption
summoned laughs from witnesses as umpire Denis Overberg called,
``Let!'' The point would be replayed.
</P>
<P>
   At that juncture of Davenport's 6-4, 6-0, victory _ which
elevated her to the semis against Amelie Mauresmo, a startling
unseeded French teen-ager _ Williams was struggling. Down, 0-2,
30-all, she needed a break, not a bead breakup.
</P>
<P>
   The replayed point went to Davenport's fiery forehand passer
along the line, and Williams faced a breaker at 30-40.
</P>
<P>
   There was a gasp from the customers as Williams uncoiled into
another serve _ hers is the speediest in the female precinct,
clocked as high as 127 m.p.h. _ because accompanying a yellow ball
were more beads. The splatter was accompanied by Overberg's voice:
``Point. Game, Davenport. She leads, three games to love.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was furious. She stormed at the man in his highchair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said a lot of things to him,'' she recalled with a smile,
``but I can't remember what.''
</P>
<P>
   She demanded that the case go to the supreme court, in this
jurisdiction the tournament referee. Referee Peter Bellenger
appeared on court to hear her arguments, nodded politely, but
confirmed the umpire's verdict. ``It's the rule, no question, even
if it's not always enforced,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though played out to a closing bagel, the match was as good as
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost my focus, my composure,'' Williams said. ``It wasn't
fair. I'm not notorious for losing my beads. It's happened before,
and I wasn't penalized.''
</P>
<P>
   But she also conceded that Overberg had issued a ``warning'' at
the first jewelry overflow, saying, ``If this happens again you
lose a point.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately it was a break point, and the beads seemed pennies
from heaven for Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   ``That rule wasn't made for beads,'' pleaded Williams. ``This
was an isolated incident. But I learned a lesson, and there's no
need to be emotional about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The rule reads: ``If a player hinders an opponent it can be
ruled involuntary or deliberate. The first time (ball falling out
of pocket, hat falling off etc.), a let should be called and player
told that any such hindrance thereafter will be ruled deliberate,
and result in loss of a point.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently those naughty beads fall (or fell) under the ``etc.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport sympathized to the extent that, ``It's happened to me
when my cap fell off a couple of times. But the beads are a little
annoying _ and I'd think dangerous to her if she stepped on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, nearly beaten by Williams in the quarters a year ago
(1-6, 7-5, 6-3), said, ``She didn't have a Plan B to fall back on
when I got out of the first set.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport slipped four break points to seize that five-deuce
battle to 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   The breathtaking, rocketing baseline duels of the two most
imposing adversaries to grace a major championship (Davenport an
inch taller, 6-3, four years older, 22) usually went to Davenport.
Williams, five lengths behind at No. 6, couldn't come up with
anything to swerve Davenport from her self-assured broadsides.
</P>
<P>
   She needs to work on volleying and beads. Would a super
hairspray prevent beadspray? Not my department, but we've all had
bad hair days, haven't we?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
