<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9586 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH27-COX     01-26 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Partisan voting expected in impeachment trial
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After three-weeks of largely bipartisan harmony,
Senate leaders predict mostly party-line votes today in the first
of two crucial test votes on the impeachment evidence against
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Key Republicans said they had the numbers to defeat a Democratic
motion to dismiss the two charges against Clinton and enough votes
to depose three witnesses requested by House prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to end the trial with some bipartisan agreement to vote
directly on the articles of impeachment evaporated Tuesday after
Senate Republicans appeared to embrace a call by House prosecutors
to depose only three witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``My instincts say that would pass,'' said Sen. Paul Coverdell
(R-Ga.), a Senate GOP leader.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the prosecutors pleaded with the Senate to subpoena
and depose Monica Lewinsky, the central player in the impeachment
drama; presidential confidant Vernon Jordan and White House aide
Sidney Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors also asked for the opportunity to question
Clinton himself, a proposal quickly dismissed by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders insisted that the three witnesses could be deposed
in fewer than five days, keeping the impeachment trial contained to
a short but undefined duration.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's lawyers and several Senate Democrats warned that
any vote to depose witnesses, no matter how few, would lead to a
prolonged trial that most Americans do not want.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are spinning this notion somehow that this can be done in
a few days,'' said Sen. Byron Dorgan (D-N.D.). ``That's nonsense.
This will take weeks, if not months.''
</P>
<P>
   Senators deliberated the motion for witnesses late into the
evening Tuesday after rejecting a second bid by Sen. Tom Harkin
(D-Iowa) to open up the deliberations to the public. The 41-58 vote
was mostly along party lines, with three Republicans joining
Democrats in voting ``yes'' and six Democrats joining Republicans
in opposition. Sen. Max Cleland (D-Ga.) voted for it and Coverdell
voted against, Sen. Barbara Mikulski (D-Md.) missed the vote after
checking into a Baltimore hospital to undergo observation for flu
symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   At some points during the day, the confluence of events bordered
on the absurd. While White House lawyers were making the case that
no witnesses should be called, Clinton himself was in St. Louis
welcoming Pope John Paul II. CNN telecast a split screen showing
David Kendall, Clinton's personal lawyer, standing in the well of
the Senate while Clinton embraced the Pope a 1,000 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time Rep. Bill McCollum (R-Fla.) was making
the case to depose Lewinsky, Lewinsky herself decamped from the
Mayflower Hotel, where she has been holed up since Saturday, and
left for an undisclosed location.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement worked out three weeks ago, the Senate will
reconvene at 1 p.m. today and vote first on a motion to dismiss the
charges that Clinton perjured himself and obstructed justice. If
that motion fails, as most predict it will, senators will
immediately vote on the motion to depose the three witnesses
requested by House prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   If that motion succeeds, Republicans plan to offer a motion that
would put the depositions on a speedy track. Sen. John Chafee
(R-R.I.), a key GOP moderate, circulated language that would limit
the depositions to a maximum of four hours, with prosecutors and
White House lawyers allowed two hours each to ask questions.
</P>
<P>
   The depositions would be videotaped and the questions to the
witnesses could relate only to the official record _ not subjects
that haven't previously been covered. Under Chafee's timetable, the
depositions could be completed by Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans suggested that the videotaping could be a way for
the Senate to avoid actually having to call witnesses to testify in
person, which will require a separate vote.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats offered no official response to Chafee's proposal, but
they signaled that they will reject any witness procedure that they
believe limits Clinton's opportunity to gather evidence and call
witnesses himself.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the Republican timetable for witnesses ``unrealistic,''
Sen. Tom Daschle (D-S.D.), the Democratic minority leader, said
there were 54,000 pages of evidence that White House lawyers have
not yet reviewed. Daschle's chief lawyer estimated such a review
could take ``weeks,'' not including additional time to prepare
their own witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of that must be made available in order for us to be fair
as we begin to consider contributions made by witnesses,'' Daschle
said. ``Our colleagues need to clearly understand that if it's a
choice between expeditious and fair, Democrats are going to fall on
the side of fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House echoed the theme both on and off the Senate
floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you have one witness or 15 witnesses, there will still
be a need for extended discovery,'' said White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart, traveling with the president in St. Louis. White House
lawyers do not plan to make their own witness list public until
after the Senate vote.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm (R-Texas) accused Democrats of posturing simply
to maintain the pressure on Republican moderates, who are leery of
dragging out the trial by deposing witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think their threats are meaningless,'' Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   The hardening positions on the part of both Republicans and
Democrats on the issue of witnesses was the latest signal Tuesday
that the impeachment trial is entering a new phase.
</P>
<P>
   Senators from both parties have congratulated each other on the
relative calm and cooperation that has characterized the trial so
far, but now some are beginning gird themselves for a period of
heightened partisan confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ron Wyden (D-Ore.) said he feared that partisanship would
escalate like a nuclear arms race, spiralling ``up and up.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry said he thought that Republicans had seized on
their first exit plan by promoting only three witnesses who would
be deposed quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to finish it on their terms,'' Kerry said. ``But it
may not be on their terms....They cannot dictate the president's
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there appeared to be no love lost between the House
prosecutors and Senate Republicans, who repeatedly told them in no
uncertain terms that any more than three witnesses would not be
supported in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had to narrow our requests down at the urgent request of
well-meaning senators who really don't want any witnesses at all,''
said Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) with more than a trace
of sarcasm.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
