<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9587 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-BLUMENTHAL-BO     01-26 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-BLUMENTHAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL WATCHERS WONDER: WHY BLUMENTHAL? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the end, Betty Currie got dumped for Sidney
Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   Republican prosecutors Tuesday said they want to call
Blumenthal, assistant to President Clinton, as one of three
witnesses on their truncated wish-list in the Senate impeachment
trial. The move surprised many legal scholars who viewed Currie,
Clinton's personal secretary, as a much more important witness.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal, a journalist turned presidential adviser, was one of
the aides to whom Clinton first denied having a sexual relationship
with Monica S. Lewinsky after the scandal became public last Jan.
21.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say his testimony would help shed light on Clinton's
efforts to obstruct justice by proving the president lied to his
aides knowing that they might be called to testify before the grand
jury and showing that the president, by depicting her to Blumenthal
as a ``stalker,'' may have been trying to conceal the true nature
of the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall, Clinton's personal attorney, said there was no
reason to call Blumenthal ``except to try to embarass the president
by the presentation of testimony from a member of his senior
staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal's attorney, William A. McDaniel, said in an interview
that ``Sidney has no objections under the proper circumstances to
testify. He would be glad to.''
</P>
<P>
   McDaniel added: ``I know what he's testified to and so does
everybody else, and I don't know why they want to get at it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The other two witnesses prosecutors want to call, should the
Senate allow it, are Lewinsky and Washington power broker Vernon E.
Jordan Jr., Clinton's confidant and golfing buddy. These two
witnesses have been widely expected to be summoned to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Peter J. Wallison, a White House counsel to President Reagan
during the Iran-Contra affair, said the decision to call Blumenthal
was ``puzzling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I could understand bringing him in if Currie was invited,'' he
said. ``I can't understand inviting him without Currie, because I
think she is more important, at least as I understand the case,
more important than he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen A. Saltzburg, a law professor at George Washington
University, also questioned the wisdom of the House prosecutors
wanting to depose Blumenthal and call him as witness, noting that
Blumenthal is one of the most impassioned defenders of the
president and First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton as can be found at
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Brandeis University, Blumenthal joined the White
House staff in the summer of 1997, after a journalism career that
began in Boston and included work as a writer for the New Yorker,
the New Republic and the Washington Post. He is considered
especially close to the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Saltzburg suggested Blumenthal was called because Republican
prosecutors ``don't have anywhere else to go,'' and Currie's
``memory got worse and worse every time she appeared before the
grand jury'' investigating whether Clinton covered up his
relationship with the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Rose O'Sullivan, a criminal law professor at Georgetown
University Law Center, said of Blumenthal: ``If that's one of their
top three, then you have to wonder how strong there case is.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Currie would have been a more logical choice because
her testimony seemed to change over time, making it useful to call
her in, nail her down on her story and subject her to
cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps they don't like the idea of calling two
African-Americans'' said O'Sullivan, referring to Jordan and
Currie, both of whom are black.
</P>
<P>
   But Leonard Garment, who was a White House counsel to President
Nixon during Watergate, disagreed. ``It was smart of them to call
Blumenthal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Citing Clinton's reference to Lewinsky as a stalker in his
conversation with Blumenthal, Garment suggested that these
misleading buttressed the case for obstruction of justice. ``That
was really bad stuff, very different from anything that has been
said or suggested. It's clear cut.''
</P>
<P>
   In making the case to call Blumenthal, House prosecutor James E.
Rogan of California told senators that, ``The White House contends
before this body that the president did nothing to obstruct their
investigation. The evidence shows that he did.''
</P>
<P>
   According to House prosecutors, Clinton told Blumenthal the same
day news surfaced of his affair with Lewinsky that she came on to
him and made a sexual demand. Clinton stated that he rebuffed
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also told Blumenthal that Lewinsky had ``threatened''
him, saying she would tell people they had had an affair, and that
she was known as a ``stalker'' among White House aides.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan said Blumenthal's grand jury testimony came before Clinton
admitted the affair with Lewinsky. He said prosecutors also want to
know of a ``potential plan to destroy Monica Lewinsky if she ever
decided to cooperate with law enforcement authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   McDaniel, Blumenthal's attorney, said such allegations were
based on ``just speculation. They have no basis for it in fact.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
