<SLUG> BC-FBN-DENVER-FEATURE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sharpe tongue tireless
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The incident that informed Denver's Shannon Sharpe he
had an uncontrollable proclivity for, well, running his mouth,
occurred when he was in elementary school. He was around 7 or 8,
and no one was talking to him, but the urge came to interject, and
he did. He hasn't shut up since.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a speech class,'' Sharpe said Tuesday at the Super
Bowl's Media Day. ``This guy named Johnny was reading, and the
teacher said, 'No, student, don't you help him. Let me help him.'
She wanted him to sound the words out.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so, he got to a word he couldn't pronounce, and the
teacher said, 'OK, Johnny, it sounds like? Sounds like?' So I said,
'It sounds like Johnny can't read.' She said to me: 'Shannon
Sharpe, you get out of the class. Get out of class.'''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Broncos treated the barrage of media as if they were
in class. They had been through it before _ last year in San Diego
_ so it was more business as usual than an annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   For Sharpe, who grew up in the tiny town of Glenville, near
Savannah, business as usual means talking. And talking. And ...
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, he enjoys the give and take.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the best blocking tight end in the NFL because my back
(Terrell Davis) got 2,000 yards behind me,'' Sharpe said. ``No one
else got 2,000 yards, so that makes me the best tight end in the
game. People said, 'Shannon Sharpe is the best catching tight end
in the game.' But they say 'Brett Favre is the best quarterback.'
They don't say, 'Brett Favre is the best handoff quarterback.' So,
why label me?''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe could go on and on _ and did. But his teammates,
especially the offensive line, have chastised him for dishing out
nasty lyrics to defenders that do not line up against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it irritates you,'' offensive lineman Mark Schlereth
said. ``Shannon always wants to trash talk against a guy he's not
playing against. We tell him, 'Don't start a fire under my guy.'
He's been better about it (recently).''
</P>
<P>
   Considering his Sharpe tongue, it's a wonder it was the Falcons'
Ray Buchanan who issued the guarantee of victory, instead of the
rangy tight end. But Sharpe did say to the Dolphins during a
playoff game on Jan. 9: ``What's it feel like to have the Super
Bowl in your house and not be invited?''
</P>
<P>
   He said he omits mothers, girlfriends and wives from his trash
talking during games; everything else is fair game. ``If you have a
deformity, yes, I will talk about it,'' he said. ``Anything to get
into someone's head. So, I'll be talking Sunday. Bet on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Bunn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
