<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHWAY-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOCK TO REPLACE DUMMIES IN TV ADS ON SEAT BELTS
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Convinced that friendly persuasion has reached its
limit, the Transportation Department is switching to shock in its
effort to convince people to wear seat belts. The department's new
television advertisements drop the clownish crash-test dummies
Vince and Larry, which have been smashed in countless
advertisements, in favor of the everyday activities of live actors
who, in the last seconds of the advertisement, fall prey to
heart-stopping crashes.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisements begin soft and friendly, like those for
long-distance telephone service, but end abruptly with a crash. In
one, a husband on a midnight run to buy the ice cream that his
pregnant wife craves is hit by an oncoming car when he backs out of
the driveway. Another features teen-age girls in a convertible and
two boys in a sedan, all giggling and pointing as they cruise down
a street, until the boys' sedan is struck by a speeding van.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't see that coming?'' says the caption. ``No one ever
does. Buckle up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Advertising Council plans to produce a series of such spots
after deciding, along with the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration, that Vince and Larry were not reaching the
one-third of the population _ mostly young males _ that still does
not wear seat belts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince and Larry are dead,'' said Kenneth Ulmer, a spokesman
for the council. But they will continue to appear in time slots
when small children are likely to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ricardo Martinez, the administrator of the highway agency,
said studies show that many people do not wear seat belts because
``they believe they are in charge and nothing will happen to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get a bit of reality out there so people understand
they're not in charge and it can happen to anyone,'' added
Martinez, a former emergency room physician.
</P>
<P>
   Seat belt use has reached a plateau, at about 68 percent for
front-seat occupants. The federal government and private campaign
organizers have been influenced by Australian television
advertisements, truly gory by American standards, that officials
there say have helped cut accident rates among young drivers. Those
spots show dead bodies and a crash survivor struggling to learn how
to walk.
</P>
<P>
   The new American advertisements, which will appear in February,
tread a fine line. Emily Soell, a member of the committee of
outsiders that reviews Advertising Council public service
announcements, said they went through several editings. ``We had to
bring them to a point where it really was believable, and it wasn't
just so depressing that you would turn off and go into denial,''
said Ms. Soell, the chief creative officer of Draftworldwide, an
advertising agency in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The new advertisements face a challenging task, said Dr. Jay
Winsten, associate dean and director of the Center for Health
Communication at the Harvard School of Public Health. ``The
seat-belt issue is not really on people's radar screen right now,''
he said. ``The biggest challenge is to get it back on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
