A9592 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DENVER27-COX     01-26 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DENVER27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atwater bats down talk of his decline
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Even before he put pen to paper, Steve Atwater knew a
five-year contract was a stretch when he signed it in 1995. He was
29, played the game as violently as it can be played and understood
that retirement was perhaps only one collision away.
</P>
<P>
   And so that time had appeared to come in November. Atwater had
been slow to come around from offseason surgeries on both shoulders
_ making five total, plus two on his knees _ and the Broncos had
started benching their captain and seven-time Pro Bowl safety on
third down for second-year man George Coghill. A final year
remained on his contract at a non-guaranteed $2.6 million. But even
if it looked like the end of the road, Atwater wasn't going to give
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothered me somewhat,'' he said. ``George is a friend of
mine, and I was supporting him as much as I could. But that really
wasn't a motivation for me... I don't regret any of it. It was just
something I went through.''
</P>
<P>
   In short order, Coghill was back on the sideline, and Atwater
returned to a form that got him to the Pro Bowl for the eighth
time. He began to feel better. In the postseason, he has been
active, causing two fumbles in the AFC title game with the New York
Jets; the second came in a fourth-quarter collision with Alex Van
Dyke, and Bill Romanowski recovered to secure the victory.
</P>
<P>
   When the retirement questions come now, he smiles at them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about it just a little bit,'' he said. ``My
body's feeling good. I don't feel like this will be my last year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every once in a while, you may look at a guy, and he may not
have had a great offseason program and he doesn't come in in great
shape,'' Broncos coach Mike Shanahan said. ``Or maybe he goes
through a preseason where he isn't as sharp as he was the year
before. And he's got to push it a little harder. Maybe he's a year
older and he's lost a step.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you can't do is lose that edge. Steve Atwater is a smart
safety. He understands the game. He's a worker, and he does
everything he can to prepare himself to play his best. And that's
why he's had an excellent year.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no denying Atwater has lost that step, but he and
Romanowski remain the top names on a defensive unit that has
allowed only 98 rushing yards in its past four games. Still a
ferocious hitter, he is a man the Falcons have to beat for a chance
to win on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just adds a dimension,'' linebacker John Mobley said.
``Steve's still one of the elite players in the league, one of the
classiest guys you ever would want to meet. He's meant a great deal
to all the younger players coming up. He's someone to look up to.''
</P>
<P>
   Still.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
