</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPLIT VOTE UNCONSTITUTIONAL, SCHOLARS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Impeach-Collins)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is a novel exit strategy for ending the Senate's
impeachment trial. It offers the opportunity for lawmakers to
harshly penalize President Clinton for his conduct _ something
members of both parties favor _ while bowing to the political
reality that there aren't enough votes to remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, legal scholars said Tuesday, is it's
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wrong, that's all there is to it,'' said Akhil Amar, a
Yale law professor and constitutional scholar.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, Republican Senators Orrin Hatch of Utah and Susan
Collins of Maine have raised the possibility of splitting the final
impeachment vote. The first would be on whether Clinton committed
perjury or obstruction of justice. If found guilty on either
charge, a separate ballot would be held on removing the president
from office.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would permit Republicans to end the trial saying they
had tried to impose as severe a penalty on the president as
possible given the political realities of 45 Democratic senators
and huge public support for Clinton. At the same time, they would
be bowing to those realities by leaving the popular Democratic
leader in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and many Democrats seem unlikely to support the
split-vote idea because it gives the GOP majority too much of what
it wants. But whatever the political considerations, legal scholars
said, the idea should be rejected because it is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a perversion of the Constitution,'' said Margaret
Russell, who teaches at the University of Santa Clara Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Added Lawrence Sager of the New York University Law School: ``If
they even tried to do this, the precedent would be a very dangerous
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Article 2 of the Constitution sounds unequivocal: the president
or vice president ``shall be removed from office on impeachment for
and conviction of treason, bribery or other high crimes or
misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Joseph Isenbergh, a professor at the University of
Chicago Law School, sees some wiggle room in that phrasing.
Isenberg, who teaches tax law, waded into the constitutional debate
over impeachment with a recent paper arguing that removal from
office was mandated only if the accused was found guilty of high
crimes and misdemeanors _ but not if the crimes were determined to
be of lesser gravity.
</P>
<P>
   Some senators are using an offshoot of Isenberg's writing to pry
a political opening for concluding the trial without seeming to
have capitulated to the Democrats or having lost a partisan war to
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Further details were not available since no formal proposal has
been drafted and ultimately might not be. But a two-thirds majority
of the Senate, or 67 votes, presumably would be needed for either
conviction or removal.
</P>
<P>
   No public official has ever been allowed to remain in office
after being found guilty of impeachable offenses. Despite questions
about the constitutionality of the proposal, the legal analysts
said the senators probably could adopt the plan because no
individual or institution could stop them.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, the Supreme Court could step in, but past rulings
make it clear that impeachment is the sole purview of Congress.
Justice David Souter suggested in a dissent that the court could
intervene if lawmakers took an action that was ``dangerously
unconstitutional,'' but doing so would raise profound questions
about the separation of powers.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, who is presiding over
Clinton's trial, presumably could rule against any measure that
would permit splitting the final votes. Even if he did, however,
the impeachment process allows a simple majority of senators to
overrule the bench on any matter.
</P>
<P>
   Sager differs from many constitutional experts by not basing his
opinion solely on the Constitution's wording. The document, he
argued, should be subject to reinterpretation as social and legal
realities change.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, though, he said that detaching the conviction from
the removal from office would water down impeachment to the point
where it could become a tool for eliminating political opponents,
rather than a complex mechanism for removing elected officials
under extreme circumstances. ``It should be avoided at all costs,''
said Sager.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
