<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9596 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-BOS &LR;      01-26 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE EXPERIENCES DELIBERATIONS WITHOUT THE THEATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After weeks of anticipation, the Senate Tuesday
entered into its second night of closed session to deliberate its
most divisive issue: whether witnesses should be called to testify
in the impeachment trial of the president.
</P>
<P>
   But there was another pressing matter. No microphones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have, out of 100 members, a certain percent who are hard of
hearing,'' said Senator Bob Kerrey.
</P>
<P>
   During the Monday meeting, Senator Herbert Kohl agreed: ``We had
to strain.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, senators fixed the problem themselves, hooking up
the sound system and, in a rare step, taking turns speaking from
the Senate well. It was one of a number of unfamiliar elements they
faced during secret deliberations, and as they emerged, most agreed
it made for a somewhat bizarre atmosphere in the chamber _
particularly as senators spoke to each other instead of the
television cameras scattered around the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stripped away the theater because the only people we were
playing to were our colleagues,'' Senator Chuck Hagel, a Republican
from Nebraska, said Tuesday afternoon. ``There was a lot of
listening going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversation flowed more freely _ even if at a quieter volume _
in part because of a formal restriction forbidding participants
from talking about it afterward. A senator can be expelled from
Congress for violating the gag rule.
</P>
<P>
   With guards positioned outside the doors, Chief Justice William
H. Rehnquist presided over the deliberations as he has over the
trial itself, calling senators to speak in turn. Nearly everyone
who spoke Tuesday night used the allotted time _ 10 minutes at
first, then five minutes, after senators agreed to shorten the time
as the session wore on _ indicating that publicity is not the only
reason the Senate has a reputation for verbosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're talking as much,'' Senator Edward M. Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Each night they broke for dinner, and on Monday, the meals were
divided along partisan lines, as Republicans feasted on fried
chicken and Democrats ate pizza, ordered by California Senator
Dianne Feinstein, aides said. By Tuesday night, the snacks had
dwindled to more meager fare: pretzels, apples and cookies brought
in by Senate staff.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of food did not deter them from pontificating; Tuesday
night, the session lasted more than three hours, the time allotted
by an earlier consent decree, with only a single 10-minute break.
</P>
<P>
   The talk was ``more personal, more frank,'' according to Senator
John F. Kerry. It was ``a little bit like being in the back room of
a committee,'' Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a Democrat from New
York, agreed. Senator Robert F. Bennett, a Republican from Utah,
described the tone as ``very civil and very frank.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some advantages to keeping you folks out,'' Bennett
told a reporter Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey, a Nebraska Democrat, joked that ``it's only useful
because it might make the case that we ought to get the televisions
out of there permanently.'' Kerrey, like 42 other Democrats, had
voted a day earlier to open the sessions to the public following a
motion by Senator Tom Harkin, Democrat of Iowa _ and said the real
value in the secrecy was observing his publicity-starved
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do I look? Who do I talk to? Where's my staff to tell me
what to say?'' cracked Kerrey, mocking the senators lost in a world
without television. ``It's fun to watch human beings behave when
there's not cameras on them.''
</P>
<P>
   And, despite the enthusiasm for the exchanging of views, the
numerous speeches did not appear to change any minds. As they head
into a vote Wednesday on whether witnesses are to be called, few
senators expect the Republican majority to fail _ a victory that
was effectively secured days before.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl, a Democrat of Wisconsin, said the closed-door sessions
were not ``anymore useful in private than it would have been in
public.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't anything said that could have been said in open
session,'' said Kohl. ``Had you heard them, you would have just
said, `OK.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
