<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9597 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MEDIADAY-COX     01-26 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MEDIADAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Super hype begins with Media Day
 &HT;    By Joe Capozzi
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It started with a police escort up Interstate 95 and a
welcome by a shirtless guy called Barrel Man. It ended 12 hours
later in a beery swing by the bay with Big Bad Voodoo Daddy.
</P>
<P>
   In between, there were football players _ wearing a dog collar,
playing a board game and answering questions like, ``What makes a
guy like you cry?''
</P>
<P>
   We're talking, of course, about Media Day, the annual ritual of
Super Hype that unfolded Tuesday at Pro Player Stadium where a
no-holds-barred circus of more than 1,500 journalists squared off
against the rosters of the Denver Broncos and Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   It's meant as a way for the media to take the pulse of the NFC
and AFC championship teams in the week leading up to the biggest
sporting event of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But the reality of Media Day is this: ``It has nothing to do
with football,'' said Broncos tight end Byron Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   OK, it has a little to do with football. But ``it's really kind
of a free-for-all,'' said former Super Bowl executive director Don
Weiss, who has watched Media Day evolve from its 1967 precursor
``Photo Day,'' which attracted 338 media members before the first
NFL Championship game.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days, Media Day often meant reporters entering a
hotel lobby to find a list with a player's name and room number.
``And we'd go knock on his door,'' recalled Vito Stellino of the
Baltimore Sun, a veteran of 25 Media Days.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a light-flashing motorcycle cop led a caravan of bus
coaches from the Hyatt Regency Hotel in downtown Miami _ the
headquarters for the 3,000-strong contigent of media accredited for
Super Bowl XXXIII _ and through rush-hour traffic toward the site
of Sunday's big game.
</P>
<P>
   At Pro Player Stadium, the throng of reporters armed with
microphones, cameras and step ladders (for unobstructed
photographs) was herded through Gate H, the perch of Tim McKernan,
a Broncos fan known as Barrel Man because of his attire.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``a cattle call,'' as one NFL official put it, the herd of
media lumbered onto the field. Lining the sidelines was a flea
market of 10 booths, some with rows of aluminum bleachers erected
in front, each with a sound speakers and a metal pole displaying a
player's name.
</P>
<P>
   Each team was given an hour, which was kept down to the last
second by a ticking clock on the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   There's Shannon Sharpe, the outspoken Denver Broncos receiver,
sitting like a clown on a dunking platform, talking about his
chlildhood heros. ``Jack Lambert. Jack didn't have any teeth. I
liked him because I didn't have any teeth at the time, either.''
</P>
<P>
   There's Ray Buchanan, the Atlanta Falcons corner back, wearing a
silver-studded dog collar around his neck. ``I bought it at the pet
store. Everyone says we're the underdogs.''
</P>
<P>
   There's John Elway, the Denver Broncos quarterback, who's barely
visible through the skyline of reporters tippy-toed on bleachers
and step ladders but can be heard answering a question for Austrian
television crew: ``This is what American football is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Wandering in the stands and on the sidelines are dozens of more
players, many aiming $700 video cameras at the media frenzy.
``Gotta take home some memories,'' said Cyron Brown, a Broncos
defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   There's Chamberlain, the Denver tight-end, sitting on a
rolled-up tarp, engaged in a game of Operation with teammate Keith
Burns. There's broadcaster Sal Paolantonio of ESPN interviewing
broadcaster Chris Berman of ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   There's Falcons defensive end John Burrough conducting a live
radio interview from his cell phone. And there's cable channel
Comedy Central's own Beth Littleford asking Falcons safety Chris
Bayne: ``How dirty is your bird?''
</P>
<P>
   That was mild compared to some of the classics that players have
been asked at previous Media Days: To Washington quarterback Doug
Williams, ``Have you always been a black quarterback?'' To
Oakland's Jim Plunkett, ``Jim, as that dead father and blind
mother, or dead other and blind father?''
</P>
<P>
   One Atlanta writer earlier this week began a column, directed at
players about the media onslaught: ``While there's still time, let
me take a moment to issue a sincere 'I'm sorry' for what is about
to happen...''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the journalists at Media Day XXXIII asked about Sunday's big
game. And the cliches echoed out the loudspeakers over each other
in stereo _ ``It's David versus Goliath...'' ``It's the dream of a
lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   By 11:30 a.m., the reporters filed out of Pro Player Stadium to
write their stories and prepare for the evening's Media Day party
with swing band Big Bad Voodoo Daddy at Bayfront Park. Several
Denver players said the media seemed well-behaved.
</P>
<P>
   ``One woman asked me about the Monica Lewinsky scandal,'' said
Denver safety Eric Brown. ``I told her I didn't have an opinion.
But if we win the Super Bowl and I get to meet the president, I'm
going to ask him about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Capozzi writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
