<SLUG> BC-FBN-PARCELLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS TO SIT OUT PRO BOWL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Bill Parcells has pulled out of the Pro Bowl. The New
York Jets coach said Tuesday that team doctors told him he would be
better off if he stayed at home instead of joining the Jets'
coaching staff in Honolulu for the Feb. 7 games.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Belichick, the Jets' assistant head coach, will lead the
staff instead.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells had two physicals after the Jets' season ended with a
loss in the AFC Championship game at Denver, and both times doctors
advised him to stay at home and rest. Parcells said he was feeling
very run down, much more than usual, when the season ended.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells and his wife, Judy, went to their Florida vacation home
for at least two weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 2050EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9600 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-STODA-COLUMN27-CO     01-26 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-STODA-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't believe the feud has ended
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ ``Bygones.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the one-word directive Ally McBeal office boss Richard
Fish issues whenever he wants the firm's lawyers to forget past
disagreements and move immediately on to new business.
</P>
<P>
   It's also what Mike Shanahan, John Elway and Dan Reeves _ Super
Bowl XXXIII's very own Bermuda Triangle _ would have everyone think
is an accurate description of how they view their own past
disagreements.
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe them.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan and Elway, as head coach and star quarterback,
respectively, of the Denver Broncos, would like nothing better
Sunday night than to win (and win big) at the expense of Reeves,
who was once their boss as head coach in Denver but now looms as a
loathsome opponent in charge of the Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, too, would like nothing better than to stick it to
Shanahan and Elway.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why it's best to ignore the chorus of ``bygones''
coming from the unholy trinity and wait for the curtain to go up on
what should be a game stuffed full of venomous animosities.
</P>
<P>
   The abridged version of the Reeves-Shanahan-Elway history is
that they won three AFC championships together in Denver, but never
a Super Bowl. Reeves subsequently fired Shanahan, who was his
offensive coordinator, for what he viewed as conduct unbecoming an
underling. And he thought Elway was in cahoots with Shanahan when
it came to usurping authority. Reeves was dismissed himself a year
later, and the guess has long been that Elway had much to do with
the ouster.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan, obviously, later found his way back to Denver in
Reeves' old job, and last year won a Super Bowl with Elway.
</P>
<P>
   There's enough bitterness in all of this to fill a blimp and
float it above Pro Player Stadium even though all parties involved
are busy floating fluff.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves brought the whole mess bubbling back to the surface last
week after the Falcons won the NFC title, but has since apologized
``for opening those wounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway has said ``it's water under the bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan has gone even further: ``I'm glad it's over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Over? This isn't over. It's just getting started.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that would make Reeves happier than winning the
Super Bowl would be winning it while beating Shanahan and Elway,
whom he considers traitors to his, if not Denver's, cause while
they were working in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just suggest that if the Falcons win, Reeves will make
sure to Dirty Bird-dance on the fresh graves of two Broncos in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan and Elway, on the other hand, would like to extend
Denver's reign as pro football champions and do so while proving _
on a global stage _ that they never needed Reeves in the first
place. And going 2-0 in Supers without him compared to 0-3 with him
would be a ferocious kick in Reeves' teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just suggest that if the Broncos are ahead, 38-3, on the
Falcons and threatening to score late (as they were, you'll
remember, against the Dolphins a few weeks back), nobody's going to
be taking a knee in a show of mercy.
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe what you're hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe Reeves' apology ``for ever having brought it up.''
Why? Because it's at least possible it was a premeditated ploy
aimed at distracting the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe Elway's re-evaluation of his relationship with
Reeves when he says ``there were a lot more positive times in
Denver than negative ... a lot more.'' Why? Because he once said it
was ``hell'' playing for the man.
</P>
<P>
   And don't believe Shanahan's posture of goodwill when he says
what Reeves ``has done in Atlanta in such a short time is
remarkable.'' Why? Because he knows winning consecutive Super Bowl
titles is what would be remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe in ``bygones.''
</P>
<P>
   Believe something else.
</P>
<P>
   Believe that Sunday will prove living well really is the best
revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Stoda writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
