<HEADER>
A9601 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-PRICES-ART-2TA     01-26 1716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-PRICES-ART-2TAKES(1,025)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BRAZIL EFFECT ON COMMODITIES: FORGET THE NEW TRACTOR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Midwestern farm-belt states, including Ind., Ill., N.D.,
S.D., Iowa, Idaho) (nk) 
By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ From a pit on the floor of the Chicago Board of Trade,
Steven P. Bruce has been watching events in Brazil make the prices
of wheat and soybeans swing with impunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``All commodity prices have been slipping,'' he said, shouting
above a crowd of futures traders who were bidding down the
long-term prices of a variety of commodities. ``We will sell less
wheat to Brazil and they will compete with us on soybeans; it's
that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   While the overall economy remains vibrant, calculations by
futures traders like Bruce are an indication that the crisis in
Brazil is already reverberating in the United States _ both
positively and negatively. As the value of Brazil's currency, the
real, has dropped by more than a third in the last two weeks, the
wholesale prices of a broad range of goods, including wheat and
soybeans, have fallen 7 percent, according to key measures of
commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the benchmark Commodities Research Bureau/Bridge index
reached another recent low Tuesday, settling at 187.60, down 0.93.
</P>
<P>
   All this comes on top of double-digit declines in the last few
years. Prices for basic industrial products like steel have been
similarly hit by events in Brazil. These declines are sending new
shock waves through the United States' grain belt and industrial
heartland.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, the drop in wholesale prices means that inflation
_ which has been lower than at any time in recent decades _ is even
more likely to remain in check. But economists and retailers say
the lower wholesale prices will not necessarily translate into
broadly falling prices at the supermarket or the auto showroom.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, bakers, benefiting from lower wheat and flour
prices, will probably enjoy fatter profits. And auto manufacturers,
who get just modest gains from the falling price of steel, will
have a little more margin to play with.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even if consumers are not reaping all the benefits of the
drop in commodity prices, most economists see the outlook for
inflation as extremely favorable. And as long as most Americans
enjoy real pocketbook gains _ wage gains go further in the absence
of inflation _ the U.S. economy should continue to enjoy steady
growth this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to go back to the 1960s to see this kind of
environment,'' said Patrick Jackman, an economist at the Bureau of
Labor Statistics, which calculates the nation's consumer price
index. ``While lower commodity prices might not generally translate
into sharp declines in consumer prices, they translate into more
stable prices. And viewing it from the point of view of the
consumer, if you find that prices have not gone up, you're usually
satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, commodity prices started to decline well before
Brazil stopped defending its currency earlier this month. Financial
crises that began a year and a half ago and swept through Asia and
Russia had already begun to dry up the demand for commodities
worldwide, including some mainstays of the Midwest. And with steep
currency devaluations in countries like South Korea, American
exports have been competing against cheaper goods, forcing
depressed prices lower. Brazil's problems have deepened the crisis
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil is really reinforcing the slowdown in the global
economy,'' said James E. Glassman, a senior economist at Chase
Securities.
</P>
<P>
   At its simplest, Brazil's decision to devalue its currency means
that the country will reduce imports while exporting its own
cheaper products like iron and steel, soybeans, wheat and coffee.
That could cause lower commodity prices throughout Latin America,
forcing U.S. producers to sell their commodities for even less, and
in some cases much less.
</P>
<P>
   But while consumers and a lot of manufacturers have seen
benefits from lower commodity prices, many basic industrial and
agriculture-related companies have been suffering for months from
the various foreign financial crises.
</P>
<P>
   Cargill, the nation's largest private company and shipper of
much of the world's grain, has lost money in the last two quarters.
USX, which operates U.S. Steel, has idled one of its blast furnaces
in Gary, Ind., and laid off contract workers.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Steel, which supplies galvanized steel to the auto industry
that is usually sold on long-term contract, may have to lower its
prices to compete with cheaper foreign imports. The price of
soybeans, already down 40 percent from two years ago, may have to
fall further because of decreased demand in Asia and elsewhere. In
trading Tuesday at the Chicago Board of Trade, soybeans for March
delivery settled at $5.14 a bushel, down 3.5 cents, a four-month
closing low.
</P>
<P>
   Economists say that ripples from the slowdown overseas are
already causing losses for the nation's farmers. Problems are
particularly acute across the northern tier of states _ from
Illinois, where farmers are getting a cash price of just $2.07 for
a bushel of corn, down from $3.97 a few years ago, to Idaho, where
wheat is being sold at $2.69 a bushel, down from $5.49 a few years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This industry is not well,'' said Bill Flory, president of the
National Association of Wheat Growers, noting that many farmers in
North and South Dakota are putting their land up for sale. ``It's a
liquidation year for the industry, and there's not a lot of light
at the end of the tunnel.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Midwestern farmers are storing their corn and soybeans in
huge grain elevators, in hope that prices will bounce back. But the
Agriculture Department projects that 1999 could be just as weak as
1998, with farm exports expected to decline 10 percent from their
already depressed levels.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of looking ahead to next year's crops, many farmers are
retrenching, holding off on fertilizer purchases or that new pickup
truck, and depressing those merchants' business.
</P>
<P>
   ``If farmers don't make money they don't replace their
equipment,'' said Larry Mitchell, an Agriculture Department
spokesman. ``It means the local equipment dealer doesn't make the
sale. The people who haul the equipment don't have anything to
haul. The equipment maker doesn't make the equipment. This all
begins to ripple.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Deere &AMP; Co., the nation's largest maker of farm equipment, said
in November that it would lay off 2,400 workers, or 7 percent of
its work force after demand for its tractors and combines
plummeted. Now, with recession in Brazil, the company's problems
are mounting.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer farmers, for instance, are lining up to purchase Deere's
new, $160,000 Maximizer combine. ``People are cutting back,'' said
Dick Gady, chief economist at Conagra, the giant food-processing
company. ``Two dollar corn doesn't buy them a lot of combines.''
</P>
<P>
   Just about any company that makes heavy equipment for the farm
is being hurt. Even Caterpillar, which is the world's largest maker
of earth-moving equipment, has seen its profit growth slow.
</P>
<P>
   Cargill, which has more than 80,000 employees in 65 countries,
says that its once-vibrant grain trade is sagging, and there has
been weaker demand for food products in emerging nations. ``People
out there just don't have the purchasing power to buy more food and
better food,'' said Linda Thrane, a Cargill spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, the steel industry has asked the
government to impose higher import duties on Japan, Russia and
Brazil, asserting that they are dumping steel at a loss into
markets here. In the last few months, several smaller steel
companies have filed for bankruptcy protection. And bigger
steelmakers are reeling. On Friday, for instance, U.S. Steel
reported a 50 percent drop in profit from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go back to the 1970s, when the steel industry had it
tough, it looks like that all over again,'' said William Szakacs,
50, an employee at Gary Works, the U.S. Steel mill in Gary, Ind.,
that is the largest in North America. ``Things are getting tighter
every day. There's not a lot of steel to roll.''
</P>
<P>
   For other companies as well as most consumers, the commodity
collapse has brought benefits. Oil prices have declined because of
slowing global demand, cutting transportation costs for big
companies as well as for millions of Americans filling their tanks
at gasoline stations.
</P>
<P>
   Other commodities are more complex. In automobiles, for example,
steel is just one component. There is only $700 worth of steel in a
$25,000 vehicle, so prices will not be affected sharply, steel
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   And when it comes to food _ coffee, sugar, corn, soybeans for
cooking oil and wheat _ Americans are not seeing significantly
lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even though the commodity price of wheat has plummeted
40 percent in the last two years, bread prices have increased
slightly, according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Food companies and retailers contend that is because commodities
make up a small part of their expenses, which include labor and
manufacturing costs, as well as substantial processing,
transportation and marketing expenses. Many economists say that, in
fact, food companies and retailers, particularly those that operate
on low margins, enjoy heftier profits when wholesale prices drop.
</P>
<P>
   So while Flory, who grows wheat on 7,000 acres of farmland in
northern Idaho, sells his grain at some of the lowest prices in a
decade, a company like Interstate Bakeries, the distributor of
products like Wonder Bread and Hostess Twinkies, holds prices
steady.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question from a cost perspective, a bakery would
benefit from lower wheat prices,'' said Mark Dirkes, an Interstate
spokesman. ``Flour is the single largest commodity we purchase.''
</P>
<P>
   For every $1 decline in the wholesale price of wheat, he said,
Interstate plans to pass along a 1.5-cent saving to the consumer.
Still, despite the windfall from cheaper wheat, he said that the
bottom line declined at Interstate in the most recent quarter,
primarily because of fierce competition and higher operating costs,
including labor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
