<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE MOVES CLOSER TO CALLING 3 MAJOR WITNESSES IN IMPEACHMENT
TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related stories: IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-ASSESS,
IMPEACH-TWO-STEP, IMPEACH-SESSIONS, IMPEACH-LEWINSKY,
IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-REPUBS, HUBBELL-TAXES, STARR-LEAKS) 
(sw) 
 By R. W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fervent arguments from the prosecution and defense
counsel on the highly divisive question of calling witnesses in
President Clinton's impeachment trial, followed by a second
straight evening of closed-door debate, moved the Senate closer on
Tuesday night to a decision to take depositions from three of the
main figures in the protracted proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers, fighting a rear-guard action against new
testimony, warned again that witnesses would delay the trial for
weeks _ a tactic that brought irked resposes from Republicans.
David S. Kendall, who heads the president's private legal team,
compared the prosecutors to Mr. Micawber in Dickens' ``David
Copperfield:'' ``always hoping something would turn up.''
</P>
<P>
   On the brief list of potential witnesses, announced by House
prosecutors in the Senate on Tuesday morning, were Monica S.
Lewinsky, whose illicit sexual relationship with the president led
to his impeachment; Vernon Jordan, the Washington lawyer who sought
a job for Ms. Lewinsky, and Sidney Blumenthal, a White House
adviser to whom Clinton gave a false account of the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   All can be subpoenaed. The Republican prosecutors from the House
also urged the Senate to ``request the appearance'' of Clinton
himself, who was in St. Louis meeting Pope John Paul II. His
lawyers and spokesman have repeatedly said he will not appear, and
a subpoena would be of doubtful validity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two people who know the most about this are Monica
Lewinsky and William Jefferson Clinton,'' said Rep. Bill McCollum
of Florida, opening the prosecutors' arguments that they should be
heard again.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate will vote on two pivotal issues on Wednesday: whether
to dismiss the case against the president, as proposed by Sen.
Robert C. Byrd of West Virginia, a Democrat, and whether to
authorize the depositions from witnesses. The Byrd motion seems all
but certain to lose, but the proposal for depositions, top
Democrats conceded, now has a better than even chance to be
approved.
</P>
<P>
   Simple majorities are required on both the procedural issues.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's debate on witnesses was shorter but more
passionate, one senator said, than Monday night's on dismissal _
perhaps because the witness issue remains in doubt. The senator,
speaking on condition of anonymity, said the discussion was not so
much bitter or partisan as highly animated.
</P>
<P>
   At least at first, the three witnesses would not appear in the
chamber where the impeachment drama has now played out over 10
tense days. They would testify in private, with only lawyers
present, although the appearances would probably be videotaped. The
Senate would have to vote anew, after it had reviewed the
depositions, if it wanted them to testify in public.
</P>
<P>
   Facing probable defeat, with several Republican senators
threatening to vote against calling witnesses, the House
prosecutors, or managers, made two important concessions that
seemed to stiffen the resolve of some waverers. They agreed to
settle for depositions instead of live testimony, and they cut back
their witness list to what Rep. Henry J. Hyde of Illinois, the
beleaguered lead prosecutor, described as ``a pitiful three.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal's name on the short list came as something of a
surprise. He testified to the grand jury that Clinton told him,
contrary to the facts, that Ms. Lewinsky had stalked him, and the
prosecution has charged that the president did so in an effort to
pass lies on to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant omission from the House list was Betty
Currie, Clinton's secretary, who was involved not only in hiding
the gifts Clinton gave Ms. Lewinsky but also in a celebrated
episode where Clinton appeared to ``coach'' her, the prosecution
contends, in anticipation of her later testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall argued that witnesses would be superfluous, noting that
the House had called none during its impeachment proceedings. He
laid heavy emphasis on the extent of evidence collected by the
independent counsel, Kenneth W. Starr _ ``10,000 pages of grand
jury testimony; over 800 pages of olther testimony, such as
depositions; 3,400 pages of documentary evidence, 1,800 pages of
audio transcripts and 800-and-some pages of FBI interviews.''
</P>
<P>
   `I will certainly say this for Mr. Starr,'' Kendall said. ``He
is thorough. He is thorough.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the House prosecutors ``sang a different song,'' he
said, quoting several of them as dismissing the need for witnesses.
Hyde, Kendall told the senators, had said on Nov. 5: ``We believe
the most relevant witnesses have already testified at length about
the matters at issue.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM CAN START HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Kendall also played for the Senate several videotapes of Jordan
speaking to reporters after emerging from his grand jury
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came here in March,'' Jordan said on June 9, as
recorded on videotape, ``I said that I helped Ms. Lewinsky get a
lawyer, I helped her get a job, I had assurances there was no
sexual relationship, and I did not tell her to lie. That was the
truth then, and that is the truth today. And I have testified five
times, over and over again, to those truths.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors also asked the Senate on Tuesday to admit into
evidence a sworn declaration of T. Wesley Holmes, a lawyer for
Paula Jones, whose sexual harassment suit against Clinton led to
the revelation of the Lewinsky affair; an affidavit of Barry Ward,
law clerk to U.S. District Court Judge Susan Webber Wright, who
presided over the Jones suit, and telephone records of
conversations between Clinton and Ms. Lewinsky, particularly a
56-minute talk they had on Dec. 6, 1997, the day Clinton learned
she was on the Jones witness list.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, who was present at the time of Clinton's deposition in the
Jones case on Jan. 17, 1998, apparently commented on whether the
president seemed to be paying attention when he allowed his lawyer,
Robert S. Bennett, to make untrue statements about the president's
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky. Holmes' document, McCollum said,
was three paragraphs long and concerned his decision to call Mrs.
Currie to give evidence in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be expeditious'' if the Senate votes to admit this
evidence and to call witnesses, Kendall said. But he added: ``In
the event the genie is out of the bottle, we need time, we need
access to defend the president in the way any client ought to be
defended.'' And that, he said, would mean extensive ``discovery'' _
depositions and the gathering of other evidence.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM CAN END HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ed Bryant of Tennessee said the prosecutors had originally
planned to ask for as many as 15 witnesses. The three persons
finally chosen, he said, gave ``the broadest coverage'' of the
impeachment articles, because they could testify on seven of eight
charges of obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky could help resolve the crucial conflict in
testimony as to the nature of her sexual contact with the
president, Bryant said. Ms. Lewinsky has said under oath that
Clinton touched her breasts and genital area, and Clinton, also
under oath, denied it. Bryant pledged that she could deal with
``salacious questions'' without mentioning ``those words.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, she could testify on the gifts and who it
was who asked her to hide them.
</P>
<P>
   It fell to Rep. Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas to outline, in part,
the kinds of information the prosecutors would seek from Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, he said he wanted to ask Jordan and Ms.
Lewinsky whether she had given him an advance look at a false
affidavit she was preparing to file after he got her a job in New
York, and whether he had urged her to get rid of notes that she had
written to the president. On some issues, he said, Jordan had never
been questioned, because they came up after his last day of
testimony. Defense lawyers denied this.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth should be determined,'' Hutchinson contended.
``Justice should be accomplished. That is done not through lawyers
up here talking, it's done not through transcripts, but through
witnesses.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rep. James E. Rogan of California, another one of the managers,
rebutted the defense argument that no witnesses were needed now
because none had been called in the House, when the Republicans had
the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the constitutional responsibility of the House of
Representatives to act as the accusatory body in an impeachment
proceeding,'' he said. ``The Constitution gives the authority to
this body to try that case. This is the place for trial. This is
the place to determine guilt. This is the place to determine
credibility. This is the place for witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   As it has so often in this case, the last word went to Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   ``The threat of prolonged hearings, I suppose, is supposed to
make you tremble,'' the prosecutor said. ``It doesn't to me, but
then different strokes, I guess, for different folks.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Sens. Tom Harkin of Iowa and Paul D. Wellstone of
Minnesota, both Democrats, moved to suspend the Senate rules to
open the debate on witnesses to the public and to television
cameras. Once again, they failed, this time on a 41-58 vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
