<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.S.-ART-305&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PILOTS OVER IRAQ GIVEN WIDER LEEWAY TO FIGHT BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As a response to Iraq's concerted challenge to U.S.
aircraft, President Clinton has within the last month expanded the
powers of military flight crews to fight back when threatened while
enforcing the no-flight zones over northern and southern Iraq, the
president's national security adviser acknowledged Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our pilots understand, and our Air Force understands, that if
there are violations of the no-fly zone, that our response be not
simply against the particular source of the violation or source of
the threat,'' said National Security Adviser Samuel Berger. ``But
our response, as appropriate, will be against any of the air
defense systems that we think makes us vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger disclosed the change in policy at a breakfast for
reporters covering the military.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Department officials confirmed Tuesday that one of the
U.S. missiles launched on Monday had missed its target by at least
18 miles and struck a residential neighborhood in Basra in southern
Iraq. Eleven civilians were killed, the Iraqi government said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the four-day air campaign against Iraq in December, U.S.
planes have encountered nearly daily provocations from
surface-to-air missiles, ground fire and radar installations while
patrolling the zones over southern and northern Iraq, the Pentagon
says.
</P>
<P>
   The zones were set up to protect Iraqi Kurds and Shiite Muslims
from attacks by President Saddam Hussein's government. But until
Tuesday the Pentagon had not admitted that it had increased the
authorization to respond beyond earlier rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're responding in a different way, and it's not
tit-for-tat,'' said a Defense Department official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity. ``Now if you challenge us, you threaten us,
we'll respond in the way we think best reduces the threat to our
pilots.``
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The bombing in Basra on Monday highlighted the risks of the new
policy, which Pentagon officials said was aimed at protecting
pilots patrolling the no-flight zones.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the pilots may now attack a variety of
installations within Iraq's air defense system even if those sites
were not the immediate source of action against American planes.
</P>
<P>
   In acknowledging the errant missile Tuesday, Kenneth Bacon, the
spokesman for Defense Secretary William Cohen, said: ``We regret
any civilian casualties,'' although he said U.S. officials had ``no
independent confirmation'' that the missile had killed any Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, U.S. planes attacked five sites in the northern
no-flight zone after hostile action by Iraqi forces, the Defense
Department said.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Steve Campbell said Iraqi anti-aircraft artillery
systems near Mosul had targeted the U.S. planes with radar,
indicating a possible intention to shoot them down. In response,
two F-15Es dropped precision-guided bombs. Earlier in the day, U.S.
planes fired on three other sites in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The new bombing policy builds on what Berger described as the
increasing diplomatic isolation and resulting frustration of
Saddam. On Sunday, Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Said Sahaf
walked out of an Arab League meeting in Cairo when the assembled
diplomats urged Saddam to comply with United Nations resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam's growing antipathy toward his neighbors as well as his
attacks on U.S. planes, Berger said, ``reflects a man who is off
balance.''
</P>
<P>
   The new U.S. policy reflects the new situation after the
evacuation from Iraq of experts from the U.N. Special Commission,
which had made fitful progress toward finding and destroying
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Now with little hope of resuming the commission's mission, the
United States has fallen back on a policy of containing Iraq, to
keep it from using its weapons against its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   After giving up on persuading Saddam to live up to United
Nations demands for disarmament, the United States is again calling
for the overthrow of the Iraqi leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``While publicly saying this is a regime that should go, we're
reverting to a containment policy,'' said William Quandt, professor
of government and foreign affairs at the University of Virginia.
``But containment's not terribly sexy. We lived with it with the
Soviet Union for 50 years and it worked. But it takes patience.''
</P>
<P>
   And Saddam's actions and language consistently provoke the ire
and impatience of the United States, to the dismay of its allies.
Only Britain gave the United States full support in its air attacks
on Iraq in December. At the United Nations, Canada and France have
submitted alternative proposals for dealing with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   In Baghdad on Tuesday, Saddam pressed his case against the
United States and said in a message about the civilians who were
reported to have died in Basra: ``Your blood will not have been
spilled in vain. Your blood will give flower to the tree of
freedom, resistance and victory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
