<SLUG> BC-FBN-DENVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROMANOWSKI STILL ON A HITTING STREAK  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ When last seen on a football field, Bill Romanowski was
being ever so gingerly helped to the sideline to find his sense of
direction after losing it in a violent collision with Curtis
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   This was two Sundays ago. Romanowski, the Broncos' Pro Bowl
linebacker, had just stopped Martin, the Jets' running back, in the
American Football Conference championship game.
</P>
<P>
   But wait. Isn't this the same Bill Romanowski who has been
labeled ``the best-conditioned athlete I ever coached,'' according
to his coach, Mike Shanahan. The same Bill Romanowski who says,
``When you get a good hit on someone, it doesn't hurt''?
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that hit didn't look good,'' Romanowski said Tuesday.
``But I was fine. I was able to get my balance back.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he wound up as the game's leading tackler with 11
takedowns. Along the way, he produced a key first-half hit on
fullback Keith Byars that dislodged the ball deep in Denver
territory and resulted in one of six Jets turnovers that helped
propel the Broncos to Sunday's Super Bowl showdown with Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 32, having made the Pro Bowl for the second time,
and producing what, in his opinion, might be his finest season,
Romanowski will now use all his wiles and his guile to get the
upper hand on anyone in a Falcons uniform. Much will be spent
banging into Atlanta's 6-foot-7-inch, 270-pound tight end, O.J.
Santiago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to take a player out of his zone, any way I can,''
Romanowski said. ``Some guys, you get in their face and they start
reacting. I'll yell something about a family member, or something
personal.''
</P>
<P>
   But wait, this is the new Romanowski, so he added: ``Santiago's
a big guy and if I tried that he'd probably work even harder. So
I'll just try to beat him with great technique.''
</P>
<P>
   Romanowski said Tuesday that he remains contrite over the most
notorious incident of his career, one that has overshadowed the
fact that he has played on two Super Bowl winners in San Francisco
and a third in Denver. The incident occurred last season, during a
Monday night game against the 49ers, when Romanowski spit at
receiver J.J. Stokes.
</P>
<P>
   The action was spotted on instant replay, and Romanowski was
fined $7,500 by the league. Because Romanowski is white and Stokes
is black, the incident also took on racial overtones and
Romanowski's own teammate Shannon Sharpe, the outspoken tight end,
said he thought the linebacker had gotten off too easy.
</P>
<P>
   The Stokes fine was the second of 1997 for Romanowski. The first
was $20,000 for a helmet-to-helmet hit against Kerry Collins, then
the quarterback for the Carolina Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of what happened last year, I'm a better person and a
better player than I was,'' said Romanowski, referring to the
Stokes incident. He spoke in his typical off-the-field fashion _
thoughtfully and softly. ``I vowed to myself and to my family it
would never happen again. When emotion is high, logic is slow.''
</P>
<P>
   As the strongside linebacker, Romanowski routinely has to handle
the opposing tight end, as well as perform the usual duties of
halting runners and receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Because Romanowski is so adept at what he does, the Falcons
decided to imitate him in practice, using backup linebacker Craig
Sauer as the stand-in. And what did Sauer do to Santiago? ``I held
him,'' Sauer said. ``Romanowski's very good. He knows the tricks.
You wonder how he does them. But he's a hard worker. You can see
him running around finishing every play.''
</P>
<P>
   Romanowski got his first two Super Bowl rings in his first two
seasons in the league _ as a 49er in 1988 and 1989. San Francisco
traded him to Philadelphia after the 1993 season and he stayed
there for two years before Shanahan brought him to the Broncos as a
free agent for the 1996 season. He proceeded to make the Pro Bowl
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought his personality was important to the football
team,'' Shanahan said in explaining why he recruited him. ``He
works out 365 days a year. After Sunday's game, he will work out
four hours.''
</P>
<P>
   One Falcon who knows all about Romanowski is the backup center,
Dave Widell, who was a Boston College teammate of Romanowski's,
whom he calls Billy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a typical Boston College guy,'' Widell said. ``It can be
summed up easily. They tend to be great interviews, great family
guys, someone you want to have dinner with. Once you got them on
the field, there's a switch. I was on the dirtiest players list in
Sports Illustrated. By dirty, if you mean do I love to play till
the whistle, yes, and I think Billy plays the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   When told of Widell's comments, Romanowski responded: ``I had a
scratch under my face mask where he tore at my face. I think the
way we play is typical of guys from the school. A lot of people
call me an overachiever. But if that's part of it, I'm guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Romanowski claims he doesn't even think of football as
a tough business. ``They say if you like what you do, you never
have to work a day in your life,'' he said. ``I've been on a
ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Robinson, the Broncos' defensive coordinator, recalled
meeting Romanowski and telling the linebacker that ``we wanted a
confidant who's an extension of the coaches, a guy in the core who
could explain what we're looking for.'' Romanowski became that
person, Robinson said, ``and it helped us.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the spitting incident, which happened in the
next-to-last game of the regular season. ``I talked to him about
that,'' Robinson said. ``I told him, `Be you and don't worry about
it.' I think afterward he started to worry what people thought, but
those around him knew who he was, it was him and his gamesmanship,
being his feisty self. You can't be less than what you are.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
