r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROW-SFCHRON &LR;      01-26 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 How to Tap Into Venture Capital Pool  &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  Venture capital is usually hard to get without a track
record and blue chip contacts. Can you suggest ways to find private
equity financing quickly and easily, preferably online?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  You probably won't snare $1 million by simply
broadcasting your business plan over the Internet. But there are
more than a dozen services specifically designed to post
information and introduce needy entrepreneurs to venture capital
firms and deep-pocket individual investors known as angels.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some online services you might start with:
</P>
<P>
   _ Garage.com ( &LR; www.garage.com &LR; ) calls itself a farm club for
venture capital firms. Since last October, the Web-based Palo Alto
company headed by former Apple Computer ``chief evangelist'' Guy
Kawasaki has been matching high-tech and medical science startups
in need of seed capital with investors.
</P>
<P>
   About 25 entrepreneurs contact Garage.com each day. But only a
fortunate few _ about 3 percent _ survive Garage.com's rigorous
screening process, says VP of Business Development Bill Joos. They
are referred on to a network of 130 venture capital firms, 60
corporate investors and hundreds of angels.
</P>
<P>
   Garage.com charges investors a membership fee. Entrepreneurs pay
no application fee but they do have to fork over a percentage of
the $500,000 to $1.5 million they may eventually raise.
</P>
<P>
   Garage.com also has started a monthly forum where entrepreneurs
make live presentations. At the end of March, it also will hold a
two-day ``Bootcamp for Startups'' conference in Mountain view
(cost: $395). Other Bay Area organizations that hold forums include
Band of Angels and San Francisco law firm Niesar &AMP; Diamond's Angel
Law Forum ( &LR; www.ndlaw.com &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   _ Venture Capital Online ( &LR; www.vcapital.com &LR; ), started by
Chicago venture capitalist Leonard Batterson, has an office in San
Francisco. This week it is launching a Web site that streamlines
the process of matching entrepreneurs with venture capital
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Among the nearly 30 early members who paid $2,000 to join the
venture capital clearinghouse are a unit of Allstate and Hambrecht
&AMP; Quist Venture Capital.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone can take a free look at the Web site, which includes
venture capital market information, capital raising guidelines and
other resources.
</P>
<P>
   Entrepreneurs who submit applications and business plans pay $99
to have Venture Capital Online screen, match and refer investment
opportunities to its members based on their investment preferences.
Entrepreneurs pay more for additional services plus a percentage of
any capital they raise.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of GROW27 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &UR;  &LR;  _ The Small Business Administration's Angel Capital Electronic
Network ( &LR; www.sba.gov/ &LR;   &LR; services/acenet.html &LR; ), is an Internet
listing service that is designed to link entrepreneurs looking for
$250,000 to $5 million with accredited investors, accountants and
securities attorneys nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The government-sponsored program also provides links to
university and nonprofit organizations that can help develop
business plans.
</P>
<P>
   Hiring on the Cheap
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are ways a startup operating on a shoe string can find
and recruit an energetic and experienced marketing assistant? We
can only pay about $500 a week and offer few benefits.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: Several books such as ``Small Business Kit for Dummies''
(IDG Books, $24.99) by San Francisco lawyer Richard Harroch, give
some pointers.
</P>
<P>
   You might not be able to afford an employment agency or
headhunter. But you probably can offer employees a ``bounty''
(perhaps a few hundred dollars) to recruit the right candidate. You
also might hire a temp and, if it works out, offer the person a
full-time position.
</P>
<P>
   Harroch says the tried-and-true method of advertising in
newspaper and trade magazines still works, as does posting
opportunities on your business' Web site or on job-related Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Use your Internet search engine to find these sites. They
include &LR;  www.careermosaic.com, www.intellimatch.com, &LR; 
 &LR; www.selectjobs.com &LR; ,  &LR; www.espan.com &LR; , &LR;  www.careerpath.com &LR; ,
Virtual Job Fair's  &LR; www.vjf.com &LR; , Monster Board's  &LR; www.monster.com &LR; 
and Online Career Center's &LR;  www.occ.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Posting job openings and company information on these sites
often costs $100 to $200. You also can access newspaper ads online.
For example, Chronicle classifieds (as well as stories) can be
found at  &LR; www.sfgate.com.  &LR; Many other papers post ads on
 &LR; www.careerpath.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   One of your best bets might be to use JobTrak
( &LR; www.jobtrak.com &LR; ). The Los Angeles company has partnerships with
850 college and university career centers and alumni associations
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to place an ad on one campus, the charge is $18 a
month. But if you want to reach all 40 Bay Area colleges, from
Berkeley and Stanford to Foothill to Cal State Hayward, the charge
is $145 a month. JobTrak posted more than 400,000 jobs last year,
and co-founder Ken Ramberg says you can target the colleges of your
choice and link your ad to your company's home page.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to  &LR; entrepreneurs(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;  or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
