<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9610 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MORTANDERSON-COX     01-26 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MORTANDERSON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Andersen's silent kicks
 &HT;    By Ethan Skolnick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Kickers are generally different, commonly
individualists. But Morten Andersen is extreme, the Henry David
Thoreau of kickers, who has seen the solar eclipse in the Guadalupe
Canal, hiked through the Himalayas on Marco Polo's trade route,
even seen monks levitate, though he concedes that may be
exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   He has been ''mentally naked,'' realized ''you're just a small
part of the world,'' gotten ''the sense of being on a planet,'' and
concluded that ''we're really dust to dust, we're small entitities,
and what we're doing here guys, in the larger scheme of things, is
not going to be defining.''
</P>
<P>
   It makes one wonder what this great Dane's doing here, in the
NFL, in his 17th season, in the twilight of a Hall of Fame-worthy
career. But wonderment stops when his starts, as he speaks in
transcendental terms about striking the ball, when his mind is
clear and he is ''just being.'' Kicking is his Walden Pond.
</P>
<P>
   ''You almost don't hear the ball making contact,'' said
Andersen, who kicked an overtime 38-yarder at Minnesota on Dec. 17,
the 26th game-winner of his career. ''It's so fluid and smooth. The
ball jumps off your foot, it's gone and it's end-over-end and
pretty. If you don't force it, it's a real treat. It's a lot of fun
when you hit the ball pure.''
</P>
<P>
   He shares these deep thoughts in English, the one of five
mastered languages he uses to wish Jean Baker a happy Mother's Day
each year. Jean and her husband Dale took him into their
Indianapolis home was an exchange student his senior year. Andersen
was born in Struer, Denmark, populated by 9,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''I came here to open my mind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So he didn't mind going with Dale Baker and his son to a
football jamboree on his 17th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a foreign exchange student, you don't really have much
information on a kid, just the front and back of a form,'' said
Baker, an offensive guard at Indiana St. ''He wrote that one of his
interests was football. Dumb old me, I know football. Well, he was
talking soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bob Wilbur's son Tim, a star quarterback and defensive
back, was supposed to be the kicker. But Andersen got a Saturday
tryout, and Baker recalls ''90 kids, lining up, bug-eyed, watching
this guy kick, trying to figure out why he was upset when he missed
from 50 yards.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Thirty yards, 40 yards, 50 yards, the things were still going
through,'' Andersen said.
</P>
<P>
   He was a kicking prodigy, if not a football one. Wilbur told him
to ''haul to the sidelines'' after kicking off, and Andersen did
more tumbling (on the gymnastics team) than he did tackling.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've never been a football player,'' Andersen said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Michigan State signed him to replace their graduating
Danish kicker Hans Nilsson, and Morten called his mother Hanne, to
say he was staying four more years. In 1982, Saints coach Bum
Phillips would call, asking if Andersen liked Budweiser and country
music.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen, naturally, would say yes. He sees putting his new
house together as a ''journey in itself,'' and says that talking to
reporters on Super Bowl media day was ''something I've visualized
for many years.'' He doesn't close his mind to much.
</P>
<P>
   Football, however, did stump him for a time. ''Have you ever
tried to explain our game of football to a foreigner?'' Baker asks.
</P>
<P>
   ''I got into college, and I figured it would be a good idea to
learn the rules,'' Andersen said. ''I thought it was a slow-moving
game. They were constantly stopping the game, it wasn't as fluid as
I was used to. As I learned the game, I became fascinated by it.''
</P>
<P>
   He has tried to introduce it to Danes, doing color commentary on
the past several Super Bowls. ''It's interesting calling the game
in Danish, because I could get away with a few things,'' Andersen
said. ''I'm not pretending that I know all the nuances of football.
I'm not John Madden.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Andersen would work off an American network's feed, and
need to explain why Madden was scribbling on a lineman's stomach.
''He could be talking about what the guy had for breakfast,''
Andersen said.
</P>
<P>
   American football is still ''not a big sport in Denmark,''
trailing soccer and team handball, according to Ekstra Bladet
reporter Troel Christensen, who came to interview Andersen. The
major Danish networks had balked at covering the game _ which airs
at midnight their time _ this year, until Andersen's kick beat
Minnesota. TV-2 outbid TV-3 for the rights Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Lassen, a Berlingske Tidende reporter, was an Danish
exchange student in Georgia. And a kicker. ''A 50-yard field goal
isn't that hard in practice, but under pressure,'' Lassen said.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen has kicked 35 field goals from that far, plus one from
60 yards and one from 59. Broncos kicker Jason Elam has a record
63-yarder.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope there are some big kicks Sunday,'' said Andersen, who
is bringing the Bakers to watch.
</P>
<P>
   If he misses a kick, he'll accept it as he did after a shank put
Jacksonville in the playoffs in 1996. ''I've realized that one kick
is not going to define my career,'' he says. With some kickers, it
has. Andersen called Scott Norwood's miss in the 1991 Super Bowl,
and now calls the reaction ``a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't carry ''mental luggage.'' He needs his mind for the
spiritual stuff, on trips like the one with friends through that
Guadalupe Canal in the Caribbean, where the moon lined up behind
the sun: ``I saw birds nesting, the sea became calm, almost a
pinkish hue in the sky, it was really bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   Bizarre?
</P>
<P>
   Thoreau in shoulder pads.
</P>
<P>
   Skolnick, writes for the Palm Beach Post
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
