<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9612 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOMMERCE-SFCHRON &LR;      01-26 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOMMERCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 E-Tailing's Rising Stars  &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Neither Matt Glickman nor Mark Selcow had a child when they came up
with the idea three years ago of launching an online company
focused exclusively on new and expectant parents.
</P>
<P>
   But Glickman and his wife were thinking about having a baby and
Selcow was familiar with the women's health market from his job at
a bio-medical company.
</P>
<P>
   The two decided to meld editorial content and commerce and
provide comprehensive information on preconception, pregnancy and
babies as well as health education and a full line of products.
</P>
<P>
   Their San Francisco company, BabyCenter Inc., has its sights set
on becoming the Amazon.com in its field _ dispensing information
about babydom and selling thousands of products from maternity
clothes to bibs and cribs over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The two are riding the boom in e-tailing, as it's called. And
Glickman, who now has a 10-month-old daughter, and Selcow seem to
have done a good job of corporate parenting so far.
</P>
<P>
   Both 33-year-olds have MBAs from Stanford. Both earned valuable
experience and made useful contacts in the real business world.
Glickman worked in marketing at Intuit, maker of Quicken financial
software, while Selcow worked for Amgen.
</P>
<P>
   With their experience and contacts they were able to get in many
doors. ``But we still had to sell our vision,'' Glickman said. ``We
got about 99 `no's' for every `yes'.''
</P>
<P>
   BabyCenter's start was a bit premature. Three years ago,
e-commerce was hardly a buzzword. But the two founders pressed
their point and rattled off favorable market data to support their
budding business.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. baby market is an $18 billion annual business, wedged
neatly between toys at $22 billion and CDs at $13 billion. In
addition, new parents are hungry for information and spend an
average of $7,100 in their baby's first year.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman and Selcow successfully won $13.5 million in startup
capital from respected venture capital investors including Bessemer
Venture Partners, Intel Corp. and Trinity Ventures. Sales and
advertising revenues are mushrooming. Its Web site
( &LR; www.babycenter.com &LR; ) has won the industry's ``Webby Award,'' and
it gets 10 million page views a month.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of ECOMMERC () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  On Monday, BabyCenter was one of more than a dozen companies
featured at Bessemer Venture Partner's e-Commerce CEO summit in
Menlo Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``We began investing in the consumer segment early because we
felt the major retail segments like baby products, furniture and
vitamins would start getting filled by the end of 1998,'' said
Bessemer general partner David Cowan.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of that market segment and the rise in e-tailing have
made for a strong combination. At Bessemer's conference, Ernst &AMP;
Young released its second annual Internet shopping study that shows
the number of retailers selling on the Web jumped to 39 percent
from 12 percent in the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers are getting more enthusiastic, too. More than half (51
percent) of online shoppers purchased at least five times over the
Internet last year, compared to only 17 percent the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse First Boston Director Lise Buyer noted that online
shopping this past holiday season jumped 230 percent to $8 billion
from $3.5 billion in 1997 and the number of online shoppers has
quadrupled in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the hype about its potential, however, online
retailing still represents only about 1 percent of retail revenues.
Ernst &AMP; Young notes that nearly two-thirds of consumers don't shop
online for fear of sending credit card information over the Net and
difficulty navigating around a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it projects online sales will grow to 9 percent of retail
sales by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   To win venture capital and ultimately become a stock market
success, Buyer of CS First Boston said it is essential to have not
just ``an online solution, but a better solution.''
</P>
<P>
   She also observed that online traffic is ``a means to an end,
not the end; you can't pay employees with page views.'' And though
``it may be important to be first, it is even more important to be
best.'' For example, Yahoo, the leading search-engine company, was
the third to go public.
</P>
<P>
   Besides e-tailing companies that target large consumer markets
like BabyCenter, eToys, Furniture.com and health supplement vendor
MotherNature.com, Bessemer is investing heavily in Internet
infrastructure companies and the business-to-business market.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrecht &AMP; Quist Internet analyst Danny Rimer believes this
so-called B2B market could outstrip the consumer market and be
worth $300 billion within three years.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of ECOMMERC () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Within a decade, Bessemer principal Ravi Mhatre believes B2B will
be a trillion dollar market and suggested if ``The Graduate'' were
filmed today, Dustin Hoffman would be advised to get into B2B
instead of plastics.
</P>
<P>
   Entrepreneurial business-to-business startups featured at
Bessemer's e-commerce summit included:
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Collabria Inc.  &LR; The Menlo Park company, which just merged with
the Corporate Stores of San Jose, provides an online solution for
automating the purchase and production of printed materials such as
business cards, data sheets and brochures. A recent survey by the
National Association of Purchasing Managers pegs commercial
printing as the biggest opportunity for e-commerce procurement
efficiencies after office supplies. Collabria's customers range
from 3Com to the University of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; National Transportation Exchange &LR; . The Chicago company has
formed an Internet site to match shippers and commercial carriers
and help fill half-empty trucks. NTE figures that trucks are
underutilized as much as half the time and the Internet could help
eliminate as much as $31 billion a year in industry inefficiency.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; SciQuest &LR; . The Research Triangle Park, N.C., company is the
leading Internet source for laboratory and scientific products from
test tubes to rubber gloves. It connects 3,500 manufacturers with
25,000 pharmaceutical, biotechnology, university and industrial
buyers and aims to grab a chunk of the $9.4 billion annual market
for scientific products.
</P>
<P>
   The third piece of the e-commerce pie, as seen by Bessemer
Venture Partners, includes ``infrastructure'' companies that help
the Internet run better and companies that use it to gain a
competitive edge. Bay Area startups in this category include:
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Tumbleweed Software &LR; . The Redwood City company has raised
$11.6 million in venture capital since 1996 to become the leading
provider of online document delivery. Its flagship product, Posta,
combines the reliability and control of overnight delivery services
with the speed and simplicity of e-mail. The company has signed
several distribution partners including United Parcel Service,
Pitney Bowes and the U.S. Postal Service to send certified
electronic mail across the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of ECOMMERC () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  _ &UR; Keynote Systems &LR; . The latest brainchild of serial entrepreneur
Umang Gupta, this San Mateo company has raised $8.5 million since
1995 and is the leading supplier of Internet measurement,
diagnostic and consulting services to companies that operate
e-commerce Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   With 70 computers around the world to measure Web traffic,
Keynote lets customers such as Amazon.com, Cisco systems and Wells
Fargo assess how quickly their customers get access to their sites
and how long it takes them to complete transactions versus their
competition. Gupta said Keynote plans to be ``the Internet
performance authority, what J.D. Power is to the automobile
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; NewChannel &LR; . &UR;  &LR; The Redwood City startup aims be the leading
provider of technology for prospecting and selling on the Web.
While most e-tailers let visitors ``pick and pay'' with little
customer support, NewChannel CEO Chris Risley said his company aims
to add human representatives to the Web sales process.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 4 of ECOMMERC () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
