<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9613 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALTAVISTA-SFCHRON &LR;      01-26 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALTAVISTA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Compaq Plans To Spin Off AltaVista  &HT;       
 By David Einstein 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Hoping to create a new Internet portal power and make a bunch of
money for its shareholders in the bargain, Compaq Computer said
yesterday that it is spinning off AltaVista as a stand-alone
company.
</P>
<P>
   The new AltaVista Co. will be based in Palo Alto, with a
development office in San Mateo. It is expected eventually to
employ up to 400 workers in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes one year to the day after Compaq
announced its acquisition of Massachusetts-based Digital Equipment
Corp., which developed the AltaVista search engine.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the acquisition, AltaVista was not viewed as one
of the linchpins of the deal, which brought Compaq Digital's
extensive service organization and its large-scale computer
business.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista was a money-losing operation quickly falling behind
other search engines such as Yahoo and Excite, which were busily
turning their Web sites into Web portals featuring news,
entertainment, shopping and free e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   For the past year, however, stock prices of portals have soared,
creating companies worth billions of dollars. Compaq decided that
it could take advantage of the exploding market by turning
AltaVista into a portal and positioning it for an initial public
offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clearly our intent to take it public,'' Compaq chief
executive Eckhard Pfeiffer told a news conference yesterday. He
said the spin-off ``will unlock AltaVista's tremendous value for
company shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he gave no timetable, Compaq officials say an IPO could
come sometime this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compaq looked out and saw what the market was bidding for
these kinds of assets, and they figured they'd be idiots not to put
it out and let the market have a field day with this puppy,'' said
analyst Rob Enderle of Giga Information Group.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq already has begun its campaign to beef up AltaVista and
make it competitive with other portals. Recently, it acquired
Shopping.com, the popular online shopping site.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, in conjunction with the spin-off, Compaq announced an
agreement with Microsoft in which AltaVista users will be offered a
version of Microsoft's Hotmail, a leading free Internet mail
service. They also will get instant messaging that Microsoft is
developing.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Microsoft agreed to use AltaVista as the
search engine on its own online service, the Microsoft Network.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say AltaVista, which trails other portals in usage
among Web surfers, has a long way to go to catch leaders Yahoo,
Excite, America Online and Netscape. But it does have a key
advantage the others lack: Compaq, the world's No.1 PC-maker,
installs a direct link to AltaVista on every home computer it
sells. Pfeiffer said those links have accounted for some 20 million
visits to AltaVista a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives them a resource the others don't have'' and could
vault it into the top ranks in short order, Enderle said.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq will invest heavily in adding content to AltaVista,
according to Rod Schrock, the general manager of Compaq's Consumer
Products Group, who will head up the new unit. ``We're going to
aggressively pick up the pace,'' he said, adding that AltaVista
soon will add entertainment and other information components to its
site.
</P>
<P>
   Schrock conceded that AltaVista probably will not be profitable
for at least two years.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq could have built a portal site without spinning it off,
he said, but decided that AltaVista would do better if it had its
own brand identity and access to the vast capital that comes with
going public.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, ``This is enough of a different business
model from Compaq's that we wanted to give it a clarity of focus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
