<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Apple Will Settle Case Of Tech Help  &HT;       
 By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Apple Computer has agreed to settle federal charges that it billed
thousands of consumers for technical support it advertised as free,
the Federal Trade Commission said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Apple will reimburse customers _ who were
charged $35 each time they called the firm for help beginning in
October 1997 _ and reinstate free, lifetime assistance for selected
computers and hardware peripherals sold from 1992 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC didn't specify how much the move will cost Apple, which
had promised free support as part of the Apple Assurance program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get a lot of complaints from individual users about
different brands,'' said Matthew Gold, the FTC lawyer in San
Francisco who worked on the case. ``When there is a pattern, like
we had with Apple, we investigate. They reneged on a promise to a
large number of consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   About 100 Apple hardware products _ including older Power Mac
desktop and PowerBook laptop models, defunct Performa and Quadra
computers, printers, scanners and digital cameras _ are covered by
the program. A complete list is available at
 &LR; www.ftc.gov/os/1999/9901/appendixa.htm &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   In its complaint, the FTC said Apple offered the free service
for products sold from September 1992 to April 1996 but in October
1997 began charging consumers a $35 fee for access to technical
support. In some cases, consumers were charged repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   But while millions of Apple-branded products were sold during
the four-year period, only consumers who called Apple's technical
help line and were charged $35 are eligible for a refund.
</P>
<P>
   ``For prospective purchasers of computer products, free access
to live technical support is especially enticing,'' Jodie
Bernstein, director of the FTC's Bureau of Consumer Protection,
said in a statement. ``Companies that make such offers have to live
up to their promises.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple told the FTC that it will send a refund check or credit a
customer's bank account for any amount paid for technical support
under the Apple Assurance program. The Cupertino company is
expected to begin payments when the agency's order goes into effect
in 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   Apple had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement is the FTC's second with Apple in three years.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1997, the FTC charged that Apple misled consumers when
it advertised that all top-of-the-line Macintosh models could be
easily and immediately upgraded to the new PowerPC desktop system.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of APPLE27 (55552 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Although the claim was true for many Macs, it didn't apply to
certain Performa models and the Mac LC. Their upgrades were not
available for a year. Apple agreed to offer discounted updates to
owners of the affected machines.
</P>
<P>
   Apple currently offers a limited, one-year warranty and 90 days
of free telephone support for most of its products purchased after
1997. Defective hardware can be returned for repairs to thousands
of Apple Authorized Service Providers nationwide, including
CompUSA, ComputerWare, Best Buy and other computer stores. The
company offers extensive technical support online at
 &LR; www.apple.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   After three months, telephone support costs $35 per incident.
Customers have the option of buying phone-support packets of three
calls for $69, or 15 for $340.
</P>
<P>
   Apple suggests that consumers call (800) SOS-APPL (767-2775) for
more information.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of APPLE27 (55552 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
