<SLUG> BC-MARKET-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARES ARE UP ON THE STRENGTH OF BLUE-CHIP COMPANIES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Better-than-expected fourth-quarter earnings reports
and stock-split announcements by a number of blue-chip companies
helped push stock prices higher Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   All major market gauges registered gains, with the Nasdaq
composite index rising to another record. The Nasdaq, far and away
the best performing index in January, jumped 64.10 points, or 2.71
percent on Tuesday, to 2,433.41, propelled by big gains in stocks
like Microsoft, Intel, Yahoo and Cisco Systems. The index is up
just under 11 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average gained 121.26, or 1.32 percent,
to 9,324.58. Announcements that IBM, McDonald's and Xerox are
splitting their stocks helped propel the blue-chip index.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index gained 18.33, or 1.5
percent, to 1,252.31. The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies
gained 3.22 points, or eight-tenths of a percent, to 425.33.
</P>
<P>
   And Thestreet.com's index of 20 Internet companies rose 23.51,
or 4.7 percent, to 520.10.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said the rise in Internet shares was caused by
expectations that America Online will easily beat earnings
estimates when it releases its quarterly report Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, a component of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, rose
9, to 155 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite the big gains in the averages, winners only
narrowly outnumbered stocks that fell in price. Traders and
analysts said this was an indication the market remained
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil, which is the biggest problem, is quiet right now,''
said one trader, who spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``When
and if the next shoe drops down there, this market is going to go
right back down again. But for the moment everything is kind of
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices surged in Brazil on Tuesday, with the country's
Bovespa index gaining 6.33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Richard McCabe, chief market analyst at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.,
said he was not encouraged by Tuesday's market action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that just over 100 issues closed higher than those
that closed lower on the New York Stock Exchange is a pretty
miserable performance when the Dow is up this much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are building a top on this post-October rally and
that we are in for a decline during the next few months that by
spring will bring the averages close to the lows they hit last
fall. That might complete a rotational, step-by-step bear market
that has been in effect for more than a year. About the only thing
it hasn't hit so far are the technology stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology shares, which slumped a bit last week, were stalwarts
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   IBM gained 3|, to 185|, after it said it would split its stock 2
for 1. Microsoft, which announced a 2 for 1 stock split on Monday,
rocketed 9 11/16, to 171 9/16. And Lucent Technologies, which had
been pounded recently on worries about slowing demand for its
products, gained 7 15/16, to 110.
</P>
<P>
   Among Internet companies, Yahoo jumped 39 1/4 to 351 1/4, and
Mindspring Enterprises, an Internet access provider, rose 14 5/16,
to 102 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies announcing stock splits included Xerox and
McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox, the copier company, gained 10 15/16 to 116 5/16 after its
fourth-quarter earnings report beat expectations and it said it
would split its stock 2 for 1.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth-quarter profits at McDonald's rose 8.8 percent from
year-earlier levels. The company also announced a 2 for 1 stock
split. McDonald's shares rose 3 1/6, to 78 15/16.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Drug stocks, which have been lower of late, recovered some
ground Tuesday on the strength of positive earnings reports.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson &AMP; Johnson gained 3}, to 82{, after reporting that
fourth- quarter profits before charges rose 10 percent. Merck
gained 6 1/2, to 144, after it said fourth-quarter net income rose
13 percent on sales of five new drugs. And Schering-Plough, maker
of the allergy drug Claritin, rose 11/16, to 52 5/8, after it
reported a 22 percent gain in fourth-quarter profits.
</P>
<P>
   Warner-Lambert did not release its earnings Tuesday, but its
stock gained 1 5/8, to 69[, after it said it will buy Agouron
Pharmaceuticals for $2.1 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Trading in Agouron, manufacturer of the best-selling protease
inhibitor to treat AIDs, was halted before the announcement. The
stock last traded at 56 13/16, up 3 21/32 from Monday's close.
</P>
</TEXT>
