</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GEORGE-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At Bowl, they're paying the Shell game
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The subject isn't always football at the Super Bowl.
Tuesday a group of reporters gathered a Pro Football Hall of Famer
in the baseball dugout at Pro Player Stadium to discuss the rules
of a different game altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The Shell game.
</P>
<P>
   It's a con, pure and simple, by the customary definition. Take a
pebble or some other small object and conceal it with such
dexterity and deception that the poor sap who believes he has found
the one shell out of three that actually covers the prize will lose
his bet again and again. Quite literally, he keeps coming up empty.
</P>
<P>
   And so it is with Art Shell, trusted assistant on the Atlanta
Falcons' Super Bowl staff. Not the poor sap part, of course. A
dominating offensive tackle during his playing days, this 260-pound
mountain of power and patience understands exactly what is
happening to him and so many other black assistant coaches around
the NFL. Team owners consistently find reasons to pass over them
when it comes to naming a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Qualified professionals, in other words, keep coming up empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to find excuses,'' said Shell, ``you can find an
excuse for any situation. Some teams have been saying lately that
they wanted to go with a coach who had experience calling plays.
Well, I didn't call plays before I became a head coach with the
Raiders. I was an offensive line coach.''
</P>
<P>
   And so he is today, getting top production from a Falcons' line
that features rookie Ephraim Salaam.
</P>
<P>
   At San Diego State, Salaam also was a 6-foot-7 basketball
center, nicknamed the ``Shaq of the WAC'' for his piledriver post
moves. Under Shell's guidance, the kid became an immediate force in
Atlanta, the first Falcons rookie since 1993 to start every game.
Tuesday he answered many questions about paving the way for Jamal
Anderson's 1,846-yard rushing season but paused often to speak of
someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even say how tremendous Art Shell is,'' Salaam said.
``He's truly a great coach in terms of football but he's also a
great coach in terms of if you ever need someone to talk to about
anything on or off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   On the field, the only thing that must be said about Shell is
54-38. That was his record as head coach of the Los Angeles Raiders
from 1989-94. And that career winning percentage, almost 59
percent, is better than Jimmy Johnson's.
</P>
<P>
   Off the field, he'll speak for himself, and against anything as
nonsensical as a league that is 70 percent black but has only three
black head coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't regret the guys who were hired,'' Shell said of a half
dozen former coordinators named to lead NFL teams since the regular
season's end despite a lack of head coaching experience. ``They're
all good coaches. I just believe there should be more opportunities
for qualified guys like Sherm Lewis and Emmitt Thomas. Just to go
and talk with a team is not enough. If a guy is going to talk, OK,
let's really talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Rhodes, the only black coach among the recent hires, has
guaranteed a place for Lewis and Thomas in Green Bay as his
offensive and defensive coordinators. He also has promised Lewis
the authority to call the Packers' plays, something he didn't have
under Mike Holmgren. A definite improvement, but still it must feel
like a consolation prize to Lewis after interviewing at Chicago.
The Bears thoroughly bumbled that process, announcing Arizona
assistant Dave McGinnis as their head coach before they had an
agreement and then turning to Jacksonville assistant Dick Jauron as
a fall-back choice.
</P>
<P>
   Shell, meanwhile, was penalized for being part of a successful
program in Atlanta. NFL tampering rules prohibit teams from talking
to job candidates until all games have been played by the
prospect's current employer. In Shell's case, the Falcons going all
the way to the Super Bowl removed him from consideration by panicky
owners who couldn't wait to settle their houses and head to the
golf course.
</P>
<P>
   The one exception was Cleveland, a reborn franchise granted a
special exemption to talk to anyone, anytime. Shell interviewed
there but Jacksonville offensive coordinator Chris Palmer,
considered a longshot at the beginning of the process, got the
Browns' job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a very strong urge to be a head coach,'' Shell said.
``I've never lost that urge. I understood what it would take for us
to have a chance to win with the Raiders but I didn't get the
chance to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Al Davis weren't such a notorious contrarian, there would
have been no opportunity at all. When Shell took over the Raiders,
he was the first black head coach in professional football since
1925. It shouldn't be this difficult, especially when owners
regularly fire coaches on a whim and then fill their positions with
such mindless haste.
</P>
<P>
   After all, when Shell was handed the Raiders four games into the
1989 season, it was because Davis had pulled the rug out from under
a kid coach who supposedly couldn't cut it.
</P>
<P>
   Some guy named Mike Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   Dave George writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 2100EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
