<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9620 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-CHAMBERS-COX     01-26 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-CHAMBERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eight Chambers of Commerce announce joint legislative goals
 &HT;    36th Texas Legistlature
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ In an unprecedented joint appeal, Texas's eight largest
chambers of commerce are asking the Legislature to spend more money
on education, job training and transportation and create new tax
credits to add fuel to the state's economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Metro Eight,'' an ad hoc group that includes the chambers
of Austin, Dallas, Houston, San Antonio, Fort Worth, El Paso,
Arlington and Corpus Christi, unveiled its five-point proposal on
Tuesday at a Capitol news conference. The chambers have coordinated
their lobbying efforts before, but this is the first time they've
hammered out a common legislative agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a synergy that comes form all of the organizations
working together, and obviously a much stronger voice before the
Legislature,'' said Glenn West, president of the Greater Austin
Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Work-force development is the business community's top concern,
West said, and three of the five proposals address education and
training issues. The chambers want lawmakers to raise salaries for
teachers from kindergarten through 12th grade, spend more money on
reading initiatives and pre-school programs, and funnel additional
dollars to fast-growing urban school districts. At the same time,
without offering specifics, they ask the Legislature to
``strengthen the financial accountability of school districts.''
</P>
<P>
   In the area of higher education, the Metro Eight proposal calls
for more money for two- and four-year colleges and universities,
and more scholarship help for middle-income families. It also calls
for increased state support of ``high-priority'' technical and
vocational programs.
</P>
<P>
   The group wants state lawmakers to substantially expand two of
the state's job training programs, the Skills Development Fund and
the Smart Jobs Program. The proposal advocates between $50 million
and $100 million a year for the Skills Development Fund, up from
the current $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Metro Eight is also urging the Legislature to pour more
money into transportation, and to make sure that gasoline tax
revenue is used only for building and maintaining highways.
</P>
<P>
   ``While public safety and security should continue to be
adequately funded, it is critical for the Legislature to address
our state's transportation-funding needs by refocusing the
dedicated gasoline tax funds for construction and maintenance of
our highways,'' the proposal states.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the group is asking lawmakers to create tax credits for
research and development and major capital investments. Leaders of
the chambers said many businesses decline to move to or expand in
Texas because the state's tax code penalizes those activities.
</P>
<P>
   . Greenberger writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Texas
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
