<HEADLINE>
BUSH TO OUTLINE PLANS FOR SCHOOL FUNDING, TAX CUTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush is expected to outline his
plans for a $2 billion property tax cut and more money for public
schools in his state of the state address to the Legislature on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes declined Tuesday to discuss
details of the speech, which governors traditionally use to focus
Texans' attention on their programs. But she said he would address
his top priorities of a tax cut and school funding.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush was expected to hold firm to the $2 billion cut in
local school property taxes that he pledged during his re-election
campaign, the governor already has hinted that he may back off of
some other tax cut promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all going to have to adjust our sights,'' he said two
weeks ago, in the face of a smaller-than-anticipated budget
surplus, an increase in basic spending needs and a warning from key
legislative budget writers.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's staff was believed to be reducing some of the
$600 million in state sales and business tax cuts that Bush also
proposed during his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's remarks also may attract significant national interest
this year, given his role as an unannounced, but anticipated,
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Although the governor has said he hasn't even made up his mind
on a White House race, a television news crew from New Hampshire,
which holds the first presidential primary of the election year, is
among media organizations that asked for credentials to cover the
speech.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Bill Siebert, R-San Antonio, said the governor, who
met privately with the House Republican Caucus on Tuesday, gave
lawmakers a ``good pep talk'' on his ``two top priorities _
education and tax relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Siebert didn't recall any specific figures from Bush's
presentation but said he believed the governor was committed to
substantial tax reductions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Bush has proposed increasing state funding for
public schools by $1.6 billion _ on top of the $2 billion the state
would reimburse local school districts for the property tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor, in remarks to the Texas Farm Bureau later
Tuesday, cautioned against the Legislature being too eager to spend
money on other new programs.
</P>
<P>
   If lawmakers spend too much money now, he warned, ``You wake up
five or 10 years from now and say, `Oops, we need an income tax.'''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``My budget proposal is designed to make sure Texas
will never have a personal income tax. I'm dead set against a
personal income tax.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's other education priorities include a pilot
program that would allow some students in low-performing public
schools to use tax-paid vouchers to attend private schools and a
new plan for ending social promotion in Texas schools.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
