<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CATHOLICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MEETING OF CONTRASTS AS PRESIDENT GREETS POPE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Sub to correct slug. Pope-Clinton sty will move shortly.) 
 
By KIM COBB 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Pope John Paul II's meeting with President Clinton
on Tuesday presented a stark contrast between the world's most
popular spiritual leader and this country's most visible,
self-described sinner.
</P>
<P>
   A cross section of Catholic leaders had said they would not
expect John Paul to use his brief visit to the United States to
chastise Clinton. The consensus was that the pope is far too savvy
a politician for that.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Michael Miller, president of the University of St.
Thomas in Houston, said the pope tends to criticize systems, not
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really not his style to address something which could so
quickly be turned to partisan use,'' Miller added.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a Southern Baptist, greeted the pontiff warmly upon his
arrival at the St. Louis airport. A few minutes later the pope
referred to ``times of trial, tests of national character'' and
challenged Americans to reach for a higher moral vision.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the same Catholics who say they don't think the
country needs spiritual healing in the wake of the president's sex
scandal and subsequent impeachment concede they would like to hear
what John Paul has to say on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is known for his ability to ``compartmentalize'' his
thoughts and feelings about one issue while he tackles another.
</P>
<P>
   So apparently too are American Catholics, who are celebrating
the pope's visit even during this current period of political
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't hear the kids talk about the president, but they get
pumped up about a 78-year-old man,'' said Mary Thole, youth adviser
to a group of Catholic teen-agers from Highland, Ill., attending
Tuesday's rally and prayer service.
</P>
<P>
   In his last visit to the United States in 1995, John Paul chided
Americans repeatedly for public and private immorality. His
frequent message, particularly to young people, is that a
permissive morality reduces freedom to a license to do as one
pleases.
</P>
<P>
   But even as sociologists talk about a deep distrust of rigid
authority among Americans born after World War II, the most
prosperous religious communities tend to be more rule-oriented than
others, said one expert on popular religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody's going to benefit (from Clinton's problems) it's
maybe that the religious leadership goes up in public esteem _
people you look up to for moral leadership,'' said Charles Howard
Lippy, Martin Professor of religious studies at the University of
Tennessee at Chattanooga.
</P>
<P>
   But Howard noted that ``the religious world'' has suffered under
its own share of sex scandals in recent years, including those of
Catholic priests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're discovering that clergy are no different than
other folks,'' Lippy said. ``We all have problems when those people
get caught.''
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Oksiupa, a student at St. Louis University, said, ``I
guess I hope he'd be addressing some of (the President's) problems.
I'd actually like to hear what (the pope) would say about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Oksiupa, 19, said she expects the pope's visit to be
overshadowed by public interest in Clinton's trial before the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   And some Catholics confessed that they'd would have liked to be
the proverbial ``fly on the wall'' when the president met privately
with the pope if the two discussed Clinton's trangressions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard a lot of people talk about the dichotomy of the
president talking to the pope,'' said St. Louis resident Frank
Fick. ``It's an interesting transposition of values.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if the president brought it up, but I
wouldn't expect the pope to,'' Fick said.
</P>
<P>
   The world leaders met privately for about 20 minutes. Their
respective press aides said Clinton and the pope talked about
challenges to peace and justice around the world, religious
freedom, and the pope's hope that the value of human beings will be
defended and protected in all circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The pope told the president that Clinton and all the other U.S.
leaders were in his prayers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
