A9636 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-CLASS-SIZE-COX     01-26 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-CLASS-SIZE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    County failing Florida's standard for class sizes
 &HT;    By Mary Ellen Flannery
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Class sizes in Palm Beach County have
been among the largest in the state during the past three years and
haven't come close to meeting the state's goals set in 1995 and
1996, according to reports from Florida's Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   The legislature wanted primary grade classes _ kindergarten
through third grades _ to have no more than 20 students. But in
1995, only 4.3 percent of Palm Beach County's first-grade classes
had 20 students or less; the figure was 5.7 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, class sizes have decreased slightly. Out of 442
first-grade classrooms this year, about 10 percent have 20 students
or less. They average 26 students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not where we want to be,'' said Sandra Richmond, school
board chairwoman, who will meet today with other board members to
discuss class sizes for 1999. ``As a teacher, I know the incredible
difference that happens when you take five students out of a class
of 40. We need to start building changes into the budget.''
</P>
<P>
   The school district wasn't alone in its failure. Statewide, 29
percent of first-grade classes met the goal in 1996. Of the largest
districts, Orange County did best with 54 percent of its
first-grade classes in compliance.
</P>
<P>
   But Palm Beach County failed most miserably _ more than
one-quarter of its first-grade classes had more than 30 students in
1996, compared with 8 percent in Broward County and 14.9 percent in
Miami-Dade County.
</P>
<P>
   The reports show that legislative goals don't carry much weight
if they don't come with enough money to accomplish them. In 1995,
the legislature appropriated $40 million to lower class sizes and
then $100 million in 1996. But based on one DOE study of 1996
figures, it would have cost $273 million to hire enough teachers to
meet class size goals.
</P>
<P>
   In Palm Beach County, it would have cost $29 million to hire the
teachers. And buying portable classrooms for every one of the
additional classes would have added about $23.5 million more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, if they gave us the money for teachers to reduce
class size, I'd support leasing portables to meet the need,'' said
school board member Paulette Burdick. ``But did they give us any
money at all? No, they did not.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of lowering class size in 1996, school board members
actually voted to raise it. In third, fourth and fifth grades,
class sizes went from 29 to 31 students, on average. At the middle
school level, they went from 28 to 29.5.
</P>
<P>
   Experts generally agree that reducing class size in the primary
grades is most critical because that's when students learn to read.
</P>
<P>
   However, most studies show that class size has to get down to 20
students to make a difference. Only one Palm Beach County school,
Barton Elementary in Lake Worth, averages 20 students or less in
its primary grade classrooms, and hiring extra teachers to lower
class size there cost the district $425,000.
</P>
<P>
   Districtwide, the average is 26 students in primary grades. But
40 percent of the district's schools had higher averages in
October. At Starlight Cove in Lantana, the primary grade classes
had 31 students on average.
</P>
<P>
   At least one school board member wants less variation in class
sizes across the district for the next academic year. A class size
of 26 should mean no class has more than 26, said school board
member Jody Gleason. ``I walked into a kindergarten classroom last
week that had 27 kids. I don't think that's appropriate,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But it's unlikely the school board will get much state support
soon. While class-size reductions have been discussed in the
Florida Senate, they weren't a priority in the governor's education
package released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Burdick said she was disappointed by the governor's proposal to
set aside $15 million to reward high-achieving schools, but nothing
to reduce class size. Doing that would have helped all schools
become high-achieving, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ellen Flannery writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
