<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL'S CURRENCY PLUNGES IN A DAY OF WIDE SWINGS
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BRAZIL-PRICES) 
 (nk) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ Brazil's currency swung wildly in
foreign-exchange dealings Tuesday and briefly fell to a low of
nearly two to the dollar because of growing uncertainty about the
country's economic health.
</P>
<P>
   The volatility in the currency, the real, came as another credit
rating service lowered its assessment of Brazil's ability to repay
debts. The action by Fitch IBCA, coming atop a downgrade by the
Duff &AMP; Phelps service on Monday, partly reflected worries that the
government lacks the leadership to deal with an economic crisis
that is growing more acute.
</P>
<P>
   But the anxiety about Latin America's largest economy appeared
to have little effect on the stock market, where the key index rose
6.33 percent on purchases by investors who thought shares were
selling at bargain levels.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil has been in an increased state of economic turmoil since
the government abruptly decided more than a week ago to stop
defending the value of the real by buying the currency in the
foreign exchange market. It had spent billions of dollars in
foreign reserves with that approach but the real's value kept
falling.
</P>
<P>
   The cheapened currency, in turn, has unnerved consumers and
investors because it threatens the return of higher inflation and
has raised the costs of servicing the country's foreign debts. An
estimated $42 billion in debts is coming due in the next few
months.
</P>
<P>
   But with pressure growing for economic austerity measures from
the government, the central bank's president, Francisco Lopes, told
the Brazilian Senate on Tuesday that no new steps were forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   A team of technical experts from the International Monetary Fund
arrived in Brazil to review the country's economic performance
under an agreement for a $41.5 billion standby loan. The fund's
approval will be needed before a second allotment of the loan,
originally due to be disbursed in late February, can be released.
</P>
<P>
   The main barometer of Brazil's economic slide has become the
real, which fell Tuesday to 1.955 to the dollar before rebounding
to settle at 1.85, compared with 1.78 on Monday. At many banks,
which charge foreign exchange fees, citizens and tourists had to
pay a rate of two reals to the dollar.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This week, the Brazilian Congress is scheduled to vote on 28
billion reals ($16 billion) of cuts to this year's budget, and to
finish voting on Social Security reform legislation. It will also
vote on extending and increasing a tax on financial transactions.
</P>
<P>
   But without any more ambitious plans to cut costs, economists
said, the Brazilian government risks a repeat of the kind of
capital flight and panic that has gripped the nation for much of
this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the events of the last week or so, you get the
impression that the government has just taken a back seat,'' said
Philip Smith, a banking expert at Fitch IBCA. ``What you've got is
very much a void where people don't know what the strategy is.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian President Fernando Henrique Cardoso, simultaneously
facing a punishing recession and the return of high inflation,
convened panels of ministers to find ways to invigorate economic
growth. Finance Minister Pedro Malan was not included on either of
the panels. Joao Pimenta da Veiga, the government's communications
minister, said, however, that Malan would be consulted.
</P>
<P>
   Telling the Senate Economic Affairs Committee not to expect any
new austerity package, the central bank's Lopes said the votes that
would be taken this week were ``of the greatest importance, and are
sufficient for the consolidation of the program of stability.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
