r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT     01-26 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS HAVE A LOT TO OVERCOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has come down to 37 games and 81 days for the Kings, a time
when all they have to do to save their season is find scoring
balance, develop a power play, learn to win at home, learn to get
off to good starts in games, and, oh yes: Major players have to
stay healthy.
</P>
<P>
   If they can accomplish all these things, they can still make the
playoffs. If not, the five-point gap that separated them from the
playoffs at the All-Star break will assume mountainous proportions,
and the Kings (16-25-4) will look back on their final season at the
Forum as one of disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   As far as coach Larry Robinson is concerned, it's a matter of
getting a commitment from all of his players. That commitment will
be tested immediately when the Kings begin a four-game trip tonight
against the Dallas Stars, who have the best record in the National
Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   ``To play the game, it's difficult,'' Robinson said. ``You're
going to have to take bumps and bruises and get hit with the puck.
It boils down to how much commitment you have to winning games. The
teams that are going to be successful are the teams that are going
to be committed to winning hockey games.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he was questioning some of his players'
commitment, Robinson said: ``I think they're trying. But a lot of
times, they almost think they're doing what they're supposed to do.
But they don't realize their feet aren't moving. They think they're
working hard. But maybe they're working hard the wrong way. They're
going south when the play is going north.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from avoiding injuries, which is out of their control,
there are several things the Kings can and must do consistently if
they are to turn their season around:
</P>
<P>
   _Get off to good starts. The Kings are only 2-19-1 when allowing
the first goal, 0-12 when trailing after one period and 0-15 when
trailing after two. Sluggish starts _ and the inability to recover
from those starts _ have been hurting the Kings all season.
</P>
<P>
   _Win at home. When the Kings concluded their recent home stand
with a 1-3 record, Robinson said he actually was happy that the
team was about to hit the road. The Kings are an abysmal 8-13-3 at
home, a comparatively acceptable 8-12-1 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   It is imperative that the Kings establish a home-ice advantage
for the final two-plus months of the season. Eight of their final
17 games at the Forum are against the Mighty Ducks, San Jose,
Edmonton, Vancouver and St. Louis _ teams they are battling for a
playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   _Get production from Jozef Stumpel. Injuries have slowed the
Kings' top center most of the season, and after getting 79 points
in 1997-98, he has only 18 this season. But with 37 games left, if
he could produce a point a game the rest of the way, it would help
the Kings immeasurably.
</P>
<P>
   _Score on the power play. The Kings hoped to improve on the
power play with the signing of free agent Steve Duchesne last
summer, but instead, they are worse with the man advantage than
they were a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   How much difference would even an adequate power play have made
this season? Of the Kings' 25 losses, 10 have been by one goal; in
four other games, they were losing late by one goal and wound up
losing by two when they pulled the goalie and allowed an empty-net
goal. In those 14 games, the Kings' power play was a combined 6 for
68 (8.8 percent), compared with a 12.7-percent overall productivity
rate, which is dismal in its own right.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the Kings' power play is costing them games. But in
Robinson's eyes, greater commitment from his team would mean at
least as much as a potent power play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still making fundamental errors that shouldn't be there
at this point,'' Robinson said. ``It's not that we haven't told
them. A lot of it is their concentration level, when they get on
the ice, is not what it should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing I see is there isn't that commitment from
the first guy on the forecheck to go and go hard. He knows where to
go, but he's not going with the conviction of getting the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you watch the game, watch how a guy goes. If he goes with
his feet apart and is gliding to be in position, he's not working
hard. When we don't have success, we're gliding. When we're going
hard and our feet are moving, then you've done your job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
