<HEADLINE>
THREE POTENTIAL JURORS PICKED IN JASPER CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
and RICHARD STEWART 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ A potential juror in the trial of a white
supremacist accused of dragging a black man to his death last
summer was excused Tuesday after saying a relative had received
racist letters from the defendant.
</P>
<P>
   The man was one of seven people dismissed as lawyers began
individually questioning 122 prospective jurors. Three others made
the cut.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Halmon, a white construction worker, volunteered that he
had read letters addressed to his step-granddaughter, Michelle
Chapman. The prospective juror said he didn't know capital murder
defendant John William ``Bill'' King personally and wasn't biased
against him. But he also said, ``I have the thought that he is
guilty,'' and after repeated questioning, conceded that opinion
might prevent him from being a fair juror.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman, who is listed in court papers along with about 50
others who have been subpoenaed as potential witnesses, is one of
several young girls King had written to while he was serving time
for probation violations at the Beto I prison in Tennessee Colony
from 1995 to 1997. Some of the letters, which were romantic in
nature but also included anti-black comments, were turned over to
investigators by the girls' parents shortly after King's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities also have theorized that King was trying to organize
a racist gang in Jasper, and had talked of planning a violent
racist act. But District Attorney Guy James Gray refused to comment
Tuesday on whether he would produce evidence during the trial to
confirm that. He also declined to say whether Chapman will take the
stand.
</P>
<P>
   On June 7, a year after King was released from prison, he was
arrested along with two buddies in the death of James Byrd Jr. of
Jasper. Byrd, a 49-year-old black man, was beaten, chained by his
ankles to a pickup and dragged about three miles to his death. His
dismembered body was dumped in the middle of a road east of Jasper,
outside the gates to an old African-American cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   King, 24, has denied involvement in the killing, though police
have said the victim's blood was found on the shoes of all three
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, King would face either the death penalty or a life
prison sentence. His co-defendants, Shawn Allen Berry, 23, and
Lawrence Russell Brewer, 31, will be tried later.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Jasper County Sheriff Billy Rowles said Imogene
Hopson, a 62-year-old woman arrested after taking a gun into the
Jasper County Courthouse the day before, is Berry's great-aunt.
</P>
<P>
   But Rowles said he was convinced Hopson had no intention of
harming anyone. She simply forgot she had the gun in her purse, he
said. Hopson was charged with unlawful possession of a handgun and
released on $5,000 bond.
</P>
<P>
   Hopson could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday morning, signs were posted at the entrance to the
courthouse, reminding visitors that no guns are allowed inside.
</P>
<P>
   Of the seven people released from jury service Tuesday, one was
eliminated because of a theft conviction and two because they could
not put their personal opinions aside and decide the case based on
what they learn in the courtroom. Four others were dismissed
rapidly when they said they could not vote for the death penalty if
King is convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Those qualified for jury service include an African-American
woman who works as a corrections officer and is married to a deputy
sheriff, a white maintenance man who works for the Post Office and
a white papermill worker.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen more people will be questioned Wednesday, but Gray and
defense lawyer C. Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs Jr. said they are
concerned about finding 46 qualified jurors from the current jury
pool. That is the number needed before they can begin the final
process of seating 12 jurors and two alternates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest handicap so far is the death penalty,'' said Gray.
</P>
<P>
   And the prosecutor conceded that he might not reach his goal of
finding at least three black jurors to match the racial makeup of
the county, which is about 20 percent black. Gray said that in his
experience, many African-American jurors are disqualified because
they oppose the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, three black men were eliminated and one black woman
was qualified, leaving only 17 more African-Americans in the pool
to be questioned in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But Gray also said he was encouraged to find that only two of
the jurors screened Tuesday were eliminated because of their strong
opinions on King's guilt or innocence. Both were white men.
</P>
<P>
   The black woman who was accepted said she had already formed an
opinion that King could be guilty. But when asked if she could set
aside that opinion and fairly consider the facts and evidence
presented during the trial, she said, ``I have an opinion. I don't
think it would influence my decision.''
</P>
<P>
   She also indicated that she had some religious reservations
about serving on the jury, but said she could handle it. ``If I'm
chosen, I can be on the jury. If I'm not, it won't offend me,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, whose family works either in law enforcement or
corrections, said she also would not be swayed by peer pressure
from relatives or co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   The postal worker also said he wouldn't bow to peer pressure.
``I think I would be a weak person to give in to something like
that,'' he said. And when defense attorneys asked if working for
the federal government would make him more sympathetic to
government prosecutors in this case, he said, ``No sir. I don't owe
my life to them. I owe them my eight hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   King's father, Ronald, who attended the first day of jury
selection, was absent Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's father, James Byrd Sr., sat on the front row of the
courtroom Tuesday morning, but declined comment. Four hand-lettered
signs written on white poster boards and posted outside the Byrd
home asked the media to stay away. ``No media,'' one sign said,
``Please, no media,'' another said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
