<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-EDDIE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELAHOUSSAYE NEAR MILESTONE
</HEADLINE>
 D-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA -- In a corner of the jockeys' room, Eddie Delahoussaye
appeared at ease as he sat with a warm towel draped around his
neck, awaiting the single mount he was scheduled to ride one day
last week.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed all he needed was a champion's cigar to go with his
peaceful look.
</P>
<P>
   After all, this is a man who has done it all in the past 31
years, providing many memorable moments for Southern California
horse racing fans.
</P>
<P>
   He scored back-to-back Kentucky Derby victories in 1982 and '83
aboard Gato del Sol and Sunny's Halo, respectively. He captured the
1988 Preakness and Belmont Stakes aboard Risen Star and the 1992
Belmont Stakes with A.P. Indy to go along with seven Breeders' Cup
winners.
</P>
<P>
   But as each day passes for the Arcadia resident, he is
constantly reminded of another big day that is looming.
</P>
<P>
   With 5,994 career wins, Delahoussaye needs six more trips to the
winner's circle to become only the 14th rider in North American
racing history to reach 6,000 victories.
</P>
<P>
   He's on four mounts today as Santa Anita's winter/spring meeting
continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing. It will be a great achievement for me
personally,'' Delahoussaye said. ``I've had to battle my weight my
whole career. When I first started riding in 1967, people told me I
wouldn't last a year because I'm as big as I am now. But I love
this sport so much, nothing was going to keep me away.''
</P>
<P>
   With a normal daily schedule of three to four mounts,
Delahoussaye could easily reach 6,000 in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think about it, just to be riding 31 years is a feat in
itself for a jock,'' Delahoussaye, 47, said. ``I'm not the kind of
guy who starts reminiscing through the years, but I think this
accomplishment speaks as much for my love of this sport as it does
my dedication to it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a dedication the legendary Bill Shoemaker saw during
countless battles with the rider simply known as Eddie D.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that often that guys like Eddie come around,''
Shoemaker said. ``Like Laffit (Pincay) and Chris (McCarron), Eddie
has a great mind and he's got the love for the sport. You need
those two things if you're going to ride this long.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Solis, who leads Santa Anita's winter/spring title chase,
says racing needs more riders like Delahoussaye.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's everything I pictured in my mind when I came over here
from Panama,'' Solis said. ``It's amazing to watch guys like Eddie
ride as they get older.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may not have the physical abilities or the strong legs he
used to have, but his mind is in great shape. Give him a good horse
and he knows what to do in a race. With all his experience and wit,
he can compete with anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Delahoussaye keeps approaching milestones, he is
constantly reminded that the end is nearing. It has become a
nagging question.
</P>
<P>
   ``People keep asking when I'm going to retire,'' Delahoussaye
said. ``How would that feel if someone kept asking you, `When are
you going to retire?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody likes to hear that, especially if you love your job. If
you don't love your job, you could say, `Hey, I'm gonna quit
tomorrow.' But when you love what you're doing, you want to enjoy
every moment of it and not think about what's coming next.''
</P>
<P>
   Delahoussaye may not get the number of mounts he received during
his glory years, but that doesn't mean his work rate has slowed.
He's still out most mornings looking for work along Clockers
Corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Successful people are usually workaholics because they enjoy
what they are doing,'' Delahoussaye said. ``If you start thinking
of the end of your career or job, you start backing off a little
bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be competitive as a jockey, you have to be out there
hustling and promoting ever day. It doesn't matter if you're on top
or not, you have to show your face, and that's what I've always
tried to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Delahoussaye hinted that his career would end if his stock
started to decline. He doesn't need more days like last week, when
he rode only one race on an entire day's card.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come in to ride one horse and he has a legitimate
chance of winning, it's worth coming in,'' Delahoussaye said. ``But
if it comes to the point where I'm coming in for one horse that's
20-1, then I'd be at the point or stage in my career where I still
enjoy riding, but I'd rather not be riding a 20-1 shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one last crack at a Kentucky Derby is enough to keep
Delahoussaye working on his diet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to be there if I got a good horse.'' he said. ``I
wouldn't go there just to ride it, I've already done that. But if I
had another realistic chance, I'd love to do it again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
