<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER CHECKPOINT ON NFL EXPANSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to determining which millionaire or billionaire
will be invited to join the NFL's most-exclusive ownership
fraternity, the league can be as dogged as a probation officer.
</P>
<P>
   There are checkpoints every few miles on the road to acceptance,
and the detail work rivals anything your local FBI could muster. If
the league were as vigilant about its background checks of players,
there would be a lot less police notices around the league.
</P>
<P>
   But the league is dealing with a billion-dollar industry here,
not some nickel back who majored in breaking and entering. It will
offer no apology for its pending financial strip search of the
three parties seeking an expansion franchise Michael Ovitz, the Ed
Roski/Eli Broad Coliseum partnership and Houston businessman Robert
McNair.
</P>
<P>
   The league's expansion committee will meet Thursday in Miami,
site of Sunday's Super BowlXXXIII, and get an update on where each
group stands in its bid for a 32nd expansion franchise. That
meeting will be followed by a special league meeting in February,
all leading to some kind of action at the annual March owners
meetings in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The league protects this process better than the Broncos do John
Elway. The line-by-line detail gets hidden by a handful of public
hard-and-fast criteria.
</P>
<P>
   To wit: One individual must own 30 percent of the team. Only
$100 million of the franchise fee can be in the form of debt (i.e.,
a bank loan). Private Seat License money can be included in the
projection, but only after the league has concluded it is feasible.
</P>
<P>
   Any proposal must include some public money, usually in the form
of direct contributions to a new stadium. And while prospective
owners have flexibility in how they erect a new stadium, the league
must sign off on it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Behind closed doors, the league is blunt and stringent. It wants
to see the money. It wants to see fluid dollars, too, not paper
assets, because it expects cash when the time comes to go forward.
It wants background on every minority owner. It wants operating
budgets which include reserves. And it wants to make sure ownership
isn't spreading its assets too thin.
</P>
<P>
   Various sources privy to how these meetings work also admit the
league has a double standard: It can be a stickler on details with
one group and a bit accommodating to another.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Baltimore and St. Louis proposals for expansion franchises
in some ways were better than those in Carolina and Jacksonville,''
said a source. ``In one case, the league just didn't like the
ownership group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league's priority is to make sure any ownership will be
able to have success,'' said league spokesman Greg Aiello. ``If you
look at some past decisions, you'll see that.'' Exhibit A would be
Tom Clancy getting bounced as prospective buyer of the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   But once the league has two or three groups in hand that meets
their criteria, the source said, ``things can then come down to
personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the two L.A. groups and Houston reach that point remains
to be seen. There are still questions to be answered about all
three. To wit:
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz/Carson: Beyond some pretty stadium sketches and one public
appearance by Ovitz, the former Hollywood agent, this proposal has
been cloaked in secrecy. Ovitz's rivals say that's because there's
nothing behind the curtain.
</P>
<P>
   No one on the well-healed list of prospective minority owners
has stepped forward publicly. If Ovitz is to be the 30 percent man,
he'll need $150 million of his own money. While his severance check
at Disney was substantial, much of it came in the form of stock
options subject to the whims of Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the partnership Ovitz has with real estate man Hebert
Glimcher, who holds the option on the property and plans to build
the adjacent mall, are still sketchy, too. Is Glimcher a part owner
of the team with Ovitz? How will the league assess his role in the
project, and will it change the way the league looks at Ovitz?
</P>
<P>
   Sources say the league is also concerned about Carson's $180
million contribution via bonds, since the proposal includes a mall
as well as the stadium. It would like to see more direct revenue.
For what it's worth, the city of Carson is still waiting for
paperwork from Ovitz that fleshes out the city's role and potential
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   New Coliseum, Roski/Broad: The addition of billionaire Eli Broad
to the New Coliseum team as the 30 percent front man was a response
to NFL concerns that Roski, the Kings owner and man behind The
Staples Center, was overextended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indirectly, I understand the NFL was very happy to hear (about
Broad),'' Roski said last week. ``If we hadn't done this, there
would have been a question in their minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Roski's Majestic Reality is one of the largest real estate
concerns in Southern California, but his equity there wouldn't have
mattered when the NFL came looking for a check. Now, Roski can
focus on financing stadium construction against his equity.
</P>
<P>
   Broad is no figurehead: He plans to run the franchise. But the
league will need time to investigate his involvement. Plus, the
Coliseum group is still claiming it can raise $100 million through
PSLs. The league is dubious, to the degree that it has hired Max
Muhelman to assess the PSL potential in Los Angeles for both
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL still needs convincing that there is a public investment
at work here. Most of the $350 million the New Coliseum group says
has been committed is in the form of work already done on
retrofitting the stadium after the Northridge earthquake and
neighborhood infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Houston: The McNair group has all of its financial ducks in a
row. McNair recently sold a company for $1.6 billion. He's been
through the process with the NFL, because he investigated buying
the Miami Dolphins before Wayne Huizenga.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Sports Authority (HSA) has already approved its
investment in stadium construction, around $195 million of a $310
million budget, financed by tax surcharges on tickets, hotels and
rental cars.
</P>
<P>
   The county has also donated the land involved; the PSL threshold
has been set at $50 million; and the HSA has already booked other
events into the stadium guaranteeing $35 million in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very fluid,'' said Steve Patterson, a spokesman for the
McNair group. ``All of the details about public investment are
there, and there may be another $200 million available. We don't
have any environmental questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the league thinks, but I've heard people say
the other groups have holes and don't have their financing
together. All I know is that every time we ask the league if they
have any questions, they say we're there.''
</P>
<P>
   At least until someone finds another question to ask tomorrow.
By the time the league meets in March, it will likely be able to
tell you if McNair wears boxer or jockey shorts, what toothpaste
Roski uses, and if Ovitz has any outstanding parking tickets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
