<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0450 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9653 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-ATLANTA-ART-2TAKE     01-26 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ATLANTA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTA ORGANIZERS SET TO FACE QUESTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the Olympic family, the Atlanta Olympic organizers
have often been looked on as poor relations _ the long-shot bunch
from this Southern city who were, in a stunning upset, awarded the
1996 Centennial Games, then managed to make a mess of them.
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1996 Summer Games, they were criticized for being too
crass in seeking sponsor dollars. During the Olympics, the Games,
mocked by some as the ``Bubba Games,'' were plagued by poor
transportation, substandard living quarters for the athletes and a
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, in what was perceived as an international insult,
International Olympic Committee president Juan Antonio Samaranch
failed to call the $1.7 billion Games the greatest ever, a standard
bouquet thrown to previous host cities.
</P>
<P>
   Now, more than two years after the Olympic flame was
extinguished in Atlanta, Olympic organizers here are set to face
the most serious inquiry into their performance: did they do
anything unethical in obtaining the Games in the first place?
</P>
<P>
   The IOC, having uncovered widespread misconduct in Salt Lake
City's effort to gain the 2002 Winter Games, has said it will
investigate how each city for the last decade earned its
designation as an Olympic site. For the moment, the Atlanta
organizers have been almost defiantly confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``No cash, no scholarships, nothing illegal, unethical,
inappropriate or untoward,'' Billy Payne, the chief architect of
the Atlanta Games, said of his organization's efforts to win the
Olympics. ``We are more than delighted and willing to show that all
that is good about the Olympic Games can be acquired following the
bid rules and doing something as simple as making friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta organizers are particularly defensive about their
behavior during the bid process because winning the bid in 1990 was
a rare and, by their telling, pure moment of euphoria. By their
account, they began the bid process as a core of seven to a dozen
civic-minded lawyers and bureaucrats who, on a relatively small
budget of $7.4 million, traveled to more than 40 countries,
befriending Olympic committee members through Southern charm and
hospitality. Athens reportedly spent more than $30 million in its
failed effort.
</P>
<P>
   They say the gifts they gave ranged from the gimmicky _
pillowcases stitched with ``Georgia on My Mind'' _ to the more
personal. When the late committee member from Cuba, Manuel Gonzalez
Guerra, admired a ceramic bulldog on Payne's desk, the former
football star at the University of Georgia bought a live bulldog
and made sure the dog had its shots and was waiting on the plane
when the Cuban member left.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Battle, the bid committee's roving ambassador, said he
was aware of the so-called agents, or vote brokers who claimed they
could deliver members, but said he was never approached by them. He
joked that the worst indignity he suffered was having to brave the
icy, polluted waters of the Danube River to swim with a
granddaughter of a Slovakian IOC member.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say that I never asked anyone if they were going to vote
for us,'' said Battle, who traveled to more than 40 countries to
enlist support for Atlanta's bid.
</P>
<P>
   There were other actions, however, that perhaps pushed at the
margins of appropriateness and that ultimately spurred others to
speak of what became known as the ``Atlanta model.''
</P>
<P>
   This past weekend, Australia's Olympic chief, John Coates, said
that former Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young, also a former U.S.
ambassador to the United Nations and an Atlanta bid committee
member, had toured Africa dispensing aid commitments in exchange
for support for Atlanta's successful bid for the 1996 Summer
Olympics. Coates remarks came as he explained why he pledged
$35,000 each to the Olympic committees of two IOC members from
Africa in a last-ditch effort to ingratiate himself with voters.
Sydney was awarded the 2000 Summer Games by 2 votes over Beijing,
45-43.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drafted the original strategies, and early on had identified
that we had to do something in Africa,'' said Coates, who offered
no evidence of his allegation against Young. ``I came to grips with
that because I knew that's how Atlanta had achieved it, so I didn't
feel uncomfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Through a spokesman, Young denied the allegation. ``It was an
irresponsible comment by John Coates,'' said Lee Echols, the
spokesman. ``It really upset Andy. It was an insulting comment to
make.'' Young has been traveling, and has not returned several
telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who has maintained ties to Africa throughout his life,
has a long relationship with one of the key figures in the Salt
Lake City scandal _ the IOC member from the Congo Republic,
Jean-Claude Ganga. He was one of six committee members expelled
Sunday by the organization's executive board after it found he had
accepted direct payments, free medical care, gifts and travel
subsidies amounting to $216,010 from Salt Lake City's organizing
committee.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Young has acknowledged that in August 1990 _ a month before the
bid vote _ he went to the Congo Republic with sports equipment.
Doug Gatlin, executive director of the committee then, said he was
with Young when they delivered 50 soccer balls, 100 handballs and
200 pairs of gym shorts, all of it donated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We handed it out directly to kids in the villages,'' Gatlin
said. ``He has enormous respect in Africa because he helped put
Africa on the U.S. radar scope while serving under President Jimmy
Carter. He helped make human rights in Africa part of the theme of
the administration. He never needed to bribe anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Gatlin said Young never promised foreign aid on their trips to
Africa. Referring to himself, Gatlin said he made calls to
international sports organizations to inquire about coaching and
athletic exchange programs, but nothing more. He said he shared
Young's belief that their work fell under humanitarian aid and not
under vote buying.
</P>
<P>
   Many African nations benefited from Young's and the Atlanta
organizers' attentions, but the Atlanta organizers emphasize that
it was after the Games were awarded to the city. When told by
Mozambique officials that their female marathoners couldn't afford
proper foods, for example, Young helped send food and protein
supplements to the country.
</P>
<P>
   After getting the Games, the Atlanta organizers helped set up a
training center for African athletes in LaGrange, Ga. With funds
from local residents and the IOC's Olympic solidarity program, the
training center hit full stride in 1994, with 20 athletes from
Africa and the Middle East. They also allowed an association of
African nations, headed by Ganga, the unusual privilege of
marketing its own merchandise during the Games. Host committees are
usually vigilant about honoring licenses to the paying rights
holders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had told every country that we intended to set up a
training center for weather acclimation, and that we'd help in
whatever way we could to make sure teams and athletes got here,''
Battle said. ``We wanted every country to have an opportunity to
compete in the games. But it was never a `vote for us and we'll do
this' kind of deal.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Atlanta won the 1996 Games over Athens, the Atlanta
organizers said they contended with the rumors about how they did
it. The Greek news media charged that Coca-Cola _ one of the
Olympics oldest sponsors _ bought the Games for its home city.
``That's one of the biggest myths,'' Battle said. ``Heck, Coke
would rather have them in Beijing, where there's 400 billion
potential Coke drinkers.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's Olympic spokesman, Ben Deutsch, said the company
policy was not to provide financial support to any host-city bid.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, the German magazine Der Spiegel reported that Atlanta
Olympic officials offered IOC members gold credit cards, free heart
surgery and scholarships for their children, as well as cash. The
Atlanta organizers vigorously deny the charges. Two incidents
involving two of the IOC members implicated in the corruption
scandal, however, have been acknowledged by Payne.
</P>
<P>
   David Sibandze, a member from Swaziland, had a heart attack
while visiting during the bid process. Atlanta organizers paid for
part of his treatment while Piedmont Hospital absorbed the rest.
Sibandze resigned from the IOC over the weekend after it was
discovered that his son was given a job at the Salt Lake City
Economic Development Office.
</P>
<P>
   And Payne said he made calls in 1991 to the University of
Georgia on behalf of the stepson of the IOC member from Russia,
Vitaly Smirnov. The stepson was enrolled at Georgia from 1992 to
1994, but received no scholarship money from the school, according
to university officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nine months after the vote, and all I did was make some
calls like I often do when asked by friends,'' Payne said.
</P>
<P>
   Several Atlanta officials say they were approached in a subtle
fashion by certain members ``to meet privately'' or to discuss
Atlanta's ``chance of winning,'' including once before the vote in
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   And so the Atlanta organizers insist that they will answer fully
and honestly a letter expected to arrive any day from the IOC
asking for details. They are currently reviewing documents
chronicling the two years spent chasing and entertaining Olympic
committee members across the globe. But they have refused to make
those records public.
</P>
<P>
   For Payne, this last look at Atlanta's Olympic experience offers
a chance for, if not vindication, some reclamation of the Atlanta
Games' legacy. ``Hundreds of thousands of Georgians spared no
effort in welcoming the world into our state and community,'' Payne
said. ``I represented them and they should know, as I do, that we
shouldn't bow our heads. We should all feel good about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 2130EST &QL; 
