<HEADER>
A9663 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      01-26 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARNER-LAMBERT TO ACQUIRE AGOURON FOR $2.1 BILLION
</P>
<P>
   Warner-Lambert, one of the hottest drug companies in the
industry, announced that it would acquire Agouron Pharmaceuticals,
a small biotechnology firm, for $2.1 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   The deal enables Warner-Lambert to add Agouron's Viracept, the
United States' leading protease inhibitor, to its pipeline along
with several other anti-viral and cancer drugs. Although the deal
was announced after the market closed, shares of both stocks
climbed steadily throughout the day before they were halted in
afternoon trading. Shares of Warner-Lambert rose $1.625, to
$69.125, while Agouron jumped $3.65625, or 6.9 percent, to
$56.8125.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings at four of the largest drug companies _ Merck, American
Home Products, Schering-Plough and Johnson &AMP; Johnson _ met or
slightly beat Wall Street expectations.
</P>
<P>
   MORE INSTABILITY IN BRAZIL
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's currency briefly tumbled to a rate of nearly two to the
dollar as another credit-rating agency lowered its assessment of
the nation's economic prospects and ability to repay debts. But the
stock market rallied as buyers sensed bargains, pushing the main
index up 6.33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has weathered the worst blows of the global economic
crisis and is not likely to suffer severe trauma from Brazil's
instability, top finance officials said.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING BEATS WALL STREET FORECASTS
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, which released fourth-quarter results that were 3 cents
a share better than expected, tried to reassure investors that it
was finally turning itself around. But Wall Street remained
skeptical, sending shares of the aerospace company down $1, to $35.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT WITNESS ON COMPETITION
</P>
<P>
   A senior Microsoft official testified in the government's
antitrust case that the company tried to persuade Netscape
Communications, its main rival in the Internet software market, to
become less of a head-on competitor.
</P>
<P>
   COCA-COLA EARNINGS DECLINE 27 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Confirming the bad news it had warned Wall Street analysts about
last month, Coca-Cola reported its fourth-quarter earnings fell 27
percent as volume and revenue dropped in many parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com, the online retailer, said its fourth-quarter loss
widened less than expected, while sales almost quadrupled, as more
holiday shoppers used it to buy gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Strong international sales and a rejuvenated U.S. restaurant
business lifted McDonald's fourth-quarter profit 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ OFFERS STAKE IN ALTA VISTA
</P>
<P>
   Rod Schrock, the executive who introduced Compaq's Presario line
of personal computers, was named president and chief executive of
the new Alta Vista. Compaq Computer, which owns the Internet search
engine, plans to sell a minority stake in it to the public as part
of an effort to expand Alta Vista into a leading player in online
advertising and shopping. The news follows the collapse of talks in
which Compaq hoped to sell a stake in Alta Vista to Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   MOODY'S LOWERS RATINGS ON MAZDA
</P>
<P>
   Moody's Investors Service lowered its ratings on Mazda Motor's
long-term unsecured debt to below investment grade, citing
continued deterioration in the Japanese car market.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH NEWSPAPER EXECUTIVE QUITS
</P>
<P>
   David Montgomery resigned as chief executive of Mirror Group,
pressured to leave by board members and stockholders who were angry
over his refusal to consider purchase offers for the company.
Montgomery's departure opens the way for a takeover battle for one
of Britain's oldest tabloid newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   SOTHEBY'S SEEKS EXCLUSIVE DEALS
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent attempt to undermine its archrival Christie's
entry into the potentially lucrative online auction business,
Sotheby's is asking art dealers to sign exclusive contracts that
would prevent them from selling wares through other auction houses
online.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
