<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0458 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9667 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ARCHDEACON-COLUMN     01-26 1309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ARCHDEACON-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SSharpe lets tongue do his talking
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Shannon Sharpe was telling about the day it became
evident that his tongue was the same as his name:
</P>
<P>
   ``It all began in a speech class in elementary school. The
teacher said, `Now don't any of you help your fellow students, let
me do it.' And then one kid got stuck pronouncing a word and she
was saying, ``Now Johnny, it sounds like . . . It sounds like . .
.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, I piped in, `It sounds like Johnny can't read!'
</P>
<P>
   ``The teacher turned to me and snapped, `Shannon Sharpe, you get
out of this classroom and don't come back until you learn how to
talk!' ''
</P>
<P>
   And learn he has.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Pro tight end of the Denver Broncos is also the league's
top lip. Back in Colorado, he's known as the Megaphone of the
Mountain Zone. Here, four days before the Super Bowl XXXIII
match-up between Denver and the Atlanta Falcons, he's quickly
established himself as the Mouth of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Tuesday's meet-the-team picture day at Pro Player
Stadium. Each marquee player gets a small podium and microphone on
the edge of the field, the press gathers around him and the stadium
clocks are set to 60 minutes, the length of the interview session.
</P>
<P>
   And when the public address announcer finally intoned, ``The
Bronco media session is beginning now,'' Sharpe, with 10 minutes of
wolfin' already in his wake, stopped in mid-sentence, glared in the
direction of the voice and offered tongue-in-cheek annoyance:
``Don't interrupt me.''
</P>
<P>
   He knew he was on a roll. Asked about the Dallas Cowboys, he
shrugged: ``They used to be America's Team, now they're America's
Most Wanted . . . We've got to be America's team now. The
(defending) champs always get that consideration. You always bet
the lead horse 'til he falters. When they saw Secretariat out 21
lengths ahead, no one ran to the window to bet the second place
horse.''
</P>
<P>
   What about the Falcons though? Since he grew up in Glenville,
Ga., played college ball at Savannah State and now lives in
Atlanta's Buckhead section, did he have some special feeling for
the team?
</P>
<P>
   ``Want me to lie or tell the truth? I didn't like 'em. They lost
all the time. If you had a pair of cleats and walked into Fulton
County, they put you in the game. Walk in with $20 and they put you
in the luxury box with the owner.''
</P>
<P>
   But these Falcons are different. They're 16-2 and in safety
Eugene Robinson, they even have a big-league talker of their own.
``Look, you can take a leopard out of the Serengeti and put him in
the zoo, but he's still a leopard,'' Sharpe said in mangled axiom.
``The thing is, Eugene played 11 years in Seattle and they were
terrible _ 3-13, 4-12, 5-11_ and he never said a word. And now he
doesn't want to get into a jawing match with me. He can't out talk
me, he can't cover me one-one-one and even though he went to
Colgate, I'm smarter than him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe calls himself the league's best trash talker _ ``If I
can't upset you, you're not human,'' _ and anyone who saw that
Monday Night game in mid-November and what he did to linebacker
Derrick Thomas and the rest of the Kansas City Chiefs won't argue.
</P>
<P>
   He noted Thomas had undersized feet and equated that to other
body parts and soon the emotional defender was in full meltdown.
Kansas City was hit with five personal fouls in the fourth quarter.
Two were by Thomas, who had Sharpe by the face mask.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Sharpe didn't just rile a team, but part of an
entire stadium of fans. As Denver was trouncing New England in
Foxboro, Sharpe came to the sidelines with a press box phone and,
as NFL Films recorded the moment, he boomed into the receiver ``Mr.
President, bring in the Army, the Navy, the National Guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it's the Miami Dolphins and their fans who want his head.
During the Dolphins embarrassing 38-3 playoff loss at Denver, he
needled Miami players: ``How's it feel to have the Super Bowl in
your house and not be invited?''
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, the Broncos now are ensconced in the
Dolphins practice complex. ``I've got Terrell Buckley's locker,''
Sharpe said of the loquacious Miami defender whom he burned for
five catches. ``I'm leaving little notes for him. Mike (Shanahan)
moved into Jimmy's office. We ran 'em right out of their own home.
They locked up their Gatorade on us, but Jimmy's fish tanks are
still in there. Maybe we'll put a little arsenic or strychnine in
'em.''
</P>
<P>
   The one thing Sharpe said he regrets is calling Miami
quarterback Dan Marino ``a loser,'' after the rout. He has
apologized _ thanks, in part, to a no-nonsense call from his
grandma back home.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Porter, Sharpe's 76-year-old grandmother, is the woman who
has hold of his ear . . . and lips. And when you talk to her, you
get to know who Shannon Sharpe really is.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe, his brother Sterling, who played for Green Bay and is
now an ESPN analyst, their sister Sherra, her mentally handicapped
son and four aunts all lived with their grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon slept with his grandma, Sterling with his grandpa. The
roof leaked in one side of the bedroom, which meant Sterling and
his granddad slept in rain coats, while Shannon moved buckets
around the room. The family was the poorest of poor, raising hogs,
picking tobacco and, in Shannon's words, ``workin' from cain't see
to cain't see. Can't see in the dark when you start work before
dawn and can't see at the end of the day when you finish work at
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Shannon always dreamed _ and talked _ of brighter days
ahead he was nicknamed Chateau. It was short for chateaubriand and
stood for a kid who had nothing and wanted the best.
</P>
<P>
   When Sharpe came out of high school, it was Sterling who
convinced him to skip going to the service and give college
football a try at the Division II school. After college, Sharpe
wasn't taken until the 192nd pick of the 1990 NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos gamble paid off. Sharpe is a seven-time NFL All Pro
selection and already ranks third in NFL history _ behind Ozzie
Newsome and Jackie Smith _ in career receiving yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever my play doesn't match my quotes, people will quit
listening to me,'' Sharpe said with a candidness that is often on
the mark. He praises Falcons coach Dan Reeves, who, as the old
Broncos coach, ``believed in me when no one else did. When I see
him we always hug.''
</P>
<P>
   He minces no words when he says the current flap between
quarterback John Elway, Shanahan and Reeves, ``should have been
taken to the high road this week,'' and he makes sense when he said
``there should be a flag for celebration dances if a player's team
is down by more than 14 points.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Atlanta cornerback Ray Buchanan, who showed up Tuesday
wearing a big spiked dog collar to poke fun at the Falcons underdog
role, Sharpe just shook his head: ``He's another one. Who ever
heard of Ray Buchanan before he ever came to Atlanta a year ago?''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe spares almost no one: ``I won't talk about your mother,
your girlfriend or your wife, but other than that . . . If you have
a deformity I'll talk about that.''
</P>
<P>
   As he was talking, the public address announcer said ``the
Broncos session is over. Sharpe momentarily glared _ ``if that guy
interrupts me one more time,'' _ and then picked up where he had
left off.
</P>
<P>
   And as you walked away and he talked on, you remembered
something else he's said about the birth of his babble: ``I
remember my grandma would say child, `Wait 'til you get to school
to talk.' And the teacher would say, `Wait 'til you get home to do
your talking.' Both of 'em wanted me to find someplace else to
talk.''
</P>
<P>
   And now he had.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Archdeacon writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
