<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9675 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBOT-GRADERS-EDUC-AR     01-26 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBOT-GRADERS-EDUC-ART-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MACHINES WILL GRADE STUDENTS' ESSAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Colo.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nothing personal. But if your application to the business school
of your choice is rejected later this year, a cold, unfeeling
machine may be at least partly responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning early in February, the two essay questions on the
Graduate Management Admission Test, taken by about 200,000
business-school applicants every year, will be scored by both a
human being and an electronic robot called the ``E-rater'' (as in
``e-mail'').
</P>
<P>
   The essay scoring system was devised by the Educational Testing
Service of Princeton, N.J., a nonprofit educational measurement and
research organization, after more than five years of research and
experimentation. Educators, not all of whom are thrilled about
machines whose inventors claim they are able to read and grade
essays, believe the technology will soon spread throughout the
field of educational testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've given it a thorough trial and are confident that E-rater
will provide a valuable assessment tool,'' said Frederic McHale, a
spokesman for the Graduate Management Admission Council, which owns
and sponsors the test which is is administered by the Educational
Testing Service.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, two experts have read each essay, assigning a grade
ranging from a low of 0 to a high of 6. If the readers differ by
more than a point, the essay goes to a third expert reader, who
assigns a final score.
</P>
<P>
   The E-rater will serve as a second reader. To prevent the
computer from dominating the procedure, if the electronic score
differs from the expert reader's score by more than a point, the
essay will be judged by a second human being before going to a
final referee if the readers still disagree.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, electronic grading has drawn sharp criticism from those
who say a computer cannot judge creativity. ``Computers can judge
only what's been fed into them,'' said Trent Anderson, a spokesman
for Kaplan Educational Centers, a major test-preparation company.
``And a creative writer is someone who writes something that's
never been seen before. Consequently, the computer cannot know
whether what it's reading is good or bad.''
</P>
<P>
   McHale defended E-rater by agreeing with Anderson. ``We're not
measuring creative writing,'' he said. ``We know we can't do that.
Instead, we are assessing organized thoughts through writing on
very specific topics. What we look for are such things as the
organization of ideas and syntactical structure. These things can
be scored by a computer.''
</P>
<P>
   McHale said his company decided to develop the E-rater to cut
costs, to provide test-takers with their scores more quickly and to
improve the objectivity of test scoring. He also said the
technology developed by the Educational Testing Service would be
used to provide instructional services, teaching students how to
improve their writing skills as they take practice tests.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan has issued a list of ``strategies'' likely to impress its
hard-wired brain. These include stressing the importance of making
an outline before writing a test essay, using such transitional
phrases as ``therefore,'' ``since'' and ``for example,'' and using
plenty of synonyms, because ``the computer rewards a strong
vocabulary.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The technology for the E-rater dates to the interest in
artificial intelligence in World War II, which gathered force in
the 1960s with the development of computational linguistics _ the
merging of computer science with the study of language.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, researchers were trying to design a machine that
could read a book and create an index for it. The effort was
successful; today, many word processors can manage the task.
</P>
<P>
   Soon money became available from the federal government and
private industry to advance the study. The Defense Department was
interested in developing language-translating machines, and
telephone companies wanted speech-recognition computers. In
general, they got what they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   A breakthrough came about two years ago, when a development team
at Educational Testing Services led by Jill Burstein invented the
E-rater.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key was that we figured a way to combine many of the
technologies that had been developed up to that time,'' Ms.
Burstein said. ``These included looking at syntactic structure like
finding a subordinate clause, analyzing discourse structure like
where a discussion starts and ends, and looking at topical content
like examining vocabulary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting all this together,'' she continued, ``made possible a
machine for reliable automated essay scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   What lies ahead?
</P>
<P>
   More literate robots in and out of the classroom, specialists
say.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Landauer, a professor of psychology at the University of
Colorado at Boulder who is a longtime researcher in the field, says
he expects that someday the descendants of the E-rater will be able
to teach as well as grade test papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never before had a tool that could help a student learn
without the presence of a teacher,'' Landauer said. ``But soon we
will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
