slipping,'' he said shouting above fellow traders who were bidding
down the long-term prices of a variety of commodities. As Brazil's
currency has dropped 30 percent, a broad range of U.S. commodities
have also fallen in price. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) CHICAGO -- Jan. 26, 1999 -- BRAZIL-PRICES-1, 1-26 --
Traders on the floor of the Chicago Board of Trade call out trades
in the soy bean pit last week. As Brazil's currency has dropped 30
percent in the last two weeks, a broad range of goods, including
wheat and soybeans, have fallen seven percent, according to key
measures of commodity prices. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
