bat mitzvah. Newberg decided to use her bat mitzvah as an
opportunity to honor the sacrifices made by victims and heroes of
the Holocaust. (Tom Herde/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- Jan. 26, 1999 -- BOEING-EARNINGS, 1-26 -- An
F-15 fighter, purchased by Israel, lands after a test flight last
year. Boeing's profit, before a tax credit, increased 55 percent in
the fourth quarter as easing production bottlenecks and strong
sales of military fighters offset weak margins in the
commercial-jet business. The earnings exceeded expectations by 3
cents a share. (Boeing/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Jan. 26, 1999 -- MASTER-CLASSES-2, 1-26 --
Are master classes for the musicians or the audience? Marilyn Horne
with Tamara Mesic. Promised is a win-win-win situation. The student
learns. The master shows not only depth of learning but also
compassion for one's inferiors. And the music lover in the seats
sees a bit of music from the inside out and learns the tips and
tidbits that apparently turn dross into gold. (Sara Krulwich/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Jan. 26, 1999 -- MASTER-CLASSES-1, 1-26 -- A
master's tips: Leontyne Price with Robert Perry. The musical master
class is an odd combination of show business and personal tutoring
whereby a series of students play or sing briefly over the course
of a few hours and receive brief words of wisdom from the master in
attendance. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Jan. 26, 1999 -- PARADISE-HOTEL, 1-26 -- Tom
Pearl in Richard Foreman's ``Paradise Hotel,'' at the
Ontological-Hysteric Theater. The production's essential premise is
that sex really isn't sexy, something the performance fully
confirms. But at least the show is up front about its intentions,
and it manages to generate considerable wit and energy in carrying
them out. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Jan. 26, 1999 -- OTTER-OPERA, 1-26 -- Anne
Sofie von Otter, a Swedish mezzo-soprano, appears at Alice Tully
Hall on Wednesday night. Now 43, she would seem to be at her peak,
a compelling artist who brings a wide range of colors and nuanced
shadings to her interpretations and who likes to explore unusual
repertory. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Jan. 26, 1999 -- MANDOLINE-2, 1-26 -- Layers
of yam teeter in a gratin at Mesa Grill. What makes this gratin so
exceptional? The precise slicing of the yams. The secret of such
perfection, the tool that no chef would live without, is the
mandoline. With this slicing tool, they can cut carrots on an angle
into exactly one-sixteenth-inch slices. (Michael Rogol/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- Jan. 26, 1999 -- MANDOLINE-1, 1-26 -- A Bron
mandoline makes apple slices almost translucent. The mandoline is
in many ways more useful than a food processor, which is cumbersome
and offers little flexibility. (Michael Rogol/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 26, 1999 -- IMPEACH-SCENE-3, 1-26 --
Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, outside a Republican caucus
room Tuesday on Capitol Hill. Senators met to debate the question
of whether to end the trial of President Clinton now or yield to a
call by House Republican managers for witnesses. (Carol T.
Powers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 26, 1999 -- IMPEACH-SCENE-2, 1-26 --
Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., speaks to reporters before Tuesday's
session of President Clinton's impeachment trial. Senators met on
Tuesday to debate the question of whether to end the trial now or
yield to House Republican managers call for witnesses. (Carol T.
Powers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 26, 1999 -- IMPEACH-SCENE-1, 1-26 --
Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., talks with reporters before going into a
Democratic caucus on Tuesday. Byrd presented a motion on Monday in
the Senate trial of President Clinton to dismiss the case without a
verdict. (Carol T. Powers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 26, 1999 -- IMPEACH-RDP-1, 1-26 --
Monica Lewinsky leaves her hotel in Washington on Tuesday. Lewinsky
