<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9678 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      01-26 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE APOSTLE OF HYPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (nk)  
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The only real question was: How far would Bill
Clinton go to ingratiate himself with the pope?
</P>
<P>
   Would he wear a black mantilla?
</P>
<P>
   Would he kiss the pontiff's ring?
</P>
<P>
   Would the Jesuit-educated Baptist married to the Methodist try,
as the saying goes, to be more Catholic than the pope?
</P>
<P>
   The president is so ingratiating toward the world leaders he
meets with that he actually takes on some of their coloration. With
Helmut Kohl, he expanded with satisfaction. With Boris Yeltsin, he
grew jovial and ruddy. With Nelson Mandela, he drew himself up
straighter.
</P>
<P>
   But this was a tricky one, even for the Great Empath. After
ignoring so many ``Thou shalt not's,'' how could Clinton snuggle up
to John Paul II and wrap himself in the beatific glow of His
Holiness' holiness?
</P>
<P>
   Two of the president's most rabid tormentors, Henry Hyde and his
impeachment lawyer, David Schippers, are devout Catholics who
became papal knights together at a ceremony in Cleveland three
years ago. The House managers were trying Tuesday to lasso Clinton
into making an appearance at his impeachment trial, even as he was
seeking papal indulgence. It would be so helpful, in the
president's personal journey toward atonement, if he could get the
pope to bless his spin.
</P>
<P>
   So there they were Tuesday in a dark, stuffy airplane hanger, an
astonishing odd couple.
</P>
<P>
   The infallible and the inordinately fallible. The moral pillar
and the moral contortionist. The Holy Father and the very Prodigal
Son.
</P>
<P>
   The sign on the bathroom behind the stage where the two leaders
met illustrated the elite nature of the summit, even harder to get
into than the closed-door Senate session. It read: ``President or
Holy Father Only.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an amazing spectacle of religion vs. religiosity.
</P>
<P>
   The pope tries to use religion to make the world a better place.
Clinton uses religiosity tactically to get beyond his troubles with
carnality and mendacity, quoting the Bible, praying with Jesse
Jackson and bringing a team of ministers into the White House to
work on his soul.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a group of scholars on Monday night at a White House
``Millennium Evening,'' the president told them, ``You all know I
am a walking apostle of hope.'' The pope, who ordinarily loves to
lecture Americans about personal morality at the drop of a miter,
steered clear of Clinton's personal morality, in his remarks and in
their private meeting. He gave a sermon against abortion and
euthanasia.
</P>
<P>
   The pope was cordial and businesslike but the president tried
for the personal. Always the respectful protege with older leaders,
Clinton took the pope's arm and helped him around the stage. In his
speech, the president put in a plug for sinners.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still need to hear your message that all are God's
children, all have fallen short of His glory,'' he told John Paul
II. Maybe the pope, who decries capitalism while allowing himself
to be marketed like a sports superstar, wanted to get a boost from
the popular president.
</P>
<P>
   Moral clarity is all well and good, but you've got to keep those
poll numbers up. This month CNN/USA Today/Gallup released a poll in
which the president easily trumped the pope in a contest for Most
Admired Man. Even though the Republicans keep foaming at the mouth,
the president has proved you can govern without moral authority.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, the pope did not want a repeat of last year's visit to
Cuba. Proving that sin gets bigger ratings than spirituality, the
anchors deserted him when the Monica story broke, dashing back to
get all the details.
</P>
<P>
   Before he was felled by sin himself during the 1996 campaign,
Dick Morris bragged that he was running Clinton not as president,
but as pope.
</P>
<P>
   Morris' theory was that you did not need personal values if you
had public values. As he recalled on Fox TV, before the State of
the Union: ``If you wanted to get voters that were turned off by
the way the president behaved in private, he needed to be
advocating a values agenda in public that would appeal to those
people, not economic, but values. ... In other words, essentially,
what the president is doing is saying, `I'm going to help you raise
your children into being better adults than I am.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bill Clinton's moral and ethical sloppiness is less
heinous than the unforgiving and hypocritical behavior of Henry
Hyde, Bob Barr and their lynch mob.
</P>
<P>
   It is worse to refuse to forgive than to need forgiveness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
