<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9680 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE-COX     01-26 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pope brings message to Middle America
 &HT;    By Charlise Lyles
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Pope John Paul II, stooped, his hands trembling,
beckoned to the young of the Roman Catholic Church to ``be a light
to the world'' in the century to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the world itself seems filled with darkness,'' the
pontiff said Tuesday night. ``The darkness of children who go
hungry and even die. The darkness of homeless people who lack work
and proper medical care. The darkness of violence: violence against
the unborn child, violence in families, the violence of gangs, the
violence of sexual abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands crammed the streets, four and five people
deep, in a wave of humanity seeking to lay eyes on the 78-year-old
pontiff, reaching out to touch those trembling hands.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Dickmann did not touch him. She did not even get close
when the pope entered the Kiel Center where he spoke to 20,000 who
attended the Walk in the Light Youth Rally. But the 19-year-old
University of Dayton freshman said that she felt the Holy Father's
aura of goodness just the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that I will be a better person because of this,''
said Dickmann. ``I believe I will be better in my faith.''
</P>
<P>
   About 4:30 p.m. Monday, after UD classes, Dickmann and a dozen
friends piled in a van and a car and drove six hours through the
heartland to the suburban St. Louis home of Dickmann's parents. At
11 p.m. they made a run for cheesy St. Louis-style pizza. Between 2
a.m. and 4:30 a.m., they tried to sleep. But Mountain Dew and a
Santa Claus-like anticipation kept their eyes open, their mouths
chattering and giggling.
</P>
<P>
   She dressed hurriedly in 5:30 a.m. darkness, downed a breakfast
bar, and the group was off to the pickup point for the downtown
rally.
</P>
<P>
   The confluence of events, the approaching millennium, the moral
debacle that the nation finds itself in as President Clinton faces
an impeachment trial and the pope's message to youth, flowed into a
moment in time that the students felt they should not miss.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, some downtown streets surrounding the Papal
Plaza were empty. So were many parking spaces. The city's
Metro-Link subway had transported only a fourth of expected riders,
St. Louis Mayor Clarence Harmon told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we gave a party and nobody came,'' he said at
midday, imploring residents to come downtown to greet the pontiff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely surprised and disappointed that there aren't
more people,'' said Pamela Day, a Dallas health-care worker who
drove her mother and three children to St. Louis. ``Especially in
comparison to the reception he got in Mexico. I don't want him to
be disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Some speculated that media predictions of heavy traffic and
crowds kept many away.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day President Clinton and first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton
</P>
<P>
   As Pope John Paul II stepped onto St. Louis soil at 1:23 p.m.
Central Daylight Time at Lambert International Airport, the youth
watching the televised arrival from inside the Kiel Center let out
a deafening shouts of jubilation, then fell silent in prayer. Some
held hands. In some eyes, tears glistened.
</P>
<P>
   By about 6:30 p.m., when the ``POpemobile'' rounded the corner
of Olive Street bound for the youth rally, crowds had swelled
considerably. As dusk fell over the city, a chilly wind whipped
after a sunny day of unseasonably balmy 45-degree weather. The Holy
Spirit Adoration Sisters, known as ``the Pink Sisters,'' had been
assigned to pray for good weather.
</P>
<P>
   In his white skullcap and cassock, the 264th successor to Peter
cut an odd figure against a backdrop of vintage Americana _ Mark
Twain's Mississippi River and floating casinos.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day of sharp contrast. There was the unbridled energy
of youth and there was withering age. Holy serenity and
pandemonium.
</P>
<P>
   There was a pope who has spoken in Mexico against greedy
capitalism as vendors hawked his holy image on souvenir mugs,
T-shirts and scarves for as much as $20.
</P>
<P>
   Bomb-sniffing hounds and police with semiautomatic weapons
cleared the way for a messenger of universal peace and love.
</P>
<P>
   There were the masses and a single man.
</P>
<P>
   They saw John Paul the showman. Once an aspiring actor and
playwright, he oozed charisma. ``I am feeling this is awesome,'' he
told the youth rally.
</P>
<P>
   They heard John Paul the uncompromising moral force. ``Do not
listen to those who encourage you to lie, to shirk responsibility,
to put yourselves first. Do not listen to those who tell you that
chastity is passe.''
</P>
<P>
   The night before, member s of three church reform groups had
gathered for a candlelight vcigial at the cathedral basiclia of St.
Louie to protest the churcsh's refuse to ordain women. But int he
crowd that greeted the pope, some could hardly bring themselves to
speak in oppossition to church teachings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women in leadership is an issue,'' said Mary McKeirnan, 42, as
the papal motorcade approached. ``But he is so uplifting. And the
man has done so much for social justice. He is a pope for the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   And they heard John Paul the recruiter of church personnel.
``Each of you has a special mission in life and you are each called
to be a disciple of Christ,'' he said. ``Many of you will serve God
as priests and religious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt the pope's visit will encourage other young
people to join the vocation,'' said Sister Catherine Marie of the
Dominican Sisisters of St. Cecelia in Nashville, Tenn. Flanking her
were 30 novitiate nuns, ages 17 to 30, their habits bouncing as
they cheered the pope.
</P>
<P>
   And they heard John Paul the lover of young people, who has
spoken he Gospel to thousands of Catholic youth in Mexico City,
Paris and dozens of his 85 trips outside Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Charlise Lyles writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
