<SLUG> BC-KTEL-CUSTOM-CD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUSTOM CD PLAN SENDS K-TEL'S STOCK UP THE CHARTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Shares in K-tel International Inc. rose as much
as 10 percent on news that the company will offer custom-made music
CDs through its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   K-tel stock closed up 87.5 cents Tuesday at $11.875, for a daily
gain of 7.95 percent. More than 884,000 shares traded hands, or 1{
times the issue's 30-day average trading volume.
</P>
<P>
   The direct music marketer, best known for kitschy television
commercials in the 1970s and '80s, enjoyed a virtual rebirth last
year after moving to an Internet-based business model. Tuesday's
announcement is another step for the organization along that road,
company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In offering custom-made CDs, which customers order by mixing and
matching compositions from a 4,000-item song list, K-tel joins the
likes of Musicmaker.com, online music retailer CDNow and the
now-defunct MyCD.com. The first two each offer far more songs than
K-tel to choose from, but those companies must pay royalties to the
artists. K-tel owns the rights to its songs outright.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a margin standpoint we have a big competitive
advantage,'' said Scott Blum, head of K-tel's online operations.
</P>
<P>
   K-tel's discs are also cheaper. The company charges $10 for 10
songs and 99 cents for each additional track. Other sites typically
charge $15 to $16 for up to 70 minutes of music. Blum declined to
say how much revenue K-tel expects to generate from its custom
music business.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the suburban Calabasas-based company have surged twice
in the past year, first on news that it was switching to an
Internet model and then that it had signed a licensing deal with
Microsoft. In each instance, K-tel shares climbed to nearly $40
before tumbling back down.
</P>
<P>
   K-tel faces an avalanche of lawsuits stemming from allegations
that it tried to hide from investors the fact that it was being
investigated by the Nasdaq stock exchange last fall for failing to
meet listing requirements.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
