A9683 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABY-DNA-IDENTIFY-NYT     01-26 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-DNA-IDENTIFY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA TRIES USING DNA SAMPLING TO PROTECT CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLANTATION, Fla. _ Lying in a hospital bed a day after giving
birth to her second child, Yanith Martinez has only the highest
hopes for her baby, Valeria.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want her to be an excellent mother and a great
professional,'' she said, signs of fatigue still evident in her
countenance.
</P>
<P>
   But grim reality, not hope, held the upper hand last week, when
Ms. Martinez became one of the first mothers in the nation to allow
the hospital to take a sample of her infant's DNA, along with her
footprints. The blood nurses drew from Valeria's tiny heel will
allow the child, or her body, to be identified should she ever be
switched with another baby, abducted, murdered or mutilated beyond
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``God forbid you should ever need it,'' Ms. Martinez said. ``My
neighborhood is quite calm, with little crime, but you move around,
so you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerned over a recent rash of highly publicized cases of child
molestation, abuse and mutilation, the Florida Department of Law
Enforcement has begun to encourage hospitals to offer parents not
only footprints of their children, but also samples of their
children's blood, which, like all substances of the body, carry
their genetic blueprint, or DNA, in an attempt to better trace
those who fall victim to violent crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The program, the only one of its kind in the country, came to
life last December, weeks after Juan Carlos Chavez, a 31-year-old
handyman, was sentenced to death in the abduction, rape and murder
of 9-year-old Jimmy Ryce in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Traces of Jimmy's dismembered body were discovered near Chavez's
home in south Miami-Dade County three months after his
disappearance. Investigators were forced to use DNA extracted from
the traces and compare it with that of Jimmy's parents in order to
identify the body.
</P>
<P>
   Although Florida does not lead the nation in crimes against
children, the state, which has sophisticated equipment for DNA
testing, has become a pioneer in the use of DNA as a form of
identification.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before his death in December, Gov. Lawton Chiles made
child welfare a priority, and victims' parents have made an effort
to bring the plight of their children to public attention.
</P>
<P>
   So far, nine hospitals have volunteered to offer parents the
blood samples, and state officials hope the practice will become
common, eventually replacing footprints as the primary form of
identification.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Nash, the director of the Woman's Pavilion at Plantation
Medical Hospital, said extracting the blood cost the hospital about
$1.40 per child but was being offered free.
</P>
<P>
   The sample is taken from blood that is routinely extracted from
a newborn's heel for a series of state-mandated tests for diseases
like sickle cell anemia and PKU, a rare disorder that can lead to
brain damage or mental retardation.
</P>
<P>
   The sample consists of three droplets of blood that are placed
on special paper the size of a small index card. The paper is
designed to preserve the DNA in the blood for at least 100 years.
The samples are put inside envelopes and given only to the parents
who can store them in a safe-deposit box, the freezer of a
refrigerator or the pages of a Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are seeking to expand the program to include older
children. Next month, four elementary schools in northern Florida
will begin offering free blood samples to parents of the students.
</P>
<P>
   And a bill that would require the state's hospitals to offer the
test to parents of newborns at a ``reasonable price'' is in a
committee of the Florida House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is only the first step in our effort to make the option
available to all parents of all children,'' said Bill Hebrock,
chairman of the Missing Children's Information Clearing House
Advisory Board, which was created by Chiles at the behest of Jimmy
Ryce's parents.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy's parents, Don and Claudine Ryce, who are members of the
advisory board, say their son's fate could have been discovered
much sooner if they had owned a preserved sample of his blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know if your child is going to be taken by a
predator,'' Mrs. Ryce said. ``We believe any caring parent would
want to have a DNA sample.''
</P>
</TEXT>
