<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: YOUR TABLE IS READY  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. _ Near the front desk at Joe's Stone Crab
restaurant, three dozen people were waiting to be seated when the
maitre d'hotel, Dennis Sutton, heard a voice say, ``The 20 Broncos
are here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bring 'em in,'' Sutton said.
</P>
<P>
   They had arrived in three white stretch limousines from their
Fort Lauderdale hotel and now, as those waiting quickly stepped
aside, these big, burly Bronco offensive linemen moved in single
file through the foyer and the bar to the long table set up for 20
_ the linemen, two assistant coaches, three equipment men and some
of their buddies.
</P>
<P>
   As others in the restaurant stared, this, too, was the Super
Bowl, especially for the Broncos' offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a dinner like this in San Diego a year ago before we
won,'' tackle Tony Jones recalled. ``But when they brought us sushi
to start, some of us couldn't look at it. I told 'em, `Bring me a
steak.'''
</P>
<P>
   Some people were surely at Joe's Stone Crab to dine on Monday
night, but the Broncos were there to eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the guys had never had stone crabs before, but they
loved them,'' K.C. Jones, the backup center who knew the restaurant
from having played at the University of Miami, said Tuesday.
``Everybody ate until they were content, but nobody overate. We
know what we're here for, to beat the Falcons on Sunday _ but
you've got to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, the Broncos' tab was $1,856.92, including
$1,039 for 20 jumbo orders of stone crabs, the Florida delicacy
that made this Miami Beach restaurant famous. It also included
$79.75 for five stone crab cocktails and $59.60 for 14 orders of
key lime pie, plus $11 for two a la mode. Their bar bill for drinks
and beer was $317.50.
</P>
<P>
   ``To pay the tab,'' center Tom Nalen said, ``we used the fine
money from our kangaroo court.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Nalen, the court treasurer, more than $5,000 in
fines had accumulated this season from violations that only the
Bronco offensive linemen recognize.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got fined $100,'' Nalen said, laughing, ``for my wife's
picture being in the Game Day program.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We get fined for crazy stuff like that,'' Tony Jones said.
``Like if your wife gets caught on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   As offensive lines go, these Broncos are different. On most
National Football League teams, offensive linemen weigh more than
300 pounds, the better to block the defensive linemen who weigh
more than 300 pounds. But all of these Broncos are listed at less
than 300.
</P>
<P>
   Not that they're undernourished, but from left to right, the
starters are the 291-pound tackle Tony Jones, the 287-pound guard
Mark Schlereth, the 286-pound Nalen, the 281-pound guard Don Neil
and the 293-pound tackle Harry Swayne _ pro football's lightest
offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   They're usually the quietest line, too.
</P>
<P>
   During the season they prefer not to talk with the news media,
under penalty of a fine from their kangaroo court, but at the Super
Bowl they must be available to talk on Tuesday, Wednesday and
Thursday, under penalty of a fine from the NFL office.
</P>
<P>
   They're also pro football's quickest and most efficient
offensive line, with two of the best assistant coaches: Alex Gibbs
and Barney Chavous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line,'' quarterback John Elway has said, ``is that
our offensive line doesn't get enough credit. They are the nucleus
of where our offense starts. If they're not doing it up front,
Terrell Davis doesn't have the holes and we don't have the time to
throw the ball. They're the guys that deserve the credit and don't
get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlereth, completing his 10th season, has two Super Bowl rings
(the 1991 Redskins and the 1997 Broncos) despite having had more
than 20 operations, primarily for damaged knees and spinal disks.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me,'' he said, ``everything is a game _ cleaning the
kitchen, putting the kids to bed. How many operations can you
endure and still continue to play? Well, all I know is that it's
been a challenge to play through all those injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   And on Monday night it was a challenge for all the Bronco
offensive linemen to eat all those stone crabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any real big eaters now,'' Lane said. ``When we
had Brian Habib, now he was a big eater. He ate everything in
sight. He'd eat dinner, then he'd have a snack an hour later.''
</P>
<P>
   What did Habib weigh?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not much,'' Lane said. ``Maybe 290.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
