</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTIES VOLLEY OVER GOP PLAN FOR DEPOSING THREE WITNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (DELETES reference to invitation to Clinton from 2nd graf, which
gave it too much emphasis. Adds phrase in 4th graf to make it clear
that only 51 votes are needed for passage.) (See related stories: IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-TRIAL,
IMPEACH-TWO-STEP, IMPEACH-SESSIONS, IMPEACH-LEWINSKY,
IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-REPUBS, HUBBELL-TAXES, STARR-LEAKS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(fe) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT and LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Democrats warned on Tuesday that calling
witnesses in President Clinton's impeachment trial would prolong
the proceedings, but Republicans countered with a plan to appease
skittish moderates that would limit the time for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   The off-the-floor skirmishing, which spilled onto the Senate
floor in closed debate Tuesday night, came after House Republican
prosecutors strengthened their case for witnesses by paring their
proposed list to three people who would, at this point, give
depositions that would be closed to the public: Monica Lewinsky,
Vernon Jordan and Sidney Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday senators are likely to adhere to party lines and
vote against dismissing the two impeachment articles. But a second
vote, on whether to depose the three potential witnesses, is too
close to call, senators said, although both sides said the momentum
was moving toward passage.
</P>
<P>
   One senior Republican senator, Ted Stevens of Alaska, said that
the motion to question witnesses would win more than the 51 votes
required for passage, estimating that it might be in the range of
53-59.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Republicans cobbled together a proposal
governing how witnesses would be handled, hoping it would satisfy
undecided senators in both parties. At a Republican caucus Tuesday
morning, Sen. John Chafee of Rhode Island offered a plan to limit
the questioning of each witness to three hours by the prosecutors
and three hours by the White House and to videotape the witnesses
so senators not at the interviews could gauge their demeanor and
credibility. Some senators suggested that excerpts from the
videotapes could be used in place of live witnesses before the
Senate itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very rational, a very modest proposal,'' said Sen.
Mike DeWine, R-Ohio. ``It is important for many of us who took the
oath, who are still weighing the evidence, who really want to see
these key witnesses testify, to have the opportunity to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader, supports
the plan, which could become the centerpiece of a resolution that
guides the Senate through the deposition phase of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate could vote on the plan as early as Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing that they were losing the battle over witnesses,
Democrats immediately took the microphones to play on Republican
fears of a protracted and unseemly spectacle. Democrats cautioned
that by opening the door to witnesses, Republicans would also have
to allow White House lawyers to peruse the 54,000 pages of House
documents they have not seen, as well as documents held by the
independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, a process they said could take
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our colleagues need to clearly understand that if it's a
choice between expeditious and fair, Democrats are going to fall on
the side of fairness,'' said Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the
Democratic leader.
</P>
<P>
   The White House would also have the right to call witnesses,
which presidential aides said would entail lengthy preparations.
``This motion for witnesses is a motion to delay,'' said a White
House spokesman, James Kennedy. ``It makes delay a certainty. There
is no doubt about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans immediately accused Democrats of employing
scare tactics to derail what they said was a legitimate part of any
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that White House has made a threat,'' said Sen.
Jon Kyl, a Republican from Arizona. ``It is not an appropriate way
to influence the Senate in deciding whether to grant the House
managers' motion.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering the third week of the trial, the Senate seems close to
following the same partisan script that engulfed the House's
contentious impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Lott and Daschle have consulted each other regularly through the
trial and brokered an unusual unanimous agreement that has steered
the Senate proceedings up to now.
</P>
<P>
   But aides to Daschle said he had not been told of Chafee's plan,
and several Republican senators said they would use their majority
to muscle the framework for questioning witnesses, if need be.
Daschle, however, has rebuffed several Republican invitations to
talk about witnesses, saying that should wait until after the vote
on depositions.
</P>
<P>
   As Senate Republicans and Democrats jockeyed over the witness
question in corridors, private hideaways and, by Tuesday night, on
the Senate floor itself, Lott was promoting a strategy to end the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Under that approach, the Senate would vote to find that Clinton
had committed the offenses charged in the two articles of
impeachment: perjury and obstruction of justice. After that,
senators would take a second vote on whether to remove him from
office.
</P>
<P>
   It was difficult to judge what chances such a plan would have of
being accepted by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst for Tuesday's off-the-floor maneuvering was the
House prosecutors' decision, under pressure from Senate
Republicans, to trim their witness list to three people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't what we would like, but we have to be realistic,''
Rep. Henry Hyde, the lead prosecutor, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were virtually united in opposing witnesses. ``They're
just reiterating what they've said from Day 1,'' said Barbara Boxer
of California.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, for the most part, praised the prosecutors. But
Sen. Susan Collins of Maine expressed dismay that they did not put
Betty Currie, the president's secretary, on the list. ``I'm really
surprised and disappointed,'' Collins said. ``She's central to the
obstruction-of-justice charges, and it's going to be harder to
resolve that without her.''
</P>
<P>
   A House Republican aide said the House managers decided that
Mrs. Currie probably would not clear up the question of whether
Clinton was trying to coach her about Ms. Lewinsky's visits to the
White House and would not resolve whether the president directed
her to retrieve gifts he gave Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the House prosecutors asked the Senate to consider,
but not vote on, whether to invite Clinton to submit to
questioning. Sen. Orrin Hatch, Republican of Utah, said that
senators would welcome the president's testimony but should not
compel it, a common view among most senators.
</P>
<P>
   Lott has not decided whether to request that Clinton testify, a
senior Republican aide said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
