<SLUG> BC-CHEMICALS-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEMICAL INDUSTRY PLANS TO ASSESS PRODUCT SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years _ maybe decades _ the chemical industry has argued
that its products are safe, and environmentalists have hollered
back, ``Prove it.'' On Wednesday the Chemical Manufacturers
Association will announce that the industry is spending more than
$1 billion to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are going to advocate decisions based on sound science,
we darned well better have some good science to base them on,''
said Lawrence Wilson, chairman of the big chemical company Rohm &AMP;
Haas, and a member of the association's research committee.
</P>
<P>
   At a luncheon in Washington on Wednesday, the chemical industry
plans to spell out the particulars of a six-year research program
that will gather data on toxicity and other details of nearly 3,000
so-called high production volume chemicals, common substances like
turpentine or acetylene that are produced or imported in quantities
of more than 1 million pounds a year.
</P>
<P>
   Some 15,000 chemical and pesticide ingredients will be screened
to see whether they adversely affect human endocrine systems, and
the mechanisms by which whole families of chemicals _ say, salts,
or halogens _ act on the environment or human health will be
studied.
</P>
<P>
   Although that last effort will probably account for only $100
million of the money, it is generating most of the interest. Many
scientists think it will provide the means to determine when it
does or does not make sense to extrapolate from epidemiological
studies and animal tests to assessments of a chemical's human
health risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will let us apply our understanding of how one chemical
behaves to predicting how a whole class of chemicals will act,''
said Roger McClellan, president of the Chemical Industry Institute
of Toxicology, the industry-financed research center that first
raised an alarm about the link between formaldehyde and nasal
cancers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will not just gather data and do tests, but they will do
true research that can develop better test protocols,'' said Dr.
Lynn Goldman, a pediatrician who until a month ago was the
Environmental Protection Agency's chief chemicals regulator and is
now a visiting scientist at Johns Hopkins University.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of the new initiative were presaged on April 21, the eve
of Earth Day, when Vice President Al Gore announced his support for
filling in the data gaps on common chemicals. In November the
chemical association said its members would probably devote $700
million toward that end.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the research initiative is a pre-emptive strike.
``Public policy is increasingly based on science, but without good
data, policy-makers can fall back on overly conservative
assumptions,'' said M.L. Mullins, a vice president of the chemical
association. Translation: The environmental agency and others could
pass rules that make it difficult to introduce new products.
</P>
<P>
   The industry has promised to post all its data on the
association's Web page (www.cma.org) as the data come in.
Eventually it hopes to have a setup in which people could type in
their zip codes and find out the composition and health data on any
chemicals made in their localities.
</P>
<P>
   The approach is already garnering support from what is usually
the opposing camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has total and continuous public transparency, and that in
itself is unique,'' said David Roe, a senior lawyer for the
Environmental Defense Fund, whose 1997 study, ``Toxic Ignorance,''
charged that there was a lack of adequate health data for more than
70 percent of chemicals produced in high volume.
</P>
<P>
   Still, data that spring from company files and
industry-sponsored research inspire skepticism along with trust.
``This is an important step in the right direction, but we will
work with them closely to ensure that all the research is done with
the right checks and balances,'' said Carol Browner, the
administrator of environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are that it will be, said Kenneth Olden, director of the
National Institute for Environmental Health Sciences. Referring to
the industry's toxicology institute, Olden said, ``The CIIT has
always operated fairly and independently and it subjects its
research to the most rigorous peer review.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
