<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9696 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-BOS &LR;      01-26 1504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS SEEK THREE WITNESSES AT CLINTON TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Frustrated House managers sought subpoenas Tuesday
for only ``a pitiful three'' witnesses, including Monica S.
Lewinsky, as the Senate's Republican majority moved toward
extending the impeachment trial of President Clinton, to the
outrage of his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The House team, abandoning hopes of calling as many as 15
witnesses, also asked the Senate to subpoena Clinton's friend,
Vernon E. Jordan Jr., and a senior White House aide, Sidney
Blumenthal, to bolster the case for removing the 42d president from
office.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise twist, the House Republican managers also
``requested'' that Clinton submit to a deposition, which the White
House promptly rejected.
</P>
<P>
   The managers dropped their plan to subpoena Clinton's personal
secretary, Betty Currie, as they struggled to fashion a narrow
witness list that would satisfy a majority of senators.
</P>
<P>
   The developments unfolded as the Senate came close to polarizing
over the witness issue, threatening to shatter the fragile
bipartisanship of the proceedings. The events played out in
split-screen as some television networks showed both the Senate
proceedings and scenes from St. Louis, where Clinton met with Pope
John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   Facing back-to-back votes Wednesday, the Senate was poised to
defeat a Democratic-sponsored motion to dismiss the impeachment
charges and approve the request by House Republicans for witnesses,
according to members of both parties. Senators secretly debated the
issues for four hours Tuesday night in their second closed-door
deliberations of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Olympia J. Snowe, a Maine Republican, said after the
session that members of both parties are seeking a compromise to
avoid partisan votes Tuesday. Members of both parties said two
senators _ Sam Brownback, a Kansas Republican, and Tom Harkin, an
Iowa Democrat _ were working on a bipartisan plan for the next
phase of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's back on,'' Harkin said of cooperation between the
parties.
</P>
<P>
   After a long day of attacks and counterattacks, the private
session appeared to have fostered fresh concern for restoring
decorum and completing the trial under a compromise pact.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want this to become perceived as being partisan,
so we're trying to find a way to avoid that,'' said Senator John F.
Kerry. ``Whether that's possible, we don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted 58-41 to keep Tuesday night's debate secret.
Kerry, who had voted to open the first session, took the opposite
position Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He issued a statement saying he voted to close the session ``in
order to respect and protect the privacy of the named witnesses and
the identity of potential witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The movement toward approving the witness request marked a
pivotal shift among Senate Republicans, just two days after several
GOP senators predicted the trial could end as early as this week
without a witness phase.
</P>
<P>
   ``There clearly has been a dramatic change,'' said Senator Phil
Gramm, a Texas Republican, before the private deliberations. ``I
believe it is now certain we will have witnesses on the floor of
the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers and Senate Democrats warned that a witness
phase would prolong the trial for weeks, if not months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has a right to defend himself properly, which
means calling Linda Tripp, calling Ken Starr, showing the
unfairness, demonstrating the rest of his constitutional options,''
Kerry said, referring to Lewinsky's former friend, Linda R. Tripp,
and the independent counsel, Kenneth W. Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the president's lawyers go the full distance under their
rights,'' Kerry said, ``we will be here for months.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Republicans said they were persuaded during private
caucuses over the last two days to support a limited number of
witnesses out of fairness to the House managers.
</P>
<P>
   Many GOP members supported a plan by Senator John H. Chafee,
Republican of Rhode Island, to complete the depositions of
Lewinsky, Jordan, and Blumenthal by early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Under Chafee's plan, each witness would be questioned no longer
than two hours each by House managers and White House lawyers. One
senator from each party would observe the depositions, which would
be videotaped and provided to all senators for review.
</P>
<P>
   Before the discussions, Republican leaders said they expected
votes next week on whether any of the witnesses will testify before
the full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee predicted before the secret talks that the request by the
House managers for depositions would be approved and possibly
carried out under his plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that they have come down with so few witnesses is a
tremendous concession,'' Chafee said of the House managers. ``It
certainly pleases me, and I think it pleases most of the
Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing an extended trial, the Senate majority leader, Trent
Lott, Tuesday asked a group of GOP senators to examine a plan that
would end the proceeedings by dividing the charges into two parts:
During the final vote, senators would be allowed to find Clinton
guilty of the charges, but would then face a second vote on
removing him from office. ``It's still very much on track,'' said
Senator Ted Stevens, an Alaska Republican, although the White House
expresses strong opposition to the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the House managers were far from pleased to cast
aside a dozen potential witnesses to satisfy the Senate's political
concerns. ``We have narrowed it down to three, a pitiful three,''
Representative Henry J. Hyde, leader of the managers, said on the
Senate floor. ``And I should think you would want to proceed with
that minimal testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton faces two articles of impeachment alleging that he lied
under oath to a federal grand jury and obstructed justice to cover
up his sexual affair in the White House with Lewinsky, a former
intern. He faces four counts of lying under oath and seven counts
of obstruction.
</P>
<P>
   House managers, in a two-hour public presentation, vowed they
would not ask Lewinsky about details of her sexual liaisons with
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the managers said, they would question Lewinsky about
help she received from Clinton and Jordan to find a job in New
York, and about gifts Clinton gave Lewinsky that Currie later
collected. The House managers said they also would ask about an
affidavit Lewinsky filed in the sexual harassment lawsuit that
Paula Corbin Jones filed against Clinton and settled last year for
$850,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's one witness that you and the American people
honestly need to hear, it's Ms. Lewinsky,'' Representative Ed
Bryant of Tennessee told the Senate. ``Her testimony in particular
would be extraordinarily enlightening in resolving factual disputes
about the very charges for which we ask you to convict the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bryant argued for Lewinsky's deposition, she was leaving a
Washington hotel for an unspecified location, with a police escort
to shield her from a media throng. Lewinsky had flown to Washington
on Saturday to comply with a court order to be interviewed by the
House managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her state of mind is, she wants to get out of town,'' said her
lawyer, Plato Cacheris. ``She's been cooped up in the hotel, she's
not able to leave, and she wants to get on with her life.''
</P>
<P>
   The House managers argued that Jordan should testify about his
role in helping find Lewinsky a job and that Blumenthal should be
questioned about a series of remarks that Clinton made about
Lewinsky last year after the scandal broke.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal has testified that Clinton described Lewinsky as a
``stalker'' who made sexual advances on him. The obstruction charge
alleges that Clinton concocted the story to induce Blumenthal to
testify falsely to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   On the Senate floor, Clinton's private lawyer, David E. Kendall,
argued that Clinton's comments to Blumenthal involved the
president's effort to avoid embarrassment by disclosing his affair
with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall argued that reams of sworn testimony gathered during
Starr's eight-month investigation of the Lewinsky matter was more
than the Senate needed to reach a verdict. ``The managers' case is
in no way hindered by being unable to call witnesses at this
point,'' Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers also sought permission to introduce three new
pieces of evidence, including telephone records that cite a
56-minute call from Clinton to Lewinsky the day after lawyers in
the Jones case included Lewinsky on their witness list.
</P>
<P>
   Although many Senate Republicans reacted favorably to the House
requests, some of Clinton's key supporters lashed out. ``The motion
for witnesses is a motion for delay,'' said Senator Edward M.
Kennedy. ``The time to end the trial is now, and the correct number
of witnesses is zero.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Anne E. Kornblut of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
