<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-JORDAN-SUCCESSION-NYT (moved on Monday, Jan. 25)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Jan. 25,
about King Hussein's selection of his eldest son, Prince Abdullah,
as his successor misstated the adopted name of the King's second
wife, Toni Avril Gardiner. She was known as Princess Muna, not
Musa.
</P>
<P>
   Because of an editing error, the article misstated the site of
Deerfield Academy, where Prince Abdullah attended secondary school.
It is in Massachusetts, not Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   BC-PERSIAN-GULF-OIL-NYT (moved on Friday, Jan. 15)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Jan. 15,
about the effects of low oil prices on the Persian Gulf region
referred incorrectly to a standard unit of measurement. The barrel,
used throughout the world to measure crude oil and other oil
products, is defined as a volume of 42 gallons. It does not
correspond to any actual container, and has no relation to the
55-gallon steel drums that are widely used for shipping liquids.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-GODOWSKY-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Jan. 19)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Frances Gershwin Godowsky, moved by the New York
Times News Service on Tuesday, Jan. 19, misstated the nationality
of her father-in-law, the pianist Leopold Godowsky. He was born
outside Vilna, in an area that once belonged to Poland but was then
part of Russia and is now in Lithuania; he was not Austrian.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CHINA-FOREIGN-BANKS-NYT (moved on Thursday, Jan. 21)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Jan. 21,
about the financial troubles at Chinese investment trust companies
misidentified a creditor of the Guangdong International Trust and
Investment Corporation. It is Sumitomo Bank; Sumitomo Trust and
Banking is a different company.
</P>
<P>
   BC-BELO-MARKETPLACE-NYT (moved on Monday, Jan. 18)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Jan. 18,
about A.H. Belo's recent financial performance, misstated the name
of its new cable venture in Texas. It is Texas Cable News, not the
Texas Cable Channel.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-TAX-SITES-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Jan. 20)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Jan.
20, about Web sites with tax information misstated the standing of
Turbotax, by Intuit, in the tax software market. Its various
versions account for more than 70 percent of the market, not 50
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
