<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-QUAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARTHQUAKE LEVELS COLOMBIAN CITY AS DEATH TOLL RISES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARMENIA, Colombia _ Bodies piled up at a makeshift morgue,
refugees huddled under plastic tarpaulins and ashen-faced survivors
inspected their crumpled homes Tuesday following the worst
earthquake to strike Colombia this century.
</P>
<P>
   The magnitude-6 quake struck Monday afternoon, wreaking havoc on
cities and villages in the fertile, coffee-growing mountains of
western Colombia. Interior Minister Nestor Martinez said Tuesday
night that at least 670 people were killed and 2,505 injured. Other
reports put the death toll at more than 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue workers have yet to pick through much of the debris, a
clean-up operation that could take months and an even higher death
toll. Hundreds of people were buried under the rubble. Some,
though, managed to get out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen so much desolation or damage,'' said
National Police Chief Rosso Jose Serrano, who toured the area
Tuesday with Colombian President Andres Pastrana.
</P>
<P>
   Armenia, a city of 250,000 about 100 miles west of the capital
of Bogota, was hardest hit. Some 15,000 houses were reported
destroyed here. The danger of cave-ins from ruined buildings was so
great that Mayor Alvaro Patino ordered the evacuation of the
central business district.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's Treasury Minister Juan Camilo Restrepo refused to put
a price tag on the damage but issued an urgent plea to the World
Bank and the Inter-American Development Bank for emergency
assistance to rebuild Armenia and other towns.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, France and Japan all dispatched excavation
experts to help in the rescue effort. The governments of Argentina,
Guatemala, Honduras and Spain also pledged their help.
</P>
<P>
   Shocked residents of Armenia roamed through the streets as the
stench of rotting corpses grew stronger in the scorching sun.
</P>
<P>
   At a university gymnasium, a red dump truck backed up to the
door. Workers, wearing plastic bags on their hands instead of
gloves, carried limp bodies past crowds of shrieking relatives.
Inside, the basketball court was covered with corpses awaiting
identification.
</P>
<P>
   Fabio Lopez, who leaned on his pickup in the gym parking lot,
couldn't stop crying. He was at work when the quake struck, and
dashed home.
</P>
<P>
   But in the rubble he couldn't distinguish which house was his.
When he asked a neighbor for help, his daughter, who was trapped
under bricks and boards, heard his voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was yelling. `Daddy! Daddy! I'm here! Down here! Lower!'''
Lopez recalled. ``No one had heard her. I dug her out, brick after
brick.''
</P>
<P>
   When Lopez reached his daughter, he discovered the lifeless body
of his 10-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   In the center of the city, a three-story fire station collapsed
into a mass of red bricks and twisted metal rods. Eight volunteer
firefighters and two cleaning women were crushed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's dead. We're trying to get at the last body,'' said
one worker, who was sweating from pounding at the concrete with a
crowbar.
</P>
<P>
   Others seemed to come back from the dead. Lilian Echeverry was
on the second floor of her house when the quake struck and ended up
on the first floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The staircase was on my legs,'' said Echeverry, who started
screaming and was eventually rescued.
</P>
<P>
   Armenia's main hospital was accepting only the worst cases.
Adriana Quintero, whose left hand was mangled when her house fell
down, was rejected by doctors Monday but tried again Tuesday as her
swollen fingers turned blue and yellow.
</P>
<P>
   The waiting room was jammed with moaning patients. Many wore
homemade splints of cardboard and tape. Outside, people on the
lookout for the missing frantically read through lists of admitted
patients posted on the hospital walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't find him,'' wailed Betty Mejia, who has no idea what
happened to her cousin.
</P>
<P>
   On the southern edge of the city, the working-class neighborhood
of La Brasilia looked like a demolition site. Where once there were
city blocks, now there are piles of rubble two stories high.
Three-inch-wide cracks split streets, and fallen electric poles
block them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, determined survivors returned Tuesday with hammers,
crowbars and shovels to salvage what they could. One man called
into the ruins for his dog. Another man gingerly removed his
amplifier, tape deck and speakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't tell where one house ends and the other begins,''
said Pedro Alberto Rojas, another homeless man.
</P>
<P>
   Lilian Echeverry mused that while her house was destroyed, her
Mazda 323 emerged from the garage with a shattered windshield, but
in working order. Urbina Serna saved his motorcycle from his ruined
bakery but lost his wife and two employees. He wore dark glasses to
hide his tears.
</P>
<P>
   Many moved in with relatives. Others erected tarpaulins and
tents in Armenia's parks and boulevards and lined up at hastily
erected soup kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very sad,'' said President Pastrana, following a tour
of Armenia. ``This is the most critical area.``
</P>
<P>
   City officials here warned that things could get worse. The
quake knocked out electricity and telephone service in the city,
and drinking-water supplies were running short. A strong aftershock
rocked the downtown Tuesday afternoon causing panic.
</P>
<P>
   Armenia's airport closed for commercial flights because it was
jammed with air force jets, helicopters, cargo planes running
relief missions. A 6 p.m.-to-6 a.m. curfew remained in effect to
prevent looting, but it also hindered rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Since most of the damage was in urban centers, it appeared that
plantations, roads and other infrastructure for Colombia's vital
coffee industry were largely unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the tragedy, Colombians pulled together to help
survivors. It momentarily took their minds off other national woes,
such as the nation's 35-year-old civil war, rising crime and a
stagnating economy.
</P>
<P>
   TV stations broadcast nonstop reports from the disaster zone,
newspapers published extra editions and radio stations spent much
of their time relaying on-air messages for victims. Banks opened
special accounts for donations and quickly received hundreds of
deposits.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need is the solidarity of the Colombian people and
international public opinion because the situation is very grave,''
said Serrano, the police chief.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's earthquake was the deadliest in Colombia since 1875,
when a quake killed 1,000 at Cucuta on the border with Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's last major natural disaster occurred in 1986 when a
volcanic eruption caused massive mudslides that buried the town of
Armero and killed 23,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
