A9700 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NHAMP-MLK-DAY-BOS &LR;      01-26 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NHAMP-MLK-DAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW VOTES ENOUGH TO OK MLK HOLIDAY, GLOBE SURVEY SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ After years of notoriety as the only state
without an official holiday bearing the name of Dr. Martin Luther
King Jr., New Hampshire is poised to join the other 49 states in
honoring the slain civil rights leader.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Globe survey of all but one of 125 new voters,
there are now almost certainly enough votes to approve the holiday
in the House. Their votes will be crucial because returning
incumbents are evenly split on the issue. Supporters have 199 House
votes _ just two short of the 201 needed for passage. There are
about 30 undecided Republicans, three undecided Democrats, and one
Democrat who could not be reached. Further, key Republican backing
for the measure _ in a GOP-dominated House _ is beginning to
emerge.
</P>
<P>
   The state Senate approved a King holiday in 1997, when it was
controlled by Republicans. Now, with Democrats having seized the
majority in the last election, the current Senate is virtually
certain to approve it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Jeanne Shaheen declared in her January inaugural speech
that New Hampshire must not enter the year 2000 without a day
honoring King by name.
</P>
<P>
   Honoring King would be another step in an evolutionary process
that has seen the state shedding the ultraconservative image that
has clung to it for more than 25 years. It is a process highlighted
not only by the election in 1996 of Shaheen, a Democrat and a
woman, to the governor's chair, but also by Democrats capturing the
Senate in the last election; the rise of women to positions of
power throughout state government; and the fact that people in both
parties are now discussing broadbase taxes _ in a state with no
sales or income taxes _ to address problems in school funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little older and a lot more tolerant,'' said
Representative David Young, an Acworth Republican who voted against
the bill in the past, but now says he supports it.
``African-Americans have made a determination'' about the
significance of Dr. King in the civil rights movement, said Young,
``and I've got to respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, when Arizona adopted a King holiday, New Hampshire
has been the only state without a holiday in the civil rights
leader's honor. The first attempt to name a holiday for King in New
Hampshire came in 1979. That effort failed, as did repeated
attempts through the 1980s. In 1991, the state adopted Civil Rights
Day and, since 1993, governors have added King's name to the
holiday by proclamation.
</P>
<P>
   Passing this year's bill, which will probably be considered this
spring, will still take some care, according to those familiar with
the legislative process.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters must make sure that all 120 returning lawmakers who
voted for the bill last time do so again. Further, they must make
sure the 13 returning supporters who left the chamber before the
1997 vote _ when it lost by one vote, 178-177 _ stay and vote this
time.
</P>
<P>
   Accomplishing that, with 201 votes needed for passage in the
400-member House, means they must find 68 votes among the new batch
of lawmakers. That appears within easy reach.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Globe survey, 66 of the new lawmakers support
renaming the holiday. Only 39 of the new members oppose it.
Nineteen are undecided and one _ Somersworth Democrat Richard Hemon
_ could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Among the undecideds are three Democrats _ Michael J. Blaisdell
of Keene, Lucien Bergeron of Nashua, and James Phinizy of Acworth.
To win on the issue, supporters need to win the backing of two of
these three _ and only two Democrats in the survey said they were
against the measure _ or pick up a few Republican votes among the
other undecided newcomers or veterans. One Democratic backer said a
survey of Republicans shows those votes would be forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the measure this year appear divided into two
camps: those with lingering and absolute dislike for King, and
those who argue that no one person should have their name attached
to Civil Rights Day because no president has a day named after him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's race-based,'' Michael Gilman, a Littleton Republican,
said of the measure. ``If he had blond hair and blue eyes, you
don't think they'd be having a day for him, do you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot vote to honor a man who was a communist, who called
our soldiers baby-killers,'' said James Johnson, a Gilford
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Among proponents there are those, like Young, who think it is
time that after, what he calls years of meaningful independence and
debate, New Hampshire honor a national decision. There are those
who love King as much as others hate him. And there are those who
want his visage on the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so important for our kids to be able to put a face on
Civil Rights Day,'' said Donald Lent, a Durham Democrat. ``I
thought we lost something when we got Presidents' Day'' _ instead
of Washington's and Lincoln's birthdays.
</P>
<P>
   It would also be a vote that would help put a different face on
New Hampshire because it would erase some of the last vestiges of
perceptions of the state as a poor and rural place run by
arch-conservatives. Never mind that it is one of the wealthiest
states in the nation, that its southern tier is a booming economic
engine, and that the conservative wing of the Republican Party here
has marginalized itself, able to push the party into nominating
conservatives in the presidential primaries and gubernatorial
races, but failing recently to put up winners.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, conservatives are blamed for driving from the party a
host of moderates, particularly women, who became a key bloc in
Shaheen's ascendancy.
</P>
<P>
   If New Hampshire, through its vote on a King holiday, is to
continue its evolution, Representative Peter Burling, the House
minority leader, will have to play a strong role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not let happen what happened last time happen this
time,'' he vowed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Correspondent Kelly Winget contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
