r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-BAD-QUARTER-LA     01-26 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-BAD-QUARTER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOUSE UNLIKELY TO ROAR AS DISNEY EXPECTED TO REPORT POOR QUARTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Wall Street trackers following The Walt Disney
Co. are bracing for the entertainment giant to post one of its
worst quarters in memory due to continued poor performance at ABC
and home video operations.
</P>
<P>
   Disney, a component of the Dow Jones industrial average, is
expected to report earnings before markets open today for its first
quarter ended Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to expect December quarter results to look ugly,''
said ING Barings Furman Selz analyst Stewart Halpern, who expected
per-share earnings to fall 38 percent to 23 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   First Call's recent survey of 15 analysts generated a mean
estimate of 24 cents a share. ``There are a lot of things still
impacting the company,'' said Edward Jones Co. analyst Linda
Bannister, who expects earnings of 24 or 25 cents a share due to
ABC's higher costs for pro football rights, declining ratings for
ABC programming and weakness in sales of Disney products in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Halpern predicts operating profit in broadcasting will fall 32
percent to $330 million due to higher costs and a 3 percent decline
in network ratings. He said creative content will decline 39
percent to $425 million because the quarter saw significant video
contributions only from ``Simba's Pride'' and because foreign
product sales will remain sluggish.
</P>
<P>
   Bannister noted strong results from ``A Bug's Life'' and ``The
Waterboy'' had been offset partly by a poor performance from
``Mighty Joe Young'' and splitting profits from ``A Bug's Life''
with Pixar Animation.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, Halpern said theme parks should post a 12
percent gain to $321 million due to Animal Kingdom's opening in
Florida and renovations at Disneyland's Tomorrowland.
</P>
<P>
   The report will follow downbeat results in the previous quarter,
when earnings fell 24 percent to $296 million, or 14 cents a share,
due to weak films such as ``Holy Man'' and ``Beloved,'' poor
foreign video performance and continuing problems at ABC. That
fiscal fourth quarter capped a year where profits fell 6 percent at
a company that had often posted year-to-year gains topping 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Disney stock has been bumped up recently by investor enthusiasm
over its launch of the Go.com portal site, which analysts believe
is worth an additional $6 a share. Shares closed Tuesday at
$34.4375, off 37.5 cents.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
