<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9704 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-STATEOFSTATE-COX     01-26 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-STATEOFSTATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    House Republicans resist Bush agenda
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr. and Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With his enormous popularity and bipartisan
support, one might think the legislative process could be dispensed
with and Gov. George W. Bush's legislative proposals, to be laid
out in today's State of the State speech, simply put into action.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, say state lawmakers, including members of Bush's own
Republican party, who themselves have killed or watered down major
Bush legislative proposals in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bush's conservative credentials are being debated
nationally, conservatives in the Legislature say they believe that
even as he reaches out to more moderate factions that he is with
them. The question for Bush is whether conservatives will stay with
him as the details of his legislative agenda are hammered out.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, for example, a few conservative Republicans killed a
Bush-backed plan to make clear that eight-liner machines are
illegal. Some conservatives also refused to pass a massive tax cut
bill that Bush supported, though they did approve a scaled-back
plan to give tax breaks to property owners. ``I respect George Bush
to no end ... but the people of Senate (district) 10 didn't send me
here to automatically jump to any drummer's beat other than what I
believe is in their best interest and what they have communicated
to me,'' said Sen. Chris Harris, R-Arlington. ``I do not give up my
right to think.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris was among conservative Republicans who rejected the
larger, Bush-backed property tax cut. Harris said the bill raised
too many other taxes to pay for the property tax cut. ``It wasn't
needed,'' Harris said. Sen. Jane Nelson, R-Flower Mound, also
rejected the larger property tax plan. She said, however, that her
split with the Bush-backed plan was based on the issue, not
philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have consistently been ranked the most conservative
member,'' Sen. Jane Nelson, R-Flower Mound, said Tuesday. ``I sure
consider him a good solid conservative who reflects the interest of
most Texans.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush Spokeswoman Karen Hughes and conservatives in the
Legislature add that Bush faces no more threat from within his own
party than he faces from others in the political arena.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday evening remarks to the Texas Farm Bureau, Bush said
his speech today would key on taxpayers and schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we ought to share the surplus with the taxpayers of
Texas,'' he said. ``I'm going to propose substantial property tax
cuts...again.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would resist efforts to spend the entire surplus, a
move he said could take Texas toward a place it has resisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd certainly hate to be in a position where we put in all
kinds of new programs ... and wake up five to 10 years from now and
say, Oops, we don't have enough money, we need a personal income
tax,'' said Bush. ``I think that would be a disaster for Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor also will push his anti-social promotion plan. The
state, as a result of years of promoting kids who didn't earn it,
now has ``a pipeline full of illiterates'' in the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   On an issue of keen interest to social conservatives, Bush said
he backs Pampa Rep. Warren Chisum's bill that would ban homosexuals
from adopting children or serving as foster parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the first thing we ought to do in any placement is we
ought to be looking for heterosexual couples,'' he said. ``To have
a male and female in the household I think provides the proper role
models for children's future.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are positions that are winning the hearts of
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is a ``conservative with wide-ranging appeal,'' said Sen.
John Carona, R-Dallas. ``He's very committed to the principles he
believes in, having limited government, lowering taxes and
individual responsibility. But at the same time, he recognizes that
effective politics today means reaching out to all segments of our
community and listening to people of different views. That's what
has made Governor Bush so remarkably successful. He's true to his
party and his conservative beliefs, but at the same time he
acknowledges that we (must) build coalitions.''
</P>
<P>
   A key conservative issue that Bush is expected to discuss in his
speech is parental notification or consent before minors get
abortions. Chisum said Bush could be more strident on that issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I clearly think the governor would be in favor of parental
consent or notification or maybe both. He's got a couple of teenage
daughters _ you put yourself in those shoes and you absolutely want
to know what's happening in their lives and in their friends
lives,'' Chisum said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he needs to tell us where he's at, if this is a
priority to him. Parental consent, that is absolutely such a basic
issue. I'd love to see him on that bandwagon, and I suspect he is
on it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Florence Shapiro, R-Plano and head of the Senate Republican
Caucus, said she, too, wants Bush to touch on the issue, but
doesn't expect the governor to focus on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A State of the State is a speech that touches on many, many,
many issues,'' Shapiro said. ``Often times, if your issue is even
mentioned in the State of the State, it gives it credibility and an
elevation in the eyes of the other legislators.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Corona, ``His speech will be one that by design is
intended to reach out broadly to people of both political
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bill Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant, noting the wide range of
conservatives and moderates in the Republican Party, said, ``Nobody
can span the entire spectrum of the Republican Party. That would be
a superhuman feat.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan B. Elizondo Jr. and Scott S. Greenberger write for the
Austin American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
