<SLUG> BC-TEX-JASPERDEATH-TRIAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A wrangling jury selection for King murder trial
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Many were called, but few are being chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors in Jasper County earn $15 a day, but even in a county
with a 12 percent unemployment rate _ more than double the 5
percent statewide average _ the jury job is proving hard to fill
for the most notorious murder trial in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, seven of the first 10 people interviewed to sit in
judgment of a white man accused of fatally dragging a black man
behind a pickup were sent home. Most opposed the death penalty, but
one man revealed that the accused killer sent his
step-granddaughter letters from prison that tout white supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called her his little Aryan princess,'' Donald Halmon said
after being disqualified for admitting he believes John William
``Bill'' King is guilty of killing James Byrd Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Jury duty notices were sent to 400 residents of this Piney Woods
county near the Louisiana border. But even before jury selection
began this week, nearly 185 people claimed medical conditions or
other personal situations that exempted them from service.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Joe Bob Golden, concerned about possible
shirkers, required a doctor's note from any prospective juror who
claimed that a medical condition would prevent jury duty. Even a
pregnant woman whose baby is due next week had to submit
verification.
</P>
<P>
   The notoriety of the case has made many prospective jurors
uneasy. They realize the world will be watching what, if any,
punishment Jasper gives to the man who allegedly masterminded the
unthinkable hate crime that killed Byrd on June 7, a crime that
brought the Ku Klux Klan and gun-toting New Black Panthers to
Jasper to protest last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Many people here believe the KKK and the black militants may
bring their hate-filled demonstrations to Jasper again, depending
on the outcome of King's murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, we don't have a problem getting enough people to
serve on a jury here,'' said Jasper County Judge Joe Folk.
</P>
<P>
   In the economically depressed Jasper area, heavily hit by a
slumping timber market, the $15-a-day job of juror should look good
to people, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looks like anybody would want to work for that,'' the judge
said.
</P>
<P>
   To help put jurors at ease, the Jasper County sheriff's office
promises to provide personal escorts to and from the courthouse
each day of the trial. The escorts will protect the 12 jurors and
two alternate jurors from contact with the media, which has been
forbidden by the judge from releasing juror names or photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and defense attorneys for King are taking a close
look at the personal backgrounds of prospective jurors. On Monday,
they gave detailed questionnaires to the 122 people who qualified
for the jury after the first elimination round of opening
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers want to know the last book read, the last movie viewed,
messages on bumper stickers, which three people the prospective
jurors most admire and what is the most important value a parent
can teach a child.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney C. Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs Jr. is looking for
jurors who are independent thinkers, people who may be willing to
hold out for a life sentence rather than the death penalty if they
find King guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want somebody who is not a follower,'' Cribbs said.
</P>
<P>
   King denies he killed Byrd, and blames the black man's death on
Shawn Allen Berry, who owned the pickup that dragged Byrd until he
was decapitated. Berry and Lawrence Russell Brewer also have been
charged in Byrd's death, but have no trial date.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray is looking for
jurors who are educated and hold professional jobs, including at
least two blacks so that the jury will mirror the county's 20
percent black population.
</P>
<P>
   He wants jurors who can understand complex DNA evidence because
authorities plan to introduce evidence of blood on King's shoes.
</P>
<P>
   And he believes educated professionals are more outraged over
Byrd's death than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It offends anybody, but it tends to offend professional,
educated people maybe a little more,'' Gray said. ``The
professional, educated people tend to be a little more liberal than
the general population and this type of offense offends liberals a
little more than it does conservatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Individual jury interviews will be conducted all week. If too
many people continue to say they oppose the death penalty or that
they have made up their mind that King is guilty, lawyers may have
to begin drawing people from two upcoming county jury pools.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Gamino writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
