<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9711 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ASSESS-1STLD-     01-26 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ASSESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE SEEKS A DIGNIFIED EXIT AS IT OPENS THE DOOR TO WITNESSES
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS last graf to delete anonymous quote, add one from Hatch;
DELETES second-to-last graf referring to White House threat to call
Starr or Tripp; SUBS graf bgng, So the vote will satisfy ..., to
tighten benefits of Wednesday's vote to GOP; minor changes
elsewhere; COMBINES takes, subs overline.) 
 (See related stories: IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-TRIAL,
IMPEACH-TWO-STEP, IMPEACH-SESSIONS, IMPEACH-LEWINSKY,
IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-REPUBS, HUBBELL-TAXES, STARR-LEAKS) 
(sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Republican leaders on Tuesday took the
gamble that they can open the door to witnesses and still bring the
trial of President Clinton to a relatively quick, dignified and
civil conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott and his deputies
have struggled to find a footing in the midst of powerful political
crosscurrents: the general public overwhelmingly wants the
impeachment drive to end, but the party's conservative base demands
that it move forward.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans have wondered just what loyalty they owe to
their colleagues in the House, who pulled them over the cliff once
before during the government shutdown of 1995-1996. And they wonder
what kind of precedents they are creating for history.
</P>
<P>
   With all these conflicting impulses in mind, Lott has now
arranged a middle ground for his party: to approve subpoenas for
just three witnesses to be desposed; sharply limit the questioning
time to just hours a witness, and arrive at an end to the trial by
mid-February at the latest. Although some Republicans were still
wavering, Lott seemed almost certain to win when the Senate votes
on Wednesday on whether to depose witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just trying to have a fair process here,'' the
Mississippi Republican said this week, ``but one that gets us to a
conclusion, as soon as possible, without rushing to judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott has been navigating his way through a caucus of many views,
not always following predictable ideological predilections.
Republicans say that conservatives senators like Don Nickles of
Oklahoma, the majority whip, or others who are former House
members, like James M. Inhofe of Oklahoma, Wayne Allard of Colorado
and Rick Santorum of Pennsylvania, have pushed to support the House
with a full trial and as many witnesses as the prosecutors wanted.
</P>
<P>
   But moderate senators like Susan M. Collins of Maine and John H.
Chafee of Rhode Island have also argued for witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Shelby of Alabama, a usual ally of Lott, has been
one of the Republicans most skeptical about witnesses. And Sen.
Richard Lugar of Indiana, usually a centrist, has been mostly quiet
in caucus, Republicans say, but sounded fierce on Tuesday when he
blamed the White House for any partisanship developing in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The White House has stonewalled almost every opportunity to
inquire about the president's activities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To hold this group together and win a majority for witnesses,
Lott has steadily reined in the House prosecutors. They once wanted
to call 15 witnesses instead of the three they ultimately settled
for on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He thus has played almost the opposite role as the leadership in
the House. There Rep. Tom DeLay, the majority whip, aggressively
pushed impeachment forward, by cleverly pushing moderates to vote
for impeachment, by not allowing them an easy out through a censure
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The House prosecutors made it clear on Tuesday they were less
than delighted. ``We have always believed and we still do believe
that 10 or 12 witnesses are what we should have, and should have
been permitted to call to prove our case,'' Rep. Bill McCollum,
R-Fla., said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lott's efforts seemed to have turned the tide on witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, many Republicans were saying the Senate could
very well decide on Wednesday to block witnesses, with six or more
Republicans voting with the Democrats. On Tuesday, by contrast,
they seemed much more certain that witnesses will be approved when
the crucial vote arrives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow we will vote in favor of deposing witnesses,'' Sen.
Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said confidently. ``And in doing so we will
reinforce the ancient precedents of constitutional impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   So the vote will satisfy those Republicans who believe it would
set a dangerous constitutional precedent to cut off the impeachment
trial and those still trying to decide whether Clinton did obstruct
justice and commit perjury. It keeps the party's conservative base
from charging that the Senate just dismissed the case. It keeps
working relations between the House and Senate majorities. And if
everything goes according to plan, the trial will end by
mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   But there are political risks for Republicans as well. Even
though they are reining in their House counterparts, Senate
Republicans will still be voting to prolong a trial that most
Americans want to see end. A poll taken by the Gallup organization
for CNN and USA Today last weekend found that two-thirds of
Americans believed the Senate should go directly to a final vote on
impeachment without hearing from witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The votes on Wednesday threaten once again to mark the
Republicans as the party of impeachment. If all goes as predicted,
the day is expected to bring what Senate Republicans had once hoped
to avoid: near party-line votes, as the Republicans first defeat a
Demoratic effort to outright dismiss the case against the president
and then most likely approve witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of the votes would be minimized if, as looked
possible Tuesday night, the Republicans and Democrats could still
agree on the plan to proceed with depositions and then end the
trial quickly. ``Even a partisan vote tomorrow I don't think will
necessarily be a breakdown into partisanship,'' said Sen. Tim
Hutchinson, R-Ark. ``At that point it might actually be the
catalyst for discussions to go on that would bring it to a rapid
conclusion.'' But if the talks break down, there is also the
possibility of partisan warfare. Before the two parties began
negotiating Tuesday night, Sen. Tom Daschle, the minority leader,
and the White House warned in increasingly strident tones that once
depositions are allowed, the trial will inevitably spiral out of
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our colleagues need to clearly understand that if it's a
choice between expeditious and fair,'' Daschle said, ``Democrats
are going to fall on the side of fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   And David Kendall, Clinton's private lawyer, warned the Senate
of a long legal process ahead ``if the genie of discovery is let
out of the bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are several ways this trial could yet be extended. As
the rules now stand, the Senate can take individual votes after
depositions on whether it wants to call Monica Lewinsky or any
other witness to testify in the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are hoping that the White House's veiled threats
of a prolonged trial are empty. ``They'd be nuts to carry this
thing on,'' said Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah. ``That was a big
bluff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
