<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9721 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLUE-HEART-THEATER-$A     01-26 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUE-HEART-THEATER-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMING APART, AS AN ART FORM  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 31) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   Matt Wolf is the London Theater critic for Variety and a regular
writer on the arts from Europe  
 (af)  
 By MATT WOLF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The woman looks at the man who may or may not be her
son and asks: ``T b k k k k l?''
</P>
<P>
   That sequence of letters is the penultimate line of ``Blue
Kettle,'' the second of two one-act plays by Caryl Churchill that
make up her double bill ``Blue Heart.'' And the reply _ ``B.K.'' _
prompted by the question is no more immediately clear.
</P>
<P>
   So it fell to the playwright's longtime director, Max
Stafford-Clark, and a game company of actors, two of whom are in
their 80s, to make lucid what is encoded on the page. (In context,
``B.K.'' means ``Yes, please.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Heart'' was widely acclaimed in its London debut nearly
18 months ago at the Royal Court Theater, where critics praised an
ever-adventurous dramatist _ perhaps Britain's most consistently
daring _ as well as a cast that illuminated fully what in lesser
hands might have come across as a stunt.
</P>
<P>
   The double-bill made its American debut on Friday at the
Brooklyn Academy of Music's Majestic Theater, following an
international tour last year. The stops by Stafford-Clark's Out of
Joint company included Estonia, Israel and Germany, among other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The engagement ends on Feb. 21 at the theater where, two years
ago, Stafford-Clark brought his Out of Joint production of ``The
Steward of Christendom'' by the Irish playwright Sebastian Barry.
``Blue Heart'' will play a final week at City Stage in Springfield,
Mass., from Feb. 24 to 28, as part of the Massachusetts
International Festival of the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Churchill, 60, declined to discuss her two recent one-acts,
beyond having described them earlier as ``just talking plays.''
This was to set them apart from such collaborative mixed-media
pieces as ``A Mouthful of Birds,'' ``Lives of the Great Poisoners''
and ``The Skriker,'' all of which incorporate music and/or dance in
various ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Skriker,'' seen in New York in 1996 at the Joseph Papp
Public Theater, also involved the manipulation of words. Ben
Brantley, writing in The New York Times, called the play
astonishing and described it as a toxic, urban variation on ``A
Midsummer Night's Dream'' in which even language appeared to be
mutating and dissolving. The title character, a shape-shifting
otherworldly creature, delivered a monologue ``poised between Joyce
and Beckett,'' Brantley said.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Blue Heart,'' Ms. Churchill seems to stretch and bend
language further. And yet the two one-acts can hold their own among
``Cloud Nine'' (1980), ``Top Girls'' (1982), ``Serious Money''
(1987), ``Mad Forest'' (1990), or any of the half-dozen or so works
with which Ms. Churchill, a fierce social critic and taker of
theatrical risks, has made a formidable reputation on both sides of
the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Heart's Desire,'' the opening play of the double bill, the
stop-and-start structure toys with form itself, fracturing a
narrative in ways both comic and frightening. The situation
involves a daughter's return from Australia to her anxious English
family, with husband and wife debating whether they should have met
the plane. Meanwhile, Aunt Maisie _ in a startling speech _ ponders
the nocturnal ``chill'' of death, amid action that involves
numerous children, two gunmen and even a bird.
</P>
<P>
   After the intermission, ``Blue Kettle'' carries the experiment
into the realm of language. A con man named Derek (played by Pearce
Quigley) tries to obtain legacies by duping elderly women into
believing he is the son they long ago gave up for adoption. As the
dialogue develops, the text is gradually taken over by the words
``blue'' and ``kettle'' and their component syllables and letters.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the language can be said to suffer a breakdown
comparable to that of Derek, who seems both to transmit and suffer
from a virus or plague that the syntactical collapse accompanies.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Daldry, the artistic director of the Royal Court in 1997
when ``Blue Heart'' opened, had that summer staged a 35-minute
Churchill piece called ``This Is a Chair'' in the same theater. An
audience of 60 sat on the Court stage, peering out at the
performers (Amanda Plummer, among them) high up in the auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   Daldry said he thought of ``Blue Heart'' as ``a playwright
saying, `What is the role of theater?' '' He continued, ``With
`Blue Kettle,' you've got a play that could be a good enough play
as it is, but there's a virus in it, and `Heart's Desire' is a play
that doesn't really have a story.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like the plays themselves are rebelling against
the idea of what a play is,'' he said, aware of the paradox that,
by breaking down form, Ms. Churchill only reinvigorates it. ``Caryl
is very, very bright. There isn't anyone else that has that degree
of joy at formal experimentation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Heart'' marks the sixth Churchill play that
Stafford-Clark has directed in a collaboration dating back over 25
years. To him, ``these new plays come out of a distrust of or an
anger with theater; they're angry little antiplays, if you like.''
</P>
<P>
   And what are they like to act?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, you have to be rather bright to be part of this,''
said Anna Wing, who is 84 and has a brief but telling scene in the
second play as one of Derek's victims. (Among her lines: ``Yes I
have blue a blue mental kettle of you with a lot of black hair.'')
``Of course, I'm not an intellectual,'' she said. ``I'm a simple
woman, really. But Caryl has an awareness of the human predicament;
she's very splendid.''
</P>
<P>
   A new addition to the cast is June Watson, who has pivotal roles
in both plays. In ``Heart's Desire,'' she is Alice, the mother,
whose efforts to set the table become a running gag that Ionesco
might have enjoyed. In ``Blue Kettle,'' it falls to her character,
Mrs. Plant, to ask the seemingly nonsensical ``T b k k k k l?'' _
which, in fact, means ``Would you like a cup of tea?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I started in the profession when I was 21,'' said Ms. Watson,
who is now 63, ``and I've never been in anything like this.'' The
first play, she said, demands the precision of farce: ``You're
continually repeating, then repeating at double and triple speed.
Everything has to be absolutely exact.'' With ``Blue Kettle,'' she,
like the entire cast, took refuge in Ms. Churchill's so-called
ur-script, which contains all the lines free of any invasive
``blue'' or ``kettle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There might be one or two people who get irritated by it,''
Ms. Watson said of that play's conceit, ``by the words being not
the words.'' But, she added, ``I would think if you're prepared to
let yourself go, it would be a wonderful experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
