u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-SHELL-BO     01-26 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-SHELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS DON'T WANT SHELL, GRIER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ If the Patriots want to add Art Shell as their assistant
head coach, they had better hope Brad Seely chooses not to join
Pete Carroll's staff Wednesday. But do they want Shell or don't
they?
</P>
<P>
   Seely, the former Carolina Panthers special teams coach, is down
to a choice between the Patriots and the Cleveland Browns, and if
he chooses New England when he makes his final decision, current
special teams coach Dante Scarnecchia would reluctantly agree to
take over New England's offensive line. Where that would leave
Shell is very likely in a shell game he has no interest in playing
and one the Patriots say they have no interest in initiating.
</P>
<P>
   Shell currently coaches the Atlanta Falcons' offensive line and
cannot even talk to the Patriots until after Sunday's Super Bowl,
but according to several of his friends, if there were no offensive
line job to occupy his time in New England, he would be unlikely to
join Carroll's staff in a supervisory role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art is not going to go there just to be a figurehead,'' a
close friend of Shell's said. ``He wants to be a head coach, but
he's not going to New England to stand around all day and look like
he's waiting to replace Pete. That's not who he is. If he goes
there, he wants to help them win, and the way for him to do that is
to coach their line the same way he's coached the Falcons.''
</P>
<P>
   But Patriots vice president of player personnel Bobby Grier
issued an unusual press release Tuesday insisting that Carroll
would finalize his staff in 24-48 hours and that Shell would not be
a part of it under any circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art Shell is not being considered for a position on Pete
Carroll's staff,'' the release said. ``We've made no effort to
contact him. In fact, he's not even available to be contacted by
another team. I expect Pete to finalize his coaching staff within
the next couple of days and I can assure you Art is not a
candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier's statement said he did not know how the Shell reports got
started, ``but quite frankly, I'm sick of this type of speculation.
If you read some of the reports in the papers, you would believe a
deal is already done. This type of speculation is a distraction to
everyone involved, and I hate to even comment on it. I'm sure Art
feels the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll has already offered the special teams job to Seely, a
longtime friend and former coaching associate who also was being
courted by the Baltimore Ravens before they filled their opening.
Scarnecchia, who was unhappy with the decision to fire offensive
line coach Paul Boudreau, initially balked at the idea of switching
to line coach but has told Carroll he would do whatever he is
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Shell, meanwhile, seems to be left where he has been for five
years _ searching for a second chance to be a head coach after
wining nearly 60 percent of his games on his first try, with the
Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday Shell declined comment on rumors that a new job might
await him after the Super Bowl, one that would make him one of the
few minority coaches in a supervisory position in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Shell confirmed that he had not been contacted by anyone in the
Patriots organization and that hadn't asked Falcons head coach Dan
Reeves for permission to so do after the Super Bowl. In fact, he
said he knew little beyond what he had read in the papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I want is a chance to sit down and talk with someone (in a
position to hire head coaches and coordinators),'' Shell said. ``If
you're asking me, do I deserve to be a head coach in the NFL, the
answer is yes. Certainly, it's been disappointing not to get a
second chance, because I feel I have something to offer. The key
thing is, I can lead men.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Shell became the first black head coach in 65 years to
lead men in the NFL, and within a year, he was named Coach of the
Year after taking the Los Angeles Raiders to the AFC Championship
Game. In his 5 1/2 years as head coach, his teams reached the
playoffs three times before he was fired after what was then viewed
by owner Al Davis as a dismal 9-7 season.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Raiders have failed to reach that level again,
yet Shell is not bitter about the firing or the fact that he has
been interviewed for only one other head job.
</P>
<P>
   He is not happy about that or about the NFL's dismal minority
hiring record, but bitterness is of no interest to him. What is of
interest is getting a second chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see the number of minorities running around football
fields, it accentuates the fact that only three guys are head
coaches in the NFL,'' Shell said. ``When Al hired me to coach the
Raiders, I felt ground had been broken and progress would be made.
I remember telling my good friend Terry Robiskie (who coached
Shell's offense) we must be successful because it would reflect on
all the minority coaches in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had success with the Raiders. Denny Green came along, and
then Ray Rhodes and Tony Dungy. We felt we'd done a good enough job
that blacks would get hired in the National Football League in
those roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, sure, it's disappointing not to have gotten a second
chance, but I've been in two other winning organizations (Kansas
City and Atlanta) since and I've seen different ways to do things.
It's helped me grow as a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was bothered by the fact that eight of the nine
vacancies this season had been filled by white head coaches, many
of whom were relatively obscure assistants, Shell said, ``Every one
of those guys who were hired are good football coaches, so I don't
know if you can say it's a race problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never become bitter about the situation, because if you
become bitter, it's nonproductive. The commissioner has been trying
to do all he can to help improve the situation, but there's only so
much anyone can do until someone gives you a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Grier, that chance won't come with the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Nick Cafardo of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
