McDONALD'S REPORTS EARNINGS GAINS, CITING PROMISING TURNAROUND 
(bl) 
By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ McDonald's Corp. said Tuesday that fourth-quarter
earnings were robust, increased by strong international sales and a
rejuvenated restaurant business in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The company also announced a 2-for-1 stock split, effective
March 5, and plans to raise its dividend 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street cheered the earnings report, which was in line with
analysts' expectations. Shares of McDonald's rose $3.0625, or 4
percent, to $78.9375, on the New York Stock Exchange, helping power
a broad rally in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   After a string of lackluster quarters and growing concerns about
the company's flagging U.S. sales in 1997, McDonald's said Tuesday
that its business had made a promising turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, the fast-food chain said that net income
rose 9 percent, to $447.1 million, or 64 cents a diluted share,
from $410.9 million, or 58 cents a diluted share. Revenues also
rose 9 percent, to $3.22 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great year,'' said Michael Conley, chief financial
officer at McDonald's in Oak Brook, Ill. ``We did change the
momentum of the U.S. business; in retrospect, we had had three
tough years.''
</P>
<P>
   While the earnings growth in the fourth quarter came as no
surprise to Wall Street analysts, who had predicted a
64-cents-a-share gain, according to First Call Corp., many analysts
said that Tuesday's earnings release offered additional signs that
McDonald's had made a strong turnaround in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   They said the company had been focusing more sharply on
profitability under Jack Greenberg, who took over as chief
executive in August, and that a new decentralized operating
structure _ which deeded more power to regional managers and
franchisees _ was showing good results.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's also saw steady growth in international markets, with
the greatest expansion occurring in Asia and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, McDonald's had worldwide sales of nearly $36
billion and profits of $1.7 billion in 1998. Earnings per share
rose 10 percent from 1997.
</P>
<P>
   That McDonald's was poised for a strong performance has been
evident in it stock performance. After falling 12 percent in 1996
and 1997, shares have risen 69 percent in the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``McDonald's has been back on track all through 1998,'' said
Joseph Buckley, an analyst at Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
