<SLUG> BC-ELECTRONIC-YEARBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEARBOOK SOFTWARE PUTS THOSE HIGH SCHOOL MEMORIES JUST A CLICK
AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- In hindsight, it was probably inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   First, typewriters were muscled out of the classroom by word
processors. Then LPs gave way to compact discs as the teen musical
medium of choice.
</P>
<P>
   Now the staid but proven high school yearbook is going digital,
thanks this time to suburban Thousand Oaks start-up YearDisc
Systems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The company, founded in 1997, has developed a start-to-finish
software package that it is marketing to schools as a cheaper,
faster and more dynamic way to record a year's worth of school
history, complete with sound, motion and hyperlinked text. As the
name implies, the YearDisc system bypasses paper and binding,
instead burning data directly to disk: CDs for now, but even more
powerful DVDs in years to come.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting yearbook, which the company duplicates for a fee,
requires a CD-equipped computer to play and, once installed,
operates much like a Web site. A main menu of buttons takes viewers
to multimedia pages dedicated to students, sports, clubs, dances
and other groups or special events.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have video clips of your prom, graduation or other
significant events in full color . . . and it's a lot easier to put
together,'' said Barry Peters, company co-founder and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   YearDisc even throws in a free autograph book with each disk so
students can continue to write year-end messages to one another.
</P>
<P>
   Already the system is in place at a dozen schools serving as
beta testers, and a crew of independent and staff sales
representatives is busy hawking it to hundreds more campuses across
the country. Peters said that by the 1999-2000 school year, more
than 300 schools should have the system in place.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal, Peters said, lies in the program's price and power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The schools pay nothing upfront,'' he said. In addition to the
proprietary software, YearDisc provides campuses at no cost with a
450-megahertz Pentium II computer on which to produce their disk,
plus enough propaganda in the form of posters, T-shirts and
brochures to get students and faculty up to speed on just what the
system offers. In return, schools commit for three years to sell
100 of the electronic books annually at a cost of about $25 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always going to be people who want that paper book,
but this gives you extra depth,'' said Robert Haar, yearbook
adviser and a history teacher at Thousand Oaks High School, a
YearDisc test site. ``And it's student-driven as far as production
is concerned, giving them some opportunities to work . . . with
programs and equipment they'll use in the work environment outside
of school.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting a cover-your-bets approach, even Missouri-based
Walsworth Publishing Co., one of the nation's top traditional
yearbook publishers, is getting in on the act, recently partnering
with YearDisc to co-promote the product along with its own
services. Noting an increased interest in electronic publishing
overall, Walsworth said it teamed with YearDisc to stay ahead of
the curve.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years ago there was a big push for video yearbooks, and
there are still some around, but not many,'' said David Massy,
Walsworth's instructional products manager. ``Maybe this'll be
something that'll stick around and maybe it won't. Who can tell?
But you never have anything to gain by standing in the way of
change.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
