A9732 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      01-26 1364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE URGES U.S. TO TAKE MORAL LEADERSHIP ROLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trims) 
 
By CECILE S. HOLMES 
and KIM COBB 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Welcomed by a beaming President Clinton and
thousands of cheering, flag-waving Catholics, Pope John Paul II
urged Tuesday that the United States aspire to a higher moral
vision.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing this country's turmoil over abortion to the
controversy surrounding slavery in the 19th century, John Paul
said, ``Only a higher moral vision can motivate the choice for
life.''
</P>
<P>
   The pontiff arrived in this historically Roman Catholic city for
a short meeting with Clinton as well as a youth rally, prayer
service and Mass spread out over two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every nation faces times of trial, tests of national
character,'' he said. ``America has not been immune to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to St. Louis' link with the 19th-century Dred Scott
case, the pope said that the landmark, pre-Civil War decision by
the U.S. Supreme Court ``declared an entire class of human beings _
people of African descent _ outside the boundaries of the national
community and the Constitution's protection.''
</P>
<P>
   But today, he said, ``the conflict is between a culture that
affirms, cherishes and celebrates life, and a culture that seeks to
declare entire groups of human beings _ the unborn, the terminally
ill, the handicapped and others considered unuseful _ to be outside
the boundaries of legal protection.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Arriving in St. Louis immediately after a five-day visit to
Mexico City, the pope wore his 78 years heavily. He moved slowly
down the jet's stairway, his shoulders stooped, and used a cane to
walk across the tarmac. He shook hands with Clinton and first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The president took the pope's left elbow and guided him through
the crowd waiting in a nearby hangar. John Paul paused once to
stroke the cheek of a toddler in a stroller.
</P>
<P>
   Joining government officials for the welcoming ceremony were the
nation's nine cardinals and Bishop Joseph Fiorenza, head of the
Diocese of Galveston-Houston and president of the National
Conference of Catholic Bishops.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Welcome on behalf of Houston,'' said the much taller Fiorenza,
bending low so that his face was even with the pope's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A deep smile crossed the pope's ruddy face as the crowd cheered
his remarks at the airport. His left arm shook visibly during his
address.
</P>
<P>
   On this, his fifth U.S. tour, the pontiff stressed that the
moral leadership of the United States should equal its economic
prowess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of America's great impact on the world as a whole, the
resolution of this new time of testing will have profound
consequences for the century whose threshold we are about to
cross,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the pope's fourth meeting with Clinton and his 85th
pastoral trip outside of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   In a 20-minute talk with the president, the pope again raised
the subject of dignity for all human life. White House spokesman
P.J. Crowley said, however, that the president had no response to
John Paul's brief private reference to abortion or to his public
remark about a ``culture of death'' in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pontiff's views on respect for human dignity and life are
well known,'' Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   In welcoming the pope, Clinton said that John Paul has touched
American hearts. ``For 20 years, you have challenged us to think of
life not in terms of what we acquire for ourselves but in terms of
what we give of ourselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``On your last visit to the United States, you called on us to
truly build a society worthy of the human person,'' Clinton said.
``Today, you visit an America that is thriving, but also striving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am nowhere near as gifted a linguist as you are, Holy
Father,'' the president said. ``But as they say in your native
Poland: May you live 100 years and more.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the St. Louis residents attending the airport ceremony
were Cris Conner, who grew up in Houston; his wife, Yvonne; and
their children, Matthew, 13, and Meredith, 12. The family won
tickets to the event in a lottery at church.
</P>
<P>
   Yvonne Conner said welcoming the pope added a new dimension to
her faith. Her husband, a convert to Catholicism, called it ``the
greatest experience imaginable.'' Matthew said he yearned to know
more about the pope's childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he spend all of his childhood years in church and praying,
or was he a comical prankster like me?'' Matthew wondered. ``Did he
have a Bible before he had a squirt gun? When he was 18, did he
have a license plate that said, ``Born to be pope?'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, it looked as though St. Louis's downtown
streets, its Kiel Center and a huge park-like area dubbed the Papal
Plaza had become the site of a huge gospel-rock concert. There were
posters, placards, big-name Christian bands and even a Christian
juggler.
</P>
<P>
   In a city where one-third of the citizenry is Catholic, a papal
visit is something to celebrate. Vendors hawked commemorative
T-shirts, and people stood five deep along sidewalks, waving,
cheering and crying as the papal motorcade wound its way to the
residence of St. Louis Archbishop Justin Rigali.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday evening, a vintage John Paul spoke during evening
prayer with 20,000 young people at the Kiel Center. Throughout his
reign, John Paul II has enjoyed a special rapport with youth,
drawing hundreds of thousands to international World Youth Days and
to huge outdoor Masses in nations circling the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Before his speech at Kiel, he met local baseball legend Mark
McGwire, a lifelong Catholic, who knelt to kiss the pontiff's ring.
</P>
<P>
   Later, despite his obvious fatigue, John Paul proved that he is
still capable of playing a crowd with a master showman's sense of
timing. At the Kiel Center, he paused, gauging youths' reaction to
one of the lighter moments in his address.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am told there was much excitement in St. Louis during the
recent baseball season, when two greater players (Mark McGwire and
Sammy Sosa) were competing to break the home-run record,'' the
pontiff said, provoking laughter and prolonged applause from his
towel-waving, baseball-hat-wearing audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can feel the same great enthusiasm as you train for a
different goal: the goal of following Christ, the goal of bringing
his message to the world,'' the pope said.
</P>
<P>
   He drew wild cheers when he told the young people: ``Tonight,
the pope belongs to you!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Young friends, in the days and weeks and years ahead, for as
long as you remember this evening, remember that the pope came to
the United States to call the young people of America to Christ, to
challenge you to be the light of the world!
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope believes in you, and he expects great things of
you!'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the pope arrived, tens of thousands of young people
huddled against the cold near St. Louis' famous Gateway Arch for a
march through downtown and a daylong youth rally featuring gospel
singers and motivational speakers.
</P>
<P>
   The youngsters whooped, cheered and sang through the streets.
Some carried banners identifying their home parishes.
</P>
<P>
   Wilford Salinas, an 18-year-old high school senior from Justin,
Texas, said this was the third trip he had made to see the pope.
This trip, he added, promised to be as exciting as the first.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Leible, a 16-year-old from Perryville, Mo., leaned on
crutches outside the Kiel Center, waiting to pass through security.
She wasn't about to miss the rally because of an injured foot, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the chance of a lifetime to even be in his presence,''
she gushed. ``I think he's just amazing. He's done so much for the
youth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of my close friends aren't Catholic,'' said Cara
Scatizzi, 17 of Wildwood, Mo. ``But when I told them I was coming,
they thought it was pretty cool.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a feeling of being part of something,'' said
her friend Matt Hay, 17.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
