<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9735 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-EARNINGS-ART-N     01-26 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-EARNINGS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING BEATS ESTIMATES AND RENEWS PROMISES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boeing Co. released quarterly results Tuesday that were better
than expected, and it tried to assure investors made wary by a
string of unpleasant surprises over the last 16 months that it was
finally turning itself around. But Wall Street remained skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, the world's largest aerospace company and the United
States' largest single exporter, beat by 3 cents a share the
average estimate of Wall Street analysts surveyed by First Call
Corp. Analysts said that the company's military and space divisions
were stronger than they had expected and that the company had
benefited from a favorable tax rate.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing earned $465 million, or 48 cents a share, in the fourth
quarter, including a $30 million tax credit worth 3 cents a share.
In the same period in 1997, the company lost $498 million, or 51
cents a share, including an after-tax charge of $876 million, or 89
cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   The company stunned Wall Street last month by announcing that
its projected earnings over the next two years would be as much as
40 percent lower than analysts were estimating. The company said it
would earn $1.5 billion to $1.8 billion in 1999 on revenue of $58
billion and $1.5 billion to $1.7 billion in 2000 on revenue of $49
billion.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Philip Condit, Boeing's chief executive, said the
company was now expecting to hit the high end of those projections.
``What you will see is a lot more aggressive attention to the
numbers,'' he told analysts, reiterating his commitment to
revamping Boeing's antiquated accounting and manufacturing systems.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore the point, he formally introduced Deborah Hopkins,
Boeing's new chief financial officer. Condit praised Ms. Hopkins,
who held a similar post at General Motors Europe, as a ``change
agent'' and added that she had already had a strong impact on
Boeing after only five weeks on the job.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Hopkins' initial progress may say more about how far
Boeing has to go than about how far it has come. Speaking to
analysts, she said she had started a companywide campaign to
educate Boeing senior executives about such common measures of
profitability as return on investment and inventory turnover. She
also said the company's top managers now know how much each Boeing
passenger airplane costs to produce.
</P>
<P>
   As impressive as Ms. Hopkins' performance may have been, Wall
Street remained cautious. Boeing shares fell $1 Tuesday, to $35, on
the New York Stock Exchange. The price is now 38 percent below its
52-week high of $56.25 set in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once burned, twice shy,'' said Byron Callan, an analyst at
Merrill Lynch, summing up the feelings of many investors. ``Is this
something of a turning point?'' he added. ``Yes. But it is going to
take time.''
</P>
<P>
   One investor who believes Boeing stock is a bargain is Boeing
itself. In the last half of 1998, the company spent $1.3 billion to
buy 3.5 percent of its stock, or 35.2 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing had revenue of $17.1 billion in the fourth quarter,
compared with $11.73 billion in the last quarter of 1997. Much of
the increase came from delivering a record 191 passenger jets. But
the company still earned no profit from making the airplanes
because of its production difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hopkins said that would change this year, when the company
plans to deliver a record 620 airplanes, compared with 563 in 1998.
Still, commercial airplane profit margins are expected to be only 2
percent to 3 percent this year and 1 percent to 3 percent in 2000,
when Boeing will cut production to 480 jets.
</P>
<P>
   The company's military and space divisions, which it acquired
from McDonnell Douglas and Rockwell International in the last two
years, helped to counter the airplane division's poor showing.
Operating profits of combined businesses rose 46 percent, to $452
million, at the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hopkins said Boeing was once again evaluating its forecast
and would announce new long-term profit targets within 30 to 60
days. But Callan of Merrill Lynch, who has seen several recent
Boeing pronouncements come to naught, was wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a side of me,'' he said of the company's projections,
``that says, `Just leave them where they are.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
