<HEADER>
A9736 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      01-26 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Crackdown on Securities Lawbreakers  &HT;       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
There's a new sheriff in town, and he doesn't take kindly to
white-collar cowboys who break securities laws.
</P>
<P>
   Robert S. Mueller III has only been U.S. attorney in these parts
for about six months, but he already is showing that he's a man of
his word. Not long after being appointed federal prosecutor for
Northern California, Mueller declared that he was going to make
fighting white-collar crime a priority, particularly insider
trading and high-tech-related fraud in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of the local Securities and Exchange Commission
office, Mueller has nabbed his first suspects. Together, the U.S.
Attorney's Office and the SEC filed insider-trading charges against
two former employees of Advanced Fibre Communications, a Petaluma
telecommunications concern.
</P>
<P>
   Three people have been named in a criminal indictment and civil
complaint. They are Chi-lin Tom, 45, a former director of design
verification, and Hong Lu, a 27-year-old engineer. Hong Lu's wife,
Yi Lu, 27, also was cited in the civil complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Both the criminal and civil charges contend that the high-tech
workers made $327,000 in profits by illegally trading in Advanced
Fibre options last June and July. The two men allegedly learned
that Advanced Fibre was going to announce lower-than-expected
revenues for the second quarter. And they used that information,
prior to the announcement, to buy options contracts that paid them
off when their employer's stock price declined.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal indictment, which was brought by a federal grand
jury on Monday, charges each man with one count of conspiracy, one
count of securities fraud and two counts of mail fraud. In
addition, each man faces four counts of making false statements to
the SEC, and one count of obstruction of justice. Both men pleaded
not guilty yesterday, and each was released on $50,000 bond.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of STREET27 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The SEC's civil complaint, which often can bring only monetary
fines and other wrist-slaps, accuses the men of committing illegal
insider trading. Advanced Fibre shares slipped only 6 cents to
$13.44 on the news.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC referred the case to Mueller's office because
investigators felt there was strong evidence that the high-tech
employees were deliberate in how they used insider information to
execute their trades, says Helane Morrison, head of enforcement at
the SEC's San Francisco office.
</P>
<P>
   But more important, ``we think they lied to us during our
investigation,'' Morrison says.
</P>
<P>
   If so, the obstruction of justice charges filed by federal
prosecutors could send the accused to the slammer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's appropriate for them to face jail time for their
conduct,'' Morrison says.
</P>
<P>
   And that's why Mueller's interest in fighting white-collar crime
could have a resounding impact on questionable trading practices in
Silicon Valley, where workers are flush with shares and exposed to
important financial information.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, insider-trading investigations are brought by
the SEC and result in noncriminal penalties, says Joe Grundfest, a
law professor at Stanford University and former SEC commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as he tells his students, any attempt to interfere with an
investigation can lead to harsher penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Perjury and obstruction of justice ``are the surest way to
convert a civil matter ... into a potential criminal offense,''
Grundfest says.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the heightened cooperation between the top cop for
Northern California and the local SEC office is no coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to have a close working relationship with the
SEC in order to pursue insider-trading and fraud cases when
appropriate,'' says Assistant U.S. Attorney Matthew Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Mueller has recruited some big guns to his staff
who boast experience in prosecuting insider-trading and other
securities fraud cases.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Mueller appointed a former New York City
prosecutor, David Shapiro, to chief of the criminal division. Among
other things, Shapiro, who most recently was in the Oakland office,
has extensive experience investigating securities, wire and
bankruptcy-fraud cases. He currently is assigned to the continuing
criminal case against executives at Media Vision Technology in
Fremont.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of STREET27 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Another recent addition to Mueller's staff is Leslie Caldwell, an
assistant U.S. attorney from Brooklyn, N.Y., who has been named
Shapiro's deputy and chief of the office's economic crime division.
One of her most recent assignments was to crack down on small-cap
stock fraud, directing investigations into such illegal practices
as market manipulation and unlawful short-selling.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, appointing some prosecutors with experience at
tracking down cheats on Wall Street isn't a bad career strategy,
either. After all, putting Michael Milken behind bars worked out
pretty well for then-federal prosecutor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
