<SLUG> BC-JAMA-EDITOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOARD OF MEDICAL JOURNAL DEFENDS AN OUSTED EDITOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By GINA KOLATA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors and members of the editorial board of the Journal of the
American Medical Association are defending the dismissed editor of
the publication in its next issue.
</P>
<P>
   The editor, Dr. George D. Lundberg, was dismissed last week
because he published a paper reporting that many Midwestern college
students, surveyed eight years ago, did not consider oral sex to be
``having sex.'' The association's vice president, Dr. E. Ratcliffe
Anderson Jr., said that Lundberg had expedited the article for a
political purpose, to coincide with the impeachment trial of
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial criticizing Anderson for dismissing Lundberg,
editors of the association's journals say that ``innumerable
commentators worldwide'' viewed that action as ``a direct threat to
the journal's historic tradition and integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Their editorial appears in next Wednesday's issue of the journal
and was released Tuesday. Jeff Molter, a journal spokesman, said
the signers of the editorial ``wanted to get this out as quickly as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The journal also released a news article to be published next
week on Lundberg's dismissal and the reactions it engendered. It
stated that the journal had received hundreds of comments from
supporters and critics Anderson's action.
</P>
<P>
   In discharging Lundberg, Anderson said that the immediate cause
was the oral sex article but that he had over time ``lost
confidence and trust'' in Lundberg. Anderson would not be specific,
but many observers said that in his 17 years as editor of the
Journal of the American Medical Association, Lundberg had nettled
some people with his strong opinions and the sometimes
controversial papers he published.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Ewe Reinhardt, an editorial board member and health
economist at Princeton University who protested the dismissal,
noted that Lundberg had irritated some doctors with his comments on
autopsies on the CBS News program ``60 Minutes.'' A ``60 Minutes''
producer, Walt Bogdanich, reported that Lundberg had said, ``Some
doctors, some medical staff, are afraid to find out what happened
in people who died.''
</P>
<P>
   The signers of the editorial state that Lundberg made the
journal ``a world-class scientific publication.'' They said that
although Anderson had the authority to dismiss Lundberg, they
strongly disagreed with the decision. And they reaffirmed their
commitment to the journal's editorial independence.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson declined to be interviewed. A spokeswoman, Linda
Stepanich, said he released a statement Tuesday that called the
editorial ``a clear, balanced assessment of several important
issues that go to the heart of JAMA's integrity and excellence.''
It added that Anderson was pleased by the endorsement of the
journal's editorial independence.
</P>
<P>
   Lundberg, reached at his home Tuesday, said he could only read a
prepared statement: ``On advice of counsel, I continue to not make
statements except to express profound gratitude to leaders of
American and international medicine for their support of me and of
the academic publication process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
