<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ATLANTA-VETS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO FOOTBALL: IN THE WORLD OF TACKLING, TWO FALCONS REIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Jessie Tuggle and Eugene Robinson, a linebacker and a
free safety, stand tall here at Super Bowl XXXIII. Both are Atlanta
Falcons. Tuggle is 33. Robinson is 35. Both have played at least 12
professional seasons and are football purists, loquacious and
spirited leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Tuggle is the leading active tackler among all National Football
League players. Counting this year's playoffs, he has made 1,701
tackles in 187 games. Robinson ranks second among all active
players with, counting the playoffs, 1,253 tackles in 218 National
Football League games.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that's some hitting. Some mileage. We can read it a couple
of ways. First, Tuggle and Robinson have played so long for such
lousy teams that they were always on the field, giving both
frequent opportunities to tackle. Also, both have such a nose for
the ball, such a feel for the flow of an offense, that they usually
finish with a hand, a shoulder, a helmet on the ball carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Cut it anyway and the conclusion is this:
</P>
<P>
   1.) Tuggle and Robinson paint the Falcons' defense with a
glowing shell of experience, appreciation, confidence, attitude and
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   2.) The Denver Broncos in Super Bowl XXXIII on Sunday must
account for these two players in their offensive game plan by
either attacking them directly or by running plays away from their
zones.
</P>
<P>
   By all means, do not ignore them.
</P>
<P>
   The careers of Tuggle and Robinson unfolded that way, with fans
and peers around the league generally ignoring their talents and
savvy. Tuggle is in his 12th pro season, all with Atlanta, and
before this season he had played in three playoff games. Robinson
is in his 14th season, and in his first 11 in Seattle he played in
two playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   Do your primary work in the regular season and people tend to
think of you _ with the infrequent exception of a player such as
Detroit's Barry Sanders _ as a regular player.
</P>
<P>
   This season Tuggle broke the NFL career record for touchdowns
scored off fumble recoveries with six and Robinson improved as the
career leader in interceptions among active players with 53.
</P>
<P>
   Both players kept making big plays for a defense that has helped
thrust Atlanta into the Super Bowl. Both were undrafted free agents
_ Tuggle from Valdosta State, Robinson from Colgate _ who used to
live in anonymity but now stand tall here at Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   For Robinson, the rise in post-season stature began two years
earlier than it did for Tuggle. This is Robinson's third
consecutive Super Bowl. He played in the last two with the Green
Bay Packers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in Seattle, and when we didn't win consistently,
people didn't come knocking on my door,'' Robinson said. ``I didn't
get attention. No big endorsements. So, I don't care now if people
jump on my bandwagon or the Atlanta Falcons' bandwagon. I have been
there when nobody was screaming and hollering. I know what that
feels like when nobody cares. So, jump right on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that Jessie feels the same way. He told me the other
day: `Hey, we've been down for so long and now we're up! And we're
going to win this thing!' I'm happy for what's happened for me and
Jessie Tuggle. The Lord has shown us much favor.''
</P>
<P>
   For both of them, for the Falcons, it took so long. ``I used to
sit there and say maybe this will be the year for the Atlanta
Falcons; no, maybe this will be the year for the Atlanta Falcons;
no maybe this will be the ... '' Tuggle said, breaking off the
thought and shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been 32 Super Bowls played and the Atlanta Falcons
have not been close to any one of them. I haven't been as a player.
I had to be realistic about it. I was beginning to think I'd play
my career without this chance. I looked around and I was getting
old and I didn't even realize it, but then it started to sink in
the last couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this game, I have the chance to show the people around the
country and the world that I can play. We have the chance to change
the whole image of the Atlanta Falcons for good. The best thing I
can say about the past is it's behind us. The greatest thing I can
say about the future is come Sunday, I know that this did not come
easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson is a rangy player in size (6 feet 1, 197 pounds) and in
the way he plays free safety. He covers plenty of ground in the
passing game yet supports the run defense. He has terrific
technique and is a thinking man's defensive back. Cornerbacks love
playing with him because they know he will always be there, over
the top, covering the cornerbacks' backside.
</P>
<P>
   Tuggle (5-11, 230) was not considered big enough to play
linebacker in the NFL. Scouts called him too short, too small. But
he has proved them all wrong. He is a consummate captain of the
Atlanta defense. And he packs a punch. When Tuggle busts you in the
mouth, you know you have been busted in the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson loves to say that: bust you in the mouth. He is
counting on the Falcons' defense to play Denver in that fashion,
not retreating or playing on its heels but fighting. Tirelessly.
The key, he said, is for his teammates to remember that the Broncos
are mere men. Tuggle, meanwhile, takes the lead in keeping the
Falcons' united _ no personal agendas, no divisive wedges. Their
teammates call Tuggle the Hammer and Robinson the Prophet.
</P>
<P>
   Tuggle and Robinson will tell you that losing, plain and simple,
stinks.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this will be the year for Tuggle and Robinson. Maybe this
will be the year for the Atlanta Falcons, maybe this will be the
year for the Atlanta Falcons, maybe this will be the ... Well,
finally, it is.
</P>
<P>
   Tuggle, Robinson and the Falcons all stand tall here at Super
Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 2230EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
