<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9741 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SUPER-FALCONS-WRs     01-26 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUPER-FALCONS-WRs-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Win or lose this weekend, Terance Mathis has had a
lifesaving year.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta receiver, whose name is generally linked with fellow
receiver Tony Martin, admitted Tuesday that alcoholism, and an
ensuing deep depression, nearly ended his career a couple of years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   In an exclusive interview with the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Mathis detailed a typical day of drinking that generally began with
couple of beers before lunch and didn't end until the wee hours of
the morning, when he would often find himself checking into a hotel
because he couldn't drive home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to come clean,'' Mathis told the paper. ``And
hopefully, doing so will allow me to help other people with the
same problem I experienced. I figure there's someone out there who
can relate, who I can help. But there was a time (when) I was
scared that my (drinking) would hurt somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Falcons coach Dan Reeves who put Mathis in touch with a
doctor. Rather than go into a clinic, he quit cold turkey. He
admits he drinks a beer or two in a social setting but says he's
cured of the need to overindulge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been chewing at me and chewing at me for a long time,''
Mathis said when questioned about the interview he gave. ``This was
the first opportunity I've had in my career when I could speak
about Terance Mathis. That was one of the obstacles I've overcome
to reach this week.''
</P>
<P>
   The realization saved his career. Mathis and Martin didn't get
as much attention as other tandems, particularly Vikings rookie
Randy Moss and Cris Carter, but the Atlanta duo finished just seven
yards behind as the second-most prolific twosome this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're right up there with those guys,'' Martin said before the
NFC Championship Game. ``But attention will come.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly came after Mathis and Martin combined for 202 yards
and two touchdowns in the Falcons' 30-27 overtime win over
Minnesota on Jan. 17, earning them some of the Super Bowl
spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people were very surprised,'' Mathis said. ``When the
magazines came out and the predictions come out, the media makes
all of their superstars before the games are played. We were always
taught that you don't hand out medals for people at the 10-meter
mark of a 100-meter race. You give the medals out when it's all
over with. You can have as many catches as you want, but the big
key for Tony and me is to know our roles with this football team.
We're going to do the job and whatever is asked of us.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no ego problems between the two. Their regular-season
statistics were nearly identical. Martin caught 66 passes for 1,181
yards. Mathis caught 64 for 1,136. Mathis, however, got into the
end zone more often, scoring 11 touchdowns to Martin's six.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis scored two touchdowns against Minnesota. Martin had a
spectacular 70-yard gain to help set up a fourth-quarter field goal
by Morten Andersen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can break the defense down by going deep,'' Martin said.
``And Terance can break the defense down by moving the sticks, with
third-down plays. That's how we complement one another, although
he's also been a deep threat this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a couple of guys who weren't expected to do much in
the NFL. Mathis was selected in the sixth round of the 1990 draft
by the Jets. He started only one game in four years and had only 93
catches for 1,242 yards and four touchdowns in that time. In his
first season with Atlanta (1994), he had 111 catches for 1,342
yards and 11 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, a quarterback in college, was a fifth-round pick in '89
by the Jets, who converted him to wide receiver. He was then
released on the final cut and picked up by Miami, which signed him
to the developmental squad. He started eight games for Miami in
four years, then was traded to San Diego (1994) for a fourth-round
pick.
</P>
<P>
   Martin proved quite a deal for the Chargers. His first catch was
a 61-yarder against Cincinnati. One week later, he tied an NFL
record with a 99-yard touchdown catch at Seattle. He helped lead
the Chargers to Super Bowl XXIX by catching the 43-yard winning
touchdown pass against Pittsburgh in the AFC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   This season, however, proved to be Martin's best. His 1,181
yards were a career high, as was his 17.9-yard average per catch.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis and Martin have been in the background all season, and
not just because of other receiving tandems. They also have been in
the shadow of Atlanta Pro Bowl running back Jamal Anderson, the
player other teams focus on when trying to stop Atlanta's offense.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Vikings held Anderson to 67 carries on 27 yards in
the NFC Championship Game, it was Mathis and Martin who kept
Atlanta's offense going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone always talks about, `If we can just stop Jamal
Anderson, we can win,''' Mathis said. ``Jamal deserves all the
talk. He's been great this year. But I think we've proven that you
can't overlook us, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to catch 100 balls apiece. We talk about our age.
We're the old guys (Mathis is 31, Martin 33) _ no respect for old
guys. We didn't talk about being the best tandem in the league; we
just talked about being the best old guys at our position. We had
fun with that. We've had fun with our age and things we've overcome
to get to this point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 2231EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
