<HEADLINE>
IVANA TRUMP AS MARTHA STEWART II?
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ivana's Living in Style, a magazine created by  &UR; Ivana Trump &LR;  and
Globe Communications of Boca Raton, Fla., began publishing this
week. The first issue featured such stories as ``How to look great
in photos.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dedicated to helping folks who love gracious living,''
said Trump, whose name does not appear on the masthead, ``but don't
have the time or the patience to hand-paint a vase.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MCCARTNEY CHARGES CENSORSHIP OF WIFE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Paul McCartney &LR;  took a half-page ad out in the Times of London
complaining that British disc jockeys are banning a newly released
song by  &UR; Linda McCartney &LR;  because it contains adult language. ``Is
this the '90s or the '20s?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Times, McCartney also complained that
the single bore a sticker saying that listeners should have
parental guidance. His ad, which didn't give the lyric, said he
thought parents should decide on suitability for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The lyric in question, from ``The Light Comes From Within'':
``You say I'm simple, you say I'm a hick, you're f_ing no one, you
stupid dick.''
</P>
<P>
   BBC presenter  &UR; John Peel &LR;  said that perhaps the song isn't being
played much because it isn't very good.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POPE TO DEBUT CD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Abba Peter,'' a CD that will combine pop and new music with
recordings of the prayers, sermons and chats of  &UR; Pope John Paul &LR; 
 &UR; II &LR; , will be released on March 23. Sony Music, which is
distributing the CD _ co-produced by Vatican Radio and an Italian
religious publisher _ says it will be the first CD to feature the
pope's voice.
</P>
<P>
   Its release date was chosen to coincide with the Holy Year in
2000 and the recent 20th anniversary of John Paul's papacy. The
Rev.  &UR; Pasquale Borgomeo &LR; , director general of Vatican Radio, said
it would suggest ``a universal pilgrimage guided by the pope
himself, through a variety of language and expressions.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S.  &UR; Rich Lieberman &LR;  says the pope went to St. Louis because
he's a big Cardinals fan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW TO GET THE JOB &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The California League of Conservation Voters, a group that aims
to protect the environment through political action, is looking for
an executive director. One recent job seeker sent an enthusiastic
application addressed to the California League of Conservative
Voters:
</P>
<P>
   ``I am totally disenchanted with the policies and program
endorsed and enacted by the elitist Democrats since the 1960s,''
the applicant wrote. ``... I am greatly disturbed by the
infiltration and domination of our higher educational institutions
by the so-called `Liberal Elitists' and contamination of the media
by their adherents.''
</P>
<P>
   No tree-hugger he, the applicant wasn't hired.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Management recruiter  &UR; Steve Pantell &LR; , looking for a nurse
manager, received an e-mail from a job applicant saying, ``As I
review the requirements, I am more uncertain that this is not the
position for me.'' (Translation: Double negative aside, the
candidate was withdrawing.)
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. If you're being interviewed for a job over a restaurant
meal and want to order pasta, Mademoiselle magazine suggests, order
penne, which doesn't need to be twirled.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Singer  &UR; Sinead O'Connor &LR;  wrote a letter to the editor of the
Irish Times in support of  &UR; President Clinton &LR; , whom she described
in an interview last month as ``the sexiest man in the universe.''
Her letter asks the Senate to stop ``this Bill Clinton nonsense.
... Does impeachment mean they're gonna turn him into a peach? If
so, can I eat him?''
</P>
<P>
   _ A Washingtonian magazine story about Jewish food in the
nation's capital reveals that  &UR; Cokie Roberts &LR;  adds a dash of
Tabasco, ``her own Louisiana touch,'' when she makes chopped liver
for her Jewish husband.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Ruth Reichl &LR; , who served on the front line of the Berkeley
food revolution of the '70s, is giving up her job as restaurant
critic of the New York Times to become editor in &LR;  chief of Gourmet
magazine, beginning in late April.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the Seattle airport over the weekend,  &UR; Al Guthertz &LR;  heard
the broadcast announcement: ``This is a smoke-free airport. That
means no pipes, cigars, cigarettes or salmon.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The ancient Sumerians had big parties and drums and rattles.
The roots of rock may go back to man's earliest efforts to get a
grip on life.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jukka Ammondt, the Finnish academic who plans to translate
Elvis Presley's songs into Sumerian. Ammondt's Web site includes a
picture of himself naked.
</P>
</TEXT>
