<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9749 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PARCELLS-PROBOWL-     01-26 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PARCELLS-PROBOWL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING HEALTH REASONS, PARCELLS WILL SKIP PRO BOWL
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Only a couple of weeks after saying that he wondered how
much he would be fined if he did not go to the Pro Bowl, New York
Jets coach Bill Parcells on Tuesday got a doctor's excuse to skip
the game. The league accepted it, and Jets assistant head coach
Bill Belichick, will run Parcells' staff at the game, which is in
Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   The game is held the Sunday after the Super Bowl and is coached
by the losing staffs in the conference championships. The day after
the Jets lost to Denver in the conference title game Jan. 17,
Parcells described himself s ``very tired'' and bemoaned pro
football's year-round workload.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has undergone four heart procedures this decade.
According to a statement released Tuesday by the Jets, Parcells
underwent a series of medical tests last week. His cardiologist and
the club's medical director, Dr. Elliot Pellman, recommended that
he not travel to Hawaii. Commissioner Paul Tagliabue concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``He clearly was showing the physical effects of the long
season,'' Pellman said in a statement. ``Given his medical history,
I told him that he should not travel to Hawaii and participate in
the Pro Bowl. He will remain under my care for the foreseeable
future.''
</P>
<P>
   A team official, who spoke only on condition of anonymity,
however, said that the 57-year-old Parcells' current condition
would not prevent him from returning, as he has said he plans to,
next season.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, who is also known to dislike flying, is believed to be
the first head coach to fail to attend the Pro Bowl since it was
recast in its present state in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   During a taping of his pre-game show with Phil Simms before the
conference title game, Parcells told his former quarterback off
camera: ``If I have to coach the Pro Bowl, I'll throw up. How much
would they fine me if I didn't go?''
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's statement from the Jets, Parcells said: ``I was in
the midst of preparation for the Pro Bowl with my staff and fully
planned to carry out my obligation under the NFL guidelines. But
after undergoing a thorough medical examination, I feel it would be
a big mistake on my part not to listen to the doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This limited period of rest will rejuvenate me and allow me to
continue to carry out my duties and commitments to the Jets and to
do everything I can to improve our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick is right in step with his head coach. Just as Parcells
had done during the season, Belichick will not allow the Jets'
assistant coaches to be interviewed by the news media during Pro
Bowl week.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 2239EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0503 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9750 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-LAMBERT-BIOTEC     01-26 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-LAMBERT-BIOTECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNER-LAMBERT TO ACQUIRE AGOURON PHARMACEUTICALS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif.) (bl) 
By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Warner-Lambert Co., one of the hottest drug companies in the
industry, announced Tuesday that it would acquire Agouron
Pharmaceuticals Inc., a small San Diego biotechnology concern, for
$2.1 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   The deal enables Warner-Lambert to add Agouron's Viracept, the
nation's leading protease inhibitor, to its pipeline along with
several other anti-viral and cancer drugs. Analysts praised the
purchase, noting that it was an inexpensive way for Warner-Lambert
to bolster its drug offerings in areas where it had expertise but
few compounds ready for market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, Warner-Lambert decided that it wanted to get bigger
in the anti-cancer, anti-viral markets,'' said Neil Sweig, an
analyst with Southeast Research Partners. ``This was a good
diversification move for Warner-Lambert into several high-growth
product areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Each Agouron share will be exchanged for $60 worth of
Warner-Lambert stock, a premium of 5.6 percent based on Agouron's
last price Tuesday. In a statement issued Tuesday, Warner-Lambert
executives noted that the exchange would be tax-free and would
require the approval of Agouron's shareholders and federal
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The companies did not announce the deal until after the stock
market had closed Tuesday. However, both stocks had climbed
steadily throughout the day before being halted in afternoon
trading. Warner-Lambert's shares rose $1.625, or 2.4 percent, to
$69.125. Agouron rose $3.65625, or 6.9 percent, to $56.8125.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call Tuesday afternoon, Warner-Lambert
executives were enthusiastic about Agouron's pipeline and Viracept.
Analysts noted that Agouron was primarily a one-drug company with
Viracept contributing 87.7 percent of the company's $466.5 million
in sales for 1998, which ended in June.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Agouron transaction is not expected to lift
Warner-Lambert's earnings this year, Viracept is projected to
remain a strong seller. Sweig expects Viracept sales to increase 40
percent to 50 percent for the year ending June 30, a strong gain
for any drug.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is clear that Warner-Lambert executives are counting on
several other drugs in Agouron's pipeline to develop into top
sellers. Analysts said Tuesday that Remune, a treatment for AIDS,
and several cancer compounds, including one for small-cell lung
cancer, had already gained some interest on Wall Street. Agouron
executives said Tuesday that Remune could be on the market as early
as 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Agouron acquisition comes when Warner-Lambert's fortunes are
especially robust. Monday, the company announced that its 1998
fourth-quarter earnings had increased 45 percent, the most of any
company in the drug industry. The gain was propelled by two drugs,
Lipitor for cholesterol and Rezulin for diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, Warner-Lambert gave investors a boon
typically found in high-technology stocks: its shares rose 81.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, in the last three weeks, analysts have begun to
speculate that Warner-Lambert's fortunes may be fading. Earlier
this month, an advisory committee to the Food and Drug
Administration announced that it would review Rezulin after it was
reported that 32 people taking the drug had died.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA's review of Rezulin appeared to have played no part in
the Agouron acquisition. Analysts noted Tuesday that even
profitable drug companies like Warner-Lambert are making
acquisitions to maintain strong earnings gains, which averaged 16
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``By acquiring Agouron, Warner-Lambert will receive some
immediate sales and get some interesting drugs at the same time,''
Sweig said. ``It's a good investment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
