<HEADLINE>
BOEING REPORTS NEGLIGIBLE PROFIT IN 1998 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co.'s once vaunted commercial airplane
business made a negligible profit last year while the company was
carried by the strength of its fast-growing space and defense
business.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Boeing's jetliner factories in Puget Sound are
returning to health, it will take time _ and a lot of efficiency
changes by Boeing _ before profit margins in the commercial
airplane building business improve to where they once were,
industry analysts said Tuesday after Boeing released its year-end
and fourth-quarter financial results.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, they said, the world's largest aerospace company
will make most of its money from its defense and space business,
known formally as Information Space and Defense Systems (ISDS).
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, ISDS will carry this company for the next couple of
years,'' said aerospace analyst Peter Jacobs of the Ragen MacKenzie
firm in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing delivered a record 559 commercial jets in 1998, up from
374 a year earlier, resulting in revenues of $35.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But those sales contributed only $63 million in profits for the
year, or a .2 percent profit margin, according to the financial
results released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's basically a zero profit margin,'' Jacobs noted. Boeing
has said it would like to see margins of more than 7 percent for
its commercial division.
</P>
<P>
   The star for Boeing last year was its defense and space
business.
</P>
<P>
   It contributed $1.5 billion in profits on sales of $19.9 billion
in 1998, for a much healthier 7.7 percent profit margin.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing did have a better fourth quarter than Wall Street
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing earned $465 million, or 48 cents a share, for the final
three months of 1998 compared with a loss of $498 million, or 51
cents a share, a year earlier. The 1997 loss reflected a special
charge of $876 million for commercial aircraft product lines of the
former McDonnell Douglas Corp., which Boeing acquired that year.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for the quarter rose to $17.1 billion, up 46 percent
from $11.7 billion. The fourth-quarter results beat the average 42
cents a share estimated by analysts surveyed by First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's stock fell $1 a share Tuesday, to close at $35.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was OK ... but not outstanding,'' said Nick Heymann,
analyst with Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, Boeing said it earned $1.1 billion, or $1.15 a
share, on total revenue of $56.2 billion. That was significantly
better than 1997, when charges related to jetliner production
problems resulted in a loss of $178 million, or 18 cents a share,
on revenue of $45.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   During a conference call with the media, Boeing Chairman Phil
Condit called 1998 ``challenging.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had significant problems and we met them head on and we
have achieved some significant success throughout our business
segments,'' Condit said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Boeing Commercial Airplanes started the year with
serious parts shortages, a high level of out-of-sequence jobs and a
high rate of overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We focused our efforts, made the necessary changes and now
production in the factories is much healthier,'' Condit said. Parts
shortages and out-of-sequence jobs are down to ``reasonable
levels,'' he said, though overtime remains too high.
</P>
<P>
   With fewer production line snags, Boeing is is close to
delivering all aircraft on schedule, said Alan Mulally, who was
named president of Boeing Commercial Airplanes in September after
the ouster of Ron Woodard.
</P>
<P>
   It was part of a top management shake-up at Boeing that also saw
the retirement of Boyd Givan, the company's longtime chief
financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Givan was replaced late last year by Deborah Hopkins, who was
chief of finance for General Motors operations in Europe. She is
the highest-ranking woman executive ever at Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, she joined Condit, Mulally and other top company
executives in answering questions from the media and industry
analysts during separate morning conference calls.
</P>
<P>
   She gave her first interview for an article published Tuesday in
the Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Though she has been on the job less than two months, she was
quoted in the story as saying she wants to run Boeing after Condit
retires. She also indicated she would not mind running the
company's commercial airplane business.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about those seemingly brash statements during the media
conference call, Condit had this to say:
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to build a team that's world class. I want every
single member of this team to feel like they have the capability of
developing, of running any part of the organization. That the kind
of team I want.''
</P>
<P>
   In the media conference call, Hopkins said she is committed to
educating Boeing leaders on financial principals such as net assets
and inventory turnover.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to go down into the organization, not just the
executive branch, but all the way to the manufacturing floor. ...
to teach, to listen and to answer questions,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Educating the business team is going to go on forever. It will
be part of my own personal scorecard of how well we do. ... We will
expect improved results as people get a better handle on
understanding what their role is in contributing to the enhanced
shareholder value of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Boeing's highest priorities, she and the other executives
said, is reducing the costs of building airplanes and restoring
commercial profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name of the game is being the lowest cost producer,''
Hopkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has acknowledged that for too long the company went after
market share at the expense of profits in the heated battle with
European airplane maker Airbus Industrie. Executives have vowed
that will change and they will make a reasonable return on the
planes Boeing sells.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing factories have not been very efficient. And becoming
more efficient will take time.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial group has forecast profit margins of from 2 to 3
percent this year, and from 1 to 3 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing already has announced plans to reduce its worldwide
employment from a high of 238,000 this year to between 185,000 and
195,000 by the end of 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
