<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A HOSTAGE IN THE POLITICAL WARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Jan. 27: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Gov. George Pataki both have national
ambitions, and New York City is getting caught between them. Their
relationship got off to a spectacularly bad start when Giuliani
endorsed Mario Cuomo, the Democratic incumbent, in the 1994
gubernatorial election. The mayor has made reparations since, but
Pataki and his aides have not forgotten. Now both these Republican
politicians have political action committees aimed at raising their
profiles for 2000, and New York state hardly seems large enough for
both of them.
</P>
<P>
   The easygoing Pataki would be a more likely vice-presidential
nominee than the mayor, but he must be frustrated by Giuliani's
ability to win national attention. Giuliani seems to have lowered
his sights to the Senate seat being vacated by Daniel Patrick
Moynihan. As a senator, the mayor could pose a threat to Pataki's
control of the state party. Perhaps that is the reason for the
continued leaks from Albany suggesting other Republican
possibilities for the Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   Since Pataki was re-elected last year he has approved several
legislative initiatives the mayor opposed, including a law that
puts the city at a disadvantage in negotiations with the police
union. Giuliani then surprised the governor by announcing that he
wanted to build a football stadium on land Pataki controls on
Manhattan's West Side. The football plan stole all the thunder from
the governor's State-of-the-State address.
</P>
<P>
   Now Pataki has surprised the mayor with plans for a major
investigation of the city's Board of Education and School
Construction Authority. Given the fact that Pataki appoints one of
the three trustees who run the Construction Authority, and that he
has shown no particular interest in its operations in the past, it
seems reasonable to ask about his motives. A recent report,
co-written by Giuliani's own Department of Investigation, found
that the governor's last appointee broke the authority's rules to
get a job for the husband of an aide. The hiring became an issue in
mismanagement that led to the death of a young girl in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Construction Authority and the school system are
much-investigated organizations that are being managed better now
than in the past. They seem to need stability more than a lengthy
inquiry that will distract the top management from its normal
duties. Critics have a right to question whether Pataki is trying
to cover his own embarrassment over his trustee's performance and
to avoid giving more aid to the city's needy schools. Giuliani,
meanwhile, should try working together with the governor on
developing Manhattan's West Side. It is a long time until the 2000
elections, and New York City cannot afford to spend it as the
captive of dueling politicians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
