<HEADLINE>
FALCONS REPORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
MIAMI _ Atlanta has four players with Super Bowl experience: safety
Randy Fuller (Pittsburgh), safety Eugene Robinson (Green Bay),
receiver Tony Martin (San Diego) and linebacker Cornelius Bennett
(Buffalo).
<TEXT>
<P>
   However, only Robinson is giving his teammates advice on how to
win the game. The other players and coach Dan Reeves (three losses
with Denver) have bad memories from their Super Bowl experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, meanwhile, is trying to find the right formula to get
his team to play a competitive game. His three previous teams lost
by the combined score of 136-40.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lost three times, and I've changed the way we prepared
every year,'' Reeves said. ``So I've tried every way you can. All
I'm asking is that our football team play well for four quarters in
all phases of the game and then see who wins the thing.'' From
birds to dogs The dirty-bird dancing Falcons officially went to the
dogs yesterday; cornerback Ray Buchanan stole the show at media day
by wearing a dog collar.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's explanation: ``I'm doing this for fun. People have us
as seven-point underdogs, so I thought I would put on my dog
collar.''
</P>
<P>
   Though teammates didn't follow Buchanan's lead, they seem to be
of the same mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been the underdog from day one,'' Archambeau said.
``From the start of the season right through the NFC Championship
Game, we have been the underdog. That's fine. It doesn't matter
what you are going into the game, only what you are coming out of
the game. We are going to come out on top of this one.'' Not the
same 14-2 The Broncos and Falcons both were 14-2 in the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   However, Reeves said the records are deceiving and that the
Broncos' 14-2 is better.
</P>
<P>
   His reasoning is that the Broncos earned their record with
pressure of having the target of Super Bowl champion on their back,
while the Falcons snuck up on some people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Broncos are the best team in football,'' Reeves said.
``This is a team that has the same record as we do, but it's a
totally different record. A lot of people didn't even get up for
us. That's never true with defending world champions. They went out
with all the pressures and responded to every challenge.'' DeBerg
plans return Those who thought Steve DeBerg's comeback was a
one-year thing should think again.
</P>
<P>
   The 45-year-old quarterback, who came out of retirement because
the Falcons wanted a veteran backup, has no plans to retire again.
</P>
<P>
   ``In July, I plan to try to make a football team,'' DeBerg said.
``I really think my concept _ coming into this situation and
contribute as a backup quarterback _ is valid. I think I proved
that. I'd like to try and do it again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
