<HEADER>
A9758 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DENVER-SHANAHAN-T GIVESAL   01-26 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DENVER-SHANAHAN-TEX </SLUG>
 DENVER'S SHANAHAN ASKS A LOT OF, GIVES A
LOT TO PLAYERS (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By KEVIN
LYONS
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Start with the travel accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   First-class hotels, and everybody gets his own room, from the
millionaire superstars to the lower-waged veterans. Even rookies.
</P>
<P>
   Meals are free. And so is Spectravision.
</P>
<P>
   Players for the Denver Broncos must wonder sometimes if they are
royalty, or if they are on a road trip to play a football game.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth-year Broncos coach Mike Shanahan would like to think that
one has to do with the other. When you feel good, you play good.
And there is certainly no doubting how good the Broncos have
played. With a victory against the Atlanta Falcons in Super Bowl
XXXIII on Sunday, the Broncos would set a league record with 46
victories the past three years. More important, they would become
the sixth team in NFL history to repeat as Super Bowl champions.
</P>
<P>
   During this remarkable run, Shanahan _ a carefree man who rides
a Harley and likes to bungee jump and scuba dive _ has been the
team's stern taskmaster and its chauffeur. One minute he may pull a
veteran into his office to grill him for goofing off in practice;
the next minute he's inviting the same veteran to his
8,000-square-foot home for casino night, which he holds once a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in doing the little things and doing them right
because we expect so much from our players,'' Shanahan said.
``That's why we buy them breakfast, lunch and all of the other
stuff. In return, when the game is on the line and you ask them to
do something they might not normally want to do, they'll do it for
you because they know you care about them, because we're all out
for the ultimate goal, and that's to win a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike is more than just a players' coach because players'
coaches may get too close to the players and not do what's best for
the team,'' cornerback Ray Crockett said. ``Mike just wants to make
it as comfortable as possible when you come to work. He told us
from Day One, `If there is anything you guys need to make you do
better and feel better when you're at work, that's what I'm going
to try to do.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the incentives, the perks. If we win, the next two
days we can come in and work out on our own time, and the next
Friday we don't have to wear helmets to practice. We call it hat
day. When we were 13-0 and went to play the Giants, the thing we
were concerned about was not that we'd lost, but that man, `We
messed up hat day.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Before Spectravision and hat day, Shanahan was a scrawny,
150-pounder at Eastern Illinois where his dreams of becoming a
wishbone quarterback ended before they started. In the school's
annual spring game in 1973, he was hit hard in the back. He went
home, got sick, then was rushed to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors had to remove a kidney.
</P>
<P>
   To stay in football, Shanahan, now 46, got into coaching. Barry
Switzer gave him his first coaching job, working with running backs
at Oklahoma in 1975-76. Shanahan spent time as an offensive
coordinator at his alma mater and Minnesota and Florida before Dan
Reeves hired him as the Broncos' quarterbacks coach in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The stormy relationship between Reeves and Shanahan might be the
talk of Super Bowl week. But back then, Reeves thought Shanahan was
one of the brightest young offensive minds around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had area scouts, and when they would come in every year for
the draft, I would ask them to list their top coaches in the
area,'' Reeves told the ``Denver Rocky Mountain News''. ``Mike was
one of those coaches that was on the top of the list of the scouts
in the Southeast. I called him in, and he was extremely impressive.
In fact, I hired him immediately when I talked to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Shanahan was fired twice before he started his run of
success; after going 8-12 as the Los Angeles Raiders' head coach,
and after his feud with Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   As the Broncos' head coach, Shanahan referred to his days as the
San Francisco 49ers' offensive coordinator (1992-94) as his guide.
He took the Bill Walsh way of offense and added his intricacies,
with more motion and more formations. He didn't just script the
first 15 plays. He scripted every minute of training camp, down to
the last minute. He even scripted some of the speeches he used
before regular-season and playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   His organization has carried over to the playing field. The
Broncos have finished among the NFL's top five in total offense in
each of Shanahan's four seasons as head coach. In 1998, the John
Elway-Terrell Davis-led unit scored a team-record 501 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got so much confidence in Mike,'' Elway said. ``He's got
a great mind, and he knows football better than anyone I've ever
seen. And he's been good with me. If there is something in the game
plan that I really don't like and I tell him, he won't call it'' in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mike is similar to Bill Walsh and George Seifert in
that the attention to detail for this football club is superior,''
said Broncos linebacker Bill Romanowski, who played for the 49ers
from 1988-93.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a perfectionist.''
Mike Shanahan bio Born Aug. 24, 1952 in Oak Park, Ill. College:
Eastern Illinois Coaching experience 1975-76: Oklahoma running
backs/wide receivers 1977: Northern Arizona backfield 1978: Eastern
Illinois offensive coordinator 1979: University of Minnesota
offensive coordinator 1980-83: University of Florida offensive
coordinator 1984: Denver Broncos receivers coach 1985-1987: Broncos
offensive coordinator 1988-1989: Los Angeles Raiders head coach
1989-1990: Broncos quarterbacks coach 1991: Broncos offensive
coordinator 1992-1994: San Francisco 49ers offensive coordinator
1995-present: Broncos head coach Career record: 55-29 (8-12 with
Raiders; 47-17 with Broncos)
</P>
