<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-BURNOUT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS NOT WORRIED ABOUT BURNOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ A hockey team can burn out during an 82-game
regular season.
</P>
<P>
   But Stars players insist they're not going to be that team.
</P>
<P>
   With 39 games remaining and coach Ken Hitchcock calling for more
emotion from his team, the Stars addressed the theory of saving
something for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A team can burn out; I've seen it happen before,'' center Guy
Carbonneau said. ``But this is a team that's built not to have that
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars captain Derian Hatcher said Hitchcock's drive for
intensity throughout the season won't be the Stars' downfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hard, but I don't think he's too hard,'' Hatcher said.
``He gives us plenty of days off, and we have to make use of those.
You can burn out, but I think we do a lot of things to prevent that
from happening.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars often are compared to the Detroit Red Wings in their
ascent toward a potential Stanley Cup. The Red Wings won three
consecutive divisional titles from 1993-96, including two
Presidents' Trophies for best record in the NHL. But they didn't
win the Stanley Cup until they finished fifth overall in 1996-97
then cruised through the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit did that, but we're not them,'' Hatcher said. ``Last
year is a good example. We didn't lose in the playoffs because of
burnout; we lost because of injuries and some other problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock drove the Stars hard from the opening whistle last
season when they won the Presidents' Trophy and the top seed in the
playoffs. He said the Stars had plenty of energy all the way
through the Western Conference Finals, where the Stars lost to the
Red Wings in six games.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's asking for the players to put their foot on the gas
once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have raw emotion in our game; it's as simple as
that,'' Hitchcock said. ``Our game is pressure and pursuit, and you
have to have emotion to play that game. When we were winding down
to the break, we didn't have that emotion and we didn't play well.
Now, since we're well-rested, we need to get that raw emotion
back.''
</P>
<P>
   But isn't the first half an indication of why the Stars have to
pace themselves? They played 43 games, hit a high point with a
15-game unbeaten streak in December and early January then
staggered into the break at 2-4-1, seemingly exhausted. They can
blame a tough road schedule in December, but they face the same
hurdle in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to us before the break is I think we had more
troubles mentally than we did physically,'' Hatcher said. ``When
you go 15 games without losing, you start to believe you can't
lose, no matter what you do. So you don't take the games as
seriously, and bad habits start to creep in.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think we learned from that, and I think it's just
another thing we'll be able to use this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau said the Stars' team system helps protect them from
burnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look, we have four lines and six defensemen and
that's why we won't wear down,'' he said. ``Even the players we do
have that play a lot don't play near as much as the top guys in the
league. So I think that helps keep us fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher leads the Stars in ice time at approximately 24 minutes
per game, ranking him 28th in the NHL. Mike Modano is the most-used
Stars forward, averaging 20:45 per game, 99th in the league.
</P>
<P>
   And if the frequent rest and balanced play isn't enough, veteran
Brian Skrudland said individual motivation can go a long way in
keeping the team from burning out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at our team, all of us are hungry. The guys who
are getting 10 minutes want 15 and the guys who are getting 15
minutes want 20,'' Skrudland said. ``I think we'll be a very hungry
team when the playoffs come, because that's who we are. We all want
\Rthe Stanley Cup\S, and that's what it's all about. We want it
now, and we're going to want it even more then.''
</P>
</TEXT>
