<SLUG> BC-NY-IVYLEAGUE-POLICE-805&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHLY EDUCATED OFFICERS FIGHT CRIME AND SKEPTICISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Adam Kasanof arrived on the campus of Columbia
University, he was a budding Latin scholar, a fan of Catullus, a
student of declensions and dactylic hexameter who was there to
pursue the life of the mind.
</P>
<P>
   But when he returned to the Ivy League campus as an alumnus
seven years later, it was not as a doctor, or a physicist, or a
Nobel laureate in literature.
</P>
<P>
   He came back as a cop, a police officer from the 26th Precinct,
there to help an emotionally disturbed woman perched atop a stone
wall who was yelling ``Dead white meat'' at anyone who approached.
</P>
<P>
   Kasanof, class of 1981, is the first to admit that this sort of
endeavor was not promoted in the catalog for Columbia, which has
little history as a finishing school for New York's Finest.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my college instructors actually said when he found out
I was going to the Police Department that I was a saintly madman,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kasanof is certainly unusual _ not everyone can score 1410 on
the SAT _ but he is not alone in forsaking the status and wealth
that prestigious degrees can yield for the modest salary and
multiple perils of a career as a New York City police officer.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bronx, there is a plainclothes narcotics officer who went
to Harvard. In Queens, there is a sergeant who graduated from
Cornell. In Brooklyn, the commander of the 67th Precinct detective
squad joined the force after earning a master's degree from New
York University. In northern Manhattan, Officer Christopher
Schmidt, who graduated from Columbia in 1993 with a 3.4 grade point
average, works the night shift riding in a radio car.
</P>
<P>
   These officers with elite degrees can find themselves astride
two worlds _ their police careers at odds with the conventions of a
first-class college, and their educational pedigrees often viewed
as eccentric in the station house. ``Some people think you are
nuts,'' said Sgt. Andrew Hatki, a 1989 Cornell graduate who joined
the force in 1992. ``They don't understand. They say, `With that
kind of education?' They think you are wasting it. But I don't feel
that way. I feel like I'm doing what I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department does not record where all of its officers
attended college, but officials estimate that a few dozen have
joined the force after studying at elite universities. Several of
these officers acknowledged in interviews that their choice of
police work, at first glance, might seem odd, but they said they
were attracted by the same sort of incentives that lure other
recruits: adventure, hefty pensions, lofty ideals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to sound corny,'' said Schmidt, ``but I always liked
helping people and this is a real helping-people job.''
</P>
<P>
   David Durk appealed to the social conscience of the
well-educated three decades ago when he showed up on Ivy League
campuses, a whistle-blowing New York police lieutenant in the midst
of unearthing a major corruption scandal. He told students that if
they really wanted change, they should drop the ``Pig'' chants and
take the police test. Many did. But Durk, an Amherst College
graduate, said the department never pushed to enroll these
candidates. ``They told me I was a starry-eyed idealist,'' he said.
``Later on they acknowledged they were not going to let these
people in, because they were going to be troublemakers.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the department seems more in touch with its academic
side. Since 1995, recruits have been required to have two years of
college or two years of military service. Candidates for captain
must have a four-year degree. Although no one is about to confuse
the department with Cambridge, some 7,350 officers, about one-fifth
of the force, now hold college degrees. Another 535 have advanced
degrees, like a law degree.
</P>
<P>
   But very few were educated in the Ivy League, where the career
orientation is decidedly white-collar and the political ethos can
be considerably left of center. Indeed, one of the darkest moments
in Columbia history is the bloody day in 1968 when administrators
called in the police to sweep the campus of a student rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Kasanof, who returned to Columbia to get his law degree in 1988,
said that while his friends supported his interest in a
law-enforcement career, some fellow undergraduates carried a
misconception that ``the people who work in the Police Department
are basically all Philistines, brutes, idiots, or that they do
something that is essentially undesirable and that is oppress
people or act as an occupying army.''
</P>
<P>
   The climate is more balanced today, said Capt. William Gorta,
who earned his bachelor's degree at Columbia in 1995, while working
as a police officer. ``Maybe they were surprised to find an egghead
with a shield,'' he said of his Ivy League classmates, ``but I
never heard a snide remark.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although few officers express regret about the decision they
made, their families can be another story. Officer Edward Conlon,
who pursues drug dealers in the Bronx and writes about police
matters for The New Yorker, has said he believes his late father,
who was an FBI agent, would have disapproved of his decision to
join the police after graduation from Harvard in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Rosendo Velez, Columbia class of 1984, said his father, a
grocer on the Lower East Side, was initially disappointed by his
choice. ``I was supposed to be the doctor in the family,'' he said.
But a chance encounter with a retired detective, who photographed
his wedding and proselytized about the nobility of police work,
convinced the young graduate to return, as a police officer, to the
mean streets his family had hoped he would escape. He has
questioned the decision only once.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first night, I had to take my gun out three times,'' he
said. ``I said to my wife when I got home, `What the heck am I
doing here?'''
</P>
<P>
   When they are finished assuaging their families, some highly
educated officers have to confront the stereotype that someone
acute enough to have attended an Ivy League school would be obtuse
patrolling the streets of New York. Though many of these officers
are savvy city natives and physically fit, there is sometimes a
lingering sentiment in station houses that what an officer needs to
know cannot be found in any book.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone seems overly academic, there is an inclination to
question whether they can handle themselves in a street
condition,'' said Chuck Wexler, executive director of the Police
Executive Research Forum, a research group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Velez said he occasionally feels that he must ``let people know
that before I got promoted, I did my share of street work and made
my share of arrests.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Kasanof, the cerebral Latin major, showed he was
much more than a student of an ancient language in 1984, when he
shot and killed a mugger who tried to rob him on a Manhattan subway
train.
</P>
<P>
   Although they have given up a lot in terms of wealth, status and
even safety for their law-enforcement careers, the officers said
they found that they were often envied by their college classmates
as people of action who are not shackled to a desk, and were
prodded at parties to detail their derring-do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you are talking to a kindergarten class or a group of
Columbia professors,'' said Gorta, ``they always ask the same two
questions. One, `Do you have a gun?' And two, `Have you ever shot
anyone?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
