<SLUG> BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR MARTIN, NEW TEAM, SAME GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Four years ago, Tony Martin and I were on the same
wavelength in this very same city at this very same stadium. Martin
was with San Diego; the Chargers were playing the San Francisco
49ers in Super Bowl XXIX.
</P>
<P>
   As a staunch fan of the old American Football League, I picked
San Diego to win, more from emotion than intellect. Martin, being a
San Diego Charger, felt the Chargers could win.
</P>
<P>
   Three plays into the game, Martin and I had the same sinking
feeling. Jerry Rice scored on 50-yard touchdown, and I looked at
the person next to me and shook my head. Martin was sitting on the
Chargers' bench. ``I remember looking at Shawn Jefferson and
saying, `This is going to be a long day,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A long day, indeed. When the nightmare ended, San Diego was
routed, 49-26.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, both of us are back _ same city, same stadium
_ but Martin is on a different team. Last June the Chargers traded
Martin to Atlanta; this week he is attempting to make sure the
Falcons are on a different wavelength, prepping them, as much as he
can, for what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them they have to be focused from the starting
lineups,'' Martin said, looking over his shoulder at the Pro Player
Stadium field.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I told them that there's going to be fireworks and
all that. Even the halftime show. I told them during the halftime
show they're going to sit in the locker room for 30, 40 minutes.
You got to warm back up again. During the regular season, as soon
as you go to the locker room, it's time to go back out. But they're
going to have to experience it for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Atlanta is experiencing something the organization
may never have thought would happen. In making its first Super Bowl
appearance, the franchise made one of the most dramatic turnabouts
in National Football League history. Martin, 33, has played a
resounding role in Atlanta's transformation. He has given the
Falcons a deep threat, and he is a feared receiver who is
acknowledged as one of the most precise runners of routes in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   In nine NFL seasons, the Miami-born Martin has refused to be
denied, and he has made himself into a star. ``I was going to make
it in the league,'' he said. ``It was a matter of who had the
patience.''
</P>
<P>
   The mantra for Martin and the Falcons is: time and patience.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was a quarterback at Mesa College in Colorado. The Jets,
coached by Joe Walton, drafted him in the fifth round, converted
him to a receiver, then cut him. Martin was picked up by the Miami
Dolphins, who put him on their developmental squad. In four years
with Miami, Martin played in all 16 games each season, starting at
least five games. In 1994, he was traded to San Diego, where he
blossomed into one of the NFL's most well-rounded receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Martin led the team in receptions, receiving yards
and touchdowns. But Martin and Chargers Coach Kevin Gilbride did
not get along. A trade was arranged with Atlanta, with Gilbride
apparently thinking he was sending Martin to an official NFL
wasteland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't see eye to eye for whatever reason,'' Martin said of
Gilbride. ``He said I couldn't get off the bump-and-run coverage,
and that other guys were having better camps than me. That was
ludicrous. Anyway, that was his opinion; the Chargers listened to
him, and now he's not there.''
</P>
<P>
   More revealing than anything Martin says about himself is what
teammates say about him. Terance Mathis, another former Jet, was
Atlanta's primary receiver the last four seasons but needed another
half. Martin has been it.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis is recovering from a drinking problem, and he said Martin
had been an immeasurable help. Mathis said when his energy was low
in a game, Martin would pat him on the back and pick him up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was my roommate in training camp; we talked about a lot of
things,'' Mathis said. ``The only thing he talked about was getting
back to the Super Bowl and being successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathis said Martin talked about how San Diego treated him.
``Tony has overcome some things off the field also,'' Mathis said,
``but he hasn't let that affect him on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Buchanan, the Falcons' cornerback, said that Martin was
``tough as nails.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let Tony Martin fool you,'' Buchanan said. ``They say
he's a smooth dresser, how laid back he is. When he gets out on
that football field, he's an animal.''
</P>
<P>
   So this is homecoming week for Tony Martin. He was born here in
1965, attended high school here and, for four seasons, played pro
ball here.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's back in the Super Bowl for the second time in five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible,'' he said. ``I pinch myself every morning
that I'm playing in the Super Bowl, again, in Miami. That has to be
a record.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
