<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOWLING-PBA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PBA, TECHNICIANS HAVE REPLACED SHOWMEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAULA CABALLERO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
Paula Caballero DALLAS _ Pro bowler Carmen Salvino moved like a
dancer on the approach, gyrating at the foul line, putting a little
body English on the ball, the pins. With his pants pitched up in
vintage-Salvino fashion, he engaged the crowd while keeping people
at home glued to ABC on Saturday afternoons.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Salvino and other stars of the 1950s and '60s such as Dick
Weber, Harry Smith, Billy Hardwick and Don Carter sold the game to
fans as not just bowling but entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't start bowling for the bowling itself. I did it
because they looked like they were having fun on TV,'' said
Marshall Holman, bowling Hall of Famer and current Professional
Bowlers Assocication tour broadcaster. ``That's what drew me to the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Pro bowling might never see another Salvino and the television
exposure that went with his era. But the tour does not lack for
marquee attractions, such as Walter Ray Williams Jr., or
up-and-comers, like 1998 rookie of the year Chris Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   The talent is on display this week at the Don Carter PBA
Classic. Qualifying competition begins today at Don Carter's All
Star Lanes-West in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The guy to root for and against might be one and the same:
Williams. He has been so dominant, some fans can't help but want to
see him lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are a lot of people who want to beat Walter Ray,
and there are probably a lot watching who want to see people beat
Walter Ray,'' Barnes said. ``It's the same with everyone who has
success. People want to see them knocked down a notch.''
</P>
<P>
   Other fans root for him because he's simply the most dominant
player in the game. He was recently selected PBA player of the
year, the third consecutive year he has won the honor, and has
earned more total money than any player in PBA history. He was
inducted into the PBA Hall of Fame in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes Walter great is the ability to understand what the
lane is looking for,'' Holman said. ``He can make the adjustment in
the least amount of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams entertains with his mesmerizing skill. Although he has
become more demonstrative as his career has progressed, he is not
apt to show the kind of enthusiasm fellow PBA Hall of Famer Brian
Voss does. Voss seems to exude charisma paired with intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems to thrive in that environment,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Weber is another player who is likely to let fans see his
emotions _ bad or good. Holman, the bad boy of his era, said he
sees a comparison between him and Weber.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very excitable and gets very angry,'' Holman said. ``I
joke with Pete and tell him he's the new me.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker Bohn III and David Ozio also rank high as fan favorites.
Bohn, a left-hander, impresses with his silky smooth game. Ozio
gets the crowd going.
</P>
<P>
   ``He yells, but it's never vicious,'' said Fort Worth bowling
pro Susie Minshew. ``He shows you, `I'm excited about my stuff' but
not `Nyah-nyah-nee-nyah-nyah.'''
</P>
<P>
   The stars of the past, however, are more compelling to some.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot looser back then,'' said Joe Doctor of Arlington,
who runs the Dallas/Fort Worth National Amateur Bowlers Inc.
tournaments. ``Every competitor seemed a lot looser. Now it's a
more serious game. I understand they're making a living, so it has
to be serious, but it seems like some take it too seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   There are reasons why fans might not see the ``looseness'' of a
Salvino on the lanes these days. Salvino and several of his peers
owned bowling centers or pro shops, creating a second source of
income. Today, many of the bowlers use tour earnings as their sole
source of income.
</P>
<P>
   The game itself has also become far more complicated and
technical, mostly because of new equipment. In the past, a pro
could arrive at a tournament armed with one or two rubber bowling
balls.Today a pro has 10 to 15 reactive resin balls.
</P>
<P>
   Although reactive resin balls might hook and hit harder, unlike
rubber balls, they also eat up lane oil, which results in constant
adjustment from shot to shot. Unlike the golfer who can see the
bunkers and the undulations of the greens, the bowler cannot see
the changes in lane conditions until the ball reacts to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just move two boards left with your feet,'' PBA
assistant tournament director Damon Sarrocco said. ``Now, you need
to jump left, change the ball, change the angle, change the speed,
change four or five different things.''
</P>
<P>
   More decisions, more choices _ more at stake.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps in time, a new showman will be born.
</P>
<P>
   ``As some of the younger players make TV, I think they'll get
into that environment, that part of the game,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I will.'' \Ntagtop:Paula Caballero, (817) 685-3863
\Ntagbottom:pcaballero\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
