<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-CAPITALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRETZKY'S 38TH BIRTHDAY IS A BASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOE LAPOINTE 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two days after winning a sport utility vehicle as
the most valuable player in the National Hockey League All-Star
Game, Wayne Gretzky observed his 38th birthday. He celebrated
Tuesday night by giving out the gift of goals.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky assisted on two scoring plays by Adam Graves and one by
Mathieu Schneider to help the Rangers gain a 4-1 victory over the
Washington Capitals.
</P>
<P>
   Ranger Coach John Muckler said, ``I was at the All-Star Game. I
watched Gretz very closely. He had a big smile on his face. He was
having some fun. Things were working for him, which is all great.
It looks like he had some fun tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Niklas Sundstrom clinched the decision with a short-handed goal
late in the third period, assisted by Graves, and Graves scored his
21st into an empty net after Washington pulled its goalie for an
extra attacker.
</P>
<P>
   Also starring for the Rangers was Mike Richter, the goalie, who
stopped 34 of 35 shots and kept the score tied when the Rangers
were overwhelmed by Washington attackers in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   The victory ended the Rangers' losing streak at four games, kept
them within range of a playoff berth in the Eastern Conference and
got them off to a good start on a difficult three-game road trip.
They visit Carolina on Thursday night and Detroit on Saturday
night. They have 43 points, 4 behind the eighth and final playoff
spot in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love to play the game,'' Gretzky said. ``Mike's a
world-class goalie. He stood on his head in the second period, and
that was the difference in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The score was tied, 1-1, after one period and it was the same
after two, only because Richter played brilliantly in the Rangers'
net and the Capitals misfired on a few glorious scoring chances.
</P>
<P>
   During the middle period, Washington outshot the Rangers by
16-3. The Rangers had a power play during the period, but were
outshot, by 1-0, during the two-minute span and never managed to
set up the attack in the Capitals' zone.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what line or defensive combination Muckler sent out in
the period, all of them seemed to be a step slower. It was not as
if the Rangers were tired. This was the first game in five days,
thanks to the All-Star Game break.
</P>
<P>
   Coming into the game, the Rangers' power play had scored only
one time in its previous 25 chances to fall from first in the
league to second. But they scored on their first manpower advantage
Tuesday night. Getting the goal was Graves, assisted by John
MacLean and Gretzky, at 11 minutes 51 seconds of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   After he took a pass behind the goal line from Brian Leetch,
Gretzky fed the puck to the front to MacLean, who moved it
left-to-right for Graves, who was parked on the doorstep of goalie
Olaf Kolzig. It was Graves' 20th goal of the season, most on the
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Graves, who could become an unrestricted free agent this summer,
has scored at least 20 in his eight Ranger seasons except for the
lockout-shortened 1994-95 season, when he scored 17. He had 23 last
season despite being slowed by injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's Adam Oates, in his first game since recovering from
a groin injury, tied the score at 1-1 by scoring at even strength
at 18:04. Assisted by Joe Juneau and Petr Bondra, Oates' was the
last shot of several during an intense foray. He collected a
rebound and beat Richter as the goalie sprawled toward him.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider, the Ranger defenseman also returning from a groin
injury, gave New York a 2-1 lead at 1:37 of the third period by
pouncing on Gretzky's rebound and firing the puck high into
Kolzig's net before the goalie could move from side to side.
Gretzky, in his 20th season, is tied for third in the league in
assists with 39.
</P>
<P>
   With the Capitals on the power play, the Rangers made it 3-1 at
12:34 when Graves rushed the puck up ice after Sergei Gonchar
failed to handle a pass near Richter's net. When Juneau neglected
to cover Sundstrom, Graves timed a pass to him and Sundstrom
steered it in from the edge of the crease. It was only the second
short-handed goal of the season for the Rangers. The other, by
MacLean, came on a penalty shot.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second game of the season between the Rangers and the
Capitals. The Capitals won the first by 5-1 on Jan. 7. They will
play three more times in the regular season. Washington is one of
the few Eastern teams trailing the Rangers. The Capitals, who went
to the Stanley Cup finals last season, are 12th, with 36 points. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
