FALCONS SAYS THEY CAN CONTAIN DAVIS, with chart 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
MIAMI _ Talk to any member of the Atlanta Falcons' defense, and
you'll get the same answer.
<TEXT>
<P>
   All together now:
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to stop Terrell Davis and the running game first.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering that Denver's Davis led the NFL in rushing with
2,008 yards, scored 21 touchdowns on the ground and was selected
the league most valuable player, that the Falcons would have to
stop Davis first is not a revelation.
</P>
<P>
   How, however, is another story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we can stop anybody,'' defensive tackle Travis
Hall said. ``We are just going to play defense like we have all
year. We've stopped most running backs. We are not going to hold
him to nothing, but we must contain him.''
</P>
<P>
   During the regular season, the Falcons allowed only 75.2 rushing
yards per game, 3.33 per play and gave up a league-low six rushing
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta safety Eugene Robinson said the Falcons will play the
safeties close to the line of scrimmage and take their chances
against the Broncos' passing game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been getting advice from other players \Raround the
league\S on how to stop Terrell,'' he said. ``You have to try to
cut out the running lanes and play an eight-man front.''
</P>
<P>
   Falcons linebacker Cornelius Bennett said they must also play
aggressive but smart.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to know your assignments and be where you are
supposed to be,'' he said. ``Terrell likes for you to overpursue.
You can't pursue straight up the field. You have to go at angles to
take away the cutback lanes.''
CHART: Nowhere to run How the Falcons' defense fared against the
run during the regular season: Second in the league in yards
allowed per play (3.33) Second in the league in yards allowed per
game (75.2) Held 12 opponents to less than 100 rushing yards Set
team record by giving up only 1,203 rushing yards Led the NFL in
fewest rushing touchdowns allowed with six
</P>
</TEXT>
