<HEADLINE>
WITH TERRERI IN GOAL, DEVILS STOP SENATORS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Nothing discouraged the Devils on
Tuesday night, not the three losses to Ottawa earlier this month,
not even a sore neck to Martin Brodeur that developed just before
the game and forced him to sit.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Terreri, Brodeur's understudy, stepped right into
Brodeur's skates and came up with an inspiring performance in goal
in only his seventh start of the season. Terreri's timely saves and
some effective finishing led the Devils to a 4-1 triumph over the
Senators, the team that has been their biggest nemesis the past
three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The victory brought revenge and redemption against Ottawa and
Damian Rhodes, the starting goaltender. The Senators eliminated the
Devils in the playoffs last spring and prevented the Devils from
making the playoffs in the last game of the regular season in 1996,
the year after the Devils captured the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Pandolfo, Brendan Morrison, Brian Rolston and Vadim
Sharifijanov scored the goals for the team's third consecutive
victory, which pushed the Devils (26-14-5) into fourth place ahead
of the Senators (25-15-6) in the overall standing in the Eastern
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Terreri won his first four starts this season before losing his
next two. He gained his fifth victory of the season Tuesday night
on 24 saves and just one blemish, a goal by Shawn McEachern, which
came late in the second, after the Devils had scored their four
goals.
</P>
<P>
   A save by Terreri in the eighth minute after a giveaway in his
zone inspired the Devils to take the lead on Pandolfo's 11th goal
of the season about five minutes later. His goal came from a sharp
angle on the left after the puck ricocheted into the net off
Rhodes' skate.
</P>
<P>
   Another good save by Terreri in the 15th minute of the first
period, this time on Aleksei Yashin, encouraged the Devils even
more. Morrison extended the lead to 2-0 with 1 minute 39 seconds
left, when he found the upper right corner from the bottom of the
right circle for his sixth goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils came out with plenty of enthusiasm for the second
period. It reached a higher level when Rolston stripped Wade Redden
at the Devils' blue line during an Ottawa power play, skated in
alone on Rhodes and beat him with a backhander.
</P>
<P>
   Rolston's goal was his 13th of the season (and fourth
short-handed) to give him his 33rd point of the season, passing his
total last season. Playing in his 300th game, Rolston had trouble
controlling his joy as he joined his teammates on the bench after
his goal.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes was under siege for the rest of the second period as the
Devils kept entering his zone in waves and Sharifijanov gave the
Devils a 4-0 lead with his eighth goal of the season with 1:48
left.
</P>
<P>
   But McEachern took part of the momentum and joy away from the
Devils by getting his 22nd goal of the season with 47.5 seconds
left to narrow the gap going into the last period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
