<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-BRUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALO CONTINUES TO SAVE HIS JOB AS WELL AS SHOTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Shots have been fired at the New York
Islanders' Tommy Salo from all angles this season. He was
considered to be good, but not a legitimate starting goalie,
someone who cracked under pressure and wasn't consistent enough.
Once the Islanders' franchise goalie, Salo was reduced to trade
bait two weeks ago when the Islanders acquired Felix Potvin, a
two-time All-Star, from the Toronto Maple Leafs.
</P>
<P>
   Salo never complained and he never demanded a trade. He never
said anything negative about Mike Milbury, the team's general
manager, who had promised to trade him as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing Milbury was preoccupied with other things last
week. Because on Tuesday night, Salo found his way back into net,
and he was outstanding again. Salo stopped 25 shots as the
Islanders beat the Boston Bruins, 4-1, at Nassau Coliseum. As the
clock expired, the 10,061 fans revived the chant ``Salo! Salo!''
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders (15-29-3) got goals from Robert Reichel (two),
Bryan Smolinksi and Zigmund Palffy in their second straight victory
under Bill Stewart, who replaced Milbury as head coach last
Thursday, when Stewart guided them to their first victory since
Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Taylor scored the only goal for the Bruins (20-17-7), who
had 16 saves from Byron Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   When the Islanders traded Bryan Berard to the Maple Leafs for
Potvin on Jan. 9, Salo's days as an Islander seemed to be finished.
Berard for Potvin, Salo for a much-needed scorer.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it has been almost three weeks since the 21-year-old
Berard was dealt for Potvin, 27, a move that was widely criticized
as shortsighted. And not only does Salo still have a Long Island
address but he has also started the Islanders' last two games.
</P>
<P>
   Looks as if the Islanders have themselves a goalie controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Potvin, and his $2.7 million contract, watched from
the bench as Salo stole another game. Salo had earned Tuesday
night's start, Stewart said, after his sparkling 26-save
performance in the Islanders' slump-busting 5-2 victory in
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   So where does this leave Potvin? In the same spot he was in at
Toronto before demanding to be traded. He has struggled since
coming to the Islanders, and has yet to start for Stewart, whose
philosophy is to play the goalie who is winning.
</P>
<P>
   So if Salo continues to win, Potvin will continue to sit.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders handed Salo a two-goal lead in the first period,
and Salo took it from there.
</P>
<P>
   Reichel gave the Islanders a 1-0 lead at 5 minutes 42 seconds of
the first period. Palffy started the play with a snappy drop pass
to Reichel, who whipped a wrist shot through a screen and past
Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   On the same shift, only 40 seconds later, Smolinski scored his
first goal since Dec. 18. Reichel set up Smolinski with a behind
the back pass into the slot. Smolinski controlled the puck and
lifted it into the corner, over Dafoe's right leg pad.
</P>
<P>
   In the second period, Reichel scored again and Palffy got his
first goal since Jan. 2 to put the Islanders ahead by 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   Reichel's second goal was set up by Trevor Linden, who threaded
a pass behind the Bruins' lone defenseman on a two-on-one rush.
When the puck hit Reichel's stick, he faked left, then right, then
left again and slid the puck under Dafoe's stick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 2257EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0530 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9779 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FELDMAN-MUSIC-$ADV31-     01-26 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FELDMAN-MUSIC-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIMMERING ORCHESTRAL TAPESTRIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 31) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may not be helpful to living musical practitioners to know
this, but death does wonders for a composer's reputation, at least
as measured by representation on CD.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous recordings of works by Luigi Nono, John Cage, Witold
Lutoslawski and Toru Takemitsu have come too late for them to hear,
and the posthumous crescendo is even more spectacular in the case
of Morton Feldman.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his death, in 1987, the CD catalogue included
barely a handful of his pieces. Now his whole immense output is
heaving into view, and the peaks are beginning to become evident.
Most recently, three releases have started to repair the neglect of
his orchestral compositions.
</P>
<P>
   Feldman's absorption with the orchestra was a phenomenon of the
1970s, when he produced 11 big scores, most of them with abstract
titles: ``Cello and Orchestra,'' ``String Quartet and Orchestra''
or simply ``Orchestra.'' The list looks monotonous, perhaps
deliberately so, and certainly the works are all alike in being
continuous, slow and generally quiet.
</P>
<P>
   But the range possible within that overall character is
astonishing. Where ``Piano and Orchestra,'' for instance, suggests
stillness, bells and clouds, ``Oboe and Orchestra'' is urgent and
intense. There was also, it seems, an increasing concern with
repeating patterns, until Feldman stopped writing for large
resources and began his great carpets of sound for piano, string
quartet or other small ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   His only composition for full orchestra after 1979 was ``Coptic
Light,'' written after a gap of seven years on a commission from
the New York Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   This unique piece amplifies the carpet manner. A string-led
orchestral body weaves stitch after similar stitch, occasionally
shifting to a different motif. Meanwhile, percussion instruments
patter with other repeated figures and the rest of the orchestra
supports held tones in an effect Feldman likened to that of a
piano's sustaining pedal.
</P>
<P>
   The textile metaphor, too, was his own. He loved, studied and
collected Oriental rugs, and titled ``Coptic Light'' with reference
to Coptic textiles he had seen at the Louvre. Like those scraps of
fabric, this music is woven, and the light surely comes from its
shimmer of similar threads repeating over background hazes.
</P>
<P>
   Long awaited on CD, this remarkable composition can now be heard
in two versions, performed by Michael Tilson Thomas and the New
World Symphony (Argo 448 513) and by Michael Morgan and the
Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin (CPO 999 189).
</P>
<P>
   The recordings are quite different. If Thomas' has more light,
Morgan's is more Coptic. One puts more emphasis on continuity, into
which the repetitions start to blur (though they blur clearly),
while the other keeps the weaving in focus.
</P>
<P>
   The American recording is also slower, by a significant 25
percent, and more laid back. Perhaps it is thereby truer to the
composer, though one might well prefer Morgan's more insistent
approach, especially when he combines insistence with objectivity.
</P>
<P>
   The music sounds as relentless as the sea washing onto a beach:
each repetition is a new wave, often only marginally distinct from
the last in its force and the outline it leaves on the sand. And
the process seems just to stop, whereas Thomas shapes the piece
toward a dissolve.
</P>
<P>
   Different couplings may help the buyer choose. Morgan's
recording comes with a set of Feldman pieces from the beginning of
the 60s, ``Durations I-V.'' Comparative miniatures in length and
sonority, these are scored for groups ranging from duet (cello and
piano) to sextet by way of two delightful and very Feldmanesque
trio combinations: violin, piano and tuba, and violin, cello and
vibraphone.
</P>
<P>
   Each instrument proceeds in its own time through a sequence of
short phrases, repetitions and lone sounds, but there is no danger
of inconsistency when the atmosphere is so calm. The performances,
by the Ensemble Avant-Garde of Leipzig, are poised and beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas offers two orchestral works from the preceding decade:
``Piano and Orchestra'' and ``Cello and Orchestra,'' with Alan
Feinberg and Robert Cohen the soloists. ``Piano and Orchestra'' is
an anticoncerto, not only in its concentration on minimal effect in
the solo part, much of which consists of single chords or note
repetitions, all quiet, but also in its use of an orchestral piano
to play some of the solo material while the ostensible soloist sits
silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cello and Orchestra,'' on the other hand, is centered on the
soloist, who lifts up one contemplative phrase after another, then
takes a wonderfully long time to find the right close.
</P>
<P>
   The performances are much surer than those to be heard in an
alternative release, again from CPO (999 483; two CDs), which
combines these two works with others of the same period, ``Oboe and
Orchestra'' and ``Flute and Orchestra,'' all played by the
Saarbrucken Radio Symphony under the direction of Hans Zender.
</P>
<P>
   But this set, on two disks for the price of one, has the
advantage that ``Oboe and Orchestra'' is so strong and moving a
piece. It starts with the oboe slowly wailing over a background of
tam-tam crashes and continues like a wild lament heard from a great
distance. Sometimes the oboe seems to be remembering its role as
orchestral tuner, though it might appear that the orchestra is
tuning the oboe rather than the other way round. At other times the
soloist's repeated motifs are wide and fraught.
</P>
<P>
   Armin Aussem is the excellent oboist, and this recording, along
with Morgan's of ``Coptic Light,'' demands to be heard widely. It
may be significant that ``Oboe and Orchestra'' came just before
``Neither,'' another high point in Feldman's output (available on
Hat Art).
</P>
<P>
   ``Flute and Orchestra,'' which came later, drifts into endless
repetitions without yet acquiring the qualities of ``Coptic
Light,'' whether the soft ferocity of Morgan's performance or the
quiet blaze of Thomas'.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 2259EST &QL; 
