A9809 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DEBT-NYT     01-26 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DEBT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI WANTS TO USE TOBACCO FUNDS TO REDUCE DEBT
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki said Tuesday that for the next
five years, New York state should use 75 percent of its share of
the national tobacco lawsuit settlement, or $1.5 billion, to reduce
state debt.
</P>
<P>
   Just days ago, his aides signaled that the governor wanted to
use some of the settlement to provide coverage for the rapidly
growing number of people without health insurance, raising the
hopes of health-care advocates that Pataki planned a major
initiative for the uninsured. But the governor made it clear
Tuesday that he had in mind a sum that would cover only a small
fraction of the more than 3 million New Yorkers who are uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   The $25 billion settlement is to be paid over 25 years, with the
state and local governments splitting the money. Pataki said in the
first five years he wanted to dedicate 25 percent of the state's
share to health care, about $100 million a year, a fairly small
amount to a state health care budget that stands at $27 billion.
Uses for that $100 million, he said, would include not only
coverage for the uninsured, but anti-smoking programs and doctor
training.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican governor was declaring his opening position in
what is sure to be a long, hard piece of bargaining with the
Legislature. His stance puts him starkly at odds with the Democrats
who control the state Assembly, and with health care advocates and
leaders of the health care industry, who had hoped that most of the
money would go toward helping the uninsured and reducing the number
of people who smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's tobacco proposal is part of a larger plan to keep state
debt essentially flat over the next five years. Independent
analysts have sharply criticized the governor for increasing debt,
even as the state enjoys record surpluses, and the debt is
frequently cited as a factor in the state's low credit rating.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco money comes from last year's settlement of lawsuits
filed by the states against tobacco companies, to recoup money
spent on treating people with smoking-related illnesses. The
companies agreed to pay the states $246 billion over 25 years. New
York's share would be $800 million a year at the start, growing to
$1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Around the country, states are just starting to decide how to
use the tobacco money, and no real patterns have emerged. But a
handful of governors have proposed that virtually all the money go
to health care.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the governor and the Legislature must decide
together how to spend the money, and Pataki's stance Tuesday puts
him at odds with both houses. The Democrats who control the state
Assembly say it should go to health care and school construction,
and the Republicans who control the Senate want a large part of it
to be used for tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, D-Manhattan, said: ``It's
totally inappropriate that the scarred lungs of New Yorkers be used
to enhance his political ambitions. He's designing his priorities
to appeal to the radical right of the national Republican Party,
instead of using these dollars the way they were intended, like
anti-teen-age smoking programs and coverage for the uninsured.''
</P>
<P>
   State Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, R-Rensselaer County,
had talked about using one-third of the money for health care
programs, one-third for tax cuts and one-third for debt reduction,
but he refrained from criticizing Pataki's proposals Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Kenneth Raske, president of the Greater New York Hospital
Association, said, ``Since these funds were predicated on the pain
and suffering of tobacco users, it ought to be used for health care
purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals stand to gain directly from any program to aid people
without health insurance, because those people are often treated in
emergency rooms and cannot pay their bills, so the burden for their
care falls heavily on hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the governor's proposal for using the tobacco money drew
fire Tuesday, his debt reduction plan attracted praise from fiscal
analysts, some of whom have been sharply critical of him in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that this is a very good first step, and I'm pleased
that the governor has shown some real commitment on this,'' said
state Comptroller H. Carl McCall, a Democrat who has frequently
called for debt reduction. ``I think he's listening to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
