<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0534 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9914 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-WRs-HNS &LR;      01-26 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-WRs-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ If Denver receivers Ed McCaffrey and Rod Smith were a
comedy team, they would be like Laurel and Hardy, Martin and Lewis
or the Smothers Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey would be the straight man. He's about as lively as
cold oatmeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what you play your whole career for,'' McCaffrey said
Tuesday about being in Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   The loquacious Smith would be the comedian. He accommodates all
requests for sound bites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got so much talent on this team _ kind of like having a
six-pack of Coke,'' Smith said. ``When you finish one bottle,
there's always another one right there ready for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Broncos, McCaffrey and Smith make a great
team _ not as comedians but as receivers. This season, they
combined to catch 150 passes (Smith 86, McCaffrey 64) for 2,275
yards (Smith 1,222, McCaffrey 1,053) and 16 touchdowns (McCaffrey
10, Smith six).
</P>
<P>
   In playoff victories over Miami and the New York Jets, Smith had
seven catches for 108 yards and a touchdown. McCaffrey had six for
118.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do everything together off the field,'' Smith said. ``My
kids play with his kids. I go to his house and play video games.
All the functions we have (off the field), we do together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed's a great competitor. I love playing with him because I
know he's going to be on the other side busting his butt. I know I
have to be just as good or better.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey was voted to the Pro Bowl, but Smith wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's taking me with him, so I'm getting a free trip out of
it,'' Smith said. ``It's good to have a friend like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith and McCaffrey couldn't be more different. McCaffrey is
white, 6-5 and 215 pounds. He grew up in Allentown, Pa., played at
Stanford, was drafted by the Giants' Bill Parcells, was cut by Dan
Reeves and earned his first Super Bowl ring with San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is black, 6-0 and 196 pounds. He grew up on the Arkansas
side of Texarkana, played at Missouri Southern, was not drafted and
signed with the Broncos as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons cornerback Ray Buchanan, who will be covering Smith and
McCaffrey on Sunday, guaranteed an Atlanta victory. Buchanan has
been outspoken, and he showed up for media day Tuesday wearing a
dog collar.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys like to have the image,'' Smith said with a
laugh. ``Nothing he says or does is going to win the game. The only
people who talk and can affect the game are the refs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of what he says or does, he's still got to come out
and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who has quietly become one of the better receivers in the
league, can't wait for the Super Bowl, because he loves to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to play with fear,'' Smith said about his
motivation. ``If you play overconfident, you'll get slapped in the
face. You've got to have the fear that somebody's trying to take
something away from you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not scared of my opponent. I'm just scared of failing the
guys that I go to work with every day. I have to come back to the
sideline and look them in the eye. I want them to say to me, `Wow,
how'd you do that?' I don't want them to say, `You cost us the
Super Bowl.'''
</P>
<P>
   Smith is a big-play receiver. McCaffrey is a clutch receiver.
</P>
<P>
   In his career, McCaffrey has played with quarterbacks Phil
Simms, Steve Young and John Elway.
</P>
<P>
   ``All are very talented, but they have different styles,''
McCaffrey said. ``In terms of accuracy, Phil was unbelievable. He
was so smart. Steve's lefthanded, so right off the bat I had to
adjust because the ball comes at a different angle. He was
extremely quick, a pretty talented passer.
</P>
<P>
   ``John has unbelievable arm strength. It's never too late to get
the ball from him. If the ball's in his hands, you've still got a
chance to catch it.''
</P>
<P>
   If McCaffrey were the vengeful type, Sunday's game would mean
more to him because Reeves placed him on waivers when he coached
the Giants. But Reeves has since said it was one of his biggest
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the best thing that happened to me,'' McCaffrey said.
``I went to San Francisco (1994), and not only did I earn a Super
Bowl ring, but I met Mike (Shanahan), who was the offensive
coordinator.''
</P>
<P>
   When Shanahan was hired as head coach of the Broncos, he signed
McCaffrey.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and McCaffrey are excellent blockers. They wouldn't be on
the field if they couldn't block, especially for running back
Terrell Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason our offense is so successful and we score so many
points is because we're multifaceted,'' Smith said. ``Man, we've
got balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrell makes it go. If we aren't working hard and blocking
for him, the running game won't work as well as it does. The reason
Ed and me were over 1,000 yards is because of Terrell. With all the
emphasis the defense puts on Terrell, Ed and me get a lot of man
coverage. We should beat man coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   And they are favored to beat the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if this is going to be John's last game or not,
but we can't let him lose this one,'' Smith said. ``Whether he
retires after this game or another year, one day I can tell my
grandkids that I caught a lot of passes from him. And I dropped a
few, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
