<HEADER>
A9903 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAXTER-COLUMN27-COX     01-26 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Witness selection is about more than facts
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There she goes, again. Monica Lewinsky and her
entourage decamped from Washington on Wednesday, her business with
the House impeachment managers finished for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough, Lewinsky is likely to be talking to the Senate, and
eventually to Barbara Walters. But she arrived and departed from
this visit without dispelling the air of mystery that has
transformed her from a California girl to a national enigma. Except
to those authorized to question her, she remained silent, lips
closed in a faint half-smile, Mona Lisa with a logo on her cap.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost exactly a year ago that the networks cut away from
their coverage of Pope John Paul II's visit to Cuba to broadcast
that footage, which we have come to know so well, of the president
greeting Lewinsky in a receiving line. This year, as Lewinsky was
leaving Washington, the president was greeting the pope in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, celebrating the beginning of its second year of
convulsion over the former White House intern, gave her a new
sobriquet, the ``Mademoiselle of the Mayflower,'' after the swank
hotel where she stayed this week.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, when the House managers conducted their
informal interview with her, several Republican senators appeared
to be backing away from calling witnesses in Bill Clinton's
impeachment trial. By Wednesday the partisan lines had formed
again, causing Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle to repeat his
prediction that witnesses are ``inevitable. ``
</P>
<P>
   ``I think those soft Republicans have turned hard,'' Daschle
said.
</P>
<P>
   To win over their Senate colleagues, the House Republicans
reluctantly agreed to pare their witness list down to only three
names. There could have been no question Lewinsky would be on the
short list. Nor was it surprising that Clinton adviser Vernon
Jordan was named, despite White House attorney Charles Ruff's
impersonation last week of the testimony he might give.
</P>
<P>
   Given the case that the managers have laid out over the past two
weeks, however, the third choice seems very odd.
</P>
<P>
   Given the number of times her name has come up, the obvious
choice would have been Betty Currie, the president's secretary who
retrieved the gifts Clinton gave Lewinsky. Arkansas Rep. Asa
Hutchinson, in fact, made reference to what the Senate might learn
from observing Currie's body language under questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of Currie, however, the third person on the list is
former White House aide Sidney Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to call Blumenthal as a witness, argued Rep.
James Rogan of California, because Clinton lied to him about his
relationship with Lewinsky, knowing that he might be called as a
witness before a grand jury where he would repeat the lie. Yet
Rogan also described Blumenthal as ``just one example of several
aides whose testimony is already on the record,'' to whom the
president lied.
</P>
<P>
   Currie, on the other hand, is the only person beside the
president who can testify about several critical matters in the
managers' case. The conversation in which the managers allege that
Clinton coached Currie about what she could say she knew about his
contacts with Lewinsky has been quoted literally dozens of times
during the impeachment trial, the House debate and the House
Judiciary Committee hearings.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton attorney David Kendall pointed out Wednesday, the
idea of calling Currie to testify has already been condemned by
Utah Rep. Chris Cannon, a Republican prosecutor, as ``a rotten,
nasty thing to do with a public servant.''
</P>
<P>
   Could it also be that the managers shied away from putting an
African-American woman on a list that already includes Jordan? And
was it a point in favor of naming Blumenthal that he is roundly
disliked by many of the reporters and pundits who will be analyzing
his testimony?
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
