<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9908 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOLK-ART-ANTIQUES-$AD     01-26 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOLK-ART-ANTIQUES-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARP-EYED COLLECTORS DRIVE UP THE PRICE OF FOLK ART  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 31) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RITA REIF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Outsider art continues to upstage American folk art
in gallery and museum exhibitions as well as in the press. But at
the auctions, traditional American folk art chalks up spectacular
prices for the choicest examples, while the quirky, visionary
Outsider art lags far behind in prices fetched at auction.
</P>
<P>
   This month's folk-art sales began with the proverbial bang at
Christie's when two extraordinary paintings by Edward Hicks rewrote
the records for the artist and for folk art.
</P>
<P>
   The first painting, ``The Residence of David Twining,'' which
had never been on the market previously, was sold by Dr. Thomas
Lincoln, a descendant of Twining and of Abraham Lincoln, for $1.4
million. Seconds later, a second painting, ``Peaceable Kingdom,''
from 1837, was sold for $4.7 million to Richard York, a New York
dealer. The total sales of folk art at Christie's was $9.3 million
and $2.6 million at Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in prices for folk art reflects the broadening and
maturing of the market. Twenty five years ago, most collectors
bought largely on instinct because the field was still relatively
new and few books had been written on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Today's collectors come armed with scholarly studies and advice
from experts, and as a consequence, they are knowledgeable about
the minutest details of objects, what makes them rare and even who
owned them.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of ``Peaceable Kingdom'' sheds light on how the prices
for folk-art masterpieces have escalated over the last 20 years.
The painting metaphorically depicts Isaiah's prophecy of the
animals of the earth in a wooded idyll while in the background
William Penn signs a treaty with Indians.
</P>
<P>
   It was auctioned in 1980 at Samuel T. Freeman in Philadelphia
for $210,000, which was then the record for the artist and for folk
art. Long admired as among the most gripping of the 62 versions of
``Peaceable Kingdom,'' it is also considered desirable because it
is one of few that include every animal in Isaiah's prophecy.
</P>
<P>
   The sales at Christie's and Sotheby's offered works from
important collections, each of which exceeded the totals expected.
The largest was the 660-piece collection of John Gordon, a folk-art
dealer in New York who had amassed pottery, weathervanes, painted
furniture and watercolors as well as the idiosyncratic 20th-century
works of Bill Traylor, Minnie Evans and Edgar Tolson. The pieces
fetched a total of $2.8 million at Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Kleckner, director of folk art sales at Christie's,
attributed the success of the Gordon sale in part to new findings
by scholars over the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Three frakturs in the sale from Bucks County in Pennsylvania,
for example, which were identified as having been painted by a man
called the Rockhill Township artist, brought from two to four times
expectations. When not attributed to an artist, similar works sold
below estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, an 18th century floral-decorated redware bowl was
expected to sell for at most $3,500 but brought $13,800. Until
recently, Ms. Klechner said, the bowl would have been identified as
generic redware from Pennsylvania, but because its origins could
now be pinpointed to Hagerstown, Md., it was more valuable.
</P>
<P>
   At Sotheby's, traditional portraits, landscapes and marine
paintings from the collection of Edgar William and Bernice Chrysler
Garbisch, well-known collectors of Americana, were sold for the
Whitney Museum of American Art for a total of $685,000. And the
collection of Outsider art works by Traylor, Henry Darger, Nelly
Mae Rowe and Lee Godie, assembled by Herbert Waide Hemphill Jr., a
pioneer collector in this field.
</P>
<P>
   The collection was sold for $239,200 by the National Museum of
American Art. The costliest lot was a surreal Traylor drawing of a
leaping man on the head of a bird, which was sold for $46,000 to
James Curtis, a New York private dealer in 20th century prints.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the best economic environment for this sale,'' said
Nancy Druckman, the director of folk art at Sotheby's. ``And we had
an unusually high number of pieces that were fresh to the market.
This was really the last public chunk of the Garbisch folk art.''
</P>
<P>
   David Wheatcroft, a folk-art dealer from Westboro, Mass., was an
active buyer at both houses this month, spending in all more than
$330,000 for about about 30 items. His buying ranged from redware
pottery and paper cutwork to a Garbisch prize, a richly detailed
watercolor, ``Berks County Almhouse, Hospital and Lunatic Asylum''
by C.C. Hofmann. The painting is the only such watercolor on paper
known by Hofmann, and it sold for $112,500, more than three times
what Sotheby's had expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serious money was spent this month on folk art,'' Wheatcroft
said. ``It's pretty obvious that the folk art field is carried by
the economy. This market is not so superheated as the late 1980s
when it was almost as good as sold when you bought it. But we did
see some wild abandon at these sales.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
