<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9909 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ORGAN-DONATIONS-FILM-     01-26 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORGAN-DONATIONS-FILM-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAITING FOR A TRANSPLANT, WAITING FOR LIFE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 31) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Neb.)   (af)  
 By JEAN NATHAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Early last month at the New York Public Library's
Donnell branch, a standing-room-only screening was held of ``The
Kindness of Strangers,'' a 104-minute documentary that provides a
close look at organ donation and transplantation from the personal
perspective of donors, survivors, recipients and their families.
</P>
<P>
   When the lights came up, teary audience members could be seen
fishing for their drivers' licenses and filling out the organ donor
consent information.
</P>
<P>
   At the reception following, attended by, among others, friends
and family of the filmmakers as well as several of the film's
subjects, nearly everyone seemed shaken. In one corner, Lola Van
Wagenen, the mother of James Redford, the film's producer, was
huddled with her two daughters. All three were weeping.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which had its premiere at the Telluride Film Festival
in September, was also shown last Monday at a special _ and
especially packed _ screening at the Sundance Film Festival,
founded by Robert Redford, Redford's father. (Photographers flocked
to the screening with hopes of catching the elder Redford, who, of
course, was there.) The decision to include the film was made by
Geoffrey Gilmore, the director of programming for Sundance.
</P>
<P>
   Almost six years ago, after years of health problems stemming
from an autoimmune disease of the liver, Redford, 36, a
screenwriter, underwent two liver transplants performed by Dr.
Byers W. Shaw Jr. at the University of Nebraska Medical Center in
Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Redford, the father of two children, runs five miles, or
skis, or mountain bikes most days near his Marin County, Calif.,
home, and his career as a screenwriter is thriving. ``Hearts and
Bones,'' based on his screenplay, starring Kiefer Sutherland and
Darryl Hannah, has just been completed and other projects are in
development.
</P>
<P>
   But Redford is also trying to write a better script for the more
than 60,000 Americans now waiting for organ transplants. In 1995 he
founded the James Redford Institute for Transplant Awareness to
produce films that would educate people about organ donation. (Each
day, Redford said, 11 people die while waiting for a transplant.)
</P>
<P>
   To find a filmmaker for ``The Kindness of Strangers,'' Redford
did not have to look far. His best friend, Maro Chermayeff, whom he
met in pre-kindergarten at the Dalton School in Manhattan, was also
a classmate at the University of Colorado in Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   While he, in worsening health, went on to earn his Master's
degree in English at Northwestern University, she came home to New
York to begin a career as a film editor and documentary filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Redford and Ms. Chermayeff, who served as one of the film's
producers as well as its director and editor, decided to use the
technique of cinema verite, dispensing with narration and letting
their subjects tell their own harrowing stories.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Chermayeff scouted for patients and families, Redford
set to work raising the $600,000 required to make the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I begged, borrowed and stole from everyone, starting with my
parents,'' Redford recalled. (Ms. Chermayeff also called on her
family's resources for help, and Chermayeff &AMP; Geismar, her father
Ivan's graphics design firm, contributed the film's credits and
graphics.)
</P>
<P>
   Shooting began in October 1995, with one-third of the budget
raised, and was completed in March 1998. Since then, the filmmakers
have been seeking a distributor.
</P>
<P>
   The final film interweaves the stories of four transplant
patients with the stories of two families on the other side of the
equation who made the wrenching decision to donate while they were
still struggling to absorb the shock of a sudden death.
</P>
<P>
   The organ recipients _ all patients at Shaw's hospital in Omaha
_ were filmed during the first year.
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to address the donor side of the equation, Ms.
Chermayeff and Christine Le Goff, a third producer on the film,
made weekly trips from New York to Philadelphia to participate in a
support group for donor families at the Delaware Valley Transplant
Program.
</P>
<P>
   After two months, having gained the trust of the group, Ms.
Chermayeff brought in the film crew. And by then, Kathy and Russell
Kilmer, whose 20-year-old daughter Meghan had died in June 1996 in
a car accident, had invited Ms. Chermayeff and her crew into their
home.
</P>
<P>
   There, they filmed the couple discussing the painful decision to
donate their daughter's organs, and their heartbreaking
descriptions of coping with the loss of their daughter. They also
watched home videos of Meghan Kilmer on her prom night and of a
family Christmas when they were all together, footage that is
incorporated into the film.
</P>
<P>
   The logistics of such a project were daunting.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout most of the two and a half years of filming, Ms.
Chermayeff wore a beeper so that she could be there if an organ was
located for two of the would-be recipients she was chronicling, as
well as every time the Delaware Valley Program received a call
about a potential organ donor.
</P>
<P>
   And constantly she had to switch gears as the story shifted
beneath her. When a 4-year-old boy she had been following died of
an infection just after his transplant, Ms. Chermayeff, who was to
begin filming his part of the story in two days, instead helped his
father carry the child's body to the morgue.
</P>
<P>
   The viewer has the sense that Ms. Chermayeff and her crew were
everywhere at once. They are on the phone line when 12-year-old
Maria Darrah, who had hepatic fibrosis, learns that a liver has
been found for her, and they are there hours later as she arrives
in Omaha from Ohio and while her father comforts her as she is
prepared for surgery.
</P>
<P>
   They are there as Peter Wiley, a hepatitis C patient, weeps with
fear and relief with his wife as he is told the bad news, that his
condition is worsening, and the good news, that he is being moved
to the head of the waiting list to receive a new liver. And they
are there as the roller coaster dips again when he is moved down
the list as his condition slightly improves and no organs are
available.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chermayeff said both Ms. Darrah and Wiley, whose eventual
transplant surgery was chronicled in the movie, are doing well more
than ``two years out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just so pleased with what they've done,'' said Shaw, now
chairman of the department of surgery at the Omaha hospital, in a
telephone interview from Omaha. ``They dug through the superficial
layer of spectacle and got down to the human interest story.''
</P>
<P>
   And he spoke of an unexpected therapeutic effect the film has
had for him: ``Everytime I watch it I get more emotional about it.
You'd think that wouldn't happen. I thought I was dealing OK with
these things. Now I realize I was dealing by repressing my
feelings. The film has helped me to deal with the tragedy I see all
the time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
