<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9910 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-HOLOCAUST-2TAKES-$     01-26 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HOLOCAUST-2TAKES-$ADV31-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEVISION AND THE HOLOCAUST: AN ODD COUPLE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 31) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID MARGOLICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What millions saw that day in May 1953 from El Kapitan Theater
in Hollywood was a classic scene from the raw, unpolished days of
early television. Primitive microphone in hand, the host of ``This
Is Your Life,'' Ralph Edwards, plucks a pretty young woman out of
the studio audience, ostensibly at random.
</P>
<P>
   He then asks the actor Jeffrey Hunter, sitting strategically at
the woman's side, to read the cover of the book Edwards is holding.
``This Is Your Life, Hanna Bloch Kohner,'' Hunter declares. Mrs.
Kohner's eyes open wide and her jaw drops. ``Oh, no! Oh, my God!''
she exclaims in an Eastern European accent before sinking her head
into her gloved hands. The music swells, the audience applauds and
Mrs. Kohner is then escorted to the stage.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcast appears to be little more than vintage schlock,
but it is actually an important historical artifact. Sandwiched
between harp glissandos and commercials for Hazel Bishop's lipstick
_ ``won't eat off, won't smear off, won't kiss off'' _ may well
have been television's first feature on a Holocaust survivor.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the ``chair of honor,'' Mrs. Kohner watches in wonder
as people from her past materialize to recall her childhood in
Czechoslovakia, her deportation in a cattle car to Theresienstadt,
her survival at Auschwitz and liberation at Mauthausen. A studio
band plays Beethoven's Fifth Symphony, ``The Horst Wessel Song''
and the Kol Nidre prayer from Yom Kippur in the background.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards has a script, of course, but by today's standards the
show seems refreshingly awkward and unrehearsed. If television was
young, so, too, were public discourse about the Holocaust (the term
itself did not even come into popular use for another two decades)
and most survivors themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kohner had ceased to be one of those mute, gaunt, ageless
figures in striped uniforms standing at the barbed wire but had not
yet become one of the aged, often vulnerable remnants of Hitler's
Europe we've heard so often since. She's a beautiful woman in her
30s, confident, composed, surprisingly good-natured.
</P>
<P>
   ``May I say, Mrs. Kohner, that looking at you it's hard to
believe that during seven short years of a still short life, you
lived a lifetime of fear, terror and tragedy,'' Edwards tells her.
``You look like a young American girl just out of college, not at
all like a survivor of Hitler's cruel purge of German Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   Television and the Holocaust are clearly an odd couple, says
Jeffrey Shandler, who teaches in the department of Hebrew and
Judaic studies at New York University. But they are also ``age
mates,'' having entered the American consciousness around the same
time. And more than film or art or literature, Shandler says, the
much-maligned small screen is responsible for turning the Holocaust
from a calamity befalling a foreign people in a different time and
place into a ubiquitous, paradigmatic part of American culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television and the Holocaust may seem strange partners,''
Shandler writes in ``While American Watches: Televising the
Holocaust,'' published this month by Oxford University Press, ``but
their half-century of shared history has shaped how Americans now
understand and respond to moral crises of modern life.''
</P>
<P>
   Scholars accustomed to maligning the medium have overlooked
television's contribution to that understanding, says Shandler, who
has a doctorate in Yiddish studies from Columbia University.
Eminent writers from television's early days like Rod Serling,
Reginald Rose and Paddy Chayefsky weighed in on the subject, in
shows featuring actors like Charles Laughton, Maximilian Schell,
John Cassavetes and Robert Redford; few then raised the point,
heard often years later, that television and the Holocaust were
inherently incompatible, that the first inevitably trivialized the
second.
</P>
<P>
   Because Yiddish culture, too, has historically been
underestimated, he says, redirecting his attention from Sholem
Aleichem to ``The Twilight Zone'' may not seem such a stretch.
``I've moved from one vernacular unjustly held in low regard to
another,'' he said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Television's ability to mold attitudes about the Holocaust stems
both from its intimacy _ its peculiar power to penetrate our homes
and lives _ and its reach. The 1978 mini-series ``Holocaust'' alone
reached 120 million Americans. But the coverage didn't come only in
extravaganzas; over the years the Holocaust has made guest
appearances on ``All in the Family,'' ``Lou Grant'' and ``Star
Trek.''
</P>
<P>
   Television helped the Holocaust infiltrate the American psyche
precisely because of the ease of the exposure; you could always
turn the channel or get up during a commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Shandler was working on an unrelated topic in the National
Jewish Archive of Broadcasting at the Jewish Museum in New York
when an excited colleague told him about Hanna Kohner's television
appearance. To Shandler it sounded like a parody from ``Saturday
Night Live.'' But when he watched the episode, he found it
grotesque, moving and utterly unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from Yiddish radio, he notes, individual survivors of
Hitler's concentration camps had been largely invisible and unheard
on the airwaves. Newsreel photographers had been more intent upon
filming bulldozers burying piles of corpses than on interviewing
anyone still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Early television approached the topic gingerly; so did American
Jewish leaders and Jewish television writers and executives. And
Holocaust survivors, then still known as ``refugees'' or
``displaced persons,'' were more intent on building new lives than
on reliving tortured old ones.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it took ``This Is Your Life'' _ which The Saturday
Evening Post once called ``the weepiest show on television,'' whose
guests had to be tricked into letting their life stories be told
and whose endings were all happy _ to make it happen. That six
million Jews were murdered isn't mentioned; that Mrs. Kohner's
parents and her first husband were among them is, but only briefly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Hanna Bloch Kohner, this is your life, safe and happy in
the country of your adoption,'' declares Edwards. He then presents
her with a charm bracelet commemorating moments from her life
(``Wouldn't you give anything to see what's on it?'' Shandler asks)
and a movie camera from the Spiegel catalogue.
</P>
<P>
   Discussions of the Holocaust, albeit in ways that underplayed
its specifically Jewish dimension, actually had became a staple of
postwar television's ``Sunday ghetto,'' those devotional programs
broadcast while people prepared for church.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In 1948 ``Lamp Unto My Feet'' featured two newly arrived
children discussing in Yiddish their first Thanksgiving in the
United States. Four years later, ``Frontiers of Faith'' did the
first English dramatization of Anne Frank's diary. More impressive
and more widely watched were the docudramas, which have since
become, quite literally, museum pieces.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Holiday Song,'' a 1952 ``Philco TV Playhouse'' production,
Paddy Chayefsky tells how a cantor rediscovers his flagging faith
in God by helping to reunite two Auschwitz survivors in Brooklyn.
To Chayefsky and other writers, Shandler says, the problem was
always ``how to present a Jewish story, especially one about
anti-Semitism, to an audience largely composed of non-Jews, during
a period when American Jews are particularly circumspect about
being distinguished as Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the producer David Susskind, a Jew himself, reportedly
complained that the script was ``too Jewish'' and asked Chayefsky
to make the cantor a minister or priest. It was Susskind's boss, a
non-Jew, who let Chayefsky change things back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playhouse 90'' presented a Holocaust-related drama in each of
its five seasons. One was Abby Mann's ``Judgment at Nuremberg,''
expanded two years later into the better-known movie; it achieved
dubious notoriety when one sponsor, the American Gas Association,
pressured CBS into bleeping out several references to gas chambers.
Another show, Rod Serling's ``In the Presence of Mine Enemies,''
featured Charles Laughton as a (British-accented) rabbi in the
Warsaw Ghetto and Robert Redford as a sympathetic Nazi who falls in
love with his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joseph Goebbels himself could not have produced such a piece
of Nazi apologetics,'' Leon Uris said afterward. Undeterred,
Serling later featured the Holocaust on several ``Twilight Zone''
episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Shandler says of these dramas: ``As documents about American
Jewish identity in midcentury, they're very revealing. American
Jews were then reaping all these benefits the country had to offer,
but at the same time they had complex and unresolved feelings about
losing their families in Europe. These two impulses were difficult,
if not impossible, to reconcile.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanna Kohner notwithstanding, the first watershed in Holocaust
television, Shandler argues, was the Eichmann trial in 1961.
Chastened into temporary public-spiritedness by the recent quiz
show scandals (in fact, Eichmann's glass booth reminded many
viewers of the isolation booths on shows like ``The $64,000
Question''), the networks began playing taped excerpts of the
trial, flown over daily from Israel.
</P>
<P>
   But many viewers were disappointed; the defendant was too
``banal, puny, enigmatic and boring,'' Shandler says. When ratings
dropped, so did the coverage. Convinced that a more palpably
loathsome Eichmann would produce higher ratings, CBS soon did a
docudrama on the subject, with Telly Savalas and Carroll O'Connor
playing Eichmann acolytes.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 17 years, the Holocaust appeared regularly in
dramas, science fiction series and even comedies, invariably to
examine issues of justice, intolerance, evil. Dennis Hopper went
through a mini-neo-Nazi phase in episodes of ``The Defenders'' and
``The Twilight Zone.'' Lou Grant has to approve a story of another
young American neo-Nazi, this one hiding his Jewish roots.
</P>
<P>
   Archie Bunker, of all people, discovers a swastika splattered
over his front door. The Starship Enterprise beams Captain Kirk and
Spock onto a planet where extraterrestrial Nazis have recreated
1930s Germany and cite Spock's distinctive physiognomy to prove his
inferiority.
</P>
<P>
   But the Holocaust moved ``from the episodic to the epic,''
Shandler says, with ``Holocaust: The Story of the Family Weiss,'' a
nine-and-a-half-hour, four-day prime-time mini-series just before
Passover 1978. It was this series that generated the first real
debate about whether television inherently trivialized genocide.
</P>
<P>
   But the same series arguably helped prompt the pope's visit to
Auschwitz, the Holocaust Memorial Museum in Washington and efforts
to videotape genuine Holocaust survivors before it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the shows he retrieved, Shandler knows that many more
are missing. For instance, he knew nothing about a drama I remember
vividly from my own childhood, circa 1960, in which a Polish
husband and wife, ignoring the ridicule of their anti-Semitic
neighbors, hide a Jewish couple under the floorboards of their
house.
</P>
<P>
   At the show's conclusion, two frail, elderly Jews, the real-life
couple, appeared on the screen; inelegantly reading a prepared
statement in heavily accented English, they thanked viewers for
witnessing their story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very often, people will mention programs I hadn't heard of,
and what is striking is that they not only remember the programs in
great detail but also the context in which they saw it, the time of
year, the room of the house they were in, who was or wasn't there,
the discussion or the bad dreams they might have had afterwards,''
Shandler says. ``It's a testament both to how much of early
television has simply disappeared into the ether and how pervasive
this subject was, even in the early years.''
</P>
<P>
   Shandler has even been told of the time a Holocaust survivor
appeared on ``Queen for a Day.'' ``It could be apocryphal,'' he
says. ``But it would be worth getting your hands on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 2313EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
