<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0540 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9917 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NOWITZKI-MAVS-TEX     01-26 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOWITZKI-MAVS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS ROOKIE ADJUSTING TO NBA SPEED, STRENGTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Mavericks long-shot rookie Greg Buckner irritatingly
hung inside Dirk Nowitzki's jersey like body odor when the
20-year-old, prized German almost snapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get off!'' yelled Nowitzki, trying to clear offensive room by
swinging his bony elbows.
</P>
<P>
   When the scrappy Buckner wouldn't relent, Mavericks coach Don
Nelson stepped in with a lesson and a warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweep the ball low to get away from him, don't throw elbows,''
Nelson said calmly to Nowitzki. ``If you throw elbows in our
league, it's a technical foul. Two technical fouls and you're
kicked out of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   After a second, Nowitzki literally scratched his head.
``Really?'' he said. ``Wow.''
</P>
<P>
   One lesson down for the Mavericks' first-round pick, one million
to go.
</P>
<P>
   After two weeks in Dallas and six days on the practice court
with the Mavericks, Nowitzki is slowly but surely adjusting to the
drastic differences in culture and competition.
</P>
<P>
   Off the court, Nowitzki is quickly becoming Americanized.
Learning to live on a $1.47 million salary after a year of
$1,000-a-month wages in Germany, he has rented a luxury car for
three months, stopped calling Reunion Arena ``a big gym,''
developed a fondness for rap music and found his way to Taco Bell
on the 10-minute drive from the Baylor-Landry Center to his
downtown apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK, but I miss mom's kitchen,'' he said, joking.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his life, Nowitzki is apart from his
parents and longtime coach/adviser Holger Geschwindner. His
girlfriend, Sybille, is coming to visit this week, but Nowitzki's
new caretakers are teammates Steve Nash, Hubert Davis and Chris
Anstey, who live in the same complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit scary being so far from home and alone,'' said
Nowitzki, who, at first reluctantly, left his tiny hometown of
Wurzburg to pursue his NBA dream. ``But right now it's OK because
all I have time to do is just eat and sleep and play.''
</P>
<P>
   In between faxes and e-mail with the folks, Nowitzki is
furthering basketball skills that will, according to Nelson, make
him a strong rookie of the year candidate, and, according to
assistant coach Donnie Nelson, ``revolutionize the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His size and skills are unbelievable,'' Nash said. ``The game
is probably a little fast for him right now because they don't play
at this speed in Germany. But once he gets more comfortable and
confident, watch out.''
</P>
<P>
   Pushing 7 feet but only 240 pounds, Nowitzki has been roughed up
by the Mavericks during the first week of training camp. Buckner, a
6-4 guard from Clemson, has frustrated him with physical defense,
and teammates said he has been passive to make his move or take the
open shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so physical,'' Nowitzki said. ``I'm not so good with that
right now. It's a huge difference.''
</P>
<P>
   In the open court, Nowitzki appears comfortable, fluid and, at
times, spectacular. But in bump-and-grind half-court sets, he has
not matched his teammates' intensity and aggressiveness. All to be
expected, Don Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's passing up some shots we want him to take,'' he said.
``But you don't get on him yet because it's not wrong how he's
playing. He's trying to blend in, and we understand that. At times
he's too unselfish, but he'll come out of his shell. I don't know
if it'll be this year or three years, but when it happens he'll be
a fantastic player.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki, slated to be the Mavericks' starting small forward in
the mold of Toni Kukoc and Kevin Garnett, said he's struggling
knowing when to say when as far as being aggressive offensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Germany I shot about 25 times a game,'' he said. ``I don't
think I can do that here. I'm mostly a shy guy, and I'm holding
back. But hopefully it will click.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Nelson said this week that Nowitzki has the talent to
post up and score on any small forward in the league this side of
the Lakers' Robert Horry, and Don Nelson said he has seen nothing
to deter the enthusiasm that led him to acquire Nowitzki in a
draft-day trade in June.
</P>
<P>
   Even the off-court transition _ including the 24-hour
availability of volunteer assistant Bill Peterson to talk or shoot
jumpers _ is progressing smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't like Sarunas Marciulonis coming from communism to
free enterprise,'' Donnie Nelson said. ``We had to show him and his
wife simple things like how to use a credit card. But it is a jolt
for Dirk, and there's going to be a transition period. We want him
to live in the gym and get better, and so far that's just what he's
doing.'' Walker next With Steve Nash signed to a six-year contract
extension, signing power forward Samaki Walker is Don Nelson's next
priority. The Mavericks have until March 13 to sign the 6-foot-9,
260-pounder to an extension or risk him becoming a free agent July
1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to lock him up, too,'' said Don Nelson, who plans to
send a proposal to Walker's agent, Norm Nixon, this week.
``Depending on the numbers, of course. But I'm confident we can get
it done. He's an important piece to our puzzle.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker, after two seasons the longest-tenured Maverick, has been
limited to 43 and 41 games because of injuries but was Dallas' most
effective low-post threat when healthy last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried either way,'' Walker said. ``If we get it
done, great, I love it here. But if I have to play it out and test
myself on the open market, that's fine too. I hope it works out I
get to stay here, but there's always the business side of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson has used the extension period, which allows rookies
beginning in '96 to sign an extension during their third season, to
sign Nash this season and Michael Finley last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
