<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS HAVE WORK TO DO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA _ Training camp is over. The training isn't over
at all.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers left Santa Barbara on Tuesday, leaving behind the
double-day practice schedule as well. But after the six-month
layoff, they have no illusions of being ready for the season that
starts, gulp, nine days from today.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say that we're ready to start the season, I don't think
anybody would say that,'' Derek Harper said. ``I'm happy that we
have another week to go, to brush out some more of the wrinkles.
Because we're facing Houston (Feb. 5) and we're playing Utah and
we're playing against a very good San Antonio team to open up the
season. There's a lot of work to put in before we face those
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's intrasquad scrimmage, played before a wild crowd
of 5,000 at UC Santa Barbara's Thunderdome, certainly showed the
wrinkles _ errant passes, air balls, airheaded plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's just overanxiousness, being out on the court in
front of a crowd, guys trying to do too much, trying to find a
rhythm again,'' said Rick Fox. ``The body does tend to turn on a
little different, the adrenaline tends to flow a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' first public display since last May did have its
bright spots, particularly the play of Shaquille O'Neal, Eddie
Jones, Derek Fisher and rookies Tyronn Lue and Ruben Patterson. It
is perhaps no coincidence that O'Neal, Jones, Fisher and Lue were
regular attendees at UCLA pickup games.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, however, the game was an uninspiring portrait, one the
Lakers hope to improve upon in tonight's public scrimmage at the
Forum and in exhibition games Friday and Saturday against the
Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely rust,'' said Kobe Bryant, who was wild at
times Monday night. ``There's a lot more to be worked out, but
we're gonna do it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is precious little time to work out the bugs. Due to the
exhibition schedule, the Lakers only are holding four or five
complete practices before their season opener. And the compacted
50-game season virtually eliminates practices between games, other
than light, shootaround-type workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so essential that we stay with it and not become
complacent,'' coach Del Harris said, ``because we have covered a
lot of material and we're not going to be able to add much as the
season goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Empty infirmary: The subject was injuries _ the lack thereof _
and so many Lakers were knocking on wood, you worried someone might
bruise a knuckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to speak too soon,'' Harris said, knocking on a
reporter's head, then his own, in lieu of wood. ``We've been
fortunate so far not to have any (injuries).''
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of bumps and bruises to go around, but no one
missed much practice time _ in stark contrast to the Lakers' last
training camp, when O'Neal and Nick Van Exel both were nursing
serious injuries that lingered all last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knock on wood,'' Bryant said, joining the cliche parade.
``Hope nobody slips in the shower. Everybody's healthy for the
first time in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Familiar faces: Training camp came and went, and the Lakers
return home with the same 14 players with whom they left. That's an
unexpected development, considering they hoped to trade for a power
forward, specifically Tom Gugliotta, during camp.
</P>
<P>
   The Gugliotta deal was thwarted by Minnesota's refusal to do a
sign-and-trade, denying O'Neal his biggest wish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to make some moves, but I guess other teams really
don't want to help us. So from now on I hold a personal vendetta
against Minnesota,'' he said. ``Add them to the list.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal said the Lakers have enough talent to win, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have liked to have that thuggish forward that I was
looking for, that Horace Grant-type guy, but what we got is pretty
good,'' he said. ``We just have to work with what we got and
everybody just has to be on the same page.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
