<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ARTIST-STRUGGLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABOUT NEW YORK: THE YEAR OF THE RABBIT BRINGS LUCK TO AN ARTIST
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like many artists, Francisco Cardenas came to New
York intent on making his mark in SoHo. ``You have to go outside of
the familiar so that people will pay attention to you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his case, he had to go outside to help pay the bills.
Recently, he took a construction job installing a smokestack at a
restaurant at Houston Street and Second Avenue. But when he looked
at the long, black tube he couldn't help thinking like an artist.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the smokestack was covered with dozens of footprints that
looked like the spoor of a sky-walking phantom. The sight was
enough to let Cardenas justify the months he spends each year
separated from his family in Mexico when he travels to New York to
show his paintings to galleries and collectors. Besides, who knows
who might see the smokestack on the way to West Broadway?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting closer to SoHo now,'' he said. ``This is one way
to leave some footprints behind.''
</P>
<P>
   While he approaches SoHo from the north, he was already
encroaching from the south. He just ended an exhibition of
paintings and drawings at the Feng Shui Gallery, a small storefront
space in what had been a Buddhist temple on Eldridge Street in
Chinatown. Much of his work is surrealistic and filled with social
commentary. Granted, it seems fittingly surreal to find his
paintings on a street filled with trading companies and small
businesses with Chinese signs. But Cardenas thinks it's a perfect
setting that fits his plan to get outside and encounter the
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I came to New York,'' he said. ``To learn the
world, you have to travel the world. Now I have a chance to meet
the Chinese. Tomorrow, maybe Russians. Next, I'll go to upper
Manhattan. But to get there I have to go through different
cultures. In New York, you don't cross the street, you cross
cultures. On every street there is another world.''
</P>
<P>
   His work got the attention of Zaihong Sara Shen in December,
when a painting _ of a cherub hovering like a guardian angel above
a red, windowed apple symbolizing New York _ was included in a
group show. She offered him a solo show at her new gallery, Feng
Shui, which she named after the ancient principles that guide
architects in choosing harmonious colors and design. After speaking
with him, she could relate to his idea that you had to journey to
other lands to find what eludes you at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here to study something that China does not have,'' she
said. ``Which is capitalism.''
</P>
<P>
   When Cardenas arrived at her gallery a few weeks ago to hang his
show, he took the usual selection of Latin-tinged images. But he
surprised Ms. Shen with six drawings of rabbits done in bold, black
brush strokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw on television back home that the Chinese were going to
celebrate their New Year,'' Cardenas said. ``The Year of the
Rabbit. A rabbit is simple, no? So I drew it fast, like Picasso.''
</P>
<P>
   The rabbit drawings went over well at Ms. Shen's gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rabbit is a very nice year,'' Ms. Shen said. ``Not like
the Year of the Dragon. People get very nervous about the Year of
the Dragon. That is a year for extremes. The Year of the Rabbit is
very smooth and nice.''
</P>
<P>
   That is just the omen Cardenas needs. In the six years he has
been in New York, he has been doing whatever it takes to get ahead.
He saves money by living with Mexican friends in Brooklyn in a
house just yards off the elevated expressway in Clinton Hill. For a
while last year, he gave painting lessons to some people he met
while doing a mural in Bushwick. His friends had let him use a few
empty rooms in their house as a studio classroom, but they
reclaimed them this year because their children needed room to run
around. Now he sleeps and paints in a little room.
</P>
<P>
   Difficult? Sometimes. Maybe it's no surprise that among all the
surrealistic paintings he showed in Chinatown, the only realistic
image was one of a Mexican peasant selling carved fish against a
wall that had a faded and cracked sign for American Express. He
titled it ``The Daily Struggle.'' He was talking about it at the
gallery a few days ago when he spotted a ragged woman rooting
through the garbage cans outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``You come to New York and you see another daily struggle,'' he
said, standing by the window. ``Only this glass separates us. We
both are struggling. We are both from different cultures. Here,
everyone has to eat, dream and live. That is the great encounter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
