<HEADER>
A9934 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-AUSTRALIAN-OPEN-6     01-26 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-AUSTRALIAN-OPEN-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEADS AND WILLIAMS FALL TO DAVENPORT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, Australia _ Venus Williams' trademark beads went
skittering across the court in the second set Tuesday, earning her
a point penalty and the chair umpire her wrath. But Williams' game
was already coming apart under the relentless baseline pressure
that Lindsay Davenport was applying.
</P>
<P>
   Deep, forceful and relatively flat, Davenport's ground strokes
are now the confident shots of a player who belongs at No. 1, and
no matter what Martina Hingis achieves the rest of this week in
Melbourne, Davenport will remain atop the women's rankings.
</P>
<P>
   The evolution from slightly self-conscious, slightly erratic and
somewhat ungainly threat to poised, consistent and fluid force is
nearing completion. Tuesday's 6-4, 6-0 victory in the quarterfinals
of the Australian Open was merely the latest example.
</P>
<P>
   In the other half of the women's draw, No. 2 Martina Hingis, the
two-time defending champion, advanced to the semifinals with a 6-3,
6-4 victory over seventh-seeded Mary Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding Davenport's impressive game, even Williams, once
parsimonious with compliments, is willing to give the Californian
credit. ``She has improved,'' Williams said last week. ``She has
made it known she wants to be a competitor, a Grand Slam winner, a
No. 1. And I have made it known that I can be No. 6, so I have to
do better.''
</P>
<P>
   And after all, who respects power more than a power player?
Davenport, one of the rare women who can look down on the
6-foot-1{-inch Williams, has now defeated her at her own game seven
times in eight meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I did pretty much everything I wanted to do,'' said
Davenport of Tuesday's encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Her opponent in Thursday's semifinal will be Amelie Mauresmo, an
unseeded French teen-ager with broad shoulders and plenty of
breadth in her tennis, too. Mauresmo had to save two match points
in the first round against Corina Morariu, but she upset
eighth-seeded Patty Schnyder in the next round and then did the
same to No. 11 Dominique Van Roost of Belgium Tuesday, 6-3, 7-6
(7-3) to reach her first Grand Slam semifinal and probably not her
last.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is probably going to be very soon in the top 20 and
probably also in the top 10 because she has the game,'' Van Roost
said of the 19-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether Nicolas Lapentti of Ecuador has the same
sort of game. Even though he was a brilliant junior player, being a
fine junior seldom guarantees Grand Slam success for men. But like
his good friend and fellow South American, Gustavo Kuerten, who
emerged from obscurity to win the 1997 French Open, Lapentti is in
the midst of a memorable run of five-set victories.
</P>
<P>
   Four of his five matches have gone the distance and Tuesday he
upset the seventh-seeded Karol Kucera of Slovakia, 7-6 (7-4), 6-7
(6-8), 6-2, 0-6, 8-6, and gave the ever-more-egalitarian game of
men's tennis its latest unseeded sensation.
</P>
<P>
   It is just as well that Lapentti is only 22 because he has
played more than 20 hours of singles and doubles in this
tournament. On Wednesday, he is scheduled to play the quarterfinals
of the men's doubles with Kuerten, who was watching in the stands
Tuesday along with Lapentti's good friend Anna Kournikova.
</P>
<P>
   His coach, Pato Rodriguez, credits Lapentti's five-set success
to a month of intense training in Chile in December and a slightly
less fraternal approach to competition. ``Before, he was a little
too nice,'' Rodriguez said. ``When his opponent was down, you had
the impression he wanted to help him up.''
</P>
<P>
   Lapentti, who had never made it past the second round at a Grand
Slam event until this year, will need to lift himself up if he is
to change Thomas Enqvist's luck. The Swede, who had already
eliminated Australia's main attractions, Pat Rafter and Mark
Philippoussis, defeated Marc Rosset of Switzerland in straight sets
Tuesday to reach his first Grand Slam semifinal.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For Davenport, advancing that far is rapidly becoming a habit.
She has not lost a set in a Grand Slam tournament since losing at
Wimbledon last summer, but she would surely not have won with quite
such ease against Williams if not for what happened in the second
set with Williams serving at 0-2.
</P>
<P>
   On the first point of the game, the chair umpire, Denis
Overberg, called a let when a string of Williams' hair beads broke
and fell to the court. Overberg then informed her that if it
happened again, she was going to lose the point. Williams played on
and at 30-40, after she hit her first serve and then prepared to
hit a backhand, more beads fell free. Overberg called ``point.''
</P>
<P>
   In tennis, there is a rule against hindrance. Balls falling out
of pockets or hats falling off heads in the middle of play are
ruled a hindrance because they are a distraction. Williams' beads
apparently fall into the same category. Williams called for the
tournament referee, Peter Bellenger, but Bellenger would stand by
his umpire, even as Williams began to get tears in her eyes and ire
in her voice. ``This has never happened to me before,'' she
shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after saying that she was ``losing control,'' she
walked away and screamed once more at nobody in particular as she
changed ends, now down two breaks of serve and 0-3. The match,
which had been of remarkably high quality early, and Williams'
ability to concentrate would not be the same again.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said she didn't think her beads falling off represented
a distraction. But Davenport said of the beads: ``You can hear
them, and you can see them a little bit. Fortunately, you learn to
play the ball. I'm not going to say it was a total distraction, but
it is a little annoying maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, it is also against the rules, but Williams has no
intention of changing her look in order to change her luck against
the formidable likes of Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like my hair,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
