<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9938 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-SONGFEST-ART-NY     01-26 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-SONGFEST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POP REVIEW: WOMEN JOIN IN FOLKY EMPATHY, WITH MORE THAN WORDS
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (bl) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Anyone looking at the lineup of ``Women in Music,
1960-1999,'' which assembled eight singers in a benefit for Zero
Population Growth on Monday night at the Theater at Madison Square
Garden, could have predicted doses of empathy, folky guitar picking
and sweet-voiced sing-alongs. Those were all part of the headlining
set by Jewel, whose fans joined in on ``Foolish Games'' and ``You
Were Meant for Me,'' and they had their place during sets by Paula
Cole, Judy Collins, Phoebe Snow and Janis Ian.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the songs were about romantic longing and healing the
wounds it left behind. But the gist of the concert had to do with
wordless music: the power of voices swooping, growling, breathing
heavily or holding high notes proudly aloft.
</P>
<P>
   At this point in pop history, the rubric ``women in music'' is
about as meaningful a category as ``men in politics.'' The mildly
eclectic concert included a young but old-fashioned country singer,
Mandy Barnett, the middle-of-the-road pop of Helen Reddy, Odetta
singing a spiritual and a blues and Phoebe Snow belting
rhythm-and-blues along with the folky contingent.
</P>
<P>
   The audience belonged to Jewel, who played a businesslike
35-minute set that was beset by technical problems and a band still
feeling its way into her newer songs. She has a gift for
heartwarming melodies; more often than not, however, she applies
them to trite lyrics, seesawing between self-pity and self-help:
``You realize that your only friend/Has never been yourself or
anyone that cared in the end.'' The awkwardness and adolescent
banality of her lyrics may bring her closer to her teen-age
audience. But her fans are also swayed by her voice: a girlish lilt
that can suddenly open up to a deep Joni Mitchell croon or a
country singer's twang or a bluesy growl, revealing the woman
within the girl.
</P>
<P>
   The concert's organizing principle _ beyond who would donate the
performances _ seemed to be that women over 40 could easily hold
their own with the young women who command major-label contracts
and Top 10 singles. From Odetta's African-tinged leaps and
syncopations to Ms. Snow's octave-hopping, gospelly glides and
Janis Joplin imitation, to Ms. Collins, whose legato phrases poured
out with her old vocal purity intact, they proved that point.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everybody showed off. For her virtuoso turn, Jewel packed
a big crescendo and a sustained peak into ``Who Will Save Your
Soul?'' Later she yodeled, with her glottal stops arriving in
quadruple time. Ms. Cole devoted most of her set to a come-on over
a funk vamp: cooing like Prince's falsetto, moaning like a
phone-sex operator and winding up with some mock-gospel
exhortations. Ms. Snow reveled in her gigantic range, from
ultrahigh near-whistling tones to low bluesy growls and siren
wails, pushing songs over the top.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ian _ wearing a Ninja headband, high-heeled sneakers and a
T-shirt that said ``Godlike'' _ sang her 1975 hit, the ugly
duckling's lament ``At 17,'' to a fully sympathetic response. Two
newer songs traded self-pity for defiance: ``Take no prisoners/Tell
no lies,'' she insisted. She then turned that song into a long
guitar showcase: strumming resonant chords, picking modal lines,
invoking the blues. Ms. Collins' showpiece was ``Colorado,'' with
her restless, quasi-classical piano lines creating flurries of
notes for a story of a kindly stranger during a blizzard. Ms.
Reddy, alone onstage with her backup on tape, struck Broadway
poses: wide-eyed, confiding, imperious.
</P>
<P>
   Mandy Barnett, the least known of the performers, arrived with a
full country band, including fiddle and pedal steel guitar, and
harked back to the sultry ease and controlled heartbreak of her
model, Patsy Cline. Her three songs used vintage country styles _
torch ballad, Western swing _ and her band had the preternatural
ease of prerock country bands. Most important, Ms. Barnett had the
vocal finesse: the husky dives, the controlled slides and the
timing to make her voice break just as she confessed ``I don't know
what to do.'' Surrounded by showboating, she made understatement
persuasive.
</P>
<P>
   After Jewel's last song, the women all returned to the stage.
There wasn't time for them to sing along to the tape of Ms. Reddy's
``I Am Woman,'' which was just as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
