A9942 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOTHEBY'S-INTERNET-NY     01-26 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOTHEBY'S-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOTHEBY'S ASKS DEALERS FOR EXCLUSIVE INTERNET RIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In an apparent attempt to undermine its archrival
Christie's entry into the potentially lucrative online auction
business, Sotheby's is asking art dealers to sign exclusive
contracts that would prevent them from selling wares through other
auction houses on the Internet for at least two years.
</P>
<P>
   The effort comes as the two famous auction houses have moved to
enter the world of cyberspace, seeking a potentially rich new
marketplace to sell the high-end goods that have been their
traditional franchise. Sotheby's announced Jan. 19 that it would
begin selling some items online, while Christie's followed with a
similar announcement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But dealers around the country who received Sotheby's 10-page
contract, which the company stipulated must be signed within seven
days, are up in arms over the auction house's demand, on short
notice, for exclusivity. Many dealers, some of whom spoke on the
condition of anonymity, said they would not sign the exclusive
agreement because the Internet auction business is still in its
formative stages and should not be hindered by exclusionary
contract provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't consider signing an exclusive contract to any auction
house which would inhibit the freedom to participate in a free and
open market,'' Barbara Mathes, a Manhattan dealer, said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Angela Westwater, a Manhattan dealer, says
she doesn't have much to lose by signing up with Sotheby's now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've signed it because we don't see a down side,'' she said.
``Two years isn't that long. Do I think it's going to be the wave
of the future for selling our best pictures? No. But why not give
it a try.''
</P>
<P>
   At stake is control of an online auction industry that a recent
study from a researcher, Jupiter Communications, said would sell
$3.2 billion worth of merchandise a year by 2002 as Internet
technology becomes more accepted as a means of commerce. The stock
price of Ebay, the online auctioneer, which was offered at $18 a
share when issued in September, closed at 220~ yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the 10-page contract that Sotheby's sent to
dealers last week, it would waive its vendor's fee, which varies
from 6 to 15 percent in live auctions for items under $100,000, if
vendors sign up within a week. The contract in turn would give
Sotheby's the exclusive right to present dealer items in
cyberspace, although it would rely on the dealers to bear
responsibility for authenticating their lots.
</P>
<P>
   Both auction houses, in stepping onto the Internet, said they
would concentrate on mostly lower-end goods. For its first online
auction this July, for example, Sotheby's plans to offer baseball
memorabilia from the collection of Barry Halper, a limited partner
in the New York Yankees. Executives at Christie's said Tuesday that
they would follow suit with an auction in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``The anticipation in the beginning is that we will be selling
things of lower value that are both easily describable and do not
require personal inspection, such as jewelry or collectibles,''
said Patricia G. Hambrecht, president of Christie's in North and
South America. ``Over time we expect that what we sell on the
Internet will change and be driven by what the marketplace wants to
buy.''
</P>
<P>
   If Sotheby's announcement of its new online foray last week took
Christie's by surprise, company officials are not admitting it.
Christopher M. Davidge, Christie's chief executive, said his
company had spent months planning a move into Internet
auctioneering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't caught off guard at all,'' he said Tuesday in a
telephone interview from his London office. If anything, Davidge
added, Sotheby's is the one feeling the pressure to jump into
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   But Sotheby's chief executive Diana Brooks said Christie's
announcement yesterday, with few details and five weeks ahead of
any official proclamation, carried a whiff of desperation. ``Their
reaction is, I think, a reaction to what we've done,'' Ms. Brooks
said.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Christie's and Sotheby's said they could not
estimate how much an Internet presence would increase business. But
Ms. Brooks said half the merchandise Sotheby's sells each year,
about 250,000 items, could eventually find a buyer through the
Internet. ``It's a new marketplace,'' she said. ``We are taking it
very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   So are other, more established virtual-auction companies like
Ebay. But it may take some time, perhaps years, before premium
brokers like Christie's and Sotheby's find themselves in direct
competition with the likes of Ebay, which is based in California
but exists only in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's such a wide gap between Christie's and Sotheby's
business and Ebay,'' said Nicole Vanderbilt, a senior analyst with
Jupiter Communications, an Internet market-research company based
in New York City. The two traditional auction houses, she added,
``might bring in some incremental business, but not nearly the
volume of the lower-end auction houses that you see online now.''
High-end luxury goods, she added, don't sell all too well online.
</P>
<P>
   But clearly the world of auction houses, still a province of the
wealthy few, now has the potential to transform itself into
something resembling an upscale home-shopping network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-four hours a day, seven days a week, you are going to
be able to buy a work of art,'' Ms. Brooks of Sotheby's declaimed
enthusiastically. ``How exciting is that?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-26-99 2342EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990126.0552 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9945 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     01-26 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WRITE-WING CONSPIRACY FOR RAIDERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's bring back the Raiders, who we never should have let get
away.'' &UR;  &QL; 
_Larry Robbins, Encino &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
``I really think it's time we quit fooling around and get (the
Raiders) back in L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _LissAnn Recup, &LR;   &UR; Northridge &LR; !off! &QL; 
``Please do whatever you can to get the Raiders back to Los
Angeles.'' &UR;  &QL; 
_Norm Zeichner, Tarzana &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LOS ANGELES _ When a newspaper is peppered with letters pleading
for the Raiders' return to Southern California, as this newspaper
has been lately, the possible explanations are various.
</P>
<P>
   It might be that Raiders fans have a little too much free time
on their hands, considering their team missed the playoffs for the
fifth straight year.
</P>
<P>
   It might be that Raiders passion burns deeper here, four years
after they skipped back to Oakland, than surveys suggest.
</P>
<P>
   It might be a vast write-wing conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Or it might be all of the above. With the Raiders anything is
possible.
</P>
<P>
   The letters have been landing on my desk and the sports editor's
desk for a few months, as many as three a week, which is a lot on
one topic. It wasn't until December that I spotted the pattern and
started to save the letters.
</P>
<P>
   The first thought was, Hey, if all these people concluded
independently that Los Angeles should invite Al Davis back, maybe I
should take their opinions more seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The second thought was, Hey, these letters have more in common
than I realized.
</P>
<P>
   They're all computer-printed on 8{-by-11 paper.
</P>
<P>
   The letter from Larry Robbins and the one from Carlos Rodriguez
have neighboring return addresses in Los Angeles; they appear to be
the products of the same printer; the date and salutation on each
is smashed together (``Dec.23,1998,'' ``Dear Mr.Modesti''); and the
stamp on each was upside down.
</P>
<P>
   LissAnn Recup uses the same space-saving style on the date, as
does Eunice Fischer.
</P>
<P>
   The letters from Robbins, Rodriguez and Fischer all are
postmarked in Los Angeles, even though Fischer's return address is
in Canyon Country.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody is behind this letter-writing campaign, and I was going
to find out who even if it meant dusting for Al Davis'
fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that hard.
</P>
<P>
   I phoned Recup. She said she wrote her letter as a favor to
Larry Robbins, who is a golfing buddy of her husband, LeRoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked, `Would you write letters?' and we said, `Sure,'''
said Recup, who, with LeRoy, is in the business of selling humidors
out of their home.
</P>
<P>
   I phoned Zeichner. He volunteered that he's an old New York
friend of Larry Robbins. They had lunch the other day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (Robbins), I told him to get Al Davis off his
backside,'' said Zeichner, 69, who is retired from the shoe
business.
</P>
<P>
   I phoned another letter writer, Mike Bernstein of Costa Mesa. He
said he knows Larry Robbins because both are in the textile
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is basically to pepper all the news outlets,''
Bernstein said.
</P>
<P>
   I'm guessing the common denominator here is... Larry Robbins?
Hello, Larry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not keeping any secrets,'' Robbins, 68, said cheerfully on
the phone Tuesday morning. ``I'm writing to all the newspapers,
(to) all the names I can get ahold of.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the other letter writers ``my group,'' and said they
number 10 to 12. Friends, business associates, season-ticket
holders from old Coliseum days. Also Robbins' wife, Sally, and
brother, Mike.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins said nobody has been paid to write letters.
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not write any of the letters over other people's
signatures _ ``I gave them !ital!suggestions!off!.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he does not work for the Raiders _ though ``I would like
to.''
</P>
<P>
   His loyalty to the Raiders stems from the fact he and Davis
attended the same high school, Erasmus Hall in Brooklyn, a few
years apart, Robbins said. Davis is one of the school's major
benefactors. The men worked together on a school reunion last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Davis knows about it (the letter campaign) and he's behind
us,'' Robbins said. But he denied Davis put them up to this.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, Robbins said, is to sway reporters, whom
torch-carrying Raiders fans believe have ignored Davis' side of the
breakup with Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the Raiders) were pushed out of here. Davis didn't leave
because he wanted to leave,'' Robbins said.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins and ``his group'' would prefer see Los Angeles try to
lure the Raiders back than pursue an NFL expansion team. They're
impatient and believe the Raiders could play here as early as next
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides,'' Recup wrote, ``I love their uniforms.''
</P>
<P>
   Would Davis come back? He probably would. He has lawsuits
working on two fronts that could clear the way _ one challenging
Oakland's hold on the Raiders under terms of a 16-year contract,
the other seeking to maintain ``territorial rights'' to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Would we want them back? A poll showed Los Angeles-area
residents would prefer an expansion team over an existing team by a
3-2 ratio, and showed that our favorite NFL team is the San
Francisco 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   A Raiders spokesman, reached in Oakland, offered no comment on
the letter campaign, and could not confirm that Davis knows about
it.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least Davis should know he has friends in Los
Angeles. Or Larry Robbins has friends. One or the other.
</P>
<P>
   They're going to keep those letters coming. Another arrived
Tuesday. What else are Raiders fans going to do during Super Bowl
week? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
