<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9953 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BOHLS-COLUMN-COX     01-26 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BOHLS-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clemens could still hang his hat in Houston
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ More than six months ago, when the Houston
Astros front office was deliberating over trades to bolster the
team for the stretch run and was considering aces like Randy
Johnson and Roger Clemens, Larry Dierker made his preferences
known.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I'd prefer Roger over Randy,'' the Astros'
second-year manager recalled Tuesday in between signing more than
500 autographs during the team's winter caravan stop.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Dierker didn't get his wish. His second choice didn't turn
out all that bad as Johnson won 10 of his 11 decisions, never lost
in the Astrodome and held opponents scoreless in 42 of his 43
innings in games pitched under a roof.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens won his fifth Cy Young Award, which is four more than
Johnson owns.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker still likes Clemens, especially since Johnson took his
talented left arm and windmill frame to Arizona's greener pastures.
Clemens remains in Toronto _ for now. Curiously enough, Dierker and
Clemens will be united, at least temporarily, when both are
inducted tonight into the Texas Sports Hall of Fame at a banquet in
Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he expects Clemens to be a Blue Jay when the season
opens in April, Dierker said, ``From what people are telling me,
probably not. It still may be possible (for him to be an Astro),''
said Dierker, who was named the National League Manager of the Year
for directing Houston to 102 wins and a playoff appearance _
albeit, a brief one _ against San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told our people I liked Roger because he's a more vocal guy
than Randy. He's a very dominant personality and has a similar
domineering personality. The two go together. He's an extremely
successful person who doesn't accept anything less, and that part
of him is what makes him great.''
</P>
<P>
   The bet here is Clemens will become an Astro, maybe by the time
pitchers report to spring training Feb. 17. Houston has all but
listed future Cy Young candidate Scott Elarton and budding outfield
star Richard Hidalgo off-limits in talks with the Blue Jays, but
don't rule out a trade that would send outfielder Derek Bell, a
pitcher such as Jose Lima or Sean Bergman and a minor-league
prospect. The Astros could even wind up with outfielder Jose Cruz
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   You might remember that the Astros flirted with Clemens last
month after the former Texas Longhorns pitcher told Toronto he
wished to be traded to a contender, preferably one closer to his
home, which just happens to be a Jeff Bagwell home run away from
the Astrodome. As All-Star second baseman Craig Biggio described
the previous negotiations Tuesday, ``the way it went down the first
time wasn't that smooth.''
</P>
<P>
   Smooth? The ugly scene between Clemens, his agents and Astros
General Manager Gerry Hunsicker made Latrell Sprewell and P.J.
Carlesimo look like bosom buddies in comparison. First, Houston
lost out on the Big Unit, and then Clemens all but flicked away the
Astros. Hunsicker railed at excessive salary demands in general and
Clemens took it personally, as he always does, and ranted in
return. Astros owner Drayton McLane then added kerosene and
announced he would handle any communications, undermining his own
GM.
</P>
<P>
   But that was adversarial then, and this is peace-and-harmony
now. Clemens extended an olive branch of sorts last week when he
said he'd still love to pitch in an Astros uniform. They haven't
completely kissed and made up, but they're puckering. Clemens would
be wise to take a public page from prodigal Astros son Ken
Caminiti, who rejected Detroit's annual $7 million-plus offer for
Houston's $5 million. Caminiti even let his agent of 11 years go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to come home,'' Caminiti said. ``I didn't really care
about the money. Roger called me and apologized (for the bitter
sound bites) and told me to apologize to the rest of our team. I
know he really wants to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker, reached at a Temple hotel, said the commissioner's
ruling against tampering precludes him from commenting about any
new talks. But he did say the hatchet's as good as buried _ and in
no one's back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had any intent of personally attacking anyone,''
Hunsicker said, ``and I don't feel I did. That's water over the
bridge right now. I'm not one to hold grudges or let anything
interfere with doing what's in the best interests of the ballclub.
I think the ball's in Toronto's court. We've got a club capable of
getting to the World Series, but it's just not as easy without a
dominant pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   A blockbuster trade for Clemens is even more critical in the
aftermath of the payroll-reducing trade of proven catcher Brad
Ausmus to Detroit, weakening Houston behind the plate and leaving a
platoon situation with Tony Eusebio and switch-hitting rookie Mitch
Meluskey. If ever there was a mixed message, it was the decision to
save $2.5 million by unloading Ausmus at the same time the club
still pursues $8 million-a-year Clemens. Even Dierker labeled the
catching move ``very risky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed,'' Biggio said. ``Usually when you have a
championship team, you want to stay strong up the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   No one could make it stronger than Clemens. And as Dierker said,
``He hasn't gone anywhere else, so no news is good news.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Bohls writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: kbohls(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
