<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISA PROBLEMS DELAY OLOWOKANDI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM DESERT _ Add at least another 172,800 seconds to the
countdown for Michael Olowokandi's arrival in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   According to agent Bill Duffy, author of an earlier escape from
an early escape-clause deal that released the 7-foot-1 rookie from
the tyranny of shot-happy Italian League guards, a delay in
obtaining a work visa will keep Olowokandi in Milan awhile longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The earliest he'll be there (L.A.) is Friday,'' said Duffy,
who had hoped to deliver Olowokandi by Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   But Jan. 29 is not bad, considering how the original clause in a
three-month deal would have kept his client in Italy through Feb.
15. ``We'll get him there as soon as possible,'' Duffy said. ``I
know he's excited about being with the Clippers.''
</P>
<P>
   A large portion of that excitement may have been established by
leaving Italy and Kinder Bologna, the team that hired the NBA's top
draft pick just before the lockout ended. And even though
Olowokandi will be paid a handsome $480,000 for three weeks of
basketball work, the perimeter-oriented European style of play
didn't exactly showcase his developing skills.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper reports from Italy suggest Olowokandi was another
potential bust for the Clippers museum, but his modest, six-game
stats _ 7.7 points and 5.8 rebounds per game _ were recorded in
only 14 minutes per game. Tendinitis in his right knee had
something to do with that. So did Kinder's reluctance to rely on
Olowokandi after he turned down an updated offer of $5 million to
stay in Italy through June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, it was a good experience for Michael,'' said Duffy,
who added that his client's knee is fine. ``He did get in game
shape, and I think _ even though things were pretty nice over there
_ he'll really appreciate being in the NBA even more.''
</P>
<P>
   Point in right direction: It appears the responsibility for
putting the ball in the hands of Olowokandi and his teammates will
be given to last year's point guards, the recently re-signed
Darrick Martin and veteran Pooh Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been very pleased with our point guards,'' said new coach
Chris Ford as the team's accelerated training camp was winding down
at College of the Desert. ``They've done everything I've asked at
both ends of the court.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a league source, the possibility of the Clippers
bringing in free-agent point guard Sherman Douglas is slim.
Instead, the team is expected to bank its $3.2 million in cap room.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly: The 5,500 free tickets made available last Saturday for
this Saturday's exhibition game with the Lakers were snapped up in
14 minutes. An estimated 100 fans already were lined up outside the
Sports Arena at 8 a.m., even though the ticket office didn't open
until noon. The team donated another 5,000 tickets for this game to
the L.A. City Parks and Recreation Department.... The Clippers will
practice at the College of the Desert this morning, then return to
L.A. for a workout at the Sports Arena tonight.
</P>
</TEXT>
