<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9956 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SHELL-BOS &LR;      01-26 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SHELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO ROOM FOR SHELL WITH PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Any chance of Art Shell coming to New England as
assistant head coach apparently ended Tuesday night as former
Carolina assistant Brad Seely accepted an offer to became the
Patriots' special teams coach, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Seely, who had a similar offer from the
Cleveland Browns, created a domino effect on Pete Carroll's staff
as former special teams coach Dante Scarnecchia agreed to take over
the offensive line, leaving no place for Shell, who is currently
offensive line coach for the Super Bowl-bound Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   After several days of speculation that Shell might end up in New
England, Patriots vice president of personnel Bobby Grier issued an
unusual press release Tuesday night saying Carroll would finalize
his staff in the next 24-48 hours and that Shell would not be a
part of it under any circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said that release came only after Seely notified Carroll
that he would accept New England's offer, which one NFL insider
described as ``a ton of money for a special teams coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the Patriots' offer were unavailable, but the Browns'
offer was for three years at $240,000, $260,000, and $280,000.
</P>
<P>
   In his release, Grier said, ``Art Shell is not being considered
for a position on Pete Carroll's staff. We've made no effort to
contact him. In fact, he's not even available to be contacted by
another team. I expect Pete to finalize his coaching staff within
the next couple of days and I can assure you Art is not a
candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why this started, but quite frankly, I'm sick of
this type of speculation. If you read some of the reports in the
papers, you would believe a deal is already done. This type of
speculation is a distraction to everyone involved and I hate to
even comment on it. I'm sure Art feels the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Seely, a longtime friend and former coaching associate of
Carroll's, also was under consideration by the Baltimore Ravens
until they filled their opening. Carroll told Scarnecchia last week
that he might be shifted to offensive line if Seely came on. After
expressing his reluctance to make such a move and his unhappiness
with the decision to fire previous line coach Paul Boudreau,
Scarnecchia told Carroll he would do whatever he was asked.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Seely had the best special teams unit in the league as
the Panthers stunned the NFL by reaching the NFC Championship Game.
But as the star of head coach Dom Capers began to fade this season,
his staff went with him.
</P>
<P>
   With Seely on board and Scarnecchia running the offensive line,
Shell would be left in the same position he has been in for five
years _ searching for a second chance to coach an NFL team after
winning nearly 60 percent of his games on his first try.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, friends of Shell said that if there was no
offensive line job available in New England, he would have been
unwilling to join Carroll's staff in a supervisory role that lacked
real duties or authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art is not going to go there just to be a figurehead,'' a
close friend of Shell's said. ``He wants to be a head coach, but
he's not going to New England to stand around all day and look like
he's waiting to replace Pete. That's not who he is. If he goes
there, he wants to help them win, and the way for him to do that is
to coach their line the same way he's coached the Falcons.''
</P>
<P>
   Shell declined to comment on the speculation beyond confirming
that he had not been contacted by the Patriots and saying they had
not asked Falcons head coach Dan Reeves for permission to talk to
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I want is a chance to sit down and talk with someone,''
Shell said. ``If you're asking me do I deserve to be a head coach
in the NFL, the answer is yes. Certainly, it's been disappointing
not to get a second chance because I feel I have something to
offer. The key thing is, I can lead men.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Shell became the first black head coach in 65 years to
lead men in the NFL, and within a year, he was named Coach of the
Year after taking the Raiders to the AFC Championship Game. In his
5 1/2 years, his teams reached the playoffs three times, but he was
fired after a dismal 9-7 season. Since then, the Raiders have not
reached that level again.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Cafardo of the Globe staff contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
