<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-26 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9964 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-SCHOOLBUS-CRASH-C     01-26 1372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-SCHOOLBUS-CRASH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aftermath of terror told as students recover from deadly crash
 &HT;    (ATTENTION: Florida editors.)
 &HT;    By Brian Crecente and Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ As the school bus carrying 16 Indian River
County grade schoolers slid to a stop after slamming into a citrus
truck Monday, 11-year-old T.J. Adams scrambled toward the front,
past his dead classmate, to the radio.
</P>
<P>
   Just three months ago, the bus driver, Mrs. C., had taught him
to use it if an emergency ever happened.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as children all around him fell silent, stunned by what had
just occurred, T.J. climbed over seats in the flipped bus. Driver
Deborah Colletti lay outside the bus, hurled through the front
window by the collision; the front axle of 1995 Thomas Vista was
ripped from its chassis.
</P>
<P>
   Past bloody handprints and a plastic Halloween pumpkin
half-filled with candy, T.J. reached the radio only to find it
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, children began screaming when ``they looked at
themselves bleeding,'' T.J. said. ``I went out the front window. It
looked like a door.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with 8-year-old Victor Dixon Jr., truck driver Sammie Lee
Hughes, 63, died in the 3:30 p.m. accident. Florida Highway Patrol
troopers investigating the accident erroneously reported a second
student's death late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   All but eight remained hospitalized late Monday. The seven are
expected to fully recover from their injuries, Indian River School
Superintendent Roger Dearing said.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses told troopers when Colletti, 36, approached the stop
sign over a narrow bridge, she appeared to keep going. She neither
braked nor stopped, they said. But T.J., who said he was just
putting his Game Boy in his pocket, remembers her stopping several
yards in front of the stop sign as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``She stopped and I think she looked both ways and didn't see
the truck,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But FHP Cpl. Shirley Lindstadt said the bus drove past the stop
at 45 mph, Colletti didn't even appear to be making a turn when the
crash occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The bus slammed into the tanker being driven by Hughes at about
45 mph. The impact, just behind the driver's side door, crushed the
right side of the tractor and nearly tore it off of its wheels. The
collision spun both vehicles in opposite directions, until the rear
of the bus hit the back half of the trailer. The tractor veered to
the right, plowing cab first into a canal on the west side of 66th
Avenue and throwing Hughes partly through the windshield.
</P>
<P>
   The bus continued to spin until it slammed into a utility pole
near the canal, slid up the pole and then back down, coming to rest
on its right side.
</P>
<P>
   Cpl. Frederick Jones, who is friends with both of those that
died, was first on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a mess,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later he was asked to identify Dixon's body and then went with
another trooper, who was Dixon's second cousin, to tell the child's
mother that he was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost harder then seeing little Jay laying there
smashed up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The intersection has proved treacherous for drivers because the
narrow bridge requires they stop before the stop sign to make room
for cars turning on to 45th Street, said district Transportation
Director Kathleen Geyer. In fact, two other accidents occurred on
the stretch on Monday, said Sheriff Gary Wheeler.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes time, engineering and money to correct these things.
With the rapid growth of this area, it's difficult to keep up,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fatalities on school buses are rare. In a given year, only about
11 bus drivers and passengers are killed, out of 23.5 million
students transported., according to the National Highway Traffic
and Safety Administration. The investigation is pending. Gov. Jeb
Bush has also asked for federal help in reviewing the case.
Colletti remains in critical condition at Indian River Memorial
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon's family, meanwhile, has gone into seclusion, declining
requests for interviews. Sharon Dixon was busy comforting other
families in a conference room off the emergency room at Indian
River Memorial when she learned her only child had died at the
scene, said Carol Marino, the principal of her son's elementary
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knew when they had her go the conference room. She just
went through this three months ago,'' when her father died, said
neighbor Jennine Dash.
</P>
<P>
   In her small neighborhood, her son's playmates described a quiet
boy, sometimes forced indoors on sunny days by terrible migraines.
Little J's favorite thing, said neighbor Andrea Burt, 12, was
Nintendo. He was expert at Sonic, the fireball spitting cartoon
character, said Sean Durkee, 11.
</P>
<P>
   Across town at the Fat Boy's restaurant, customers mourned the
passing of a regular and a friend, said Durkee's mother, Jessica, a
waitress who has known Hughes for 24 years. Hughes drove for Graves
Brothers Harvesting for two decades and trucks in general for 40
years, said his daughter Debra Smith, who drives buses for the St.
Lucie County School District.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a precious man. So happy, go lucky,'' Durkee said. ``He
always had the same: eggs over medium, bacon, grits and toast.''
</P>
<P>
   In the hours after Monday's accident, school officials
implemented an emergency plan adopted just two months ago.
Initially, school officials frantically tried to identify students
on the bus by tracking down school rosters. At the scene, a
passerby rounded up uninjured children and had them write down
names to keep them occupied, said T.J.'s mother, Fran Adams.
</P>
<P>
   By 9:45 p.m. all had been accounted for and teachers and other
officials contacted, Marino said. Tuesday morning, nine counselors
went to Rosewood Elementary and 12 to Osceola. Counselors were also
available to teachers and drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Parents dropping off students Tuesday said their children were
fearful of riding the bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shock. My kids have friends on the bus. My daughter
knows Victor,'' said Kathy Price, whose two children ride the bus
but were not on it Monday. ``The kids told me Mrs. C., the bus
driver, was very safe. They just loved her.''
</P>
<P>
   For students on the bus, many were concerned about Colletti.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Johnson, 7, who was flown to St. Mary's Medical Center in
West Palm Beach asked immediately ``how is my bus driver,'' Geyer
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a very good rapport with the children,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Colletti drove for the district from 1991 to 1993 before moving
back to her hometown in Falls River, N.J., where she also drove a
bus for the local district.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was an excellent driver who was always willing to do what
was needed,'' said district spokeswoman Pat Hanlon.
</P>
<P>
   Colletti returned to Vero Beach and resumed driving, picking up
the route she was driving Monday more than a year and a half ago,
Geyer said. Records show she received over 40 hours of training
initially and underwent eight hours of additional training in
August.
</P>
<P>
   Records also show the three-year-old bus with more than 63,000
miles passed its last monthly inspection in November when its
brakes were adjusted along with some other minor repairs.
</P>
<P>
   For Superintendent Dearing, the accident was particularly
disturbing: just six months ago his 20-year-old daughter was left
paralyzed after the family's car collided with a car on a trip to
Miami. Dearing assured families that the district's risk management
department would handle insurance matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our thoughts right now are with the family of Mr. Hughes and
of course the little boy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Falzarano, 7, and Ryan Besancon, 9, were both in
satisfactory condition and Colletti remained in critical condition
at Indian River Memorial Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor Rosemond, 7, was in good condition at Arnold Palmer
Hospital for Women and Children in Orlando. Tyler Griffin, 6, was
in stable condition at Holmes Regional Medical Center in Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Haywood, 11, of Vero Beach and Johnson of Fellsmere were in
stable condition and being moved into a regular pediatric ward at
St. Mary's.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Crecente and Jenny Staletovich write for the Palm Beach
Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
